<HEADLINE>
LIGHTS! CAMERA! ARPAIO! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - No sooner did an Arizona production company announce
its plans to make a ``cute or fun'' movie about Maricopa County
Sheriff Joe Arpaio when serious casting problems set in.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arpaio sees Robert DeNiro or Al Pacino in the title role of a
film to be based on his book, America's Toughest Sheriff, though he
says he's willing to settle for Joe Pesci.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, producers have floated the name of Roseanne's
ex-husband, Tom Arnold, perhaps because the late Jackie Gleason
isn't available to reprise the Sheriff Buford T. Justice character
he perfected in Smokey and the Bandit.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just the beginning of the casting quandary.
</P>
<P>
   Who will play Arpaio's right-hand man, double-dipping Deputy
Dave Hendershott?
</P>
<P>
   Don Knotts is still alive, but anyone who knows Hendershott can
tell you Knotts isn't a big enough actor to fill the deputy's
shoes, or any other part of his wardrobe. Still, the role cries out
for the performer who immortalized Barney Fife.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the chief executive officer of Desert Winds
production company told The Republic that the movie of Arpaio's
life will be ``cute or fun.``
</P>
<P>
   But what about David Michael Pecard? Who'll play the AWOL
soldier from Fort Huachuca who talked his way into the sheriff's
inner circle, obtained keys, a badge and an office, and even posed
as Arpaio's bodyguard?
</P>
<P>
   I hear O.J.'s available.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the deputies who say they were forced out of
their jobs by henchmen trying to purge news leaks from the
Sheriff's Office? Perhaps they could play themselves. They need the
work.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll get the ``cute or fun'' role of Wayne Bates, the postal
worker who was hauled off to jail in front of TV cameras for using
pepper spray on a pair of fenced-in dogs? No charges were filed,
though Bates did file a whopping lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   And who will they cast as Tim Griffin, a one-time inmate at
Joe's jail who was denied medical treatment for a perforated ulcer
after begging for help? A Superior Court jury ordered the county to
pay him $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll play George E. Sullivan and Gene Miller, experts who
produced reports on the brutality in Joe's lockups?
</P>
<P>
   A convincing young actor is needed to portray Jeremy Flanders.
He was beaten by inmates at Joe's Tent City jail and later awarded
more than $900,000.
</P>
<P>
   And what about Richard Post? He's a paraplegic abused while in
sheriff's custody and later paid $800,000. There aren't many actors
who can do ``cute or fun'' from a wheelchair, particularly when
being roughed up.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be especially difficult to cast the part of County
Attorney Rick Romley. The local prosecutor recently joined the long
list of those who've filed suit against Arpaio. It's all part of a
two-man feud that's been nastier, longer-running and more
entertaining than the one made famous by Boss Hogg and the Dukes of
Hazzard.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there's the problem of financing. Movies are expensive
propositions. They require the support of wealthy investors.
</P>
<P>
   I'm personally acquainted with a nice couple who recently came
into $8.25 million. Jaron and Deena Norberg received the cash from
Maricopa County to settle a lawsuit they'd filed after their son
died horribly at the hands of Joe's guards.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, even if some of that $8.25 million was used to solve
money problems for producers of the ``cute or fun'' movie they'd
still be left with a tricky casting dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Who'll play Scott Norberg? &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at &QL; 
Ed.Montini &LR; Arizona Republic.com or at (602) 444-8978. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
