<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HELLING-TEX </SLUG>
 HELLING WORKING TO SEPARATE LABOR ROLE FROM
PITCHING (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The clock is ticking toward another labor
showdown between baseball owners and players. When it happens _
later this season or in the off-season _ Rangers pitcher Rick
Helling plans to be in the middle of it.
</P>
<P>
   Helling is beginning his second season as a member of the Major
League Players Association's executive board, which is directly
involved in negotiations with the owners about the Basic Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with my education, I've always kind of been a
lawyer,'' said Helling, who graduated from Stanford in 1993. ``I
like to argue. I like to be involved in the discussions. I'm not
worried about what might happen. I'll be on the front lines, and
that's exactly how I want it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Basic Agreement expires after this season, although the
players' association has an option to extend it through the 2001
season. Helling said ``more chances than not'' the union will
exercise that option.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, a new agreement must be negotiated within the next
two years, and baseball owners and players have never reached an
agreement without an owners' lockout or a players' strike.
</P>
<P>
   The last time that happened was in 1994, when the players walked
out in August, and the World Series was canceled. But Helling said
he thinks the two sides can reach an agreement without a strike or
lockout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not to say it will be easy, but I don't think the
players and the owners want to go through what happened last
time,'' Helling said. ``On the owners' side, a new television deal
is coming up. They need to go to the networks and say `There's
labor peace for the next six or seven years; you don't have to
worry about a strike.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The players, we know how hard it was to get back the fans, and
we don't want to have to go through it again. Both sides want to
get the best deal possible, but there are reasons to get it done
and make it as peaceful and as smooth as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would also like to avoid an ugly situation similar
to the one that happened the last time one of their best starting
pitchers was heavily involved in labor matters.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown was pitching for the Rangers in 1994 when he was the
team's player representative and on the union executive board. But
after winning a combined 36 games in 1992-93, Brown went 7-9 with a
4.82 earned-run average in 1994, easily his worst season in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   He became a free agent after the season, and the Rangers
mercurial ace,] refused to even offer arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're looking at different personalities,'' Rangers
general manager Doug Melvin said. ``Rick is a pretty level-headed
guy. You can sit down and have a good conversation with him on
anything. Rick is the kind of guy who understands both sides,
management and player.''
</P>
<P>
   Other labor warriors have been able to keep high-level
negotiations from affecting their performances. Pitcher David Cone
has long been a high-ranking member of the union, and, in 1994, he
won the Cy Young Award while pitching for the Kansas City Royals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Rick can handle it,'' said pitching coach Dick Bosman,
who served eight years as a player representative and was once
released by Oakland A's owner Charlie Finley because of his union
duties. ``\RHelling\S knows it's business as usual when you come to
the ballpark. I don't think players have a lot of problems with
management that they used to. They realize it's business and
nothing personal.''
</P>
<P>
   There are a couple of significant differences between Helling
and Brown. First, Helling doesn't have the double duty of being the
Rangers' player representative. Tim Crabtree handles that job.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Helling has avoided the hostile salary disputes Brown
went through with the Rangers every off-season. Brown went through
two bitter arbitration hearings with the club and, before that,
staged a one-day walkout in spring training in a salary dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Helling has avoided two years of arbitration by signing a
three-year contract with the Rangers before last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it took us a day and a half to get it done,'' Melvin
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see \Rthe union role\S affecting me,'' Helling said.
``I'm pretty good at separating baseball from the business side and
from family. Whatever happens in the meeting room or at home, once
I step on that field, it's all baseball. It's all part of the
business. The owners are trying to get the best deal they can;
we're trying to get the best deal we can.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
