r s BC-BBN-ASTROS-TEXDESPITE ASTROSKEEPLIDONSPENDIN   02-29 1065
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-TEX </SLUG>
 DESPITE STADIUM REVENUE, ASTROS KEEP LID ON
SPENDING (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By SIMON
GONZALEZ c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ There's a modern baseball theorem that goes
something like this: When you get a new stadium, you go on a
spending spree.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and the Cleveland Indians became contenders after
moving into state-of-the-art, revenue-generating ballparks that
allowed them to bump payrolls.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners upgraded to the high-rent district midway
through last season, then spent the off-season signing six free
agents, including John Olerud and Aaron Sele.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers are moving into new digs this year. To
celebrate, they traded for Juan Gonzalez and offered him a
megabucks contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Astros also have a new ballpark this season. They're
abandoning the Astrodome, the mausoleum of a stadium they called
home since 1965, and moving into Enron Field, a modern facility
with all the bells and whistles that add up to tremendous new
revenue streams.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros have won the National League Central three
consecutive seasons, and intend to contend again this year. But
they won't do it the way the Rangers and Indians did, and the way
the Mariners and Tigers plan.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the increased revenue that comes with a new
ballpark, the Astros didn't significantly bump their payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even with new stadiums and the prospect of sellout crowds, we
can't afford a payroll that some of the major-market clubs can
afford,'' Astros general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``As we move
into the new stadium, our commitment to being competitive is still
there. But we are not committed to the continuation of deficit
spending and losing $10-15 million every year.''
</P>
<P>
   By spending more on payroll _ it was about $52 million last
year, seventh in the league _ than the Astrodome generated in
revenue, the Astros put a championship-caliber team on the field.
But the years of deficit spending forced them to be the antithesis
of other clubs with new ballparks. Instead of bringing in
high-profile players, the Astros had to get rid of them.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hampton, a 22-game winner, was traded to the New York Mets.
Carl Everett, a 25-homer, 27-steal center fielder, went to the
Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   The two players can become free agents after this season, and
even though projections show revenues increasing as much as 60
percent because of the move to Enron Field, the club couldn't
afford to keep them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We spent the money before we received it,'' Hunsicker said.
``As we move into the new stadium our revenues are going to
significantly increase, but our expenses have already exceeded our
revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Astros' divisional rivals improved.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds, who won 96 games last season and finished a
game behind the Astros, added Ken Griffey Jr. The St. Louis
Cardinals rebuilt their pitching staff. The Chicago Cubs traded for
pitcher Ismael Valdes and second baseman Eric Young.
</P>
<P>
   Even the division's small-market clubs, the Pittsburgh Pirates
and Milwaukee Brewers, made moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``In sports, it's what have you done for me lately,'' Astros
second baseman Craig Biggio said. ``We've won the last three years,
but that's over with. This division has gotten better. Every team
in this division is better and has a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   A cursory analysis indicates the Astros, after replacing proven
stars Hampton and Everett with youngsters such as Octavio Dotel and
Roger Cedeno, aren't better. Thus, the trendy pick in the Central
this year is a team other than the defending champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be a way of life in Houston to be the underdog,''
Hunsicker said. ``Year in and year out, we don't seem to get a lot
of national recognition. People seem to underestimate what we're
doing. But we've found a way to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were supposed to be headed for a down year in '98
after 19-game winner Darryl Kile departed as a free agent. Instead,
they won a club-record 102 games.
</P>
<P>
   They were supposed to slip again last season when they couldn't
re-sign Randy Johnson. They won 97 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are again,'' Hunsicker said. ``They're down on us
again. Maybe this will be the year. You keep playing the red on a
roulette wheel, and sooner or later red is going to come up. It's
impossible to win every year. But we've certainly beat the odds
recently, and I have a lot of confidence in this ballclub.''
</P>
<P>
   With good reason. Biggio is back, and so is first baseman Jeff
Bagwell. Biggio widely is considered the best second baseman in the
league, and Bagwell and Mark McGwire are considered the two best at
first.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros like the idea of the speedy Cedeno batting behind
Biggio at the top of the order, and they like the potential of a
right-field platoon with Richard Hidalgo and Daryle Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, they feel they've added the equivalent of an impact free
agent with the return of left fielder Moises Alou, who batted .312
with 38 homers and 124 runs batted in during 1998 then missed last
season because of a knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling about Alou is he's one of the premier players in
the game,'' manager Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros expect Alou to more than compensate for the loss of
Everett, and for the offense to be as productive as any in the
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' cautioned Bagwell, ``offense is not the problem in this
division; it's pitching. Whoever pitches the best is going to win.
Everybody's going to score runs; everybody's going to hit home
runs. It's who's going to keep the opposition from scoring less.
That's going to be the key.''
</P>
<P>
   That's where the Astros could miss Hampton, who was 22-4 with a
2.90 earned-run average and threw 239 innings in 34 starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big thing about Hampy is that's a lot of innings we
lost,'' Biggio said. ``That's the thing that's going to be hard to
replace. But somebody else is going to step up and fill the void.
That's kind of the way this team is. We'll go out there and deal
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been easier to deal with if revenue from the new
stadium had allowed the Astros to sign a free agent or two, or at
least keep the players they were forced to trade. Still, they're
not ready to concede the Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have a good team,'' Biggio said. ``We have a chance,
and that's you can ask for when you break camp.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
