<SLUG> BC-BBN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING HIS PITCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ The clubhouse jocularity is gone. In its
place is a serious, business approach. And the Dodgers hope also
returned is the focus that helped make Carlos Perez one of the
up-and-coming left-handers in the game when he was with Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   His arm angle is higher, and in his case, higher is better. The
velocity of his fastball has returned to the high 80s, his control
is improved and his physical condition is the best it's been in
years.
</P>
<P>
   But there is this other side of Perez. The side that breeds
skepticism. It can be described in many ways, but nothing
illustrates it like the numbers:
</P>
<P>
   Perez was 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA in the first year of a
three-year, $15.6 million contract. And he is owed $12.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're optimistic, but it's not blind optimism,'' said general
manager Kevin Malone, who signed Perez to the multiyear deal. ``The
optimism is based on real issues that have been addressed. One, his
request for help. Two, his humility. Three, the way he worked in
the offseason. Four would be his focus. Five would be the way he
pitched in winter ball and six is that he showed up here in good
shape with a great attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds pretty good. But how can you forget the 2-10 record with
a 7.43 ERA? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is not an ordinary spring training for a guy who has two
years left on a large contract. Perez isn't working to be ready at
the end of spring training. He needed to be ready two weeks ago,
when pitchers and catchers reported to camp. He is guaranteed
nothing, which is also what most people think he'll deliver.
Instead, all eyes are on Orel Hershiser, signed as a free agent
during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was quickly assigned to the bullpen, insurance in case
Perez falters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to show my (butt) out there and everything will take
care of itself,'' Perez, 29, said. ``I'm fine. My mind is so clean.
It's what I need. I already forgot the past. They already paid for
it and I don't like to make money that way. I like to do my job. I
like to show what I've got. I feel happy when I win when my games.
I feel relaxed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be happy because I make money. Money, to me,
doesn't mean (anything). I remember two years in a row when I made
$160,000 a year. Every time I would shove my (butt) on the mound I
was doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   That was before Perez went 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The primary reason for the optimism (other than it being spring
training) is based on reports from the Dodgers personnel who
visited Perez in the Dominican Republic during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching coach Claude Osteen, assistant general manager Bill
Geivett, farm director Jerry Weinstein, senior vice president Tommy
Lasorda, senior scouting advisor Don Welke, pitching coordinator
Jim Benedict and strength and conditioning coordinator Todd
Claussen each met with Perez.
</P>
<P>
   According to all, Perez was pitching well, working hard and
intent on proving the club didn't make a mistake in signing him to
a three-year deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely see a difference and I think anybody will really
see a difference between last year and this year, just in terms of
his arm action and his delivery,'' Geivett said. ``He really looked
like he was pushing the ball a lot last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you're looking at a pitcher like this that's had a
very good amount of success at the major-league level, they're
going to go through some rocky times, or the guy's going to have a
bad year. This guy's shown what he can do at the major-league
level. It's just a matter of getting back to that. It's not like
this guy's never done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers catching prospect Angel Pena caught Perez last seaso and
said there's no comparison to how he threw in winter ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used the fastball more and nobody could touch it because
they were waiting for the changeup,'' Pena said. ``He threw the
fastball, inside, up and away, and he was doing great. The last
time he threw 92, 93. I looked to the guy with the (radar) gun and
said, `God.' `'
</P>
<P>
   Perez's fastball is average, at best, but his changeup and
split- finger fastball were so good with the Expos, it didn't
matter his fastball rarely broke 90 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the fastball reached 80 mph and made the changeup
ineffective, shattered his confidence and left him so frustrated he
pummeled a water cooler in the dugout after being taken out of a
game.
</P>
<P>
   It was a clip that was on every sportscast in North America but
not the only off-field news Perez made. He missed a start in May
because of a knee injury. He said he hurt the knee shagging fly
balls on Montreal's rock-hard artificial turf. The Dodgers thought
differently, particularly that Perez injured his knee when he fell
during a night on the town. Workers at the team hotel said Perez
didn't arrive until the early-morning hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I saw right away when I was in the Dominican is he's
much more focused,'' Osteen said. ``He looks better physically. I
know he's in better shape. I told him, 'You have to keep your focus
and keep your priorities in line. You've got one thing to do and
that's win a job.' I think he's pretty much resigned to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the 2-10 record with a 7.43 ERA starting to fade from your
memory? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perez said there are things he will do differently this season.
His hope is he's doing it for the Dodgers instead of the
Albuquerque Dukes.
</P>
<P>
   Amidst the failure, the flawed mechanics and the pressure to
perform on a club expected to contend for a title, Perez got
confused. His personal life was flying around twice the speed of
his fastball. He was readying for the birth of his second child and
his ineptness on the mound, coupled with his exorbitant contract,
had folks chirping in his ear constantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay away from some people. I want some people to
leave me alone, to let me work,'' said Perez. ``I'm not used to
having so many people all over when I wear my uniform. I'm growing
up, I'm learning at the same time. I think if they let me do my
stuff, like I'm supposed, I'll do good. I know people want to help
you, but when you need to concentrate, you need to concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough when you warm up in a bullpen to pitch in a game.
It's tough when you have somebody around you and they tell you some
stuff. I never saw that and I don't want to see that. After I
finish a game, they can come to me and tell me how to do this, how
to do this. I've already talked with some people here. Things are
going to be different.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter where he turns, Perez will hear it. Even if he has a
scoreless, even hitless, spring, 1999 is always lurking. In case
you haven't heard, Perez was 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA. It'll take a
while for anyone to forget it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
