r s BC-HKN-STARS-MARSHALL-TE MARSHALLHOPESTOREG   02-29 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-MARSHALL-TEX </SLUG>
 PLAYING WITHOUT PAIN, MARSHALL HOPES TO
REGAIN FORM (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By JEFF
CAPLAN c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The clock is ticking on Grant Marshall's season. But
now, for the first span since last season's NHL Western Conference
finals, time might be on his side.
</P>
<P>
   On the lonesome road to recovery from two groin injuries,
Marshall is finally playing pain free. It has taken nine grueling
months. In Game 7 of the conference finals, he tore his left groin,
which agonizingly forced him out of the Stanley Cup Finals and the
first four games of this season. Two games into his return,
Marshall shredded his right groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a bit of a write-off year when it comes to my
body, but hopefully there is a turnaround coming down the
stretch,'' said Marshall, who has four points, all assists, in 30
games. He has posted three assists in the past four games but has a
plus-minus rating of minus-8.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Ken Hitchcock can live with few points from Marshall. What
Hitchcock needs is the return of the abrasive and brash play he
demands from his fifth-year checking right winger. Last season,
Marshall played in all 82 games and was named the team's
most-improved player. He set career highs in games, goals and
points while improving his role as the team's on-ice lightning rod.
</P>
<P>
   But, a groin injury can zap a player, and Marshall has been
dealing with two of them. The injury can hamper everything from
fighting off checks to chasing loose pucks to outracing opponents.
It all spirals downward to diminishing physical play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mentally, it's got to be tough because you want to do a lot
more things than you can when your body tells you no,'' center Mike
Modano said. ``The groin is such a key thing for skaters and hockey
players in general. He'll be a key guy when he's healthy and really
strong for us down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the demand for Marshall to regain his aggressive, physical
form is there now. Marshall's job description calls for him to draw
the undivided attention of his opponents on every shift. When he
does that, he creates time and space for his linemates.
</P>
<P>
   Those are Hitchcock's demands. Demands the coach said Marshall
has been slow to fulfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see Grant Marshall at the top of his game, it's when
you know that the other team is reacting to what he's doing on the
ice. They're having to pay special attention to him as a physical
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what the team needs for us to win. He has to have the
other team looking over their shoulder, worried about him where he
is on the ice, reckless. That's the type of player we need. I don't
think he's there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Marshall wants to disagree, but he has no argument to the
contrary.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my role and lately I think I've been doing that pretty
good,'' he said. ``I've missed so many games due to my groin
injuries, but you know he's \RHitchcock is\S right. I've got to
compete. I've got to battle. I've got to make sure they know that
when they get hit they're going to be in for a war. I'm playing
better, I'm slowly coming, but I've got a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Time is ticking and Marshall isn't naive. He knows forwards Joe
Nieuwendyk, Jere Lehtinen and Brian Skrudland are expected back in
the lineup by playoff time. The addition of players also
necessitates subtraction.
</P>
<P>
   Time ran out on him last season. With 19 games remaining,
Marshall has ample time, who of late has played on the fourth line
with Aaron Gavey and Jamie Wright, to excavate his complete game
for another run at the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I went through with my groin is very frustrating. Guys
bug me a little bit about not scoring, and they know I'm trying,
I'm working hard,'' Marshall said. ``You've got to prove yourself
every night, but I'm not worried. I know that this team needs me.
I'm going to make sure I have my spot, and, if I don't, then I'll
work hard to get it back.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
