<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAT STUN KNICKS, 85-76 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was late in the New York Knicks' blissful first
quarter, when they were making off with the milk money of the Miami
Heat, a team turned weakling without Alonzo Mourning, and a loose
ball trickled toward the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Childs gave a half-hearted chase, bent halfway to reach
it, and watched it skip out of bounds. It was hard to manufacture
desperation when the Knicks were on their way to a 20-point lead
early in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was so easy, it was too easy. After the Knicks rubbed
their hands together as if sitting down for a feast in the first
quarter, they finished looking like full-bellied diners as players
like the aging Dan Majerle _ bad back and all _ tossed their bodies
on the floor for loose balls.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Heat found inspiration in its effort and determination
from its defense, it unearthed a 20-7 run in the closing minutes of
the second quarter and took the lead for good in the closing split
second of the third. The dramatic twist in this game left the
Knicks in disbelief as they exited the American Airlines Arena with
a 85-76 loss to Miami, which was without Mourning and Voshon
Lenard.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first quarter, no one played well offensively,''
Coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``I give the Heat a lot of credit. We
have been struggling since the All-Star break, and tonight was no
different. Anyone that thought it was going to be easy when we have
a 20-point lead was kidding themselves. But obviously, I still
thought we were going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   It seemed unfathomable, but Latrell Sprewell had seven
turnovers, and Allan Houston made just 5 of 13 shots around Majerle
and Bruce Bowen. It seemed unthinkable, but P.J. Brown held Patrick
Ewing to just 8 points and Kurt Thomas allowed Clarence
Weatherspoon to grab 12 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The defense of Tim Hardaway (3 steals), the offense of Jamal
Mashburn (24 points) and bench production of Weatherspoon (14
points) brought about the Knicks' collapse. The Knicks, who began
shooting 61.9 percent in the first quarter, ended the game by
hitting just 18 of their last 63 shots. Another lead blown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we kind of relaxed a little bit, but they just
out-worked us tonight,'' said Houston, who finished with 15 points.
``I think that's what it came down to. They played hard, got the
loose balls and made the extra effort. That's how they got back
into the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Knicks never responded. Not one star came through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played terrible,'' said Ewing, who was 3 for 10. ``We won
the first quarter, and they won the rest of the game. They made
everything tough for us. And we didn't do the same at the other
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough loss. I'm disappointed that we lost because this
is a game we should have won. We stopped playing and they didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were faced with the Heat, a team led by Hardaway and
Majerle. This was the core of the Heat's firepower, two superstars
on the downside of their careers. They were the ones who had to
make up for the 34 points per game Mourning and Lenard contribute
nightly.
</P>
<P>
   In the game's opening 14 minutes, the Knicks had no sympathy for
them. They had their own injuries _ with Marcus Camby and Charlie
Ward having missed the last three weeks _ and had managed.
Suddenly, it was obvious which team had the safety net built into
the roster.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks could lean on Kurt Thomas, John Wallace, Chris Childs
for support. Pat Riley stared down at his spare parts and saw Bowen
_ fresh off the waiver wire _ Anthony Carter and Duane Causwell.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the Knicks were merciless in attacking the depleted
Heat. Demoralizing Mashburn, Larry Johnson hit his first five shots
and scored 13 first-quarter points while Thomas and Sprewell took
turns getting their offense together. By the time the second
quarter was 3 minutes old, the Knicks had a gaudy 20-point lead and
were on their way to an uncommonly easy victory in a back-to-back
game situation.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Heat started to intensify its effort on defense, and
the whole game changed. The Miami players were double-teaming and
putting pressure on the ball, hovering and putting a body on their
man, en route to a 1-point lead at the end of the third period.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were stunned. From the three-minute mark of the third
quarter until 10 minutes were left in the fourth, the Knicks missed
11 shots in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Heat started a 20-7 run in the second quarter while the
Knicks seemed blissfully unaware that their lead was being chopped
to bits. After shooting 61.9 percent in the first quarter, the
Knicks were held to just 25 percent in the second quarter. After
taking such a commanding lead, the Knicks were hanging on to a
43-37 lead at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks needed one star _ any star _ to come through. How
about Ewing? He was either exhausted by his second game in two
nights or suffering a letdown without Mourning to inspire that
Georgetown kick. Houston was having trouble getting a good look and
Sprewell going two possessions without a turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had to throw out the life preserver to the Knicks. He
sprang free of Mashburn for his seventh point of the third quarter
when he delivered a timely 3-pointer after the Heat had cut the
Knicks' lead to 3 points on Mashburn's jumper. Johnson gave the
Knicks a 60-54 lead with 3 minutes left in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But the Heat came back to take the lead by the end of the period
and went on from there to bury the Knicks. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
