r s BC-BKC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     02-29 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 TUBBS ISN'T READY TO TRY RETIREMENT (For
use by NYTimes News Service clients) By JIM REEVES c.2000 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ You're 63, or 64, or maybe even 65 years old
_ you're darn sure not telling because you've learned, by now, that
what you say can and almost always will be used against you _ and
the only thing you've ever done, only thing you've ever wanted to
do, is coach basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Oh sure, everybody knows Billy Tubbs loves to play golf, but
who's kidding who? It's hardly the same, you know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends who should know tell me golf is not nearly as fun when
you can do it anytime you want to,'' you're always telling folks
who ask why you don't just walk away from all the aggravation and
spend the rest of your life on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   And danged if it doesn't seem like every other person is
suddenly asking that question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only thing anybody wants to talk about these days,'' you tell
a visitor who drops by your office one day last week. ``Shoot, I
can't imagine not coaching, not doing anything. Even worse, my wife
can't imagine it either.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, since when has Billy Tubbs ever walked ``away'' from
aggravation?
</P>
<P>
   You've always been the aggravator, never the ``aggravatee.''
You're the straw that stirs the stink, and proud of it. Mellowing
in your old age? Forget about it. Smarter maybe, but hardly mellow.
``Never'' mellow.
</P>
<P>
   You're preening a bit in your office in a new golf shirt,
sucking in what gut you have, which isn't much, ready to tell
anyone who wants to listen that the world looks the same through
your eyes, which, in case anyone's wondering, remain cataract free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still get my thousand miles a year in running,'' you point
out, tossing the challenge on the coffee table casually, as if to
say, ``And how many miles did you run today, friend?''
</P>
<P>
   So why is everybody suddenly so interested in how much longer
your contract runs? Since when has that ever been a big deal in
your six years at TCU?
</P>
<P>
   OK, you say, let's lay all the cards on the table. You've heard
the rumors, the ones that hint that Billy Tubbs will finish out his
contract _ and how long that runs is another state secret; ``two or
three more years,'' you say casually _ and then walk off into the
sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever started that rumor, though, obviously didn't run it by
you first. The question that has to be in your mind, though you
don't come right out and voice it, is whether or not it originated
in the athletic director's office.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't helped that athletic director Eric Hyman basically
refuses to discuss your situation at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be the TCU coach as long as TCU wanted me to be the
coach,'' you say vaguely. ``If TCU didn't want me to be the coach,
then I don't want to be the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   And why wouldn't TCU want you to be the coach? Sure, your Frogs
(16-13) are winding down an un-Tubbs-like season, but this will be
the first time in four years that your team hasn't won 20 games and
you've still never had a losing season since coming to TCU in
1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter. You keep score a little differently than most
folks. For Billy Tubbs, this is a bad year. Period. No excuses. You
began thinking about how to make it better next year a long time
ago.
</P>
<P>
   But these rumors aren't about performance. They're about
comfort. When the new administration _ new president, new athletic
director _ came in two years ago, there were changes, some subtle,
some not so subtle.
</P>
<P>
   The comfort level that was there with the old regime
disappeared. This isn't particularly unusual. You've been through
changes like this before. Philosophies change, you shrug, and where
you fit into the grand scheme of things can change, too.
</P>
<P>
   A new AD comes in, he's naturally thinking about putting his own
people into place. You did the same thing with a whole new staff of
assistant coaches when you arrived at TCU. Had nothing to do with
how the previous assistants had performed. You just wanted people
you knew and were comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, just maybe, you're not Hyman's kind of coach. Certainly
he has never sat you down and told you that you were. Maybe the
Tubbs in-your-face, smart-mouth style of coaching makes him
uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   If this seems a little ungrateful, considering the state of
Horned Frog basketball when you came here, and the fact that you
basically put TCU back onto the athletic map long before football
``wunderkind'' Dennis Franchione arrived on the scene, that's not
something you fret about. Or at least that's what you'd have
everyone believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't need pats on the back or somebody to make over me,''
you half-growl when the subject of appreciation comes up. ``I
search myself out, and I know when I'm doing things right and when
I've made a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to feel comfortable within yourself about anything
that goes on. I know whether I'm doing right or doing my best. I
don't need somebody running around, jacking me up all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this unsettled feeling that's been hanging around lately
has gotten so strong, you've actually thought about leaving to
coach somewhere else. Not quit, mind you. But to keep coaching
somewhere else ...
</P>
<P>
   It's just that you and wife Pat both love TCU and Fort Worth so
much. Leaving at this stage is really the last thing you want to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, taking TCU into Conference USA after the 2001 season is
the kind of challenge Billy Tubbs has always relished. This step
will be the biggest TCU has ever made, and you wonder if everyone
else even begins to realize the difficulties that lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a conference that could produce a national
champion,'' you whisper, as if afraid a spy might be eavesdropping
outside the door.
</P>
<P>
   You pause a moment, thinking this next thought out carefully, as
if afraid that saying it aloud might somehow jinx it. But what the
heck. It's not like you've ever been afraid to say what's on your
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't see that I have to put a limit that I'm only
going to coach so many years,'' you say, circling back to the
original question. ``But if I do, then here's my limit: If we win
the national tournament, I'm through.''
</P>
<P>
   Now how could anybody argue with that?
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
