<SLUG> BC-BBC-UPDATE-TEX </SLUG>
 PITCHING AIDS TEXAS CLIMB IN POLLS (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) By WHIT CANNING c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Among other achievements in a long and
distinguished career, Texas baseball coach Augie Garrido has become
a master of the thought-enhancing deadpan response.
</P>
<P>
   So, Augie, do you really plan to maintain this 2.05 staff
earned-run average throughout the entire season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, of course, Garrido also notes that the season has
31/2 months remaining ... assuming that you intend to still be
playing in June, when the College World Series opens. Many a
capricious wind will blow between now and then, but for now the
Texas pitching staff looks like a fistful of aces.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: When the Longhorns (13-3, 3-0 Big 12) completed a
three-game sweep of Iowa State with a 4-0 victory Sunday behind
Phil Seibel (4-0), it was the staff's fourth shutout of the season.
The last time a Texas team had that many was when the 1994 team
managed five over a full season.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the seventh, Seibel gave way to closer Charlie
Thames, who picked up a win and two saves last week. Thames (2-0)
now has five saves and a 0.00 ERA over 221/3 innings, allowing 13
hits, two walks, an unearned run, and racking up 19 strikeouts.
Opponents are hitting .169 against him.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Texas won, 7-1, behind Beau Hale, who has already
pitched a no-hitter this year. But Garrido liked the Saturday game,
when D.J. Jones got roughed up a little but the Longhorns won
anyway, 13-5. There was a nice contribution from sophomore
pitcher-outfielder Ryan France, who made his first college homer a
grand slam and went 4-for-4 with six runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to win games in different ways now, and that's
encouraging,'' Garrido said. ``We're playing defense well, and
we're more productive with the bats.''
</P>
<P>
   A key figure in both areas is junior second baseman Tommy
Nicholson, who is hitting .410 and has a 1.000 fielding average on
77 chances. Career-wise, he has seven errors in his past 390
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked fourth and eighth in the two major polls, Texas will prep
for a weekend series at Missouri with a journey to Houston tonight
to face the Cougars (13-3), who are ranked third and fifth and
outscored LSU, 31-11, in a three-game sweep in Baton Rouge over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're looking forward to getting us in a
Cougar-friendly environment,'' said Garrido, whose team won two of
three from UH earlier in the year in Austin. The mound assignment
will go to Dax Leone who was Texas' most effective pitcher down the
stretch last year but is trying to overcome a sore arm.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor (11-3, 2-1) is also strong on the hill and ranked fifth
and 16th after winning two of three from Oklahoma State last
weekend. Chad Hawkins pitched a complete game in the opener, giving
up three hits, walking one and striking out nine but losing a 2-1
duel to preseason All-American Matt Smith. All three runs were
unearned. A 13-1 Baylor victory in the second game was halted by
the 12-run rule after seven innings, with the win going to Kyle
Evans (4-0). The Bears won the third game, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M (8-7, 3-0) collected 41 hits and 37 runs in a
three-game sweep of Kansas State as Jason Gremminger went 6-for-9
with three homers and 11 RBI. The Aggies will face the Bears this
weekend, with the Friday game scheduled to be played in College
Station and the Saturday-Sunday games in Waco.
</P>
<P>
   Still missing staff ace Brandon Roberson, who is rehabilitating
an injured arm, Texas Tech (8-8, 1-2) dropped two of three at home
to Missouri. About the only place the Raiders aren't hurting is the
third spot in the batting order, where designated hitter Chaz
Eiguren is hitting .500 (31-of-62) with seven home runs, 33 RBI and
a .952 slugging percentage. Over the past four games, he has hit
.619 with five homers and 16 RBI.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
