<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 RANGERS SIGN TWO CUBAN INFIELDERS (For use
by NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ The Rangers took a plunge into the
potentially lucrative Cuban baseball market yesterday by signing
infielders Jorge Diaz and Osmani Garcia. Both defected from Cuba in
1998 and were members of the Cuban national team. Diaz, a second
baseman who turns 25 on March 16, is much closer to the major
leagues. He signed a Triple-A contract with a $50,000 bonus and was
invited to big-league camp. The Rangers say he could be their
starting second baseman at Triple A and play in the majors later
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty close,'' Rangers scouting director Chuck McMichael
said. ``He does all the things you'd want from a second baseman.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz, who is hoping to get his work visa and be here by the
middle of next week, played with the Cuban national team from
1995-97 and spent five seasons in the National Series, Cuba's
regular season. He had a career batting average of .283 and is
considered an above-average defensive player, McMichael said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, a 25-year-old third baseman who received a $25,000
bonus, played in the National Series for five seasons and with the
national team in 1997. He was a career .300 hitter and was the
league MVP in 1995. The Rangers want him to start at Class A and
develop some power.
</P>
<P>
   The two players left Cuba by boat in 1998 and went to Nicaragua
but were denied residency. They were granted residency in Costa
Rica last February and have been working out in the Dominican
Republic since October.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are very hungry and eager to prove they can play,''
McMichael said.
</P>
<P>
   The signings aren't considered on the same level as the New York
Yankees signing Orlando Hernandez or the Tampa Bay Devil Rays
signing Rolando Arrojo. But it's the first time the Rangers have
signed former players from the Cuban national team. McMichael said
at least five other teams were competing for their services
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows me something, that we were able to get some guys
that everyone else wanted,'' said first baseman Rafael Palmeiro,
who was born in Cuba and follows that country's baseball program.
``It shows we're trying to do the best we can to stay competitive
with other teams.''
Rogers takes lead Rangers manager Johnny Oates isn't ready to
announce his Opening Day starter, but he has put Kenny Rogers in
that position. Oates said yesterday Rogers will start Friday in the
exhibition opener against the Minnesota Twins.
</P>
<P>
   Oates has set up his spring training to have Rogers lead the
way, followed by Rick Helling on Saturday against the Cincinnati
Reds, Darren Oliver on Sunday against the Reds and Esteban Loaiza
on Monday against the Boston Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Perisho and Mark Clark, the leading candidates to fill in
for Justin Thompson as the fifth starter, are scheduled to pitch
Tuesday against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays. Rogers follows them and
precedes Helling, which puts him in position to be the Rangers' No.
1 starter.
Hoping for Oliva Former Cincinnati Reds slugger Tony Perez will be
the first Cuban-born player in the Hall of Fame when he's inducted
this summer. Rafael Palmeiro is hoping for a second one today when
the Veteran's Committee considers former Twins outfielder Tony
Oliva.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm an Oliva guy,'' Palmeiro said. ``He won some batting
titles in his time. I'm not aware of his career numbers, but, from
everything I heard, he should be in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thrilled when Tony got in. He waited a long time, and
you're not sure how people will look at him. But I was hoping he'd
get in.''
Venafro throws Rangers reliever Mike Venafro, sidelined with a
strained ligament in his left middle finger, began throwing again
yesterday. Venafro was able to keep the finger from bothering him
by taping it tightly to the index finger.
</P>
<P>
   Venafro is hoping to throw off a mound next week and be ready to
pitch by Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year after the strike, pitchers had just three weeks to
get ready,'' Venafro said. ``We still have five weeks, so I should
be all right.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
