<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN'S-HOLY-WAR-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN TURNS UP THE HEAT ON BUSH, RELIGIOUS RIGHT  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (TIMELY for Tuesday, Feb. 29 primaries)   (This 500-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VIRGINIA BEACH _ Senator John McCain dramatically turned up the
heat in the battle for the Republican presidential nomination
Monday, attacking the influential religious right as hypocrites in
a speech described as ``astounding'' and ``epoch-making.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to a rapturous audience at the Frank W. Cox High School
in Virginia Beach, Va., on the eve of three crucial Republican
primaries, McCain threw down the gauntlet to his rival for the
party's presidential nomination, George W. Bush, and reiterated his
claim to the political legacy of Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friends, I am a Reagan Republican who will defeat Al
Gore,'' he said to deafening applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately'' _ he went on, as the audience rose to its feet
_ ``Governor Bush is a Pat Robertson Republican who will lose to Al
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, the leader of the Christian Coalition, allied himself
with Bush at the start of the presidential campaign and has made
recorded phone calls to voters in several key primary states,
casting doubts on McCain's conservative credentials. Virginia Beach
is Robertson's base of operations.
</P>
<P>
   In words that sounded not just like a bid for his party's
nomination, but like a bid for the presidency, McCain said
``neither party should be defined by pandering to the outer reaches
of American politics and the agents of intolerance, whether they be
Louis Farrakhan or Al Sharpton (black activists) on the left or Pat
Robertson or Jerry Falwell on the right.''
</P>
<P>
   (Falwell, a television evangelist, distinguished himself last
year by condemning the Tellytubbies toys for encouraging a gay
lifestyle because Tinky Winky carries a handbag.)
</P>
<P>
   McCain also set out to seize the high ground of Republican
conservatism from Bush, using the word ``conservative'' no fewer
than 16 times in his 15 minutes speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a pro-life, pro-family, fiscal conservative and advocate
of a strong defense,'' he said. ``And yet, Pat Robertson, Jerry
Falwell and a few Washington leaders of the pro-life movement call
me an unacceptable presidential candidate. They distort my pro-life
positions and smear the reputation of my supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican senator from Arizona was making his one and only
campaign speech in Virginia on the eve of today's (Tuesday's)
primary in the state, at the start of a day which would take him
across the United States from east to west via North Dakota and
Washington State and on to California.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota and Washington hold caucuses and a primary today
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Until three weeks ago, Bush had been forecast to win an easy
victory in Virginia, a relatively conservative state, and McCain
had had no plans to campaign here.
</P>
<P>
   This changed after McCain's victory in Michigan last week, and
Monday's speech in Virginia Beach reflected a last-minute decision
to make one major campaign appearance in a state where polls show
the two men in a close race. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 500-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
