<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT IS HAVEL'S HANDPICKED SUCCESSOR, RUMOR CLAIMS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 525-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By ADAM LEBOR  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrives
in Prague next week on a trip that many in the Czech capital see as
a declaration of interest in the country's presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Czech-born Albright is being touted as a possible replacement
for Vaclav Havel, whose term of office ends in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   President Havel, a former dissident turned playwright, was the
leader of the 1989 Velvet Revolution that toppled the Communist
regime and has become the country's best-known ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from Havel, who retains immense admiration both at home
and abroad for his moral qualities, the perpetual squabbling and
infighting of most Czech politicians has left them in low esteem
with the public and there are no obvious successors to him.
</P>
<P>
   Havel told Albright a year and a half ago that he wanted her to
replace him, according to a report in Time magazine Monday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials denied that Albright, who speaks fluent Czech,
was interested in the post. She has been approached several times
by senior officials of her native land as a potential presidential
candidate, but has always refused, said her spokesman, James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has dismissed it, although she is certainly flattered that
that the Czechs would consider her for the post of president of her
native land. She has never given this serious consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   With three years of President Havel's term left to run, it's too
early to consider the U.S. secretary of state as a serious
presidential candidate, said Prague-based sociologist Ivan Gabal,
who has met her several times.
</P>
<P>
   Still there is nationwide goodwill towards Albright, both for
her Czech origins and because of her role in integrating the
central European nation into NATO. The Czech Republic, together
with Hungary and Poland, joined the alliance last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is definitely a serious person, but it's not on the agenda
yet. She is known here as the U.S. secretary of state, but not as
someone who would run for presidential office.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she is perceived positively here, as a sympathetic person
because she understands our position in central Europe and very
much helped bring us into NATO,'' said Gabal.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Zantovsky, former Czech ambassador to Washington, said
in Prague that he met last week with Havel and discussed, among
other things, the possibility that Albright might run to succeed
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never made it a secret that I think that Madeleine Albright
could, one day in the future, play a big role in Czech politics,''
Zantovsky said. He stressed that the idea is not new and that it
would not dominate Albright's agenda in the Czech Republic next
week.
</P>
<P>
   In Prague, Havel's chief-policy adviser, Pavel Fischer, told
Time magazine that the idea could be on the agenda: ``It is not
impossible that they will talk about this.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Czech constitution, the president needs to be a
Czech citizen. As Albright was born in the former Czechoslovakia,
to Czech parents, she would have to reclaim her citizenship, which
would be likely to be granted. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
