<SLUG> BC-GM-FOODS-`COVERUP'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. `COVERED UP' SCIENTISTS' WARNINGS ON GM FOODS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 500-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 By JACK O'SULLIVAN  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Prime Minister Tony Blair's fresh skepticism
about GM (genetically-modified) foods was bolstered Monday by
claims that the U.S. government has covered up the safety fears of
its own scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations will support public concerns, acknowledged by
Blair in an article for The Independent on Sunday over the weekend,
that GM foods are potentially harmful.
</P>
<P>
   Internal documents from Washington's food safety agency indicate
U.S. government scientists advised against the assumption that GM
crops are as safe as ones developed by traditional methods.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption of ``substantive equivalence,'' made by the Food
and Drug Administration (FDA), means GM foods face less stringent
testing than, for example, genetically-modified drugs.
</P>
<P>
   It has allowed the speedy commercialization of GM crops through
the U.S., with some products reaching the U.K. market without
further safety checks.
</P>
<P>
   One of the FDA scientists, Dr. Linda Kahl, said the agency was
trying to force the conclusion that the two seed-breeding methods
are equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of genetic engineering and traditional breeding
are different, and according to the technical experts in the
agency, they lead to different risks,'' she said in a memo.
</P>
<P>
   The documents with her comments, and those of other FDA
scientists, were disclosed during a lawsuit demanding tougher
testing, led by Steven Druker, a public-interest lawyer, who Monday
accused the FDA of ``shoddy'' safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   Druker is attending this week's conference in Edinburgh on GM
food safety sponsored by the Organization for Economic Cooperation
and Development.
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``The FDA's own scientists warned that genetic
modification may generate unexpected toxic carcinogens, allergens
and anti-nutritive substances in foods that were not being tested
for.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet the agency covered that up and said it had no information
that GM foods differed in any way from other foods.''
</P>
<P>
   Druker's claims were rejected by the OECD. Patrick Kearns of the
OECD's health and safety department, said: ``Substantive
equivalence is part of a safety assessment. It is about a standard
of safety that means what we are looking for is a similar level of
safety to normal food.''
</P>
<P>
   But he refused to rule out the possibility that GM foods had
created new toxins and carcinogens which were potentially harmful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything in the world is possible. We have to think
about what is reasonably possible and what is unlikely.''
</P>
<P>
   Druker's concerns were backed by mainstream scientists within
the conference, which has brought together 400 GM experts with the
aim of reaching a consensus that can then advise a G7 summit of the
world's leading industrialized nations in Japan in July.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Mowlam, Britain's cabinet office minister, told the
conference she rejected claims that the prime minister had
performed a U-turn on GM safety. ``What we have always said is
there are potentially harmful effects,'' she said. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 500-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
