for a long war whose effects will almost certainly spill over into
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   For Shevardnadze it is a delicate balancing game. Because of the
war Russia needs Georgia's cooperation more than ever before. It
may try to gain this through fostering closer links with Tblisi.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time it can put pressure on Georgia through its
influence on secessionist movements and its position as supplier of
most of Georgia's electricity and gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Georgia fears the sound of Russian guns across its
northern border. &QL; 
