<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORY OVER HORNETS DOESN'T ADD UP
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ When the game finally ended, Sonics coach Paul
Westphal still searched for a few redeeming qualities.
</P>
<P>
   There were none.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were vastly outrebounded. They ended up with 11 fewer
possessions. And, in the ultimate head-scratcher, the Sonics missed
almost as many free throws in the fourth quarter as their opponent
attempted for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed,'' Westphal admitted after the Sonics somehow
escaped from Charlotte Coliseum Monday with an 84-81 victory
against the Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like the numbers didn't add up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were outrebounded 51-41 and made just 12 of 26 free
throws, but they had an equalizer in Gary Payton and enough
defensive pressure to continue what they do as well as any team in
the league.
</P>
<P>
   They find ways to win on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a bad home loss to Atlanta last Friday, the Sonics
began this five-game road trip by holding Charlotte to just 36
percent shooting. The defensive stand coupled with Payton's near
triple-double (32 points, nine rebounds and eight assists) helped
the Sonics improve their record to 17-13 away from KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come in here and be on a long road trip, we needed this
win,'' Payton said. ``We were slapping at the ball and they were
slapping at the ball. And the refs were letting us play. We were
just more active with our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an ugly game in which the team that played the poorest
wasn't necessarily a lock to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this:
</P>
<P>
   -- The Sonics shot 39 percent and were outrebounded 28-17 in the
first half but trailed 47-42 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   -- Charlotte trailed 82-74 with 2:35 left in the game but still
had a chance to tie with 5.9 seconds left because the Sonics missed
nine of 12 free throws in the final frame.
</P>
<P>
   With the Sonics clinging to a three-point lead, the sloppy game
finally ended when Anthony Mason committed Charlotte's 17th
turnover. He threw away the Hornets' chance to tie by heaving a
pass directly at Payton, who allowed the clock to expire while he
held the ball at midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like two teams playing in the mud,'' Sonics guard Brent
Barry said. ``We played terrible in the first half and were just
down five points. We're a team that you don't know what you're
going to get at home. But we're pretty good on the road. It wasn't
pretty, but it's a road win in a tough building.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics had lost three of their last four games on the road.
Still, they have been most competitive on foreign turf, while most
of their lopsided losses have taken place in KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   How important is it that the Sonics continue to be road
warriors?
</P>
<P>
   Even though they play Eastern Conference foes in Orlando, Miami
and Atlanta this week, those games still have playoff implications
in the West. The victory Monday put the Sonics a half game behind
Phoenix for the fifth seed, which means starting the playoffs on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though tonight was kind of in slow motion, we know what
time of year it is,'' Sonics forward Vin Baker said. ``Things
change fast in the standings, so the more we concentrate on taking
care of business the better off we'll be when the real season
begins.''
</P>
<P>
   It appeared the game against the Hornets didn't start for the
Sonics until Payton got hot. He scored 12 of his game-high 32
points in the third quarter when the Sonics took control.
</P>
<P>
   Payton made clutch basket after clutch basket in the second
half. He made five of 11 3-pointers, and his last bomb put the
Sonics ahead by eight points late in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Payton, Barry (13 points on 5-for-11 shooting) and
Rashard Lewis were the only other offensive factors. Lewis' 11
points matched the Hornets' entire bench production.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, I thought we stepped up and played good defense in the
fourth quarter,'' Westphal said. ``Rashard Lewis gave us a boost
off the bench, and Gary made those big 3-pointers like I told him
to. He just wouldn't let us lose.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped that the Hornets played the fourth without Derrick
Coleman, who left in the third with a sprained ankle after
colliding with Payton. Charlotte was intent on feeding Coleman in
the post, and he responded with 14 points and eight rebounds before
the injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed by as many as 10 points in the first half but
were able to use a smaller, quicker lineup to steal the tempo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing Derrick hurt,'' said Charlotte's Eddie Jones, who had
23 points. ``It was an off night. We missed a lot of open shots.
Other than that, I thought we played a pretty good game. But we
can't take anything positive away from this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics weren't exactly trying to win a beauty pageant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to play great and lose,'' Westphal said, ``and I love
to play bad and win. We'll take it.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
