<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' DEFINING MOMENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Phil Jackson has a trick hip, so he's not
exactly up for dancing around the issues. Certainly not when it
comes to tonight's game between his Los Angeles Lakers and the
rival Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   He could have offered up the one-game-in-82 cliches, but there
is simply no use downplaying a game that pits the NBA's two hottest
teams against each other for the final time this season. So the
Lakers coach defined it in precise terms that will do nothing to
calm the hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team that wins this game . . . more than likely
will win the division, at least,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   So there, it's out there: Game 57 on the schedule is officially
the game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it is just one game,'' Jackson said, ``but it has a lot
of emphasis on it. It's one of those 82 that you say there might be
8 or 10 of in a season that are really big games, and this is
certainly one of those. We do have five games, though, between
(today) and next Monday, so we can't get sidetracked by just one
game being the ultimate goal or quest for us in this season.''
</P>
<P>
   It's close, though, for obvious reasons: The Lakers and Blazers
are tied atop the Pacific Division with 45-11 records, tied for the
top seed in the Western Conference, tied for the best record in the
NBA. Even their winning streaks are even, as they've both won 11
straight.
</P>
<P>
   But this Leap Day game's true impact will be felt in late April.
</P>
<P>
   One of these two teams is likely to claim the No. 1 seed in the
West playoffs, and the homecourt advantage that goes with it. By
NBA rules, the other team will fall to No. 3, behind the Midwest
Division winner, and will probably have to face the
defending-champion San Antonio Spurs in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   So far, neither the Lakers nor the Blazers has been able to
shake the other off their tail, so it's no wonder Jackson considers
this such a defining game. Even more so for the Lakers, who are
down 2-1 in the season series and will lose the head-to-head
tiebreaker if they lose tonight.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, the Lakers are trying to maintain a sense of
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a lot of hype,'' Kobe Bryant said of what's riding on the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really think about it really. I think us as players,
our job is to go out there and play. Phil, coaching staffs, they
like looking at the standings and things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant concedes the Lakers do covet the homecourt advantage,
though, and that race ``makes for good competition. It boosts up
your spirit competitively.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the teams will provide an extreme contrast in
styles. The Lakers are built around three big-time stars _ Bryant,
Shaquille O'Neal and Glen Rice _ who rank among the top-scoring
trios in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Portland boasts a more egalitarian bent _ no Blazer ranks in the
NBA's top 20 in any of the six major statistical categories
(scoring, rebounds, assists, blocked shots, steals, minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they spread the wealth among a host of midrange stars
and one future Hall of Famer (Scottie Pippen). They win with waves
of talent and a second unit _ Jermaine O'Neal, Brian Grant, Detlef
Schrempf, Bonzi Wells and Greg Anthony _ that could spank the
Clippers five nights a week.
</P>
<P>
   Five Blazers average double figures in scoring, led by Steve
Smith and Rasheed Wallace (15.4 points per game each), followed by
Damon Stoudamire (12.9) and Pippen (11.1). All are capable of much
bigger numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do they have a real deep starting five, they have a
real deep bench,'' Shaquille O'Neal said. ``I think their bench
averages 20 to 30 points a game, so you have to stop their starting
five and their bench. You know, it's going to be a tough game, but
if we can do what we've been doing, we'll be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just that the Blazers pose challenges in the Lakers'
weakest areas. They have a wealth of big bodies _ Arvydas Sabonis,
Wallace, Grant and Jermaine O'Neal _ to throw at Shaq and take
fouls. They have athletic big men (Wallace, Grant) who cause
problems for Lakers forwards Robert Horry and A.C. Green. And they
have a 5-10 speedster in Stoudamire to penetrate and cause havoc on
screen-and-rolls.
</P>
<P>
   On top of everything else, the Lakers have a deficit in the
psychology department. They've lost in their last seven regular-
season trips to the Rose Garden. They admittedly need a win now, if
for nothing else, to prove they can do it in the (inevitable?)
rematch in the conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'm sure they think that we can't beat them at home, so
we have to go up there and try to kind of put a dent in their
confidence a little bit,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   And what does Jackson, the master motivator, tell his team with
so much on the line?
</P>
<P>
   ``I will cry if we lose, that's what I told them,'' he said.
``Naah, I said don't worry about this game. It's an important game.
We just want to measure ourselves up to what we have to become as a
team. And then if we don't win the ballgame, we still have four
left in this week, and you go back and you win those four, so that
you put yourself in a position to win again, the next opportunity
that comes along.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 0039EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
