<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RUSH-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDEN RUSH FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA sophomore JaRon Rush's 2-month ordeal ended
Monday in surprising fashion _ with the NCAA appeals committee
cutting his suspension from 29 games to nine and allowing him to
play Saturday at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he'd be back this year,'' UCLA athletic
director Peter Dalis said. ``I didn't know when we'd get closure.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 1, the NCAA suspended Rush for 15 games for accepting
$200 from sports agent Jerome Stanley and 29 games for accepting
$6,325 from former AAU coach Myron Piggie.
</P>
<P>
   Rush has been out since Dec. 10, so the Stanley penalty ended
earlier this month. The Piggie penalty covered the last 12 games
this season and the first 17 next.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins appealed the Piggie penalty but didn't think Rush
would return this season. They just wanted him back for the start
of next season. But the appeals committee, comprised of five
college administrators from around the country, had other ideas.
Thursday's showdown at Cal is the ninth (and final) game of the
reduced suspension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it has hit too many of us,'' Bruins forward Rico
Hines said. ``He was practicing with us and somebody said he would
play Saturday. We're like, `He's out 44 games and now he's playing
Saturday?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to play it low-key, but I'm sure tonight he'll go
somewhere and say, `Yeah!'
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long road.''
</P>
<P>
   Although surprising, the reduction is not unprecedented. Rush's
brother, Kareem, a Missouri freshman who reportedly accepted $1,800
from Piggie, had a 14-game suspension reduced to nine last month.
</P>
<P>
   Before his career ends, Rush must repay the $6,525 to a charity
of UCLA's choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very happy that the NCAA has reduced my suspension and I
am relieved that this situation is finally over,'' Rush said in a
statement released by UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Rush was not available for comment because of his role in an
ongoing federal investigation of Piggie on possible charges of tax
evasion and fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Rush's ordeal began in November, when he testified before a
Kansas City grand jury about his relationship with Piggie. That
testimony prompted the FBI to notify UCLA of possible NCAA rules
violations. Rush was suspended Dec. 10 while UCLA conducted an
internal investigation and submitted its findings to the NCAA. The
focus of the investigation was Rush's relationships with Piggie and
Kansas City businessman Tom Grant.
</P>
<P>
   Grant is a Kansas booster who served as Rush's benefactor
throughout high school. He leased Rush a car and paid for his
education at Pembroke Hill School. He was also the general manager
of Rush's AAU team.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA investigated the Rush-Grant relationship and cleared
both parties of wrongdoing because Rush did not attend Kansas. But
it suspended Rush 29 games for accepting money from Piggie _ some
of which allegedly helped pay for a Chevy Blazer.
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal, UCLA argued that Rush did not distinguish Grant's
money from Piggie's money. After all, Piggie worked for Grant as
coach of the AAU team.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA felt it could make a separation between what happened
under Tom Grant and Myron Piggie,'' Dalis said. ``We argued that it
was very difficult for JaRon to make that distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Sylvester James, Rush's Kansas City-based attorney:
</P>
<P>
   ``JaRon didn't know where the money was coming from. What was
the difference between a GEO Tracker that Grant bought and a Blazer
that Piggie got?''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA hired Rich Hilliard, a former NCAA director of enforcement
who's based in Kansas City and helps schools present cases before
the NCAA. Hilliard knew the appeals committee's history of reducing
penalties, but he focused on the complicated and unusual nature of
Rush's case. Because of Grant and the AAU links, this was not as
simple as a player taking money from an agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is the (appeals) committee realized the uniqueness of
JaRon's case and came to the conclusion that a reduction was
warranted,'' Hilliard said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are thrilled. Rush won't be available for the most
important game of the season (Cal), but he'll play Saturday in
Maples Pavilion, where UCLA will need all the help it can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge lift, because we've had as tough a season as you
can probably have at UCLA,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin. ``We've kind
of been on a roll for a week following the bottoming-out (at
Arizona and Arizona State). Since that point, we've been on an
upswing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
