<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-JAZZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAZZ DEFEAT NETS, 106-101 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ Two hours after showering him with a thunderous
standing ovation, the fans of the Utah Jazz were booing Keith Van
Horn with all their might. Van Horn was at the foul line midway
through the fourth quarter with the score tied and the possibility
of an upset appearing very real.
</P>
<P>
   The former University of Utah star made one of two free throws
to give the New Jersey Nets a 1-point lead, but the advantage was
fleeting. In their fourth game in five nights, the aging Utah Jazz
proved to be far from fatigued, holding the Nets without a basket
for 7 minutes 13 seconds to take command and leave the Delta Center
with a 106-101 victory.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Nets' ninth straight loss to Utah, a team they have
not defeated since Jan. 17, 1994. In a near triple-double
performance, Karl Malone led the Jazz with 35 points, 12 rebounds
and 9 assists. Converting most of Malone's assists was Jeff
Hornacek. The veteran off guard Hornacek made 10 of 11 field-goal
attempts, including five 3-pointers, to score 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury led the Nets with yet another fabulous
performance, recording 34 points and 11 assists. After the Nets
went 13 straight possessions without making a basket to fall behind
by 9 points, Marbury hit a driving layup and an ensuing free throw
to pull them within 98-92 with 1:37 to play. He scored two more
baskets, including a 3-pointer with 16.8 seconds left that cut
Utah's lead to 103-101. But Hornacek promptly answered with two
free throws, and Scott Burrell missed a 3-point attempt for the
Nets to end the suspense.
</P>
<P>
   In his first professional game in Utah, Van Horn was received
with great appreciation before the game. He put on an adequate
performance, finishing with 18 points and 13 rebounds before
fouling out in the final minute. Kerry Kittles followed Marbury
with 22 points for the Nets, who fell to 5-22 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn's intentions were clear early. Just 10 seconds into the
game, he took the ball strong to the basket against Malone, getting
2 points on a goaltending call on Olden Polynice. Moments later,
Van Horn put back an offensive rebound, then scored 2 free throws
to account for 6 of the Nets' first 8 points.
</P>
<P>
   The adrenaline that was driving Van Horn, who had six rebounds
in the first six minutes, was no more evident than on a block of a
Malone shot three minutes into the contest. After falling when
Malone received an entry pass in the paint, Van Horn jumped to his
feet to swat Malone's layup attempt. He was called for goaltending,
but his vigor was nonetheless impressive.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the Nets seemed energized as well, and the result
was one of their best offensive quarters of the season as they
grabbed a 35-28 lead. Marbury scorched the future Hall of Famer
John Stockton for 11 points and 6 assists in the first quarter.
Kittles scored 9 in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McIlvaine provided strong protection around the basket,
swatting four shots in the opening 12 minutes. But otherwise, the
Nets' effectiveness on offense was not matched on the defensive
end. Utah, with its intricate screening and cutting, picked the
Nets' defense apart for several backdoor layups, and took advantage
of the Nets' laxity around the 3-point line. Hornacek began what
would be an outstanding half by scoring 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Casey may have unwittingly cooled off Van Horn by sitting him
down for the last two minutes of the first quarter, because his
second period was unproductive. After re-entering at the
eight-minute mark, Van Horn missed all four of his shots and
committed two turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Nets, Marbury and Kittles stayed hot.
Marbury went into the half with 15 points, 7 assists and 4
rebounds. Kittles had 13 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
