<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-TECH-WORKERS (Bombay) _ A growing though still modest
number of India's biggest American success stories, high-tech
workers whose lives are now firmly rooted in the United States, are
beginning to come home to India, and not just to visit relatives,
but also to start companies, invest their capital and indulge their
philanthropic instincts. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-RIGHTS (United Nations) _ China, faced with the Clinton
administration's determination to have Beijing's human rights
record condemned at this year's U.N. Human Rights Commission
session, is mobilizing its defense by using the kind of U.N.
mechanisms that can make it relatively easy to avoid censure when a
country is big and powerful. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   TERROR-U.S. (Washington) _ Middle Eastern and American officials
say they believe that a key lieutenant of Osama bin Laden, the
Saudi exile, coordinated a terrorist plot that targeted Western and
Israeli tourists in Jordan in December. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   BAHAMAS-DEVELOP (New Providence, Bahamas) _ The tourists who
scuba dive among the reefs and tan themselves on the sandy shores
have probably seen more of this island's coastline than Therell
Bethell ever has. She cannot remember the last time she visited a
decent stretch of beach, since the development boom over the last
decade brought gated communities and exclusive resorts. ``Bahamians
do not have access to the beach,'' said Bethel, a legal secretary
in Nassau. ``Bahamians have to have a puddle in our backyards to
swim.'' The long-simmering resentment over the loss of their
beaches has crystallized in opposition to a proposed luxury
community on the longest remaining stretch of undeveloped coastline
in New Providence, the most populated island in the Bahamas. By
David Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-INFANT-MORTALITY (New York) _ In central Brooklyn _ where
storefronts are boarded, housing projects stand in defiant
opposition to the boom times, and the hospitals are more or less
broke _ too many babies are dying. They die at rates that the city
as a whole has not seen in nearly two decades. And they die, in
some cases, at a rate double what the federal government has set as
the infant mortality goal for the nation. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
