<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-KANSAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK STARTS HELPS TEXAS TOP KANSAS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Texas-Kansas matchup may not have had the
import once thought months ago, but it was nevertheless a Big
Monday for the Longhorns.
</P>
<P>
   Texas jumped on the Jayhawks with a terrific defensive effort in
the first half, kept KU at arm's distance in the second half, and
won a 68-54 victory that clinched a first-round bye in next week's
Big 12 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 16 Longhorns (21-7) pushed their conference record to
12-3 and assured themselves of at least a fourth-place finish,
while dropping No. 23 Kansas (21-8) to 10-5. KU now faces the
possibility of playing on the first day in Kansas City for the
first time in the league's four-year history.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the Longhorns' first victory over Kansas in Big 12
play. Texas is 1-3 against KU in Big 12 play and 2-7 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard Ivan Wagner led the Longhorns with a career-high 19
points, including 8 of 10 free throws in the last 3:31. Senior
forward Gabe Muoneke, who started his last home game, responded
with 16 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the emotion and hype surrounding this game, we never
lost sight of the big picture,'' Wagner said. ``We knew we were
playing for seeding in the Big 12 tournament, and in the NCAA, and
we executed our game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas held Kansas to a season-low 21 points in first half,
contesting every shot and limiting the Jayhawks to 6-of-29
shooting. Kansas made only two of its first 15 shots as the
Longhorns raced to a 24-6 lead. In the half, Texas converted 12 KU
turnovers into 14 points and scored five times off the break.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas shot 31.1 percent, making UT 16-0 when holding teams to
less than 40 percent this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to put that first half (defensively) in a bottle,''
UT coach Rick Barnes said. ``We've learned from every loss. The
biggest thing we've realized since the Iowa State loss is that
every role on this team is important. The last two games we've
really played our roles well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They slowed us down a little bit and we got a little tentative
against their zone in the second half. But our guys stayed sharp
and we never let it get under 10.''
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by freshman point guard Kirk Hinrich, Kansas inhaled a
little of Texas' intensity after the half. After trailing by as
much as 20 points in the first half, KU pulled to within 10 points
three times. But each time, Texas responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug ourselves a hole in the first half and coach gave us a
motivational speech to come out and play in the second half,'' KU
forward Drew Gooden said. ``We gave it our best, but it wasn't
enough. We dug ourselves so deep, we just got our hands out of the
hole and couldn't pull ourselves up.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Chris Mihm wrestled with foul problems and scored only
nine points. But the 7-foot junior pulled down a game-high 12
rebounds and heard chants of ``one more year'' and ``come back
Chris'' from the Erwin Center crowd of 13,561.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it was extremely tough for me to get the ball
inside,'' Mihm said. ``But everyone just played a fantastic game
tonight. They chose to try and take me out of the game, but we have
a fantastic team and they will take it right to you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm reiterated that he has not made his mind up about going to
the NBA a year early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to know the town and the students support and care
about you,'' he said. ``No matter what happens, it was special for
all of us. I can't start to talk about (the NBA) now, but that was
special.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
