<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANK-ROBBER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EX-COP ACCUSED IN 10 BANK ROBBERIES  &HT;     By MANNY FERNANDEZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jerry Del Olson locked up scores of criminals during his lengthy
career as a police officer in the Sierra Nevada town of
Placerville.
</P>
<P>
   Now, however, Olson is the one behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   The former cop is the same man, FBI agents say, who is
responsible for a two-month string of Northern California bank
robberies.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-year-old Olson, who now lives in Concord, was arrested in
Reno on Saturday, police said, when they caught him fleeing after a
Wells Fargo Bank holdup. Authorities say the arrest ends Olson's
string of successful bank robberies stretching from Walnut Creek to
Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Olson was arrested on suspicion of robbing only the Reno bank,
but FBI agents say they have enough evidence to link him to nine
other bank robberies since January. That evidence includes
statements made by Olson and as well as from witnesses to the
previous heists, FBI spokesman Nick Rossi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clothing he has worn at the robberies has been very
consistent, so surveillance photographs and videotapes have helped
us connect a number of these to the same person,'' said Rossi, a
special agent in the FBI's Sacramento office.
</P>
<P>
   Rossi would not say how much money was stolen in the holdups.
</P>
<P>
   The rash of robberies sparked an investigation involving the FBI
and law enforcement officials in Sacramento, Auburn, Stockton,
Walnut Creek and Pleasant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The first holdup attributed to Olson occurred January 14 at a
U.S. Bank in Auburn. Credit unions and banks in Walnut Creek,
Stockton and Sacramento soon followed. Earlier this month, there
was the February 5 robbery at a Wells Fargo Bank in Pleasant Hill
and a February 12 U.S. Bank hold-up in Sacramento. Another heist
occurred again in Stockton, as well as others in Fresno and Santa
Rosa.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities said Olson's luck appeared to run out Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 9:30 a.m., Reno police responded to a robbery at
the Wells Fargo Bank on Neil Road in the southeast area of the
city. Officers had a description of the suspect and spotted Olson
leaving the area in a vehicle, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Olson was pulled over and detained. A witness later identified
Olson as the robber, and an undisclosed amount of money was
recovered inside his vehicle, Reno police said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents took custody of Olson, who is being held in the
Washoe County Jail in Nevada. He is scheduled to make his first
federal court appearance Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured during the robberies, but investigators
believe Olson pointed a handgun at a security guard while fleeing a
bank in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Arresting a former law enforcement officer for such serious
offenses is disturbing, though rare, Rossi added.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those facts of life that we just have to deal
with,'' he said. ``Occasionally, even those who have had law
enforcement training act in ways that are inconsistent with their
prior obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   Olson was an officer in Placerville for nearly two decades,
authorities said, though the circumstances involving his departure
from the Police Department were unclear Monday. Placerville police
officials could not be reached for comment last night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
