r n BC-REGISTRATION-PRIMARY-     02-29 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REGISTRATION-PRIMARY-SFCRHON </SLUG>
  
 PARTY REGISTRATIONS SEE LITTLE CHANGE BEFORE PRIMARY  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Despite well-publicized efforts by political campaigns to
convince voters to switch parties, California's party registration
figures will be virtually unchanged going into the state's March 7
primary election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had more registration changes than normal, but nothing
overwhelming,'' said Hugh Denton, registrar of voters for Contra
Costa County. ``We didn't see either party gain a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, whose insurgent try for the Republican
presidential nomination depends on attracting independent and
Democratic voters to his banner, convinced a reported 30,000 voters
to re-register Republican. But in a state with 14.6 million
registered voters, that's barely a blip on the political radar
screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``California is a really big state,'' said Bob Mulholland, an
adviser to the state Democratic party. ``Except for the month
before the presidential election, any registration activity by any
group is just a mosquito bite.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Democrats registered in the state dropped by
91,516, or 1.35 percent, between January 1 and February 7, the
close of registration for next week's election. Republican
registration grew by 21,578, or 0.42 percent, while 77,145 more
voters declined to state a party affiliation, an increase of 3.83
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Independent voters will find themselves on the outside looking
in when it comes to next week's presidential primary vote. Under
California's blanket primary initiative, passed in 1996, voters can
choose any candidate, regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   But both the Democratic and Republican parties have ruled that
only votes by their registered members will count toward selecting
the presidential candidate this year.
</P>
<P>
   A number of local counties did see independents changing their
registration so their votes would count in the party primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the blanket primary law, we always saw independents
re-registering before the primary and then changing back right
after election day,'' said Theresa Rabe, a spokeswoman for the
election department in San Francisco. ``We're seeing that again.''
</P>
<P>
   In a number of cases, it was the Republican party, where
McCain's attempt to catch Texas Gov. George W. Bush has drawn
plenty of attention, that got the local registration boost.
</P>
<P>
   San Mateo County, for example, is 51 percent Democrat, 29
percent Republican and 17 percent independent. But between January
1 and February 7, 673 Democrats re-registered as Republicans,
compared to 334 Republicans who became Democrats. At the same time,
315 independents signed on as Democrats, while 364 became
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had 6,000 people register, with about half of those
re-registrations,'' said Mary Lavelle, an elections specialist with
the county. ``That's a lot for a county our size.''
</P>
<P>
   The registration changes did cause a few problems for Bay Area
counties. Because some absentee ballots were sent out before the
registration deadline arrived, a number of voters who changed
parties late ended up with the wrong ballot, said Xixi Castillo, a
registration supervisor with Alameda County.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to send inquiries out to those people and then have
them return their ballots so we could issue them the right one,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing effort to purge nonexistent voters from county
registration rolls also played a part in the tiny statewide
increases. In Los Angeles County alone, Democratic registration
dropped by 145,893 and Republican registration by 55,570 as the
county tried to clean up its list of eligible voters. On a smaller
scale, Stanislaus County has dropped more than 6 percent of its
voters from the rolls this year.
</P>
<P>
   But even the small boost was good news for California
Republicans, who still trail the  &LR; Democrats in statewide
registration, 46 percent to 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're excited,'' said Stuart DeVeaux, a spokesman for the
state Republican party. ``This sends a key message to the
Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest trend in the state continued to be the move toward
independent voters, whose numbers have been steadily increasing in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 1996, the number of independent voters has grown by
563,658 while Democratic and Republican numbers have fallen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
