<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TCU-SMU-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TCU RIDES FAST FINISH TO SWEEP OF SMU
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ARTHUR GARCIA 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Think Monday night's TCU-SMU showdown at Moody Coliseum
wasn't intense? Just check under Billy Tubbs' right eye this
morning.
</P>
<P>
   TCU's veteran coach will no doubt wake up with a welt on his
upper cheek, compliments of a penny hurled out of the stands
seconds after the Horned Frogs completed a season sweep of SMU with
a 86-83 comeback victory.
</P>
<P>
   Tubbs laughed off the coins thrown at him after the game _ ``My
lawyer told me not to comment'' _ and instead praised his team's
resilience in the second half. The Frogs rallied from seven points
down with five minutes left, after making up a 13-point deficit
earlier in the half, and held their breath on two SMU 3-point tries
in the final seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an outstanding game and a hard-fought game,'' said
Tubbs, now 11-2 against the Mustangs. ``We felt that defensively we
had to be the aggressors, and it paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs (16-13, 7-6 Western Athletic Conference) broke a
two-game losing streak and might have rekindled their NIT chances.
TCU outrebounded the Mustangs in the second half and nailed 7 of 10
3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to come out strong and rebound,'' said Marquise
Gainous, who scored 17 of his 27 points and grabbed 12 of his 14
rebounds in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``At lot of times we knew where the ball was coming (off missed
shots) and as long as we got a hand on it, we could put it back
in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs' last three baskets, including Gainous' shot that gave
TCU an 80-79 lead with 2:19 left, followed offensive rebounds.
Bingo Merriex made the last two, including a tip-in with 29 seconds
left for a 84-81 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Tubbs told us at the (halftime) break we needed to go
hard to the boards, and that got us back in the game,'' said
Merriex, who scored 15 points and made 3 of 5 3-point tries.
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs had a chance to send the game into overtime after
TCU's Thomas McTyer made the first of two free throws with 11.6
seconds left. SMU quickly advanced the ball up the right side of
the court, but Stephen Woods misfired on a 3-point try. The ball
bounced out past the 3-point line on the left side, and Renaldo
Bratton missed an off-balance shot as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two good looks with two good shooters,'' said Woods,
who scored 18. ``We just didn't knock them down.''
</P>
<P>
   After falling behind 52-39 four minutes into the second half,
the Frogs went on a run similar to their 32-10 spurt that closed
out a 92-75 victory against SMU in Fort Worth on Jan. 29. This time
it was a 26-9 run, capped by a 3-pointer from Ryan Carroll that
gave TCU a 65-61 lead midway through the half.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll scored 20 points on 9-of-17 shooting in 35 minutes and
admitted a little trash talking by SMU's Jeryl Sasser before the
game helped light a fire. Sasser, the Mustangs' leading scorer,
made only 2 of 13 shots and scored six points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a rivalry,'' Carroll said simply. ``And it really got us
hyped up when Sasser said there's was no way we could come in here
and beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mustangs (21-6, 9-4) were counting on a victory to keep
their WAC title hopes alive and solidify their NCAA Tournament
hopes. Now, even if SMU beats league-leading Tulsa (11-2) Saturday,
the Mustangs will probably finish third.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs also got a unexpected lift from Myron Anthony, who
scored 13 points and pulled down five rebounds in 29 minutes off
the bench. Anthony scored in double figures for the first time
since Jan. 13 against San Jose State, and his eight first-half
points earned him a second-half start.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've felt in a long time,'' he said. ``I had
a good week of practice. My shot felt good, and my legs felt good.
I'm back.''
</P>
<P>
   With so much at stake coming into the game, both teams spent the
opening minutes working out the jitters. The teams committed eight
turnovers in the first five minutes, and the Frogs missed nine of
their first 10 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Davis helped the Mustangs build a 17-9 lead with an
inside-outside scoring display.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs pulled within one (19-18) on Gainous' 3-pointer at the
8:55 mark, but SMU kept the lead for the remainder of the half,
mainly because of its dominance on the glass. The Mustangs held a
rebounding edge in the half, and grabbed 10 offensive rebounds. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
