<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-DEBATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MCCAIN QUESTIONED OVER DEBATE DECISION  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDDING, Calif. _ GOP presidential hopeful John McCain brought
his ``Straight Talk Express'' to the Golden State Monday night for
a three-day campaign swing to convince Californians that he hasn't
given up on their state after canceling a debate with Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   While hundreds of loyal Republicans turned out to see him at an
airport rally on a misty night in Redding, some voters said they
wanted straight talk on why the Arizona senator will skip the only
scheduled GOP debate before the March 7 primary in crucial
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure seems like a bad time ... just when they're getting
down to the wire,'' said Rick Stephens, an engineer from Redding
who waited more than an hour to see McCain last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he has so much knowledge of policy, then this is the time
to show it,'' said Stephens' wife, Pam, a registered Republican who
said she is still undecided and wants to be convinced that McCain
deserves her vote. ``But he found a nice little opportunity to
cancel. It's that rubber-hits-the-road thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The comments illustrate how McCain, who has campaigned on a
message of ``straight talk,'' appears to have undercut his own
sales pitch by backing out of the debate with his GOP rivals,
political insiders and voters are saying this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is politics as usual _ and it undermines McCain's whole
argument that he is different and he does not play those games,''
said California political analyst Sherry Bebitch Jeffe. Worse, ``it
lends the perception that he's afraid of (Texas Gov. George W.)
Bush, afraid of risking momentum. Isn't he the insurgent?''
</P>
<P>
   McCain campaign officials _ after criticizing Bush earlier for
hesitating to participate in the debate _ confirmed Monday that
McCain had backed out of Thursday's Republican presidential debate
sponsored by CNN and the Los Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   They said McCain would debate Bush instead on NBC's ``Meet the
Press'' on Sunday, but Bush's campaign said there are no such
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Word of McCain's decision, which was apparently made last week,
came as the senator was scheduled to arrive in California last
night in Redding for an airport rally. He is scheduled to take his
``Straight Talk Express'' bus through the Central Valley Tuesday
and then to Southern California before heading to New York, his
campaign said.
</P>
<P>
   But now, as he tries to woo California voters, he will have to
explain his apparent decision to de-emphasize California and
concentrate his time and resources on New York, where polls show
him holding a narrow lead over Bush.
</P>
<P>
   With just a week to go before the crucial March 7 primaries,
when 16 states, including California and New York, will select
delegates, McCain's decision to skip the California debate _ the
only nationally televised debate between now and ``Super Tuesday''
_ has flabbergasted some state political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   They say that in the nation's most populous state, where recent
polls have shown McCain gaining in the popular vote, the move is
clearly ``a major mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the life of me, I can't understand what they're doing,''
said Republican consultant Sal Russo. ``When you're behind, like
McCain, you need all the exposure you can get.''
</P>
<P>
   Bebitch Jeffe was even more critical, saying McCain has lost an
opportunity to deliver his message ``in a national debate, not just
a state debate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision not to debate in California could be the
equivalent of the Bob Jones (University) decision on the Bush
side,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; McCain Campaign Explains
</P>
<P>
   Top McCain campaign officials insisted the senator is still
committed to winning this state's primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is putting in more time on the ground in
California than Bush, and more time on the air,'' said Dan Schnur,
McCain's communications director. ``Our goal ... is to convince
grassroots Republicans that following the party establishment onto
the Bush train is the wrong decision.''
</P>
<P>
   A Field Poll released Monday showed California's Republicans
backing Bush over McCain in the March 7 primary by 48 percent to 28
percent in the contest for the state's 162 convention delegates, a
ratio virtually unchanged from a Field Poll earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   But in the state's open primary, where voters can choose from
among all the presidential candidates regardless of party, McCain
has seen his support among all likely voters surge from 10 percent
in January and 15 percent earlier this month to 20 percent today,
just 2 percentage points behind Bush and 8 points behind Democratic
front-runner Al Gore's 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it increasingly conceivable that McCain could beat
Bush among all California voters, yet badly lose the
Republican-only count that will determine who receives all of the
state's national Republican convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic pollster Paul Maslin, who is watching the McCain rise
with interest, said McCain's camp also is watching those numbers _
and what appears to be his stronger chances elsewhere. That is one
reason why, he said, the senator may have had to make tough
decisions about where to spend his most valuable commodity leading
up to Super Tuesday _ his time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the short run, it hurts him,'' said Maslin. ``'But if he
wins Virginia (Tuesday) after attacking Pat Robertson and Jerry
Falwell in their home state _ then you've got a monster on your
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, McCain will take his campaign through Stockton, Fresno
and Bakersfield. Tomorrow, he will travel to San Bernardino and
Riverside counties before heading to Los Angeles on Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle Washington Bureau Chief Marc Sandalow contributed to
this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
