<HEADLINE>
TEAM SCORING LEADER SET FOR CANUCKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Kings leading scorer Ziggy Palffy will
be in the lineup tonight against the Vancouver Canucks at the
Staples Center after missing Saturday's game in San Jose with back
spasms and an injured neck.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy awoke Saturday morning with the same lower-back pain that
first surfaced in December. He also got up angry, knowing he had
been cross-checked across the neck last Friday by Vancouver's Matt
Cooke.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something has to change, the referee can't keep ignoring these
plays,'' Palffy said.
</P>
<P>
   But with 20 games left in the regular season and the playoffs
approaching, on-ice officials are less likely to call penalties.
Several times on the last trip, the Kings were wise not to
retaliate during close games. But they will see more muscle from
opposing teams in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ziggy has taken some bumps to the body, but I thought the
reason he didn't play against San Jose was because his lower back
tightened up overnight,'' coach Andy Murray said. ``That is part of
the game this time of year.''
</P>
<P>
   It also is a reason the Kings are looking into acquiring a
rugged forward with playoff experience before the March 14 trade
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Murray missed Palffy's playmaking, which
accounted for seven goals and 12 assists in his previous 12 games.
Murray was upset that there was no one to take over in Palffy's
absence. The Kings blew a 2-1 lead in the second period and lost
6-3 to the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed him, but I was not happy with our team,'' Murray
said after Monday's practice. ``I got after them today. I respect
what they went through on the (seven-game) road trip, but we lost
some individual battles. We need everybody on board and Saturday
night we didn't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Spoiler's role: The Canucks are coming off Sunday's 2-1
victory over Phoenix, the team that leads the Kings by two points
in the Pacific Division. Vancouver is 6-3-1 since the All-Star
break, collecting 13 of 20 points, a .667 pace the Canucks likely
need the rest of the way to have a shot at the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess they're pretty desperate, trying to get into the
playoffs,'' said ex-Canuck Jyrki Lumme, now with Phoenix. ``We
should be desperate, too. We just didn't have the legs. We didn't
have any jump. We couldn't get anything going.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick whistles: Stephane Fiset, who defeated Vancouver 5-2 on
Friday night, will be in net tonight against the Canucks. . . .
Sharks general manager Dean Lombardi said he is casting his Norris
Trophy vote as the league's best defenseman to St. Louis' Chris
Pronger over the Kings' Rob Blake. ``Not to take anything away from
Blake, but I think this guy is pretty special,'' Lombardi said of
Pronger. ``He's the equivalent of a Dominik Hasek for defensemen
right now. He can completely control a game in all phases.'' . . .
Kings defenseman Garry Galley, who aggravated a season-long neck
injury last Friday, will play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
