r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCRHON     02-29 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCRHON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT TAKES A CHILD TO SHOW THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The homeless guy was jaywalking across Market
St. at Fifth when a slow-moving car hit him and knocked him to the
pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Fleming, who is 13 and lives in Union City, was waiting
for a bus, on her way to visit her father and stepmother. Katie saw
the whole thing.
</P>
<P>
   The driver didn't stop; the car kept moving slowly in the heavy
afternoon rush-hour traffic, and two people walked alongside the
car, knocking on the driver's window _ ``Hey! Stay here, you hit
someone!''
</P>
<P>
   The driver didn't stop, and as soon as the traffic cleared, the
car sped away.
</P>
<P>
   Katie and a frail elderly woman went to the aid of the
hit-and-run victim lying in the busy street. The man said he wanted
to get up and struggled to his feet. Katie and the woman were
overmatched by the traffic and asked passers-by for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   By crazy coincidence, each of the many well-dressed folks
hurrying home from work or to the next tourist spot was in too much
of a hurry to lend a hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get guys to help us,'' Katie says. ``No one
responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Katie and the woman finally helped the man off the road. The
cops came. Did anyone get a license number? Yes, Katie noted and
memorized it. And she was the only eyewitness who stuck around to
talk to the cops.
</P>
<P>
   The man declined medical attention and wobbled away.
</P>
<P>
   There is no record of a police report, and since there is no
victim to testify, it's unlikely anything would happen anyway. So
the hit-and-run driver gets a free pass, and a pedestrian-shaped
sticker for his or her car door.
</P>
<P>
   Katie is an eighth-grader at Barnard White Middle School in
Union City. She worked last summer in an S.F.
homeless-environmental-elderly volunteer program.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Mr. Mayor, how about a key to the city for Citizen Kate?
</P>
<P>
   TOO BAD about John McCain deciding not to honor his promise to
debate George W. Bush in California this week.
</P>
<P>
   Looks like the Straight Talk Express came to a fork in the
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``STOMP,'' the show the theater critics love and the theater
cockroaches hate, is coming to San Francisco. Hundreds of wannabe
stompers lined up outside the Alcazar Theater on Geary Monday
morning to suck in fumes from an asphalt cooker and wait their turn
to audition.
</P>
<P>
   The show's percussion instruments are all items you find on the
street. In Stomp's five-year run in New York, cast members went
through 5,200 brooms.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder where they're going to find brooms in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   WILL THE Giants' new ballpark be breezy? The answer, my friends,
is blowin' in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hundley noticed that the newly planted sycamore trees in
front of the park on King Street ``are already leaning quite
noticeably in the direction of the wind. Is Pac Bell Park destined
to be nothing more than Candlestick North?''
</P>
<P>
   BIG OIL busts two-buck barrier by the bay!
</P>
<P>
   The Shell station at the corner of 8th and Harrison, reports
Scott McKellar, was selling premium Monday for $2.05 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Used to be you'd tell the attendant, ``Fill 'er up.'' Now you
hand the man your wallet and say, ``Empty 'er out.''
</P>
<P>
   EYE-OPENER: Chuck Barragan was strolling past the Javalencia
coffeehouse on Valencia one recent morning and noticed a very large
pig's head lying in the doorway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think?'' asks Chuck. ``Someone didn't get their
kosher muffin? An offering to the gods of misfortune?''
</P>
<P>
   The shop owner tells me he has no idea, but he quickly disposed
of the head. Th-th-that's all, folks!
</P>
<P>
   THE SCOOP on the poop: In Yuba County, a developer and his
partner are in trouble with the law for applying treated sewage
sludge to their farmland.
</P>
<P>
   The news story in the Marysville Appeal-Democrat (sent by Doris
Buell) says the men who are using these ``biosolids'' on their
cropland are named Fran Arciero and (drumroll, please) ... Slick
Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   THEY'VE INVENTED a new game in San Pablo, where the cops and the
homeless don't always see eye to eye.
</P>
<P>
   One homeless man often visits with his 5-year-old son in a city
park. One day, a police officer caught the youngster bowling with
plastic soda bottles and a playground ball, and told the boy that
his game might very well be illegal.
</P>
<P>
   So now dad plans to apply for a city permit to use the park for
games of ``San Pablo Bocce Ball.''
</P>
<P>
   BIG SHOOTOUT at the Washington Square Bar &AMP; Grill Monday! Cops
and bad guys blasted away, shattered the Washbag's windows, bad
guys got shot up good and were carted off in a meat wagon.
</P>
<P>
   And, Cut! A happy ending, as Nash Bridges wrapped up another
messy case, Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   ``REMOTE RAGE'' was setting in.
</P>
<P>
   Jenefer Bickers had lost her TV clicker. Looked everywhere,
including previous hiding places like the refrigerator and the
garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Is there anything more annoying?
</P>
<P>
   Desperate, frantic, Bickers finally phoned a psychic friend, who
told her to look again behind a sofa cushion. And there it was.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks for that tip, Jenefer, but if that psychic was really
your friend, she would have phoned you first.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
