<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1716 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-PRIMARIES-GOP-SFCHRON     02-29 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-GOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MCCAIN RIPS INTO `INTOLERANT' LEADERS OF RELIGIOUS RIGHT  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of primaries in Virginia and Washington,
Republican presidential candidate John McCain ripped into Christian
televangelists Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell Monday as ``agents
of intolerance'' who ``shame our faith, our party and our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   The blistering broadside _ issued in Virginia Beach, near the
Christian Coalition's headquarters _ was a first for any Republican
presidential candidate and a daring assault on conventional wisdom
that has long held that Christian conservatives are vital to the
GOP base.
</P>
<P>
   As McCain courted the Republican moderates, independents and
Democrats he hopes will support him in Tuesday's GOP primaries, his
rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, campaigned in Washington state,
denouncing the Arizona senator's speech at a Seattle news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't lead America to a better tomorrow by calling people
names and pointing fingers,'' Bush said. ``Ronald Reagan didn't
point fingers _ he never played to people's religious fears like
Sen. McCain has shamelessly done, ascribing views to me that I
don't hold.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats, Tuesday's primaries could prove to be a
watershed for former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley, who desperately
hopes that the huge amounts of time and money he has spent in
Washington state will give him the first victory he needs to stay
in the race against Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bradley and McCain are hoping for momentum going into Super
Tuesday next week, when California, New York, Ohio and 13 other
states hold primaries.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, polls show Bush and McCain running neck and neck,
and  &LR; with Bradley trailing Gore. In Virginia's GOP primary, Bush
leads McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But last-minute polls have proven unreliable, especially in
states like Washington and Virginia that have open primaries and
large contingents of moderate and independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, McCain held back nothing in his attack on Falwell and
Robertson, calling them right-wing versions of Nation of Islam
leader Louis Farrakhan and the Rev. Al Sharpton, a New York
activist.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also called the televangelists ``mirror images'' of ``the
union bosses who have subordinated the interests of working
families to their own ambition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the party of Ronald Reagan, not Pat Robertson,'' McCain
declared, as the crowd of more than 2,000 cheered. ``We are the
party of Theodore Roosevelt, not the party of special interests. We
are the party of Abraham Lincoln, not Bob Jones. Join us. Join us.
Join us, and welcome anyone of good faith to our ranks. We should
be, we must be, we will be a party as big as the country we
serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson, a Bush supporter, had sent out recorded messages to
Christian conservatives in Michigan before its primary last week
calling McCain's campaign chairman, Warren Rudman, a ``vicious
bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's speech was reminiscent of the 1992 ``Sister Souljah''
campaign speech by then-candidate Bill Clinton, whose denunciation
of the rap artist's gritty lyrics and similar extreme positions on
the left helped him stake out a new political middle.
</P>
<P>
   Standing at McCain's side as he delivered the attack was Gary
Bauer, a Christian conservative who dropped out of the GOP race and
is now supporting McCain. Even as he denounced Robertson, McCain
praised religious values and ``a faith that unites and never
divides.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; High-Risk Strategy
</P>
<P>
   McCain declared himself a staunch conservative and ``proud
Republican,'' while deriding those who would restrict the party to
``card-carrying Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the height of foolishness,'' McCain said, ``to build a
wall around our party in fear that we are so narrowly defined that
new faces and fresh ideas, in accord with our basic principles,
will jeopardize our values.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. David Dreier, a Southern California Bush supporter who
describes himself as a libertarian Republican, called McCain's
attacks ``very, very unfortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing more clearly differentiates Bush from McCain than a
statement that likens Pat Robertson to Louis Farrakhan,'' Dreier
said. ``You can have whatever view you want about Pat Robertson,
but we as Republicans are trying to come together.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican strategist Bill Kristol, who backs McCain, called
McCain's speech ``a very important moment for the Republican
Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristol has maintained that the conservative movement is
floundering, citing recent election losses as proof that it no
longer constitutes ``a natural governing majority.'' The sharp GOP
contest, he said, ``is the way political evolutions happen _ you
end up with leaders that were not expected.''
</P>
<P>
   At an evening rally in Alexandria, Va., McCain drew supporters
from across the political spectrum. Many said they were drawn to
McCain's character.
</P>
<P>
   John Ingalls, an Alexandria consultant and Democrat, called the
idea that Democrats are trying to hijack the GOP primaries ``pure
baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We vote our consciences,'' Ingalls said. ``We vote for who we
think is going to be the best for the country. I'm an economic
conservative and a social liberal, and there are huge numbers of us
who are disappointed with both parties. That's what McCain has
picked up on.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Tighe, 32, who called himself a ``very conservative
Republican'' who worked for 1996 GOP nominee Bob Dole, said ``I
truly don't believe we in the United States should be in the
business of coronating princes to be presidents.'' Tighe added that
he thinks McCain ``has a very, very solid record, and his character
is flawless.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Foster, a small businessman who voted for Ross Perot in
1992, liked McCain's stand on paying back the national debt rather
than cutting taxes, and he called Bush ``a Bible thumper.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
