<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LOS ANGELES _ There was still about an hour until the opening tap
when Rudy Tomjanovich rounded a corner in the bowels of the Staples
Center and came upon a familiar face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, welcome back, buddy,'' Rudy T said to the tall, almost
regal-looking figure who was leaning against a concrete wall. ``But
I always thought you were too smart to get into this part of the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' said Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, ``just call me a
masochist.''
</P>
<P>
   What you can also call him, finally, is a coach.
</P>
<P>
   After roughly five years of knocking on doors and having most of
them never even open just a crack, the NBA's all-time leading
scorer is at last back on the inside of the game over which he
ruled for so long.
</P>
<P>
   How far inside is still open for debate when you consider the
team to finally throw Abdul-Jabbar a lifeline was the Clippers, who
barely register on the radar of pro sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to be here and to have been given a chance to
show what I have to offer to the game,'' he said. ``There is no
question that I encountered a great many obstacles along the road
to getting here, and I can't tell you that I have an explanation
for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you could point to any number of reasons why I had
such difficulty even getting interviews over the last four or five
years. I guess the bottom line is a lot of people felt they didn't
need me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had talked to a great number of general managers around the
league, and a lot of them gave me encouragement to go after a job.
But when I made the phone calls, I didn't get very many back. All I
can conclude is that they've all been waiting to see something from
me. However, I can't begin to tell you what that something was.''
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. His sky hook might have been the single greatest
offensive weapon ever in the game as he piled up 38,387
regular-season points and another 5,762 in the playoffs. He was
named to the All-Star team 18 times and won six NBA championships,
and the league he dominated turned its back. Which is like telling
Heidi Klum she isn't worth the film in the camera.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it had to do with his reputation as being strong-willed,
individualistic. Maybe there were too many coaches, general
managers, entire organizations that were intimidated at the thought
of having him work for them. Maybe it had to do with the time he
spent distancing himself from the game following his retirement
after the 1988-89 season.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than pouring himself right back into basketball after his
playing days, Abdul-Jabbar went on the lecture circuit. He wrote
three books and worked as an actor and movie producer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to get away,'' he said. ``I was totally, completely,
thoroughly burned out on the game, and I had to give myself a
chance to get my mind back in order. At that time, I needed to
regain my sense of equilibrium.''
</P>
<P>
   But eventually the game he had played for roughly 30 years, the
game that was deep in his blood, resurfaced in the form of an itch
he needed to scratch. So five years after retirement, Abdul-Jabbar
began his quest to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to the chancellor at UCLA, and there was definite
interest,'' he said. ``But then I spoke to the athletic director,
and there wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also spoke to my (college) coach, John Wooden, and he was
excited, I think, at the idea that I wanted to get into the
profession and try to teach some of the aspects of the game that he
taught me. I just never thought it was going to be so difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his alma mater, the Lakers, with whom
Abdul-Jabbar played the majority of his NBA career and won five NBA
titles, turned a deaf ear. This is a team that had made a habit of
making ex-Lakers with no experience _ Pat Riley, Magic Johnson,
Kurt Rambis _ the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to ask them,'' he said. ``I can't explain it.''
</P>
<P>
   So he took his knowledge of the game and his desire to coach to
the remote outpost of Whiteriver, Ariz., and became an unpaid
volunteer coach for the high school team at the White Mountain
Apache Reservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was about more than basketball,'' said Abdul-Jabbar.
``That was about teaching some kids who have a hopeless view of
their lives and what they might accomplish that they can go to
college; they can cope. And it let me get my feet wet.''
</P>
<P>
   Then two weeks ago, the Clippers let him jump back into the
pool. When Chris Ford was fired, new head coach Jim Todd hired a
pair of former greats in Abdul-Jabbar and Dennis Johnson as his
assistants.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind starting at the bottom with the Clippers. Never mind
being the stepchildren to the Lakers in the same brand-new, shiny
building. This is all Abdul-Jabbar has wanted _ a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``What really fueled my interest was all of the things that I
see lacking in the game today,'' he said. ``It's become a different
game from the time that I retired, and not a better game.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot about the game is not being taught, not being
translated, and as a result what I see is every level of the game
is suffering. It's become all about money and fame and glamour, not
about learning teamwork and what it means to work toward a common
goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players today have great size, great agility. But they
don't know what it means to commit themselves to each other, to
play fundamental basketball, to play the kind of defense that wins
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about money. The money has been taken out of public
schools, and there are no P.E. classes where you learn the basics.
The kids are running to these AAU teams chasing glory. They are
jumping out of college after a year or two, and they arrive in the
NBA not knowing half the things they should know to play in the
league. Frankly, a lot of them are clueless about how to play the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not the game the way it was taught to a young
Abdul-Jabbar _ then Lew Alcindor _ by Wooden, the Wizard of
Westwood, at UCLA. Bounce passes. Layups. All of the basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have a show-business mentality now,'' Abdul-Jabbar
said. ``It's all about seeing if they can be on Play of the Day.
That's not basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   It may sound odd coming from a member of the Lakers' Showtime
outfit of the '80s. Led by Kareem and Magic, they put glitz in
their five championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played a running style, but we were all about taking care
of business, about winning basketball games,'' Abdul-Jabbar said.
``Nobody ever talked about those teams playing great defense, but
we did.''
</P>
<P>
   He is paying his dues as an assistant coach now, staying up late
nights to break down game film, taking a position on the court two
hours before a game to work with the young players. At 7-2, he
stands so tall on the court, his body lean, his bald head gleaming,
his goatee now flecked with gray but his eyes still fiery, intense,
penetrating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying this,``Abdul-Jabbar said. ``Coach Todd has been
great, and this has so far been a wonderful experience. I'm in this
coaching business for the long haul, until further notice. And I do
believe that I have something to offer the game.''
</P>
<P>
   After all these years, finally, someone is willing to listen.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
