<P>
   &UR; JITTERY GEORGIA FEARS BEING SUCKED INTO THE CHECHEN WAR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TBLISI, GEORGIA _ In the snow-covered mountains of northern
Georgia, soldiers can hear the roar of battle across the border in
Chechnya creeping gradually towards them. Georgia, the fragile
republic on the southern slopes of the Caucasus Mountains, is
trying hard to stay out of the Chechen conflict. A weary-looking
Georgian President Edouard Shevardnadze told The Independent
Saturday, ``we are doing everything we can to avoid getting
involved.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Patrick Cockburn, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., Feb. 28) &QL;
</P>
