<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SST-ARMY-RADIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING PICKS SENIOR SYSTEMS TO MAKE HIGH-TECH MILITARY RADIO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY CHARLES F. BOSTWICK 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Calif. _ Senior Systems Technology has been picked by
Boeing Co. to manufacture components and assemble a new high-tech
military radio, which company officials say could result in $3
million to $5 million in business annually for five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's Information and Communications Systems Division in
Anaheim has an Army contract to build Grenadier Brat radio units
for evaluation, and hopes to get authorization to start low-rate
production later this year, a Boeing official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the program has significant potential,'' said Harvey
Magidow, Senior Systems' director of sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Systems doesn't know if additional workers will be needed
at the 18-month-old Palmdale plant. More than 300 workers now work
at the facility, which manufactures electronic devices that range
from very high-speed telecommunications modems to controllers for
irrigation systems.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring depends on the level of production for the radio, which
has drawn interest from NATO nations, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   About three times the size of a cellular phone, the Grenadier
Brat would combine a radio transmitter and receiver with a global
positioning satellite system, allowing an Army commander to track
all his unit's vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing picked SST to manufacture circuit cards, assemble the
radios and test them, said Robert Moses, Boeing subcontracts
manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they have a pretty good operation,'' Moses said
of the Palmdale plant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
