A1724 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LA-FINANCE-LADN     02-29 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-FINANCE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAYOR'S FINANCE PLAN STALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV AND MICHAEL COIT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR; L &LR; OS ANGELES _ In the biggest clash yet over power under the
new City Charter, a key council committee stalled a plan Monday
from Mayor Richard Riordan and Controller Rick Tuttle to
consolidate all the city's finances in a single department.
</P>
<P>
   The new charter, which will take effect July 1, creates an
Office of Finance but leaves some discretion on how much power it
will have, prompting weeks of sparring between the mayor, who
claims his plan could save tens of millions of dollars annually,
and the council.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's plan, backed by Tuttle, came before the council's ad
hoc committee on implementing the new City Charter, in a three-hour
hearing that left key issues unresolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great mistake to make all these changes at once
without further study,'' said Councilwoman Laura Chick, chairwoman
of the committee and a candidate for controller. ``The voters
approved a broad framework and asked us to fill in the details.''
</P>
<P>
   Chick asked for a time line on changes, and Councilman Mike
Feuer, a candidate for city attorney, indicated he wants the Budget
and Finance Committee he chairs to look at some of the details.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether the city administrative officer should
retain power in some critical financial jobs not specified in the
charter.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new charter, the city treasurer, with responsibility
for cash management and investment, will move into the Office of
Finance, given authority to take over the city clerk's function of
collecting revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The chief administrative officer retains authority to provide
independent analysis and review and to prepare budgets in what will
be the newly named Office of Administrative and Research Services,
but the charter is silent on functions now under this top
administrator, including estimating revenues, borrowing and
managing risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view this as an opportunity for some bold changes to
streamline government and make changes in the finance functions,''
Deputy Mayor Jennifer Roth said. ``The pieces we have proposed are
in the best interests of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the committee, Riordan and Tuttle recommended
consolidating most financial functions in the new Office of Finance
rather than relegating it ``to being simply a bill collector.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The dispersion of financial functions throughout our city
departments and offices has created an unwieldy and inefficient
system of financial management,'' the two officials say in their
letter.
</P>
<P>
   Under their proposal, authority for revenue-estimating and
long-term financial planning would move from the chief
administrator to the finance office. The controller still is
required to provide an independent estimate of city revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing, a major component of the city's financial operations,
and managing debt would move to the finance office.
</P>
<P>
   Risk management, now spread throughout city government, would be
moved into the finance office. A professional likely would be hired
to oversee workers' compensation, property and liability issues,
and insurance litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the proposal noted that an organization of the
nation's top municipal financial officers rated Los Angeles behind
most other major U.S. cities in administrative cost, efficiency and
use of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles might save tens of millions of dollars on
administrative costs alone if it adopted the best practices of the
nation's other major cities, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   But Chief Administrative Officer Bill Fujioka voiced concern
over the breadth of changes proposed, including the transfer of
functions analyzing the city's debt from his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This involves a fundamental principle of checks and
balances,'' said Fujioka, who has been at odds with the Mayor's
Office. ``When it comes to revenue forecasting, I believe there is
a role for the CAO to play. To have the same office looking at
revenue and debt management creates a conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee also quarreled with the Mayor's Office on the role
of city lobbyists and who speaks for the city.
</P>
<P>
   The new charter designates the mayor as the spokesman for the
city, with the approval of the council on specific policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Mayor Kelly Martin said she was concerned that a proposal
before the committee was too narrow and would not allow the mayor
to take positions on measures in Sacramento and Washington that
could generate money for the city.
</P>
<P>
   However, the committee said the mayor would be allowed to do so
with the agreement of the City Council's president and subsequent
confirmation by the council.
</P>
<P>
   Martin also said department heads should be required to submit
their positions on legislative matters to the Mayor's Office for a
coordinated response, rather than requiring all information to go
to City Council members at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Erwin Chemerinsky, who chaired the Elected Charter Reform
Commission, however, said the council also needs timely information
to take a position on issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 0145EST &QL; 
