<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETS HAMMER CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As a parting gift for showing up to be smeared by
the Lakers on Sunday, the Houston Rockets were allowed to stick
around for another day and take a few swings at the Los Angeles
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers _ absolute sweethearts at hospitality _ led with
their chins.
</P>
<P>
   Treating prosperity like a grenade, the home team saw its
winning streak ended at one Monday, snuffed by a 96-77 Rockets
victory in front of 12,940 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   If you only see one Clippers game this season, feel blessed for
missing this beauty. The Clippers missed almost everything,
shooting a franchise-low 26.8 percent from the field. No Houston
starter reached double figures in scoring, but the Rockets rolled,
getting 63 points from their bench.
</P>
<P>
   The program included a pterodactyl routine from Maurice Taylor
(12 points, 3 rebounds), who acknowledged a round of boos by
flapping his arms as he strolled to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers even lost their built-in alibi. Rookie Lamar Odom
is dragging a sore right shoulder around Staples these days and
wasn't expected to play. But Odom, who didn't start, did suit up
and competed like a healthy citizen, contributing 20 points and 10
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   But he and his teammates squeezed off 47 shots in the opening
half and had a 25-percent success rate (a dozen went in), to trail
58-36 at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   Beer should be this cold.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor momentarily sabotaged his free-agent audition by missing
13 of his 17 field-goal attempts before he was jeered on the way to
his seat at 7:30 of the fourth quarter. Michael Olowokandi missed 5
of his 6 shots and Eric Piatkowski bricked 6 of 7. Derek Anderson
missed 10 of his 13 offerings and Tyrone Nesby was a toasty 5 of
15.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets (22-35) didn't seem to miss Hakeem Olajuwon (virus)
or suffer from a sub-par effort by monster rookie Steve Francis,
who was 1 for 8 from the field in the opening 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers (12-46) really went crazy to open the second half,
trimming the deficit to 16 before their motionless offense and
soft-hearted defense invited Houston to push its advantage to 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 0148EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
