<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month, Bob McNair agreed to pay a record $700 million for a
NFL expansion franchise for Houston. Now, he needs a little help
paying for a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Thanksgiving Day, McNair will begin selling 41,000
Permanent Seat Licenses for the 69,500-seat stadium scheduled to
open in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The licenses -- priced from $600 for an end zone seat and $3,900
for a lower midfield one -- allow the buyer to own the seat as long
as he or she buys season tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Like most other chattel, the owner can sell the licenses, trade
them or bequeath them after death. In other cities, PSLs are so
coveted, they provide contention in divorces.
</P>
<P>
   The money from the licenses will pay for $50 million toward the
cost of the world's first retractable-roof, football-only stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That represents the football team's upfront payment for a
stadium budgeted at $310 million, but which could come in closer to
$350 million.
</P>
<P>
   Groundbreaking for the stadium adjacent to the Astrodome is
slated March 8, when the new team's name will be unveiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's one (financing) increment left -- the fan,`` said
North Carolina marketing guru Max Muhleman, who has helped sell
PSLs for other stadiums, including the one in Nashville, home of
the former Houston Oilers, now the Tennessee Titans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think people will take pride in helping build the finest
football facility ever,`` Muhleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Known as PSLs, the seat licenses have been used with great
success to finance stadiums for the Titans, Cleveland Browns,
Baltimore Ravens, Carolina Panthers and Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some failures. The NFL Oakland Raiders had
problems selling PSLs for stadium renovations when they moved back
from Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   But Muhleman said he does not anticipate problems in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Foremost, he said, Houston has a burning desire to regain the
sport after Bud Adams moved his Oilers to Tennessee three seasons
ago. Muhleman noted that more than 7.5 million hits have reached
the new team's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Then there will be the one-of-a-kind stadium, which Muhleman
predicted will attract more than one Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   As part of McNair's enormous franchise fee, NFL officials
pledged to give Houston the 2004 Super Bowl. And because games can
be comfortably watched in the new stadium regardless of the
weather, NFL officials will give it priority with New Orleans,
Phoenix and Miami as preferred locations, Muhleman said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, PSL prices here will be fairly modest and
they will be fewer in number compared with NFL standards.
</P>
<P>
   Nashville, for example, sold PSLs for 85 percent of their seats,
with the prices ranging from $2,500 to $4,500.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the relative scarcity in Houston -- 60 percent --
they should have greater value in future years as owners consider
selling them, Muhleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Names of the founding PSL owners will be etched on a ``wall of
honor`` inside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who buy their PSLs by Dec. 10 will have first dibs on seat
assignments. Other assignments will be on a first-come, first-serve
basis.
</P>
<P>
   For any Super Bowl here, PSL buyers will be included in a
lottery for a smaller selection of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers can pay for PSLs in three equal, annual payments,
interest-free. Southwest Bank of Texas, Wells Fargo and Chase Bank
of Texas will offer financing.
</P>
<P>
   If a PSL holder declines to buy season tickets, that fan will
forfeit their seat license.
</P>
<P>
   PSL applications will be available in Chronicle ads starting
Thursday, at www.2002stadiumfund.com on the Internet and in
brochures at participating banks.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 40 percent of the tickets will be sold in the
upper decks on a season or individual game basis. In addition, the
stadium will have pockets of seats below $20 each and an
alcohol-free zone for families.
</P>
<P>
   The Harris County-Houston Sports Authority will chip in at least
$195 million of the stadium's cost through taxes on rental cars and
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, McNair will pay about $4 million and the Houston
Livestock Show and Rodeo $1.5 million in lease and maintenance
payments annually.
</P>
<P>
   The sports authority will collect the revenues from the PSLs to
avoid tax liabilities. If the PSLs are privately issued, the issuer
has to pay income tax on them.
</P>
<P>
   Under McNair's October 1998 letter of agreement with the county,
sports authority and rodeo to build the stadium, $45 million in PSL
revenues would count against design and construction and $5 million
against the concession build-out.
</P>
<P>
   Additional revenues generated by PSLs would be counted against
additional items the football team desires.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Patterson, vice president of McNair's Houston NFL
Holdings, said the PSLs could raise $70 million, with the net
exceeding $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The letter of agreement is under reconsideration as the cost
escalates, but McNair has said he will not pay any costs above what
he agreed to in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Authority Finance Chairman Ric Campo said there is
currently no consideration about using excess PSL revenues for the
additional stadium costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 0840EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
