<P>
   As a result of the relative scarcity in Houston -- 60 percent --
they should have greater value in future years as owners consider
selling them, Muhleman said.
</P>
<P>
   Names of the founding PSL owners will be etched on a ``wall of
honor`` inside the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Fans who buy their PSLs by Dec. 10 will have first dibs on seat
assignments. Other assignments will be on a first-come, first-serve
basis.
</P>
<P>
   For any Super Bowl here, PSL buyers will be included in a
lottery for a smaller selection of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers can pay for PSLs in three equal, annual payments,
interest-free. Southwest Bank of Texas, Wells Fargo and Chase Bank
of Texas will offer financing.
</P>
<P>
   If a PSL holder declines to buy season tickets, that fan will
forfeit their seat license.
</P>
<P>
   PSL applications will be available in Chronicle ads starting
Thursday, at www.2002stadiumfund.com on the Internet and in
brochures at participating banks.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 40 percent of the tickets will be sold in the
upper decks on a season or individual game basis. In addition, the
stadium will have pockets of seats below $20 each and an
alcohol-free zone for families.
</P>
<P>
   The Harris County-Houston Sports Authority will chip in at least
$195 million of the stadium's cost through taxes on rental cars and
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, McNair will pay about $4 million and the Houston
Livestock Show and Rodeo $1.5 million in lease and maintenance
payments annually.
</P>
<P>
   The sports authority will collect the revenues from the PSLs to
avoid tax liabilities. If the PSLs are privately issued, the issuer
has to pay income tax on them.
</P>
<P>
   Under McNair's October 1998 letter of agreement with the county,
sports authority and rodeo to build the stadium, $45 million in PSL
revenues would count against design and construction and $5 million
against the concession build-out.
</P>
<P>
   Additional revenues generated by PSLs would be counted against
additional items the football team desires.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Patterson, vice president of McNair's Houston NFL
Holdings, said the PSLs could raise $70 million, with the net
exceeding $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   The letter of agreement is under reconsideration as the cost
escalates, but McNair has said he will not pay any costs above what
he agreed to in the letter.
</P>
<P>
   Sports Authority Finance Chairman Ric Campo said there is
currently no consideration about using excess PSL revenues for the
additional stadium costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 0853EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 09:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1797 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-DISNEY-FIGHT-HOUSTON-     02-29 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-FIGHT-HOUSTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTE MAY LEAD ABC AFFILIATE BEING PULLED OFF TIME WARNER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Making Houston its battleground for what appears to be
a nationwide showdown, ABC said late Monday that its local
affiliate will pull its signal from the Time Warner cable system
this week, a move that will affect as many as 680,000 subscribers
who receive KTRK-TV from that service.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is retransmission consent, part of the 1992 Cable TV
Act that authorizes cable companies to collect and transmit signals
of broadcast channels. It is known as the ``must-carry rule,'' but
ABC, CBS, NBC and Fox instead choose to negotiate cable carriage.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 13's retransmission consent agreement with Time Warner
expired Dec. 31, as did agreements involving ABC-owned stations in
New York, Los Angeles, Raleigh-Durham, N.C., and Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Since January, Time Warner Communications and Disney-owned ABC
agreed to two contract extensions to negotiate a new retransmission
agreement. But now ABC claims that Time Warner has stopped
negotiating, while Time Warner says a deal was in place, then
rejected when Disney/ABC effectively increased its price by $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and Time Warner have agreed to a 30-day extension on the
retransmission agreements in the other markets, but ABC has decided
to fight Time Warner in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   So fractious has the situation become, the two sides could not
agree Monday on when the extended contract ends. Time Warner says
12:01 a.m. Thursday, meaning Channel 13 will be dropped as of then.
Channel 13 says 12:01 a.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've given Time Warner every opportunity to continue
negotiating in good faith, but they refuse to discuss a fair
deal,'' said Henry Florsheim, KTRK general manager and president.
</P>
<P>
   The station decided Monday to launch a public campaign to inform
viewers of the situation. It said it is close to a deal with
DirecTV and EchoStar to make satellite dishes more easily available
to Houston customers. Details were still being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner will offer its cable customers free antennas so
Channel 13 viewers can pick the KTRK signal off the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney is holding Houston hostage to try and force us to
accept a deal that would raise cable prices for our Houston
customers,'' said Ron McMillan, president of Time Warner-Houston.
``Mickey Mouse doesn't like Houston, I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, broadcasters have worked out retransmission
consents by getting cable companies to carry sister channels. Cable
carriage of ESPN2, for example, was the bargaining chip in a
previous ABC and Time Warner negotiation. ESPN2 and ABC are owned
by Walt Disney Co.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the deal discussed since January were sketchy. ABC
wants Time Warner to carry Toon Disney and a 24-hour serial
channel, SoapNet, in exchange for Time Warner being able to carry
Channel 13, the most-watched station in Houston. (Ironically,
Houston was the market in which SoapNet was tested last fall.
According to ABC, it was well-received here.)
</P>
<P>
   The deal also asks that Time Warner move the Disney Channel from
premium to basic cable.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan says the deal would force Toon Disney and the Disney
Channel on customers who do not want them _ and the costs of those
services would be passed on to them, as well.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan said Time Warner had a written agreement with Disney in
January but that Disney changed its mind and requested another deal
that would have cost the cable company an additional $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney has refused to modify its demands,'' he said. ``In
Texas, a deal is a deal, but apparently in the wonderful world of
Disney, a deal is just a fairy tale.''
</P>
<P>
   Florsheim disputes the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Warner's numbers are the fairy tale,'' he said. ``There
was no deal. Time Warner should come back to the table instead of
issuing misleading information.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC believes Time Warner, which owns such cable networks as CNN,
Cartoon Network, TBS and TNT, is being discriminatory about its
channel pickups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're offering competing programming, and they're refusing to
give us fair value for that programming,'' said Alan Braverman, ABC
senior vice president and general consul. ``When you reach the
point when you believe no progress can be made, you have to stand
up and say we have a right to have fair value for our product, we
have a right to have nondiscriminatory access to viewers,
particularly if we have a compelling product.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston was chosen as the battleground because it would be the
least disruptive of the five cities, Braverman said. Houston's
cable penetration is less than in the other markets (about 57
percent here compared with 67 percent nationally).
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney is trying to make an example of Houston just to bring
the rest of the country to heel,'' McMillan said. ``If I were an
advertiser on Channel 13, I'd ask them about the refunds for the
more than 660,000 (Time Warner's figures) viewers they may not
reach anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The specifics are not critical; there are a number of issues
on the table,'' Florsheim said. ``The big issue is that we're not
talking to them at all. It is our hope that we can get the talks
started again.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
