<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 09:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1828 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GUNS-CONGRESS-0301-1s     02-29 1557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-CONGRESS-0301-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SHOOTS FOR GUN CONTROL, BUT FOES SAY HE'S OFF TARGET
 &HT;    For release Wednesday, Marc h 1
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects release date 
 &HT;    With GUNS-STATS and GUNS INTERNET
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton keeps talking about guns.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few weeks, the White House has discussed gun
shows, gun locks, gun clips, gun dealers, gun tracing, gun
licenses, gun accidents, gun prosecutions, gun safety courses, guns
in schools and guns in public housing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has spoken about the recent shooting deaths of high
schoolers in Washington, D.C. and in Littleton, Colo. He honored
Jim Brady, who suffered a gunshot wound to the head in the 1981
attempted assassination of President Reagan. And in his State of
the Union address last month, Clinton invited the Colorado father
of a victim of the Columbine High School massacre as his personal
guest.
</P>
<P>
   Some would call it a full court press. With less than a year
left in his presidency, Clinton is pushing hard for ``common
sense'' gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   But some East Texas Democrats don't see any ``common sense'' in
the proposals . Reps. Max Sandlin of Marhsall and Jim Turner of
Crockett, oppose many of Clinton's gun-related objectives this
year. Among them: mandatory safety locks on handguns and a ban on
importing large capacity ammunition clips or ``magazines.'' In
addition, Rep. Ralph Hall, of Rockwall, joins them in opposing a
72-hour waiting period for buyers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration is absolutely wrong on this issue,''
Sandlin said. ``When they're wrong, I refuse to support them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandlin, a longtime hunter and fisherman who owns ``15 to 20''
guns, said his constituents have grown up around firearms and are
not afraid of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We view guns as a part of sports and part of protecting our
homes,'' he said. ``We have a constitutional right to bear weapons
and that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding another Clinton proposal to create a state-based
licensing system for all handgun purchasers, Sandlin said, ``If the
administration wants a picture of people purchasing weapons in
Texas, they'd better load up a Polaroid and come down here because
that's the only way they're going to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall and Turner also own firearms and represent heavily rural
districts. All three lawmakers receive money from the National
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``The use of firearms for sporting purposes in East Texas is
just part of the culture,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In urban America I think there is a great deal of fear of
firearms. . .that may be the most significant difference between
rural and urban America.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Waco, said elected officials might make
a mistake assuming that the vast majority of Texans side with the
NRA in opposing child safety locks and gun show background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have confidence that the majority of my constituents want to
protect their children from gun accidents and their families from
criminals being able to easily buy guns at gun shows,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who is a hunter and owns a shotgun and a pistol, said
he supports the NRA on some issues but not when it comes to
``common sense gun safety legislation that will save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   On those issues, ``I feel comfortable siding with the mothers
and fathers in this district rather than the NRA,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Edwards' district was the scene of the largest mass
murder in the nation's history when a gunman killed 22 people at a
Luby's cafeteria in Killeen.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the massacre, Congress was scheduled to vote on a
sweeping ban on several types of firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caused me to search my conscience. What did I truly feel
was the right thing to do?'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   He decided to vote in favor of banning 19 types of assault
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not used by hunters or families but were used,
according to the FBI, by thugs, and drug dealers and organized
criminals to efficiently kill people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Edwards is considered a moderate Democrat in Congress, his
East Texas colleagues _ Sandlin, Hall and Turner _ are more
conservative. All three belong to the Blue Dog Caucus, a group of
Democrats who tend to cast conservative votes on taxes, budgets and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Their opposition to several gun control proposals could prove a
key element in upcoming House debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be a very important cog,'' said Sandlin. ``With a close
vote, I think it's very clear that the Texans _ especially the Blue
Dogs _ will vote pro-constitution, pro-gun and hopefully, that will
make the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, gun control took the spotlight in Congress after
Columbine High School students Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold
horrified the nation by using high-powered guns to murder 12
students and a teacher before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The tragedy and other highly-publicized school shootings had a
great impact on the public and lawmakers despite the fact that gun
homicides have dropped over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.S. Bureau of Justice Statistics, gun
homicides in the United States dropped from 14,740 in 1995 to
10,976 in 1998. Homicides committed by teens between the ages of 14
and 17 also dropped from 2,692 in 1995 to 1,433 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control proponents argue that the numbers are still
staggering and that gun violence will only drop significantly when
the number of firearms is reduced.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the Columbine shooting, the Senate stunned the
powerful gun lobby and voted for a juvenile justice bill which
included stricter background checks on buyers at gun shows. The
50-50 vote allowed Vice President Al Gore to cast an unusual
tie-breaking vote. Both Texas senators opposed the measure.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the bill has been stuck in a House-Senate conference
committee that is trying to resolve differences. Last week,
Republicans said they are considering stripping the bill of the
controversial gun control provisions in an effort to pass the
underlying $1.5 billion bill, which would impose stiffer penalties
on teens convicted of weapons crimes, as well as allow state
governments to post the Ten Commandments in public buildings.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Senate Democrats are expected to offer gun
control amendments to one of 13 pending appropriations bills
although the details are still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control advocates and most Democrats say that the GOP will
get hammered at the polls if it fails to pass some form of gun
control.
</P>
<P>
   But some Texas Democrats wouldn't mind that at all _ especially
if lawmakers dump a proposed 72-hour waiting period to purchase
firearms at gun shows .
</P>
<P>
   The gun show waiting period is probably the most controversial
gun control provision this year. Some lawmakers are proposing a
shorter one-day wait while others, like Sandlin, prefer some kind
of instant check.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton weighed in on the issue earlier this month, saying that
the waiting period is necessary to provide a ``cooling-off period''
for somebody ``who is really hot'' and ``buys a gun with a bad
intent.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton said the waiting period must be long enough
to allow gun sellers to make the checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you move away from 72 hours to a shorter period, then the
question is, since so many of these gun shows occur on the weekend,
will there be access to the records to do the check,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
   In response to that dilemma, Sandlin said, ``I don't believe
that we trample on the Constitution because someone may be out of
pocket on the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want my family or any other family in Central Texas
exposed to a murderer who has gotten out of prison and goes to a
gun show and buys as many guns as he can afford without a criminal
background check,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   In light of their opposition to gun control proposals, Sandlin,
Hall and Turner are among the Democrats who receive campaign
contributions from the NRA.
</P>
<P>
   In the two years leading up to his 1998 election, Sandlin
received $14,400 from the NRA. That was more than any other Texas
House member, including powerful Republicans such as Majority
Leader Dick Armey of Irving and Majority Whip Tom Delay of Sugar
Land, who each received $9,900 from the group.
</P>
<P>
   Turner and Hall also benefit from NRA dollars. Turner received
$9,900 from the group in the last election cycle and has received
$4,950 for his latest reelection bid. Hall received $3,500 last
time and at least $2,000 for this year's election. Sandlin's
coffers include $3,000 in NRA contributions for his latest race.
</P>
<P>
   Much like the NRA, Turner believes that the solution to gun
violence lies in enforcing current laws instead of creating new
ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could get the guns out of the hands of convicted felons
who are walking around on parole and on probation in this country,
we would eliminate a lot of the problems that we're seeing with
regard to gun violence,'' he said. ``The law already prohibits
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards declined to comment on the opinions of his East Texas
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll let them speak for themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Eunice Moscoso can be reached by e-mail at
eunicem(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
