<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1860 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-LEWIS-PROSECUTOR01-CO     02-29 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-PROSECUTOR01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    District attorney in the hot seat amid Lewis trial
 &HT;    By Bill Torpy
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Producers for ``Court TV'' love blockbuster murder
trials. Prosecutors aren't as enamored.
</P>
<P>
   ``A high-profile case is a danger zone,'' said Gwinnett County
District Attorney Danny Porter. ``In any high-profile case, if it's
screwed up you're going to pay the price. And you don't get a lot
of credit if you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors are expected to win the big trials, he said. ``And
there's something in the back of your mind where you don't want to
make a fool out of yourself in front of a national audience.''
</P>
<P>
   While Fulton County District Attorney Paul Howard will probably
not be in the courtroom if Ray Lewis is tried on murder charges,
his name will be all over the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   And on the ballot this year.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, 48, has ratcheted up the stakes by quickly indicting
Lewis and two others in the stabbing deaths of two men after the
Super Bowl and by holding a news conference with Atlanta Mayor Bill
Campbell to announce the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Now, legal experts say, he'd better deliver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the only way Howard wins is if he convicts Lewis,''
said Mark Kadish, a law professor at Georgia State University who
has worked with Howard and Lewis' chief attorney, Ed Garland.
</P>
<P>
   Former Cobb County District Attorney Tom Charron knows the
importance of a big case. A botched murder prosecution led to his
election, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charron's opponent, District Attorney Buddy Darden, had
convictions on seven defendants thrown out by a federal judge in
the 1971 home invasion murders of Drs. Rosina and Warren Matthews.
Charron used that notorious case as a cudgel to beat the tar out of
Darden's incumbency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I got to be DA was the Matthews case,'' said
Charron, who now trains prosecutors at the National Advocacy Center
in Columbia. ``No question. That case propelled that election.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other lawyers, Atlanta defense lawyer Mark Spix
wonders why the defendants in the Buckhead case were indicted so
quickly. Defense attorneys can't seek a speedy trial until an
indictment is filed. Once that occurs _ as it did in the Lewis case
_ the meter is running. Meanwhile, police and prosecution
investigators are still running down witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see why I would hurry my investigation,'' said Spix, a
former prosecutor. ``Now they're looking at a trial before June.
Whoops. Hope they're ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the potential to bring (candidates for Fulton DA) out
of the woodwork,'' he said. ``People smell blood in the water. He's
vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard had appeared to be a shoo-in for re-election. He had
raised more than $65,000 in contributions since 1996 and until last
week had no opposition on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Page Pate, 32, a lawyer with no prosecutorial
experience, announced he will run for DA as a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past week, I've talked to former assistant (DAs),
some judges and defense attorneys,'' Pate said. ``There's a
desperate need for change in that office.''
</P>
<P>
   Pate says Howard's office uses little discretion in deciding
whether to bring charges against a suspect. ``He charges everyone
with everything,'' Pate said.
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying for the office begins in April, with primaries in
July.
</P>
<P>
   With jury selection in the Lewis case set to begin May 12,
voters will most likely know the outcome before the election.
</P>
<P>
   Howard, an accomplished trial lawyer turned administrator, set
his sites on his job long ago, constructing his resume and a strong
political base with aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Midville, a small town in Middle Georgia, Howard got
degrees from Morehouse College and Emory University law school. He
is married to Petrina Moody and has three children.
</P>
<P>
   He started as an assistant Atlanta solicitor. He then served as
a prosecutor for eight years under longtime Fulton DA Lewis Slaton
and later moved to defense work. His courtroom presence was so
powerful that some Gwinnett County jurors approached him for his
business card after they acquitted his client in a murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Howard was elected Fulton solicitor, but he was just
biding time. In a 1993 interview, longtime Howard friend and
campaign treasurer John Sweet predicted that Howard would one day
be Fulton's top prosecutor. Slaton retired and Howard was elected
in 1996 after a tough campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With a court-imposed gag order in the stabbings case, Howard
declined to be interviewed for this article. But Sweet, in an
interview last week, said, ``This next race is very important to
see if people are satisfied with his incumbency.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweet said an exodus of prosecutors from Howard's office and a
burgeoning caseload are ``growing pains. The fruit of his
innovations will be seen in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard enjoys a wide range of support, with contributions coming
from diverse sources, including Garland, Steve Sadow and Bruce
Harvey _ the high-profile attorneys for the three defendants in the
stabbing case; Mitch Skandalakis, the attack-dog conservative
Republican; and Phillip Morris, the tobacco company, which gave him
$1,000 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a sincere interest in getting bad guys off the
street,'' said Skandalakis, who as Fulton Commission chairman was
impressed by Howard's push for additional funding to hire more than
30 new prosecutors. ``There's not anyone out there who can beat
him. There's always some goofball lawyer out there who thinks he
can do better. Ain't gonna happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadow, like several other observers, believes Howard is shooting
for higher office. Sadow said the donations do not affect how
Howard deals with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire his judgment and work ethic,'' Sadow said. ``And if
he hit me up right now, I'd give him more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadow, who represents Joseph Sweeting in the stabbing case,
won't be very cozy with Howard for the next three months. Last
week, Sadow filed a motion that indicates he is exploring a
self-defense claim. And he joined in on the speedy trial request.
</P>
<P>
   The defense clearly is hoping to catch prosecutors with
incomplete investigations and a hastily prepared strategy. But the
prosecutors think 11 weeks is plenty of time to compile a strong
case.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing the quick indictment was not a bad strategy, says John
Turner, a former Fulton prosecutor who ran against Howard in 1996
and is considering another run this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were trying to avoid a preliminary hearing where
their case could be screwed up,'' Turner said. In a preliminary
hearing, defense attorneys draw out prosecution evidence and use
the opportunity to cross-examine prosecution witnesses and glean
the DA's strategy. ``You get a version of what they are saying and
you get them boxed in.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Lewis and his co-defendants are scheduled to be tried
together. Legal experts differ on how that will play out, but more
seem to think it helps the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Charron, the former Cobb prosecutor, said trying all three
together could hurt Lewis even if the jury finds that he didn't
stab either man, because ``you can paint all by the same brush.''
The prosecution has portrayed Lewis as a rich athlete who
surrounded himself with ``felons, drug dealers and thugs.'' Lewis'
co-defendants are convicted felons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, you can divide and conquer, put the screws to the
others,'' Charron said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, prosecuting all three men at one time increases
the chances that one will ``flip'' _ accept a deal with the
prosecutor and testify against his co-defendants, Charron said.
</P>
<P>
   Professor Kadish agrees that cutting a deal may be the key for
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're tried together, surely it would be good strategy
for (the DA's office) to make an offer that one of the purported
knifers couldn't resist _ to testify that Lewis was a party to the
crime,'' Kadish said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, lawyers who covet the Fulton DA job will be ``lurking
in the winds hoping (Howard) will lose,'' Kadish said.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be watching. And taking notes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1861 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-RAINBOW-PEOPLE01-COX     02-29 1890
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAINBOW-PEOPLE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Peace, love and grunginess
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OCALA NATIONAL FOREST, Fla. _ Jane La Flam is not ready to
accuse anyone of eating her dog.
</P>
<P>
   But someone needs to explain what happened to Beethoven. The
year-old German shepherd disappeared from La Flam's rural Lake
Eaton home when the Rainbow Family started arriving five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   No, she says flatly, it's not possible the dog ran away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved it at our house,'' she says. ``And what about the
four other dogs missing from our neighborhood? My 9-year-old still
cries about it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past 13 years, the Rainbow Family has had mid-February
gatherings in this 430,000-acre national forest 65 miles west of
Daytona Beach. Some people who live near the forest describe
Rainbows as peaceful, polite, flower children with a devout respect
for themselves, the earth and other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't bother anyone,'' says Barbara Slater, who lives in
Altoona. ``We've even picked a couple of them up in our pickup
truck. They always say `thank you.' If you had a problem on the
road, they'd probably help you.''
</P>
<P>
   And then you hear about dog-eating, shoplifting hippies who
gather in the forest to dance naked, smoke pot, trip on LSD and
have random sex.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the Rainbow People into the forest, and you'll find both
sides of the truth.
</P>
<P>
   COME ON PEOPLE NOW, SMILE ON YOUR BROTHER
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow People. The Rainbow Family. The Rainbow Family of Living
Light. Warriors of the Light.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the name, Rainbows take pride in a sketchy history, no
leaders, no membership numbers and no rules. Their shared
philosophy borrows from Native American folklore, Tibetan Buddhism,
Taoism, Hinduism or any other ``ism'' based on tolerance,
nonviolence, peace and love.
</P>
<P>
   To a Rainbow, the 9-to-5 world is Babylon.
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbow Family, they're fond of saying, is open to everyone
with a belly button. And this family ranges from 2-month-old
infants to aging Baby Boomers. Teen runaways are a chronic problem.
Marion County Sheriff's Lt. Mel Haun found two in the forest. But
many of the Ocala Rainbows were twenty-somethings _ college kids
with expensive, top-of-the-line camping gear _ as well as premature
burnouts and dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   Deputies and U.S. Forest Service workers say what surprises them
most about a Rainbow gathering are the BMWs, Jags and other
expensive cars parked near the camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were at least four lawyers, six registered nurses and
probably two doctors, but they were really quiet,'' says Barry
Sacharow, 44, a member of the governing Rainbow Council and a Fort
Lauderdale paralegal.
</P>
<P>
   The first Rainbow gathering was in 1972 near Strawberry Lake in
Colorado, when counterculture survivors extended an invitation to
Vietnam vets. The Rainbow Gathering theme, then as now, remains
``Welcome Home.'' The Vietnam vets brought survival skills to the
deep-woods party, and the counterculture brought a willingness to
learn and work.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what the two groups established 28 years ago and after
is the basis of gatherings such as the one in Ocala that ended
Sunday. Camps are set up with communal kitchens and a CALM (Center
for Alternative Living Medicine) tent. Single mothers with small
children camp at Kid Village. Rainbow veterans park their campers
at Bus Village. Teens camp at the Ghetto.
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow decisions are made by a fluid, ever-changing council
open to anyone who shows up at the meeting. Those making decisions
are called focalizers because they are willing and able to focus.
</P>
<P>
   There are regional gatherings, such as Ocala, and national and
international ones. The next annual U.S. meeting, expected to draw
more than 30,000, will happen somewhere in Montana, sometime around
July 4. Rainbow scouts have yet to find or announce a site.
</P>
<P>
   Even basic Rainbow information evolves at its own pace. Some
will find out through word of mouth, some on the Internet, some by
phone.
</P>
<P>
   THE CAMP
</P>
<P>
   The Rainbows at Ocala _ more than 2,000, says the group; more
like 1,000, says the U.S. Forest Service _ camped deep in the
forest of weathered cypress and stately pines.
</P>
<P>
   From the nearest dirt roads, it was a 2-mile hike to the camp's
hub, Main Circle, the site of nightly bonfires. You walked through
raw forest and along dry, grassy trails. There were no signs to
guide you.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of every winter meeting is the week leading up to the
Saturday night with a full moon that's closest to Feb. 14. If
there's no full moon, the first Saturday after Valentine's Day will
do.
</P>
<P>
   Some Rainbows, called Road Dogs, begin camping in October for
the February event. They are usually strapped for food, and this is
when the shoplifting and missing dog reports begin.
</P>
<P>
   With a full moon Feb. 19, there was a festive mood approaching
the gathering's big night.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, around noon, campers were crawling out of tents and from
under pieces of plastic and wet sleeping bags under trees. Maybe
there would be coffee or tea at the communal Shanghai Kitchen near
the Heart Fire. Maybe at the Aztec Groves Cafe, there would remain
some of the grapefruits that a skilled Dumpster Diver from Vermont
scored from a Costco trash bin in Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   Much like any city, there were popular stops. Zsu-Zsu's could be
loosely called a bakery with its sugar food, such as cookies and
Kool-Aid, to combat low blood sugar and dehydration. For
entertainment there was The Granola Funk Theater, offering
No-Talent, Talent and Skit nights. Various workshops were impromptu
_ drum tuning, weaving, guitar playing, herb tours or whatever
someone was willing to teach.
</P>
<P>
   At dusk the free kitchens served rice and beans.
</P>
<P>
   And then came the main event at the Main Circle's Heart Fire: a
bonfire built in a pit shaped like a heart.
</P>
<P>
   Campers, many with drums, circled the raging fire, some naked,
some too high to stand and take off their clothes. The party went
on all night, with the drummers and dancers becoming like machines
fueled by pot, hash and LSD. Under the stars and benevolent moon,
there were enough drugs to drum and sing and dance until the sun
rose and muscles finally gave out and, like the rising sun,
exhaustion couldn't be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   But that was night. Daytime was not so dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   When the sun warmed, there was skinny-dipping in any of the
half-dozen ponds and lakes, each home to alligators. Ask a Rainbow
man if that's not dangerous, and he'd tell you Brother Gator knows
Rainbows won't hurt him, ``but we have lost some of our dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from a stand of scrub pines into a clearing was a
scrawny kid dirty as tree bark. A striking woman passed him. She
was in her early 20s, dressed in crisp, clean, flowing Indian
gauze, purple and green. She looked like she could have been headed
to market in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morning, sister,'' the scrawny kid said as she followed the
path he just left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, brother.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the trees, within seconds she screamed,
``EEEEEE-YEWWW!''
</P>
<P>
   The scrawny kid froze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, sister, I forgot to cover it.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no restrooms at a Rainbow gathering.
</P>
<P>
   LOSE THE SOAP
</P>
<P>
   If you enter a Rainbow gathering with your pockets full of LSD,
bricks of hash and pot under each arm, and a bar of soap in hand,
you'll be told to lose the soap.
</P>
<P>
   Soap is not allowed. Rainbows say soap can pollute the forest's
rivers, lakes and ground water.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone shows up smelling from shampoo,'' says author and
Rainbow scholar Michael Niman, ``people are going to get all over
their case. It's an environmental thing.'' One benefit, he adds, is
that the smoky grime that covers everyone's skin is a natural bug
repellent.
</P>
<P>
   Arresting a Rainbow is dreaded by Marion County deputies because
of the long drive down U.S. 40 to jail in Ocala. ``They smell so
bad,'' says Lt. Haun, ``you've got to ride with the windows down.''
</P>
<P>
   The smell factor cuts down on more than mosquito bites, says
Niman, an American studies professor at the State University of New
York at Buffalo. He spent 13 years researching the Rainbow movement
for a doctoral thesis that became the 1997 book ``People of the
Rainbow: A Nomadic Utopia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's also why it's not the big orgy that the media makes it
out to be. The bottom line is that people smell bad after a few
days in the woods, and you don't want to get close to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spending a week in the woods is rough on human aesthetics.''
</P>
<P>
   `A' CAMP
</P>
<P>
   Some Rainbow brothers and sisters consider this winter camp the
Rolling Stones-At-Altamonte of gatherings. There are more drugs,
more losers and lunatics than at any other gathering.
</P>
<P>
   When campers start arriving, weeks or months before the actual
event, Haun and other Marion County Sheriff's deputies start
getting calls from grocery stores and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoplifting,'' Haun says, glumly, ``that's constant.''
</P>
<P>
   But it can get worse.
</P>
<P>
   In January, a man calling himself a Rainbow robbed a Winn-Dixie,
at one point holding a hunting knife to the manager's throat. He
was caught in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Haun, a 17-year veteran, has worked the past eight Rainbow
Gatherings from his sheriff's substation at the north end of the
forest. He says the bad guys aren't the real Rainbows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real Rainbows are just the hippie types in old, handmade
clothes,'' he begins. ``They're hard to describe, but they're not
the hard cases.''
</P>
<P>
   The hard cases are at ``A'' Camp.
</P>
<P>
   Rainbows segregate alcohol drinkers. Those people live at A Camp
at the north entrance. It's easily accessible for beer runs _ and
arrests. Every serious offense at the Ocala gathering was at A
Camp. A Rainbow who took a swing at a U.S. Forest Service law
enforcement officer was arrested. Two A Camp men were arrested for
beating each other with a baseball bat.
</P>
<P>
   A Camp is any Rainbow gathering's lunatic fringe. Panhandling at
the entrance. Breaking into cars. Breaking into fights. A-Campers
are known to wash down LSD with beer and liquor.
</P>
<P>
   The A Camp presents a philosophical dilemma for Rainbows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we have no leadership, we can't kick anybody out,''
says Sacharow. ``And you can't really call a Rainbow Gathering
nonviolent if you call the police with guns and clubs and handcuffs
to take away anybody who might be violent. Then you're not
nonviolent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an embarrassing reality that Utopia has a ghetto.''
</P>
<P>
   SO WHAT HAPPENED TO BEETHOVEN?
</P>
<P>
   Rainbow veteran Whistler, 53, says, ``I'm not going to sit here
and tell you a Rainbow never ate a dog.'' But then he added that
it's his experience, going back to the '72 gathering, that missing
local dogs usually go home when the camp breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Eating a dog sounds a bit bizarre and definitely un-Rainbow-like
to Niman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rainbows aren't about covering things up,'' he said. ``If
anyone had an inkling, they'd freak out at the thought that someone
was stealing dogs and eating them. You're dealing with a large
population of vegetarians who are horrified that people eat ham
sandwiches.''
</P>
<P>
   It's even more unlikely, says Niman, that the notorious
A-Campers and Road Dogs would harm a dog. ``These people live on
the road, and being hermits, often, their closest friends are their
dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
