<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 11:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1862 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-BLACKGISWW11-COX     02-29 1707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKGISWW11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bulge vet fought on two fronts: Enemy and discrimination
 &HT;    By Douglas Kalajian
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ In the Balkanized Boston of the 1930s
and '40s where Harold L. Vaughan grew up, every working-class kid
had a neighborhood to call his own.
</P>
<P>
   Irish neighborhoods, Jewish neighborhoods, Italian neighborhoods
and other ethnic enclaves all poured their progeny into public
schools that were among the best in the country and where the only
segregation was by gender.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys went to school with boys,'' recalls Vaughan, who grew up
in what was then called the colored neighborhood. ``We all got
along. You had friends from all over.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan discovered an uglier side of the world in his late teens
when he and his pal, Malcolm Little, quit their shoeshine jobs to
work on the railroad for the summer. Vaughan tried to hail a cab
during an overnight stop in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy at the cab stand told me, `Cabs for your people are
around the corner,''' he says. ``I just looked at him. He said,
`Cabs for colored people.' Then I understood. I was in the South.
But I was also in our nation's capital. That hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   He understood much more after a few trips farther down the line.
He was not accustomed to being called ``Boy,'' and he was not
interested in learning the peculiar regional rules of submissive
behavior _ much less running the risks that came with ignoring
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson I learned was not to get off the train,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   A few summers later, Vaughan was once again on a train heading
south, and this time he had no choice but to get off where he was
told and to follow orders, no matter how degrading.
</P>
<P>
   Like millions of other Americans during World War II, he'd been
drafted into the Army.
</P>
<P>
   But the armed forces that swallowed up Vaughan and nearly a
million other blacks were almost entirely separate from white
units, with little pretense of being equal. Even during the
costliest combat in the Pacific and Europe, nearly all blacks were
held back from the fight. Most were assigned to support roles:
packing supplies, loading ammunition, driving trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan, who had been working at the Watertown Arsenal before he
was drafted, was sent to the Aberdeen Proving Grounds in Maryland
for training in Army weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   ``That became a horrible experience,'' he says. ``Maryland might
as well have been the Deep South. Colored troops would go into town
and do something that was perfectly normal back home and get
arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan decided to stay on base until his training was done and
a troop ship carried him to England as a replacement member of the
3077th Ordnance Motor Vehicle Distributing Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day after we landed, I was on my way to pick up my winter
uniform when I heard someone call, `Hey, Vaughan,''' he recalls.
``I looked over and saw prisoners in blue denim uniforms. I
recognized one of the prisoners as a friend. I went over and asked
what in the world had happened.''
</P>
<P>
   His friend, a black American soldier, had arrived in England
earlier. He quickly discovered that each time a dance was held for
servicemen, the black companies were sent on overnight bivouac.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night, a few of the Boston guys refused to go,'' Vaughan
says. ``They rebelled. Insubordination. They got six months in the
stockade. That's the sort of situation you'd run into.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan did his best to steer clear of insurrection as well as
indignities. Most black soldiers did the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 80 percent of the troops in my company were Southern,
and they were accustomed to white supervision,'' he says. ``A few
of us Northerners had a problem with it. But when in Rome, you do
as the Romans do _ and you shut your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan was assigned to an office job and eventually promoted to
technical sergeant. He remembers frequent lectures from the white
captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd tell us not to mess up any of the vehicles, because it's
a lot of time and work to get a replacement for a government
vehicle,'' Vaughan says. ``But he told us we could be replaced with
no problem. He'd say, `Go ahead and get yourselves killed. I don't
care.'''
</P>
<P>
   The risks increased as the company crossed the English Channel
after the Allies invaded France in June 1944. Vaughan got to Paris
soon after it was liberated. He was surprised to see black
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``They turned out to be old American soldiers who stayed after
World War I,'' he says. ``They didn't see any point in going back
to Mississippi or Alabama. They found a more comfortable life over
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3077th was assigned to deliver tanks and trucks loaded with
guns and ammunition from a depot in Cherbourg, France, to fighting
units that were spreading rapidly toward Germany. As the supply
line known as the Red Ball Express strained to keep up with the
advancing troops, Vaughan was called out from behind his desk and
pressed into service as a driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put me in a big Sherman tank,'' he says. ``It had a
diagram that showed how to start it. All they told me was that it's
simple to drive _ you pull this lever, you steer it like this. It
took off like a shotgun shell.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan fell into line and followed the other tanks along a dirt
road, but they churned up a dust cloud that was impossible to see
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden _ bang, I felt stunned,'' he says. ``There was
a sharp right turn that I didn't see. I went straight through a
brick wall and and down into a drive bed, wedged between two giant
oak trees.''
</P>
<P>
   The concussion knocked him out. Vaughan doesn't know how much
time passed before the other tank drivers realized he was missing
and rescued him. His injuries were serious enough to merit a
partial disability award _ but not until the war was over. Soon
after the crash, he was back behind the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Supplies were just beginning to catch up with Allied troops when
the Germans came roaring back across the Belgian border in December
1944, setting off the Battle of the Bulge. Scrambling to avoid
becoming trapped, many American units abandoned tanks, arms and
other supplies. The 3077th rushed fresh ordnance to the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd load up a truck, hook a cannon on the back and take
off,'' Vaughan says. The snow and ice that made fighting in the
Ardennes Forest difficult made driving nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The dark made things even worse; tape covered all but a thin
slit of each headlight to avoid drawing fire from enemy planes.
There was also no time for rest. Truck drivers got little more
sleep than GIs in foxholes, and even the ever-louder echo of
exploding shells didn't always keep them alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were driving through Belgium, and I'd gone two days without
sleep,'' Vaughan says. ``I fell asleep at the wheel. I drove into a
gully and over a big rock. That jolted me. I automatically hit the
brake. There was a massive tree right in front of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan and the other drivers finally reached their destination
near Bastogne, Belgium, but they did not see the company of
embattled troops who were to receive their supplies. ``We searched
around and found three infantry guys,'' he says. ``They said they
were the only ones left alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3077th dropped off the supplies for the expected replacement
troops but found the return road blocked by fresh fighting. They
meandered along unfamiliar back roads until they came to an
American command post. Their relief quickly turned to anger when
the guard insisted on proof that the black soldiers weren't Germans
in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guard started asking us questions like, `Who's Joe
DiMaggio? Who's Mickey Mouse?''' Vaughan says. ``I asked him: `Have
you ever seen a colored German?' They finally let us pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The 3077th kept up the deliveries throughout the six-week battle
and until the Allied victory in May 1945. Vaughan expected to be
sent to the Pacific, where fighting continued, but instead got a
discharge when his father died. He returned to Boston unsettled by
his experience in the segregated Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``The colored troops had to fight on two fronts _ the enemy and
discrimination,'' he says. ``I was so cynical about the Army and
about the country that I was uncomfortable with how I felt.''
</P>
<P>
   For Vaughan, the antidote to cynicism was politics. Soon after
the war, he started selling real estate and campaigning for
Democrats in local and state elections. He worked hard on John F.
Kennedy's campaigns for Congress, Senate and president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack told me something I never forgot,'' he says. ``He said,
`Your people don't have money, but they can vote. Your vote counts
the same as mine. It's the great equalizer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughan's help in turning out the vote won him friends in high
places. He got a job as aide to Boston Mayor John B. Hynes and was
put in charge of arranging ceremonies for visiting dignitaries. He
got to hobnob with Louis Armstrong, Jimmy Durante, Emperor Haile
Selassie of Ethiopia and Queen Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to become Boston's tax assessor for 30 years. He also
became a lawyer and ran for lieutenant governor of Massachusetts in
1964. ``I lost, but I had a great time,'' he says. Now 75, he is
retired and living with his wife, Josephine, in Palm Beach Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Among his many memorable encounters over the years was a visit
from his old shoeshine pal, Malcolm Little. While Vaughan went off
to the Army, Little went off to prison after becoming a burglar and
petty thief. He was also moved by his experience and turned to
politics of a different sort. He changed his name to Malcolm X.
</P>
<P>
   The Armed Forces were officially desegregated in 1948 by order
of President Harry Truman. No black servicemen were awarded the
Medal of Honor for World War II heroics until 1997, when seven
awards were granted simultaneously. Six were posthumous.
</P>
<P>
   To Vaughan, the contributions of black troops are still largely
unrecognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did what we were asked to do, even though the treatment was
unbelievable,'' he says. ``Although we were mostly in support
units, the work was essential. The fact remains, they couldn't have
won the war without us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
