<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0089 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 11:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1863 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i BC-VIETNAM-PHOTOS01-COX     02-29 2224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-PHOTOS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reflections on a war
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ James Gillam didn't choose to be in Vietnam. Sean
Flynn did.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1970, the two young Americans found themselves
in the jungles of the central highlands as U.S. troops launched the
invasion of Cambodia. Gillam, an indifferent student who had lost
his deferment and been drafted, was leading an Army infantry unit.
Flynn, the thrill-seeking son of actor Errol Flynn, was a
free-lance photographer who liked to race ahead of the other
journalists on a red Honda motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was living the swashbuckling roles his father had played in
the movies,'' says Gillam, who got to know Flynn as a drinking
buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Gillam's unit was engaged in a firefight across the Cambodian
border. He heard a motorcycle engine and knew Flynn must be near.
When the shooting stopped, soldiers discovered a riderless cycle
with the motor running. They searched but never found the
photographer.
</P>
<P>
   Now a history professor at Spelman College, Gillam has been
thinking about that firefight again because of an exhibition
opening today at the Atlanta History Center. ``Requiem'' displays
more than 200 pictures taken by the 135 photographers who died or
went missing during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   The renowned Robert Capa was among the first. Life magazine's
Larry Burrows was among the last. Flynn and scores of others died
or vanished in between.
</P>
<P>
   They took some of the most memorable images of the war. A
captured Viet Cong sniper hangs upside down like a trophy marlin. A
helicopter crew chief breaks down crying after a bloody mission. A
medic, his head swaddled in bandages, cradles the head of another
wounded soldier.
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost 25 years since the war ended with the fall of
Saigon in April 1975. To mark the occasion, the History Center
assembled a panel of veterans, refugees, journalists and scholars
to advise it on programs to go along with ``Requiem.''
</P>
<P>
   They see different things in the powerful images by the dead and
missing photographers. They would. There were many viewpoints, many
experiences, many private wars in Vietnam. Here are a few of them.
</P>
<P>
   THE GOOD SOLDIER
</P>
<P>
   If Bill Poole has mixed emotions about ``Requiem,'' perhaps it's
because he has such definite opinions about the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of what I did in Vietnam,'' says the 55-year-old
lawyer, a member of the Atlanta Vietnam Veterans Business
Association. ``I think we were right to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole grew up in Lithonia and went to the U.S. Military Academy
on a football and scholastic appointment. After he graduated, the
Army taught him Vietnamese and shipped him to the Mekong Delta in
1968 as a district adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived with those people. Ate with them. Spoke their
language. When I entered the district, it had been overrun by the
Viet Cong. We reopened roads and canals. We helped conduct village
elections. That's a side of the war you don't usually see.''
</P>
<P>
   You don't see much of it in ``Requiem.'' The show reflects the
media's understandable focus on the progress of the war. It dwells
on the guts and grit of combat, not the intangible battles for the
hearts and minds of the Vietnamese.
</P>
<P>
   Poole certainly experienced the former; he saw a U.S. soldier
blown apart by a 3-year-old child booby-trapped with a bomb. But he
prefers to remember other aspects of the war; his Atlanta office
has a photo of a grateful Vietnamese woman on the day the Americans
reopened her village market.
</P>
<P>
   When Poole was sent back to the States in 1969, his superiors
warned him not to wear his uniform in airports. America was turning
against the war; the military was plummeting in popularity. He
enrolled at the University of Georgia law school and sought the
counsel of its best-known professor, Dean Rusk, the former
secretary of state who had been a key figure in formulating U.S.
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still agree with him,'' Poole says. ``If we hadn't stood up
to the Communists in Vietnam, all Southeast Asia would have gone
Communist. I've thought about it a lot. It seems like half my
football team at the academy got killed over there. I still think
it was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   Poole admires the pictures in ``Requiem'' and respects the
courage of the people who took them. But if he had his way,
photojournalists would never again get that close to U.S. troops in
combat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole time I was in Vietnam,'' he says, ``my wife tried to
avoid the TV news because she was afraid she'd see her husband get
killed. It's probably good to restrict media access during war.
Most Americans aren't ready to see that sort of thing. If we hadn't
had some of the coverage in Vietnam, maybe we would have been
allowed to fight the war and win it.''
</P>
<P>
   THE NATIVE DAUGHTER
</P>
<P>
   Yung Krall finds it difficult to look at the photos in
``Requiem.'' That's her country being destroyed, her people being
killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``So painful,'' she says. ``So sad.''
</P>
<P>
   One of at least 20,000 Vietnamese in metro Atlanta, the
54-year-old Krall counsels immigrants as director of multinational
relations at Emory Northlake Regional Medical Center. When she
talks with refugees from Kosovo or some other war zone, she
understands what they're going through personally.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam War split Krall's family. Her father, a member of
the Communist Politburo, abandoned his wife and children in the
Mekong Delta. They opposed communism and moved frequently, changing
their names to avoid reprisals. She left the country in 1968,
marrying a U.S. Navy pilot and moving to America. Her 1995 memoir,
``A Thousand Tears Falling,'' is banned in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Requiem'' was first shown in 1997 at the Newseum in
Arlington, Va., some Vietnamese protested because they considered
it soft on communism. Krall warned the History Center that the same
thing might happen here.
</P>
<P>
   But she has another, contradictory reaction to the pictures:
pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go around the country talking to groups, people think
the South Vietnamese did not fight. I'm grateful the U.S. fought
for our freedom. But we had been fighting for it all our lives. You
couldn't be a draft dodger in Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   Krall lost four relatives in the fighting, on both sides. If she
were putting together a ``Requiem'' for them, the photos would show
the impact of the fighting on Vietnamese civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see people fleeing from a burning village. The VC have
mortared the elementary school with artillery they've bought from
Americans on the black market. Women and children are dead. They're
buried in a mass grave.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she hasn't been back since the North Vietnamese took
Saigon and renamed it Ho Chi Minh City, the country hasn't loosened
its grip on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to people about Vietnam twice a week, and I always tear
up,'' she says. ``Gosh, yes, I still love it. I love America, too,
because it adopted me. But Vietnam is blood.''
</P>
<P>
   THE STUDENT AND TEACHER
</P>
<P>
   At 51, Marc Gilbert has been teaching and writing about Vietnam
for 19 years as a history professor at North Georgia College and
State University in Dahlonega. He's researching a book on the war
and the American South, a subject he'll talk about during a panel
discussion March 25 at the History Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnam War had a distinctly Southern flavor. Many of the
men who prosecuted it were Southerners _ President Lyndon B.
Johnson (Texas), Secretary of State Rusk (Georgia), General William
Westmoreland (South Carolina). With its long fighting tradition and
profusion of military bases, the South ranked as the most hawkish
region of the country in public opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even here, there was an anti-war movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It paralleled the rest of the nation, running slightly
behind,'' Gilbert says. ``The biggest difference is that is wasn't
fashionable to speak out here like it was elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   It definitely wasn't fashionable at Gilbert's school. ``This is
a military college,'' he says. ``They had a streaker, but I don't
think they had an anti-war protest.''
</P>
<P>
   The politics of peace was complicated in the South by the civil
rights movement. Anti-war activists were assumed to be pro-civil
rights, Gilbert says, and that made them doubly subversive in the
eyes of the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most famous photos in ``Requiem'' mutely addresses
the intertwining of the two great issues of the '60s. Taken by
Larry Burrows, the image ran across two pages of Life magazine in
1966, at a time when the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. was taking the
civil rights movement north. It shows a wounded black Marine
staggering toward a mud-caked white Marine in a first-aid camp.
Green fatigues, brown mud, crimson blood _ these colors, the photo
testifies, are the only ones that matter in battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A picture like that,'' Gilbert says, ``is worth more than a
thousand words.''
</P>
<P>
   THE OTHER SHOOTERS
</P>
<P>
   Lon Holmberg was a photographer in Vietnam, but you won't see
any work from his colleagues in ``Requiem.'' They toted cameras for
the U.S. Army. For the most part, the exhibition includes only
photographers who worked for accredited media.
</P>
<P>
   Now a documentary filmmaker in Orange, Va., the 55-year-old
Holmberg will be part of a panel discussion on Vietnam reporting
today at the History Center. He was curious how many military
photographers died during the war, so he asked the National
Archives to research the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said there were 17 through 1970,'' Holmberg says.``I
imagine there were more. I want to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   Military photographers had the full range of Vietnam
experiences, from combat to shooting grip-and-grin's for the Army
press and small-town papers back home. Holmberg volunteered to go
out with the troops and arrived in the field just as the invasion
of Laos was beginning in 1971. After four months, he gladly
retreated to Saigon to take pictures for Gen. Creighton Abrams, the
U.S. commander.
</P>
<P>
   That's where he came closest to getting shot _ by friendly fire,
no less.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Henry Kissinger flew in to meet with Abrams.
Their motorcade was getting ready to pull out when Holmberg
realized he didn't have a seat. An admiral said he could ride with
him, and he ducked into the car, almost lethally surprising a
Secret Service agent in the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spun around and pointed a nickel-plated revolver at me and
said, `I should have shot you.''' Holmberg laughs. ``Probably too
much coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   THE RELUCTANT WARRIOR
</P>
<P>
   James Gillam teaches a seminar on Vietnam at Spelman College. A
few years ago, a student interrupted him: ``Can we stop this? My
father died there. I never met him. This is all a bit heavy for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gillam, a 53-year-old father of three, knows how she felt.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam was particularly vexing for a young black man in the
'60s. A disproportionate number of the early casualties were
suffered by working-class minorities. When Gillam took charge of
his infantry unit in 1969, more than 40 percent of the men were
black or Latino.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland native was already opposed to the war. His opinion
started to turn when he saw how his brother, a Marine, was treated
in Vietnam. His platoon left him for dead in the field, sick with
malaria and dysentery; an Army unit found him walking around in
delirium.
</P>
<P>
   As if that weren't enough, Gillam had a scrape with bigotry
after he was drafted and sent south for training. He got in a fight
when a bar near his base refused to serve him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to die for American foreign policy, and they
wouldn't even serve me a drink in Leesville, La.?'' he says. ``It
made me think.''
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Vietnam proved every bit as nasty as Gillam had
heard it would be. He caught a bullet in the knee, shrapnel in the
chest and forehead, and was briefly taken prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was body count,'' he says. ``You'd stay in the
jungle until you got your quota. There'd be arguments over parts.
Can you count a single leg as a kill? Does that puddle of blood
count?''
</P>
<P>
   After he was discharged, Gillam joined the Vietnam Veterans
Against the War and was arrested at a demonstration. He also ran a
veterans rehabilitation program and went back to college with an
emphasis in Asian history. He's taught at Spelman since 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Gillam has always wondered what happened to Sean Flynn, the
dashing young photographer he met in the jungle almost 30 years
ago. He feared the worst; neither Flynn nor his corpse ever
appeared. But no one knew for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Requiem'' has answered the question. The exhibition grew out
of an effort to discover the fate of Flynn and another
motorcycle-riding photographer who vanished with him that day, Dana
Stone.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Page, a fellow photographer who had been wounded in Vietnam,
went back 10 years ago to investigate the journalist MIAs. Based on
government intelligence and interviews with villagers, he concluded
that guerrillas had held the two captive for 13 months before
finally executing them. Locals identified them from pictures. One
old man offered three teeth that he said came from the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gillam hadn't heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did kill him?'' he says. ``Well, damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey is a staff writer for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
