<SLUG> BC-TESTDRIVE-LANDROVER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Land Rover Discovery ready for civilization
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For anyone who's about to venture into real unpaved
territory and wants a vehicle that's thoroughly tough, determined
and not likely to remind you constantly of the family sedan,
there's nothing quite like the Land Rover Discovery II.
</P>
<P>
   While not the ultimate Rover, the Discovery is just fine for
tooling around the American outback, suburbs and city. It's
base-priced at $34,150 but can be had with enough options to push
the total to the test vehicle's $43,875. Bigger and stronger Range
Rovers go for $59,000 and $67,300 and are suitable for just about
anywhere on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Land/Range Rover name conjures images from old Field
and Stream stories of hardy outdoorsmen and brutally
rough-and-ready vehicles, look elsewhere. Today's Discovery is
quite civilized despite having a trucklike ride, a tall body that
makes entry and exit a bit strenuous and driving characteristics
far removed from the image of vehicles marketed by parent company
BMW.
</P>
<P>
   To many, Range/Land Rover is the benchmark of sport-utilities,
and it's a well-earned tag. After a near-total overhaul last year,
the Discovery emerged longer (185.2 inches), wider (74.4 inches)
and roomier (seating for five or seven with a maximum 63.3 cubic
feet of cargo room).
</P>
<P>
   It's not losing ground in the race for the upper end of the
mainstream market. Nor is the Discovery falling behind in off-road
capability. It catches flak in the power department because its
4.0-liter V-8 makes but 188 horsepower. But it makes 250
pounds-feet of torque at 2,600 engine rpm, and that's enough to
climb seriously rugged terrain. The getting-down process is
smoothed by Discovery's hill descent control, which uses the brakes
to help slow the 4,500-pound Discovery when it's in low range.
</P>
<P>
   While that feature may not mean much to owners in everyday use,
Discovery's optional cornering enhancement package ($2,900) is
easily appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   It allays fears of the tall (76.4 inches) vehicle rolling and
pitching in turns and keeps it on a near-level keel.
</P>
<P>
   The interior, too, is modernized with self-dimming lighting,
drink holders and comfortable seats. Front and side visibility is
great because of seat height and wraparound glass, but rear
visibility is poor because of the rear-mounted spare tire and when
there's a middle passenger in the third seat (the headrest also can
be a problem).
</P>
<P>
   The nicely packaged instrumentation is quickly read, and
controls are sensibly arrayed, although familiarity is vital and
the ignition switch is awkwardly positioned on the steering column.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel mileage, as might be expected of the V-8 powerplant, is a
weak point, with premium gasoline recommended. The EPA figures of
13 and 17 mpg city and highway, respectively, are difficult to
match.
</P>
<P>
   The mud-and-show radials that are standard on Discovery are fine
for those situations, but are noisy and send vibration into the
cabin at speed on paved surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe that's Discovery's way of reminding that its heritage
and capabilities are not predicated on having optimal driving
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Test vehicle: 2000 Land Rover Discovery II four-wheel-drive
sport utility vehicle
</P>
<P>
   Price as tested: $43,875 (base: $34,150, plus $625 delivery fee)
</P>
<P>
   Drivetrain: 4.0-liter V-8 engine (188 horsepower), four-speed
automatic transmission with sport mode and two-speed transfer
gearbox
</P>
<P>
   Safety features: dual front and seat-mounted side air bags,
front and rear door impact beams, power anti-lock disc brakes,
traction control, optional active cornering enhancement system
($2,900, includes 18-inch alloy wheels, speed-rated radial tires)
</P>
<P>
   Other options on test vehicle: package with dual power sunroofs,
third-row seats, rear-step, self-leveling suspension, rear audio
controls, $3,250; heated seats and windshield, $500
</P>
<P>
   EPA figures: 13 mpg premium unleaded city, 17 mpg highway
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
