<HEADER>
A1868 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN01-COX     02-29 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Challenge: To see young dads in added dimensions
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Talk about a tough sell. Michael Hayes is vending
Slushies in an ice storm. Before an audience mostly of females,
many who work with teen moms every day, he asks them to see the
young dad's side of things.
</P>
<P>
   The seminar is ``The Father Factor: Understanding the
Significance of Male Involvement in Teen Pregnancy.'' Hey, we know
the male significance. It's like that calculus song on MTV:
</P>
<P>
   ``You plus me equals us.''
</P>
<P>
   And baby makes three? Figure again, Babe, because I'm
subtracting me.
</P>
<P>
   Tough sell. As director of the Austin-based Texas Fragile
Families Initiative, Hayes rises to the challenge often, as he did
here recently at a seminar sponsored by Planned Parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes said that when society dismisses the male's role in teen
parenting, it can make a bad situation worse. First, having an
adversarial relationship makes it tougher to get dads to follow
through on child support. Second, a nonwarring relationship and a
partnership can make life better for a child.
</P>
<P>
   Fragile families, as defined by a Ford Foundation initiative,
are young, never-married parents and their children. Tellingly,
rather than advocacy for either gender, the initiative is
``child-centered.''
</P>
<P>
   If arithmetic is of the essence, Hayes says it's compelling.
Among young dads who have no contact with their children, less than
a third pay child support. And that includes some fathers who want
contact.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they feel they're being pushed out of the picture, why
keep trying?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes has no illusions that the average pairing in tender years
is going to result in marriage. Indeed, he assumes mother and
father will live and grow apart. He discourages the term
``co-parenting.'' After all, a child can only live in one house.
What he encourages is ``team parenting'' _ meaning that though
there's a starting squad, a mom and most likely her parents,
there's someone in reserve, a biological dad, ready and willing to
handle the ball, baby-sit, almost serve as a business partner.
</P>
<P>
   Contact is key, said Hayes. Contact equals support, or at least
that's the idea. Something about those peepers, that baby talk,
will make a dad want to act like a dad in ways he can.
</P>
<P>
   In the audience were representatives of the Texas attorney
general's office, trying to get some tips on how to bring young
fathers into the fold without ropes, chains or subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   Also on-hand as part of a panel were three young fathers from
San Angelo. Its Healthy Families Program is a model from which 13
similar efforts are to start this summer, including one in Waco to
be administered by Camp Fire.
</P>
<P>
   Some people will point out that the concept ``healthy family''
is already breached and broken when a teen bears a child. Healthy
Families seeks only to make the best out of a bad, but too common,
situation.
</P>
<P>
   To get the seminar participants past the stick figures in their
heads, Hayes handed out markers to small groups. Draw a father.
Give him the features he needs.
</P>
<P>
   A cumulative portrait was far more than skull and bones. You had
big ears, for listening. You had big feet, for stability. The
cumulative dad had eyes to be observant, long arms for sharing, a
shoulder for leaning. He had a smile for sharing a sense of joy,
and a heart that leaped off the page.
</P>
<P>
   This cumulative father was no Fabio. But he was no
one-dimensional cut-out. Hayes' point is is that if we want young
fathers' help, we'd better see them in more than 1-D.
</P>
<P>
   We are all aware of the fact that too many males, though they
supply the plumbing and the DNA, are miserable at fathering. The
point of Hayes' sales job is that when it comes to potential _
eyes, ears, feet, arms and heart _ every father is anatomically
correct.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
