<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Toyota touting its sporty MR2 Spyder to online crowd
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Toyota is joining the roadster revolution in bringing
back the MR2, a limited-production sports car that developed an
almost cultlike following. The new MR2 Spyder is Toyota's first
convertible-only vehicle, but one backed with 15 years of history.
</P>
<P>
   The fanfare that is accompanying the introduction is edgy, meant
to appeal to young and hip buyers who are skilled Internet users.
Instead of the customary media hype in print, television and radio,
Toyota is going online. The campaign, in fact, is similar to the
evolution of the MR2.
</P>
<P>
   The new MR2 Spyder, with only 5,000 units expected annually,
looks similar to the Porsche Boxster. It will face competition in a
segment that is seeing new entries almost every year. Starting with
the Mazda Miata, the roadster niche has filled quickly with entries
from BMW, DaimlerChrysler and Honda, with Ford and General Motors
soon to follow.
</P>
<P>
   The new MR2 is a departure from the larger, heavier 1991-95
series that shared many components with the Celica. The new MR2
returns more to its roots. The original cars offered from 1984 to
'90 were lighter and based on the Corolla.
</P>
<P>
   While the early MR2 produced a following among enthusiasts,
there were problems. It wasn't the cars themselves, but the way
people drove them. Always with a mid-engine configuration, the
early MR2s handled so well that less-skilled drivers frequently
would get in over their heads and lose control of the vehicle. That
led to the heavier, more stable second generation.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent similar problems in the new MR2, Toyota has stretched
the wheelbase and engineered in an inherent understeer
characteristic. It's due in showrooms this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Back to that cult following.
</P>
<P>
   The more than 40,000 owners of previous MR2s and more than 100
Web sites dedicated to the marque had an effect on Toyota's MR2
marketing strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the Echo and Celica as the third member of Toyota's
``genesis plan'' for the youth market, the MR2 ad campaign began
with pre-launch commercials on the Internet, followed with
product-specific ads in publications such as Premiere and Wired.
Perhaps the more novel angles are a relationship marketing program
designed to hold the interest of customers on the
``waiting-to-purchase'' list and the concept that the message and
media will be crafted to appeal to consumers willing to work hard
to keep up with new trends.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are directed to www.isthistoyota.com, a
video-enhanced, nearly text-free site. Toyota claims to have
designed the site to encourage repeat visits.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a mid-engine, reasonably priced convertible sports
car is appealing. The idea of being pleased to ``wait to purchase''
_ that could be another story. But it's been some time since I fell
into the category that Toyota is targeting for the MR2.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sharp, a training consultant to auto manufacturers, writes
for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
