<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ Few sights are sadder than that of new love,
just lit, guttering out before its flame can come to full glow.
Yet, alas, there's no getting around it: annulment seems the
certain future for Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger. Cupid, come next
February, may be tempted to swap his quiver for a Kalishnikov.
(Teepen, Cox News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ MIAMI _ These are the best of days for Fidel
Castro. How he must be chortling. As he has been so capable of
doing over the past four decades, he has solidified his rule based
on a highly successful ``offended party syndrome.'' (Kleinberg, Cox
News Service.) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   MURRAY-COLUMN _ DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: A magnolia tree
stood straight and tall on a narrow ridge at the northeast end of
Big Pond, and next to it a giant holly, and next to the holly a
giant white oak, the sentinel of the ridge. On the smooth bark of
the magnolia were carved the letters LUM BENSON, the landmark for
my grandfather, my dad, my son in our hunting territory.
(Irvine/Murray, Cox News Service). MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ There is an indefinable age
at which folks begin to scan the morning paper's obit section, not
so much to see who has left in the night, but to reassure
themselves that whoever it was, he or she was a lot older than
they. (Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   YOUNG-COLUMN _ WACO, Texas _ when society dismisses the male's
role in teen parenting, it can make a bad situation worse. First,
having an adversarial relationship makes it tougher to get dads to
follow through on child support. Second, a nonwarring relationship
and a partnership can make life better for a child. (Young, Waco
Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
