<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1876 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-THE-MECHANIC01-COX     02-29 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Continuing education a priceless tool
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Contrary to the opinion of my teen-age son, I believe
that when one has learned all there is to know, it's time to meet
your maker.
</P>
<P>
   I am continually humbled by life's daily lessons. Although I
bear the credentials of a journeyman/master mechanic with almost 30
years in the automotive profession, my quest for knowledge must
equal or exceed my students'.
</P>
<P>
   I preach and practice the value of continuing automotive
education and training. My personal update training commitment
often exceeds 100 hours a year in manufacturers' and aftermarket
classes. The investment proves its worth when the knowledge I
gained guides me through a repair I would have been unable to
perform without it.
</P>
<P>
   I can teach tomorrow's mechanics what is coming, not just what
has been. I also tell them that for every dollar they spend on
tools, they must put aside another dollar for training. It isn't
cheap, but it's priceless. A $30,000 tool inventory locked up in a
shiny red box may look impressive, but it doesn't mean you can fix
cars.
</P>
<P>
   Too many people in the profession have an aversion to continuing
their educations and honing their skills. I've heard all of the
excuses: ``It's too expensive'' or ``I'm too tired after work'' or
``I don't need to know that stuff anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Year after year, I continue to see the same faces in most of the
classes I attend. About 20 percent of the mechanics out there are
pursuing the skills they need, but 80 percent are muddling through
and changing parts. This certainly is among the reasons why the
public perceives mechanics poorly and why we have so many consumer
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   When you take your car in for repairs, ask to see the
credentials of the person who will be working on it. These include
ASE certifications and documentation of continued training. Don't
settle for ``Don't worry, our guys are experts.''
</P>
<P>
   Training costs the mechanic and the shop both time and money.
Typically, the cost of a two-night class is $160 to $190.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers can sign their people up for manufacturers' training but
must pay the mechanic for the time he is in school while losing the
revenue he would have made at the shop. This additional cost of
doing business right is passed on to the consumer, usually
reflected in the shop's labor rate.
</P>
<P>
   It may not appear to be a bargain coming in the door, but it
could be the best bargain you've ever driven.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of bargains, this is for mechanics and motorists who
want to improve the quality of the repairs they are receiving. I
have a ``no excuses'' deal for you.
</P>
<P>
   The Automotive Service Association of Georgia (www.asashop.org)
is hosting its third annual 2EXCEL high-tech training and expo on
March 4. This event is open to professionals and is part of the
ASA's commitment to continuing education and service excellence.
</P>
<P>
   The seminars offer a plethora of subjects ranging from collision
and paint for body shops to solid-state and lab scope diagnostics
to automotive management training. The classes will be conducted by
some of the industry's most distinguished instructors.
</P>
<P>
   I have attended the 2EXCEL training classes for the past two
years, always leaving with my brain and my stomach stuffed.
Besides, it's the social event of the mechanics' season. For
information on 2EXCEL, call Jonelle Cellucci at ASA of Georgia,
(770) 455-9326.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Carter, who has 27 years of experience in the auto repair
industry, writes for Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
