   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SLEEP-APNEA (Troy, N.Y.) _ Michael I. Savic, a sound specialist
and engineering professor at Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute, is
working to perfect a computer program that can detect potentially
fatal episodes of sleep apnea. This would offer physicians an
easier and cheaper way to diagnose their patients. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   NAIL-DISEASE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Nail infections affect up to 5
percent of Americans, causing nails to become brittle, dry,
discolored. In some cases, the infections are so severe that they
can cause pain with walking or grasping objects. Recently, the
government approved a nail polish, the first ever, to treat
hard-to-heal fungus infections and is expect to be on pharmacy
shelves soon. By SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MONEY-COLUMN (Houston) _ Nearly 55,000 homes were sold in
Houston last
</P>
<P>
   year, the most ever in one year. Since selling a home is not a
yearly
</P>
<P>
   event for most people, this tax season may be confusing to those
who
</P>
<P>
   have to account for those sales on their tax returns. By SHANNON
BUGGS
</P>
