<HEADLINE>
WINE OF THE WEEK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: For release Friday, March 3) 
 
By MICHAEL LONSFORD  
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
For March 3, 2000 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ Today is the 153rd anniversary of the birth of Alexander
Graham Bell. Where was Bell born? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Today is also the 105th anniversary of the birth of U.S. Army
Gen. Matthew Ridgeway, who led the 82nd Airborne Division in World
War II. For what was Ridgeway famous during the Korean War? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week's featured wine is worth a long-distance call or two,
because it's both tasty, different and imminently affordable. The
 &UR; 1998 Abbaye de Valmagne Blanc  &LR; _ 4 stars _ is a blend of unusual
grapes that works out very well as a seafood wine. This dear Abbaye
is brisk, crisp, with a bit of mineraly-earthy quality, and it's
from one of France's oldest vineyards, dating back to 1138.
</P>
<P>
   The $10.99 won't outrank your budget, either. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANSWERS:
</P>
<P>
   _ Edinburgh, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   _ He replaced Gen. Douglas MacArthur in Korea in 1951, after
MacArthur was fired for threatening massive retaliation against
Communist China.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WINE RATING: &QL; 
5 stars _ outstanding &QL; 
4 stars _ fine &QL; 
3 stars _ good &QL; 
2 stars _ fair &QL; 
1 star _ poor &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
