<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAIL-DISEASE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TREATING NAIL INFECTIONS CAN BE A MEAN FEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SYLVIA WOOD  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Barbara Ross-Cassidy spends all day working on
hands and feet, clipping, filing and polishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell a lot about somebody by their nails,'' said
Ross-Cassidy, who owns a nail salon in Saratoga Springs, 30 miles
north of Albany. ``If you're not taking in the right vitamins and
minerals, it will show.''
</P>
<P>
   Other problems, including fungal infections, are more
conspicuous, even to the untrained eye. You've probably seen the
symptoms in a dark, yellow thick toenail, or a scaly fingernail.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is finding a way to cure one of the most common and
stubborn of nail diseases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely frustrating and it's a hard problem to live
with,'' said Dr. Joseph S. Baler, chief of the division of
dermatology at St. Peter's Hospital in Albany and president of the
Capital District Dermatology Society and the Central New York
Dermatology Society.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you take the medicine and it works, there's still a
chance that it will come back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Nail infections affect up to 5 percent of Americans, causing
nails to become brittle, dry, discolored. In some cases, the
infections are so severe that they can cause pain with walking or
grasping objects.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, physicians have had only oral medications to
work with, including some with potentially serious side effects.
</P>
<P>
   In December, however, the Food and Drug Administration approved
a nail polish, the first ever, to treat hard-to-heal fungus
infections. Manufactured by Aventis Pharma Deutschland of
Frankfurt, Germany, Penlac is expected to be on pharmacy shelves
this month.
</P>
<P>
   Yet most physicians acknowledge the problem is far from solved.
In various clinical trials, Penlac Nail Lacquer was effective in
only 5 percent to 12 percent of patients. Other topical treatments
have proved just as disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem in treating fungal infections is finding a
way to get medicine deposited into the nail so it can grow
normally, Baler said. Another is the prevalence of fungi.
</P>
<P>
   With more than 100,000 species worldwide, these simple parasitic
life forms are everywhere in our environment. In most cases, fungi
are harmless or beneficial to human health, from yeasts used in
baking and brewing to molds that are the source of antibiotic drugs
and mushrooms used in cooking.
</P>
<P>
   But some fungi can also cause illness and sometimes fatal
diseases in humans, especially those with compromised immune
systems as a result of AIDS, cancer or diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Nails are only one of the many potential targets. Jock itch and
yeast infections are also caused by fungi, as are some serious lung
and skin infections.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to nail infections, ``the prevalence increases
with age,'' said Dr. George Murakawa, chief of the division of
dermatology at Albany Medical Center. ``Most elderly will grow
fungus underneath their toenails.''
</P>
<P>
   The toes are also more susceptible than hands, mostly because
fungi like the warm, damp environment caused by foot perspiration
and ill-fitting shoes or socks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have wet, sweaty feet all the time, it wouldn't hurt to
use an over-the-counter, anti-fungal powder,'' Murakawa said.
</P>
<P>
   While keeping your feet and body dry are good preventive
strategies for fungal infections, Baler emphasizes that the problem
is not a hygiene issue. For reasons that aren't clear, some people
are believed to be more susceptible to nail infections than others.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it doesn't hurt to wear flip-flops when using the shower
at the gym. Or to make sure your nail salon uses only clean,
sterile equipment. Ross-Cassidy is especially meticulous about
getting her clients to take care of their nails.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can hide your feet,'' she said. ``But your hands are
always out there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Sylvia Wood can be reached at 518-454-5445 or by e-mail at
swood(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
