<HEADER>
A1938 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-SALON-INTERNET-ZINE-N     02-29 2661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALON-INTERNET-ZINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 SALON: from OUTER SPACE to THE SKINNER BOX  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax, By HELEN THORPE  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    When the Internet magazine Salon went public last June, nobody
got obscenely rich.
 &HT;    The IPO did underwrite a few perks, however, that give the
company the appearance of new-economy prosperity.
 &HT;    Its swank new office in downtown San Francisco includes a
communal kitchen with an impressive stainless-steel fridge and a
balcony where the staff gathers for cocktails every Friday night.
 &HT;    On a recent day, at noon, David Talbot, Salon's chairman and
editor in chief, emerges from the weekly business meeting, his blue
eyes showing signs of bleariness. Driving to work earlier this
morning, he heard the news that AOL was merging with Time Warner.
The deal sent tremors through the whole Internet establishment, but
for Salon, it's the equivalent of a full-blown earthquake.
 &HT;    The homespun, seat-of-your-pants era of the Internet _ the era
in which Salon rose to prominence and which it, in some sense, grew
to symbolize _ is history. Forging strange alliances, old and new
media giants seem poised to carve up the Internet for themselves,
leaving maybe a few table scraps for independent outfits like
Salon.
 &HT;    In his 15th-floor office, Talbot is happy to talk business.
Specifically, he is intent on dispelling a myth that he fears is
depressing the price of his company's stock (which has been
languishing around $7 per share, about half of its peak price).
 &HT;    Salon is not, Talbot says seriously, a magazine.
 &HT;    Frankly, that's what it looks like to most people. On its Web
site, Salon covers culture, technology and politics. Garrison
Keillor writes a quirky advice column and Camille Paglia fires out
antifeminist provocations. At its best, it mixes polished writing
and a healthy disregard for the conventions of print journalism. At
its worst, the writer Dan Savage tries to infect Gary Bauer with
the flu. But we'll get to that later.
 &HT;    The point is, if Salon is not a magazine, what is it?
 &HT;    Talbot grabs a red marker and starts drawing a chart on a white
board that stands beside his desk. It is a routine that he has
probably performed countless times, but he does it with enthusiasm
and vigor.
 &HT;    He lists the key components of Salon's business and,
conspicuously, Print Content is merely one of five.
 &HT;    The others are as follows: Broadband, under which Talbot writes
Salon TV and Salon Radio. Salon now broadcasts programming put
together by the Dial, an on-line radio company, and later this year
will introduce an original mix of talk and music. A TV program is
set to make its debut in the fall on the Bravo channel.
 &HT;    Next on the list is E-commerce, which is essentially the site's
gift shop, where it sells T-shirts, coffee mugs, Salon compilations
and _ coming soon _ high-end writing utensils.
 &HT;    Then there's Media Sales, which means the hiring out of Salon's
ad sales team to other Web ventures. This arm of the company is a
work in progress too. So far the only client is a ticketing outfit
called CultureFinder.com.
 &HT;    And finally, there's Tech Projects. The design of Salon's Web
site is highly regarded, and Talbot wants to license this
architecture to other Internet companies.
 &HT;    So there it is, the Salon media empire. It still looks an awful
lot like a magazine. But it's easy to see what motivates Talbot. As
the new brand names of the industry seek to monopolize more and
more of the traffic on the Internet, Talbot is fighting to prevent
Salon from being marginalized as a virtuous bit player.
 &HT;    ``What I want Salon to be is a smart tabloid,'' he says. ``I
don't want to be publishing a highbrow zine for the literati. To
me, the great cultural models are the Beatles, Dylan, Francis Ford
Coppola, Martin Scorsese. These are people who have a very strong
creative vision but want a big audience. They didn't just want to
stay in art houses.''
 &HT;    As it is, Talbot is already at the mercy of forces much greater
than himself. Last year he paid $250,000 to be featured on AOL, a
deal that provided Salon with its greatest source of readers.
 &HT;    Talbot declines to confirm any hard figures, but word in the
industry is that when Salon approached AOL about upgrading its
placement, the new price for a two-year deal was in the mid-seven
figures. Given that AOL is acquiring all those Time Warner
magazines, eventually Salon may not be able to rent space on AOL
for any price.
 &HT;    Talbot's response to all this is to set Salon on a do-or-die
course to get big fast. And despite his elaborate pitch about
branching off into new ventures, his greatest project will be
transforming the magazine itself.
 &HT;    Steadily, he has been devoting more and more resources to
flashier news, celebrity coverage and gossip to attract a wider
audience. But his nascent empire _ and along with it the whole idea
of an independent Internet media company holding its own against
the conglomerates _ will amount to very little if he can't strike
the right balance between rewarding his loyal readers and pandering
to the masses.
 &HT;    The first thing everybody mentions about Talbot is his charisma.
There is a Clinton-like aspect to his character _ ``I like an
audience that claps,'' he says at one point _ and in his presence,
it's hard not to be won over by nearly everything he says.
 &HT;    He thrives on creative tension, a talent he probably learned
from being brought up in a highly polarized household. Talbot's
father, a talented Hollywood actor who never made it big, was a
Goldwater man and used to drag the children to Nixon rallies. His
mother, an ex-showgirl, supported Kennedy, Johnson and the Great
Society. (His sister, Margaret, is a contributing writer for The
Times Magazine.)
 &HT;    In terms of political leanings, David took after his mother _ he
grew up into a lefty journalist, collaborated on a book about
Americans' sexual habits and eventually went to work as an editor
at Mother Jones.
 &HT;    But he never did quite fit the mold. One of his articles in the
early 1980s suggested that the emerging entrepreneurial culture of
Silicon Valley might have socially liberating effects. In 1986,
Talbot was recruited to The San Francisco Examiner by the
publisher, William Randolph Hearst III, who wanted him to shake up
its arts coverage. He did just that, but to a degree that often
created problems.
 &HT;    ``If you got two or three angry letters, it caused huge
ripples,'' Talbot recalls. ``I think the Internet came along at
this marvelous time, because the media had become so timid, so
politically correct, so dumbed down, so marketing driven.''
 &HT;    Talbot discovered the Web during a rancorous strike when Scott
Rosenberg, then a film critic for The Examiner, helped publish a
union paper on the Internet. It required no newsprint, no ink, no
pressmen, no trucks and no drivers.
 &HT;    In search of liberation, that eternal California soundtrack,
Talbot made the jump to the on-line world in 1995 _ along with
Rosenberg, now Salon's technology columnist and managing editor,
and Gary Kamiya, its executive editor _ and eventually he hired
away some of The Examiner's most talented writers and editors.
 &HT;    Start-up money came from Apple: first $60,000, then another
$40,000 _ meager sums by today's standards, but enough to finance a
modest weekly Web zine that was primarily about books. The business
side evolved slowly.
 &HT;    ``In those days, you would sit down with somebody, and you
weren't sure if you were supposed to pay them or if they were
supposed to pay you,'' remembers David Zweig, Salon's first
publisher. ``It was like being in outer space. You had no way of
getting your bearings.''
 &HT;    Over the next two years John Warnock, the CEO of Adobe Systems,
steered $5 million to Salon. The editors took advantage of freedom
they never had before.
 &HT;    A peculiarly West Coast sensibility reigned. Laura Miller, who
worked for a feminist erotica cooperative in San Francisco before
joining Salon (and is now the New York bureau chief), says that the
staff defined itself in opposition to the ``status-obsessed
culture'' of New York.
 &HT;    Talbot lured new readers with coverage of family matters,
technology, academia, media and sex. Courtney Weaver's Unzipped
column was an early hit. It was sometimes erotic, sometimes just
plain dirty.
 &HT;    Talbot also provided an outlet for unusually intimate memoirs
and stark confessionals. Anne Lamott, writing about everything from
parenthood to spirituality, developed into a star attraction. So
did James Poniewozik, a media columnist who was eventually hired
away by Time magazine.
 &HT;    Talbot assembled a fiercely loyal team of editors and writers _
and along with it an equally committed readership. By the time of
its IPO, Salon was drawing 1.2 million visitors a month.
 &HT;    The glorious naivete of salon's early days could not last,
however. Virtual magazines started popping up all over the place,
and some had real business plans and ideas about making money.
Salon had to get with it.
 &HT;    So back in 1996, after Zweig and Talbot split over which
commercial alliances to pursue, Talbot brought in Michael
O'Donnell, a former salesman of software and computer games. An
evangelist of growth, O'Donnell describes Salon's target audience
as ``upscale mass market,'' a term that no one would have taken
seriously until a few short years ago.
 &HT;    ``We're not really aiming to be The New Yorker of the Web,''
O'Donnell says. ``The market we're going after is the market that
watches 'Seinfeld.'''
 &HT;    One of O'Donnell's first moves was to hire an enterprising young
man named Alexander Hughes as Salon's circulation manager. Hughes
viewed the Internet as ``the ultimate Skinner box,'' by which he
meant a highly accurate gauge of human behavior.
 &HT;    Borrowing concepts from HotWired, he redesigned Salon's
architecture to track the way traffic moved through the site in
stunning detail.
 &HT;    With Hughes' system, Talbot can tell exactly how many readers
visit Salon, and by what means they arrive. He can tell what
departments readers go to, which articles they click on and whether
they make it to the last page. Most content providers have access
to some traffic information, but few know as much about their flow
as Salon does.
 &HT;    ``What we built allows you, on a daily, weekly, monthly or
annual basis, to analyze whether you are breaking even on any given
piece of content,'' explains Hughes, who now works at C/Net, a site
for high-tech products. ``For each story, you can answer the
question, Did we pay for this?''
 &HT;    Having access to this information had a huge psychic impact on
Salon's writers and editors. Suddenly they were privy to the print
equivalent of Nielsen ratings.
 &HT;    ``At The Examiner, I thought: Aha, I work at a newspaper with a
circulation of half a million people! Therefore, half a million
people read my stories,'' Rosenberg says. ``Of course, it wasn't
true, but we never got our faces shoved in it.''
 &HT;    Lately, an average of 110,000 people have been visiting Salon
per day. Perhaps one-fifth of them click on Rosenberg's technology
column. Knowing precisely how many people read his column ``is a
shock at first,'' he admits. ``But once you know the numbers, you
can't imagine doing without them.''
 &HT;    Salon's editors have learned to be vague when speaking to
writers about traffic stats. But everyone understands how the
system works _ that if the word ``breasts'' is used in a cover
link, traffic will go off the charts, and that articles about
foreign news go virtually unread.
 &HT;    The tabloidy stuff almost always scores high. The two articles
Salon ran about the death of Diana, Princess of Wales, in August
1997 attracted record numbers of traffic. Last year, an
unremarkable article about the death of John F. Kennedy Jr. was
Salon's most widely read item _ it got more than 250,000 hits.
 &HT;    These numbers make Talbot's job easier in obvious respects, but
a lot more complicated in others.
 &HT;    ``It's daunting, because, you know, if Anne Lamott's page views
are going down, what do you do?'' he says. ``I think you don't
necessarily pull the plug on someone. Garrison Keillor, for
instance, started out slow, and now his column is one of our top
page-drivers. Sometimes you have to be patient. Other times, if you
see some long trend, it does give you a warning signal. You say,
'Well, does this jibe with your sense that the writer is running
out of steam?'''
 &HT;    Among Salon's impressive moments, a freelancer, Daniel Forbes,
broke the story in January about the collusion between network TV
producers and White House policy makers to embed antidrug messages
in prime-time shows. Every other media outlet in the country played
catch-up, and in a matter of days the practice was halted. It went
a long way in establishing Salon as a reputable news organization.
 &HT;    But weeks later that momentum was squandered when Dan Savage,
who writes a nationally syndicated sex column, was assigned to
write about the Republican presidential hopeful Gary Bauer.
 &HT;    Savage describes himself as deeply offended by Bauer's anti-gay
rhetoric, and he set out to retaliate. Masquerading as a volunteer
for the candidate, he tried (unsuccessfully) to infect Bauer with
the flu by licking doorknobs, pens and coffee cups in the campaign
office.
 &HT;    When Savage's bizarre account was published in Salon, Talbot was
hit with a barrage of criticism. He responded in curious fashion,
posting this disclaimer on Salon: ``We still believe publishing the
article was the right choice, but we also feel compelled to say: We
didn't assign Savage to infect Bauer. We don't condone or endorse
what he says he did.''
 &HT;    Salon editors, in other words, not only disavowed responsibility
for their reporter's conduct, they also wouldn't vouch for the
veracity of what he had written.
 &HT;    Toward the end of last year, Salon experienced a surge in
traffic. In December, the number of people who visited Salon jumped
to 3.4 million, up from 1.9 million in September. Advertising is up
sharply too. Total revenues rose to $3 million last quarter, a 193
percent increase over the year before. Plus, the IPO last June
brought in $26 million, and just before that O'Donnell raised $15
million from private sources.
 &HT;    But money is still going out faster than it is coming in. Salon
has only enough cash on hand to survive for a year and a half.
 &HT;    Meanwhile, takeover rumors circulate. In the past, both
Amazon.com and Time Warner have tried to buy Salon. Last year,
Bravo expressed interest in a bigger piece of the company. So far,
Talbot and O'Donnell have rebuffed all offers. This may be because
the bids were low.
 &HT;    Or perhaps Talbot is stubborn enough to hang on to his creation.
``My dream is that I would pass it along to the next generation,
and that they would keep it independent,'' he says. ``It would be a
shame if Salon were gobbled by a major media company.''
 &HT;    Yes, it's not too hard to imagine what a bunch of suits would do
with that artfully constructed ``Skinner box.''
 &HT;     c.2000 Helen Thorpe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Helen Thorpe lives in Austin, Tex., and has written for Texas
Monthly, George and New York.) &LR;
</P>
