<SLUG> BC-MONEY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX RULES ON SALE OF HOUSE REVISED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SHANNON BUGGS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Nearly 55,000 homes were sold in Houston last year,
the most ever in one year.
</P>
<P>
   Since selling a home is not a yearly event for most people, this
tax season may be confusing to those who have to account for those
sales on their tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't been keeping up with the changes in the tax code,
you are in for a surprise.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Congress repealed the rule that allowed home sellers to
defer for two years paying taxes on any gains from selling their
primary residence, to roll over the gains tax-free into a new home,
or to be exempt from paying taxes on gains of up to $125,000 if
they were 55 years or older.
</P>
<P>
   I repeat: Taxpayers no longer have to buy another home or be age
55 to avoid paying taxes on the profit they make when they sell
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Congress replaced the rule with a tax exemption on up to
$250,000 in profits on a house sale, or up to $500,000 for married
couples filing joint returns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TWO-YEAR RESIDENCE REQUIRED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To qualify for this tax break, sellers have to meet two
requirements, but one of them has some flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers can keep all the gains on a house as long as they have
not sold another primary residence in the past two years and if
they lived in the house for two of the five years before they sold
it.
</P>
<P>
   The law does not say that the person has to live in the home for
two consecutive years. So a person could live in a house for one
year, rent it for three, move back in for a year _ and keep all the
profit when she sells it at the end of that year, says E. Rhett
Buck, a certified public accountant and tax attorney.
</P>
<P>
   There's another loophole in the rule. People can get a prorated
tax exemption on any capital gains even if they sell the home
before the 24-month time period if there is a change in the
taxpayer's health, employment or other unforeseen circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Those can include taking a job in another city, divorce, the
birth of a child or other events that force people to sell their
homes, says Juanita Dailey, a tax law specialist in the Houston
office of the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   To calculate the prorated exemption, you take the number of
months you lived in the home, divide it by 24 months and multiply
that by the $250,000 single-filer exemption or the $500,000
joint-filer exemption.
</P>
<P>
   For this tax year alone, you can get the prorated exemption
without having to show that you moved for an unexpected reason _ if
you sold your house before Aug. 5, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HOME-TRANSACTION FORM ABOLISHED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The most confusing part of all these changes is that there is no
form for you to file with the IRS to account for the gains. Home
sales used to be accounted for on Form 2119, which would be
attached to a return, but that is no longer necessary, says Dailey.
</P>
<P>
   You also don't have to include home sales on a Schedule D for
capital gains and losses, although you might want to if your title
company sends you a form 1099S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 10 years, title companies have been told to send
out those forms,'' says Greta Hicks, a CPA and former IRS manager.
``Now the burden is on the title company to determine if it's a
taxable event for each of their clients, and a lot of them just
don't have the time to figure it out, so they send the form to
everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   If that happens to you and you qualify for the exemption,
contact your title company and ask for a corrected 1099S, stating
that you are exempt. If the title company is not helpful, submit
the 1099S with your return and a letter to the IRS saying that you
are exempt.
</P>
<P>
   There is free help out there for those of you who do your own
tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   Call the IRS at 800-829-1040 to get help over the phone or visit
its Web site at www.irs.gov.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also has volunteers at 164 locations in Southeast
Texas on Saturdays and weekday evenings to help with your forms.
They will even fill them out for you, if you bring all your
financial information.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
