<SLUG> BC-PILLSBURY-BAKEOFF-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COOKS TURN CREATIVE IN ANNUAL BAKING CONTEST 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By EMILY GURNON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco, the home of renown chefs and
restaurants, played host to 99 amateur cooks from across the
country who competed in the 50th anniversary Pillsbury Bake-Off
cooking contest.
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million grand prize was awarded Tuesday to Roberta
``Bobbie'' Sonefeld of Hopkins, S.C. Her dessert contest entry was
Cream Cheese Brownie Pie.
</P>
<P>
   Decked out in blue Pillsbury aprons, the contestants lined up at
their ovens in the Marriott Hotel ballroom at 8 a.m. Monday and
proceeded to show off their culinary innovations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I entered the very first (contest), and I have dreamed of this
for 50 years,'' said Pat Parsons, 75, of Bakersfield, Calif., who
became one of the 100 finalists (one couldn't make it because she's
expecting a baby and cannot travel) with her recipe for Guess Again
Candy Crunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting into this contest has been one of the goals of my
life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In order to qualify, contestants had to create original recipes
that use a Pillsbury product _ which includes brands owned by
Pillsbury's parent company, such as Hungry Jack, Old El Paso,
Progresso and Green Giant. They chose one of four categories: Easy
Weeknight Meals, Fast &AMP; Fabulous Desserts &AMP; Treats, Yummy
Vegetables or Casual Snacks &AMP; Appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   Parsons got inspired to make her dish by looking at the list of
this year's qualifying ingredients. One of them was Progresso bread
crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, what's the most unusual thing you can make with
bread crumbs? And I thought, candy!'' She called it Guess Again
because ``nobody can guess what makes it crunchy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is so easy,'' she said. ``And the only cooking I do is melt
chocolate in the microwave.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Quick and easy'' was the theme of this year's contest, which
has evolved considerably since its debut in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original idea was, how do we get people excited about
flour?'' said George Pillsbury, 78, whose grandfather, Charles A.
Pillsbury, started the Minneapolis company in 1869.
</P>
<P>
   An advertising agency came up with the notion for a contest, and
the first winner, according to Pillsbury archives, was Mrs. Ralph
E. Smafield of Rockford, Ill., who won for her recipe for
Water-Rising Twists, a nut sweet roll raised under water.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Pillsbury continues to hold the contest is to
get a ``peek into America's kitchens,'' said Pillsbury spokeswoman
Marlene Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the years, recipes have changed with America's tastes
and cooks' time restraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we see are a lot of bold, impactful flavors in
recipes,'' Johnson said. ``America's palates are not timid
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The average age of all the finalists was 46.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest was Lauren Eggeman of Massillon, Ohio, who became a
finalist with her original recipe, Sugar and Spice Black Pepper
Cookies, made with Pillsbury Cinnamon Swirl Quick Bread and Coffee
Cake mix.
</P>
<P>
   At the ripe old age of 11, Eggeman is a veteran cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was, like, 2, I watched my mom, and when I was, like, 5
or 6, I would make my own things, never measure anything,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She got the idea for adding pepper to her cookies from her
grandmother, who used to do the same thing. ``My mom said it tasted
really good,'' Lauren said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, mangoes are in. So is coffee or coffee-flavored
dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Patrice Hurd, 44, of Bemidji, Minn., dreamed up her creation,
Crescent Potato Puffs, over nine months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every night as I drifted off to sleep, I thought of food
combinations, and something different you could do with the
(qualifying) products,'' she said. She kept a pencil and paper by
the bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been cooking and baking all of my life, and if you
bake, this is the contest,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When the entry period was over, Hurd said, ``I could not sleep.
I had nothing to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Sonefeld, the other category winners who each won
$10,000 were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lorraine Maggio of Manlius, N.Y., baked the winning Easy
Weeknight Meals dish, Ham and Swiss Crescent Braid.
</P>
<P>
   _ Judith Mettlin of Snyder, N.Y., prepared the top Yummy
Vegetables recipe, Island Paradise Salad.
</P>
<P>
   _ Judy Wood of Vestavia Hills, Ala., was category winner in
Casual Snacks &AMP; Appetizers with Pesto Crescent Twists with Feta
Spread.
</P>
<P>
   The three finalists in each category who won $2,000 prizes were:
</P>
<P>
   _ Kristine Snyder of Kihei, Hawaii; Betsy Dell of Rochester,
N.Y.; and Debra Kelly of Wheeling, Ill. (Easy Weeknight Meals)
</P>
<P>
   _ Inez Duke of Mars Hill, N.C.; Rosemary Leicht of Bethel, Ohio;
and Mary Jones of Cumberland, Maine (Yummy Vegetables)
</P>
<P>
   _ Janice Kollar of Woodbridge, N.J.; Marge Bergemann of
Greenbelt, Md.; and Heather Wight of Los Angeles (Fast &AMP; Fabulous
Desserts &AMP; Treats)
</P>
<P>
   _ Kelly Roos of Pottsville, Pa.; Thomas Stuteville of Parsons,
Kan.; and Tracie Ojakangas of Springfield, Mo., (Casual Snacks &AMP;
Appetizers)
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the GE Innovation Award was Pat Parsons of
Bakersfield, Calif. She won a GE Profile Performance Kitchen
(valued at $5,000) for her recipe, Guess Again Candy Crunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
