<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 13:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1951 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-ATROCITIES-RUSSIAN-CH     02-29 2188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATROCITIES-RUSSIAN-CHECHNYA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
310-996-0089. 
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 THE GRUNTS of GROZNY  
 &HT;     (This article has already moved to Centerpiece clients. To
publish as a ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased _ the
rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 310-996-0075; fax, By MICHAEL GORDON  
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine  
 &HT;    The first thing Lt. Vyacheslav Kiselyov did before leading his
platoon into Grozny was to yank the metal plates from his
bulletproof vest, leaving only the panel that covered his heart.
Then he crammed the jacket with extra cartridges of ammunition.
 &HT;    It was one of those trade-offs Russian soldiers make to maximize
their chances of survival.
 &HT;    The regular supply of ammo _ four magazines with 32 cartridges
each _ is good for only about 20 minutes of fighting. The fire from
Chechen rebels can sometimes get so intense, however, that it
sounds like eggs on a griddle, and Vyacheslav felt his best
protection was having enough bullets to answer back.
 &HT;    He also put aside his helmet. It was nice to have if you were
manning a checkpoint. But when a soldier has to run for his life
and dodge snipers, the ill-fitting helmet just gets in the way.
 &HT;    As Vyacheslav recalled not long ago, he was creeping up on a
warehouse in the eastern part of Grozny when he saw that two of his
soldiers were pinned against the ground, bullets whizzing over
their heads.
 &HT;    He began lobbing smoke grenades so that they could make their
escape. It was then that a 5.45-millimeter bullet ripped into his
hand.
 &HT;    That, Vyacheslav now says, was a bit of luck. If it had been a
7.62-millimeter, it would have torn off a finger.
 &HT;    Vyacheslav told me his tale in Room No. 8, which was not a room
at all but a tent set up on the grounds of the military hospital in
Mozdok, just a few miles northwest of the Republic of Chechnya.
 &HT;    He spoke in a low monotone, as if he were talking about another
soldier in some far-off battle. It was a dirty little war, but it
was his lot to fight it. He had not bothered to tell his parents
about his wound. It would only worry them, and there was nothing
really that they could do.
 &HT;    ``I don't know whether we are fighting for the motherland or
not,'' Vyacheslav said. ``But if it was up to me all the bandits
would be destroyed. It's not nice to see your friend's head blown
off by a grenade.''
 &HT;    I was one of a handful of foreigners who had tagged along with
Russian TV crews as they helicoptered in and out of Chechnya this
winter, the Russian forces blasting their way into the Chechen
capital. An obsequious military press service generated publicity
for Russia's field commanders.
 &HT;    These officers were a blustery lot, boasting about their
triumphs and reveling in the medals that Vladimir Putin, Russia's
acting president, bestowed on them. What interested me, though, was
not these officers but the soldiers who fought under them _ young
men who, like Chechnya's civilians, bore the brunt of Russia's
``victories.''
 &HT;    These soldiers were not the grizzled combat veterans the Kremlin
insisted it was sending to the front. They were untested conscripts
plucked from Russian factories and farms in the provinces,
down-on-their-luck mercenaries unable to find steady work at home,
militiamen more accustomed to policing a rock concert than
searching for snipers.
 &HT;    And they were young officers like Vyacheslav, who went to a
military school to become a border guard and never imagined he
would end up in the Chechen caldron.
 &HT;    They suffered thousands of casualties in the course of seizing a
ruined capital and chasing bands of battle-hardened militants into
their lairs in the Caucasus mountains. No one considered himself a
hero, and nobody was anticipating any parades when, or if, he
returned home.
 &HT;    In Mozdok, a dismal military town, besieged by fog and drowning
in a sea of mud, the hospital where I met Vyacheslav is situated
inside a guarded compound near the base. According to official
figures, more than 1,100 Russian soldiers and Interior Ministry
troops have been killed and more than 3,500 wounded since the
campaign in Chechnya began Oct. 1.
 &HT;    Even before the Kremlin began to acknowledge that casualties
were high, it was obvious in Mozdok. You don't erect a small tent
city in winter on the grounds of a hospital unless you have run out
of room to accommodate the wounded. Some of those wounded die after
reaching the hospital but are not listed as having been killed in
action. They are included in a separate, Orwellian category: Those
who perished as a result of trauma.
 &HT;    When I spoke with Col. Vladimir Ivantsov, the deputy chief of
the military's medical service here, he explained that the wounds
suffered by soldiers in Grozny were particularly severe because
troops fighting block by block in a city are likely to meet the
enemy up close _ and be met by accurately fired bullets.
 &HT;    ``There are more head injuries, more brain and skull injuries
and more abdominal injuries too,'' he said. ``Unfortunately, our
soldiers don't always use their protective gear, and large-caliber
bullets can punch through our bulletproof vests.''
 &HT;    Snipers took their toll. And though Ivantsov did not say it, so
did Russian ``friendly fire'' from artillery and air strikes.
 &HT;    The generals like to boast about their ``precision strikes.'' In
the time I was in Chechnya, I never heard a general admit to a
single instance of friendly fire. The soldiers often talked about
it, however, with the same resignation that they spoke of the
frigid weather.
 &HT;    The assault on Grozny was carried out by a hodgepodge of units
with somewhat convoluted command relations: Interior Ministry
troops, the Russian army, militia from Russian cities,
rapid-reaction teams and pro-Russian Chechens. The Russian troops
in Grozny said the pro-Russian Chechens followed behind during the
assault on the capital.
 &HT;    The Mozdok hospital offered terrible evidence of the Russian
army's fighting in Chechnya. Noncommissioned officers,
inexperienced conscripts and ``kontraktniki'' _ generally older
mercenaries who sign six-month to one-year contracts and fight for
pay, a totally unknown category in the old Soviet army _ all were
represented in the Mozdok hospital.
 &HT;    When I visited, Room No. 8, which also doubles as a ward, had
about 20 double-decker bunks pressed together.
 &HT;    Vyacheslav told me he was born in the Amur region of eastern
Siberia, a stunning swath of coniferous forests, rivers and dormant
volcanoes, and wanted to be a forester when he grew up. ``I used to
pick up my rifle and go to the taiga every weekend to hunt,'' he
said. ``I'd go after small game like wolverine, or if I went with
some of my relatives we might go after bear.''
 &HT;    But he is also a young man from the old school _ that is, part
of that shrinking sliver of Russian society that still aspires to
join the military, a faint echo of the old Soviet patriotism. He
found that the soldier's life was not so bad at first. The troops
fed on kasha and tins of meat. Mail arrived once a week. There was
only one radio for the soldiers of his unit, but it was enough to
allow them to follow the news, which was not particularly grim.
There was fighting, but it was limited, and the Russians soon had
things under control.
 &HT;    It might have all ended in Dagestan for Vyacheslav had not
President Boris Yeltsin installed Putin as Russia's prime minister.
Putin, a former KGB officer determined to make his mark as a
Russian strongman, saw Chechnya not as a quagmire, but as an
opportunity.
 &HT;    Sergei Stepashin, Putin's predecessor, told me that he had urged
Putin to take a cautious approach by sealing the borders and taking
the northernmost, pro-Russian third of Chechnya, which is separated
from the rebellious part of the republic by the Terek River.
 &HT;    But Putin, backed by Russia's generals, who were looking to even
the score for their humiliating defeat in the 1994-'96 war in
Chechnya, opted for an all-out invasion, which culminated in bloody
street fighting in the Chechen capital.
 &HT;    ``I have some experience in taking Grozny,'' said Stepashin, who
had served as the head of the Federal Security Service, an heir to
the old KGB, during the first Chechen war. ``So I knew the
resistance would be fierce.''
 &HT;    The generals this time promised a ``special operation'' to
liberate Grozny, saying they would not storm the capital. But their
tactics displayed little finesse. The Russians leveled blocks of
apartment buildings, as if Grozny were not a city containing
thousands of Russia's own citizens. The generals decided to make
war this way, and soldiers like Vyacheslav Kiselyov were sent to
fight it.
 &HT;    ``The soldiers I had were too young,'' Vyacheslav said. ``They
were just 18 years old. I had a sniper in my unit. He leaned out of
a window for 10 seconds and a Chechen grenadier blew his head off.
Only the lower jaw and ears were left.''
 &HT;    Conscription was a holdover from Soviet times, and during the
1996 presidential election campaign Yeltsin promised to do away
with it altogether. But as with most of Yeltsin's plans, the one to
create an all-volunteer force foundered for lack of funds. And
these days more than 90 percent of the privates and noncommissioned
officers in the Russian army are conscripts.
 &HT;    The Moscow establishment, which has hailed Putin's war and which
is trying to ride his coattails, beat the system. It shielded its
own sons with student deferments.
 &HT;    But others, such as Viktor Zlodeyev, 19, didn't even think about
trying to find a way out. The product of a flawed conscript system
that sent ill-prepared young men to war and paid them virtually
nothing for their trouble, he was precisely the kind of soldier
Vyacheslav Kiselyov worried about.
 &HT;    Wounded in Grozny, Viktor, who was also in Room No. 8, told me
he was from the southern Russian city of Krasnodar, where his
father works as a truck driver and his mother serves as an
administrator in a nursery school. He completed nine years of
schooling and then transferred to a trade school to learn how to be
a bricklayer. The army grabbed him before he found a job.
 &HT;    ``My mother did not want me to go into the army,'' he said with
a shrug. ``She said, 'Why do we need all that?' But she said I
should go if I had to, and I never thought about faking a health
problem. After they took me I told the army I did not care what
kind of unit I was in but wanted to serve in Krasnodar, where my
parents live.''
 &HT;    Instead, the army sent him to Chechnya in October. To comfort
his parents, he did not tell them he was in Chechnya. When Viktor
writes his parents he tells them that he is with his brigade in
Budyonnovsk, a town in southern Russia.
 &HT;    Young conscripts told me their base pay was about 40 rubles
($1.40) a month before they arrived at the Mozdok base. Once there,
the pay was boosted to 400 rubles ($14) a month. Indeed, one of my
enduring impressions of the Russian army is that it seems to be
manned by a legion of beggars _ troops without the money to buy
decent cigarettes, which they are forced to bum from visitors.
 &HT;    As part of the orchestrated patriotism of the Chechen campaign,
local governments throughout Russia sent ``humanitarian aid'' to
the troops: candy, canned food and the like. But the officers took
it all, the soldiers told me. Even the officers are not above
asking for favors.
 &HT;    Despite his inexperience, Viktor was given one of the toughest
jobs. He was made a scout in the 205th Reconnaissance Battalion.
His first duty in Chechnya was on the Tersky Ridge. He did not fire
a shot, however, until just before New Year's Day, when he was sent
to Grozny. He was shocked by what he saw.
 &HT;    ``I experienced real fear when I saw the 200's for the first
time,'' he said, referring in Russian army-speak to the corpses of
fallen soldiers. ``They had lain there for a week before we came
in, and we had to bring them out. Some were lying on the street.
Some were in a burned-out armored personnel carrier.''
 &HT;    The ``200's'' is army shorthand for the Russian dead, and some
say it is derived from the fact that a zinc coffin and the wood
crate in which it is shipped together weigh 200 kilos.
 &HT;    A battered old bus used to travel from Grozny to Mozdok carrying
dead Interior Ministry troops. To expedite its passage through the
numerous checkpoints a small sign was placed inside the windshield:
``Cargo 200.''
 &HT;    One and all, the soldiers gave it a wide berth.
 &HT;     (Michael Gordon is the Moscow bureau chief of The New York
Times.) 
 &HT;     c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
