<P>
   &UR; BUSH OR MCCAIN: WHICH ONE IS THE REAL REPUBLICAN? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just after learning to his evident amazement that
his presidential ambitions were still alive, thanks to the voters
of Michigan, Senator John McCain issued a curious appeal. ``Don't
fear my campaign, fellow Republican,'' he pleaded, ``join it, join
it.'' Mindful that only 40 percent of all U.S. voters are
Republicans and that anyone who wants to be president must appeal
across party lines, George W. Bush responded with an appeal of his
own, calling on ``Republicans and like-minded independents'' to
support him. Which candidate will capture the hearts _ and votes _
of Republicans? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Dejevsky, The Independent of London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved Mon., Feb. 28) &QL;
