<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAIDER-GOOSESTEPS-DOWN-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAIDER GOOSE-STEPS DOWN AMID DER FUROR  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 400-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By IMRE KARACS  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ The Austrian far-right leader Joerg Haider stunned
political friends and foes alike by announcing Monday that he
wanted to step down as leader of the Freedom Party.
</P>
<P>
   Haider told allies he had grown tired of international
criticism, and would henceforth concentrate on his job as governor
of the southern province of Carinthia. He suggested that Susanne
Riess-Passer, vice-chancellor in the new government that has
provoked fury abroad and mass demonstrations on the streets of
Vienna, should succeed him.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Party executive met Monday night to discuss their
leader's latest flamboyant gesture, which took even them by
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Haider said the government he had worked so hard to build was in
danger from the ``prejudices'' his personality was attracting. It
also made sense, he added, that a member of the new government
should be entrusted with the leadership of the party.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no danger of Haider, the most successful politician
in postwar Austria, disappearing. His retreat is likely to prove a
tactical gambit.
</P>
<P>
   Haider, who turned 50 last month, has never concealed his
ambition of becoming chancellor of Austria one day. Asked in an
interview Monday if he had given up that dream because of the odium
heaped upon him in recent weeks, Haider replied: ``Why? It's become
even more likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanishing from the rough and tumble of national politics for a
while serves this long-term strategy. A stint in government should
make the Freedom Party more respectable, but possibly at the risk
of its own popularity.
</P>
<P>
   None of the xenophobic election slogans are likely to become
reality, but a lot of difficult decisions will have to be taken as
the coalition tries to grapple with an overregulated economy.
Already the Freedom Party is dropping in the polls, and ministers
have started bickering among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Haider will sit out these troubled times in his provincial power
base, nurturing his political virginity, and awaiting the moment
when he can return to Vienna as savior.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, his grip on the party is assured. Haider took
over the then-fringe party with a voter base of five percent 13
years ago, and has turned it into the second biggest political
force in Austria. In elections last October, it gained 27 percent
of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   Without him, as everybody knows, the Freedom Party would sink
back into oblivion. Whatever his title, Haider remains the
undisputed leader. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 400-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
