<HEADLINE>
BUSH OR MCCAIN: WHICH ONE IS THE REAL REPUBLICAN?  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Political, Commentary Editors)   (This 900-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``p''
political news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By MARY DEJEVSKY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just two hours after learning to his evident
amazement that his presidential ambitions were still alive, thanks
to the voters of straitlaced Michigan, Senator John McCain issued a
curious appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't fear my campaign, fellow Republicans,'' he pleaded,
``join it, join it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since that enchanted Tuesday evening, he has travelled the
length of the West Coast, from Seattle to San Diego, preparing for
the next set of primaries, this week and next, when the fate of his
self-styled crusade will once again be on the line. And those words
have resonated in his wake.
</P>
<P>
   To his opponent, the party establishment's favorite, George W.
Bush, they were a welcome cause for ridicule. What sort of a
Republican candidate is it that has to reach out to his fellow
Republicans?, he quipped at every campaign stop.
</P>
<P>
   His point was that John McCain had won the Michigan and New
Hampshire primaries courtesy of thousands of registered Democrats
and non-party voters who had crossed party lines to vote in a
Republican primary.
</P>
<P>
   A good half of the voters in Michigan were not Republicans and
it was they who gave McCain his victory.
</P>
<P>
   A disconsolate Bush camp spent last week accusing him of
everything from ``borrowing'' Democrats to ``hijacking the
Republican primary.''
</P>
<P>
   However, mindful of the truth _ articulated on occasion by
McCain _ that only 40 percent of all U.S. voters are Republicans
and that anyone who wants to be president must appeal across party
lines, Bush formulated an appeal of his own, calling on
``Republicans and like-minded independents'' to support him.
</P>
<P>
   As the primaries progress, the Bush team calculates that the
threat from what McCain has termed ``the McCain majority'' will
fade. They look forward to the coming primaries where only
Republicans may vote.
</P>
<P>
   With the party hierarchy at national and local level still
firmly behind their candidate, they reckon that Bush will be home
and dry with the presidential nomination before the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   Accepted wisdom has it that if he is to prevent Bush taking the
nomination, McCain needs to capture the party mainstream.
Thereafter he can, and must, make broader alliances, but for now
his problem is winning over the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   His proliferating references to the legacy of Ronald Reagan in
recent days suggest that he already has his sights on that
traditional, Republican constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Yet McCain's sweeping victory in the Arizona primary, which was
``closed'' to all but registered Republicans, suggests that where
he is well-known (Arizona is his home state) and where he is
running expressly against the local party establishment (the
governor and her administration backed Bush), the personal
supersedes the political.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, an analysis of McCain's support _ extrapolated
from exit polls in the states that have so far voted and augmented
by local apocrypha _ suggests he may not be so far removed from the
mainstream as the Bush camp likes to think, especially after Bush's
turn to the right to win South Carolina's primary .
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, those voters _ independent, Democrat and even
Republican _ who cast their ballot for McCain gave many reasons for
their choice.
</P>
<P>
   They included a desire to get back at the fervently pro-Bush
state governor over entirely local grievances, as well as an
aversion to being told by the governor how to vote, and dislike or
disapproval of Bush for his high birth and perceived shallowness.
</P>
<P>
   But the main reason people said they voted for McCain was the
same reason people gave in New Hampshire and elsewhere: because
they like him.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush camp has tried to use McCain's supposed unpopularity in
the Senate and in Arizona's political circles to argue that ``the
better people know Mr. McCain the less they like him.'' But the
impression from the campaign trail so far is quite the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   The more the voters see of McCain, the more his poll ratings
rise; conversely, the more they see of Bush, the less they like
him.
</P>
<P>
   His personal appeal is partly to do with his past as a Vietnam
war hero; but this would count for little without his authority on
the stump and the direct way he connects with his audiences, live
or on television.
</P>
<P>
   TV cameramen have described him as a ``dream,'' someone with
``no bad angles.'' Live, he galvanizes his audiences as none of the
other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   As he has become better known, both the gender and age gaps
among voters have also closed.
</P>
<P>
   Until Michigan, Bush _ who has allegedly adopted a specifically
female-friendly vocabulary _ took a majority of the women's vote.
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, though, which is more of a microcosm of America
than any state that has voted so far, McCain took 53 percent of the
women's vote, compared with 41 percent for Bush. He led among male
voters, too.
</P>
<P>
   Young people are turning out for McCain in droves and their
comments are especially illuminating, given the perpetual
complaints of political commentators about the apathy of the
under-25s.
</P>
<P>
   This group finds McCain ``genuine,'' ``authentic'' and someone
worthy of their respect, who does not indulge in the double-speak
or image-switching they have grown used to from politicians.
</P>
<P>
   That they do not subscribe to all his policies, on abortion, for
instance, bothers them not a whit; they just think he would make a
good president. &QL; 
