<SLUG> BC-GEORGIA-JITTERS-CHECHNYA-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JITTERY GEORGIA FEARS BEING SUCKED INTO CHECHEN WAR  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 575-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By PATRICK COCKBURN  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBLISI, GEORGIA _ In the snow-covered mountains of northern
Georgia soldiers can hear the roar of battle across the border in
Chechnya creeping gradually towards them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are worried that the Russians will push the Chechen
fighters into Georgia,'' said a Georgian official in Tblisi, the
Georgian capital.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, the fragile republic of five million people on the
southern slopes of the Caucasus Mountains, is trying hard to keep
out of the Chechen war.
</P>
<P>
   It has strenuously denied Russian claims that Chechen guerrillas
regularly cross its 50-mile-long border with Chechnya, bringing in
supplies and reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   A weary-looking Georgian President Edouard Shevardnadze told The
Independent Saturday ``we are doing everything we can to avoid
getting involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Shevardnadze said that it was Russia's responsibility to police
the border on the Chechen side and it had the troops in place to do
so. But, in some of the worst terrain in the world, it is unlikely
that the Russian army can stop guerrilla detachments escaping into
Georgia, already home to 5,000 Chechen refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are all the ingredients for a Palestinian-type situation
here in which Chechen guerrillas would base themselves among the
refugees in Georgia and make raids across the border into
Chechnya,'' said an international official Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Cook, the British Foreign Secretary, was at pains
Saturday, during his visit to Georgia, to reassure Shevardnadze
that the outside world is committed to preventing the spread of
instability in the Caucasus and protecting the independence and
integrity of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   He said an expanded force of monitors from the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) would provide ``eyes on
the ground'' along the Georgian-Chechen border.
</P>
<P>
   It may not be enough. Georgia is not a country which can take
much pressure. It is already impoverished by having to feed 300,000
Georgian refugees driven out of the breakaway region of Abkhazia,
whose secession was covertly backed by Russia, in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the Chechen war last year Georgia vehemently
rejected a Russian demand to station border guards on the Georgian
side of the Chechen border.
</P>
<P>
   Russian aircraft later accidentally bombed a Georgian village.
Moscow threatened to make the large Georgian diaspora in Russia
apply for visas.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis in relations was partly defused when Shevardnadze met
Vladimir Putin, the acting Russian president, in January.
</P>
<P>
   Georgian officials said that Shevardnadze was able to convince
Putin that claims by Russian military intelligence that Georgia was
a staging area for Chechen rebels were inflated. Putin spoke of
Georgia as being ``a friendly state.''
</P>
<P>
   The goodwill may not last. Putin spoke Saturday in St.
Petersburg of opening talks with the Chechens, but only when the
rebels have been defeated.
</P>
<P>
   In effect Russia is not prepared to negotiate with any Chechen
leader with any credibility among his own people. This is a recipe
for a long war whose effects will almost certainly spill over into
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   For Shevardnadze it is a delicate balancing game. Because of the
war Russia needs Georgia's cooperation more than ever before. It
may try to gain this through fostering closer links with Tblisi.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time it can put pressure on Georgia through its
influence on secessionist movements and its position as supplier of
most of Georgia's electricity and gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Georgia fears the sound of Russian guns across its
northern border. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
