   (NOTE: 100-word trim at 825; total uncut is 1,025) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-E-COMMERCE-NIRVANA?-825&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMARY COLOR: QUIRKY MOMENTS ON THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (This week's droll ``Primary Color'' column) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Humor, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-PRIMARYCOLOR-COLUMN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEATTLE: AMERICA'S `SPOILED RICH KID' GETS A REALITY CHECK &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the weirdest state I ever saw,'' says a Seattle man
who has lived in Washington state for 23 years after spending time
in Chicago, New York and California. ``Washington has cheap
electricity, no real social problems, companies like Microsoft,
Boeing, Starbucks and Nordstrom, a mild climate _ it's the spoiled
rich kid of the nation.'' Yes, but even for a rich kid life has
problems (ask George W. Bush). This is beginning to dawn on
Washington, and particularly on the state's largest city, Seattle.
Is paradise lost? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Seattle) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 175; total uncut is 1,000) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-SEATTLE-BLUES-400&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOHN MCCAIN AND THE GHOST OF VIETNAM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John McCain may be splitting the Republican Party asunder. But
when it comes to the rather more important question of the country
as a whole, he is more of a healer than a divider. Ever since
Saigon fell to the Communists in 1975, the U.S. has been suffering
from post-Vietnam stress disorder. McCain is a vital part of the
country's struggle to put the disorder behind it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 2 trims, totaling 350; total uncut is 1,125) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-VIETNAM-MCCAIN-375&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IT'S, LIKE, SO AUTONOMOUS: L.A.'S RENEGADE SAN FERNANDO
VALLEY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Valley girls and Valley-speak remain the target of
comedians, the San Fernando Valley in Southern California is about
to be taken a bit more seriously. A secessionist movement is
underfoot to break the San Fernando Valley, which lies to the north
of the Santa Monica Mountains, away from the larger portion of Los
Angeles that lies to its south, creating two cities out of the one
that exists today. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: California) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 3 trims, totaling 375; total uncut is 1,200) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-LA-BALKANIZED-450&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE AMERICAS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LIGHTS, CAMERA, CENSOR!: BLACK COMEDY INDICTS MEXICAN
POLITICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's long-ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI)
knows all about the power of cinema. For 30 years until the 1960s,
the country's film industry, like the PRI itself, enjoyed a golden
age. It dominated Latin American screens, with stirring but
politically soothing tales of love, treachery and Mexican cowboys.
The memory of the medium's power still lingers, it seems. How else
to explain the PRI's clumsy attempt to censor ``Herod's Law,'' a
movie that casts a piercing gaze at that bygone period? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS: Potentially offensive language in 4th graf) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-MEXICO-CINEMA-PRI-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO DESCENDS INTO CHAOS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For now, the biggest tug of wills over Kosovo's future is
unfolding in the muddy, foggy streets of Mitrovica, where the Ibar
River has become a virtual dividing line between Serbs in the
northern fifth of Kosovo and ethnic Albanians to the south. How
firm that division becomes, and how many families survive on the
``wrong'' side of the line, will be a tough and telling test for
both the U.N. and NATO, which is rushing to boost the size of its
force from the current level of 30,000 to meet the challenge. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: 125-word trim at 700; total uncut is 1,025) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-KOSOVO-UNRAVELS-700&AMP;add-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRACKING NAZI-LOOTED ART, `THE LAST PRISONERS OF WAR' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nazi-looted works of art still held in museums and private
collections around the world _ ``the last prisoners of war'' _ are
the largest unresolved Holocaust-era matter, and the trickiest.
Efforts to find and identify these works have been intensified in
recent years, ever since the end of the Cold War opened up Eastern
Europe's archives. Now those recovery efforts are beginning to pay
off. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (EDITORS: Note Feb. 29 reference, 6th graf) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-NAZI-ART-SNOOPS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ASIA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHINA: FIRST HONG KONG, THEN MACAU _ NEXT TAIWAN? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ever the enigmatic oracle, Mao Zedong once said that it might
take China 100 years to bring Taiwan back into the fold of a
reunified motherland. On Feb. 21, China suddenly stepped up the
pressure, threatening to resort to ``all drastic measures possible,
including the use of force'' if Taiwan were to refuse
``indefinitely'' to negotiate with the mainland on reunification.
The timing is not coincidental. On March 18, Taiwan is due to hold
an election to find a replacement for President Lee Teng-hui. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (975 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-CHINA-EYES-TAIWAN-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOK CLUBS AND THE INTERNET: A HAPPY ENDING? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When book-buying on the Internet took off, it seemed like the
read-it-and-weep demise of book clubs. Now the story looks a little
different: not so much new technology kills old business, as old
business reinvents itself to use new technology for its own ends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Business Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WEB-BOOKCLUBS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS BRIEFS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE WEEK IN INTERNATIONAL BUSINESS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A compilation of international financial briefs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WORLDBIZ-ECONOMIST-NTYSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `FATHER COURAGE': MEN BEHAVING DADDILY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If proof were needed that we are past halftime in the sexual
revolution, it is provided by a lively new book, ``Father
Courage,'' by Suzanne Braun Levine (Harcourt; 228 pages; $24). A
chronicle of the struggles of American fathers trying to find a new
balance between the ``Triple Crown'' (family, work and social
life), it shows the other side of the phenomenon of the working
woman: the phenomenon of the family man. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Book Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-WORKING-SUPERDADS-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAPANESE ANIMATION FILMS: TOY STORIES FOR GROWN-UPS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The increasingly stunning animation emerging from the U.S. (in
films like ``A Bug's Life'' and ``Toy Story 2'') is, quite
literally, child's play alongside the full-length animated films
that have been pouring out of Japan since the 1980s. Nothing could
be farther from the comforting world of Bambi than Japan's edgy,
provocative, documentary-like ``anime.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-JAPANIMATION-CINEMA-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW THE WORLD MIGHT END &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By and large, scientists are an optimistic bunch. Some of them
can even remain cheerful when pondering something that most people
would regard as deeply depressing: the eventual destruction of the
earth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Iowa, Michigan Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Moved as BC-EARTH-APOCALYPSE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF &LR;  &QL; 
