<P>
   &UR; THE FEAR OF LOATHING ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-McCAIN-ADS-TV _ Are negative advertisements so much
worse than positive ones? Is either category actually a bad thing?
And does either really matter? The answers are no, no and a lot
less than you probably think. At the national level, the
brainwashing powers of political advertising have long been
exaggerated. Given the rise of channel surfing, mute buttons, the
Internet and irony, traditional advertising is becoming only less
effective, in the view of a number of media consultants. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GRUNTS OF GROZNY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATROCITIES-RUSSIAN-CHECHNYA _ The soldiers who helped Russia
take Grozny were not the grizzled combat veterans the Kremlin
insisted it was sending to the front. They were untested conscripts
plucked from Russian factories and farms, down-on-their-luck
mercenaries unable to find steady work at home, militiamen more
accustomed to policing a rock concert than searching for snipers.
And they were young officers like Lt. Vyacheslav Kiselyov, who went
to a military school to become a border guard and never imagined he
would end up in the Chechen caldron. By Michael Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SALON: FROM OUTER SPACE TO THE SKINNER BOX &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SALON-INTERNET-ZINE _ When the Internet magazine Salon went
public last June, nobody got obscenely rich. The IPO did underwrite
a few perks, however, that give the company the appearance of
new-economy prosperity. But the homespun, seat-of-your-pants era of
the Internet _ the era in which Salon rose to prominence and which
it, in some sense, grew to symbolize _ is history. Forging strange
alliances, old and new media giants seem poised to carve up the
Internet for themselves, leaving maybe a few table scraps for
independent outfits like Salon. By Helen Thorpe.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (New York headquarters: 212-499-3300 or 1-800-972-3550; fax,
212-499-3382.) &LR;
</P>
