<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MCCAIN (Washington) _ California's Democratic governor,
Gray Davis, says former Sen. Bill Bradley has `a very large hill to
climb'' to beat Vice President Al Gore in next Tuesday's California
primary because the Clinton-Gore administration has done a lot for
the state. Meanwhile, on the Republican side, Sen. John McCain
appears to face an increasingly tough race in the New York primary
against Gov. George W. Bush. Pollster John Zogby says Catholic
voters are shifting to Bush after he apologized for failing to
criticize anti-Catholic teachings at Bob Jones University. By DAN
FREEDMAN and STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COURT-SEARCHES (Washington) _ Supreme Court justices ask tough
questions in hearing oral arguments in two cases dealing with when
police may stop and frisk people who don't appear to have broken
the law. The court's decisions could have a major impact on the way
police try to control drug trafficking and gun violence. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Religion has had an underground
influence on political campaigns since this nation was founded. But
not since John F. Kennedy publicly confronted the issue of
anti-Catholic hostility has religion played such a central role as
it is doing in this year's Republican primary contest between John
McCain and George W. Bush. Kennedy had to convince voters he was
not a captive of his church; McCain is trying to convince voters
the GOP is no longer a captive of the religious right. By MARIANNE
MEANS.
</P>
