<SLUG> BC-MARRY-MILLIONAIRE-TVSHOW-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WANTS TO STRANGLE THIS DOPEY MULTIMILLIONAIRE? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   ``His elevator doesn't go all the way to the top.'' _ The
ex-fiance of Rick Rockwell, in a 1991 petition for a restraining
order.
</P>
<P>
   ........................
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, none of us had heard of Rick Rockwell, the
leading man of the Fox-TV special, ``Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire''?
</P>
<P>
   Now I've got a 40-page file on the guy, brimming with news
clippings, Internet scoops, his show-biz resume, notes from people
who know him, court documents and publicity shots.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happens when you place yourself in the middle of a
pop culture phenomenon: Most of your life gets thwacked on the
media's doorstep, landing with all the subtlety of a big bag of
steaming ... information. And in Rockwell's case, we've found out
that he's a lot goofier and a bit more complex than the charming,
wealthy groom who proposed to one Darva Conger and then exchanged
wedding vows with her in front of a huge and stunned TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out Fox could have come up with all sorts of alternative
titles for the show, like, ``Who Wants to Marry a Publicity
Hound?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Who Wants to Marry The Star of `Return of the Killer
Tomatoes'?''
</P>
<P>
   Or, ``Who Wants to Marry a Dude Who Drives a Volkswagen?''
</P>
<P>
   By now, a hungry media have uncovered all sorts of interesting
trivia about the no-longer-mysterious groom. (And perhaps it's only
a matter of time before one of Darva's ex-boyfriends sells naked
Polaroids of her on the Internet or spills secrets about her life
to the tabloids.)
</P>
<P>
   We now know that the former Richard Balkey is a cheesy comic and
rabid publicity dog who wrote and appeared in two ``Tomatoes''
sequels, did corporate comedy gigs, played a Russian guy in a
series of commercials for AM/PM mini-markets and was on ``Star
Search'' a half-dozen times.
</P>
<P>
   Among Rockwell's other stunts: Telling jokes for 30 straight
hours; bicycling from LA to Las Vegas to promote a comedy club; and
chartering a plane to take him to comedy gigs in six cities in one
night.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever a comic is that desperate for attention, you can be
sure of one thing: He ain't going to be that funny.
</P>
<P>
   When Rockwell emerged from the shadows and showed up on Fox's
doomed show, veterans of comedy clubs _ especially in Pittsburgh
and San Diego, where Rockwell has lived _ were falling out of their
chairs in disbelief. He's the Sugar Daddy! No way!
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Cohen, who now lives in Chicago, instantly remembered
Rockwell from her days doing standup comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm watching that downfall of modern society on TV, and it
turns out I know that multimillionaire!'' she laughed. ``He used to
play the Pittsburgh Funny Bone about three times a year, and he hit
the Chicago Improv regularly back when that was open.''
</P>
<P>
   An AP story quotes a San Diego dating-service owner who has
known Rockwell for years: ``I thought, `That's your millionaire?
You've got to be joking. He's a likable guy and he's funny, but
we're all wondering, when did he become a millionaire? How did we
miss that?''
</P>
<P>
   Some comics have accused Rockwell of joke-stealing. A woman told
a San Diego radio station that Rockwell professed his love for her
just before he did the TV show. An ex-girlfriend told a San Diego
station that Rockwell told her he was doing the whole thing as a
gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   In Vancouver, one real-estate agent claimed Rockwell's only
holding is a ``low-end condo that leaks,'' while another called him
a ``loser'' and a ``flake.'' Meanwhile, the San Diego Tribune noted
that Rockwell lives in a one-story, 1,200-square-foot house and
drives a Volkswagen. While the guy apparently is a millionaire on
paper, he's a long way from megarich. The lovely Darva has probably
been hit on by wealthier guys at her health club.
</P>
<P>
   And now, far from fantasyland, the glitzy couple will be just
one more set of statistics in the rosters of failed matrimony. The
torrent of negative publicity has been so relentless that Fox
canceled plans to air a one-hour repeat of the show. No doubt their
internal memos have headings like, ``Who Wants to Strangle This
Dopey Multimillionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents I've perused, an ex-fiance of
Rockwell's had some troubling things to say about him. Whether or
not her claims are true, his romantic past probably should have
been discussed with his new bride, as would be the case in almost
any marriage that doesn't take place six minutes after the couple
meets.
</P>
<P>
   When a 42-year-old and a 35-year-old get together, they're going
to have to address some bumps and mistakes in their respective
pasts. It's best to talk through at least some of it before saying,
``That's OK, I love ya anyway babe!''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe on that cruise ship they learned all kinds of things about
each other _ and life as well. Maybe they found the keys to such
puzzles as, ``What kind of an idiot marries a total stranger on
national TV?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ----------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1415EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0163 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2031 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ASADOORIAN     02-29 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ASADOORIAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 RED SOX DID SOME HOME WORK ON YOUNG ASADOORIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Rick Asadoorian, the native son drafted first
by the Red Sox last June, comes from a Massachusetts town so small,
it's really not a town at all. Whitinsville (pop. 5,500) is
basically a borough of Northbridge, a relative metropolis of 13,000
located on the Mumford River, 14 miles southeast of Worcester.
</P>
<P>
   You can count the number of stoplights in Whitinsville on one
hand. There's one near the Burger King, another at the intersection
of Church and Prospect streets, and a double set of lights in
Memorial Square.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's Pizza is the most popular place to eat in town. There's
a diner that has gone through numerous name changes. It's Peg's
now, but when it was known as Fred's, it recruited a star athlete
from neighboring Auburn to play basketball. Him, you might have
heard of. Arthur Pappas grew up to be the Red Sox team doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But Pappas's name is on a short list of celebrities with
Whitinsville ties. Jane Swift, the lieutenant governor, lives here.
The in-laws of Millard Fillmore, the 13th President and one of the
least distinguished, once lived here. That apparently had the
locals busting with pride, because in the town history book,
there's a photo of the schoolhouse in which Fillmore's portrait
hangs above George Washington's.
</P>
<P>
   The town takes its name from John C. Whitin, founder of the
Whitin Machine Works, which at the height of the war employed
around 7,000 workers but is now shut down. Varkis Asadoorian, the
son of Armenian immigrants, worked 40 years there as a foundry
worker. He was a core maker, hard work in a mill town full of hard
workers, many of them with Armenian roots.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Popkin Kasparian was the oldest living player in
Northbridge High School history. Kasparian was a boy in Armenia
during the Turkish genocide in World War I. The Turks threw all the
boys of the village in a pit, then doused them with gasoline and
set it aflame. Little Popkin escaped the pit by climbing onto the
shoulders of his bigger brothers.
</P>
<P>
   One day, dodging death in Armenia. The next, living to play
football in America. That is a story that will be passed down from
generation to generation in Whitinsville. This may well be another,
the story of a gifted teenage outfielder who already has evoked
comparisons to one of the most beloved of all homegrown Sox
players, Tony Conigliaro. And it begins in Varkis Asadoorian's
backyard, where his grandson, 4-year-old Rick, first played Whiffle
Ball with his older brothers, Greg and Steve.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never let me hit,'' he said. ``I always had to shag.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning here, before the big leaguers took over the
premises, Asadoorian was still shagging, running down fly balls hit
to him by 80-year-old Johnny Pesky. The little boy has long since
grown into a 6-foot-2-inch, 185-pound frame, with more filling out
sure to come.
</P>
<P>
   Asadoorian moves with an easy grace that bespeaks his
athleticism, one that not only had the baseball scouts coming in
droves but enabled him to be a record-setting wide receiver and
kicker on the football team and shooting guard on the basketball
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, I like this kid,'' Pesky said. ``He reminds me of the
young Tony C.''
</P>
<P>
   Pesky was the Sox manager when Conigliaro first caught New
England's fancy. Conigliaro was 19, the same age as Asadoorian, who
was born after Conigliaro retired and knows of Tony C only through
his father and mother, Steve and Virginia. Steve Asadoorian was
Northbridge High class president and his future wife, Ginger
Tessier, was vice president and three-sport star in 1965, the year
after Conigliaro made his big-league debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad has told me some things about Tony C,'' Asadoorian
said. ``I don't really know the meaning of it, but I know it's a
really big compliment.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the summer after his junior year in high school that
Butch Hobson, the former Sox third baseman and manager, was
Asadoorian's manager in the Area Code games, a gathering of the
best high school players in the country held in San Diego that
July. Hobson pulled aside Asadoorian's father one morning and told
him: ``Your kid has a real chance to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   By last spring, there were plenty of big-league types who felt
the same way. Ray Fagnant, the Sox scout based in New England, had
been watching Asadoorian for some time. Sox scouting director Wayne
Britton came to see for himself, as did Eddie Haas, Dan Duquette's
special assistant. But they were hardly alone. At one Northbridge
game, there were 42 scouts in attendance, by Steve Asadoorian's
reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the afternoon Duquette showed up. ``My teammates
told me he was there, but I didn't see him,'' Asadoorian said. ``I
had a pretty good day, though. I think I went 4 for 5.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the draft last June, Asadoorian was on his senior
class trip in Connecticut but was carrying a pager he'd borrowed
from a cousin. The pager went off early that afternoon. ``I looked
at it,'' Asadoorian said, ``and it said, `Red Sox. No. 17.' I
thought, `Awesome.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who picked 17th, signed Asadoorian two months later to
a $1.725 million bonus, the largest ever given by the Sox to a
drafted player. So much for the option of going to the University
of Florida. On the night the team announced the signing, Fagnant
said: ``I could scout for 30 more years and not come across another
like Rick. He has all the tools. His arm is a jaw-dropper. And he's
bright, mature, confident and humble.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagnant said he told Asadoorian: ``Opening Day, 2003, center
field in the new Fenway Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Asadoorian knows that just as with the new Fenway, it may not
happen that quickly. In that sense, this is not Tony C redux. He'd
love to begin his pro career playing a full schedule in Augusta
(Ga.) of the South Atlantic League, but knows he may start in
Lowell, which plays a shorter season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm not ready to play in the big leagues or even Double
A and maybe not Single A,'' he said. ``I don't have a time limit
for myself. I don't say I have to be there in three years. When I
talked to Wayne Britten he said, `There's no reason to rush.' I
don't want to put added pressure on myself.''
</P>
<P>
   On that giddy first night in Fenway, when Asadoorian was asked
to say a few words during the Sox radio broadcast, his thoughts ran
to Varkis Asadoorian, who had come to so many of his games and
whose picture was on the family refrigerator, his grandson in his
No. 44 jersey, arm wrapped around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Grampy,'' Asadoorian said.
</P>
<P>
   Asadoorian attended the Sox instructional league last fall, then
came back on his own after Thanksgiving and except for a quick trip
home for Christmas, has been working out ever since. This week, he
has been taking part in the team's minicamp for its top minor
leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Steve and Ginger Asadoorian hope to visit their son here next
week. Rick's brother, Steve, is a senior on the UMass baseball
team, which will be playing Florida at Gainesville, then the family
was going to drive down here. Steve was going to take time off from
his job as a union rep for the Mass. Federation of Teachers, Ginger
from hers as a math professor at Quinsigamond College.
</P>
<P>
   Varkis Asadoorian so much wanted to come see his grandson, too.
But his health is failing rapidly. A diabetic, he already has had
one leg amputated and may soon lose the other. He also is legally
blind, another consequence of the condition.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Rick's father also was diagnosed with diabetes.
``You see it and you wonder if that's in front of you,'' Steve
Asadoorian said, ``but you deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's something of a tradition in Whitinsville. Remember Popkin
Kasparian, the boy who climbed out of a pit of fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone can't wait to see Rick play someday in Boston,''
Steve Asadoorian said, ``Maybe his grandfather can't see him play
anymore, but he is so thrilled and proud that everybody is rooting
for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
