u s BC-OLY-HERBERICH-BOS &LR;      02-29 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HERBERICH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERBERICH OPTS TO PUT HIS SLED ON ICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ACTON, Mass. _ Jim Herberich comes down to greet a visitor in
the lobby of the environmental consulting firm where he works. He
is wearing a buttoned-down shirt and slacks, indoor clothes for
what used to be his outdoor season. ``I'm not used to coming here
when it's snowing out,'' Herberich says.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, he normally would have been driving a bobsled on
the World Cup circuit. Instead, Herberich was sitting in front of a
computer in Nagog Office Park, analyzing hydrological data. ``All
I'm doing,'' he says, ``is picking up for a full year what I used
to do for a half year.''
</P>
<P>
   For the other half, from October through February, Herberich
would steer a rattling metal jalopy with one or three other men
aboard at 80 miles per hour down an iced concrete run.
</P>
<P>
   Herberich had been doing it since the Reagan era, when he was a
quarter-miler fresh out of Harvard, looking for a new athletic
diversion before he joined the 9-to-5 crowd. He had made the US
team again last autumn and was on track to make his fourth Olympic
team for the Games in Salt Lake City two years from now.
</P>
<P>
   And then, just before he was scheduled to fly across the ocean,
Herberich put his helmet on the shelf. He was 36, had been riding
the roller coaster for 15 years and had enough USA logo gear to
fill a closet. That was enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of things coming together,'' Herberich says.
``The travel and the lifestyle had really begun to wear on me even
before the 1998 Games. Living out of a bag for half the year wasn't
what I wanted to be doing any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Making yet another trip to Olympus wasn't enough reason to keep
sliding. Salt Lake held no romance for him. Herberich has been
there often enough that he can draw its street grid from memory.
``Part of the interesting thing about the Olympics is being
somewhere else,'' he says. And what founder Baron Pierre de
Coubertin said about the Games _ that the most important thing is
taking part _ isn't as true the fourth time around.
</P>
<P>
   Herberich has been seventh at Olympus before. The only reason to
go back was to win a medal. No American driver has managed that
since 1956 and Herberich wasn't sure he could make the commitment
required to make the podium. ``There are so many variables,'' he
says, ``and I didn't think I had control of enough of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Herberich had been getting the retirement itch even before
Nagano, but he came back the next October for another go and
competed all season with a fractured pubic bone. When the symptoms
returned last fall, Herberich came home for a bone scan _ and a
career assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I laid out all the pros and cons,'' he says. ``At first I
thought, maybe I should just go away for a while, then come back
and train again. Then I said no, I don't want to do that. It just
seemed like a good time to quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Herberich had been going up the mountain since 1985, when he got
one of the recruiting letters that were being sent to athletes
(like including football players, decathletes and runners) who
might make good bobsledders. The federation was looking for ``big,
fast, crazy guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You qualify on the third count,'' Harvard track coach Frank
Haggerty assured Herberich.
</P>
<P>
   So Herberich went to Lake Placid, took a special fitness test
and topped it. Matt Roy, the top US driver, promptly tapped
Herberich for his brakeman and three years later Herberich was in
Calgary for the Olympics. ``I'm pretty much hooked on this,'' he
concluded, ``but I'm not going to push any more.''
</P>
<P>
   So Herberich switched to driving and became a fixture on the US
squad. During autumn and winter, he hopscotched from Germany to
Switzerland to Latvia to Austria to Italy to France. During spring
and fall, he worked for ENSR, an international firm that does
environmental consulting and engineering work.
</P>
<P>
   His employers were terrific about his dual life, Herberich says,
and his colleagues were delighted to have an Olympian on the
premises. ``Everyone was very supportive,'' he says. ``People get
excited when they have a personal connection to the Olympics. They
were always coming up and saying what a wonderful thing it was to
watch the Games knowing I was competing.''
</P>
<P>
   Herberich made the team again for Lillehammer in 1994 and again
for Nagano. He had become a lock as USA II, right behind Brian
Shimer. And though his best results came in the two-man event,
Herberich loved the four-man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like driving a 1,400-pound truck down a mountain at
death-defying speed,'' he says. ``It's like a roller coaster ride.
Scare yourself silly _ and go do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobsledders call it the ``champagne of thrills'' and Herberich
could have kept going all the way to Utah. ``It wasn't just the
excitement and thrills, but the challenge,'' he says. ``But it was
a full-time job for two minutes of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   So even though the bone scan came back negative last fall,
Herberich's mind was made up. ``I sort of expected this,'' US coach
Steve Maiorca said when Herberich called him. The tougher task was
breaking the news to brakeman Dave Owens. ``That was hard,''
Herberich says. ``We'd tied our futures together. He was in Newark
on his way to Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens caught on with Shimer's crew and four-man pusher Doug
Sharp was picked up by Todd Hays. And Herberich put on his street
clothes and went back to the office park. ``It was the first time
in 15 years that I was home for Thanksgiving,'' he says. ``And my
girlfriend is extremely happy that I'm not on tour all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   On weekends, Herberich went online to check on the action from
St. Moritz and Cortina and Altenberg and the rest of the tracks he
could drive in his sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd pull up the results on a Sunday afternoon to see how they
did and there was no feeling like, gee, I can beat these guys,''
Herberich says. ``That really proved to me that I made the right
decision.''
</P>
<P>
   When he went to Germany last month for the world championships
in Altenberg, his favorite track, Herberich went as a technical
observer. When 2002 comes around, he'll be the director of race
operations for the Olympic bobsledding events at Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a crime for me not to keep involved in some way,''
said Herberich. ``Bobsledding is the one thing I've done for a
longer time than anything in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He still has his old two-man sled. ``And when I'm in Park City I
can give passenger rides and get it out of my system,'' he says.
But the USA gear is staying in the closet for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I would have liked to have won some races, done better
at World Cups and better at the 1998 Olympics,'' Herberich shrugs.
``But I don't look back on anything with regret.''
</P>
<P>
   He rode the icy roller coaster longer than most and walked away
in one piece. ``I broke a bone here and there,'' Herberich says.
``Broke a collarbone in 1988 in Calgary. Shimer and I crashed an
old sled.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing that scrambled his brains or put him in a body cast.
Quitting while ahead is one of the vanishing arts in America. ``The
only sport I'm doing now,'' says Jim Herberich, ``is seeing how
fast I can run through the channels on the remote control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
