<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2033 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-29 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLITICIAN SPEAKS IN CODE THAT MAKES SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I don't know what the California version is of
the Congressional Medal of Honor, but I think State Sen. Debra
Bowen ought to get one.
</P>
<P>
   A Democrat from Marina Del Rey, Bowen has finally done something
so sensible _ and overdue _ it's hard to believe it came from a
politician.
</P>
<P>
   She recently introduced a bill that would require the California
Public Utilities Commission to assign new telephone area codes on
the basis of technology, not geography.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is hardly new. Since the very first Americans learned
that competition among carriers and the proliferation of cell
phones had forced a ``split'' of their longstanding area code,
plenty of phone customers have wondered: ``Why don't they give cell
phone users their own area code and leave the rest of us the hell
alone?''
</P>
<P>
   For awhile, the excuse was ``the technology'' being too
unsophisticated. This really meant: We could do it, but it would
cost a lot of money, and then we couldn't spread cell phones like
some airborne virus throughout the population.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead, city after city and region after region was carved
up and subdivided. People who had had the same area code since the
system went public back in the Eisenhower era _ when all area codes
were an easy-to-remember numerical sandwich with a ``0'' or a ``1''
as the meat _ suddenly found themselves with nasty three-digit
combinations like 582 and 831.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, they suddenly found themselves forced to dial more
numbers to call Grandma or the office, just a few miles away, even
though neither party had moved an inch.
</P>
<P>
   How out of control have things gotten?
</P>
<P>
   Until Bowen's bill, San Francisco, a compact city whose borders
have long stopped at 49 square miles, faced one of two equally ugly
fates: A geographic split into two area code parcels or a ghastly
``overlay'' system.
</P>
<P>
   With the former, a gerrymandered line that cuts off downtown and
the Financial District from the rest of the city and Marin County
would be used to determine who keeps ``415'' and who loses it.
Folks who may have owned their home and the same rotary dial phone
for 45 years in the Sunset District might get the weird new code.
Or some 100-year-old business downtown might get it.
</P>
<P>
   The only alternative offered for this stupidity was another
stupidity: the dreadful ``geographic overlay.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody with ``415'' could keep it, but all new phone service
_ even for the house next door _ would get the new area code. And
everybody would have to dial the area code plus the seven-digit
number, even for phones in the same code.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we look around the state at what's happening, area code
after area code is changing,'' Bowen told the San Francisco
Examiner. ``It doesn't make any sense to wait until we're near a
crisis and running out of numbers to then go and change numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   God bless Bowen for at least trying to mitigate total disaster.
</P>
<P>
   If her bill passes _ and that first requires the Federal
Communications Commission to lift its antiquated prohibition
against separate area codes for cell phones and digital pagers _
the new area codes would be assigned to the new wireless phone
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Is that sensible or what?
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Sen. Bowen, you go, girl. For the first time in decades,
California has a solution to its area code problem that's easy as
1-2-3.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
