<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2034 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LUCENT-VENTURING-BOS &LR;      02-29 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LUCENT-VENTURING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUCENT GROUP LOOKS WITHIN FOR IDEAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last time Stephen Socolof stood before a roomful of Harvard
Business School students, he had just braved a howling blizzard on
a drive from New Hampshire. Harried and snow-coated, the MBA
student from Dartmouth's Tuck school burst into a waiting room to
interview with a hot consulting firm. His Harvard rivals were
neatly pressed, sitting in silence, staring at him.
</P>
<P>
   How the roles have reversed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Harvard MBA class is going to school on Socolof's
work. He is a partner and vice president of Lucent Technologies
Inc.'s New Ventures Group, a $200 million-plus portfolio of
business ideas culled from the brainy depths of Bell Laboratories.
He visited the school last month to hear students discuss a case
study on the operation, which is seen as one of the best examples
of ``corporate venturing'' among US firms.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucent group is an incubator for more than a dozen
early-stage businesses. Many would never have seen the light of day
without this new focus, started in 1997. Bell Labs claims four new
patents a day, but ideas can wither inside a giant company.
</P>
<P>
   More than a year after Lucent's spinoff from AT&AMP;T, there was a
move to shed the phone-company culture and to become more
entrepreneurial. As venture capital and the IPO market took off,
Lucent didn't want to miss opportunities lurking within its very
walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to emulate the Silicon Valley model inside Lucent,''
Socolof said during his recent visit to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the group tried outside venture deals while also
mining ideas from Bell Labs. That didn't work, Socolof said; the
attention still darted outside. So the efforts were separated.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent started Palo Alto, Calif.-based Lucent Venture Partners
Inc. It invests in classic venture deals through a $100 million
fund and is expected to launch a second fund soon.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Socolof's group zoomed in on Lucent's home-grown
technologies, and results quickly followed. The group spawned a
digital radio company, half of which was sold to outside investors.
Other innovations involve electronic fingerprinting, analysis of
huge volumes of phone calls, and faster 911 responses by police and
fire departments.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ventures have been acquired by Lucent itself. None
has gone public yet, but Socolof hopes to deliver an IPO by the end
of the year _ a development that makes the group more financially
important to Murray Hill, N.J.-based Lucent than the top brass ever
dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure our companies are ready to stand up on
our own,'' Socolof said. ``We'll end up with a large part of (the
stock) after the public offering.''
</P>
<P>
   Even without an IPO, the new venture unit has produced a
triple-digit return in three years, Socolof said. That's better
than his goal of returning an average 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for big returns is a huge draw for corporations
that wade into VC, said Rosabeth Moss Kanter, the Harvard Business
School professor and innovation expert whose class studied Lucent's
venture program.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon goes in cycles, she explained, based largely on
the health of the IPO market (because IPOs are typically the exit
strategy for VC investors). Intel Corp. is a big participant now,
as are scores of computer makers, media conglomerates, and
industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
   Companies supplied $7.3 billion to entrepreneurs last year, or
15 percent of the total $48.3 billion of venture financings in
1999, according to Venture Economics. That's up from $1.3 billion,
or 7 percent of the total, in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   During the late 1960s and early 1970s, lots of big companies
jumped into venture investing, Kanter explained. But when the IPO
market dried up in 1973, so did the venture capital. Things heated
up again in the 1980s, but they evaporated after the '87 crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I love about the new economy is that no one
has any memory of anything that's ever happened before,'' Kanter
said. ``Companies are going public earlier, faster. But that
doesn't mean that you don't have to manage some of the same
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, Kanter said, it was popular to discuss why
corporate venturing doesn't work. While companies can make big
money and get closer to new technologies, venture capital tends to
run counter to the big-company culture.
</P>
<P>
   In times of vast technology booms, like we're experiencing now
with the Internet, telecommunications, and software, Kanter said,
big companies want to invest in promising innovations. But often,
she said, the bureaucracy creeps back in: ``The mainstream of the
business starts rebelling. . . . These entrepreneurs break the
rules and get to have so much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Socolof and his partners are working to avoid those
pitfalls. They've spent time getting top executives to buy into
their mission. They're imposing financial discipline on their
upstarts. Even so, various units of Lucent are trying to be more
innovative, in a sense competing with New Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she said, corporate venturing is ``a piece of a
bigger change process.'' And that's good for business.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IPO watch
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some initial public offerings scheduled for this week:
</P>
<P>
   ImageWare Systems Inc., San Diego, 1.5m shares, priced $8-10,
business services and software; MatrixOne Inc., Chelmsford, Mass.,
5m shares, priced $12-14, business services and software; Net
Genesis Corp., Cambridge, Mass., 4.25m shares, priced $11-13,
business services and software; Niku Corp., Redwood City, Calif.,
8m shares, priced $20-22, business services and software.
</P>
<P>
   Onvia.com Inc., Seattle, 8m shares, priced $11-13, business
services and software; Prime Response Inc., Cambridge, Mass., 3.5m
shares, priced $11-13, business services and software; Register.com
Inc., New York, 5m shares, $15-17, business services and software;
Switchboard Inc., Westboro, Mass., 5.5m shares, priced $10-12,
business services and software; Urban Cool Network Inc., Dallas, 2m
shares, priced $9-11, business services and software; Versata Inc.,
Oakland, 3.85m shares, priced $12-14, business services and
software.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Beth Healy can be reached by e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
