<HEADLINE>
SAN DIEGO SIZES THINGS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They think big in San Diego and vicinity. Here, from the San
Diego Visitors &AMP; Convention Bureau, are some of the sunny area's
claims to largeness:
</P>
<P>
   --The opulent Hotel del Coronado on Coronado Island is the
largest wooden structure in the United States. (The Del itself
merely says it is ``probably one of the largest wooden structures
in the United States.'')
</P>
<P>
   --The world's largest outdoor pipe organ is at the 2,400-seat
Spreckels Organ Pavilion in Balboa Park.
</P>
<P>
   --The Birch Aquarium at Scripps in La Jolla is the largest
oceanographic museum in the country. The aquarium has 33 tanks,
including a two-story, 70,000-gallon kelp forest. A living tidepool
is outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   --San Diego is home to the largest military complex in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   --Mission Bay, at 4,600 acres with 27 miles of beaches, is the
world's largest aquatic park.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about San Diego (or to dispute these
claims), write to the San Diego Visitors &AMP; Convention Bureau, 401 B
St., Suite 1400, Dept. 700, San Diego, CA 92101-4237; call
619-236-1212; or visit www.sandiego.org. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Wouldn't it be wonderful to have a zoo in San Diego? I
believe I'll build one'' _ Dr. Henry Wegeforth in 1906. Today's San
Diego Zoo is among the finest in the world. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Which US city has, on average, the lowest summer
temperature? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: Women may not wear pants in Tucson. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Disneyland cleans up: In one year, the California park uses up
1,000 brooms, 500 dustpans, 3,000 mops, 20,000 gallons of paint,
11,000 gallons of liquid disinfectant, 26 million hand towels, and
19 miles of toilet paper. Each night 500 custodians, painters,
welders, electricians, decorators, costumers, and horticulturists
keep the park clean and bright. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of Disneyland: Throughout 2000, Disneyland will be
celebrating its 45th year with a new ``45 Years of Magic'' parade,
a new fireworks show, and more Disney characters spending more time
in the park. For more information, call 714-781-4565 or visit
www.disneyland.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Perfect ``crime'': An old stone obelisk in the Plaza in the heart
of Santa Fe commemorates New Mexico's defenses against hostile
Indian attacks. A plaque on the obelisk once referred to ``savage''
American Indians. But some three decades ago, during the busiest
part of the day, someone with ``City of Santa Fe'' stenciled on his
jacket and a hard hat on his head chiseled out the word ``savage,''
then disappeared into the crowd. The faux city worker was never
found, and the offending word has never been replaced. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel bookshelf: ``Best Places: Southern California'' (Sasquatch
Books, $19.95) was researched and written by a dozen southern
Californians and even comes with a money-back guarantee. The
guidebook lists the top 1,000 restaurants and lodgings, including
places for romantic getaways, weekend retreats, and family trips.
The many attractions of this multifaceted region are included, as
are what's new and what's hot. Also from Sasquatch is ``Best
Places: San Diego'' ($18.95). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Freebie: The 2000 Official State of Alaska Vacation Planner is a
96-page guide filled with trip-planning advice, whether you are
planning to fly, drive, or cruise. The guide includes a directory
of services for the entire state, regional highlights, a statewide
calendar of events, fishing opportunities, and facts on Alaska's
vast parklands. For a copy, call 800-862-5275 or visit
www.apr.travelalaska.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Barrow, Alaska, with an average temperature of 36
degrees Fahrenheit. &QL; 
 &QL; 
