<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVE-REPARATIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROMINENT BLACK SCHOLARS JOIN PUSH FOR REPARATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move that could take the issue of paid reparations for
American slavery from the fringes of black political debate into
the mainstream civil rights agenda, a group of prominent black
academics are looking into a possible class-action lawsuit on
behalf of the descendants of those injured by slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Law School professor Charles Ogletree, Harvard
Afro-American Studies Department Head Henry Louis Gates, and many
others of the country's top black intellectuals say they are
considering legal and legislative action to secure reparations for
the descendants of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Other groups, such as Japanese-Americans interned during World
War II, have turned to the courts to right historical wrongs. And
activists since Emancipation have argued that America should be
made to pay for the horrors it visited upon its first black
residents. But until now, the issue has largely been championed by
isolated lower-level political leaders and left-wing activists, and
the country's potential debt for slavery has not been tested in the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking at what's the viability of legal action and
political viability of legislative action and then more morally how
can we get beyond the history of slavery to think of ways to
comprehensively remedy it,'' Ogletree said.
</P>
<P>
   Gates said he is planning to ask the board of the Harvard's
W.E.B Du Bois Institute to examine the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics, though, worried that an organized demand for
payment, whether in the form of a lawsuit or federal legislation,
would be so divisive that it could set back race relations at a
time when blacks are overcoming some of the social and economic
disadvantages of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with some of the policies that are being discussed,''
said Kwame Anthony Appiah, also a professor at Harvard University
and a board member of the Du Bois Institute. But ``guilt tripping
on a whole is not an effective way to make political policies
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   And some legal scholars questioned whether Ogletree and others
would be able to successfully sue so long after the events, with
all of the direct victims long since dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between the people actually enslaved and
those bringing the lawsuit,'' said Jules Coleman, a professor at
Yale Law School. ``The question is: Would the courts recognize the
latter?''
</P>
<P>
   But Harvard-trained attorney Randall Robinson, who helped
rekindle interest in the idea of reparations with his book ``The
Debt: What America Owes Blacks,'' said slavery is a human rights
crime dating from the day Africans were first forcibly brought to
the colonies until 1965, after voting rights act was passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not just talking about slavery but the century of
discrimination that followed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said the 40 race riots, 4,700 or more lynchings, as
well as more institutional discrimination such as redlining _ all,
he argues, extensions of slavery _ have accounted for an estimated
$1.4 trillion loss in wealth for African Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no surprise that blacks are on a whole poorer than
whites,'' Robinson, a leader in the fight against South African
apartheid, said. ``The genesis in the poverty gap can be found in
slavery and sustained by laws.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, demands for reparations have never gained much
political currency. Former Massachusetts state senator Bill Owens
repeatedly demanded reparations be paid to blacks _ while others,
including some black political opponents in his own district,
argued that the cause was fruitless and emblematic of an outmoded
'60s style of activism.
</P>
<P>
   But rap group Public Enemy wrote songs about reparations,
bringing the cause into the college-radio scene. And John Conyers,
a US Representative from Detroit, has been trying in vain to push a
reparations bill in Congress for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Now, said Conyers, ``It is coming out of the eccentric phase and
being considered something that really ought to be given serious
scrutiny and examination.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, Robinson called a number of well-known scholars from
the nation's top schools as well as mainstream civil rights leaders
to discuss the issue in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Among those who attended the meeting and are now joining
Ogletree were Dorothy Height, director of the National Council of
Negro Women; actor Danny Glover; and political consultant Ronald
Walters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any question they have given this issue
new altitude,'' said Robinson of the academics. ``I think there is
a broader consensus than assumed in the black community.''
</P>
<P>
   If the effort moves forward, though, it's not clear what its
proponents would demand. They could ask for a cash settlement of
some kind, but, more likely, said Robinson, they would ask for
broader programs to help blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agreed that a legal case would be daunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is the court route is the rougher route because the
US government has to allow itself to be sued, before we can pursue
it,'' said Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   And the case, said some, might even involve other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I advocate European and American governments engaged in the
slave trade to forgive debt for all African Nations and, secondly,
subsidizing drug-related treatment for HIV positive (black)
victims,'' said Gates.
</P>
<P>
   But Ogletree said his goal is not to make individuals rich but
to close the book on one of the most painful chapters in American
and European history.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a situation of someone sitting at the mailbox
waiting for a check, that trivializes the broad purpose,'' said
Ogletree. ``The real point is to put closure to a very sorry period
in our history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
