<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT GUIDED BY HIS RIGHT TO PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Ballplayers. Fans want to watch them. Fans
want to know about them. As your humble servants, it's our job to
tell you about them. But how much do you want to know? And how deep
are we obligated to dig?
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox have a new center fielder and we know so little
about him. Carl Everett seems like a nice-enough young man. He's
friendly with teammates, cooperates with reporters, signs
autographs for fans, and does a nice job at the plate and in the
field.
</P>
<P>
   There's a four-page biography of Everett in the Sox 2000 press
guide. The bio is jammed with facts, stats, and minutia. It tells
you that Carl hit .325 with 25 homers, 108 RBIs and 27 steals with
the Astros last year. It tells you that Carl went to the same Tampa
High School as Dwight Gooden and Gary Sheffield and that he rushed
for 948 yards as a senior running back. It also tells you that he
weighs 190 pounds, which is 30 pounds less than he actually weighs.
</P>
<P>
   ``One ninety was my rookie ball weight,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing in the bio about the fact that Everett was a
catcher in high school and ran a 10.3 100. It doesn't tell you that
he loves to draw and hates to smile for photographs.
</P>
<P>
   And there's no mention of Carl's family.
</P>
<P>
   Family history is usually part of a player's press guide bio. It
is in the press guide that we learn that Scott Hatteberg's wife
goes by ``Bitsy.''
</P>
<P>
   The guide was the best way to keep things straight when dealing
with Kody, Kory, Koby, and Kacy Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   But the Everett bio offers no mention of wife, Linda, or his
five children.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my request,'' Everett said, sitting in front of his
locker after a workout at the Sox minor league complex.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox acquired Everett from Houston for minor-leaguers
Adam Everett and Greg Miller last December. Boston then signed the
28-year-old switch-hitter to a three-year, $21 million contract.
He's never played a game in Fenway Park, but has already been
annointed Boston's best center fielder since Fred Lynn. Everett's
bat is supposed to provide punch and protection for Nomar
Garciaparra in the heart of the Boston batting order. He's a
multi-tool player with Earl Campbell thighs and his presence has
some fans thinking the Sox might be able to overtake the mighty
Yankees this season.
</P>
<P>
   Do we need to know about his family situation? Is it anybody's
business that Everett and his wife lost custody of two of his
children when he was an outfielder with the Mets in 1997? And is
Everett under any obligation to explain any of this as long as he
does his job and obeys the law?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a private family and that's what I think a lot of
people don't like,'' said Everett. ``I think everyone feels
violated, when you're here to play baseball and other things like
that try to interfere with it. I just overlook those people. I give
'em their opinion, they can say what they want to say, continue to
be whom they are, I don't worry about it. It's over.''
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, a child-care provider at Shea Stadium expressed
concern about bruises on Shawna and Carl IV, who were 4 and 5,
respectively. The children were put in city custody and the
Everetts went to Queens family court which ruled that Linda Everett
(who is Shawna's stepmother) used ``excessive corporal punishment''
and that Carl Everett ``failed to take appropriate action.'' The
court ordered the Everetts to parenting classes and mental health
evaluations. Carl IV was eventually returned to his parents. Shawna
went to live with a grandmother, and Everett is evasive when asked
if he has regained custody of his daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's in Tampa,'' he said. ``Everybody's home in Tampa. We're
gonna end that. It's over with. I don't worry about it. That's
water under the bridge. I don't worry about that anymore. It's over
with and my kids are safe, that's all I care about.''
</P>
<P>
   Every family has issues. Here in the sports department, it seems
like a good idea to let families of athletes keep their problems
private as long as they're not missing games because they're in
court. Red Sox outfielder Wilfredo Cordero was run out of town
after beating his wife a few summers ago. Drew Bledsoe, Max Lane,
and Scott Zolak made news when a young woman was hurt on the night
they were stage-diving at the Paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Everett is entitled to his privacy. He just wants to play ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Houston it was fine,'' he said. ``Houston doesn't look for
stuff like that. Houston takes you as a player. That's what you
like about it. No matter what you say, people are gonna have their
opinion about things, so you just go ahead and let 'em do it. I
don't worry about how people think about me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox' first spring game is Thursday against the Twins. It
says so. Right there in the press guide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
