<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2045 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-REUSABLE-PAPER-BOS &LR;      02-29 1579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUSABLE-PAPER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE E-PAPER CHASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Imagine that the newspaper you are now
holding is digital. After reading it, you place it on the breakfast
table until tomorrow morning, when it will be automatically,
wirelessly updated with a fresh batch of stories.
</P>
<P>
   Except it's not really paper; it's ``electronic paper'' embedded
with ``electronic ink.''
</P>
<P>
   That scenario is not as futuristic as it may seem. Two companies
_ eInk Corp. in Cambridge, Mass. and Xerox Corp. in Palo Alto _ are
racing to deliver the next-generation publishing medium to
consumers. Each has made significant steps toward that goal,
although both acknowledge that a marketable product may not be
available for years. But with billions spent annually in the
publishing and display markets, the payoff could be huge.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast is the fabled Xerox Palo Alto Research Center,
known as Xerox PARC, the laboratory that invented laser printing;
the ethernet; and the point-and-click, menu-driven graphics common
to computer software.
</P>
<P>
   On the East Coast is eInk, a small start-up founded by a
professor and two students from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology's Media Lab, whose whacky, wearable inventions have a
penchant for grabbing headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the e-paper chase. The prize: electronic paper that
looks and feels like its paper cousin but can morph from ``War and
Peace'' to ``Anna Karenina'' at the click of a button.
Theoretically, an e-paper book can store an entire library on a
computer installed in its spine.
</P>
<P>
   The market potential is more than just books, however. It's
electronic magazines and newspapers that can be regularly updated,
price tags that can be instantly changed by remote control to
reflect a sale, and, eventually, displays that will pop up on all
sorts of electronic gadgets, even smart ``wallpaper'' that can
change patterns to match a room's decor.
</P>
<P>
   The race is being keenly followed by several giant companies,
including Hearst Corp., Lucent Technologies, 3M Co., and Motorola
Inc., all of which have either backed the projects financially or
have entered into technical partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   While the ultimate goal of the contest _ the electronic book or
newspaper _ now seems within reach, analysts are skeptical that it
will ever completely replace the world of paper and ink.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't expect paper and ink to go away anytime soon,''
said Matthew Harrigan, senior vice president and media analyst at
Seisel, Nicolaus, Hanifen, Imhoff in Denver. ``It's going to be a
complementary technology. The notion that this is a huge
replacement of newspaper may be overzealous.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, other analysts see greater potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's exciting,'' said Charlene Li, an analyst with
Forrester Research in Cambridge. ``It allows paper to be
interactive.''
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts also point out that publishers can distribute
their content to e-books over the Internet or wireless radio waves,
saving on printing and distribution costs. For newspaper
publishers, e-paper could solve the two biggest reader complaints:
inky fingers and old newspapers that pile up.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the basic technology of both companies works:
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between sheets of clear, flexible plastic are
ultra-thin transistors that direct billions of tiny black and white
balls to arrange themselves in ways that would display letters or
pictures. Think of hundreds of people at a Patriots game holding up
black-and-white placards that spell a slogan or form a team logo.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between Xerox and eInk lies in the ping pong-like
balls. Xerox's ``ePaper'' project has created balls, each measuring
one-tenth of a millimeter, that are exactly half black, half white.
The balls rotate, displaying either black or white depending on the
electric charge being applied.
</P>
<P>
   eInk's product involves similarly sized, transparent spheres
containing black oil and dozens of tiny white beads that, through
an electric charge, either float to create a white image, or
submerge to appear dark.
</P>
<P>
   Looked at another way, e-paper is just another mode for
displaying text, like a computer screen. But the advantages of
digital paper over the liquid crystal displays, or LCDs, used in
computer screens are numerous, says Jim Iuliano, chief executive of
eInk.
</P>
<P>
   The first is power consumption. LCDs must be fed with a
continuous power source; turn off the power and the display
disappears. Digital paper requires power only when it is changing
its display, consuming 50 to 100 times less power than LCDs,
according to Iuliano.
</P>
<P>
   The second advantage is that e-paper is a lot easier on the eyes
than LCDs, which constantly blast viewers with light. LCDs are made
with expensive, heavy, breakable glass whose properties limit the
size of the screen. Digital paper, on the other hand, can be
lightweight and shatterproof, and it can be manufactured by the
mile in the same way paper is made into rolls.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably take at least five years before either Xerox or
eInk will cross the finish line and create commercially viable
electronic paper. Both companies say there are major hurdles ahead
that they are feverishly trying to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious challenge is to come up with full-color displays.
Right now, the technology can accommodate just two colors at any
one time. Xerox is is working on ``subtractive color,'' a
technology that involves multicolored beads that when mixed could
create a full-color spectrum. eInk is working on a method that
mimics the technology in liquid crystal displays.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem for both companies is making the spheres even
smaller to improve the resolution. At 100 microns in diameter, the
current size that can be economically achieved by both companies,
the balls create an image of about 100 dots per inch. At 50
microns, the resolution improves to 200 dots per inch or better. By
comparison, a typical liquid crystal computer screen has a
resolution of about 70 dots per inch.
</P>
<P>
   A final, broad set of issues revolves around the manufacturing
process, according to Pierre Wiltzius, a researcher at Lucent's
Bell Laboratories in Murray Hill, N.J., eInk's technology partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we think all the elements are there, we are now in the
stage of taking this out of the lab environment and trying to turn
it into real technology that can be mass produced,'' Wiltzius said.
``It's a bigger step than you might think.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will win the race?
</P>
<P>
   Although Xerox had a head start, eInk is rapidly catching up.
And both have formidable resources.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox, for example, has Nicholas Sheridon, the ``father of
e-paper,'' a 64-year-old physicist who in the mid-1970s invented
the black-and-white spheres and holds several dozen patents on the
process. It also has a $19.4 billion annual revenue stream and an
exclusive manufacturing agreement with 3M.
</P>
<P>
   The project, which once counted just Sheridon and an assistant,
now has ``considerably more'' scientists working on it, said
Sheridon, who said the exact count and the money Xerox has spent on
the project is proprietary.
</P>
<P>
   When it's done, Xerox is aiming to produce 8.5-by-11-inch sheets
of paper with the thickness of glossy magazine paper for $5 a page,
and a device costing about $100 that can hold up to 10 full-size
books and transfer its content onto the page.
</P>
<P>
   eInk got its start in 1995, when Joseph Jacobson, an MIT
professor working at the school's Media Lab (whose scientists have
come up with computerized jackets and shoes), hired several
students to work on developing an electronic book.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his students, J.D. Albert and Barrett Comiskey, came up
with the microcapsules after they had trouble reproducing
Sheridon's work. The two formed eInk in April 1997, two months
before they graduated from MIT.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company has raised $52.8 million from 19 companies,
including Motorola in Schaumburg, Ill., The Hearst Corp. in New
York, Atlas Venture in Boston, Cabot Corp. in Boston, and the
Vivendi Group in France. In October, eInk formed a technology
partnership with Lucent, which is developing ultra-thin, flexible
transistors that can be ``microprinted'' to control the electronic
ink.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has allowed eInk to be the first to introduce a
commercial product, the Immedia advertising display, which has been
used by Yahoo Inc. and in test stores owned by J.C. Penney and
Eckerd Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The boards, which measure 4 feet by 3 feet, aren't cheap,
costing $1,000 or more per sign. In November, Yahoo used eInk's
technology in creating sandwich boards promoting Yahoo online
shopping services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sandwich boards allowed us to reach people where they
shopped,'' said LuAnne Calvert, a brand marketer at Yahoo. ``It
definitely caught people's attention. It was so unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem: The signs could not operate in freezing
temperatures and had to be moved from Chicago to Dallas after
several weeks. ``We had anticipated that,'' Calvert said.
</P>
<P>
   Cold temperatures aside, there are plenty of other wrinkles to
be ironed out to keep eInk and Xerox busy for at least five more
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about some pretty far-out technologies,'' said
Alan Alper, an analyst at Gomez Advisors in Lincoln Mass. ``It's a
matter of being able to get it there in a cost-effective, foolproof
way. But the intrinsic business value is definitely there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
