u a BC-AOL-TIMEWARNER-BOS &LR;      02-29 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-TIMEWARNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS SEE REASONS TO FLEE AOL-TIME WARNER DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON AND HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even though the planned deal between America Online Inc. and
Time Warner Inc. is still firmly on track, a lot of investors have
chosen to hop off the train.
</P>
<P>
   Time Warner shares spiked upward on news of the deal, but have
lost a good portion of those gains. And AOL shares have fallen off
sharply. Even last week's strong upturn, spurred by a positive
report from a major Wall Street analyst, hasn't brought AOl back to
its premerger price.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's stock was trading at 73 3/4 before the deal was announced
on Jan. 10; last Tuesday it had fallen to 49 5/8. Time Warner
soared from 64 3/4 to 92 1/4 on Jan. 10, but had slipped back to 73
9/16 last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Blodget, the respected Internet analyst for Merrill Lynch,
came to the rescue on Wednesday. Blodget issued a hefty report
hailing the AOL-Time Warner merger and urging investors to buy both
companies' shares.
</P>
<P>
   The report predicted the combined company will benefit from the
Internet's impact on the global media and communications
industries, as well as the development of consumer interactive
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would own the stock if for no other reason than this,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   The vote of confidence caused a substantial rally in AOL shares,
which closed Friday at 59 5/8. Time Warner ended the week at 84.
Both trade on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that puts AOL 20 percent below its predeal price.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's stock has been hammered partly because many investors who
thought they held shares in a high-flying Internet company fled
after discovering they would own part of a slower-growing media
company burdened with debt.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors are still raising questions about how to value
such a giant hybrid company and whether there will be long-term
benefits from the merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of (AOL investors) are voting with their feet,'' said
James Waggoner, an analyst with the investment firm Sands Brothers
&AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Waggoner has been a vocal critic of the deal. America Online, he
said, will surely benefit by absorbing Time Warner's content and
revenue stream. But he argues that AOL investors would fare better
_ and the same corporate goals would be accomplished _ if the two
companies had opted for a joint venture instead of a merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The AOL shareholders will be asked to carry the ball and chain
of the Time Warner debt and the much slower growth of the combined
companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As AOL becomes less of a fast-paced start-up technology firm and
more of an old-guard company with slower growth, it also may have
trouble retaining and attracting employees, some analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The possibility of a brain drain is real,'' said Pat Dorsey,
an analyst with Morningstar Inc.
</P>
<P>
   But the retention problem is widespread in the technology
industry, as employees abandon older firms for the chance to make
it rich with stock ownership in upstart companies.
</P>
<P>
   Most industry observers agree that the proposed union is
unlikely to be abandoned by either party. But it's not a done deal
until the last paper is signed, one analyst said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no doubt that both parties want the deal to get done,''
said Scott Davis, an analyst with Schroder &AMP; Co. in New York. ``But
I don't think you can say the risk is zero that the deal won't go
through.''
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with analysts last month, Michael Kelly,
AOL's chief financial officer, sought to allay fears about the
deal. He said the combined company's earnings before interest,
taxes, depreciation, and amortization would be 30 percent in 2001.
That growth rate would put the merged company in line with large
technology firms like Microsoft Corp. and Cisco Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we are confident in our ability to drive superior
results,'' Kelly told analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say it would take much more than plummeting stock
prices for Time Warner or AOL to shelve the deal.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, neither side demanded back-out clauses in
the event that company shares hit a minimum price. And there are
stiff penalties for ending the engagement. AOL would have to pay a
$5.4 billion breakup fee. If Time Warner ditched AOL, it would owe
$3.9 billion. Both companies can walk away from the deal if it's
not consummated by May 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an indication that both side are saying, `We're going
to go ahead and do this thing,' '' analyst Dorsey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado-based Janus Capital Corp., the biggest
institutional shareholder in both companies, strongly supports the
deal, according to assistant portfolio manager John Schreiber.
</P>
<P>
   ``The logic behind the merger is impeccable,'' said Schreiber.
``The combination of the two companies will create a media
powerhouse the likes of which the world has never seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Schreiber blamed the declining stock price on ``uneducated
institutional money fleeing both the Time Warner and AOL sides
because they couldn't figure out how to value the company.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said that AOL attracts many individual investors who
also have sold shares out of confusion about the deal. By contrast,
Time Warner has a higher proportion of institutional holders
willing to hang on for the ride. Schreiber said that this explains
why AOL stock fell further than Time Warner's in recent weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1431EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
