<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2053 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-29 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEET NORM PAYSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; He graduated from Massachusetts Institute of Technology in
1970 with a degree in earth sciences and mathematics. Then
Dartmouth Medical School, followed by two years service in the
Indian Health Service in Arizona, to cancel the debt.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, he practiced medicine, then moved into management.
In 1985 he founded Healthsource, a health maintenance organization
based in Hooksett serving rural New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years later, fueled by a string of acquisitions of
physicians' practices financed on Wall Street, Healthsource had
sales of $1.7 billion and operations in 15 states.
</P>
<P>
   When he sold the company to Cigna Corp. for $1.7 billion in
August 1997, Payson cashed out with $94 million.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, he was back, this time as chief executive of
Oxford Health Plans, a publicly owned firm which is one of biggest
managed care companies in the Northeast, with more than 2 million
members in New York, New Jersey, and Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Oxford was on the brink of bankruptcy, the result of pell-mell
growth and computer problems. Its share price dropped to less than
$6 a share from a high of $89
</P>
<P>
   Payson was recruited by worried investors to turn the firm
around. Texas Pacific, a group of wealthy investors including David
Bonderman _ who had made a bundle on buying Continental Airlines at
a fire-sale price _ put in $350 million, expecting to own 22
percent of Oxford. Payson put in $10 million of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Oxford is in much better shape, selling at
about $16 a share. Payson closed several unprofitable lines of
business, raised premiums on the rest, and spent heavily on new
information systems. Doctors in particular praised the turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Payson is the human face of for-profit health care _ one
human face, anyway. Oxford is among the potential investors who
have expressed an interest in Harvard Pilgrim health plan. I have
no way of knowing whether he is seriously interested, but I'd be
very surprised if he were not.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly, who is
overseeing the receivership of the troubled HMO, says he thinks
Harvard Pilgrim needs something like $238 million in order to
continue operations.
</P>
<P>
   At a certain point in the deliberations Friday, one wag
suggested: Why not just reorganize, capitalize the Harvard name as
an asset, and recognize it on the balance sheet?
</P>
<P>
   That, plus the sale of some $150 million in real estate, might
improve matters to the point that the HMO could resume operating
without state protection from its creditors.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there will be no such accounting sleight-of-hand. Nor
apparently is Harvard University going to help the ailing
Harvard-Pilgrim organization, despite having blown life into it 30
years ago and having semi-governed it until it got into trouble.
That was then, this is now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that . . . the university is somehow responsible for
the bailout is just a nonstarter,'' Harvard's vice president for
public relations Paul Grogan told The Boston Globe's Richard Knox.
``We have no corporate affiliation with Harvard Pilgrim. We're not
responsible for its condition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're deeply concerned, as are many employers, and want to
help. Somehow that has been construed in a way that's very
unrealistic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Reilly told the Globe that Harvard ``hasn't shown any
degree of seriousness to helping in a substantive way'' to resolve
the impasse. He called the university's insistence that any loans
it made be guaranteed by the state ``preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's teaching hospitals _ Massachusetts General, Brigham
and Women's, and Beth Israel chief among them _ are independently
chartered and not owned by the university. But they owe their power
and prestige to their affiliation with it, share power with the
Harvard Medical School, and, in several cases, have substantial
endowments of their own. The hospitals are said to have demanded a
return to state rate-setting as a condition for their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's options seem to boil down to two:
</P>
<P>
   Call the bluff of the hospitals, persuading them to accept some
manner of debt rescheduling, at the same time seeking state loan
guarantees to provide some fresh money. A mandatory increase in
reserve requirements for other HMOs, Harvard-Pilgrim, presumably
would require premium increases sufficient to return Harvard
Pilgrim to good health.
</P>
<P>
   Or sell it _ to a willing buyer like Payson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
