<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-29 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTANA GUIDE'S FORTE IS THE ROAD LESS TAKEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, you want to see the real West, and you may be looking for an
authentic alternative to the Alaska Inside Passage cruise.
</P>
<P>
   The answer is to seek a specialist _ one who knows the
territory, loves it, and wants to share it with visitors. Bill
Bryan is that type of person.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Maine, he's been leading Off The Beaten Path for
more than 15 years. The company (27 East Main St., Bozeman, MT
59715; telephone 406-586-1311; or www.offthebeatenpath.com) has
been specializing in the Rockies and the Southwest, now Alaska and
also Patagonia, way down in Chile and Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   As Bryan notes in the company brochure, ``We are the friends you
wish you had here, who will steer you to the remarkable places that
make these regions so appealing.'' Off The Beaten Path runs
organized but small tours, will customize a vacation, and even
provide personal travel consulting. While you pay for these
services, what you get in return is the vacation experience of a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Yellowstone, the Canadian Rockies, Wyoming, Colorado, Glacier
National Park, undiscovered vacation spots, real ranch vacations,
authentic Alaska _ whatever your vision is of the West or Alaska,
seeking out people like Bryan may be the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus is on the realization that the traveler wants to be
an `insider,' not a tourist,'' says Bryan. ``And, at the same time,
the Western traveler wants a quality experience that has a
learning/educational element and is rooted in authenticity. We are
also seeing more family adventures in authentic and learning
environments. We are seeing more families coming on trips to the
West that involve a variety of activities. And we're seeing the
rise of families wanting to go on small group trips with other
families.''
</P>
<P>
   The company started with sizable fees, which met some resistance
at the outset, Bryant says. But Off The Beaten Path has not only
become acceptable, it is well known throughout the specialty travel
business, and with travel agents.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Garden visits &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking for some gardens that are open to the public? ``The
Garden Conservancy's Open Days Directory: The Guide to Visiting
Hundreds of America's Best Private Gardens'' (Abrams, $14.95)
offers gardens that are open to the public on select weekend days
from March through October. This year 17 new cities were added to
the book, including destinations in New Hampshire and Long Island's
North Shore. The book can be ordered ($14.95 plus $3.50 shipping)
by writing to the Garden Conservancy, PO Box 219, Cold Spring, NY
10516 or calling 888-842-2442. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Safety first &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jiminy Peak in Hancock, Mass. is going all out to reduce
accidents and provide a more enjoyable environment for skiers. The
most visible safety effort is the creation of non-speed zones where
skiers and snowboarders are required to keep at the average speed
of the users of that particular slope. On the seven trails marked,
Mountain Safety Patrol members will be giving tickets to those who
violate the rules. Consistent violators will lose their lift ticket
but get an opportunity to redeem it by watching a mountain safety
video. The safety patrol is a volunteer organization with 40
members (very visible in their bright yellow jackets) that started
five years ago. For more information, check out
www.jiminypeak.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Summer reading &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like to spend your summer reading and discussing great
works of literature, philosophy, and the opera, take off for Santa
Fe. Each summer St. John's College, nationally recognized as the
great books school, offers a unique educational experience in a
small group, seminar-style setting. The Summer Classics is a series
of weeklong seminars, with participants choosing one seminar a week
for up to three weeks. Mornings are dedicated to the seminar, with
afternoons free for studying or participating in college-sponsored
excursions. For information, write to Summer Classics, St. John's
College, 1160 Camino Cruz Blanca, Santa Fe, NM 87501; telephone
505-984-6104; or visit www.sjcsf.edu.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATA to Chicago &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ATA (American Trans Air) will begin nonstop service between
Boston and Chicago's Midway Airport May 7. Three flights daily
(except Saturday) will be offered. Direct, same-plane service will
also be offered between Boston and Dallas/ Fort Worth, Denver, and
Seattle. To introduce the service, ATA will offer fares to Midway
beginning at $79 each way for travel May 7-June 30. Tickets must be
purchased by March 31. From Boston, other introductory fares
include Dallas, $99/$109; Denver, Las Vegas, Seattle, and San
Francisco, $119/$149. Fares are one-way and for off-peak and peak
periods. For information, call 800-1-FLY-ATA.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Good deals &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Ciboney Ocho Rios spa and beach resort in Jamaica has a
Diamond Package that for $99 a person above the standard provides
an upgrade to a Diamond Villa suite (all-inclusive rack rates begin
at $240 a person through March 31, and $205 April 1-Dec. 22). The
villa package includes an attendant to prepare breakfast, do light
washing and ironing, and pack. The package also includes an
in-villa romantic dinner for two with a personal balladeer, and
five spa treatments a day per person. The nine-year-old resort is
undergoing a complete renovation, which ``will not disturb the
guest experience,'' said Peter Trench, co-general manager. For
information, call 800-CIBONEY.
</P>
