<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-DURANGO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DURANGO DELIGHTS CAPTURE A FAMILY OF THREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURANGO, Colo. _ Return to Durango. It sounds like a 1950s
western directed by John Ford. Starring Henry Fonda. In
Cinemascope.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not a movie. It's part of a six-week trip through the
American West, starring our family of three and a rented Buick. We
first visited this part of southwestern Colorado seven years ago,
and vowed to return. So when we were laying out our 6,500-mile
itinerary, we made certain it included this former mining town of
15,000 souls, even though coming here would require me to motor
through the San Juan Mountains with my eyes closed _ in the back
seat. More about that later.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I especially like about Durango. Although it's
clearly a tourist town, especially during summer and fall, it's
also the real Western deal. It has art galleries populated by
shoppers from Dallas and pool rooms with shooters from down along
the Animas River. It has folks from Illinois who've come to
day-trip on the Durango &AMP; Silverton Narrow Gauge Railroad, and
cowboys from New Mexico who are here for the Durango Pro Rodeo
Series. It has RVs bound for nearby Mesa Verde National Park and
horse trailers headed for the nearest stock auctions. It has
brewpubs where visitors raise pints of porter and saloons where
locals nurse near-empty glasses of Coors. And it stages an annual
Cowboy Gathering that features _ yes _ poetry.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting for 15 minutes one afternoon on a green metal bench on
Main Avenue, a National Register Historic District that's laced
with restored Victorian buildings, this is what I saw: a cowpoke
sporting a tattoo that proclaimed him an Enemy of the State, a
portly gent sporting a Kansas City Board of Trade cap, a member of
the Southern Ute Indian Tribe in a Western hat with a perfectly
curved brim, a woman in a Hawaiian-print pantsuit, a teenage girl
in well-scuffed Western boots and a dirty red bandanna, a
horse-drawn carriage hired by a beaming family of four, a quartet
of Harley bikers in all-black gear, a tour bus unloading its brood
in front of the 112-year-old Strater Hotel, and a guy with a Texas
longhorn in his trailer.
</P>
<P>
   The fellow with the steer was Jeff Mannix, a local rancher who
came here via Marblehead, Mass., where he grew up, and Boston
University, from which he graduated in 1966. Mannix is also a
partner in the local rodeo, which is why he sometimes parks a
one-ton bull on Main Avenue. Passersby tend to stop to inspect such
a critter, and when they do Mannix gives them a rodeo flier and
talks up the show. He can also wax rhapsodic about the American
West, about how big everything is, about how ``free'' Durango
feels. ``I can leave town and drive 15 miles down to my ranch and
it's like I'm in Montana,'' he said, grinning. Then he handed out
another flier, urging folks to come see the rodeo tonight.
</P>
<P>
   (Which we did, incidentally. The crowd of about 700 people
included a group of 30 foreigners. When the announcer asked one of
them where they were from and was told Florence, he replied
``France! That's great!'' Whereupon he worked a bit of French into
many of his announcements. Whereupon all 700 of us, locals and
tourists alike, repeatedly hollered ``Italy! Italy!'' at him.)
</P>
<P>
   Durango is nothing if not a great place to be outdoors. The San
Juans, which rise as high as 14,000 feet above sea level, are the
largest range in the Rocky Mountains. The San Juan National Forest,
which contains many of these peaks, consists of some 2 million
acres. Sitting on that bench on Main Avenue, therefore, means
you'll also encounter more than a few hikers, campers, rafters,
bikers, boaters, rock climbers, anglers, hunters, horseback riders,
four-wheelers, kayakers, and, if you wait long enough in the year,
skiiers and snowboarders bound for Purgatory Ski Resort, 25 miles
north of town.
</P>
<P>
   We tried modestly to do our outdoor part during our four-day
stay. We hiked the eight-mile Animas Mountain Trail one morning,
climbing the switchbacks 1,600 feet above the Animas Valley and
town itself to points that are usually covered with deep snow from
November through May. We swam at Trimble Hot Springs, a trio of
pools 6 miles north of town in a neighborhood featuring an
assortment of small farms, a place where the water must be cooled
from its in-ground temperature of 130 degrees. (``It's great here
during a snowstorm,'' a local teenage swimmer advised us.) We
picknicked amid the Ponderosa pine at Vellecito Dam, 20 miles
northeast, and we piloted an alpine slide at Purgatory _ although
at $8 for the three-minute trip, we should have simply ridden the
chairlift up and down the mountain for free.
</P>
<P>
   But there are two things you absolutely must do while in
Durango, whether yours is a return trip or otherwise: Spend at
least a day at Mesa Verde and take a ride on the D &AMP; SNGR.
</P>
<P>
   Mesa Verde, 36 miles west of town and high above the Montezuma
and Mancos valleys, draws about 700,000 visitors a year. Small
wonder. Between AD 600 and 1300, it was home to a remarkable
civilization of some 4,000 Ancestral Puebloans _ people known as
Anasazi the last time we were here, but since renamed in the
interest of their current descendants, many of whom still live in
New Mexico and Arizona. There are a number of stunning cliff
dwellings you can visit at Mesa Verde, following eager park rangers
downward to the remains of elaborate sandstone structures that are
tucked into steep canyon walls. Mysteriously, the residents of
these communities departed their homes forever in the late 1200s,
leaving no written records behind. The ruins were accidentally
rediscovered by cowboys in 1881, and Mesa Verde is now the largest
architectural preserve in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of my wife's favorite places. Margery loves the
mystery of Mesa Verde, loves to stand among the ancient courtyards
and kivas and wonder why people lived here and why they left.
(Prevailing theory regarding the latter: drought.) This time we
spent a night at Far View Lodge, the modest 150-room park hotel
with a 100-mile view and, somewhat to the dismay of our 12-year-old
son, Ethan, no in-room phones or television sets. We visited the
ruins of communities now known as Long House and Cliff Palace,
trekking down steep pathways and climbing up log ladders. We did
not do Balcony House, because I do not do ladders more than 30 feet
long, whether they're in national parks or leaning against my home.
Indeed, when it came time to depart Cliff Palace, I wasn't
especially eager to walk through a narrow rock crevice and ascend a
20-footer near the top of the canyon. ``Would you rather spend the
night here?'' my wife asked. I climbed.
</P>
<P>
   (Margery's Red Hot Mesa Verde Travel Tip: Visit the park's
popular Chapin Mesa Archeological Museum early in the morning or
late in the afternoon, when it's least crowded. When you arrive at
the park, book guided tours of the much-visited Cliff Palace and
Balcony House during the same time periods. Book a tour of Long
House, which is well worth a visit but is not as popular, during
the busy midday.)
</P>
<P>
   But if carving a community out of the side of a cliff is
impressive, what about slicing a railroad out of one? Two days
later I was peering 400 feet straight down at the churning Animas
River, rocking gently in an open gondola car that was being slowly
pulled 45 miles northward from Durango to the Victorian mining town
of Silverton by a 150-ton vintage steam locomotive. The D &AMP; SNGR
was blasted through the mountains and forests here during the early
1880s to haul precious metals. Today it carries an equally valuable
cargo: about 200,000 tourists per year. I'm no railroad buff, but
plenty of folks who ride this remarkable train are dead serious
about rails. Overheard at the historic Durango depot before we
left:
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe I'm riding another train, Grandma.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll ride a lot of trains if you hang around with Grandpa
long enough. I think he'd like me better if I had steam coming out
of my ears.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip is a wonderful ride past sharp mountain peaks, stout
Douglas fir, abandoned mines, a limited-access resort, and . . ..
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear!'' someone yelled, and all us us scampered to one side of
the car to see a large black bear loping up a hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bear, bear, bear!'' someone else hollered a mile later, and we
dashed to the other side to see a mother with two cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the only place to be,'' smiling conductor Frank Cianci
declared, referring to the fact that the alternative to an open
seat is an enclosed coach where some folks actually pass the time
by reading newspapers or napping.
</P>
<P>
   (Nathan's Red Hot D &AMP; SNGR Travel Tip: Don't take children on a
round-trip excursion, which includes two 3 1/2-hour legs as well as
a two-hour-and-15-minute layover in Silverton. Instead, have them
take the train to Silverton with Adult A. Have Adult B drive to
Silverton, about an hour's journey by car. Adult A and the kids
then drive back to Durango, while Adult B returns aboard the train.
Aggravation and money are thereby saved.)
</P>
<P>
   I was not eager to depart Durango, for more reasons than one.
Foremost among them was that we would be leaving via a section of
the 236-mile San Juan Skyway known as the Million Dollar Highway.
The origin of this name is vague, but to me it simply means the
amount of money required to lure me to this stretch of road, which
peaks at 11,018 feet and threads a two-lane path along precipitous
slopes without the niceties of guard rails. A 20-foot ladder is one
thing; looking into the abyss from a Buick is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   I handed the car keys to Margery, assigned Ethan to the
copilot's seat, and hunkered down very low in the back seat. I'm
told that the iron-colored Red Mountains were majestic, the sheer
sides of Uncompahgre Gorge breathtaking, and the waterfalls
breaking over the tunnels lovely. I wouldn't know. I didn't surface
until we'd safely descended into the alpine village of Ouray _
rhymes with ``Hooray!'' if I'm not mistaken.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
