<HEADER>
A2059 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-SANTA-MONICA-B     02-29 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-SANTA-MONICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA MONICA IS SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA WITH A DIFFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILLIAM A. DAVIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA MONICA, Calif. _ You can't help liking a town that may be
an affluent celebrity haven but whose signature structure is a
humble Ferris wheel.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, this is Santa Monica, geographically in Greater Los
Angeles but philosophically a non-glitzy and low-tech loving place
that does things its own way. Which explains why the civic icon is
no ordinary Ferris wheel.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing it's been in Pacific Park, the amusement park on
Santa Monica Pier, ever since it opened in 1916 _ making it
practically Pleistocene by Southern California standards. Nine
stories high, it is also visible from just about anywhere along the
3-mile-plus crescent of beach-rimmed Santa Monica Bay. At night,
when the gaudy neon trim is switched on, the Ferris wheel resembles
a giant pinwheel.
</P>
<P>
   The distinctive Santa Monica touch, however, is that Pacific
Park's Ferris wheel was the first in the world to be solar-powered.
But then, Santa Monica is also the first city whose municipal
facilities are powered entirely by recycled energy, geothermal
power in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``The People's Republic of Santa Monica'' in the
1970s, when it adopted (but has since rescinded) rent control, the
city has long been known for its liberal politics and environmental
activism. This is a community that prefers the nonpolluting to the
high-powered, likes to preserve as well as develop, and
enthusiastically supports foot-powered activities of all sorts.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of California may still be car-crazy but in Santa
Monica people walk. Impressive numbers of them also jog, bike, and
roller-blade from place to place. A local institution is the Friday
Night Skate, when roller-blading enthusiasts meet at the base of
Santa Monica Pier and kick off on a 10-mile-long group loop around
the city.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Monica even has that relative rarity on the West Coast, a
good public transportation system. It is served by buses of both
the Los Angeles Metropolitan Transportation Authority and its own
Big Blue Bus line, which covers all of Santa Monica and also West
Los Angeles neighborhoods, such as Brentwood.
</P>
<P>
   However, the environmentalists' pride and joy _ and the most
convenient way to get around downtown Santa Monica and its
beachfront _ is the Tide Shuttle. The shuttle's colorfully
decorated electrically powered (i.e., non-polluting) minibuses run
daily every 15 minutes from 10 a.m. to 10 p.m. weekdays and until
midnight on weekends. The fare is just 25 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Monica is also proud of its car-free Third Street
Promenade, a three-block-long walking street lined with some of the
city's best shops, restaurants, and cafes and dotted with kiosks
and public art. The promenade is much frequented by musicians and
street performers.
</P>
<P>
   There are also many panhandlers. Liberal Santa Monica is more
tolerant of the homeless than other coastal communities, such as
its famously conservative neighbor, Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   Pedestrian streets are also created by temporarily closing them
to traffic for Santa Monica's outdoor farmers' markets, the largest
in the Los Angeles area. This is a health- and diet-conscious place
and market stalls _ many belonging to organic farmers _ are piled
high with fresh-picked produce, including many exotic varieties of
lettuce, spinach, and other vegetables rarely seen in East Coast
supermarkets. Markets are held around the intersection of Third
Street and Arizona Avenue on Wednesdays and Saturdays and elsewhere
in the city on other days.
</P>
<P>
   Another great place for walkers and people watchers is Palisades
Park, a lushly planted 25-acre park overlooking the Pacific.
Located on Ocean Avenue, it runs for 10 blocks and has footpaths
and a bicycle path that connect with coastal bikeways in Venice and
Marina del Rey. Stairs and pedestrian bridges over the Pacific
Coast Highway connect the park with Santa Monica's broad beach,
familiar to TV viewers as the backdrop for many ``Baywatch''
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Palisades Park recently got new plantings and an improved bike
path as part of an $8 million beach improvement project that
included the reopening _ with new state-of-the-weightlifter's-art
equipment _ of Muscle Beach, the area's original and most famous
seaside workout spot. For the less athletic, there is also
International Chess Park on Ocean Front Walk, south of the pier.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Monica has been a popular resort since the turn of the
century and has a number of old beachside hotels that have been not
only preserved but restored. One of the first to get this treatment
was the Shangri-La, a classic Art Deco hostelry on Ocean Avenue
across from Palisades Park. The most recent and grandest, however,
is the Renaissance Revival-style Casa del Mar, the last hotel
allowed right on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Built as a private club in 1926 _ and frequented by the likes of
Douglas Fairbanks Sr., Mary Pickford, and Charlie Chaplin _ it
eventually fell on hard times and in recent years was a ``longevity
center.'' It has been beautifully renovated in period style with
elegant public rooms that have a nice but not hokey 1920s feel to
them _ and terrific ocean views.
</P>
<P>
   Another new addition to the waterfront is The Lobster, a
restaurant beside the entrance to Santa Monica Pier. It, too, is
born again, sort of. Although essentially a modern building with
wraparound windows that provide patrons with long views of the
beautiful coastline and an up-close one of the Ferris wheel, The
Lobster's entrance incorporates the original 1930s seafood shack of
the same name. Santa Monica has a lot of good restaurants but The
Lobster's setting is special and it really takes the fruits of the
sea seriously: You can get Maine lobster as well as Pacific spiny
lobster, the white crab soup is exquisite, and the treatment of
fish such as black bass and John Dory is savory and imaginative.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, perhaps because its walkability gives it an
Old World feeling, Santa Monica has a large resident British
community. As a result, the community also has quite a few genuine
English pubs, the best known of which are The Brittania and Ye Olde
Kings Head. The atmosphere in these establishments, from the
accents of the patrons and staff to the beer on tap and the soccer
games on TV, is as English as bangers and mash _ usually found on
the menu along with fish and chips and boiled Brussels sprouts.
</P>
<P>
   Far more common in Santa Monica than pubs are art galleries, and
the city boasts some 75 galleries and museums. Nearly 30
contemporary galleries are clustered at Bergamot Station on
Michigan Avenue, the site as well of the Santa Monica Museum of
Art.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Monica also makes a convenient base from which to visit
the not-to-be-missed Getty Center: an architecturally dramatic
hilltop art complex in the foothills of the Santa Monica Mountains
in Brentwood, just over the LA line. Admission to the Getty Center
is free but parking is severely limited and spaces in the parking
garage must be reserved, sometimes days in advance.
</P>
<P>
   However, the number 14 Big Blue Bus stops right at the center's
street-level entrance, from where a computer-operated tram carries
visitors to the hilltop site. As the tram snakes its way up the
hillside, there are sweeping views of Los Angeles and the
mansion-speckled slopes of Brentwood while the center itself stands
out against the horizon like a contemporary version of the
Acropolis. The center is built, in fact, largely of travertine _ a
beige-colored stone that resembles marble _ from the same Italian
quarries used to build the Colosseum in Rome and other monuments of
the ancient world.
</P>
<P>
   Although it contains the art collection of the late oil tycoon
J. Paul Getty, the center is not a museum in the conventional
sense. Rather, it is a campuslike complex of six buildings _
clustered around a central courtyard like an ancient temple _
housing offices of the Getty Foundation and facilities for study
and research in art-related fields as well as exhibition galleries
and pavilions.
</P>
<P>
   Architect Richard Meier sited the low-rise buildings so that
they seem to fit naturally into their hillside but also offer
viewing platforms and openings that frame views and vistas. There
are fountains and reflecting pools and the entire complex is
surrounded by superbly landscaped gardens that are a delight any
time of year.
</P>
<P>
   Although certainly interesting, and containing a number of minor
masterpieces, the collection _ which includes paintings, sculpture,
and illuminated manuscripts _ isn't in the same world class as its
architecture. Nevertheless, the Getty Center is an extraordinary
place that invites lingering _ there is a good restaurant and
several cafes and coffee bars _ and can be hard to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
