<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2061 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS &LR;      02-29 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOLTON'S OFFER NEARLY BROUGHT R&AMP;B DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, while many of us were preoccupied with the unholy
matrimony of Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger and the Versace hanky
Jennifer Lopez tried to pass off as a dress at the Grammys, we were
narrowly missed by a disaster of world-shaking proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bolton almost bought the song catalog of the Isley
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   For some time, Bolton had been trying to buy out the assets of
Ronald Isley, leader of the greatest and most prolific R&AMP;B group in
music history. Despite 40 years of hits, Isley has so mismanaged
his money, it's a wonder the ``Behind the Music'' folks haven't
shown up at his door. Many others, though, have come a-knockin,'
including the Internal Revenue Service, which claims Isley owes
more than $5 million in taxes. The singer filed for bankruptcy
protection in 1997, and in December, the courts ordered liquidation
of his assets so his creditors could get paid.
</P>
<P>
   Into the fray came Bolton with a $5.3 million offer for Isley's
estate, which, among other things, would have given him the rights
and royalties to more than 200 Isley compositions and recordings _
everything from ``Shout'' to ``This Old Heart of Mine,'' ``It's
Your Thing'' to ``Fight the Power,'' and ``Voyage to Atlantis'' to
``Between the Sheets.''
</P>
<P>
   In a court statement, Bolton maintained his offer was ``clearly
in the best interest of creditors.'' But a Los Angeles Federal
court judge didn't agree, approving a competing _ and smaller _
offer from a Wall Street financier, thus bringing an end to
Bolton's bid.
</P>
<P>
   Thank heavens for Judge Kathleen March.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, if you will, rival composer Antonio Salieri laying
claim to the works of Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart. Or Pat Boone, who
made his early career in the 1950s sucking the air and energy out
of such songs as ``Tutti Frutti'' and ``Ain't That a Shame,''
buying the catalogs of Little Richard or Fats Domino. Bolton owning
the music of the Isley Brothers would have been just as ironic and
devastating.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think for a minute Bolton's offer had anything to do with
magnanimity, or a desire to help an artist down on his luck. You
might recall that in 1994 a Los Angeles jury labeled Bolton a
plagiarist after they found significant similarities between his
1991 hit, ``Love Is a Wonderful Thing,'' and a 1966 song of the
same title _ which happened to belong to the Isley Brothers. Bolton
and his record company were ordered to make things right to the
tune of $5.4 million, and an appeal is still pending. But if the
judge overseeing the Isley estate had accepted Bolton's offer,
Isley would have lost his share of the settlement, and Bolton would
have been off the hook.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another part to this. Lest anyone forget, Bolton
built his career on the backs of black artists, mauling,
manhandling, and generally massacring soul and R&AMP;B classics. With
his big yelping voice and remarkably small talent he laid to waste
such songs as Otis Redding's ``Sittin' on the Dock of the Bay,''
Percy Sledge's ``When a Man Loves a Woman,'' and Ray Charles's
``Georgia on My Mind.'' He sang every song with such unharnessed
histrionics it seemed like his head might explode _ yeah, if only.
</P>
<P>
   Considered by some as a blue-eyed soul singer (Van Morrison
might have something to say about that), the hole-in-his-soul
Bolton sold millions of records to folks who just didn't know
better. Wrote Stephen Thomas Erlewine in the ``All Music Guide'' of
Bolton's soul covers: he ``removes any pretense of subtlety,
straining any emotions from the song with his overwrought
delivery.'' And that's putting it kindly.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been nothing short of an abomination and a
travesty had Bolton been allowed to profit so directly from the
Isleys, whose music remains vital, and has long been popular in
television commercials, movies (try to think of ``Animal House''
without ``Shout'') and hip-hop samples.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this brush with near-catastrophe has taught Ronald Isley
anything about better financial management remains to be seen. But
this much is unassailably clear: Michael Bolton will thankfully
come no closer to the Isleys' song catalog than the ``I'' section
of his local record store. And that, to paraphrase Isley, is a
wonderful thing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
