<HEADLINE>
HAMILL'S `FORK' TURNS TOWARD A LOVE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN KOCH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FORK IN THE ROAD 
By Denis Hamill 
Pocket Books, 480 pp., $24.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the heart of Denis Hamill's ``Fork in the Road'' is the aptly
named Gina Furey. Poor, passionate, and wildly unconventional,
tender and primally scary, she is the center and high-revving
engine of this very entertaining novel, Hamill's sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Gina is the product of a Dickensian past, and Hamil captures the
bloody violence and romance of her Irish background in bright,
sharp prose. She lives in a Dublin slum that today seems a
throwback to an earlier era: ponies, goats, and dogs forage for
food among the covered wagons, garbage, and auto parts that
decorate the seething neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   This book is a departure from Hamill's usual hard-boiled crime
thrillers _ it's a fiery, knockabout love story, although abounding
in crime. The misdeeds are mostly Gina's. She is a ``traveler,'' or
Irish gypsy, steeped in a life of scamming and thievery. As
Hamill's narrator-protagonist, Colin Coyne, says of Gina and some
accomplices he spies pilfering clothes in a department store,
``These chicks could con Houdini.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a mercurial young woman like Gina, restless and prickly
and bound by ancient tradition to an itinerant life of crime,
living in residential Queens or attending the Academy Awards
ceremony in Los Angeles. She does both in ``Fork in the Road,''
whose often hilarious and sometimes poignant culture clashes give
it the quality of the first ``Crocodile Dundee'' movie, only more
literate and artful _ in the end, perhaps two parts art to one part
melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   It is through Gina's usually light-fingered pickpocketing that
we first encounter her. Colin has come to Dublin to mull over his
mother's recent death and search out a subject for a feature film.
He's a hungry young moviemaker, an Irish-American artist-stud from
Queens with a street savvy that can't quite match Gina's.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he cleverly manages to track her down after she
pockets his wallet. And Hamill, in the process, flavorfully evokes
the city and its inhabitants, often in fine, simple observations
such as this: ``Many of the gray-haired ladies reminded him (Colin)
of his mother, inherently industrious and moving in a double-time
step as if they were perpetually late for life itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Colin is magnetized by Gina's raw allure and brazen, illicit
lifestyle, so he not only follows her but falls for her. His
attraction, he wants to believe, is more professional than
romantic. So in sketching out a screenplay about her, he distances
himself by creating a naive alter ego, a character called Kieran.
Hamill presents Colin's notions about the film in italics, as when
Kieran ``falls for her the way some women fall for gangsters.
Kieran is a good guy who falls in love with a bad girl.''
</P>
<P>
   The device helps steer the novel around the shoals of
sentimentality, and serves to launch some of the book's
laugh-out-loud humor _ even if, by the end, it seems intrusive and
sophomorically pretentious. Nothing is funnier, by the way, than
the raucous visits of Gina's thieving, sponging family to America,
where one of them torches a Queens bar and Colin decides to hide
the family silver in a toolbox. The novel's virtues far outpace its
few distinct flaws, including a breathlessly action-oriented but
much too convenient conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Though mostly credible, Colin is a caricature: Gorgeous women
line up for his attentions, beefy men collapse under his fistic
prowess. Still, Hamill choreographs the couple's tumultuous,
picaresque pas de deux with gleeful energy, an unerring sense of
place, and a terrific ear for dialect. The jargon of the Irish
travelers, whom Hamill has clearly researched in detail, is
especially rich, often droll, and rampant with animal images. Says
Gina, for example, when Colin takes her to an upscale restaurant
for a salmon steak, ``That'll do me like a dog on a rat.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, there is Gina herself, a woman of appetites who can
``go from coarse hostility to blinding sweetness like a costume
change,'' and who's clever enough to wow a Hollywood producer with
her outspoken insights but so tied to traveler tradition she can't
stop stealing from Rodeo Drive boutiques. Perhaps ``Fork in the
Road'' isn't a masterwork, but this inspired and unforgettable
character is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
