<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPO LEFTOVERS: A NICE FIT WITH OLD LISBON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON _ If you missed Expo '98, as I did, and show up two years
late, that's OK. It's still here, and looking very good.
</P>
<P>
   Why tear down a handsome, imaginative district that was created
to welcome the world to Portugal's riverside party two years ago?
Leave it in place, was the smart decision, and let Lisboans and
visitors keep on enjoying it. Like these schoolchildren, in blue
caps and smocks, giggling their way along Volcano Row and marveling
at the periodic in-your-face eruptions that may splash them
harmlessly (with water, not lava) if they're not alert.
</P>
<P>
   The volcanoes, a lineup of 15-foot ceramic cones in bright reds,
greens, and yellows, spout as kids shout. They are just another of
the innumerable examples of Portuguese artistry in tile (azulejos)
through the ages. Then, at their teachers' suggestion, the
field-trippers move away to other attractions, like a pyramid of
ropes that just begs to be climbed.
</P>
<P>
   My friend, Aurelio, unable to resist any such clambering
prospect, ascends like a galleon's nimble deckhand in the rigging.
Her adult presence in their lair amuses the fellow-climbing kids,
who will go on to a variety of play sites amid gardens, fountains,
waterfalls, and captivating sculptures of African animals, among
them a towering, whimsical giraffe looking into a looking glass.
</P>
<P>
   An aerial tram offers a scenic overview that more fully reveals
the futuristic science center and the mushroom-shaped 16,000-seat
arena, to host the season-concluding ATP Masters tennis
championships in November.
</P>
<P>
   Once an unsafe neighborhood of warehouses and dingy domiciles
along the very broad Tagus River, the conduit for international
shipping to the Atlantic Ocean, it was upgraded spectacularly by
the Expo '98 concept. Spruced and rehabbed, it is distinguished by
exciting, innovative architecture that left such as an apartment
building masquerading as an ocean liner in its wake.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving by train, subway, or bus at Oriente Station, you are
overwhelmed by the feathery, airy structure that itself is enough
reason to look in on Lisbon. A city that pre-dates Christ, the town
is decorated by plenty of ancient evidence of Romanesque and Gothic
architects, like the compelling Monastery of Jeronimos or the
fortress called the Tower of Belem. Guarding the mouth of the
Tagus, from which Vasco da Gama and other renowned explorers of the
15th-century ``Age of Discovery'' set out on their voyages to
create a Portuguese empire, the tower seems a fancy wedding cake in
concrete. Looks good enough to eat, but only if you're the
steel-jawed Godzilla.
</P>
<P>
   Steel-ribbed is Oriente Station, perhaps owing something to
those old church builders of the Middle Ages. This masterpiece of
steel and glass _ a cathedral of transportation _ came from the
drawing board of the Spanish genius of design, Salvador Calatrava.
You might call it Calatrava Gothic, a modern takeoff on the
medieval: Three lanes of tracks as the nave and aisles extend
beneath steel-supported glass archways that dart heavenward 60
feet, seeming gossamer wings.
</P>
<P>
   Gawking at his intricate ceiling as you would the groined
vaulting of, say, the cathedral at Chartres, you are similarly
enchanted _ but here the sky enters in as an element, embellishing
the design. Way below, underground, the subway terminal is a happy
collage of tile murals.
</P>
<P>
   Close by, his bridge across the Tagus is another beauty. And,
currently underway, Calatrava's remake of Milwaukee's Museum of
Fine Arts, roofed by moving wings, will be regarded as one of the
world's wonders. Red Sox management should keep him in mind if they
ever really re-create that gem of Back Bay Gothic named Fenway
Park.
</P>
<P>
   A Boston architect, Peter Chermayeff, conceived Expo's
centerpiece, the Oceanario, an aquarium clearly deserving a
creme-de-la-creme rating (or is it cream of the water?).
Chermayeff, designer of the Boston aquarium, may be a fish's best
friend, at least a fish that has to lead a sheltered life. With a
``one ocean'' theme of blending all oceans, he has created habitats
that may pass as genuine-down-home in the minds of the thousands of
maritime roomers, swimming, flying, and growing.
</P>
<P>
   You could spend days absorbing a planet's worth of sea life _
underwater and on shore _ in huge display tanks. Denizens of every
ocean and temperature zone _ icy to balmy _ are on display, making
their daily rounds. Sharks and barracudas cruise menacingly.
Blue-eyed Antarctic penguins frolic. Gallant male cardinal fish,
incubating their young in their mouths, may starve in the maternal
role. Razorbill auks wing close to the water, and are able to
submerge and swim beneath the surface. Red algae bloom in tidal
pools. Coral reefs abound with life. Furry sea otters are the
comedians, backstroking, mugging, belly-flopping like clowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those otters are so cute and energetic, they make you hungry
just watching them,'' says Aurelio. She is tempted to dive in and
join in their shenanigans, but I persuade her that Chermayeff would
disapprove of humans integrating with the residents in his oceanic
fun house.
</P>
<P>
   Since the otters have aroused hunger, we compromise by mingling
with a fork in a seafood luncheon at Tapas Marina, one of the Expo
restaurants on a pier reaching out into the Tagus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
