<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HAVASU-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE LAND OF THE HAVASUPAI 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN CUNNINGHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The relaxed mood from my vacation began wearing off at 9:37 on a
Monday morning as I was driving to work. The place? A half-mile
before the toll booths on Boston's Tobin Bridge in stalled traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar tense feeling one gets in the stomach and shoulders
when commuting to Boston had returned. That white SUV in the right
lane with its wheels turned a bit to the left? No way am I letting
it cut in front of me, particularly since the driver is not
signaling. Look through the rear-view mirror. The woman driving the
car in back is creeping too close while talking on a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic crawls into a tunnel. Beyond, silhouetted against the
sky, are the girders and concrete structures of the Big Dig
project. It takes 50 minutes to go two miles. I am among tens of
thousands traveling into a city of nearly 600,000 inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   During the just-ended vacation in Arizona, my wife and I took
about the same amount of time to drive 60-plus miles one Monday
morning on a road bordered by ponderosa and pinon pine and saw only
one other moving vehicle, a pickup truck going in the other
direction.
</P>
<P>
   We were part of a group of nine to gather at a trailhead for a
hike down to Havasu Canyon, one of the prettiest spots in the Grand
Canyon area. Soaking in the pools beneath its waterfalls and hiking
its trails, one can easily forget everyday aggravations.
</P>
<P>
   In five days, we hiked more than 40 miles, saw a lot of
spectacular scenery, and met some nice people who lent a hand (and
a knee) to trail companions.
</P>
<P>
   We were in the land of the Havasupai _ The People of the
Blue-green Water.
</P>
<P>
   Water is always on one's mind there. It weighs down packs.
Hikers drink lots of it, more than you would imagine if you had not
hiked in the arid Southwest. Try three quarts, or a gallon a day if
you can get it.
</P>
<P>
   Water creates, water destroys, water creates. It's an endless
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Water brings life to Supai, the Indian village eight miles from
Hualapai Hilltop. It sustains gardens and fruit trees, and creates
a natural beauty that attracts visitors whose spending helps the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   It also can bring danger. At times in summer rains, called by
some the ``monsoon season,'' the creek can swell, endangering all
who live or camp along it. Hundreds fled a flash flood in August
1997. Similar floods were reported in 1990 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The water creates its own beauty and paves its pathway. As it
rushes on its winding route to the Colorado, the water carries
minerals in solution that reflect the blue sky, and which coat the
creek bed and nearby rocks with a rust-colored material called
travertine.
</P>
<P>
   We started hiking early on the first day, hoping to get to camp
or at least the village before the sun became most intense. The
first two miles or so were down a steep wall, but switchbacks
relieved some of the burden on our legs. We began seeing hikers,
often accompanied by a dog or two from the village, heading back up
to their cars.
</P>
<P>
   Dogs also come along with the pack trains and horseback riders
we saw a bit later. The dogs are remarkably well-behaved and seem
to consider it all in a day's work to tag along.
</P>
<P>
   Whose dogs are they? ``They belong to all of us,'' Dianna Sue
Uqualla, a village resident who gave a talk to us later in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   As the morning advanced, the sun beat down on us. Despite
sending some gear down by pack train, I began to feel the effort of
carrying a backpack. Perhaps spending the previous two days
overeating at Las Vegas buffets and playing the slots in smoky
rooms was not the best prelude to this kind of exertion. Two quarts
of water were consumed quickly. Greenery came into view as we
approached the creek and there was a bit of a cooling effect.
</P>
<P>
   When you get to Havasu Creek, you hear it before you see it, and
it is noisy as it flows past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't hear you when the water's running,'' was the response
to a soft-spoken comment.
</P>
<P>
   There are large cottonwood trees along the creek's banks. One
sees large white flowers on a thick stalk _ a type of morning
glory. Even the prickly pear cactus seems in bloom, sporting a
darkish fruit colored like a ripe eggplant.
</P>
<P>
   Trip leader Bruce Banker called our attention to a red-rock
ridge overlooking the village. There, silhouetted against the sky,
stood two pillars called the Wigleeva, said to be guardian spirits.
A legend says that the village will be destroyed if they fall.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Supai is like walking down a dusty country lane. Small
houses and their corrals are fenced off from the road. After an
eight-mile hike, the sight of a satellite dish in a yard challenges
one's preconceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The village seems to have one foot in the past and one in the
present. It is neither a museum piece nor a tourist trap. We had
been cautioned to take no pictures of people without permission.
Pack trains go back and forth, and the center near a store and
restaurant can seem busy. Visitors walk and ride in, and a small
helicopter brings people and some supplies.
</P>
<P>
   There is a basketball court and a Head Start headquarters, and
notices are posted for school board and other elections. Supai has
its own post office. Mail is delivered and sent out via four legs,
not four wheels. There are no cars in the village, just some
tractors and other small vehicles used on jobs.
</P>
<P>
   We camped two miles beyond Supai. The gear we had sent down was
waiting for us. A hiking companion, Richard Bass of Houston, had
won our gratitude by arranging for a load on one of the mules in a
supply train and offering us a share. The cost of $30 to send 30
pounds down, and up at the end of five days, was a bargain. Our
knees and back appreciated it.
</P>
<P>
   We set up camp within sight of each other, my wife and I tenting
near and sharing a picnic table with Ash and Boni Mukherjee of
Riverside, Calif., who had felt the pull of the Grand Canyon and
taken up backpacking just recently.
</P>
<P>
   Richard tented near Richard and Anne Gollnick of Green Bay, Wis.
Richard said he had first visited the Grand Canyon at the South Rim
visitors' center when he was a child. With his mother and brother,
he had ridden a horse down about 50 years ago and he returned in
recent years to hike in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The Gollnicks said they had come to Arizona to see the Chicago
Cubs at spring training a few years ago, took a side trip to the
Grand Canyon, and decided they had to walk down. That led to
further interest in hiking and to this trip.
</P>
<P>
   Greg and Doug Hoke, a fit father and 21-year-old son, were on an
outing together before Doug began his final year of college. They
found a flat spot and spread out a tarp, going without a tent. They
stayed warm enough but discovered mice and mosquitoes ruled the
campground at night. ``Lights out and the camp's theirs,'' one of
our companions said. ``Like it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce, who took a site about in the middle of all of us, is a
former Park Service ranger who now leads trips for the organization
that arranged this outing, the Grand Canyon Field Institute, and
for Elderhostel. This was his 11th backpack to Havasu Canyon in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   We dunked in the creek, ate, and made some plans. Bruce spoke
that night about hiking up to a ridge, but in the morning
suggested, instead, we might like to get a taste of the trail we
were going to be on for 12 hours Wednesday. So Tuesday we took
light packs and ambled off for Mooney Falls.
</P>
<P>
   The trail went to a point where we looked 200 feet down to where
the falls ended in a large, clear pool. We walked around on the
rock. Here was a chain railing and an entrance to a tunnel whose
floor dropped steeply. ``That's the trail?'' Yes.
</P>
<P>
   With varying degrees of anxiety, we entered. Helping each other,
we worked our way down, stepping into unlikely indentations,
holding dangling chains, grabbing steel rods driven into the rock.
</P>
<P>
   Where the holds were too far apart for those with shorter legs,
Bruce braced himself: ``Step on my knee.'' We did, using him as a
foothold.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1441EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0182 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2067 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-BABITSKY-0301-     02-29 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BABITSKY-0301-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MISSING RUSSIAN REPORTER ALIVE AND TALKING OF TORTURE
 &HT;    (700&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After more than one month in captivity, Russian
journalist Andrei Babitsky was returned Tuesday to his home in
Moscow, alive, well and talking about the torture he allegedly
endured while in the hands of Russian forces.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky re-surfaced last Friday in the Russian republic of
Dagestan, which adjoins Chechnya, after a mysterious set of events
in mid-January _ when Russian authorities admitted that they had
detained the investigative journalist, and then handed him over to
Chechen rebels in a prisoner-of-war exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In two separate interviews Tuesday, one with his own news
agency, U.S.-funded Radio Liberty, and one with the independent
Russian television station NTV, Babitsky, 35, looked weary and sick
as he spoke for the first time about his ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   In chilling detail, he told about the treatment of those
detained, himself included, by federal forces and held in the
notorious Chernokozovo filtration camp. The camp was set up by the
Russian army to weed out Chechen rebels from the civilian
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the hands of sadists who kept me in Chernokozovo
concentration camp. The word beating takes on a new meaning there.
It's torture,'' Babitsky said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a journalist, I was only subjected to a very light
'initiation' procedure which consists of crawling some distance
under the strikes of rubber batons. It's painful, but it is nothing
compared to tortures of those who are suspected of involvement with
the illegal armed formations (Chechen rebel groups),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Russian soldiers) would entertain themselves by making people
run on their knees along the corridor,'' he said, adding that he
heard women screaming in ``unbearable pain'' while he was there.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has come under fire in recent weeks for alleged war
crimes against civilians during the six-month war against Chechen
rebels _ including summary executions of women and children, and
torture and rape at ``filtration camps'' like Chernokozovo.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with Cox Newspapers, survivors from these camps,
who either had escaped or bribed their way out of captivity,
described sweeping arrests by Russian forces, followed by periods
of detention in which Chechens are beaten, tortured and raped.
</P>
<P>
   Chernokozovo, located about 30 miles east of the Russian
southern military headquarters in Mozdok, appears to be the largest
of the detention centers. From the outside, it appears more
desolate than evil, a dingy white concrete structure surrounded by
barbed-wire fences.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Russian authorities accompanied Western journalists
on a tour of the facility. Maj. Gen. Mikhail S. Nazarkin, the
director of Chernokozovo since Feb. 10, told reporters that he had
gone to great lengths to fix up the facility, but dismissed reports
of torture as ``stupidities and rubbish.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The Chernokozovo story is only part of Babitsky's experience.
His orchestrated handover on Feb. 3 from Russian authorities into
the custody of masked men has been a thorn in the side of Russian
acting President Vladimir Putin. Russia's Western allies and
journalists have decried the exchange as illegal; Russian
authorities said Babitsky agreed to it.
</P>
<P>
   Questions remain as to whether Babitsky was in the hands of
rebels, Russian security forces or pro-Moscow Chechens. Babitsky
revealed Tuesday he had no idea who held him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were Chechens, but they weren't field
commanders'' like the Russian government had contended, he said.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, the whole affair has taken on a surreal tinge,
with Kremlin spokesmen issuing statements that contradict others
made by the Russian military and Interior Ministry about the
details of Babitsky's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian government has always insisted the journalist was
alive, but would not allow his lawyer or wife access to what they
called top secret information confirming this fact.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the government opened a criminal case against
Babitsky, alleging that he was involved with the Chechen rebels.
That accusation of treason could carry a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Until Babitsky showed up in Dagestan Feb. 25, his colleagues
felt for certain he was dead. Speculation ran rampant that the
reason for his disappearance had to do with what he had seen in
Chernokozovo.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky said he was freed by the people who had held him since
the Russian prisoner exchange. They left him in the town of
Makhachkala, with an Azeri passport and none of his own identity
papers.
</P>
<P>
   He spent his first hours of freedom checking into the Hotel
Dagestan and then going to a cafe to eat. There, he was approached
by Interior Ministry troops and arrested for holding counterfeit
papers. He then spent the weekend in their custody.
</P>
<P>
   Putin himself had remained quiet about the whole affair until
Monday, when he made a public remark saying he doubted Babitsky was
dangerous enough to warrant being held in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Within 24 hours, Babitsky was put on a government plane and
flown to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   He still faces charges of treason and counterfeiting, and is
restricted from travelling outside of the Russian capital while the
investigation into those charges continue.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky said he's happy to be back home, but warned
congratulations were premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Investigators) believe the case against me should continue no
matter how insignificant the reasons for it are,'' Babitsky said.
``The different levels of power are in disagreement about what to
do with me. There is no planned approach. There is no agreement.
But they can destroy anyone who gets in their way. This is the way
our system works.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
