<HEADER>
A2071 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-29 0507
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASHING THE CORONATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A friend phoned the other day to complain about the
``coronation'' of George W. Bush as the Republican presidential
candidate. It's not that she's a McCain supporter; she just can't
stand the verb that always comes slouching along when TV and radio
commentators get onto this subject, the despised coronate. ``Why
not just say crown?'' she wondered.
</P>
<P>
   The same cloud of annoyance hovers over administrate, a verb
that usually means just what administer does, and shadows
orientate, preventative, and similar words with syllables they
don't really need. In the 1926 editon of Modern English Usage, H.W.
Fowler compiled a list of Long Variants, and these examples fall
into the category he labeled ``Needless lengthenings of established
words due to oversight or caprice.''
</P>
<P>
   His list offers some comfort to the tormented, though. Of the 13
words Fowler condemns, only administrate and preventative are still
bugging significant numbers of language watchers. We've chosen to
defy him on extemporaneously; Fowler and his fellow schoolteachers
preferred ex tempore, but we no longer throw Latin around with such
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   And most of his other worries proved groundless. Filtrate for
the verb filter, experimentalize for experiment, perfection for the
verb perfect _ nits of the early 20th century, apparently _ are
nowhere to be seen. So coronate, too, may be just a vogue word,
something today's reporters grab for in the hope that it sounds
less literal than crowned, but not a usage with legs.
</P>
<P>
   Another presidential-election pain is electoral, increasingly
pronounced with the accent on OR. It should be e-LEC-tor-al, not
e-lec-TOR-al (we're ignoring phonetics here, except for the
accents), just as mayoral should be pronounced MAY-or-al. In ``The
Big Book of Beastly Mispronunciations,'' Charles Harrington Elster
notes that e-lec-TOR-al gets a disapproving mention on its first
appearance _ in the 1961 Webster 3 unabridged dictionary, which
disapproved of very little _ and ``did not appear in another
dictionary for 25 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Coronate can claim a better pedigree than e-lec-TOR-al. It goes
back centuries, and it's not an ignorant coinage, according to the
Merriam-Webster usage czars, but a borrowing from the Latin past
participle form. But scions of even the best families can go
astray, and coronate is unwelcome to many educated ears, even if
it's now recognized by our dictionaries.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you like a good fight, and if you'd rather defend your
language than your candidate, go with the debatable usages. But if
you say crown instead of coronate, and accent electoral on the
second syllable, you won't have listeners wailing and gnashing
their teeth, and missing the substance, if any, of what you're
trying to say.
</P>
<P>
   (What's the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The
Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
