<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-BRANCACCIO-ART     02-29 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-BRANCACCIO-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 AUTHOR'S AID TO THE RICH: SPEND THAT POCKET CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NATHAN COBB  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's tell a small fib. Let's say I have 100,000 extra dollars.
This, of course, is preposterous, particularly for someone whose
retirement plan largely consists of buying Mass Millions tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind. We're living at a time when lots of people _ many of
them so young that they think the Watergate scandal had something
to do with fluoride _ are walking around with that kind of spare
change. They've sold their companies, or they've inherited from Mom
and Dad, or they've even won Mass Millions. They're semi-flush.
</P>
<P>
   So I ask you: what should I do with my $100,000? Actually, I'm
asking David Brancaccio. Brancaccio, the host and senior editor of
``Marketplace'' on public radio, is the author of the
recently-published book, ``Squandering Aimlessly: My Adventures in
the American Marketplace.'' The 39-year-old Maine native, who lives
in Los Angeles with his wife and three children, took 10 trips in
16 months and then turned his meanderings into a 283-page look at
10 possible ways of disposing of burdensome cash. He schmoozed with
investment gurus, hung in Vegas, and considered suburban real
estate. He hunkered down with would-be entrepreneurs and wandered
the Mall of America. He visited a future ``retirement campus.''
</P>
<P>
   So I sent e-mail to Brancaccio: ``Dear David,`` I wrote. ``I
have $100,000 looking for a home. No kidding. Meet me in Boston and
tell me what to do with it.'' (The only thing I was kidding about,
of course, was the ``no kidding'' part.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Love to,'' Brancaccio replied to my invitation. But he also
warned me about ``Automotive Indigence,'' which he explained refers
to a car's ability to sense an economic windfall and break down at
a cost equal to the amount of that windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't worry,'' I wrote back. ``The combined worth of my three
cars is $17,000. No chance of spending $100,000 on any of them.''
</P>
<P>
   We met for lunch at a Boston race track, an appropriate setting.
One of the options explored by Brancaccio in ``Squandering
Aimlessly'' is that of gambling (or ``gaming'' as they call it in
Las Vegas) with your windfall. Perhaps he would suggest that I put
my $100,000 on a horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handicapping is a bit like picking stocks,'' he said as we
settled into a table overlooking the track's clubhouse turn on a
rainy afternoon. ``A skilled handicapper can look at this stuff,
divine some meaning, and it becomes a game of positive
expectations. We can probably, if we're good enough, actually win
here.''
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't too sure about the we part. In his book, Brancaccio
recounts betting $5 on a horse at 16-to-1 odds and winning $41.50.
But he should have received $80 plus his $5 original wager. Is this
the kind of guy I want giving me financial advice? ``I must have
remembered the odds wrong,'' he confessed sheepishly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see,'' he said a few moments later, ``I can't tell you
what to do with your money, `cause I don't know you well enough.''
And indeed, ``Squandering Aimlessly'' makes it clear that what a
person should do with extra cash depends on who the person is.
Still, Brancaccio had a few ideas: put as much money as I'm legally
allowed in my 401(k) account, donate some cash to charity, and
spend some ``fun money'' on something frivolous. ``In other words,
do something that you don't have to explain to anybody, even your
wife'' he said, referring to the last suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   I took notes furiously. ``That still leaves me about $90,000,''
I announced. ``Maybe I should do something about my son's college
education. He's 13.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, my goodness,'' Brancaccio replied, looking straight into
my eyes. ``Thirteen? Oh, my goodness. You gotta grow this money.''
</P>
<P>
   So we tried to determine how much interest I had to earn to
``grow'' $90,000 into $120,000 _ our projection for the cost of a
college education _ over the next four years. Alas, Brancaccio
explained that he hadn't brought along the proper calculator to
come up with such a figure. ``I left it back in my hotel room,'' he
apologized. ``Call me later today.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, we considered a few options. We talked about buying real
estate and about taking a flyer on an Internet start-up company.
Brancaccio suggested possibly cutting back on my job and thereby
creating more time to spend with my son. ``It's nice to invest in
our children that way, particularly if we don't want to use our
extra money to bail them out of jail,'' he explained. ``There could
be an expensive downside to not doing that type of thing. There
could be lawyers' fees.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, it was time for the day's first race. Surveying the
sloppy track, I suggested a small wager on Stanley's Comet, a
4-year-old fillie who had won a race in a similar swamp three
months earlier. Leaving the starting gate at 7-to-1 odds, the horse
lumbered through a headwind to win by nearly three lengths. My $6
bet _ $2 to win, $2 to place, and $2 to show _ produced a profit of
$23.20. Brancaccio's $10 bet on Stanley's Comet to show put him $19
in the black.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be damned,'' Brancaccio declared. ``You should have put a
little bit more down, though. You analyzed the situation correctly,
but you have to have the power of your convictions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe so, but now I've got $93,023.10 to `grow','' I pointed
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if I'd advised you to put your entire $100,000 on that
horse to win?'' Brancaccio asked. ``How much would you have won?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Over $600,000,'' I replied, wondering why he hadn't.
(Actually, such a wager would have driven the odds on Stanley's
Comet so low that my profit would have been only $10,000.)
</P>
<P>
   We wisely left the track before the second race, our profits
safely in our pockets and the future of my alleged wad still
uncertain. When I called Brancaccio later at his hotel, he told me
he'd calculated that I needed to earn about 7 1/4 percent interest
over the next four years to ``grow'' my $93,023.10 into a college
education. ``And if you wait a couple of weeks,'' he said,
``30-year bonds will be paying just about 7 1/4 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Which sounded wise, but boring. Maybe I should have invested a
lot more money in Stanley's Comet. On the other hand, I remembered
what Brancaccio had told me about such a strategy as we were
leaving the track. ``You would have been stuck with the same
problem,'' he pointed out. `` `What do I do with my money?' See,
money itself is the problem. The more you have the more you have to
think about it.
</P>
<P>
   Money itself is the problem? What a relief. Thank goodness I
really don't have the 100,000 extra dollars that, as far as I know,
David Brancaccio still thinks I have.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
