<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2077 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-HAVASU-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     02-29 1606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HAVASU-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... a foothold.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunlight. Those who were first at the bottom greeted each of the
following hikers with cheers and applause. ``Good going.'' ``All
right!'' ``You did great.''
</P>
<P>
   Strangers yesterday, we had become friends today. I think we had
passed some kind of test our leader had in mind all along.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the falls, we went under a thick overhang of travertine
and saw branches that had fallen into the creek were coated with
the mineral and incorporated into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   A certain Daniel Mooney, for whom the falls was named, became
part of this natural process. The story told is that he descended
near the falls one day in 1880, only to discover his rope was too
short. It broke when his companions tried to pull him up, and he
fell to his death. The next year, his body was found beneath the
falls, allegedly covered with a layer of travertine, and he was
interred there.
</P>
<P>
   We went on a way toward Fern Canyon. As we approached huge
boulders at the entrance, we heard music, clear notes echoing off
the walls. Were we hallucinating, someone asked. When we climbed up
and squeezed through an opening in the rocks, we saw a young
couple, the man sunning himself and the woman playing an ocarina.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us climbed to the back of the box canyon. Looking back
we could see how it was shaped by and at the mercy of the
occasional heavy rains. An enormous, curving gash scoured in the
solid rock on one side indicated where water carrying sand, pebbles
and boulders from the heights above apparently shot down. Fern
Canyon would be a swirling, tumultuous place in a storm.
</P>
<P>
   We returned to the campground with half the day left and soaked
in the creek at the swimming hole we favored. We played in the
current, fighting our way upstream as far as we could and floating
back without effort.
</P>
<P>
   At nightfall the stars showed distinctly in the sky above the
narrow canyon. Bruce had once given stargazing talks to North Rim
visitors. We learned to spot the summer triangle, Deneb, Altaire,
and Vega.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, we got up early and hit the trail shortly after 6
a.m. We had 14 miles to go.
</P>
<P>
   Between our tent sites and the falls, we passed a spot where an
old cottonwood tree, rotted at the base, had crashed down the night
before, the trunk missing an occupied tent by about six inches.
</P>
<P>
   We climbed down the tunnel with a little more assurance, and
went off toward the Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond on a cliff face, we could see the metal framework for a
most unlikely ladder. Actually, a series of wooden ladders attached
to the metal had extended more than 250 feet to a ledge where
vanadium was once mined. The Park Service has removed the ladders
themselves. Looking up to the top and imagining the climb gives one
some appreciation for the single-mindedness of such miners and the
dangers they endured.
</P>
<P>
   The day was long and pleasant. There were a few sections where
the trail rose high and narrowed; there was a rope that helped us
get up a steep stretch. We saw or heard a summer tanager, Wilson's
warbler, and ladderback woodpecker.
</P>
<P>
   Creek crossings were unavoidable. We would stop and change from
boots to sandals and back again many times. It was somewhat
inconvenient to do this, but the water helped cool us off. The
current was strong and we had to pick our way carefully, sometimes
taking a hand or offering one to others.
</P>
<P>
   For several miles, we saw nobody else on the trail. The rough
contours of stream and rock were occasionally made to look smooth
by grapevine running wild and covering everything, and we could
imagine we were in waist-high fields of grass.
</P>
<P>
   At some point we crossed the boundary of Havasupai land into the
Grand Canyon National Park Park.
</P>
<P>
   Near Beaver Falls, we began to see people coming up from the
Colorado River, four miles away. The falls is a favorite
destination for those on rafting trips who want to exercise their
legs and swim in the pools.
</P>
<P>
   When we reached the Colorado River, it was running swift and
muddy. We could put a hand or foot in it, but it was too dangerous
to wade in.
</P>
<P>
   We returned the same way we had come, getting to the campground
in twilight and making a quick meal. Despite the long day, some
felt energized and stayed up later than usual, chatting. Finally,
we called it a day. As I lay in my sleeping bag, I looked through
the tent's netting at the Milky Way, as distinct as I had ever seen
it.
</P>
<P>
   After a few days, the campground of 200 sites started to seem
like home and we began to know some of our neighbors and their
eccentricities.
</P>
<P>
   There were the two young women who brought trimmed-down bamboo
poles with large garden-party torches attached to the top. They
would use them as walking sticks during the day, and set them in
the ground at night and illuminate their campsite with them. They
were delighted to hear that they had become known throughout the
campground as the ``Tiki Torch Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were ``The Cowboys,'' led by David ``Pop''
Bartholomew. Lean, gray-bearded, and wearing a well-used cowboy
hat, Pop looked like an old cowpuncher, but he was just a guy on
vacation from La Habra, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   He had been visiting the canyon with his sons, daughters, and
friends every year since 1959 or '60.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take this same site every year, right by the wall,'' Pop
said.
</P>
<P>
   He had first read about the canyon in ``Arizona Highways,'' a
monthly magazine unsurpassed for its stories and pictures of the
state. So, shortly after leaving the Marines, he said, ``me and a
friend I got discharged with, we said why not come on down.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys ran a busy and friendly camp. They rode horses down
to the campground and had their gear delivered. By neighborhood
standards, the camp was luxurious, with large tents, a two-burner
campstove, food like ham and bacon, and even a CD player. A visitor
could get a cup of coffee and even a meal there.
</P>
<P>
   All in the group seem to be thoroughly enjoying themselves,
spending their days hiking some trails, swimming behind 100-foot
Havasu Falls, fishing and playing cards.
</P>
<P>
   The day before we hiked out, we went to the village to hear
traditionalist Dianna Sue Uqualla.
</P>
<P>
   In the yard outside the tourist office, Dianna Sue sprinkled a
mixture of sage and tobacco around herself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The circle is sacred to the Indian,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dianna Sue wore a representation of traditional Havasupai
clothing _ a long dress, moccasins and a shawl that could keep a
woman warm, or carry a baby or a load of firewood.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of Havasupai now live year round in the village. In the
past the tribe summered in the canyon bottoms and went to plateau
lands in winter. Much of their land was taken from them in the 19th
and 20th centuries. A 1975 law restored thousands of acres above
and below.
</P>
<P>
   Dianna Sue says children still learn the tribe's language first,
and then English. She said most continue to make the village their
home when they grow up.
</P>
<P>
   It is a small and, apparently, tight group. ``We are one heart,
one mind,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A gentle woman with a soft voice and, yet, commanding presence,
Dianna Sue said she sees it as her special ``destiny'' to encourage
the perpetuation of the Havasupai traditional ceremonies and
culture and to explain aspects of them to those who are interested.
She had always been shy, she said, and was surprised the day when
she first was asked to speak to a group visiting the village. She
said she agreed and then wandered off wondering what she had done,
what she would say. She would get so nervous when she first began
these presentations, she said, that often she would cry.
</P>
<P>
   She was immersed in the everyday life of the village of the
present as she spoke about the enduring values of the past. A
little boy walked between her and her small audience, got his
bicycle, and rode off. A woman on one of the village work vehicles
went by on a nearby path, calling out a greeting. ``I taught her
how to drive that,'' Dianna Sue said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Later that day I relaxed at the picnic table next to our tent
while others took a short hike. Writing in a journal and sipping
tea out of the scratched plastic cup that has been part of my
camping gear for more than 20 years, I could not have felt more at
peace, the rough edges of everyday life smoothed down through days
of physical exertion and the wonder of new experiences. Pop
Bartholomew walked over and said there was one thing he must say:
that he felt there is something special, maybe magical, about the
place and it is his hope that his family keep up the 40-year
tradition of camping there, introducing it to his grandchildren and
beyond. He'd even like it to be his final resting place, if
possible, as it is Mooney's.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a legend that everyone who comes done here returns,''
he said. ``It must be true. Everyone I've ever taken down here has
come back one time or another.''
</P>
<P>
   On the last day we broke camp quickly and had breakfast at the
village cafe. It was Friday. The village looked busier. Thousands
visit the village and campground during the year, and it appeared
weekends were a popular time. It was our time to go. We shouldered
the packs carrying our essentials _ water, snacks, and whatever
camp gear and extra clothing we did not send up on our share of a
mule.
</P>
<P>
   Near the top, two Indian women descended with effortless
strides. They wore no hats, carried no water. One had a small
plastic bag, making her look as if she had just stepped out of a
department store with a purchase, as they walked the eight miles
down to the home of the Havasupai.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
