<HEADLINE>
LABOR CONTRACTS NOT TO BLAME FOR BIG DIG WOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If you believe some general contractors, a major reason why
there is a $1.4 billion cost overrun on the Big Dig is the
existence of the state's Project Labor Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   By eliminating what its critics call the ``union-only'' project
labor agreement, which they say adds 5 to 10 percent to the cost of
a construction job, Big Dig savings could be 10 percent, or $1.42
billion, almost equal to the $10.8 billion project's cost overrun.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with this argument against PLAs is that they are
based on distortions and omissions of facts.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-PLA contractors tried these arguments in the courts and
lost. The Massachusetts Supreme Judicial Court, for example, upheld
the PLA involving the construction of Malden public schools. They
tried to have it eliminated in the Legislature, but lost.
</P>
<P>
   Malden Mayor Richard Howard praised the court's decision to
uphold the PLA, saying in the Malden News that the quality of the
school projects and the fact that they were finished on time is
testament to the agreement's significance.
</P>
<P>
   A survey showed the courts have found PLAs lawful in at least 28
cases and found legal problems with PLAs in only six cases. These
legal problems, based on challenges raised on bidding, antitrust
and labor laws, have been addressed and ``found to be without
merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Now anti-PLA contractors are hoping to have PLAs eliminated in
the court of public opinion using the Big Dig cost overruns as
ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   One argument employed by an anti-PLA group, the Merit
Construction Alliance, an association of nonunion contractors, is
that construction projects with PLAs are open only to contractors
which employ only union workers. That's simply not so.
</P>
<P>
   Under PLAs, which are jointly negotiated between labor and
management, workers give up their right to strike, and contractors
pledge not to lock out workers. In addition, nonunion contractors,
after a period of time working under a PLA, must pay their workers
the same wages and benefits paid to union workers, and provide them
with the same protections union workers enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   Some nonunion contractors have said PLAs actually keep them from
bidding on projects. But that was disproven when Douglas MacDonald,
executive director of the Massachusetts Water Resources Authority,
reported that of 257 subcontractors on the Boston Harbor Cleanup
Project, 102 have been nonunion. In fact, the MWRA praised the PLA
on the project for reducing costs from $6.1 billion to $3.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   What some nonunion contractors such as Merit are not saying is
that they don't want to pay workers the same wages, benefits, and
protections of union workers as required under PLAs.
</P>
<P>
   Even without PLAs, all contractors, union and nonunion, must pay
prevailing wages, which are based on collective bargaining
agreements in the geographical areas of that project, on all public
and private projects.
</P>
<P>
   Many nonunion contractors tried unsuccessfully to repeal the
state's prevailing wage law, which has been in existence for more
than 80 years. And now they are trying to eliminate the PLAs, which
have been in existence in this state and throughout the nation for
more than 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   What PLA critics are not saying is that the only reason they
want it eliminated is because they don't want to pay the wages or
benefits, or provide the protections to nonunion workers who would
come under these agreements.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, PLAs are not why the Big Dig has a $1.4 billion cost
overrun. Federal auditors examining the project will soon find the
real reasons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
