<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEETBOSTON HAMPERED BY PROBLEMS OF PEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FleetBoston Financial Corp. must feel like a guy who owns a nice
home in a bad neighborhood: No matter how much he fixes it up, he
can't get anyone to buy it for what it is really worth.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet lives in a bad neighborhood called bank stocks. Bank
stocks have been crushed in recent months. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
index of regional banks has dropped 35 percent since its 1999 high.
</P>
<P>
   The banks are suffering from multiple ills: rising interest
rates, the perception that they are old-economy companies, and the
well-publicized troubles of a few big banks. The problem banks _
Bank One, First Union, Bank of America _ all made major
acquisitions in the past two years and later announced
disappointing earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet made a big acquisition last year when it bought
BankBoston. Fleet hasn't announced disappointing earnings. In fact,
the bank has had nothing but good news to report. Unfortunately,
investors seem to be practicing a form of guilt by association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is waiting to see if another shoe drops here,''
complained Eugene McQuade, Fleet's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts don't expect that to happen. Most are bullish on
Fleet's prospects. They say that when interest rates top out,
possibly later this year, Fleet stock will be well worth owning.
``Once we see a turn in this sector, Fleet should be one of the
better performers,'' said Lisa Welch, a bank analyst with John
Hancock Funds.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet stock has a lot of lost ground to make up. The stock has
shed 38 percent of its value in the last four months. With a gain
Monday, it is back to 27, just where it was three years ago. Over
the same time frame, the Nasdaq index has climbed 250 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's actual performance has been surprisingly good. Earnings
climbed 14 percent last year and are expected to rise another 11
percent this year. Gerard Cassidy, a bank analyst with Tucker
Anthony, says Fleet has the best chance of any major bank in the
country of beating its earnings estimates for the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Why the enthusiasm? Much of it is based on the growing strength
of Fleet businesses that lie outside the conventional banking
realm.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson Stephens, the investment bank acquired by BankBoston,
claims to have been the lead manager on more Internet deals than
any of its competitors last year. Robertson Stephens revenues
doubled last year to $950 million and the bank recently announced
its best January ever.
</P>
<P>
   Quick &AMP; Reilly, the discount brokerage, saw its earnings climb
40 percent in 1999. Fleet's private equity business had a huge 1999
and currently is sitting on at least $1.5 billion in unrealized
gains, much of that in Internet companies. ``My sense is the gain
ultimately will turn out to be a multiple of that number ($1.5
billion),'' said McQuade.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the BankBoston deal, Wall Street was worried
about the South American operations BankBoston brought along. The
Brazilian economy was in a funk and the fear was bank earnings
would turn funky as well. It never happened. International earnings
rose to $330 million in 1999, up from $240 million the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's basic banking business is more pedestrian, but even
there, McQuade expects double-digit gains this year.
</P>
<P>
   What could cloud Fleet's sunny outlook? An economic slowdown,
for one thing. Fleet can make money even if interest rates rise,
say analysts, but a weaker economy would curtail new business and
possibly expose credit problems.
</P>
<P>
   A severe market correction would hurt too, especially if the
technology stocks that support Robertson Stephens and Quick &AMP;
Reilly took a nosedive.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a collapse of Fleet's deal to sell 278 branches to
Sovereign Bancorp also would do some damage. Fleet has been
promising that the transaction is on the verge of approval, but
investors want to see the sale consummated soon. ``The uncertainty
is driving the market crazy,'' said Steven Wharton, an analyst with
Loomis Sayles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nearly all of those who follow Fleet are upbeat about the
stock's long-term fortunes. They believe the market has punished
Fleet unfairly for sins committed by others. They don't expect the
stock to move much before Alan Greenspan is finished hiking rates,
but most think it is not too early to buy on the anticipation of
better times ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stock isn't going to double or triple,'' said Kevin
Timmons, an analyst with First Albany. But Timmons thinks the stock
will rise and that it represents good value.
</P>
<P>
   For an old-economy company, that is probably the most you can
hope for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
