<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 15:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2143 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-BAKE-OFF-MAIN-LADN &LR;      02-29 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKE-OFF-MAIN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WANTS TO BE A BAKE-OFF MILLIONAIRE?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So who is this year's Bake-Off millionaire? Roberta (Bobbie)
Sonefeld of Hopkins, S.C., captured the $1 million grand prize
Tuesday morning at the 39th Pillsbury Bake-Off 50th anniversary
contest in San Franciso with her Cream Cheese Brownie Pie. The
recipe, which Sonefeld created just for the contest, was the Fast
and Fabulous Desserts and Treats category winner.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Sonefeld and 98 other finalists (one finalist was
unable to compete at the last minute due to a medical emergency)
from 36 states and ranging in age from 11 to 82 years old cooked
their dishes for the judges in mini-kitchens in a ballroom at the
Marriott hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The judges described Sonefeld's recipe as a combination of
indulgence and convenience. The layered creation, which takes just
15 minutes to prepare, uses a brownie mix and a refrigerated pie
crust and is filled with a cream cheese mixture. Cream cheese is a
key ingredient in the recipe's success, noted the winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most brownie pies I make are dry, but the cream cheese helps
to keep it creamy. It's easy, inexpensive and my two sons love
it,'' said Sonefeld, a passionate baker, who is an administrative
assistant for a commercial mortgage banking company. Her dream is
to someday open a bakery or pie shop with her sister.
</P>
<P>
   Three other category winners each earned $10,000. Judith Mettlin
of Synder, N.Y., prepared the winning Island Paradise Salad in the
Yummy Vegetables category. Lorraine Maggio of Manlius, N.Y., baked
the winning Easy Weeknight Meals dish, Ham and Swiss Crescent
Braid. In the Casual Snacks and Appetizers category, Judy Wood of
Vestavia Hills, Ala., won with Pesto Crescent Twists With Feta
Spread.
</P>
<P>
   Three finalists in each of the four categories won $2,000 _
including Southern Californian Heather Wight (see accompanying
story).
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the GE Innovation Award (and a GE Profile
Performance Kitchen (valued at $5,000) was Pat Parsons of
Bakersfield for her recipe, Guess Again Candy Crunch, selected as
most innovative by the judges.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes were judged on taste, appearance, consumer appeal,
creativity and appropriate use of eligible products. The final
selection was a combination of two components: scoring from the
judges who tasted the dishes on Monday, and consumer research
results conducted prior to Monday that asked consumers to score the
dishes (by looking at recipes and photos) on appeal and the
likelihood of their making the dish.
</P>
<P>
   A book containing the 100 finalists' recipes (each with a color
photo) should be available soon at supermarkets and newsstands for
$3.50. To order by mail, send $3.99 (includes postage and handling)
per copy to: Pillsbury Publications, Department 8077, P.O. Box
2063, Harlan, Iowa 51539.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that the prize-winning recipes that follow won
using Pillsbury products, and substituting other brands might not
produce the same results. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CREAM CHEESE BROWNIE PIE &QL; 
($1 million Winner, &QL; 
Roberta Sonefeld, Hopkins, S.C.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 refrigerated pie crust (from a 15-ounce package), softened as
directed on package &QL; 
1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese, softened &QL; 
3 tablespoons sugar &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
3 eggs &QL; 
1 (15.1-ounce) package thick 'n fudgy hot fudge swirl deluxe
brownie mix &QL; 
1/4 cup vegetable oil &QL; 
2 tablespoons water &QL; 
1/2 cup chopped pecans
</P>
<P>
   Prepare pie crust as directed on package for one crust filled
pie using a 9-inch pie pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine cream cheese, sugar, vanilla and 1
egg; beat until smooth. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve hot fudge packet from brownie mix for topping. In a
large bowl, combine brownie mix, oil, 1 tablespoon water and
remaining 2 eggs; beat 50 strokes with a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Spread 1/2 cup brownie mixture in bottom of crust-filled pan.
Spoon and carefully spread cream cheese mixture over brownie layer.
Top with remaining brownie mixture; spread evenly. Sprinkle with
pecans.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 40 to 50 minutes or until
center is puffed and crust is golden. If necessary, cover edge of
crust with strips of foil after 15 or 20 minutes of baking to
prevent excessive browning. (Pie may have cracks on surface.)
</P>
<P>
   Place hot fudge from packet in a small microwave-safe bowl.
Microwave on high power 30 seconds. Stir in remaining 1 tablespoon
water. Drizzle fudge over top of pie. Cool 3 hours or until
completely cooled. Store in refrigerator. Makes 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 600 calories; 36 grams fat; 8
grams protein; 60 grams carbohydrates; 370 milligrams sodium; 115
milligrams cholesterol. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HAM AND SWISS CRESCENT BRAID &QL; 
($10,000 Easy Weeknight Meals Winner, &QL; 
Lorraine Maggio, Manlius, N.Y.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
3/4 pound cooked ham, chopped (2 1/4 cups) &QL; 
1 cup frozen broccoli florets, thawed (see Note) &QL; 
1 cup shredded Swiss cheese (4 ounces) &QL; 
1 (4.5-ounce) jar sliced mushrooms, drained &QL; 
1/2 cup mayonnaise OR salad dressing &QL; 
1 tablespoon honey mustard &QL; 
2 (8-ounce) cans refrigerated reduced-fat OR regular crescent
dinner rolls &QL; 
1 egg white, beaten &QL; 
2 tablespoons slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   Use an ungreased large rectangular baking stone or spray a
cookie sheet with nonstick cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine ham, broccoli, cheese, mushrooms,
mayonnaise and mustard; mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Unroll both cans of dough. Place dough with long sides together
on ungreased baking stone, forming a 15x12-inch rectangle. Press
edges and perforations to seal.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon and spread ham mixture in a 6-inch strip lengthwise down
center of dough. With scissors or sharp knife, make cuts 1 1/2
inches apart along long sides of dough to within 1/2-inch of
filling. Twisting each strip once, alternately cross strips over
filling. Tuck short ends under; press to seal. Brush dough with
beaten egg white; sprinkle with almonds.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 28 to 33 minutes or until deep
golden brown. Cool 5 minutes. Cut into crosswise slices. Makes 8
servings.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: To quickly thaw broccoli, place in a colander or strainer;
rinse with warm water until thawed. Drain well. &QL; 
NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 430 calories; 27 grams fat; 18
grams protein; 28 grams carbohydrates; 1,270 milligrams sodium; 40
milligrams cholesterol. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ISLAND PARADISE SALAD &QL; 
($10,000 Yummy Vegetables Winner, &QL; 
Judith Mettlin, Snyder, N.Y.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DRESSING: &QL; 
1 teaspoon grated lime peel &QL; 
3 tablespoons honey &QL; 
2 tablespoons fresh lime juice &QL; 
1 tablespoon canola OR vegetable oil &QL; 
SALAD: &QL; 
2 cups frozen sugar snap peas &QL; 
3 cups torn romaine lettuce &QL; 
3 cups torn Bibb lettuce &QL; 
1 avocado, peeled, pitted and cut into 1/2-inch cubes &QL; 
1 large ripe mango, peeled, seed removed and cut into 1/2-inch
cubes &QL; 
1 small red onion, thinly sliced and separated into rings &QL; 
1/2 cup unsweetened OR regular shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   For Dressing, in a small bowl, combine all dressing ingredients;
mix well.
</P>
<P>
   For Salad, cook sugar snap peas as directed on package. Drain.
Rinse with cold water to cool. Drain well.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine cooked sugar snap peas and all
remaining salad ingredients except coconut. Add dressing; toss to
coat. Sprinkle with coconut. Makes 8 (1 1/4-cup) servings.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 170 calories; 9 grams fat; 2
grams protein; 19 grams carbohydrates; 10 milligrams sodium; 0
milligrams cholesterol.!end! &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
PESTO CRESCENT TWISTS WITH FETA SPREAD
</P>
<P>
   ($10,000 Casual Snacks and Appetizers Winner, &QL; 
Julia Wood, Vestavia Hills) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TWISTS: &QL; 
2 (8-ounce) cans refrigerated crescent dinner rolls &QL; 
1/2 cup purchased pesto &QL; 
2 tablespoons finely chopped walnuts &QL; 
SPREAD: &QL; 
1/4 cup dairy sour cream &QL; 
1 cup crumbled feta cheese (4 ounces) &QL; 
1 (3-ounce) package cream cheese, softened &QL; 
2 teaspoons olive &QL; 
1 teaspoon purchased pesto
</P>
<P>
   Grease cookie sheets. For Twists, unroll 1 can dough onto a
cutting board or sheet of wax paper. Firmly press perforations to
seal. Press or roll to form a 13x7-inch rectangle. In a small bowl,
combine 1/2 cup pesto and walnuts; mix well. Spread mixture over
dough.
</P>
<P>
   Unroll remaining 1 can dough. Firmly press perforations to seal.
Press or roll to form 13x7-inch rectangle. Carefully place dough
rectangle over pesto and walnut filling. Cut filled dough in half
crosswise to make 2 (7x6 1/2-inch) pieces. Cut each half into 8
strips. Twist each strip tightly; place on greased cookie sheets.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 14 to 19 minutes or until
golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, make Spread. In a medium bowl, combine sour cream,
feta cheese and cream cheese; mix well until blended. Place in a
small serving bowl. In another small bowl, combine oil and 1
teaspoon pesto. Drizzle over cheese mixture. With tip of a knife,
stir to marble.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm twists with spread. Store any remaining spread in
refrigerator. Makes 16 appetizers.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER APPETIZER: 200 calories; 15 grams fat;
4 grams protein; 12 grams carbohydrates; 370 milligrams sodium; 15
milligrams cholesterol. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
