<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 15:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2146 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r d BC-BAKE-OFF-SOCAL-LADN &LR;      02-29 2053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAKE-OFF-SOCAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHLAND PILLSBURY BAKE-OFF FINALISTS COMPETE FOR THE DOUGH
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NATALIE HAUGHTON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four cooks from the greater Los Angeles area were among the 99
finalists competing Monday in the 39th Pillsbury Bake-Off in San
Francisco. And Heather Wight of West Hollywood walked away with
$2,000 with her Banana-Nut Cupcakes With Maple Frosting. Wight,
along with Candy Barnhart of Hollywood, Elizabeth Castle of Sunland
and Mary Capone of Long Beach, were all first-time finalists in the
Pillsbury contest.
</P>
<P>
   Wight, 21, moved to California eight months ago from Bethlehem,
Pa., and entered this, her first recipe contest, on a dare from a
co-worker who knew she liked to cook. She submitted five specially
developed recipes including Banana-Nut Cupcakes. Based on the
banana birthday cake she baked for her grandfather's 90th birthday
a year and a half ago, she turned the idea into cupcakes using a
Pillsbury banana quick bread mix and the same frosting as on the
cake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pleasant surprise to be selected as a finalist,''
said Wight, who sent her entries via the Internet on the last day
of the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Wight, who currently works as an administrative assistant for a
catering company in Beverlywood, grew up cooking in an Italian
household with lots of good food prepared by her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cooking is fun for me _ and a hobby. I have a natural instinct
for cooking everything and adapt to whatever occasion I'm cooking
for. Presentation is always important to me.'' Wight's dream is to
go to culinary school and pursue a career in this area.
</P>
<P>
   For Barnhart, 53, a homemaker, homeowner association archivist
and volunteer librarian, being selected as a finalist was the
ultimate honor for the amateur cook, who considers herself
creative. ``I felt like I was being nominated for an Academy
Award.'' Barnhart _ who dabbles in cooking and has entered several
recipe contests including the Bake-Off numerous times over the last
30 years _ submitted five favorite creations with the quick and
easy contest theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was inspired to enter this year because it was the 50th
anniversary of the Bake-Off and a new millennium; the time was
right. I didn't create these recipes just for the contest. I'm not
an armchair tester (referring to those who enter recipes in
contests without kitchen testing them).''
</P>
<P>
   Three were pulled from a little envelope of prized recipes she
has collected for years and kept in a kitchen drawer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very particular _ and only have 25 special recipes in that
envelope.'' The Grands Roast Beef Sandwiches with mustard sauce is
one of them that she has been serving for lunch or dinner to her
family for the past four years. She uses roast beef from the deli _
and Grands biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost didn't enter the recipe because it is too basic _ and
I lean more toward desserts and baked items.''
</P>
<P>
   Castle couldn't believe it when she was notified in November
that her recipe Slow-Cooked Taco Casserole was selected as a
Bake-Off finalist. She was so excited she dropped the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel very special that I was picked. It's been the high
point of my life so far,'' said the 26-year old single mother of
three, who has won numerous ribbons and prizes in cooking contests
since the age of 15.
</P>
<P>
   Winning recipe contests runs in the family. Her mother, Marina
Castle, was a finalist in 1990 and Elizabeth accompanied her to the
Bake-Off in Phoenix that year. So this year Marina accompanied her
daughter to San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth, a first time Bake-Off entrant, submitted 30 recipes,
20 of which she developed and tested especially for the contest.
``The recipe Pillsbury picked was my least favorite. It tastes
good, but I didn't think it had a good chance. But I love it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the recipe came when Castle wanted to make tacos
but didn't have enough clean dishes. Instead she tossed all of the
ingredients into a slow cooker and walked away. It's delicious
comfort food, great for an easy weeknight meal and kids like it.
</P>
<P>
   Castle, who considers herself an above-average cook, enjoys
experimenting. ``I like to cook big meals and main dishes _
including Thanksgiving dinner, pot roasts, and Mexican and Chinese
creations.''
</P>
<P>
   An avid cook for more than 40 years, the 51-year-old Capone was
so set on becoming a finalist that she sent in 36 recipes. ``It was
the $1 million grand prize that prompted me to enter my first
recipe contest ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Capone's collection entered were ethnic-style dishes such
as Mexican Two-Corn Stew and Thai Chicken Pizza, and desserts, such
as Apricot Almond Crescents and Grape Expectations. ``I had fun
creating them.''
</P>
<P>
   But the recipe that actually snagged her a spot as a finalist
was deceptively simple _ really a glorified fish stick. Halibut
With Corn and Lime-Cilantro Butter takes just 20 minutes to
prepare, involves a minimum of chopping and uses only one pan.
</P>
<P>
   The idea behind the recipe, said Capone, who grew up in Maryland
and began cooking at the age of 10, was to make fish more palatable
to non-fish eaters. The corn dressing and the breading were
designed to disguise the fish. ``I was pleased that Pillsbury
picked the fish recipe, which was among my top four favorites
submitted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been pretty exciting to be a finalist _ everybody has
been so proud of me. The Bake-Off is a slice of Americana that
brings warm, nice feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   So what encouragement and tips would these finalists share with
future recipe contest entrants? ``Don't give up; I speak from
experience,'' said Barnhart. ``Pay attention to the contest
rules,'' recommended Wight. ``Enter a recipe that is easy and
tastes good,'' said Castle. ``Try to come up with something that is
relatively simple, but is different from day-to-day dishes and
stands out,'' advised Capone. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SLOW-COOKED TACO CASSEROLE &QL; 
(Elizabeth Castle, Sunland) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds ground beef sirloin &QL; 
1 small onion, chopped &QL; 
1 garlic clove, minced &QL; 
1 (1.25-ounce) package taco seasoning mix &QL; 
1 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon pepper &QL; 
9 (5 1/2-inch) corn tortillas &QL; 
1/2 cup chicken broth &QL; 
1/2 cup tomato sauce &QL; 
1 (10-ounce) can enchilada sauce &QL; 
1 1/2 cups finely shredded Cheddar cheese &QL; 
2 (15-ounce) cans pinto, black OR kidney beans, drained and rinsed &QL; 
1 (11-ounce) can whole kernel corn with red and green peppers,
drained &QL; 
1 (4.5-ounce) can chopped green chiles &QL; 
1 (2 1/4-ounce) can chopped ripe olives &QL; 
Dairy sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Brush inside of a 3 1/2- or 4-quart slow cooker with oil, or
spray with nonstick cooking spray.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, brown ground beef sirloin with onion and
garlic over medium-high heat 8 to 10 minutes, or until thoroughly
cooked, stirring frequently. Drain. Stir in taco seasoning mix,
salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Place 3 tortillas in bottom of oiled slow cooker. Top with beef
mixture, broth, tomato sauce and enchilada sauce. Sprinkle with 1/2
cup cheese. Layer 3 more tortillas. Top with beans, corn, green
chiles, 1/2 of olives and 1/2 cup cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Top with remaining 3 tortillas. Sprinkle with remaining 1/2 cup
cheese and olives. Cook on high setting 2 1/2 to 3 hours, or on low
setting 6 to 7 hours. Uncover slow cooker last 30 minutes of
cooking time.
</P>
<P>
   Top individual servings with sour cream. Makes 8 (1 1/4-cup)
servings.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 420 calories; 23 grams
protein; 45 grams carbohydrates; 16 grams fat; 1,500 milligrams
sodium; 60 milligrams cholesterol. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
GRANDS! ROAST BEEF SANDWICHES &QL; 
(Candace Barnhart, Hollywood) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
SANDWICHES: &QL; 
1 (1-pound, 0.3-ounce) can extra-large refrigerated buttermilk
biscuits (Grands!) &QL; 
2 tablespoons margarine OR butter, melted &QL; 
1/4 cup garlic herb bread crumbs &QL; 
1/3 cup mayonnaise OR salad dressing &QL; 
1 (4.5-ounce) can chopped green chiles &QL; 
8 (1-ounce) slices cooked roast beef (from deli) &QL; 
1 cup finely shredded Monterey Jack cheese &QL; 
SAUCE (optional): &QL; 
1/2 cup mayonnaise OR salad dressing &QL; 
1/4 cup Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   For Sandwiches, separate dough into 8 biscuits. Brush top and
sides of EACH biscuit with margarine; coat with bread crumbs. Place
2 inches apart, crumb side up, on an ungreased baking sheet.
Sprinkle any remaining bread crumbs over biscuits.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 375-degree oven 14 to 16 minutes, or until
golden brown. Remove from oven; cool 5 minutes. Set oven to broil.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a small bowl, combine 1/3 cup mayonnaise and green
chiles; mix well. Split biscuits; place tops and bottoms, cut side
up, on same baking sheet. Spread mayonnaise mixture evenly on top
halves of biscuits. Arrange roast beef slices on bottom halves,
folding to fit. Top with cheese.
</P>
<P>
   In preheated broiler, broil 4 to 6 inches from heat source 2 to
3 minutes, or until cheese is melted and mayonnaise mixture is
bubbly. Place top halves of biscuits over bottom halves.
</P>
<P>
   For Sauce, in a small bowl, combine 1/2 cup mayonnaise and
mustard; blend well. Serve with sandwiches. Makes 8 sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SANDWICH: 500 calories; 15 grams
protein; 28 grams carbohydrates; 36 grams fat; 1,440 milligrams
sodium; 40 milligrams cholesterol. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
BANANA-NUT CUPCAKES WITH MAPLE FROSTING &QL; 
(Heather Wight, West Hollywood) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CUPCAKES: &QL; 
1 (14-ounce) package banana quick bread and muffin mix &QL; 
1 cup buttermilk (see Note) &QL; 
1/4 cup vegetable oil &QL; 
3 tablespoons real maple syrup OR microwave-ready regular syrup &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
2 eggs &QL; 
1/2 cup finely chopped walnuts &QL; 
FROSTING: &QL; 
4 ounces cream cheese, softened &QL; 
2 tablespoons butter OR margarine, softened &QL; 
3 tablespoons real maple syrup OR microwave-ready regular syrup &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon imitation maple flavor &QL; 
2 cups powdered sugar &QL; 
1/4 cup finely chopped walnuts
</P>
<P>
   For Cupcakes, line 16 muffin cups with foil or paper baking
cups.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine all cupcake ingredients except walnuts;
stir 50 to 75 strokes with a spoon until mix is moistened. Stir in
1/2 cup walnuts. Spoon batter evenly into lined muffin cups.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 400-degree oven 16 to 20 minutes or until a
toothpick inserted in center comes out clean. Cool 5 minutes.
Remove from pan. Cool 30 minutes or until completely cooled.
</P>
<P>
   For Frosting, in a small bowl, combine all frosting ingredients
except powdered sugar and walnuts; beat at low speed until smooth.
Gradually add powdered sugar, beating until mixture is of spreading
consistency. Use to frost cooled cupcakes. Immediately sprinkle
with 1/4 cup walnuts. Store in refrigerator. Makes 16 cupcakes.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: To substitute for buttermilk, use 1 tablespoon vinegar OR
lemon juice plus enough milk to make 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER CUPCAKE: 290 calories; 4 grams
protein; 42 grams carbohydrates; 12 grams fat; 200 milligrams
sodium; 25 milligrams cholesterol. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HALIBUT WITH CORN AND LIME-CILANTRO BUTTER &QL; 
(Mary Capone, Long Beach) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
1 tablespoon milk &QL; 
1 egg &QL; 
1/4 cup all-purpose flour OR unbleached flour &QL; 
1/2 cup garlic herb bread crumbs &QL; 
4 (6-ounce) halibut fillets (OR any firm white fish) &QL; 
4 tablespoons butter OR margarine &QL; 
2 tablespoons olive oil &QL; 
1 garlic clove, minced &QL; 
1 1/2 tablespoons fresh lime juice &QL; 
1/4 cup chopped fresh cilantro &QL; 
1 (11-ounce) can white shoepeg corn, drained
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, combine milk and egg; beat well. Place flour
and bread crumbs in separate shallow bowls. Coat fish with flour;
dip in egg mixture. Coat with bread crumbs.
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, combine 2 tablespoons butter, olive oil and
garlic. Heat over medium heat until hot. Add halibut; cook 10 to 12
minutes, or until golden brown and fish flakes easily with a fork,
turning once. Remove fish from skillet; cover to keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Add remaining 2 tablespoons butter, lime juice and cilantro to
same skillet; stir to scrape up any brown bits from bottom. Add
corn; cook 2 to 4 minutes or until thoroughly heated.
</P>
<P>
   Serve corn mixture over halibut. Makes 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: For Chicken With Corn and Lime-Cilantro Butter, substitute
4 boneless skinless chicken breast halves for fish. Cook chicken 12
to 14 minutes, or until fork-tender and juices run clear.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 520 calories; 42 grams
protein; 32 grams carbohydrates; 25 grams fat; 720 milligrams
sodium; 140 milligrams cholesterol. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
