<P>
   RESTAURANT-MONITOR (New York) _ While you savor your tuna
tartare in an elegant dining room, your companion may not be the
only one to notice you are ignoring the sesame toasts the chef made
to accompany it. The chef may be fretting about it, too. While he
observes you from video screens in the kitchen. As you blithely eat
your meal, he may be watching for just when you put your fork down,
so he can get your next course rolling. Even in restaurants that
have not invested in video technology, your name, phone number,
address and even where you work may be stored away on a computer
hard drive without your knowledge. Computers have been in
restaurants for years but until recently they were used only for
conveying orders from the dining room to the kitchen. Now they can
track how much wine you drink, how often you order the foie gras,
how much you tip and how many times you didn't show up for a
reservation. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT1.
</P>
