<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2170 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-PERSON-REVIEW-LADN     02-29 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERSON-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILMMAKER MORRIS SPEAKS IN THE `FIRST PERSON' FOR BRAVO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Filmmaker Errol Morris has a neat little knack for rooting out
utterly bizarre subject matter and fascinatingly quirky individuals
to populate his documentaries. Tonight, on his new Bravo TV series
``First Person,'' he makes it a weekly, rather than semi-annual,
habit.
</P>
<P>
   Morris is famous for getting his interviewees to expose more of
themselves than they may have bargained for, largely through
keeping silent when they've finished their thought. If they resume
jabbering at that point, watch out _ they may reveal something they
shouldn't have. Using this method, Morris unraveled the mystery of
a cop killing in his classic film ``The Thin Blue Line'' and helped
rescue an innocent man on Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, death seems to be the overriding theme in ``First
Person,'' if the first three episodes are anything to go on. Each
episode, likewise, burrows into the cerebral cortex of increasingly
strange individuals _ watching each episode in sequence, I sat,
incredulous, as the stories got exponentially weirder. If this
procession continues in similar fashion, the last episode of the
series might just trump the shocking spectacle of ``Who Wants to
Marry a Multi-Millionaire?'' (In a good way, that is.)
</P>
<P>
   Tonight seems mild only by comparison, but is a fascinating
profile of Temple Grandin, a woman who was diagnosed with autism
but overcame her affliction, and in fact, put some of its symptoms
to good use _ to design ``humane'' slaughterhouses. She's a little
reminiscent of the subject of Morris' latest film, ``Mr. Death,''
who was a successful designer of Death Row regalia _ except that
Grandin didn't throw in with neo-Nazis. She calls one design _ in
which cattle are calmly lured onto a ramp leading to their demise _
her ``Stairway to Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week, in an episode titled ``I Dismember Mama,'' Morris
interviews Saul Kent, a guy who helped start a cryogenic company,
and subsequently enlisted his mother as a client. After she died,
he decapitated her and put her skull on ice in the hopes of
resuscitating her brain at some indeterminate time in the future.
His theories of longevity and life-expectancy might make your own
blood run cold.
</P>
<P>
   With luck, you'll have picked your jaw up off the ground in time
for the third installment, ``The Killer Inside Me,'' in which
Sondra London, a serial-killer groupie, reveals more about herself
than you might want to know. Her recitation of her current
infatuation's crimes is shockingly dispassionate to the point of
being comic. When both she and her current beau _ younger and
better looking than her previous mass-murderer, she notes _
serenade one another (he, during a court appearance _ there's a
great shot of the court stenographer typing out his crooning),
you'll need to go retrieve your jaw once again.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, glimpses of oddball archival footage and swirling
music from the late Caleb Sampson are spun into the mix, combining
with the tunneling into these unique minds to create a mesmerizing
effect. Think of Morris as a highbrow Jerry Springer, mining human
oddities for fun and profit, but also shining a light into some of
America's darker recesses. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``First Person.'' &QL; 
What: Documentary series from filmmaker Errol Morris focusing on
quixotic personalities. &QL; 
Where: Bravo. &QL; 
When: 10:30 p.m. Wednesdays. &QL; 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1548EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2174 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-29 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VOTE FOR BOY GEORGE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After wasting millions of dollars and bloodying
each other's noses over religion, reform and who's the real Reagan
Republican, John McCain and George W. Bush are blowing off Ronald
Reagan's home state.
</P>
<P>
   Following months of public appearances and debates in the weird
and puny states of New Hampshire and South Carolina, the Republican
candidates for president are giving California a week of
trickle-down campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three months, Bush has spent all of one day in
California. McCain has spent more time here (the Arizona senator
always says, ``I like to visit my water''), and will take his bus
tour through the Central Valley this week. But he backed out of the
one statewide televised debate.
</P>
<P>
   The polls say McCain can't carry California Republicans on March
7, but he's close in New York. Thus, we'll be hearing a lot about
New York issues like _ what? _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, Rudolph
Giuliani and the right of policemen to empty their handguns when
threatened by black people brandishing loaded wallets.
</P>
<P>
   California may be more representative of new American realities
than New York, but who says this Republican primary is about
reality?
</P>
<P>
   This is a race in which Bush thought he could make a big
symbolic statement to South Carolina fundamentalists by speaking at
the racist, anti-Catholic Bob Jones University, and yet he thought
that wouldn't make a big symbolic statement elsewhere in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Then Bush took 24 days to admit he made a mistake. If he runs
the country the way he does his campaign, don't expect high
intelligence or quick decisions on anything.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, McCain is pounding Bush for his links to right-wing
fundamentalists, which ought to play well in New York and much of
California. But what was McCain thinking when he tried to say he
only uses the word ``gook'' about his North Vietnamese captors and
not Asians in general?
</P>
<P>
   It's reminiscent of racist Southerners who used to say that only
certain African-Americans deserved to be called by the N-word.
Sorry, it doesn't cut it, and neither do any of McCain's excuses
about skipping the California debate.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe McCain is tired and didn't want to risk using the word
``gook'' in California. I was on the East Coast when he said the
word. It raised a fuss in the San Francisco press, but received no
mention at all in the Boston or New York papers.
</P>
<P>
   There's always been a strong East Coast bias in the national
media, but I didn't know it extended to a blackout when candidates
slur major ethnic groups _ even if those groups are more strongly
represented in the West.
</P>
<P>
   We need to see these guys in action, not just in their stump
speeches and rehearsed town meetings.
</P>
<P>
   McCain made a big mistake canceling the debate. A lot of us
really wanted to see if he's as much of a hothead as he seems, or
if Bush is as inarticulate as he sounds in sound bites, which get
caught in his throat so badly they call for sound Heimlichs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week he tied his tongue in knots about the Bob Jones
University disaster, accidentally saying he was against interracial
dating, when he meant he was against the college's ban on
interracial dating.
</P>
<P>
   When he tried to say the word ``bigotry'' it came out
``bigocy.'' As in big idiocy.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the pattern of self-destruction it established with
the Clinton impeachment obsession, the Republican Party
establishment still backs George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If the guy were a stock, they would have unloaded him weeks ago.
They invested $70 million in Boy George, whose resume would fit on
a post-it note, and he's already spent most of the money losing New
Hampshire and winning a Pyrrhic victory in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   McCain irritates the GOP establishment, so it undercuts him
every chance it gets, even though he's the one guy who can beat Al
Gore in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   So the question for Democrats, including those of us who
re-registered as Republicans for the California primary, is how do
we help the Republican Party destroy itself?
</P>
<P>
   Why not be a little vengeful and cast a negative vote? After
all, Republicans in Congress wasted years of our time trying to
destroy a popular Democratic president.
</P>
<P>
   When I registered as a Republican a few weeks ago, my idea was
to vote against the party-anointed nonentity who spoke at a bigoted
college and still thought he could be president.
</P>
<P>
   McCain isn't all that different in his conservative philosophy
than Bush. They believe that women have no right to abortion, that
gays are second-class citizens and that trillions should be spent
on hare-brained schemes to shoot rockets out of the sky. The idea
was just to vote against Bush, not for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed. Now it looks like I'll have to vote for Boy
George. He has one clear advantage over McCain. Gore can beat him
like a set of bongos.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe my wife and I will just cancel out each other's votes.
Being a Republican is hard work, almost as hard as being a Democrat
was in 1972, when the idea was to lose big with another George,
that McGovern guy.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
