<SLUG> BC-AUSTRIA-REACT-675(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPE DISMISSES HAIDER RESIGNATION AS TACTICAL MANEUVER  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ European governments on Tuesday dismissed the abrupt
resignation of Joerg Haider from the leadership of his
anti-immigrant Freedom Party as a tactical maneuver and said
punitive measures against Austria would remain in place.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the British government said: ``Our concern over
what has been happening in Austria has been about policies not
personalities. The Freedom Party is still in government. It is
still extremist.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Guterres, the Portuguese prime minister and current
holder of the rotating presidency of the 15-member European Union,
said there would be no change in position ``for the moment''
because the key question ``is the nature of the Freedom Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The European stance appeared certain to maintain pressure on the
already strained coalition of Wolfgang Schuessel, the conservative
chancellor, who took his People's Party into government with the
Freedom Party three weeks ago and so ended three decades of Social
Democrat-led rule in Austria.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented intrusion into the domestic politics of a
member state of the European Union, the 14 other governments froze
bilateral relations with Austria, determined that Austrian
ambassadors would only be received at the ``technical level,'' and
vowed not to support any Austrians for senior positions in
international organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Schuessel made clear that he viewed Haider's resignation as an
attempt to overcome international mistrust. Throughout Austria, an
initial feeling that the European measures would prove ephemeral
has given way to the grim understanding that they are likely to
last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe this is a game or a tactical maneuver, but a
serious offer to ease pressure on the government,'' Schuessel said.
``I take this offer very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that personal attacks against Haider and his family at
a demonstration in Vienna in mid-February must have been ``almost
physically painful for anyone that has any sensibility.''
</P>
<P>
   People close to Haider, including the deputy speaker of the
parliament, Thomas Prinzhorn, have also suggested that he has been
wounded by the extent and intensity of the attacks on him. Haider
appears to have believed that his apologies for isolated past
remarks praising aspects of the Third Reich would be broadly
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The chancellor, who obliged Haider to issue a formal statement
before the government was formed saying the revisionist comments
about the Nazis were a mistake, appeared largely isolated in his
view that the resignation should be taken as a serious invitation
to normalize ties with Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Only Italy, which has been irked by German suggestions that it
too may face European sanctions if a rightist party joins the
government, hinted that the resignation could open the way for a
reconsideration of the European position.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberto Dini, the Italian foreign minister, said that if the
Freedom Party turned its back on extremist positions it sometimes
adopted in the past, ``It will be possible to see if normal
relations can be reestablished with a country that is such a friend
of Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy's far-right National Alliance, led by Gianfranco Fini,
briefly joined a government in the mid-1990s. There was no reaction
then from a European Union still consumed with its economic
integration through the creation of the euro rather than with its
political identity.
</P>
<P>
   Belgium, which has been virulent in its criticism of Austria and
even suggested the country might leave the European Union, showed
no sign of softening its tone. ``Nothing has changed,'' said Louis
Michel, the Belgian foreign minister. ``Joerg Haider obviously
remains in the party and this party will continue to listen to his
orders.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a statement issued Monday explaining his resignation, Haider
said that he wanted to concentrate on his job as governor of the
southern state of Carinthia and thought the six Freedom Party
ministers in the government should be freed of his shadow. But
asked whether he still has ambitions to be chancellor, he replied:
``I do not exclude it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander van Bellen, the leader of the opposition Green party,
said, ``The government is clearly a shadow cabinet, despite Mr.
Haider's resignation.'' Just how long the government will last has
become an open question in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   But angered by the European reaction, and convinced that the
ousted Social Democrats have played a central role in orchestrating
the outcry against Austria through fellow center-left parties in
government, both Schuessel and Haider have vowed that their
coalition would not bow to external pressure.
</P>
<P>
   One man who clearly could not take the pressure was the Freedom
Party's Michael Krueger, 44, who resigned as justice minister on
Tuesday after just over three weeks in office. He was said to be in
a hospital suffering from stress after a tenure marked chiefly by
his widely noted desire to have a Jaguar as his official car.
</P>
<P>
   The government faces some potentially unpopular decisions over
cutting Austria's budget deficit and ballooning debt, and it seemed
plausible that Haider's decision was rooted in a desire to avoid
direct criticism and so position himself to return as a kind of
national savior in the next elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact remained that the decision to resign must have been
painful to a man with a strong taste for power. It therefore
suggested that the personal and political pressure on him has been
close to overwhelming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
