<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL HISTORY YOU CAN SINK YOUR TEETH INTO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What's the story behind the name of the Watergate cake?
</P>
<P>
   _ E.S., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Watergate cake and Watergate salad got their names from the
scandal that caused President Nixon's resignation, but the
connection between politics and dessert isn't clear.
</P>
<P>
   Both recipes use pistachio instant pudding mix, which was
introduced by Kraft Foods in 1975. The original recipe for
Watergate salad was developed that year by Kraft to promote the new
product.
</P>
<P>
   However, Kraft named it Pistachio Pineapple Delight. ``The
company didn't refer to it at all as Watergate salad until
consumers started requesting a recipe for Watergate salad,''
according to the Richmond Times-Dispatch.
</P>
<P>
   Watergate Salad was reportedly named by a Chicago food editor
for an article, but neither the article nor editor has been tracked
down. The full name of the cake is Watergate cake with cover-up
icing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to the Old Jacksonville Ceiling Fan Co.?
</P>
<P>
   _ T.W., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Old Jacksonville fans were built by Nichols Cusan in
Jacksonville, Texas, but the company went out of business about 10
to 15 years ago, said Mike Evans, owner of Gulf Coast Fans near
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Gulf Coast repairs Old Jacksonville fans and sells replacement
parts. ``They don't make fans like that anymore,'' Evans said. ``If
something goes wrong, it's probably a flywheel _ the rubber part
that holds the blade.''
</P>
<P>
   The company sells a $49.20 replacement flywheel with phone
support for do-it-yourself repairs. For more information, call
(281) 495-6434 or visit the Web site www.eceilingfans.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where can I write to former Dallas Maverick Jim Jackson?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.C., Fort Worth
</P>
<P>
   A: Write to Jackson or any other Atlanta Hawks player in care of
the team at 1 CNN Center, Suite 405, South Tower, Atlanta 30303.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 29, has played for five teams since Dallas traded him
in 1997: the New Jersey Nets, Philadelphia 76ers, Golden State
Warriors, Portland Trailblazers and Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   An off-season resident of Dallas, Jackson is a vice president of
the NBA Players Association.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
