<SLUG> BC-INDIA-MILITARY-475(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA, A NUCLEAR POWER, RAISES MILITARY SPENDING 28 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ With relations between India and Pakistan at
their worst point in three decades, India on Tuesday announced a
28.2 percent increase in military spending, the largest single-year
boost in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shall not shrink from making any sacrifice to guard and
protect every inch of our beloved motherland,'' the finance
minister, Yashwant Sinha, said in presenting the annual budget to
parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement comes less than three weeks before President
Clinton is scheduled to arrive here on a mission that is at least
partly intended to ease the strain between two of the world's
nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   The big jump in military spending is no surprise. It has been
expected since India fought intense battles with Pakistani-backed
forces in Kashmir six months ago. The Indians drove off the
invaders, but the incursion revealed weaknesses in the nation's
defenses. The military complained that a decade of belt-tightening
had left it without needed funds for basic supplies, surveillance
equipment and upgraded weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, tensions have grown worse. Pakistan's military
overthrew the elected government in Islamabad. Guerrilla attacks
have increased in Kashmir. India blamed Pakistan for the hijacking
of an Indian airliner on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   ``India is sending a message with the new budget,'' said George
Perkovich, author of the new book ``India's Nuclear Bomb.'' ``It's
saying to Pakistan, `OK, you may want to use a bellicose strategy
against us, but you're broke and we're not. We're going to spend 28
percent more. Can you match that?'''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Pakistan is deeply in debt. But India, too, has a
ballooning fiscal deficit that needs attention. The budget for the
year beginning on April 1 calls for tax increases on higher-income
people, a review of state subsidies, and cuts in the government
payroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we are considering downsizing,'' Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee told reporters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cuts in personnel will not include the military, which will have
an allowance of $13.5 billion. Nearly half the money will go to the
army. It is unclear how much will be devoted to nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really mind-boggling how a country could increase a
budget 28 percent if it was just for conventional forces,'' said
Maj. Gen. Rashid Qureshi, a spokesman for Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   In May of 1998, India tested a nuclear device and Pakistan
followed suit 17 days later. Ever since, there has been fear of an
arms race in South Asia.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The rise in India's military budget is a victory for those who
have been wanting to beef up the armed forces. However, it is also
a repudiation of the view that nuclear weapons would buy a better
defense for less money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going nuclear hasn't done much for India's security, has it?''
said P.R. Chari, director of the Institute for Peace and Conflict
Studies in New Delhi. ``The country seems to be moving in several
directions all at once.''
</P>
<P>
   But others see a bigger military budget as an overdue payment.
``India has a 1-million-man army, a two-fleet navy and a
35-combat-squadron air force, and that takes money,'' said Uday
Bhaskar, deputy director of the Institute for Defense Studies and
Analyses here.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, when India was experiencing a financial crisis, the
military budget was cut back as a percentage of the gross domestic
product, Bhaskar said. The decline continued throughout the decade.
Last summer's fighting in Kashmir was a wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that's happening now is that we're catching up,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
