<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARDONNAY OF STEEL: CHABLIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any time you think you've got a grape figured out, along comes a
wine that knocks it out of its pigeonhole. The best chardonnays,
for example, whether from California or Burgundy or even Australia,
tend to be rich and creamy, full of exotic flavors buttressed by
sensations of toasty vanilla and butter that are induced by aging
in oak barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Chablis, one of my favorite wines and an exception
to most other wines made from the chardonnay grape.
</P>
<P>
   Genuine Chablis, not to be confused with those jug wines tagged
with the name chablis, comes from the Chablis region of France
southeast of Paris. Chablis produces only white wines made from the
chardonnay grape, like the best white Burgundies.
</P>
<P>
   Though Chablis is generally lumped in with Burgundy, the region
is actually about 75 miles north of where most white Burgundies are
produced, which partly accounts for the singular nature of Chablis.
Because the vineyards are in a much cooler region, Chablis tends to
be crisp, lean and taut rather than fat and lush like so many other
chardonnays around the world.
</P>
<P>
   That crispness is partly a result of acidity. As grapes ripen,
the fruit's natural acids turn into sugar. Since grapes grown in
warmer areas have a longer growing season and thus tend to ripen
further than in cooler areas, they become sweeter and less acidic.
</P>
<P>
   When these grapes are harvested and fermented, that sugar
converts to alcohol, giving warm-weather grapes generally more
alcohol and less acid than cooler-weather grapes.
</P>
<P>
   Theess of Chablis is also a result of style. Most Chablis
is fermented in stainless steel tanks rather than oak barrels,
resulting in wines that reflect the characteristics of the fruit
and the vineyard, without added oak features.
</P>
<P>
   Even Chablis, though, has its exceptions. Rene and Vincent
Dauvissat, for example, are among the best Chablis makers, who use
oak carefully to augment the flavors of the grape. It's a rounder,
mellower style that still exhibits the steely mineral character of
Chablis.
</P>
<P>
   Chablis has four levels, depending on where the grapes are
grown. Grand cru is the best and most expensive, followed by
premier cru, Chablis and Petit Chablis. These six wines are listed
in order of preference. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOMAINE BARAT, CHABLIS PREMIER CRU, LES FOURNEAUX, 1998 $15 &QL; 
Aromas of minerals and apples, bright and delicious. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOUIS MICHEL &AMP; FILS, CHABLIS PREMIER CRU, MONTMAIN, 1997 $33 &QL; 
Aromas of honey, wet rocks and apple; dry and steely. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RENE AND VINCENT DAUVISSAT, CHABLIS PREMIER CRU, VAILLONS, 1996
$50 &QL; 
Mineral, anise and apple flavors mellowed by oak. &QL;
</P>
