<HEADLINE>
YOU DON'T WANT TO MISS THE DANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I don't know much about fortune cookies. However, I truly enjoy
cracking open those cute little delicacies that always accompany my
order of sesame chicken and an egg roll. Inside the cookie is a
small slip of paper containing a prediction or maxim.
</P>
<P>
   I always open the fortune cookie at the end of my meal. I wait
until I'm finished with my meal because that's what I've seen other
people do. In retrospect, I'm not sure that I should wait until
I've finished eating to read my fortune. Suppose it says, ``Avoid
egg rolls this week or you will have bad luck.'' That has never
happened but, just in case, I think I need to know about that
before my meal, don't you?
</P>
<P>
   I've been thinking a lot about the future lately. I've been
thinking about dreams, visions, and goals.
</P>
<P>
   Dreams are the seeds of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Dreams are merely images in the mind, something unreal. No one
else can see our dreams. That makes life difficult when we are
trying to make our dreams come true and it seems like no one else
supports us. Don't get angry because others don't embrace your
dream. If everyone could see it, it would be a vision, not a dream.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you do need help, and most of us do, you have to
take your dream and make it a vision, that is, an object of sight.
That's all a business plan or marketing plan or degree plan is,
actually. When you take something intangible and remote and make it
real and believable, your dream becomes a goal. Then, you will find
people willing to help you.
</P>
<P>
   I saw a psychic on television a few days ago. She seemed to have
an incredible ability to predict the future. For a moment, I
thought that would be a great ability to possess. However, some of
the best and hardest lessons of my life have come from the
unanticipated results of my choices. I might have made different
choices if I could predict the future, but I don't think I would
have become the person that I am without the thrill of victory and
agony of defeat that accompanied those choices.
</P>
<P>
   The worst times of my life have been the days and weeks when I
stopped dreaming. I lost my sense of purpose, my sense of hope. So,
no, I don't want to know the future; who's going to live or die,
who's going to betray me, or who will move away some day. What's
the fun in that?
</P>
<P>
   I think Garth Brooks said it best, ``I'm glad I didn't know the
way it all would end, the way it all would go. Our lives are better
left to chance. I could have missed the pain, but I'd have had to
miss the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564, or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St., Arlington
76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
