<HEADLINE>
THE TALENTED WRITER BEHIND `THE TALENTED MR. RIPLEY'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A current movie titled ``The Talented Mr. Ripley'' is both a
critical and commercial success. Surprise: The film is adapted from
a novel titled ``The Talented Mr. Ripley.'' Surprise: The novel was
published 45 years ago. Surprise: Its author was born in Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has prompted a renewal of interest in the late
Patricia Highsmith, several of whose works focused on the
diabolically charming Tom Ripley. Highsmith has long been regarded
as one of the best practitioners in her chosen genre. Suspense was
her racket. She did not write murder mysteries, because the murders
that occur (often) in her fiction are witnessed by the reader and
leave no doubt as to who did it. Her dark tales often take the
point of view of the evildoer.
</P>
<P>
   America's literary critics are reluctant to grant distinction to
authors who work the crime beat. Raymond Chandler and Dashiell
Hammett now are ennobled as masters of detective fiction, but with
no other companions in the pantheon. Europeans, however, are more
serious-minded about literary melodrama; and particularly in
France, Patricia Highsmith is considered a major American author.
</P>
<P>
   Because of her novels' worldwide popularity, Highsmith was
enabled to spend most of her adult life in the expensive serenity
of Locarno, Switzerland, where she died at age 74 in 1995. She was
writing to the end; and the posthumously published ``Small g: A
Summer Idyll,'' was her 22nd novel. Her short stories were
collected in several volumes, and a how-to nonfiction entry _
``Plotting and Writing Suspense Fiction'' _ was published in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Her first novel is the work with which Highsmith has been most
easily identified, again with some indebtedness to Hollywood. She
was 29 when ``Strangers on a Train'' was published. Movie rights
were purchased by the talented Mr. Alfred Hitchcock. In 1955, ``The
Talented Mr. Ripley'' became Highsmith's fourth published novel.
For years, it remained a favorite work for many readers and for the
author herself, so in late career she brought Tom Ripley back in
four sequels. If you've now seen the movie and are wondering what
happened later, be assured that yes, he got away with it.
</P>
<P>
   So is the movie like the book? Most of the book is in the movie,
but the movie adds important characters and events that are not in
Highsmith's original. In the novel, Tom Ripley and Dickie Greenleaf
actually were acquainted in their youth before Ripley's contrived
meeting with the latter in Italy. There's one less murder in the
novel. I'll say no more.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is retired books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
