<HEADLINE>
SO MUCH TASTE, SO LITTLE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The idea of preparing cassoulet in 40 minutes or less
is heresy, but I was determined to find a reasonable compromise
when I realized I would be unable to schedule the usual three-day
production to serve to friends before the weather turned warm.
</P>
<P>
   Authentic cassoulet from southern France contains beans, braised
mutton, sausage, confit of goose or duck and maybe a slab of bacon,
all stewed together so the flavors meld, and finished with a
crunchy topping of bread crumbs. It is glorified pork and beans,
but the glory is in the nuanced taste and richness. The depth of
flavor is impossible to replicate fast, so my goal was simply to
turn braised beans into a feast.
</P>
<P>
   I thought about starting with dried beans and simmering them
with thyme, garlic and fatty pork, but I wanted to take every
possible shortcut. So I used frozen white beans, which are now
being sold in some supermarkets, and combined them with tomatoes
and lots of garlic. If you can't find frozen beans, use canned, but
drain and rinse them first.
</P>
<P>
   Although the combination of beans, tomatoes and garlic is
already pretty potent, I figured that some flavorful cooking liquid
would help. I used red wine because it was handy. (I was going to
serve it with the stew.) Canned stock wouldn't add much flavor, but
if you go with dried beans, their cooking liquid would be
harmonious.
</P>
<P>
   In this cassoulet, there is no time for tenderizing tough meat
like mutton; you need instant flavor as well as tenderness. Pork
tenderloin, cut into chunks, meets both requirements: it tastes
good and it cooks quickly. Sausage, the sweet, fennel-scented kind,
is another fine addition, adding a little fat to the stew, which is
not only traditional but necessary. The sausage benefits from a
five-minute browning to crisp the skin and deepen the flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of duck confit, which my supermarket doesn't carry, I
used duck breast. I seared it on both sides until it was nice and
brown but still slightly rare, and I added its juices to the
simmering stew.
</P>
<P>
   If you have extra time to start with dried beans, you can cook
them with a few sprigs of fresh thyme, half a head of garlic and a
piece of salt pork or bacon. The garlic can be sauteed in a little
duck fat before you add the tomatoes and beans.
</P>
<P>
   You can also substitute browned duck confit for the duck breast;
add some of the confit's fat as well, if you have it. Or you can
just finish the dish by toasting some bread crumbs seasoned with
salt and pepper in the fat left over from browning the duck.
Sprinkle these on top of the stew just before serving.
</P>
<P>
   All my work was done on top of the stove, and quickly, but the
results surprised and delighted me. This rapid-strike version of
cassoulet was not as magnificent as those I've slaved over in the
past, but it was as delicious as most of those I have had in
restaurants. Though the amount of food here should serve eight, I
list the yield as four to six because it's one of those dishes you
can't stop eating. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   STREAMLINED CASSOULET &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chopped tomatoes, with their juice (canned are fine)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   4 cups white beans, nearly fully cooked (drained if canned)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup stock, dry red wine, bean cooking liquid or water
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon cayenne pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Italian sausage, preferably in one piece
</P>
<P>
   1 pound pork tenderloin, cut into 1-inch cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 boned duck breast &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine tomatoes and garlic in a large saucepan, bring to a
boil and add beans. Bring to a boil again, stirring occasionally,
then reduce heat so mixture bubbles regularly but not furiously.
Cook about 20 minutes, adding stock or other liquid when mixture
thickens. Add salt and cayenne when beans are tender and flavorful.
</P>
<P>
   2. While beans are cooking, put sausage in a skillet, and turn
heat to medium-high; brown on both sides, turning only once or
twice. Add to pot with bean mixture, along with pork cubes. Raise
heat a bit if necessary to keep a simmer going. Stir beans
occasionally so pork cooks evenly.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cut a {-inch crosshatch in skin side of duck breast, right
down to fat layer. Put breast, skin side down, in skillet that
sausage cooked in, and turn heat to medium-high. Cook until nicely
browned, pouring any rendered duck fat and juices into bean
mixture. Turn duck, and brown meat side. Then crisp up skin side
again for a minute or so, once more pouring any fat into beans.
Total cooking time for breast will be 6 to 8 minutes. When it is
done, add breast to beans.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, carve sausage and duck breast into serving pieces,
and place on plates. Top with beans and pork.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1625EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
