<SLUG> BC-IRS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS SCORED FOR FAILING TO PURSUE TAX CHEATERS
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Internal Revenue Service came under fire on
Capitol Hill Tuesday for letting tax cheaters off the hook and for
hiring people charged with crimes as temporary workers.
</P>
<P>
   Government Reform subcommittee chairman Steve Horn, R-Calif.,
said the agency operations ``have placed an unacceptable burden on
taxpayers and equally unacceptable loss of revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Governmental Affairs Committee Chairman Fred Thompson
said that ``once again we see that the IRS can't keep its own books
while demanding that taxpayers keep theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials appeared before Horn's subcommittee to
respond to a sharply critical audit of the tax-collecting agency
issued by the U.S. General Accounting Office, the investigative arm
of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS's acting chief financial officer, Lawrence W. Rogers,
blamed many of the accounting problems on the agency's ``archaic''
computer system, which is to be replaced over the next several
years.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO focused much of its criticism on the tax agency's
failure to pursue tax scofflaws. Among the examples:
</P>
<P>
   _ A doctor who owed $100,000 in taxes going back to the 1980s
had an income of $200,000 as of 1998, and yet he was ``not being
actively pursued,'' said GAO official Gregory D. Kutz.
</P>
<P>
   _ Employers reneged on $43 billion in Social Security and
Medicare payroll taxes and late penalties over the past decade.
</P>
<P>
   _ The IRS reports $231 billion in unpaid tax assessments, but
collection efforts are so unsuccessful that more than half,
totalling $127 billion, have been written off.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS acknowledged that in 1999 it hired nearly 5,000 people
to handle checks and tax returns before their criminal background
clearances were complete.
</P>
<P>
   Of those new employees, 138 were later found to have unsuitable
backgrounds, including criminal charges for theft and weapons
violations. At least 65 were either fired or forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   IRS chief operations officer John M. Dalrymple told the
lawmakers the rushed hirings were necessary at peak times ``when we
have tremendous amounts of mail coming in'' around April 15 tax
filing day.
</P>
<P>
   Although he said the FBI can provide criminal background checks
within eight days, ``we can't completely commit'' to waiting that
long.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
