<P>
   EICHMANN-DIARY (Dateline to kum) _ Israel, at request of defense
in a libel case in Britain, releases Eichmann's diary, which has
detailed plans of death camps. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT5.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-JOURNALIST (Moscow) _ More than a month after he
disappeared in Chechnya, a Radio Liberty reporter returned to
Moscow on Tuesday and said he had been beaten at a Russian
detention camp. The case of the reporter, Andrei Babitsky, who
angered the Russian military with his reports from Grozny, has
spurred concerns about press freedom in Russia. The United States
has said it was holding the Kremlin accountable for his safety. And
his sudden reappearance has been a relief to his family and
friends. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-DIVORCE (Cairo) _ A new divorce law takes effect in Egypt
on Wednesday that greatly expands women's rights. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS (Washington) _ Two lively Supreme Court arguments on
police practices found the government on the defensive Tuesday, as
the justices suggested that the police may have violated the
Constitution by frisking a Miami teen-ager on the basis of an
anonymous tip that he was carrying a gun and by squeezing a bus
passenger's soft-sided luggage to see if it contained drugs. The
court appeared surprisingly unimpressed by the government's
arguments, in one case that guns are so inherently dangerous that
the police are justified in acting on the basis of a bare-bones tip
that might otherwise be insufficient, and in the other case that
passengers relinquish any expectation of privacy in their luggage
once they toss it into an overhead bin where it can be pushed and
shoved by others seeking room for their own bags. By Linda
Greenhouse.
</P>
