<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVOCADOS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVOCADO SKIPS THE APPETIZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By STEVEN RAICHLEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guacamole may be the dip of summer, but avocados are at their
prime right now. This tropical fruit, with its soft, pale flesh,
can go a long way in adding interest to a winter diet. Green
vegetables often disappoint at this time of year, but the avocado
brings a blast of summery freshness.
</P>
<P>
   Botanically speaking, the avocado is a fruit, and in some parts
of the world _ notably Southeast Asia and Brazil _ it is' treated
as such. Brazilians, for example, combine the flesh with sugar to
make desserts. The Vietnamese whirl it with sweetened condensed
milk and ice in a blender to make milkshakes.
</P>
<P>
   But in most places, including the United States, the avocado is
treated as a vegetable. It is mashed into dips, pureed in soups and
diced over fajitas, and its pale green slices are fanned over
salads. But the avocado can play more central roles, a virtue
appreciated by the Mexicans, who inherited their taste for it from
the Aztecs, and who seldom eat a meal without it.
</P>
<P>
   The fruit may have been considered an aphrodisiac in years past,
but today it is prized for its softly firm flesh, its sweet
herbaceous flavor and a buttery richness that is' unique in the
world of plants.
</P>
<P>
   This richness comes from the avocado's high fat content _ a
hefty 20 percent. Avocados are so rich in cholesterol-free
vegetable fat they've been called poor man's butter (I prefer the
notion of vegetable foie gras).
</P>
<P>
   You have surely recognized this quality if you have ever spooned
guacamole over dry grilled meats in taquitos or carnitas. Perhaps
this was the inspiration for a silken avocado sauce I enjoyed in
Mexico City, where it was served with simply grilled fish.
</P>
<P>
   There are two main commercial varieties of avocados: a large,
shiny green variety called alligator pear, which is grown in
Florida, and the Haas, from California. The Haas is the more
familiar type, with wrinkled leathery black-green skin, pale
yellow-green flesh and an oval pit in the center. For both, the way
to check for ripeness is to gently squeeze the fruit between thumb
and forefinger: when ripe, it will gently yield.
</P>
<P>
   Avocados ripen well at home. Store them, unwrapped, at room
temperature. You may want to buy them a few days before you plan to
use them to allow for ripening. Or buy fresh avocados every few
days, so you will always have a ripe one on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Many recipes call for diced or sliced avocados. There are two
easy ways to cut them. For avocado slices, using the tip of your
knife, make four shallow lengthwise slits in the skin from end to
end. Pinching one corner of the skin between the knife blade and
your thumb, gently pull it away from the avocado, almost as you
would peel a banana. Repeat to remove all four sections of the
skin. Then cut the flesh off the pit in lengthwise wedges.
</P>
<P>
   To dice avocado, first cut the fruit in half lengthwise with a
single cut to the pit, rotating the fruit 360 degrees while
cutting. Twist the halves in opposite directions; the pit will
separate from one half. Sink the blade into the pit and gently
rotate the knife; the pit will pop out of the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Using the tip of the knife, make a series of parallel cuts
through the avocado flesh but not through the skin. They should be
half an inch apart. Now, make another series of cuts at a 90 degree
angle to the first. Use a spoon to scrape the avocado out of the
skin. The flesh will come out in neat dice.
</P>
<P>
   Avocado discolors quickly, so squeeze fresh lime or lemon juice
over the flesh to keep it from browning.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes here are a soulful avocado chicken soup inspired by
the tart, tangy lime soup of the Yucatan; an avocado and white bean
salad that would be at home in Tuscany; and a broiled salmon with
avocado sauce fragrant with roasted chilies.
</P>
<P>
   Let March winds howl: the taste of summer is only an avocado
away. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   AVOCADO SOUP WITH CHICKEN AND LIME &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 corn tortillas, cut into matchstick slivers
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 medium white onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   8 cloves garlic, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 to 6 jalapenos, thinly sliced (as many as you can stand)
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces boneless, skinless chicken breasts, thinly sliced
across the grain, about [-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   4 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lime juice, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe tomato, seeded and cut into {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe avocado, peeled, seeded and cut into {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   \ cup chopped fresh cilantro. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven or toaster oven to 400 degrees. Arrange tortilla
strips on a baking sheet and bake until lightly browned, 3 to 5
minutes. Transferto a plate to cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat olive oil in a large saucepan. Add onion, garlic and
jalapeno slices and cook over medium heat until lightly browned,
about 4 minutes. Stir in the chicken, chicken broth, lime juice,
tomato, salt and pepper. Gently simmer until chicken is cooked,
about 3 minutes. Add avocado and cilantro and cook until warm, 1
minute. Adjust seasonings, adding salt or lime juice to taste: soup
should be highly seasoned. Ladle soup into bowls and sprinkle with
toasted tortilla strips.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SALMON WITH AVOCADO SAUCE AND FRIED GARLIC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 30 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4 8-ounce boneless, skinless salmon fillets
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground coriander
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the avocado sauce: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 poblano chili (or small green bell pepper)
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno
</P>
<P>
   { medium white onion, cut in two pieces
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic (2 whole cloves peeled, 4 cloves peeled and
thinly sliced)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe avocado, peeled and seeded
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped cilantro, plus 4 sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   { cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   { cup bottled clam broth or water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice, or to taste. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Season salmon fillets with salt and pepper, and sprinkle with
coriander and garlic. Arrange in a baking dish and pour \ cup lime
juice and \ cup extra virgin olive oil over them. Marinate for 30
minutes, turning once or twice.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, prepare sauce. Heat a heavy skillet over a
medium-high flame. Roast poblano chili, jalapeno, onion and 2 whole
garlic cloves until nicely browned, 8 to 10 minutes for the poblano
and onion, 4 to 6 minutes for the garlic and jalapeno. Transfer to
a plate and let cool. Seed poblano chili and jalapeno.
</P>
<P>
   3. Heat the 2 tablespoons olive oil in a small skillet over
medium heat. Fry sliced garlic until lightly browned, 1 to 2
minutes. Do not let burn. Drain garlic in a strainer.
</P>
<P>
   4. Place roasted poblano chili, jalapeno, onion and garlic in a
blender with the avocado, chopped cilantro, cumin, cream, clam
broth and lime juice. Puree until smooth, running blender in short
bursts, adding broth or water as needed for a thick but pourable
sauce. Adjust seasonings, adding salt, pepper and lime juice to
taste. Add half the fried garlic and pulse just to mix. Keep sauce
warm in a saucepan over low heat.
</P>
<P>
   5. Preheat broiler to high. Broil salmon until cooked, 4 to 6
minutes a side. Arrange salmon on plates and pour sauce over them.
Garnish with remaining fried garlic and cilantro sprigs and serve
at once.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AVOCADO SALAD WITH PINE NUTS, CANNELLINI BEANS AND PROSCIUTTO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe avocado, peeled, seeded and cut into {-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 cups cooked cannellini beans, rinsed well and drained
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons top-quality Tuscan extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces thinly sliced prosciutto, cut into thin slivers
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons toasted pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely chopped red onion
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons finely chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons chopped fresh rosemary, &QL;
</P>
<P>
   plus 4 sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Sea salt and finely ground black pepper. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine avocado and lemon juice in a mixing bowl and toss
gently. Add beans, oil, prosciutto, pine nuts, onion, parsley,
rosemary, salt and pepper, and gently toss to mix. Adjust
seasonings, adding salt and lemon juice to taste.
</P>
<P>
   2. Transfer salad to martini glasses or plates and garnish with
rosemary sprigs.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
