<HEADER>
A2218 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GRANNY-D-0301-COX     02-29 0450
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRANNY-D-0301-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'GRANNY D' ENDS THE WALK, BUT NOT THE TALK
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After walking the walk for 3,200 miles and more
than a year, talking the talk on campaign finance reform came
easily on Tuesday for 90-year-old Doris Haddock _ ``Granny D'' to
her legions of followers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come for reform or for some new senators,'' she
warned, standing on the U.S. Capitol steps and speaking in a strong
New England accent and wearing a broad-brimmed straw hat.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan majority in the House has passed a bill to ban
so-called ``soft money'' in political campaigns but the measure has
been blocked in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock, a lifelong political activist from Dublin, N.H., began
her long protest march about 14 months ago at the 1999 Rose Bowl
Parade in Pasadena, Calif. She was hospitalized from dehydration in
the Mojave desert, saw the bluebonnets bloom last spring in Texas,
and trudged through Pennsylvania snow this winter. She walked 10
miles a day, 1400 steps to a mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doris Haddock has given us her 90th year and then some,'' said
Ronnie Dugger, head of the Alliance for Democracy, which advocates
public funding of elections. ``She has walked into our hearts and
walked into history.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Lloyd Doggett, D-Texas, was among the members of Congress
who welcomed ``Granny D'' by walking with her on the final steps of
her journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Washington, as Granny D walked across America, special
interests with unlimited secret funds continued to walk all over
Americans on one critical issue after another,'' said Doggett. ``We
can never give up on meaningful reform because nothing less than
the future of our democracy is at stake.''
</P>
<P>
   A widow and great-grandmother of 12, Haddock said she began her
walk after hearing Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., and other opponents
of campaign finance reform say that people don't care about the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have come to tell them that they are wildly mistaken,'' she
told hundreds of cheering supporters, including David Crosby, the
singer. The crowd took up the chant when Rep. Connie Morella,
R-Md., urged, ``As the Beach Boys said, 'Go Granny Go'.''
</P>
<P>
   Haddock described walking beside the rows on white crosses at
Arlington National Cemetery and thinking that those fallen soldiers
did not give their lives ``so laws might be sold to the highest
bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans she met along the way gave her a message to bring
to Washington, she said: ``We come a'sweeping.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Dart can be reached by e-mail at: BobDart(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
