<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SYRIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARON ARGUES AGAINST AID TO SYRIA AS PART OF ANY PEACE DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Presuming that Israeli-Syrian peace talks will
resume because President Clinton ``will make every effort to see
that it happens,'' Ariel Sharon, leader of the opposition Likud
Party, began campaigning Tuesday against Western aid to Syria as
part of any deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to sound the alarm before it's too late,'' Sharon, a
right-wing former general, said in an interview. ``Once and if and
when this process will start, the time will be short. And I really
worry that Syria will get the financial means to purchase modern
weapons and threaten the qualitative edge that Israel must
maintain.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been widely rumored in Israel and in Washington that
Israel and Syria will soon return to the negotiations that were
suspended in January. In Jordan, Arab diplomats said Tuesday that
talks would resume in March, and that an announcement would be made
in the next 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli and U.S. officials deny that there has been any
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no indication whatsoever about the possibility of
resuming talks,'' said Gadi Baltiansky, spokesman for Prime
Minister Ehud Barak. ``The Americans are trying to revive them, but
so far there is no movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Barak has publicly signaled his readiness by hinting
earlier this week that he would consider a complete withdrawal from
the Golan Heights _ a hint that Syria welcomed but demanded in
writing.
</P>
<P>
   And the Israeli opposition, sensing that a return to the talks
is imminent, is gearing up for battle.
</P>
<P>
   A Likud member, Silvan Shalom, is trying to build support among
conservative members of Barak's coalition government for a bill
that would require a majority of all eligible voters, not just
those who go to the polls, to approve a withdrawal. The bill is
thought to be an attempt to dilute the role of the many Israeli
Arab voters and to command a ``Jewish majority.''
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary vote on the bill is expected Wednesday, with
members of three parties in the coalition _ the Russian immigrants,
the National Religious Party and the ultra-Orthodox Shas _ voting
against the government.
</P>
<P>
   And Sharon, who rarely speaks to foreign reporters based here,
took the uncommon step Tuesday of issuing a press release and
summoning an American reporter to his office at Parliament. He said
he had been driven to do so by news that liberal American lobbying
groups were trying to persuade members of Congress ``to overcome
their natural resistance'' to provide Syria money as part of a
peace package.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think they're going to do?''' he asked. ``Spend it
on education?''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon singled out the Israel Policy Forum, a pro-peace group
that advocates an active U.S. role in the peace effort. He said the
group is ``creating a dangerous situation'' by stepping up its
lobbying efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Smerling, director of the Israel Policy Forum's
Washington center, said that when peace negotiations get serious,
opponents often try to undermine the U.S. role to ``pull the plug
on the whole enterprise.'' He said his group doesn't lobby for aid
to Syria, but encourages Congress to see the strategic value of
peace with Syria and ``not to foreclose any options before a deal
is struck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Opponents of peace have long viewed Congress as the soft
underbelly of Israel's peace initiative,'' Smerling said, adding
that anti-peace groups are playing to Congress members' budget
anxieties by highlighting the high cost of a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   It is considered unlikely that Congress would ever provide Syria
with much financial assistance. If negotiations resume restarted
and an agreement reached, it is more likely that European and Arab
nations would provide the bulk of aid to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon said that investment in Syria would be a better way to
support the country and bring into the world economy. ``Just don't
give them cash,'' he said. ``We know what they will buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposed to conceding the Golan Heights at all, Sharon warned
that Israel would be pressured to ``give it away'' by the offer of
``smart weapons.'' Technology itself, he said, cannot replace
conventional weapons and the strategic depth that Israel would lose
by giving away the Golan Heights and especially Mount Hermon. Also,
Israel cannot afford some of the weaponry being discussed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It would be another ``huge mistake,'' Sharon said, if Americans
stationed troops on Mount Hermon as part of an agreement. The first
casualties of U.S. soldiers would be ``disastrous'' for
Israeli-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he felt confident that the negotiations would resume
and that these issues would be relevant, Sharon said, ``I see the
effort of Mr. Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt the president is a friend of the Jews,'' he said.
``But one must remember that American presidents come and American
presidents go and Israel has to survive forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
