<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., March 5) 
(jt) 
 By RAY CORMIER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Touring Jewish Budapest &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Four of us will be in Budapest for three days this summer. We
would like to hire an English-speaking guide to learn about the
city's Jewish history and culture. _ Maxine Greenberg, South
Windsor, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   A. Jews were a strong presence in Budapest as early as the 13th
century, and a large Jewish community was part of Hungarian society
until the Holocaust. Among the sites you'll probably want to visit
are the great Dohany Street Synagogue in central Pest _ among the
largest in the world, seating 3,000 _ and its museum and Holocaust
Memorial, a sculpture of a weeping willow.
</P>
<P>
   The Hungarian National Tourist Office, can provide a list of
English-speaking guides in Budapest, according to Nicole Rona,
assistant to the director. It also has a free brochure, ``Shalom:
Jewish Relics in Hungary,'' to help with your explorations of
Erzsbet Town, the old Jewish quarter. Contact the office at 150
East 58th St., New York, N.Y. 10155; (212) 355-0240, fax (212)
207-4103; or see www.gotohungary.com,
</P>
<P>
   Among the travel agencies in Budapest that can arrange Jewish
cultural tours is Cityrama Sightseeing Travel Agency, Bathori Utca
22, 1054 Budapest; (36-1) 331-0305, fax (36-1) 312-5424. It offers
a walking tour at 10 a.m. on Sunday, Monday, Wednesday and Friday
after April 1. Besides the Dohany Street Synagogue, it goes to
three other synagogues and, from May till October, the Raoul
Wallenberg Memorial and a medieval synagogue, among other places.
Requests to visit particular sites are welcome, Emese Dombovari of
Cityrama said.
</P>
<P>
   This tour lasts three hours and includes a lunch stop at a
kosher restaurant, with free cake and beverage. The cost is about
$16, at 260 forints to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Dombovari said that City-rama, which also has offices in Vienna
and Prague, arranges private tours in minibuses for $26.50 an hour,
with a minimum of three hours.
</P>
<P>
   Another similar walking tour is offered twice daily except
Saturdays and holidays from mid-March through October by Expo
Travel, Rozsa Utca 71, 1064 Budapest, (36-1) 311-9050, fax (36-1)
353-1515. It lasts two and a half hours, costs $20 and stops at a
nonkosher restaurant. Private tours by car in Buda and Pest cost
$100 a day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Around and About Garda &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have rented an apartment in Lazise, Italy, on Lake Garda,
as a base to explore the area, including Venice, on day trips.
Should I take trains or use my rental car? _ Peter Iserloth, Fair
Haven, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   A. Lazise, on the southeast shore of Lake Garda, is perfectly
situated for visiting other cities in the area, like Brescia,
Verona and Venice. Though small, Lazise has a few notable
monuments, including a 12th-century castle with five towers and the
Romanesque church of San Nicolo with its 12th-century frescoes. For
centuries, the Dogana Veneta, or Venetian customs house, at the
town's small port was the point from which the Venetian Republic
controlled commerce on the lake. The town still preserves large
sections of ivy covered medieval walls.
</P>
<P>
   There is no need to travel by car to reach interesting cities in
Lombardy and the Veneto, where finding parking is problematic and
can be expensive. In Venice, for example, one has to park at the
Piazzale Roma, where theGarage San Marco can cost as much as $24
for any period up to 24 hours, depending on the type of car.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably easier to drive to Peschiera del Garda, the
nearest train station, five to six miles from Lazise. From
Pescheria, there are dozens of trains to various cities.
</P>
<P>
   Trains leave for Venice, about a 1-hour 45-minute trip, at 8:13
a.m., 8:50 a.m., 10:13 a.m., 12:50 p.m., 1:13 p.m. and 2:15 p.m.;
the fare is $10.30, or $17 in first class. These all stop in Verona
and many stop in Vicenza and Padua. Going west, Brescia is a
half-hour trip ($4.50 or $7.25), and there are a couple of trains
every hour. Many continue to Milan.
</P>
<P>
   Buses go to many of the cities on Lake Garda as well as Verona
and Brescia, though buses from Peschiera are more frequent. A bus
from Brescia to Verona stops at the Esso station near the Peschiera
train station. Another goes toward Verona, stopping in Castelnuovo
del Garda, home of Gardaland, a large amusement park. Information:
SAIA Bus in Brescia, (39-030) 223-761.
</P>
<P>
   Another line stops in Lazise and goes up to Riva del Garda, the
northernmost city on the lake (about $4). Information: the APT in
Verona, (39-045) 800-4129.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Disabled in Monument Valley  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you any information regarding tours of Monument Valley
for the disabled? _ Daniel Jackson, Houston
</P>
<P>
   A. Monument Valley, whose rock formations are famous as the
backdrop of many western movies, lies in a Navajo tribal park. All
guides in the park are Navajos and all tour operators must be
licensed by the tribe, according to Ronnie Biard of Goulding's
Lodge, which the Utah Travel Council says is the biggest of the
operators. The tribe requires that anyone heading into the back
country hire a Navajo guide, to protect sacred ceremonial areas
from visitors, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Biard and the county tourism office said that they knew of no
tour vehicles with lifts for wheelchairs among the roughly 15
licensed companies. But both Biard and Martha Bennett of Bennett
Tours, a Navajo company, said they would be happy to do whatever a
disabled person is comfortable with to tour the area _ for example,
having guides lift them into the open-air trucks they use for most
tours, or using enclosed four-wheel-drive vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Except in bad weather, most private cars can manage the 17-mile
loop in the valley, Biard said, though he added that it was a
rough, unpaved road.
</P>
<P>
   You can request a list of licensed operators and information on
accessibilty in the area from the San Juan County Visitors
Services, Post Office Box 490, 117 South Main St., Monticello, Utah
84535; (800) 574-4386, fax (435) 587-2425.
</P>
<P>
   Goulding's Lodge, Post Office Box 360001, Monument Valley, Utah
84536, (435) 727-3231, fax (435) 727-3344, offers an eight-hour
tour, with a picnic lunch, for $60, $45 for ages 8 and under, and
three-hour excursions for $30 and $18. Four of the lodge's 62 rooms
are wheelchair accessible, Biard said; rates are $60 to $128.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett Tours, Post Office Box 360285, Monument Valley, Utah
84536, (800) 862-8270, fax (435) 727-3334, offers several
excursions, from an hour ($15) to all day ($80) with a steak or
Navajo taco lunch at Rain God Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
