<HEADLINE>
&HT;        CELLUCCI CALLS FOR FEDERAL ANSWER TO OIL SHORTAGES
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Alex Canizares  
 &HT;    c. 2000 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 29 - Massachusetts Governor Paul Cellucci,
joined by other New England governors concerned about the region's
heating oil crisis, urged a US energy official to devise a federal
answer to prevent against supply shortages.
</P>
<P>
   At a National Governors' Association conference in the nation's
capital this week, Cellucci said while New England's economy is
booming, low supplies of oil have put the region in a ``dangerous
situation,'' with prices soaring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that because we can't completely control price,
that means we can't completely control supply,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he supported creating a private, regional reserve in the
Northeast to avoid shortages. Sen. Edward Kennedy unveiled such a
plan last week.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of Energy T. J. Glauthier told the governors
the department was considering its options, including a plan to
temporarily draw oil from the Strategic Petroleum Reserve, to be
returned later.
</P>
<P>
   This option is under ``active discussion,'' he said, but the
Department is waiting to see whether the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, or OPEC, agrees to ease its restrictions on
oil shipments at its meeting next month.
</P>
<P>
   The reserves are to be used only in when there is an
interruption in oil supplies.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
