<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-FIRST-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      02-29 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FIRST-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIRST PERSON': WHAT LIFE MAY DEAL TO BEAST AND MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Broadcast notes appear at end of review. Time and channel
are for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(DW) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Documentaries and so-called reality programming are not the same
thing, no matter what defenders of the latter may say. Bravo's two
new half-hour Wednesday night series prove it.
</P>
<P>
   When Temple Grandin describes a cow's experience of the
slaughterhouse to Errol Morris on the fascinating ``First Person,''
it's art. When Jay Schadler films a man caring for his wife, who
has Alzheimer's disease, in the tacky ``Talelights,'' it's
voyeurism.
</P>
<P>
   Morris is the documentary filmmaker who did ``The Thin Blue
Line,'' about the murder of a Dallas police officer (a movie so
persuasive that the case was reopened and the man originally
convicted was released from prison), and, most recently, ``
Death,'' about a consultant on executions. Morris has death on his
mind again in the first episodes of ``First Person.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's episode, ``Stairway to Heaven,'' is amorphous
but compelling. Grandin, a college professor, has the distinction
of having designed what many consider a particularly humane
slaughterhouse. But the more she talks about it, the more horrible
the idea of killing animals for food seems. One design feature is a
chute that is curved so that the cows can't be frightened by things
up ahead. All a cow sees, Grandin explains, is the rear end of the
animal in front of her; each animal is shot in the head, and
because the chute walls support the animal it doesn't fall down.
</P>
<P>
   Morris shows film of cows (some of it in slow motion), of meat
hanging from hooks and of a crawling baby in a depth-perception
experiment, plus seemingly unrelated surreally fast-moving clouds.
The result is effectively dreamlike. The episode also spends
considerable time on Grandin's autism.
</P>
<P>
   Sondra London, the subject of a forthcoming episode, has
interesting taste in men. Her story begins with the handsome boy
she dated in high school (``Everyone in my family just loved him,''
but ``he loved graveyards'') who grows up to be a serial killer.
She remembers his telling her once about having seen a girl
undress. His reaction was ``arousal and anger,'' rather than
arousal and pleasure, and he said, ``I'll put a stop to that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, bored with writing computer manuals for a living, she
wrote to him in prison and suggested doing a book about his life
and crimes. But what makes London's story so compelling is her
relationship with a second serial killer. Her woman-in-love glow is
remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   The subject of the future ``I Dismember Mama'' episode is Saul
Kent, whose field is cryonics. His visions of future immortality
involve the creation of new bodies (including a younger, healthier
one for his mother, whose head he has frozen) so that someone might
be physically 21 but with the experience and wisdom of an
octogenarian. Kent was 10 months old when his father died of
rheumatic heart disease, now a curable condition.
</P>
<P>
   The first episode of ``Talelights'' includes a Maine woman (the
daughter of the woman with Alzheimer's) talking about her abusive
husband. Although she agrees on camera to let Schadler (who
hitchhikes in order to meet subjects) film her, her narrative has
the distasteful confessional quality of a segment on ``The Jerry
Springer Show.'' What this show seems to lack, and ``First Person''
has in abundance, is an attempt to understand the subjects on
screen and to suggest a certain universality of need if not of
action.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `TALELIGHTS' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Thursday on Bravo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `FIRST PERSON` &QL;
</P>
<P>
   10:30 p.m. Thursday on Bravo &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1700EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2231 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MURRAY-COLUMN0301-COX     02-29 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN0301-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: Bonnie and Clyde, cemeteries and
chicken-fried steak
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I stopped off the other day in a small Southern town, just
inside the East Texas border, to visit an old friend who runs the
local daily.
</P>
<P>
   The stories that a small town has.
</P>
<P>
   The stories that a small-town editor can tell.
</P>
<P>
   We went for lunch at the place where most everybody goes for
lunch. My friend allowed that he hoped we were in time, that they
hadn't run out of food yet.
</P>
<P>
   I checked my watch. It was a few minutes after 12 noon. Surely,
I told him, we're not too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' he said. ``Folks started lining up as early
as half an hour before the doors open. It's that good.''
</P>
<P>
   It was that good: chicken-fried steak, three choices of
vegetables (I had peas and rice and turnip greens), cornbread, hot
rolls and a slice of chocolate pie. The bill for both of us for
less than $14, tax included.
</P>
<P>
   The stories were free.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's Mr. So-in-so,'' the editor said, nodding and smiling.
``How-do, Mr. So-in-so,'' he spoke up across the room, loudly.
</P>
<P>
   Then he continued in a quieter voice, just for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. So-in-so's claim to fame is that Bonnie and Clyde once
stole his car, and that was the car they were driving when they
were ambushed and killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. So-in-so, I further learned, is still driving himself at a
somewhat advanced age. Speculation is that he may have lived to
become a greater menace than Bonnie and Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all look out when we see him coming,'' the editor said.
</P>
<P>
   It's politicking time, I was told, and the hot local race is the
sheriff's election.
</P>
<P>
   The incumbent, it seems, had been dressing up in the disguise of
a homeless person, going around town begging money.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, it all came to light when a misunderstanding of
sorts developed and the cops were called, only to discover that the
homeless man was, indeed, their own high sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   He later explained that it was research for a book on sociology
that he's doing. Obviously, he's not you're average, everyday,
downhome, small-town Texas sheriff.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the editorial house. That's the name my friend
the editor has given it.
</P>
<P>
   This is small, white frame house, a few blocks or so from
downtown, where the owner expresses his views in red writing neatly
painted in letters several inches tall along the front of his home.
</P>
<P>
   When he runs out of room _ evidently, he never runs out of
opinions _ he repaints the house white and starts over.
</P>
<P>
   I should have taken better notes, but the only comment I recall
was something to the effect that every time LBJ ran for office he
promised women and minorities everything there was to promise.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the editor insisted that I see their cemetery. I say
``their.'' But it's not everybody's. As the sign at the gate notes,
you have to be ``sanctioned'' to be buried there.
</P>
<P>
   In small Southern towns, not even death puts folks on equal
terms.
</P>
<P>
   I was fascinated by the cemetery's speculator statuary, most
particularly a larger than life-size weeping angel perched atop the
grave of a young man _ ``the only son,'' we are told in hard, cold
marble _ who died in his early 30s down in Mexico, a short time
into the 20th Century.
</P>
<P>
   The editor didn't know that story. But I'd like to think Pancho
Villa was somehow involved. It would fit well with the one about
Bonnie and Clyde.
</P>
<P>
   (P.S. I have to wonder what ``sanctioned'' involves for joining
a cemetery. If it's a vote of the members, that's the kind of
election ol' Lyndon could have appreciated.)
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)Lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
