<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PROKOFIEV-OPERA-2TAKE     02-29 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROKOFIEV-OPERA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY HOVERS DARKLY OVER PARIS OPERA'S `WAR AND PEACE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ At the final dress rehearsal of the Paris Opera's new
production of ``War and Peace'' in February, some guests were
evidently piqued by Prokofiev's _ and before him Tolstoy's _ take
on the French invasion of Russia in 1812. The portrayal of Napoleon
as a buffoon and French troops as savages proved too much. At the
curtain call, hearty cheers for Napoleon turned to boos for Marshal
Kutuzov, the Russian general who drove out the French.
</P>
<P>
   Were Parisians really closing ranks around the humbled emperor?
Or were they simply like children heckling the wicked witch in a
pantomime?
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a joke,'' said Francesca Zambello, the American who
directed the lavish production, ``a sort of joke.'' Indeed, on
opening night _ in a rare display of unanimity by the Paris Opera's
fickle public _ singers, director, designer, conductor and
orchestra were all given an ovation. And yet it is a measure of the
political force of ``War and Peace'' _ or at least of the second,
``war'' half of the opera _ that it cannot only stir ghosts from
the past but also mirror events of today. Le Monde's critic, for
instance, still saw a ``great anti-French epic'' unfolding at the
Bastille Opera. And it was Hitler's invasion of the Soviet Union in
1941 that inspired Prokofiev to adapt Tolstoy's 19th-century
masterpiece, so Stalin could also be imagined hovering over
Kutuzov.
</P>
<P>
   During the scene showing the fall of Moscow _ with French
soldiers committing atrocities and Russian civilians fleeing with
their meager belongings _ it was hard not to be reminded of recent
events in the Balkans and Chechnya, with the twist that Russian
nationalism, mobilized onstage to defend the motherland, is today
supporting a military offensive in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was asked why I hadn't made the production contemporary,''
Zambello said in an interview. ``You only need to watch television.
People can draw the parallels between 1812, 1941 to 1944 and 2000.
Of course two years ago we didn't known Chechnya would be
happening, but it was a conscious decision not to update the
opera.''
</P>
<P>
   A less obvious contemporary dimension is provided by the cast.
In 1990 Zambello directed ``War and Peace'' in Seattle with a
half-American and half-Russian cast. This time most of the singers
are Russian, and all but two of them are performing the opera for
the first time. And many, it seems, are discovering the work
through the prism of Russia's complex transition to democracy,
including the rise to power of its acting president, Vladimir
Putin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten years ago, many of the Russians were in the West for the
first time, and the Soviet experience was very present,'' recalled
Zambello, a 42-year-old New Yorker. ``Now many have Western
careers, some live in the West, so they're straddling the Soviet
Union, Russia and the West. And it's hard for them to ignore what's
happening in Moscow. Some worry there is now a warmonger in the
Kremlin. Two members of the opera chorus are from Chechnya. They
said Putin is like Kutuzov. I said he's more like Napoleon.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Caucasus politics were hardly the reason that Hugues
Gall, the director of the Paris Opera, chose to present this rarely
performed opera. ``I thought, what are we going to do for this
stupid year 2000?'' he said. ``Let's do something special,
something you don't always do. This is the biggest thing we've
done. It's probably the biggest opera ever written.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now ``War and Peace'' had never been put on by the Paris
Opera, and it had been staged only once in Paris, at the Theatre
des Champs-Elysees in 1986, in a Bulgarian National Opera
production directed by the Russian Boris Pokrovsky. A major figure
in the history of Prokofiev's ``War and Peace,'' Pokrovsky was the
first to present all 13 scenes of the two-act opera, at the Bolshoi
Theater in Moscow in 1959, six years after the composer's death. He
was also the first to present the opera at La Scala in Milan, in
1964, and at the Metropolitan Opera in New York, in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   It is not too surprising that ``War and Peace'' was infrequently
performed in the West during the Cold War: not everyone had an
appetite for bombastic Soviet propaganda disguised as hymns of
glory to the Russian people. But there was another reason. With 72
singing roles and huge battle scenes inspired by Prokofiev's love
of cinema (he was a close friend of Eisenstein and wrote the music
for ``Alexander Nevsky'') the opera is immensely expensive to put
on.
</P>
<P>
   The composer would not have been disappointed by the Paris
Opera's production. Even with the overture dropped and about 25
minutes cut from the second half, this is still an ambitious
enterprise, running more than four hours, including intermission,
and costing close to $4 million for the seven performances through
March 11 and seven more scheduled for fall with the same cast.
</P>
<P>
   For the 62 singing roles that survived the cuts, no fewer than
45 singers were hired, most of them Russians making their debuts at
the Paris Opera. (Two of the male lead roles are sung by Americans,
Nathan Gunn and Robert Brubaker.) To the opera's 100-member chorus
were added some 150 extras, many of whom alternated between playing
Russian and French soldiers. And to make them look their parts, the
opera house made 735 costumes and 450 wigs. Both armies were also
well equipped, with dozens of rifles and no fewer than 16 cannons
between them.
</P>
<P>
   One challenge posed by this opera is that it is effectively two
operas: peace and war. The first half, in which Zambello and her
British designer, John MacFarlane, used sliding walls to create
different domestic interiors, is essentially a love story in which
Natasha Rostova (sung to much acclaim by the 28-year-old Russian
soprano Olga Gouriakova) is prevented from marrying her first love,
Andrei Bolkowski ( Gunn) and ends up falling for the ne'er-do-well
Anatole Kuragin (Stefan Margita), to the dismay of Pierre Bezukhov
(Brubaker).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the seven scenes of Act I Prokofiev evidently also felt free
to be lyrical as he follows Natasha's emotional helter-skelter,
with only the act's final chorus, announcing Napoleon's invasion of
Russia, anticipating the nationalist frenzy that follows. (
Zambello and the French-Israeli conductor, Gary Bertini, moved this
chorus from the beginning of Act I, but the change works well.) Act
II, however, caused the composer endless headaches as he tried to
satisfy the Soviet cultural authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Having left Russia at age 26 at the time of the October
Revolution to wander the United States and Europe, Prokofiev
visited Moscow in 1927 and finally settled there in 1936. Three
years later he abandoned his wife, Lina, for a young Communist
Party militant, Myra Mendelssohn, who later helped him write the
libretto to ``War and Peace.'' He began work on the opera in August
1941, and in April of the following year he sent 11 scenes, six for
peace and five for war, for official approval.
</P>
<P>
   The response from the Committee for Artistic Affairs was
negative, and he was invited to be more lyrical and to give greater
emphasis to the role of the Russian people. Prokofiev made
revisions, adding a scene to Act I. And eventually, thanks to
friends, the first eight scenes were staged in 1945. Yet when Act
II was presented in 1947, the authorities banned the work after
just one performance. The opera lacked heroism and patriotism,
Prokofiev was told. By the time he died in 1953 (one day before
Stalin), he had never seen a performance of the entire opera.
</P>
<P>
   With today's eyes, Act II seems drenched in heroism and
patriotism. In the Paris Opera production a dramatic back curtain
of dark clouds and splashes of light changes color to suit the mood
of the story as Kutuzov (Anatoly Kotcherga) prepares his soldiers
for war, Napoleon (Vasily Gerello) appears on the battlefield of
Borodino, Moscow is occupied and burned, Natasha finds the dying
Andrei, and finally Napoleon's dejected and humiliated troops
retreat.
</P>
<P>
   French critics singled out Zambello's command of her own army of
singers and extras as she led them in battles and forced marches:
at one point, almost 300 people are on stage. ``Francesca Zambello
takes us to the center of the horrors of war,'' Le Figaro's music
critic, Pierre-Petit, wrote. ``Cannons are dragged onstage, torches
blaze, people run, are wounded, are killed. We're even shown
summary executions carried out against tottering walls.''
</P>
<P>
   Zambello, who has already demonstrated her ability to direct
large crowds in ``Billy Budd,'' said that in some ways Act I was
more difficult. ``In war you are the general of the battlefield,''
she said. ``In peace you're trying to squeeze 1,500 pages of
Tolstoy into eight minutes and make the characters resonate even
though you won't see them for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if ``War and Peace,'' too, tended to vanish from sight
for long stretches after each production (the last in the United
States was in San Francisco in 1991), that now appears to be
changing, thanks not only to the Paris Opera. A new co-production
of the work by the Kirov Opera and the Metropolitan Opera is to
open in St. Petersburg on March 11, will travel to Covent Garden in
London in July and to La Scala in September. It is scheduled to
reach the Met in the 2001-02 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
