<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THIEF-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     02-29 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THIEF-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ALONE' AND `THE LITTLE THIEF': SCHOOL OF HARD KNOCKS AND ITS
GRADUATE PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end) 
(jt) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For Amelie and Esse (or ``S''), life is about to go
from not very good to far worse.
</P>
<P>
   Amelie and Esse are, respectively, the protagonists of ``Alone''
and ``The Little Thief,'' two absorbing, meticulously observed
studies of rootless youth fueled by rebelliousness, anger and
anomie in a double bill by Erick Zonca that plays for two weeks
beginning Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Zonca is the same French-born filmmaker whose debut film,
``Dreamlife of Angels,'' about two young Frenchwomen adrift, won
best actress honors for its stars at the Cannes International Film
Festival and further acclaim when it was shown as the concluding
film in the New York Film festival in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alone,'' which takes only 34 minutes to track Amelie's descent
from rejection in a tryout as a waitress to desperado to police
prisoner, was filmed before ``Dreamlife of Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   Made after ``Dreamlife,'' ``The Little Thief,'' to which
``Alone'' compares as a short story does to a novella, takes 65
minutes to map Esse's route from apprentice baker in Orleans to
apprentice gangster in Marseille and back to apprentice baker.
</P>
<P>
   In neither film does Zonca's subject utter more than a few
words, but his gift lies in an eloquent choice of detail as he
tells his stories through the eyes of his quietly expressive
actors.
</P>
<P>
   Amelie (Florence Loiret), criticized for her clothes, her talk
and her attitude, loses her waitress' job as soon as she arrives
late for work one day. A dispute with her landlord, she explains to
her boss. ``You better change everything,'' he advises, handing her
a few hundred francs. She goes home to discover that new tenants
are occupying her apartment, and that the landlord intends to keep
most of her belongings until she pays him several thousand francs
in back rent.
</P>
<P>
   As Amelie sits disconsolate in a rear yard, a commotion in an
apartment above directs her eyes upward. A young man, clearly
besieged by the authorities, reaches out the window and tries to
hide an automatic pistol by balancing it on a drainpipe. The weapon
falls beside Amelie, who picks it up and goes on her way.
</P>
<P>
   Her impulse is to seek an honest living. With little to offer,
she meets with scant success. She tries in vain to learn to beg.
The only apparent friend she makes steals what is left of her
belongings, except for the pistol. Hungry, alone, forlorn,
increasingly desperate, Amelie decides to put the weapon to use.
</P>
<P>
   Like Amelie, Esse (Nicolas Duvauchelle) loses his job and his
living quarters when he turns up late at the outset of ``The Little
Thief'' and is told he is bound for trouble. Unlike her, he is
dismissive and defiant.
</P>
<P>
   Esse tells his girlfriend, Sandra (Emilie Lafarge), he doesn't
intend to be anyone's slave. Rather than be a victim, he'll take
advantage of others. Sandra asks him what he intends to be, a
gangster?
</P>
<P>
   That night, after sleeping with Sandra, Esse steals her pay
envelope and when next seen is the apprentice in a Marseille gang
that specializes in burglary, prostitution and waterfront theft.
</P>
<P>
   As the newcomer, Esse's duties include participation in
burglaries, keeping an eye on a prostitute, occasionally driving
for the big boss and tending to an ailing elderly woman who turns
out to be the mother of his immediate boss, Sylvain, also known as
the Eye (Jean-Jerome Esposito).
</P>
<P>
   In time, in the boxing club that the Eye introduces him to, and
far more brutally in the conduct of the gang, Esse will discover
that he is not such a tough guy after all. Perhaps he can cheat
death, but for him, and for Amelie, destiny is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE LITTLE THIEF' Directed by Erick Zonca; written (in French,
with English subtitles) by Zonca and Virginie Wagon; directors of
photography, Pierre Milon and Catherine Pujol; edited by
Jean-Robert Thomann; production designer, Kristina Zonca; produced
by Pierre Chevalier; released by New Yorker Films. Running time: 65
minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Nicolas Duvauchelle (``S''), Yann Tregouet (Barruet),
Jean-Jerome Esposito (The Eye), Martial Bezot (Chacal) and Emilie
Lafarge (Sandra).
</P>
<P>
   `ALONE'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Erick Zonca; in French, with English
subtitles; director of photography, Pascal Poucet; edited by Jean
Robert Thomann; released by New Yorker Films. Running time: 34
minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Florence Loiret (Amelie) and Veronique Octon (Sophie).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
