<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2241 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-VIETNAM-BOOK-REVIEW-N     02-29 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AUTHENTIC VIETNAMESE COOKING': BASIC VIETNAMESE COOKING AS A
CULINARY CROSSROADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The story of Corinne Trang's family personifies the story of
Vietnam. And so her book, ``Authentic Vietnamese Cooking'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, $30), not only serves as a good introduction to the
cuisine, but also gives a sense of how the country's history has
shaped its food.
</P>
<P>
   Trang's father, grandparents and aunts and uncles lived in
China, Cambodia and Vietnam, ``moving from place to place, country
to country, and culture to culture'' to avoid political turmoil,
she writes. She was born and raised in France _ her mother is
French _ and traveled to Asia as a child and as an adult both
before and after settling in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Some of this personal history is outlined in a short but lovely
preface, replete with vintage black-and-white pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Trang points out that Vietnam has long been a culinary
crossroads, a cuisine influenced by French, Chinese, Cambodian,
Thai, Indian, Russian and even American tastes. And yet, Vietnamese
cooking is usually quite simple. All those influences of traders
and invaders did not catapult the cuisine into the ranks of the
world's greatest, especially compared with Thai or Chinese cooking.
Nevertheless, they made it more interesting than the cuisines of
many other small countries.
</P>
<P>
   What make the cuisine lively and appealing are the frequently
appearing flavors of garlic, ginger, scallion, lemongrass, soy,
fish sauce (called nuoc mam here, nam pla in Thailand) and a
plethora of fresh herbs, especially mint, Thai basil and cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks at least in part to the French influence, Vietnamese
cooking can also be quite subtle, and Trang's recipes largely
capture those subtleties. They call for small amounts of assertive
flavors _ though chilies are used in many dishes, fiery food is
rarely served in Vietnam _ and combine them to create synergies
that are not only complex but even mysterious.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes originated with Trang's Vietnamese relatives and
friends and, she writes, are all from the ``family table.'' In
Vietnam as in many Third World countries, home and restaurant
cooking are closely linked. The exception is pho, the staple daily
soup, a rich broth loaded with noodles, a couple of kinds of meat,
an assortment of vegetables and sometimes tofu; it is easier for
restaurants to make.
</P>
<P>
   The hundred or so recipes in Trang's book feel unified, and many
confusing techniques are simplified. Generally, the recipes are
accurate and written with reasonable clarity, and the attractive
design enhances the book's overall usefulness _ although older
cooks might wish that a larger type had been used for the recipe
directions.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe selection is representative of basic Vietnamese
cooking, and little has been left out: there are a couple of rice
porridges, three classic phos, braised fish in caramel sauce and a
classic duck recipe called laque. There are surprises as well, like
a braised pork shank in coconut juice.
</P>
<P>
   But I was disappointed that the book didn't go further. A
section on frogs and snails contains no snail recipes and only two
obvious recipes for frogs' legs. The poultry chapter contains only
seven recipes _ after five pages of introductory text _ and again
they are the most obvious choices. Worse, two of them are virtually
identical save for the main ingredient and roasting time.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly one could expect a little more range in a 250-page,
$30 book. If you already own a good Vietnamese cookbook, like
Nicole Routhier's ``Foods of Vietnam'' (Stewart, Tabori &AMP; Chang,
1989), you may find ``Authentic Vietnamese Cooking'' superfluous.
If you do not, it's a good starting place. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LAQUE DUCK &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Authentic Vietnamese Cooking'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 90 minutes, plus 24 hours' marination  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup nuoc mam
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon thick soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons five-spice powder
</P>
<P>
   1 5-pound duck
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces ginger, peeled, cut into 4 slices and lightly crushed
</P>
<P>
   4 scallions, trimmed, halved crosswise, and lightly crushed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Whisk together nuoc mam, soy sauce, honey and five-spice
powder in a broad, deep dish. Carefully loosen skin of the duck by
gently running your fingers between the skin and the meat, trying
not to tear the skin; you may need a paring knife at first.
</P>
<P>
   2. Place the duck in the dish and rub the marinade over it,
inside and out and between the flesh and the skin. Drain and
refrigerate the duck, uncovered, for 24 hours, turning
occasionally.
</P>
<P>
   3. Preheat the oven to 425 degrees. Place the ginger and
scallions inside the duck, then truss it. Use a metal skewer to
poke the skin all over. Place the duck, with the breast side down,
on a rack in a roasting pan and roast for 45 minutes, basting every
15 minutes with the drippings. Turn the duck breast side up and
continue roasting, still basting every 15 minutes, until the juices
run clear, about 45 minutes more. Carve and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 to 3 servings as a main course.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
