<SLUG> BC-SECRET-TUNA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: Tuna Tartar Keeps Diners Coming Back   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Tuna tartare, a mix of chopped raw fish and
seasonings, has become a popular appetizer at trendy restaurants.
In many cases, the chefs add so much to the fish that its delicacy
is obliterated, but this version by Scott Newman at Rubicon is
different. It's as pared down as the restaurant's handsome
interior.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Newman's recipe includes only a few complementary ingredients _
radish, shallots and ginger _ that accentuate the tuna, rather than
mask it. The soy vinaigrette consists of only two other elements _
lemon and olive oil _ to balance the salty liquid. This dish is so
good that it has become one of the most popular at the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Rubicon has won raves for its food but it has garnered as much
publicity for its celebrity owners _ Robert De Niro and Robin
Williams, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The interior is the epitome of urban sophistication _ thick
brick walls and black metal earthquake beams are paired with
refined mahogany and starched white linens.
</P>
<P>
   Rubicon also has a great wine list and the country's best
sommelier, Larry Stone. Clearly, the restaurant is at the top of
its game.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Rubicon, 558 Sacramento (near Montgomery), San Francisco;
(415) &LR;   &LR; 434-4100. Lunch weekdays, dinner Monday-Saturday.cq &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
SECRETS OF SUCCESS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Selecting the tuna. &LR;  We all like a bargain but the best fresh
tuna is never cheap. Don't skimp on the quality or the taste and
texture will be inferior.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ A sharp knife. &LR;  A good edge is essential to get a clean cut
on the tuna. A dull knife will mash and tear the flesh, destroying
the texture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TUNA TARTARE WITH SOY VINAIGRETTE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound top-quality fresh tuna, cut into 1/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches scallions, trimmed and thinly sliced (white part and
as much of the green as you like)
</P>
<P>
   Leaves from 1 bunch cilantro, cut into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   3 shallots, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   6 radishes, finely julienned
</P>
<P>
   1 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Salt and finely ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 package (1 ounce) daikon sprouts
</P>
<P>
   Toast points
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Place the tuna in a large bowl. Add the scallions, cilantro,
shallots, ginger and half of the julienned radishes; stir gently to
combine.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together the olive oil, soy sauce and lemon juice until
well blended. Stir half of this vinaigrette into the tuna mixture,
then season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkle a serving platter with the remaining radishes and the
daikon sprouts. Gently form the tartare mixture into a mound and
place in the center of the platter. Drizzle the remaining
vinaigrette over the tartare and serve with toast points.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 660 calories, &LR;   &LR; 30 g protein, 13 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 56 g fat (8 g saturated), 51 mg cholesterol, 1,081
mg sodium, 2 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
