<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2246 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WORKING-SFCHRON &LR;      02-29 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 THE WORKING COOK: Diners Join the Party by Building Their Own 
 Tacos   By Tara Duggan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  My family claims no Mexican heritage, but at
gatherings my uncle Brent often tells stories of how he used
cranked out a taco or two a minute when he worked in a Lake Tahoe
snack stand during his summer vacations.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes we still get to have taco night when we visit him.
He's still fast, which means the fried tortillas are crispy and hot
when they get to the table. Inside is piquant ground beef, shredded
cheese and cool, crisp lettuce. As you pick them up, hot, spicy oil
dribbles down your wrists. Delicious!
</P>
<P>
   This week's 30-Minute Main Dish _ Shrimp Tacos with Black Pepper
Slaw _ is my Y2K version of the the now all-American taco. Golden
tortillas wrap up cool green cabbage slaw, rosy shrimp and bright
orange mango salsa. The slaw, with its rush of lime juice and fresh
ground pepper, is an appealing counterpoint to the sweet, garlicky
shrimp and fruity salsa. The best part is when you bring all the
components to the table and everyone builds their own tacos.
</P>
<P>
   In the Fast &AMP; Fresh recipe _ Pork Chops With Polenta and
Balsamic Reduction _ the reduced vinegar makes a simple but
complex-tasting sauce that works particularly well with pork.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared polenta may not have the satisfyingly creamy texture of
homemade, but a few minutes under the broiler turns it into a fine
side dish for the pork and a delectable sponge for the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The Now &AMP; Later recipe _ Bread Soup With Garlic and Wilted
Greens _ is a hearty vegetarian soup that takes little time to
make. The wilted cabbage and kale enrich the savory broth, while
the toasted bread adds texture. Delicate sorrel contributes a hint
of citrus; if sorrel is unavailable, squeeze in some lemon juice.
And the raw garlic rubbed on the toast and infused in the broth
packs a wallop that will lick any winter cold.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   PORK CHOPS WITH POLENTA &AMP; BALSAMIC REDUCTION
</P>
<P>
   If you have a grill pan, use it to broil the pork chops. If not,
leave room for them on the baking sheet and cook next to the
polenta.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 small shallot
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup aged balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup low-salt chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   1 bay leaf
</P>
<P>
   1 (35-ounce) roll prepared polenta (see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper + pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   4 center-cut boneless pork loin chops (about 6 ounces each),
about 3/4 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to broil. Position rack at top of oven with room to
fit a pan under the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Mince the shallot. Melt 1/2 tablespoon of the butter in a small
saucepan. Add the shallot and saute for 1 minute. Add the vinegar,
chicken broth and bay leaf. Bring to a boil, reduce heat to
medium-low and keep at a low boil for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If you're using one, place a grill pan in the oven to heat.
</P>
<P>
   Slice the polenta into eight 1/2-inch-thick rounds (you will
have one third of the roll left). Arrange on a small baking sheet
lined with aluminum foil and place under the broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the salt, pepper and paprika. Season the pork chops
on both sides with this spice mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Flip over the polenta rounds and return to a lower rack of the
oven. Put the pork chops on the hot grill pan and place directly
under the broiler. Broil for 4 minutes, then turn the chops and
broil 1 minute longer. Remove both the polenta and the pork chops
from the oven.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the balsamic reduction from the heat and whisk in the
remaining 11/2 tablespoons butter. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place each pork chop on 2 polenta rounds and drizzle
liberally with sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  You can find prepared polenta in a refrigerated case in
the supermarket. I used Santini brand polenta with good results.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 385 calories, &LR;   &LR; 36 g protein, 4 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 19 g fat (8 g saturated), 118 mg cholesterol, 770 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   SHRIMP TACOS WITH BLACK PEPPER SLAW &AMP; MANGO SALSA
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   6 cups (about 8 ounces) prepared coleslaw mix or thinly shredded
cabbage
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   31/2 tablespoons fresh lime juice (juice of about 11/2 limes) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup + 2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   12 soft corn tortillas
</P>
<P>
   3 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds cleaned and deveined shrimp
</P>
<P>
   Mexican hot sauce or Tabasco sauce to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mango salsa or other fresh fruit salsa
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Toss the coleslaw or cabbage with the pepper and 3 tablespoons
of the lime juice, then season with salt. The slaw should be both
tart and peppery. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1/2 cup oil in a large skillet. Working in batches, quickly
fry the tortillas on both sides until slightly crisp, about 30
seconds each. Fold each tortilla in half and drain on paper towels.
Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the remaining 2 teaspoons oil in a medium skillet over
medium-high heat. Add the garlic and saute for 1 minute. Add the
shrimp and a few dashes of hot sauce; sprinkle with the remaining
1/2 tablespoon lime juice. Cook, stirring frequently, until the
shrimp just begin to curl and turn pink, about 2 to 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place the tortillas, shrimp, slaw and salsa on serving
platters/bowls and let diners ``build'' their own tacos.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 560 calories, &LR;   &LR; 44 g protein, 59 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 19 g fat (2 g saturated), 259 mg cholesterol, 275
mg sodium, 11 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer
</P>
<P>
   BREAD SOUP WITH GARLIC &AMP; WILTED GREENS
</P>
<P>
   To freeze this soup, prepare everything except the bread, sorrel
and Parmesan. Let the soup cool, then cover tightly and freeze.
After defrosting, reheat the soup, stir in the sorrel and cook only
until it wilts. This last-minute touch restores the soup's fresh
flavor. To further enhance the flavor, toast fresh bread and
garnish with freshly grated cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   10 garlic cloves
</P>
<P>
   2 loaves crusty Italian bread, sliced 1/2 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   3 large onions
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil + oil to taste
</P>
<P>
   21/2 pounds potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches kale
</P>
<P>
   4 quarts vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds savoy cabbage
</P>
<P>
   3 cups water
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 bunches sorrel, stemmed, leaves very thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly crush 2 garlic cloves and rub the bread slices with
them. Toast the bread in the preheated oven for 10 minutes on each
side. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Thinly slice the onions; mince the remaining garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large stockpot. Add the onions and saute
over medium heat until lightly caramelized, about 15 minutes. Add
the minced garlic and saute for 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Peel the potatoes and cut into medium dice. Trim off 3 inches
from the stem ends of the kale; cut the leaves into 1/2-inch
ribbons.
</P>
<P>
   Add the stock to the pot and bring to a boil. Add the potatoes
and kale and simmer until just tender, 8 to 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Quarter the savoy cabbage. Remove the core, then thinly slice
the leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Add the cabbage and the water to the soup and bring to a boil.
Reduce heat and simmer until wilted, about 2 to 3 minutes. Season
with salt and pepper. Stir in half of the sorrel and let wilt for 1
minute.
</P>
<P>
   To serve, place a piece of toast in each bowl. Spoon some
Parmesan on the toasts, then ladle in the soup. Top with the
remaining sorrel and a drizzle of olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 260 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 45 g carbohydrate,
5 &LR;   &LR; g fat (1 g saturated), 3 mg cholesterol, 300 mg sodium, 5 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
