<SLUG> BC-POTPOURRI-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 WINE POTPOURRI: California Wine Business Thrives in Spite of 
 Protests   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  North Coast wineries and grape growers are under
attack from a variety of people who claim that grape growing is
ruining the environment. The protesters say that new vineyards are
squeezing out other agriculture and that vineyards, in general, are
not very friendly to an already delicate environment.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The protests, which seem to be growing in number, have been
making wine cultivators crazy, but seem to have had little impact
on a healthy California wine economy. According to a recently
released report commissioned by the Wine Institute and the
California Association of Winegrape Growers (CAWG), California wine
is the No.1 finished agricultural product in retail value,
accounting for $33 million in wages, revenues and economic
activity. Independent wine industry consultants, Motto, Kryla &AMP;
Fisher LLP prepared the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report is packed with gee-whiz statistics. For example,
California's wine industry generated an estimated $12.3 billion in
retail sales in the United States in 1998 and another $1.2 billion
in tourism directly related to the wine business. ``California, if
it were a nation, would be the fourth leading wine producer
worldwide,'' the report crows.
</P>
<P>
   Providing some counter-thoughts to the often overwrought
argument of those who see the California wine industry as the evil
empire, is CAWG president Karen Ross.
</P>
<P>
   ``California's wine community is uniquely tied to the land and
natural resources of this state. Vineyards represent a long-term
commitment with a significant statewide investment mainly by
families and family-owned corporations,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   California also led the nation in retail wine sales in 1998 with
$2.6 billion, followed by New York, Florida, Texas and Illinois.
Nevada and the District of Columbia, long believed to be major wine
markets, are 23rd and 33rd respectively in retail wine sales.
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of the wine industry report is a look at
wine grape acreage, prices and yield trends since 1990 by Richard
Cartiere in his Wine Market Report, released at the California
Grape Crush Report Forum last month.
</P>
<P>
   Cartiere says that approximately 250,000 acres were newly
planted and redeveloped since the spring of 1990 and that the
investment is conservatively estimated to reach $5 billion in the
first half of 2000. He predicts that wine grape acreage should
reach 530,000 acres, up 60 percent since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Wine Q &AMP; A
</P>
<P>
   _ Sasikala Devi of McKinleyville, enjoyed the recent piece on
Chartreuse, maintaining that the liqueur is best served neat and at
room temperature. She also wondered about a special bottling of
Chartreuse labeled V.E.P. Vieillissement Exceptionnellement
Prolong &LR; e &LR;  (VEP) loosely means ``extra (prolonged) aging in wood
vats.'' Chartreuse V.E.P. is aged 12 years in wood and is available
in both original yellow and green at $103, compared to the regular
bottling for $45.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Duca of San Francisco, wanted to know why recent
coverage of Italian wines only mentioned the wines of Piedmont and
Tuscany, and not the value wines from Sicily and other lesser known
Italian wine regions. Good point. Sicily has a reputation among
Americans, but it isn't about Sicilian wines. Keep reading, Sicily
is slotted in as a subject for a future Wine Potpourri.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1725EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
