<HEADER>
A2248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-INTERNET-TAXES01-COX     02-29 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-TAXES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOVERNORS PONDERING A BAN ON ALL SALES TAXES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nation's governors overwhelmingly agree that
every retail sale, whether made in a mall or on line, should get
equal tax treatment. But achieving such fairness may mean
eliminating all sales taxes, Gov. Michael Leavitt, R-Utah, said
Tuesday at the close of the National Governors' Association
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four out of five governors believe we have to move to a level
playing field'' rather than leave Main Street merchants at a tax
disadvantage, said Leavitt, who chairs the bipartisan organization.
That could mean either imposing taxes on Internet purchases or
radically restructuring state finances to wipe all sales taxes, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, governors want to retain the power to set sales
tax policy, he said. Currently, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., is
pushing a plan to have Congress pre-empt states with a permanent
ban on taxes on Internet sales.
</P>
<P>
   After a private meeting with most members of the Senate, the
governors emerged with no consensus on taxes. But a decision must
be made within two years or ``the opportunity will be lost'' amid
the frenzied growth of electronic commerce, Leavitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The governors' association is now backing away from its own
proposal, which recommended state governments create a ``trusted
third party'' to collect and remit sales taxes on Internet
purchases. During their meeting, the governors realized that any
plan creating another bureaucracy would not survive, Leavitt said.
</P>
<P>
   But the possibility of eliminating all sales taxes remains on
the table, he said. Such a change would be wrenching for the 45
states that now collect them. Sales taxes provide one-third to
one-half of revenues for most states and local governments, raising
more than $150 billion each year.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, states require brick-and-mortar retailers to collect
taxes on purchases. But online and mail-order merchants collect
taxes only from customers who live in the same state. ``Remote
sales,'' made to residents of states where the merchants have no
operations, generally escape taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Governors are worried about the shift to electronic commerce,
which now amounts to about $20 billion a year. If Internet sales
continue tripling every year as they have been, states will be
losing about $10.8 billion annually by 2003, according to a recent
study by the University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The governors also discussed the problem Monday with President
Clinton, who urged them to move quickly. Otherwise, shoppers will
grow so accustomed to tax-free shopping on the Internet that
governors will find it politically impossible to begin imposing
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But while most governors want a uniform tax system that treats
all purchases alike, a few object, saying they don't want to
threaten the economy's ``golden goose.'' Gov. James Gilmore, R-Va.,
says the Internet's fantastic growth has created so many jobs in
his state that revenues from income and property taxes are soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes, D-Ga., left the gathering unpersuaded that
swift action, either by Congress or state legislatures, is
necessary because the Internet economy is still fragile. ``We don't
want to stop the growth of the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NGA vice chairman Gov. Parris Glendening, D-Md., said that while
the sales tax question is unsettled, all governors agree Internet
access should not be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gilmore and Leavitt are among the 19 members of the
congressionally appointed Advisory Commission on Electronic
Commerce. That group, composed of federal, state, business and
consumer leaders, is studying the Internet tax question and is due
to send recommendations to Congress by April 21.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, a nationwide moratorium is in effect, blocking taxes
aimed specifically at the Internet until October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is likely to extend that moratorium for perhaps two
years to allow more time for debate. Leavitt said most governors
would not object to such an extension.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1725EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
