<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CITADEL-BOOK-REVIEW-N     02-29 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITADEL-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GLORY'S SHADOW': INVADING A CITADEL OF HOSTILE ATTITUDES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(Maureen Corrigan is the book critic for the National Public Radio
program ``Fresh Air.'' She teaches literature at Georgetown
University.) 
(DW) 
 By MAUREEN CORRIGAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's probably safe to say that many feminists, myself included,
gave Shannon Faulkner the same kind of grimacing endorsement that
we would accord to, say, prostitutes. We supported Faulkner's right
to be what she wanted to be: the first female cadet to attend the
Citadel, the all-male, publicly-financed military college in
Charleston, S.C. At the same time, we wondered why on earth anyone
would want to pursue such a unpalatable vocation in the first
place. After all, the Citadel has figured in the post-1960s
American popular imagination as an anachronistic and deeply weird
place: a haven for young men who read ``The Lord of the Flies'' in
high school and thought that Piggy deserved what he got.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, the year Faulkner breached the Citadel's confines,
enrollment had diminished so drastically that the corps of cadets
might have been expected to welcome just about any able-bodied
applicant _ even a woman _ who would plump up their numbers. But,
as Catherine S. Manegold recounts in her new book, ``In Glory's
Shadow,'' during Faulkner's three-year legal battle to gain
admission, she was subjected to death threats, obscenities (some
spray-painted on her parents' house), and lesser attacks, like
being dubbed ``the divine bovine'' in the school newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The years of harassment and the looming prospect of being one
woman isolated among nearly 2,000 mostly angry men eventually took
their toll. The summer before Faulkner entered the Citadel,
Manegold discloses, she asked her mother to make an appointment for
her with a gynecologist. If she was raped, Faulkner explained, she
didn't want to become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Faulkner spent most of her few days as a cadet in the infirmary;
when, stressed to the breaking point, she left the Citadel, cadets
gathered near the gates to sing ``Hey, hey, the witch is dead!''
Others flexed their muscles in unison.
</P>
<P>
   ``An odd truth lay hidden deep within'' the Citadel men's rage,
writes Manegold, a former reporter for The New York Times. ``Their
passion and their persistence grew not from what they wanted to
preserve but from what they knew they had already lost.''
</P>
<P>
   This is only one of the elegantly astute passages in the book,
which chronicles not only Faulkner's legal struggle (which
ultimately wound up in the Supreme Court) but also the intricate
social and psychological history of the Citadel from its founding
in 1842 to its flailing at the advent of Faulkner and the women
cadets who would succeed her.
</P>
<P>
   Manegold covered Faulkner's story for The Times, and most of her
insights in ``In Glory's Shadow'' are smart and informed.
Sometimes, though she gets a little too giddy at the prospect of
breaking loose from her reporter's rigor and indulges in the kind
of grandiose game of connect-the-dots between historical context
and individual lives that literary critics like Stanley Fish have
bemoaned as the flaw of modern biographies in particular. Here is
how the author introduces Faulkner's lead lawyer, Valorie Vojdik:
</P>
<P>
   ``Vojdik was four when the Tonkin Gulf resolution was signed,
the same year that Stanley Kubrik's `Dr. Strangelove' mocked a
military mind-set gone berserk.'' She was ``14 when the House
Judiciary Committee recommended that the president be impeached.
... Against that backdrop of war and political turmoil, Vojdik
learned early that nothing was quite fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   Well maybe or maybe not. Other kids who grew up during that same
period went on to join the Young Americans for Freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Those occasional lapses of analytic prudence aside, the years of
research and interviews Manegold conducted while covering the
Faulkner story allow her to offer nuanced and sometimes offbeat
readings of the story and the people involved.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, she broaches the interesting theory that a prime
mover behind the Citadel's hostile treatment of Faulkner was the
long-deceased four-star general, Mark Clark, the school's
charismatic president from the mid-1950s to the mid-'60s, during
which time it fought fiercely against racial integration.
</P>
<P>
   As Manegold observes, the cadets who had once been ``Mark
Clark's boys'' (and thus shaped by his diehard traditionalist
attitudes) had become the men running the Citadel by the time
Faulkner applied for admission.
</P>
<P>
   Manegold's rendering of Faulkner herself resists hagiography.
She comes across as a spunky, likable young woman whose initial
application to the Citadel (in which she successfully masked her
gender) was motivated not only by outrage that a publicly financed
school could exclude women but by an impish desire to stir things
up as well. The author points out the irony that Faulkner ``was a
modern teen-ager who did not believe in rote obedience yet chose to
pit herself against an institution that taught it as a religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Manegold's most provocative ``character'' readings
are lavished on the Citadel itself, arguably the principal player
in the Faulkner drama. In the hazings and humiliations that define
the life of a first-year student. She ingeniously perceives a
fascination with a pre-Civil War paradigm of mastery and
subjugation that dates to the school's earliest days. Writing of
the promise of community and the yearning to be tested that lure so
many students to the Citadel, the author says of Shannon and her
classmates: ``They went to find their way, as though old maps could
help them navigate in a new world.''
</P>
<P>
   In her engrossing book, Manegold helps skeptical readers like me
understand, at least somewhat, why Faulkner fought so hard to get
into the Citadel; she also makes us understand why, once she made
it inside the walls, Faulkner would use the last reserves of her
strength to turn around and bolt.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `IN GLORY'S SHADOW'
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Faulkner, the Citadel and a Changing America
</P>
<P>
   By Catherine S. Manegold
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 330 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $26.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1725EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0251 </DOCNO>
