which now amounts to about $20 billion a year. If Internet sales
continue tripling every year as they have been, states will be
losing about $10.8 billion annually by 2003, according to a recent
study by the University of Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   The governors also discussed the problem Monday with President
Clinton, who urged them to move quickly. Otherwise, shoppers will
grow so accustomed to tax-free shopping on the Internet that
governors will find it politically impossible to begin imposing
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But while most governors want a uniform tax system that treats
all purchases alike, a few object, saying they don't want to
threaten the economy's ``golden goose.'' Gov. James Gilmore, R-Va.,
says the Internet's fantastic growth has created so many jobs in
his state that revenues from income and property taxes are soaring.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes, D-Ga., left the gathering unpersuaded that
swift action, either by Congress or state legislatures, is
necessary because the Internet economy is still fragile. ``We don't
want to stop the growth of the Internet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   NGA vice chairman Gov. Parris Glendening, D-Md., said that while
the sales tax question is unsettled, all governors agree Internet
access should not be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gilmore and Leavitt are among the 19 members of the
congressionally appointed Advisory Commission on Electronic
Commerce. That group, composed of federal, state, business and
consumer leaders, is studying the Internet tax question and is due
to send recommendations to Congress by April 21.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, a nationwide moratorium is in effect, blocking taxes
aimed specifically at the Internet until October 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is likely to extend that moratorium for perhaps two
years to allow more time for debate. Leavitt said most governors
would not object to such an extension.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Geewax's e-mail address is marilyng(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
