<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 LEARNING TO COOK: Rich Bavarian Cream Garners Raves   By Marion Cunningham  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; If you learn to make this Bavarian Cream, you
really don't need many more dessert recipes. This dish gets raves
every time it's served.
<P>
   It can be designed to suit whatever season you wish. Serve it
with berries, soft stone fruits or _ my favorite _ a simple rich
butterscotch sauce.
</P>
<P>
   The sauce keeps indefinitely in a covered jar in the
refrigerator and it, too, has some versatility. Serve it over
poached pears or baked bananas, or just over a scoop of ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; BAVARIAN CREAM
</P>
<P>
   This gelatin-based custard must be made several hours before you
plan to serve it. It's great paired with cut-up fresh strawberries,
or a mixture of fruit _ or with a rich butterscotch sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 envelope unflavored gelatin
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cold water
</P>
<P>
   4 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Preparing the gelatin: &LR;  Sprinkle the gelatin over the cold
water; stir to blend. Set aside to soften for 5 minutes. (It won't
hurt to let it sit longer.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mixing the ingredients: &LR;  Put the yolks in a bowl and, using a
whisk or fork, stir briskly to blend. Slowly add the sugar and
continue to stir until well mixed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cooking the custard: &LR;  Pour the milk into a saucepan and place
over medium-high heat. Stand right by the stove and watch for tiny
milk bubbles to form around the edge of the pan. The milk should be
hot, but not boiling. It is better to underheat than to boil. As
long as the milk is hot it will work fine.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the yolk/sugar mixture into the hot milk, then add the
softened gelatin and stir with a large spoon or whisk to blend
well. Cook, stirring slowly, but constantly for 3 or 4 minutes.
Tilt the pan until you can see the bottom. If there is a thin coat
of custard on the bottom that doesn't flow as readily as the rest,
it's ready. Remove from heat. Do  &LR; not &LR;  let the custard boil; it
will be fine if you remove it too soon rather that too late.
</P>
<P>
   Stir in the vanilla. Pour the custard into a bowl and
refrigerate for 30 minutes, or just long enough for it to begin to
gel. It should be thick but pourable.
</P>
<P>
   This last step is the secret of a fabulous Bavarian Cream: Beat
the cream only until it holds soft peaks. If the cream is too
stiff, the dessert will be too firm. Fold the whipped cream into
the custard. Spoon into a 2-quart mold or bowl, cover with plastic
wrap or a lid and refrigerate several hours, to allow the dessert
to gel.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bavarian Cream is in a mold, turn it out onto a plate
before serving. Otherwise, spoon into dessert bowls.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 5 or 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 310 calories, &LR;   &LR; 5 g protein, 28 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 20 g fat (11 g saturated), 201 mg cholesterol, 42 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RICH BUTTERSCOTCH SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the sugar, butter and cream in a small, heavy saucepan.
Cook over moderate heat, stirring constantly, until the sauce is
melted and smoothly combined.
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat and whisk a little to blend thoroughly. If it
seems a little thicker than desired, thin with a little milk.
</P>
<P>
   May be made ahead and stored in a covered jar in the
refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1 cup.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 110 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 protein, 9 g carbohydrate,
8 &LR;   &LR; g fat (5 g saturated), 26 mg cholesterol, 55 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
