 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 TASTER'S CHOICE: It's Jar vs. Can in the Battle of the Bean   By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Many recipes call for canned beans as a way of
cutting the time needed for cooking beans from scratch. But is
there a difference from brand to brand? According to The
Chronicle's tasting panel, there is.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted eight different beans from cans and jars.
We included all beans labeled white beans, small white beans or
specific small varieties such as Great Northern. We did not include
larger cannellini beans. All were drained and rinsed but not
heated.
</P>
<P>
   The far-and-away favorite was  &UR; Whole Foods &LR;  (20.35-ounce jar,
$1.69 at Whole Foods). Panelists were particularly fond of the
beans' texture, and two noted the flavor. They also thought this
brand would work particularly well in soups or salads. All would
buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Annalisa &LR;  (12.3-ounce jar, 99 cents at
Tower Market). Most panelists liked the texture, although one
wanted the beans to be more firm. Most also liked the flavor.
Panelists recommended using this brand as a side dish to meat or
pureed into a bean dip. Two would buy it; three might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The top canned variety was  &UR; S &AMP; W &LR;  (15 ounces, 95 cents-$1.19 at
many supermarkets). Four panelists detected a smoky flavor, which
one thought was overbearing. Another thought the beans tasted
chemical. One panelist liked the firm texture, but two others
though the beans were mushy. Two would buy it, one might buy it,
and two would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Albertsons &LR;  (15 ounces, 69 cents at
Albertsons). Two panelists thought these beans tasted raw and
undercooked; two others detected a soapy aftertaste. But one
panelist liked the neutral flavor and thought it would blend well
with other ingredients. Three might buy it; two would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Sun Vista &LR;  (15 ounces, 79 cents at Andronico's) came in fifth.
Panelists disliked the mushy texture, though some thought the
flavors were good. Two recommended this brand for a bean dip. Two
might buy it; three would not.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also tasted Westbrae Natural, Eden Organic and
ShariAnn's but they scored too low to rate.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Donna Katzl,
chef-owner, Cafe For All Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot,
chef-owner, La Folie in San Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and
Menlo Park; Kim Severson, Chronicle staff writer; and Kirk Webber,
chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are tasted
blind. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
