<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods.  BEST WAY: Cooking Long-Grain Rice  
   
 By Lynne Bennett  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  It sounds simple, but isn't _ what's the best way
to cook white, enriched, long-grain rice so it maintains its
distinct grains and is not sticky? We tested 15 batches of rice to
find out.
<TEXT>
<P>
   We started with six different cooking methods: simmering the
rice in a covered saucepan; boiling, then steaming it covered;
boiling it; baking it; using an electric rice cooker; and using a
plastic microwave rice cooker.
</P>
<P>
   We initially tested the ratio of 1 cup rice to 2 cups water,
seasoned with 1/2 teaspoon kosher salt. This standard proportion _
found on most rice packages _ produced soft, sticky rice, which is
typical in many Asian dishes but was not what we were looking for.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of 1 cup rice to 11/2 cups water worked better,
but 11/4 cups water proved best. To be sure, we retested the 1 cup
rice to 11/4 cups water ratio using a a different brand of
long-grain rice and got the same good results.
</P>
<P>
   Our next step was to try the six cooking methods with this
proportion, and found we liked the rice baked in a 350-degree oven
best. Runner-up was the traditional method of adding the rice to
boiling water then simmering it, covered, for 20 minutes. The rice
that was boiled and drained like pasta was very soft and rather
soggy although one Food staff member liked it because she grew up
eating rice that way.
</P>
<P>
   Both rice cooker methods were disappointing, turning out rice
that was dry and overly firm. We decided the Best Way water
measurement _ 11/4 cups _ needed to be increased for these two
cooking methods so we tested them again using 11/2 cups water for
the rice cooker and followed the microwave cooker recipe of 3/4 cup
rice to 11/3 cups water. We repeated the Best Way oven method with
11/4 cups water for comparison.
</P>
<P>
   This time, all three methods _ oven, electric rice cooker and
microwave cooker _ produced rice that was very good, with separate,
distinct grains that were thoroughly cooked but firm enough to
stand up to a dish like a seafood gumbo. Because it does not
require any special equipment, we favored the oven method.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Place 1 cup of white,
long-grain rice and 1/2 teaspoon kosher salt in a small, ovenproof
baking dish. Add 11/4 cups boiling water, stirring once to dissolve
the salt. Cover the dish first with heavy-duty plastic wrap and
then with aluminum foil, making sure the plastic is completely
covered by the foil. Bake for 30 to 35 minutes, until all the water
is absorbed.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the rice from the oven and allow it to rest for 5
minutes. Stir gently, then recover the dish loosely with the
plastic wrap and let the rice rest for 5 more minutes before
serving. Makes approximately 31/2 cups. (Note: To double the
amount, use 2 cups rice, 21/8 cups water and 1 teaspoon of kosher
salt.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; APPEALING ALTERNATIVES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The traditional method of simmering the rice in a covered
saucepan is tried and true, producing good results. If you have an
electric rice cooker or a plastic microwave rice cooker (which took
14 minutes), by all means use them, although they take more water
than the Best Way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
When Life Gives You Rice... &QL; 
The inevitable outcome of testing 15 different batches of
long-grain white rice for today's Best Way column was finding a lot
of leftover rice in the refrigerator the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to waste a single grain, I whipped up a batch of
fried rice for my Food Department colleagues. It wasn't just any
old fried rice, however. My version uses no oil or liquid other
than soy sauce and the natural moisture from the ingredients. It's
a great recipe, clean and light-tasting with no greasy aftertaste.
Each grain of rice is fluffy and separate.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a versatile recipe. I chose a combination of Chinese
sausage and ham as the meat, and used defrosted frozen peas as the
vegetable. But you can use whatever you like or have on hand. I
like to add a sprinkle of sesame seed oil right at the end. It adds
a little fat, but is worth it for the flavor and aroma it lends to
the dish.
</P>
<P>
   One trick to assure success is to use the rice straight from the
refrigerator, or let it come to room temperature. Do not reheat it
before adding it to the pan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SIMPLE `FRIED' RICE
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons milk
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped green onion
</P>
<P>
   21/2 cups leftover cooked rice (see Best Way box, this page)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced cooked meat or poultry
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup diced cooked vegetables of choice
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   Heat a nonstick frying pan over medium heat. Lightly beat the
eggs with the milk; then add to the pan and scramble until just
cooked but still fluffy and moist. Remove from pan and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Add the green onion and rice to the pan and cook, gently
stirring and pressing the rice with a spatula until it begins to
warm and the grains separate.
</P>
<P>
   Reduce the heat to medium-low, add the meat and vegetables and
continue to cook, stirring frequently. Sprinkle the soy sauce over
the rice and stir until thoroughly mixed. Quickly chop the reserved
scrambled egg and add it to the rice. Cook, stirring, until all
ingredients are well mixed and hot. Season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yields approximately 4 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER CUP (without meat or vegetable): &LR;   &LR; 180 calories, &LR;   &LR; 6 g &LR; 
 &LR; protein, 32 g carbohydrate, 3 g fat (1 g saturated), 106 mg &LR; 
 &LR; cholesterol, 340 mg sodium, 0 fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
