<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
 
 AT THE SOURCE: St. George Cheese Is the Darling of Santa Rosa 
 Farm   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SANTA ROSA, Calif. _  For Sylvia Tucker, cheesemaking is a hands-on
affair _ literally.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most days, she hand-mixes curds to make St. George cheese at Joe
Matos Cheese Co., her parents' farm and business outside Santa
Rosa, where 25 to 30 Holsteins graze in mooing distance of a small
factory and sales room.
</P>
<P>
   Jose and Mary Matos brought the cheese recipe with them from the
Azores islands, where his family had been making the traditional
cheese _ known as St. Jorge in Portuguese _ for the better part of
a century. The couple set up business in Sonoma County in 1979,
with Mary as the main cheesemaker.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, a young woman _ also from the Azores _ took over
the arduous job, and when she left a few years back, daughter
Sylvia stepped up to the plate (or the vat, as it were) to become
the fifth generation of cheesemakers in her family.
</P>
<P>
   This farmstead cheese is sometimes described as a cross between
Monterey jack and cheddar, but unlike the way cheddar is made, the
curds for St. George are not stacked and milled but rather turned
by hand until they have the right consistency.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long?'' Tucker answers a question. ``Hard to say. You just
develop a feel for it; you feel it when the consistency is right _
sort of like Jell-O.''
</P>
<P>
   After the whey is separated from the curds, it is placed in
hoops and pressed with homemade weights _ buckets of hardened
cement _ for 48 hours. Then the wheels of fresh cheese are dried
for two months or more; the flavor becomes more assertive the
longer the cheese is aged. During this time, the wheels of cheese
are ``turned and turned and turned,'' Tucker says, and they develop
distinctive rinds. They're completely edible _ ``no wax,'' Tucker
says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   She admits that the Matos' way of making cheese may be
old-fashioned, but believes that mechanically produced cheeses
don't have the character of a handmade cheese.
</P>
<P>
   St. George has a buttery, slightly nutty flavor that makes it a
perfect companion to a chunk of French bread and a glass of wine,
the cheesemaker says. Her family _ husband Steve and three
children, aged 5 to 11 _ also likes the cheese in quesadillas,
grilled sandwiches and, dried a little longer, grated over pasta.
</P>
<P>
   And it makes a mean mac and cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  Joe Matos Cheese Co.'s St. George cheese is available at &LR; 
 &LR; Cowgirl Creamery in Pt. Reyes Station, Artisan Cheese in San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco, Cheeseboard in Berkeley and Oakville Grocery stores &LR; 
 &LR; throughout the Bay Area, for $9-$13 per pound. The cheese is &LR; 
 &LR; also sold at the farm at 3669 Llano Road (off Highway 12), &LR;   &LR; Santa
Rosa (off Highway 12), from 9 a.m.-5 p.m. daily for $4.50 &LR;   &LR; a
pound. Call the farm at (707) 584-5283 for more &LR;   &LR; information.cq &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
