<HEADER>
A2258 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-WINTERBLAHS-SFCHRON &LR;      02-29 3427
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINTERBLAHS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 Beating the Blahs: How chefs put pizzazz in their
dead-of-winter  menus   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  You might call this the awkward season _ it's
March, which means that spring is not too far off, at the same time
it's still the dead of winter. Produce bins, by and large, yield
little excitement, so we are challenged to put pizzazz into our
menus.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's make ``challenge'' the operational word. After all, it's
easy to make meals sparkle when luscious stone fruit and berries,
plump tomatoes and tiny new potatoes fairly tumble into our market
baskets. This time of year, when the winter vegetables _ the hard
squashes, the sturdy cabbages, the rutabagas and all their root
cousins _ have lost their blustery-weather appeal, it takes
imagination to circumnavigate the dining doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   We asked some of the Bay Area's most imaginative restaurant
chefs how they punch up their menus. They all agreed that right now
_ mid-February to mid-March _ is a hard time for menu planning. Not
surprisingly, these also are the months that restaurants are the
emptiest, according to the National Restaurant Association _ an
added incentive for chefs to give their clients something to talk
about and to entice them to come back.
</P>
<P>
   Home cooks can take a leaf from the pros' strategy books for
keeping things lively on the stove.
</P>
<P>
   So what do chefs reach for in this difficult time? Many stick
with the ``local and seasonal'' mantra. Roland Passot of La Folie
and Left Bank restaurants still makes his weekly pilgrimage to the
Saturday morning Ferry Plaza Farmers' Market. There is plenty of
interesting food that is in season, he maintains _ all the
varieties of citrus fruit, from blood oranges to grapefruit and
tangerines (the latter might add vibrancy to a scallop dish); good
carrots, Belgian endive (braised for a salad or the base for those
tangerine-accented scallops) and mushrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Passot gets a steady supply of ``lovely little haricot vert''
from San Diego, somewhat of a luxury item, but he also sings the
praises of prosaic all-American green celery, which he blanches
briefly in salted water, then braises with a few spoons of chicken
stock and a little lump of butter. He also turns the celery into a
gratin dish, adding a bit more stock and topping it with a grating
of Parmesan and Gruy &LR; e &LR; re. After a few minutes under the broiler to
melt the cheeses, it's a fine side dish _ ``very simple, very
inexpensive,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   There is a good chance that while shopping at Ferry Plaza,
Passot might run into Rose Pistola's Eric Cosselmon, who thinks
that here in California we always can find great produce as long as
we are willing to experiment. Cosselmon, as well as the other chefs
interviewed, does not try to cheat Mother Nature by buying imported
out-of-season produce, with the exception of early asparagus and
tropical fruit from Mexico. Those, he asserts, are natural crops of
their regions, not specifically raised _ and possibly forced _ for
the export trade.
</P>
<P>
   For extra variety, Cosselmon browses the Alemany Farmers'
Market, ``with its wonderful ethnic mix.'' Here he buys items such
as fresh shallots grown by Vietnamese farmers; and green garlic, a
Korean specialty that ``can really wake up your palate,'' like when
he chops and sprinkles it over thinly sliced fried zucchini chips.
</P>
<P>
   He also enlivens his menu with meats that are popular in Europe
_ tripe, tongue and brains _ but viewed with trepidation by many
American diners. ``We make a terrific calf brain antipasto,'' he
says. ``People who like it love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Denham also uses the late winter lull to entice
all-American meat-and-potato eaters into lesser-known territory at
his restaurant, 42 Degrees. Appetizers include Iberian blood
sausage with piquillo peppers, and rich, garlic-accented roasted
marrow bones.
</P>
<P>
   Denham bridges the seasonal gap by using lots of onions _ in one
dish, three different ways: roasted onion risotto finished with
Madeira-laced red onion jam and honey-rosemary glazed cipollini
onions.
</P>
<P>
   Winter herbs, he finds, are custom-made for punching up dishes.
A fragrant Calabrese sausage served over pasta marries lamb with
mint, parsley and rosemary in addition to garlic and shallots.
Gremolata, the Mediterranean mix of minced parsley, garlic and
lemon zest, adds a delightful fresh note to veal osso buco.
</P>
<P>
   Meat figures large in the current menu of Montage chef Jennifer
Cox as well. This season she tends to make meat portions a bit
bigger than the rest of the year. ``I concentrate on protein,'' she
says. She often forgoes the standard trio of meat, vegetable and
starch on the plate, instead presenting just two elements. Nor does
she adhere to the school that dictates every serving must be
colorful. Cox sees nothing wrong with a monochromatic plate, such
as a steak served with a potato-leek gratin. One of her more
brightly colored plates _ seared scallops on a bed of greens, with
coinlike golden kumquat slices and wine-poached dried cranberries
and a Meyer lemon vinaigrette _ features that combination not so
much because it looks pretty (it does), but because the seasonal
flavors enhance one another.
</P>
<P>
   If Cox had her druthers, no tomato would be seen in her kitchen
until the first local fruit appears, but being in a tourist
destination (Montage is in the Sony Metreon complex), she puts the
obligatory slice of tomato on lunchtime hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   The season's comparatively limited produce choices might be
expected to hit hardest in a restaurant that doesn't serve meat or
seafood, but Annie Somerville of Green's, San Francisco's
award-winning vegetarian restaurant, is undaunted. She uses capers,
nuts, croutons, dried fruit, olives and good cheeses to add zest to
her dishes.
</P>
<P>
   A compote of quince and dried cranberries sparks creme
fraiche-anointed griddle cakes of yams and Yellow Fin potatoes. Her
current favorite salad pairs hearts of romaine lettuce with mizuna
and arugula (all in good supply), adds quartered eggs and chunky
sourdough croutons and dresses it all in a champagne-caper
vinaigrette. Another salad combines wilted red and white cabbage
with Sierra Beauty apples, goat cheese and walnuts, with an apple
juice and balsamic vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   Early asparagus and citrus are on Somerville's menu, with the
two sometimes playing off each other, as in an asparagus soup
swirled with creme fraiche mixed with orange juice and zest.
</P>
<P>
   Citrus fruit in all its variety comes up again and again when
chefs talk about punching up their between-season menus.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Birnbaum, the New Orleans-born chef of Catahoula in
Calistoga and Sazerac in Seattle, says citrus has a great affinity
for chile peppers _ a fire and sunshine combination.
</P>
<P>
   If he needs inspiration, says Birnbaum _ another adherent of the
local-and-seasonal school _ ``I go to the dry store room.'' Such a
trip results in creations like his much-ordered Beans That Make You
Crazy, a cassouletlike dish that can feature any number of meats,
including duck confit.
</P>
<P>
   And in a pinch, Birnbaum says, you can't go wrong with potatoes,
citing favorites such as his version of a potato latke with salmon;
flavored mashed potatoes; and scalloped potatoes that get a quick
trip into the brick oven for a hit of smokiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brain is stuck on default when it come to potatoes,'' he
admits with a chuckle _ and that goes double this time of year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MONTAGE'S CITRUS-KISSED SCALLOPS
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the cranberries and kumquats a day or two ahead. The
vinaigrette may be mixed two hours ahead, making this a very quick
first course.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried cranberries
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup dry red wine
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Kumquats
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 whole star anise
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon Sichuan peppercorns (optional)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon whole allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound kumquats, very thinly sliced, seeded
</P>
<P>
   Meyer Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons Meyer lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons syrup from kumquats
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon champagne vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon minced Meyer lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons mild-flavored oil such as grapeseed
</P>
<P>
   Scallops
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound mache or watercress
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive or grapeseed oil
</P>
<P>
   18 large sea scallops
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; For the cranberries: &LR;  Combine the cranberries, wine and
orange juice in a small saucepan. Bring to a simmer. Remove from
heat, cover and let steep for 15 minutes. Strain, reserving berries
and liquid separately.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; For the kumquats: &LR;  Combine the water and sugar in a small,
nonreactive saucepan; cook until the sugar dissolves. Wrap the
spices in cheesecloth and tie with kitchen string. Add to the
liquid along with the kumquat slices. Cook until the fruit is
slightly tender, about 5 minutes. Transfer contents of pan to a
covered container and refrigerate for at least 1 day. Remove spice
bag just before using.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The vinaigrette: &LR;  Combine everything but the oil in a bowl.
Slowly whisk in the oil. If made ahead, whisk again before using.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The scallops and assembly: &LR;  Place the greens in a large bowl.
Dress with the vinaigrette and divide among individual salad
plates. Sprinkle an equal amount of cranberries and kumquats over
each serving.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in medium saute pan over medium-high heat. Pat the
scallops dry with paper towels, season with salt and pepper and add
to the hot oil. Cook, turning once, until the scallops are golden
on both sides. Remove with a slotted spoon and place 3 scallops on
each salad plate.
</P>
<P>
   Drizzle the scallops with a little kumquat syrup and liquid from
the cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 205 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g protein, 23 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 10 g fat (1 g saturated), 15 mg cholesterol, 446 mg sodium, 3 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; GREENS ASPARAGUS SOUP WITH ORANGE CREME FRAICHE
</P>
<P>
   Greens chef Annie Somerville likes to serve this soup as a
transition from winter to spring.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds asparagus, woody ends broken off
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon light olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 cups thinly sliced onion
</P>
<P>
   Salt and white pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 russet potato, sliced (about 1 cup)
</P>
<P>
   5 cups light vegetable stock, homemade if possible
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   Orange Creme Fraiche
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup creme fraiche
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons freshly squeezed orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon minced orange zest
</P>
<P>
   Chive blossoms for garnish (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cut the asparagus into 2-inch pieces. Set aside 1/2 cup
2-inch-long asparagus tips, cut on the diagonal, for garnish. Heat
the oil in a soup pot and add the onions, 1/2 teaspoon salt and a
pinch of white pepper. Saute over medium heat about 5 minutes,
until the onions are soft.
</P>
<P>
   Add the potato and 1 cup of the stock, cover and cook until the
potato is soft, about 10 minutes. Add the asparagus, 1/2 teaspoon
salt and the remaining stock; cook uncovered over medium heat until
the asparagus is tender, about 5 minutes. Puree the soup in a
blender or processor; return it to the pot and add the orange
juice. Taste for salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Drop the reserved asparagus tips into lightly salted boiling
water and cook until just tender. Rinse them under cold water.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the Orange Creme Fraiche: &LR;  Combine the creme fraiche,
orange juice and zest in a small bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish each serving with a few asparagus tips and a swirl of
the orange creme fraiche, plus the optional chive blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 120 calories, &LR;   &LR; 4 g protein, 12 g carbohydrate,
8 &LR;   &LR; g fat (4 g saturated), 20 mg cholesterol, 9 mg sodium, 2 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
CATAHOULA'S BEANS THAT MAKE YOU CRAZY
</P>
<P>
   Chef/owner Jan Birnbaum, known for stick-to-the-ribs dishes
year-round, enlivens this meal-in-a-dish with a robust spice
mixture based on chili powder, cayenne, black pepper, cumin, dry
mustard and paprika.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds large white beans, soaked overnight in 1 gallon
water
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound boneless pork or lamb shoulder, cut in large cubes
</P>
<P>
   2 large duck legs
</P>
<P>
   Spice Mix (see recipe)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon light olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound sausage (your choice)
</P>
<P>
   4 slices thick-cut bacon, cut into 1/2-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   3 cups chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   5 garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced jalapeno pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup molasses
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon hot red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup canned plum tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   5 cups chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Kosher salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the beans, discarding the water. Season the pork or lamb
and duck with about a third of the spice mix. Heat the oil in a
large, heavy pot and sear the meat cubes, duck and sausages in it
until lightly browned. Remove and reserve. Add the bacon and cook
until the fat is rendered.
</P>
<P>
   Add the onion, garlic and jalapeno; cook over medium heat until
the onion begins to caramelize. Add the beans and stir to coat. Add
the molasses and cook 5 minutes. Add the red pepper flakes and
tomatoes and cook 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the stock and bring to a simmer. Add the meat cubes and duck
legs, reserving the sausages for later. Add part or all of the
remaining spice mix (using all the mix will give you a red-hot
dish). Cover and place in the oven; cook until the beans and meats
are tender, about 1 to 11/2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Add the sausages and vinegar; taste and season with salt, if
necessary. Cover with a thin layer of breadcrumbs and return to the
oven just until the crumbs begin to brown.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Spice Mix:  &LR; Combine 2 tablespoons kosher salt, 1 tablespoon
ground black pepper, 2 teaspoons paprika, 1 teaspoon cayenne
pepper, 1/2 teaspoon ground cumin, 1/2 teaspoon dry mustard and 1/2
teaspoon chili powder; blend well. If made ahead, store in an
airtight container.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 to 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (using half of the spice mix): &LR;   &LR; 815 calories, &LR; 
 &LR; 61 &LR;   &LR; g protein, 93 g carbohydrate, 23 g fat (8 g saturated), 128
mg &LR;   &LR; cholesterol, 1,607 mg sodium, 21 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; ROSE PISTOLA WILD MUSHROOM TART
</P>
<P>
   Chef Erik Cosselmon uses wild mushrooms in this first course
that could double as supper, served with a spinach or mixed greens
salad.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds assorted wild mushrooms
</P>
<P>
   1 pound Yellow Finn potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 extra-large eggs
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces grated pecorino cheese
</P>
<P>
   Leaves from 3 thyme sprigs, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pastry for a double-crust, 9-inch pie
</P>
<P>
   Egg wash: 1 egg beaten with 1 teaspoon water
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Clean the mushrooms, chop them and dry-roast in a cast-iron or
other heavy skillet.
</P>
<P>
   Thinly slice the potatoes, then blanch in boiling salted water
until barely tender; drain.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the 2 eggs, cream and cheese and season with the
thyme, salt and pepper. Fold in the mushrooms and potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Roll out slightly more than half of the pastry and line a 9-inch
pie pan with it. Trim off pastry even with rim of pan. Line with
wax paper and fill with pie weights or dry beans. Bake until the
dough is golden. Remove the weights and paper and spoon the filling
into the shell.
</P>
<P>
   Increase oven heat to 375 degrees. Roll out the remaining
pastry. Carefully transfer to top of tart; trim to 1 inch from rim
of pan, then crimp, tucking cut edge under to make a decorative
border around perimeter of tart. Cut a couple of steam vents in the
pastry. Brush the egg wash over the top. Bake until the tart puffs
up and is deep golden, about 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Let cool on a rack for at least 10 minutes before cutting into
wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 560 calories, &LR;   &LR; 18 g protein, 40 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 30 g fat (11 g saturated), 133 mg cholesterol, 763
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
42 DEGREES' CALABRESE SAUSAGE PASTA
</P>
<P>
   The freshly made sausage in this recipe doesn't need to be
stuffed into casings &LR;  _ it might be compared to a high-end sloppy
Joe &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds lamb stew meat
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds pork butt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound fatback or bacon
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced shallots
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced fresh mint
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon pimenton (smoked Spanish paprika, see note)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fennel seeds, toasted, crushed in a mortar or spice
grinder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   11/2 tablespoons salt
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 egg
</P>
<P>
   6 cups freshly cooked pasta, such as penne or fusilli
</P>
<P>
   2 cups tomato sauce (homemade or purchased), heated
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cube the lamb, pork and fatback, discarding the bones. Chop into
1-inch cubes and mix thoroughly. Add the garlic, shallots, mint,
parsley, rosemary, paprika, fennel seeds, cayenne pepper, sugar,
salt and pepper. Mix well. Cover and refrigerate for at least 1
hour or overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Put the meat through a meat grinder fitted with a 1/4-inch dye.
Or use a food processor, working in batches and using on/off
pulses. Be careful not to process beyond the stage resembling
coarsely ground hamburger. Add the egg and mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Saute the mixture in a nonstick skillet, stirring frequently,
until the meat is no longer pink. Taste for seasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon over hot pasta and top with tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 to 8.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Look for pimenton in specialty markets, such as Tower
Market in San Francisco, Dean &AMP; Deluca in St. Helena, Mill Valley
Market, and Draeger's in San Mateo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 715 calories, &LR;   &LR; 47 g protein, 41 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 39 g fat (14 g saturated), 169 mg cholesterol,
1,727 mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
LA FOLIE'S GATEAU DE CRAB
</P>
<P>
   Chef-owner Roland Passot serves these appetizers with a
citrus-infused sauce and four elaborately arranged garnishes. But
you can use as many of these delicious embellishments as you like.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound crabmeat
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   11/2 teaspoons Dijon mustard
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup shredded celery root (celeriac)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fine dry breadcrumbs
</P>
<P>
   Sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup carrot juice
</P>
<P>
   1 cup fresh orange juice (preferably from blood oranges)
</P>
<P>
   1 small carrot, cut into 1/16-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   Garnishes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 English cucumber, peeled, seeded and thinly sliced, mixed
with 1/2 cup rice vinegar and a big pinch of sugar; let marinate
for at least 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 tomato, peeled, seeded, finely diced and seasoned with salt
and pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 avocado, peeled, cubed and seasoned with a drop of Tabasco
</P>
<P>
   1/2 mango, peeled, diced and mixed with 1/2 bunch chopped chives
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the crabmeat with the mayonnaise, mustard, celery root
and breadcrumbs. Mix well. (Cover and refrigerate if not used
immediately.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the sauce:  &LR; Pour the vinegar into a medium-size heavy
pan, place over medium heat and cook until the vinegar has reduced
by approximately one quarter. Add the carrot and orange juices and
reduce by half. Add the diced carrot and cook briefly. Keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Shape the crab mixture into 6 cakes, each about 2 inches in
diameter.
</P>
<P>
   Heat about 2 teaspoons olive oil in a heavy nonstick pan. When
hot, but not smoking, add the crab cakes and fry until golden
brown, about 4 minutes per side.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the cakes to individual salad plates and spoon some of
the sauce around each. Garnish with any or all of the garnishes. If
using the cucumber slices, squeeze out excess moisture before
using.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (without garnishes): &LR;   &LR; 130 calories, &LR;   &LR; 9 g
protein, &LR;   &LR; 18 g carbohydrate, 3 g fat (1 g saturated), 26 mg
cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 226 mg sodium, 1 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM &QL;  &LR; 
