<P>
   MINDSPRING-MCQUARY _ Before the merger between MindSpring
Enterprises and EarthLink Network, Mike McQuary was happy to be the
force behind the scenes and let the company's charismatic founder
Charles Brewer take center stage. But McQuary, or ``McQ'' as he's
known to friends and associates is a strong personality in his own
right. In his new role as president of EarthLink McQuary will be a
much more visible presence than he has been to date. A Q&AMP;A session
with him. (Katz, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25. WITH PHOTO.
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-AIRLINES _ Delta and UPS, with American Airlines and Polar
Air Cargo, are competing for a new route designation to Beijing,
allowing 10 weekly flights to China. Today was the deadline for the
carriers to complete arguments supporting their applications to
U.S. DOT. The new flights are scheduled to begin April 1, 2001.
Three carriers now fly US-China. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   DOW _ Blue-chip stocks have declined sharply so far this year,
after stellar gains in recent years. Now, investors are bargain
hunting, which led to Monday's recovery in many blue-chip issues.
Among those investors buying is Atlanta money manager James
Barksdale, who considers himself a ``value'' investor. Barksdale
discusses the current market environment and his strategies for
``buying on dips.''
</P>
<P>
   (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HERRING _ ATLANTA _ They came, they saw, the scrounged for cash.
And there was lots of it floating around, chasing the Next New New
Thing.... The Red Herring brought more than 700 people to the
Ritz-Carlton to hear quickie presentations from 44 companies that
each have plans to be huge. Each can cite a mega-billion market
opportunity and each has a killer approach. But what is new, here?
What do the entrepreneurs have to say? And where is the money
going? What are the deep pockets looking for? And what does all
this say about Atlanta, the Southeast, and the nation's tech trends
_ just where are we heading?
</P>
