<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELIN-GUIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHELIN GUIDE, 100, GIVETH AND TAKETH AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Dining)  
 (af)  
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Le Grand Vefour in Paris, the newest three-star restaurant in
the Michelin firmament, is hardly new at all. The restaurant,
anointed in the latest Michelin guide to France, which was
published on Monday, is a piece of the city's history.
</P>
<P>
   Tucked into an arcade in the back of the Palais Royal gardens,
it began in 1784 as the Cafe de Chartres. Jean Vefour bought it and
renamed it in 1820. It is now one of seven Michelin three-star
restaurants in Paris. The others are Taillevent, Alain Ducasse,
Arpege, Pierre Gagnaire, L'Ambroisie and Lucas Carton.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Paris, France has 15 three-star restaurants. Seventy
restaurants in this year's guide have two stars, and 410 have one.
The Michelin inspectors visit the restaurants anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   In the rest of the latest Michelin lineup, another venerable
stop, -L'Espadon at the Ritz in Paris, was demoted from two stars
to one, and the Regence in the Plaza Athenee climbed from one to
two.
</P>
<P>
   Helene Darroze, one of 16 women who have earned Michelin stars
as chefs, moved her one-star restaurant from Villeneuve-de-Marsan
in the southwest of France to Paris last fall and retained her
rating.
</P>
<P>
   Alain Ducasse, who has earned three stars at two restaurants
(Louis XV in Monte Carlo and Alain Ducasse), won a star for his new
place, Bar et Boeuf, also in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   This year's guide is the 100th anniversary edition. The French
edition, now known simply as Le Guide Rouge (The Red Guide), has
added brief descriptions of all establishments. Those who buy it in
France will receive a bonus, a facsimile edition of the original,
from 1900.
</P>
<P>
   The international edition, sold in the United States ($26) does
not include this bit of nostalgia, but 116 of the 5,661 hotels in
the guide have been marked with a ``100'' to show that they were in
the orginal guide. Michelin began evaluating restaurants in 1920.
The star system was inaugurated in 1926. The guide has a Web site,
www.Michelin-travel.com, which will provide the guide free until
June 30.
</P>
<P>
   As for Le Grand Vefour, it became a famous gathering place for
intellectuals, including Victor Hugo, Georges Sand and, more
recently, Jean Cocteau and Colette, whose favorite burgundy
banquettes bear their names on brass plates.
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant's popularity declined after World War I. In 1948,
Louis Vaudable, the owner of Maxim's, bought it and turned the
kitchen over to Raymond Oliver, who eventually became the
restaurant's owner. It earned three Michelin stars, a rating it
maintained until 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The Taittinger Champagne family bought it in 1984, restored its
glorious 19th-century landmark interior and in 1991, after false
starts with other chefs, hired Guy Martin, a native of the Savoy
region. He had earned two Michelin stars at the Chateau de Divonne
in Divonne-les-Bains in the French Alps.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 43, skillfully orchestrates tradition and innovation in
such dishes as pigeon in a sauce thickened with blood, creamy foie
gras ravioli and desserts made with candied fennel. His cart of
farmhouse cheeses from Savoy is unsurpassed.
</P>
<P>
   Le Grand Vefour, at 17, rue Beaujolais, is open Monday through
Friday for lunch and dinner. In addition to an a la carte menu, it
offers a 390-franc menu (about $58) at lunch. The phone number is
(011) 33-1-42-96-56-27.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1746EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BRITAIN-NAZI-ART-NYT &LR;      02-29 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-NAZI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH LIST 350 WORKS NAZIS MAY HAVE HELD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Germany, France, Belgium, Britain)   By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ After combing through their holdings, Britain's art
museums and galleries released a list of more than 350 works of art
Tuesday that have murky provenances for the period around World War
II and may have been seized by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   The list was drawn from 10 major institutions across Britain,
including the Tate Gallery, the National Gallery and the Victoria
and Albert Museum, and it includes paintings by van Gogh, Picasso,
Renoir, Munch and Matisse. Among them are Delacroix's ``Christ on
the Cross,'' which is part of the National Gallery's collection;
Cezanne's ``Avenue at the Jas de Bouffan,'' which is held by the
Tate Gallery; and a still life by Diego Rivera, which is also held
by the Tate.
</P>
<P>
   Sir Nicholas Serota, the chairman of the National Museum
Directors' Conference, which prepared the report, said that there
was no factual evidence that any of the works had been stolen by
the Nazis before the works found their way to Britain after the
war. But he said the institutions involved were eager to solve the
mystery of where the pieces had been and who had owned them from
1933 to 1945, when the Nazis helped themselves to the best art in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to share this information with our colleagues,
nationally and internationally,'' said Serota, announcing at a news
conference that the list would also be posted on the Internet. ``We
need assistance to reduce the list of works around which there is
some question.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We are very much more ready than we have been to
deal with any claims or requests for information.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain is the latest European country to make an official
effort to restore artworks stolen by the Nazis to their rightful
owners. Critics point out that in many countries restitution or
compensation has been hard to come by.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, for instance, the French government identified
nearly 1,000 paintings, drawings and sculptures that had been
appropriated by Nazi occupation forces and returned to France after
the war but had not been claimed by the original owners' families
or estates. But only a handful of these works were ever returned to
their owners, although the government posted details on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that this is passive research _ this is not
research at all,'' said Hector Feliciano, an expert on Nazi looting
and the author of ``The Lost Museum,'' published in English in
1997. ``You really can't wait for people to come to the Internet
and claim their Picassos or whatever. You have to be active and try
to compensate for the 60 years in which the paintings have been
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish Congress,
which is based in New York, said he welcomed the British move as a
``very forward-looking initial step.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that the museums should make aggressive efforts to
identify owners and return the works to their heirs or estates.
``The fact that they have identified 350 has to be regarded in
itself as a positive step,'' he said. ``But the proof of the
pudding is in the tasting.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Steinberg also chastised the United States,
saying it lagged behind Europe in this area. ``I wish the American
museums had come this far,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago American art museums promised to make inventories
of their holdings and identify suspect works, but so far there has
been no comprehensive listing of pieces that might have been stolen
by the Nazis and are now held by American museums. Although several
American museums have grudgingly relinquished works identified by
outsiders as having been stolen, Steinberg said, ``to this day no
museum has yet identified a single work of art in their holdings
which they have announced they were turning over.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Page, the chief legal officer for the Tate Gallery,
acknowledged that it would be virtually impossible to establish
beyond a doubt where each piece on the list of suspect works in
British museums had been during World War II. ``I think the
likelihood is that there may well remain a number of gaps in the
provenance of many of these works that we will never be able to
completely close,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a variety of reasons works of art have gaps in their
provenance,'' she explained. ``A lot of records were lost during
the war. Dealers and galleries were bombed and destroyed. People
had to move out very quickly and things were not taken with them.
Keeping their files in a spic-and-span state probably wasn't their
No. 1 priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, she said, record-keeping in the art world was much less
stringent 60 years ago than it is now. ``Transactions in works of
art were carried out in a relatively informal way,'' she said. ``It
was done often by people who knew each other and had been dealing
with each other for years. Contracts and letters that you might
expect to find in other transactions you wouldn't find in art
transactions. Things didn't have the enormous monetary values that
they have now.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord Janner, chairman of the Holocaust Educational Trust,
Britain's largest Jewish organization, said that only one claim had
been made against a work in a British museum. An elderly, infirm
Jewish man who moved from Germany to England before the war says
that a 1710 painting of Hampton Court Palace by the Dutch artist
Jan Griffier the Elder, now in the Tate Gallery, was owned by his
parents.
</P>
<P>
   The man's father, a banker, was killed by the Nazis in 1937, and
his mother fled to Belgium with their art collection. She then had
to sell the Griffier and other paintings to buy food, the claim
says, and was sent to a concentration camp for the rest of the war.
She survived and moved to England, dying in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The government is establishing an advisory panel to consider
this claim and future ones. Janner said at the news conference that
rapid government action was important. ``This is a moral issue on a
major scale,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
