u e BC-TV-NOTES-NYT &LR;      02-29 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV NOTES: ABC'S RATINGS SWEEP; LETTERMAN AND CAMPAIGN 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABC Sweeps The Sweeps  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How much difference is ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' making
for ABC? The latest evidence: the game show pushed ABC to its first
victory in the February ratings sweep in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the sweep does not end until Wednesday night, ABC's
victory was across the board in every significant category, and
every other network conceded the sweep title to ABC.
</P>
<P>
   They all credited it to ``Millionaire,'' of course, pointing out
that ABC filled an enormous portion of its prime-time schedule, 18
percent in total, with 16 hours of ``Millionaire.'' Several of
those hours were added to the schedule late, when NBC was making a
run at nosing out ABC.
</P>
<P>
   NBC most pointedly suggested that ABC might be risking
overexposure with the series. But Lloyd Braun, the co-chairman of
ABC Entertainment, noted that the show had improved on its already
overwhelming performance in the November sweep by 18 percent. That
has convinced ABC that the show has not reached the saturation
point.
</P>
<P>
   But Preston Beckman, the executive vice president for
programming at NBC, pointed out that NBC began to beat ABC in
February when ABC used only three ``Millionaire'' shows a week.
``Now it takes four a week to win,'' Beckman said.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from ABC, NBC and CBS all pointed to what they said
was the best trend in February: stronger overall performance by
network television. Leslie Moonves, the president of CBS
Television, said the combined rating for the three biggest networks
rose for the first time since February 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, whose ratings declined about 9 percent in February, was not
included. Fox suffers the most from ``Millionaire'' because the
game show never plays after 10 p.m.; NBC and CBS have programming
after 10, but Fox does not.
</P>
<P>
   NBC emphasized the strong performance of many of its hit series,
including ``ER,'' which had its best rating in three years; the
venerable ``Law and Order,'' which was up 20 percent from February
last year; and ``Frasier,'' which NBC noted had improved every week
of the month even though it faced ``Millionaire'' every time.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives also emphasized that their 10 p.m. shows
dominated the competition, an important point because the sweep
programming is intended to help local stations and especially their
late news programs.
</P>
<P>
   CBS made the point that it was the only network whose median age
declined in February, though its audience remained by far the
oldest of any network. Moonves said CBS's median age dropped to 52
from 53, while NBC climbed to 45 from 42 and ABC rose to 44 from
41.
</P>
<P>
   NBC executives said their new dramas, like ``The West Wing'' and
``Special Victims Unit,'' were pulling in slightly older viewers,
though they noted that those viewers also tended to be
well-educated and rich, two factors that NBC intends to pitch
heavily to advertisers who are unhappy that it is drawing an older
audience.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives cited the horde that ``Millionaire'' is pulling
in as one reason for the rise in age.
</P>
<P>
   Letterman and Politics
</P>
<P>
   David Letterman continues his convalescence _ and that includes
the ratings kind _ Wednesday night when he tries to extend his
participation in the political campaign by bringing on George W.
Bush as part of a running ``Campaign 2000'' comedy bit.
</P>
<P>
   Bush became Letterman's target of opportunity after his show
scored a ratings coup with Hillary Rodham Clinton the same week in
January that he went into the hospital for emergency heart surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Since the surgery, Letterman has been welcomed back by
much-higher-than-normal ratings, though they have clearly started
to retreat since their high on Feb. 21, his first night back.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Letterman scored a rare victory over Jay Leno and the
``Tonight'' show, even though his ``Late Show'' on CBS used two
guest hosts on the nights Letterman took off. Both Bill Cosby and
Kathie Lee Gifford posted strong ratings for their guest-host
shows.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of bringing Bush on as the next political guest began
the night after Clinton's appearance, when Letterman started
pressing his executive producer, Rob Burnett, on the air to book
Bush. After the five-week hiatus for the surgery, Letterman took up
the call for Bush again in between comments describing the Texas
governor as a ``likely pinhead.''
</P>
<P>
   That apparently did not deter Bush's advisers, who, Burnett said
Tuesday, were eager to have him appear with Letterman. Bush is, of
course, busy trying to fend off Sen. John McCain, so he will appear
with Letterman on Wednesday night via satellite from St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was almost too easy to book,'' Burnett said. ``I called and
they said yes. This is one of those happy examples where we use
them and they use us.''
</P>
<P>
   The example has not been lost on McCain, whose representatives
were on the phone with Burnett on Tuesday looking to squeeze in an
appearance with Letterman before next Super Tuesday primaries in
New York, California and elsewhere. McCain had a problem, though.
He was planning to tape a show with Letterman in New York on
Thursday but then decided at the last minute to re-enter the CNN
debate scheduled for Thursday in California.
</P>
<P>
   That means he may be able to tape an appearance with Letterman
only on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been busy on late night anyway: Bush will have
competition for late-night viewers Wednesday night because McCain
will be on with Leno. And if McCain manages to appear on
Letterman's show Monday, he'll have competition from Bush sitting
next to Leno.
</P>
<P>
   As Burnett put it: ``This is really no different from show
business. We're media and these guys need media.''
</P>
</TEXT>
