<HEADER>
A2298 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FILM-NEXT-BEST-FEATUR     02-29 1426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NEXT-BEST-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARM, FUZZY _ AND POLITICAL _ `THE NEXT BEST THING'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If ``The Next Best Thing'' doesn't cause controversy, there's
something wrong.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it focuses on a child custody battle that will
naturally make viewers take sides. And one of the participants is a
homosexual, played by the openly gay actor Rupert Everett, who does
not conform to the sexless, effeminate stereotype that Hollywood
movies find comfortable. The other main character is played by
Everett's longtime friend Madonna, whose every move seems to stir
debate _ even more so when it involves the pop star's
ever-questionable acting talents.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, and there's that dance version of ``American Pie.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the usual conservative critics have been complaining
more about movie violence in the post-Columbine cultural climate
and laying off films with more sexually based themes recently.
Witness the absence of predicted thunder from the right about the
``Lolita'' remake and the yet-unmaterialized attacks on
abortion-rights Oscar nominee ``The Cider House Rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, as Madonna, Everett and veteran director John Schlesinger
hope, times have simply changed enough for ``Next Best Thing'' to
be considered a contemporary family comedy-drama rather than a
lightning rod for political advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   As long, that is, as you agree with their point of view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every story is different,'' says provocateur and noted single
mother Madonna. ``I think, more than anything, it's important that
people understand that families come in all shapes and sizes.
People have to learn to be much more open and tolerant of those
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   But with everything from the Elian Gonzales contretemps to
Proposition 22 to the David Crosby-Melissa Etheridge-Julie Cypher
revelation in the news these days, it's obvious that tolerance is
only one of a wide range of reactions to modern family issues. Of
course, that also means ``Next Best Thing'' is clearly a reflection
of the times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a film for now,'' notes Schlesinger, who began his
filmmaking career with such of-the-moment '60s features as
``Darling,'' ``A Kind of Loving'' and the Oscar-winning, X-rated
``Midnight Cowboy.'' ``I don't think we made it saying, `This is an
issue, therefore, this is something we should be doing.' We just
moved to a situation where, in life, families take on all sorts of
different configurations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also the fact that we're discussing, much more openly
than we ever did in the past, issues that we never would have
dreamt of bringing up just a few decades ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow Englishman Everett, who's stolen such films as ``My Best
Friend's Wedding'' playing drolly matter-of-fact gay characters,
helped rewrite Thomas Ropelewski's original ``Next Best'' script to
make his role more realistic. But Everett insists that the film's
primary concerns go beyond the representation issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is a gay film,'' Everett says. ``It's about
family, love and parenthood. My character is a very positive gay
role model, in that he's a good man. In the original screenplay, he
was an asexual, flubby interior decorator whose answer to every
problem was to get some whipped cream out of the refrigerator and
squirt it around. We made him into an ordinary '90s man who was a
practicing homosexual and a great father.''
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Everett's Robert, an L.A. landscape designer,
commiserates with his oft-jilted best friend, Madonna's yoga
instructor Abbie, over one long, drunken, holiday weekend following
the funeral of a close friend. One thing leads to another, and not
long after the shocked pair awakens in each other's arms, Abbie
discovers that she's pregnant. Deciding to have the child, she
offers Robert as much or as little involvement in its upbringing as
he wishes.
</P>
<P>
   To even perhaps his own surprise, Robert moves in with Abbie.
For more than half a decade, they lovingly raise their son, Sam
(played by newcomer Malcolm Stumpf), like any other devoted couple
who keep separate bedrooms. Robert still sees lovers, but his first
commitment is always to his son. Ditto Abbie, until she's swept off
her feet by New York-based investor Ben (``Law &AMP; Order's'' Benjamin
Bratt), whose proposal involves a cross-country relocation.
</P>
<P>
   Though all three adults basically mean well, an ugly court fight
ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Schlesinger, who addressed gay issues in such films as
``Darling'' (1965), ``Cowboy'' (1969), ``Sunday, Bloody Sunday''
(1971) and ``An Englishman Abroad'' (1988) long before it was
generally acceptable, notes that certain producers and the studio
releasing ``Next Best,'' Paramount, expressed reservations about
the film's tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were disagreements with the production side,'' notes the
74-year-old filmmaker, who remains sharp-witted but is noticeably
frail a few months following open-heart surgery. ``They were
worried about the characters being rude to each other or seeming
unsympathetic. But what interested me in doing the movie was the
chance to be honest about the characters in every way. We worked
very hard to make it so and I think it is that. But sometimes, it
was an uphill battle.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, early critical response to the film seems to be more
negative toward Abbie's behavior than to anything that Robert
represents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching the movie with one of my best friends and she
slugged me in the middle of the screening!'' Madonna reveals.
``She's like, `How could you do that?' and I said, `I didn't do
that, my character did it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Schlesinger feels that such reactions _ especially from people
who aren't her friends _ result from the extra baggage that comes
with everything Madonna does.
</P>
<P>
   ``The character does true and honest things in situations that
she doesn't know how to deal with, not wicked things,'' he
observes. ``People impute all too easily and quickly. Madonna is a
controversial character as herself, and I think that people are
very ready to jump on a bandwagon and say, `Isn't she terrible.'''
</P>
<P>
   The director does concede, however, that when it comes to the
singer's acting abilities, those who found something lacking in
``Who's That Girl,'' ``Body of Evidence'' and even ``Evita,'' among
others, had a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the one word that a performer never wants to hear
is `relax,''' Schlesinger notes. ``And I was conscious that she is
so deliberate in what she's created that one wanted to get rid of
that and make it just happen. Now, I don't know how we did it
because we did occasionally spar, but that stopped quite early on
and she became flexible. She understood her character very well,
and it really was a question of gaining her confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Madonna is a pretty good sport about the touchy
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you; I'll say it,'' she quips. ``Now I have gotten
better in choosing movies.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to the questionable cover of Don McLean's poetic
baby-boomer narrative, however, a shift-the-blame game kicks in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't my idea, it was Rupert's,'' she says of the newly
syncopated ``American Pie.'' ``I didn't care about it in the
beginning. I kept saying, `You should do it, it's your idea.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, she did it!'' Everett hedges. ``But I wanted to find an
original song that could be part of the motif for the film. I
wanted some kind of honky-tonky, guitar-piano song that could
almost be something you'd hear from car radios driving by parts of
L.A. And, for promotional and other reasons, it had to be
convertible to techno, so I thought `American Pie' was ideal.''
</P>
<P>
   At least that's one potential controversy that's been weathered.
Listeners, including McLean himself, have endorsed the refurbished
classic.
</P>
<P>
   As for the movie, expectations among the key players are mixed
but upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if the film will be attacked from political
quarters, but I can't be sure,'' Schlesinger says, then lets loose
a jolly laugh. ``But if that's the way they see it, so be it,
there's nothing I can do to change it. Yes, it is what it is. But I
don't think it's shocking. It's quite sweetly done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What I would like people to take away from the film would be a
re-evaluation of family values,'' Everett says. ``What makes a
family? Blood isn't the only thing in a family. Commitment is in a
family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen _ I think the most important thing for families is
love,'' Madonna concludes. ``And that comes in all different
forms.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
