<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dig in for a 24-karat fall
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   All that glitters is not gold. But all that's gold is suddenly
trendy.
</P>
<P>
   As the fashion shows in New York, Milan and Paris have shown so
far, silver's popularity is plummeting. Call it a knee-jerk
reaction to the ever-booming economy, but gold _ the
internationally recognized color of money _ is becoming the new
standard of stylishness.
</P>
<P>
   Its true weight won't fall on us until the next crop of
cold-weather wearables reaches shops. But the glint of gold's
growing appeal was evident Sunday during a stroll down Paris'
chicest strip of stores, the Rue du Faubourg St. Honore.
</P>
<P>
   Mannequins at Versace had their white linen suits accessorized
with thin gold chains. Gold zippers on the tie-dyed snakeskin jeans
at Roberto Cavalli gave the pants extra pizazz. The belted cashmere
cardigans at Van Laak had golden buckles. The buttons on Louis
Feraud's tropical weight wool suits were gold as well.
</P>
<P>
   To my eye, gold doesn't have the same modern appeal as silver or
platinum. Nor does it seem to meld as well with clothes on the
cooler end of the color spectrum. But gold's what's new now. So let
the mining begin.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
