r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE02-COX     02-29 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    My appreciation of houseplants deepens as their numbers fade
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   As March ushers houseplants off center stage, in favor of all
those outdoor harbingers of spring, let us give thanks to our
tireless potted friends that labored mightily throughout the winter
to keep our homes agrowing.
</P>
<P>
   I garden indoors as seriously as I garden outdoors, although in
an effort to pare down and practice some semblance of moderation, I
am amazed to say that my interior plants number far fewer than
several years ago. Then, watering upstairs and down amounted to a
three-hour pleasure on some days (as all gardeners know, watering
is never just watering, outdoors or in; there's the close
examination, the reacquaintances, the touching, looking for
changes).
</P>
<P>
   Now, I water in an hour.
</P>
<P>
   This big change (it has come through giveaways, throwaways and
deaths) has opened new pathways throughout the house _ and improved
relations with Lyn, who had complained for more than a decade that
running a vacuum or mop through the house was like running an
obstacle course.
</P>
<P>
   Like paring down anyplace _ in the outdoor garden or in life _
the slimmer indoor collection offers increased opportunities to
appreciate what remains. In the library, for instance, ferns used
to hang from the ceiling, and the floor was covered with little
pots of Christmas cactus, along with a huge jade. Now, the cactus
plants and ferns have found new homes, the jade, alas, up and died,
and all that remains is one huge grape ivy that hangs from the
ceiling. I never fail to stop and stare at it when I enter the
room.
</P>
<P>
   In the rear parlor, two ornamental figs, a coffee plant, a
gardenia, episcia and peace lily grow where three times that many
plants once lived.
</P>
<P>
   And by the windows in the kitchen, once home to dozens of
path-blocking pots, only a few survive the down-paring, including a
tall old crinkly-leafed aralia and our 15-year old friend Sarah
Frond (the first plant Lyn and I ever owned together). Some 20
plants used to live in the east-facing room.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if growing fewer indoor plants and appreciating
them more as individuals had anything to do with the jewel orchid's
blooming comeback, but I'm glad to see it.
</P>
<P>
   Orchids in general always have been spectacular indoor plants,
as their flowers last for weeks and weeks, lending a colorful and
tropical air to interior spaces, even in the gray of winter.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, I have never had much success in coaxing new
blooms from my orchids after the initial nursery-grown blossoms
fade. The lone exception to this pitiful pattern was the jewel
orchid, which I began growing about 10 years ago. (It is the only
one I've grown in regular potting soil instead of the special
orchid mixtures of shredded bark, peat and such.)
</P>
<P>
   For the first few years, the jewel orchid bloomed. Then,
nothing. Until December, when I noticed a swelling pinkish bud
emerging from the tip of the vinelike plant. The single bud,
nestled among the velvety green leaves with burgundy veins, slowly
grew larger, so slowly that by January, I figured it soon would
retreat to where it was trying to come from. Instead, it rode atop
a matchstick-diameter stalk that eventually lengthened to about 10
inches, gradually opening into a shower of tiny white flowers with
yellow centers.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, I counted the little winged blossoms radiating in all
directions, until, by the end of February, 15 had opened, with one
to go.
</P>
<P>
   As I anticipate that final pop akin to the satisfying sigh of a
champagne cork, I salute the bejeweled orchid, the season's
comeback king. And all its housemates. They've kept me growing
inside, gotten me to the verge of spring, outside.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May's Gardening Life column appears every other week in Home
&AMP; Garden for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution..
</P>
<P>
   Lee May is a regular columnist on gardening lifestyles. E-mail
him at leemay(at)bellsouth.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
