<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2302 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PILLSBURY-BAKEOFF01-C     02-29 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILLSBURY-BAKEOFF01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The 50th Pillsbury Bakeoff
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With a little yelp that could summon Darva
Conger from a mile away, Bobbie Sonefeld of Hopkins, S.C., became a
millionaire yesterday at the 50th annual Pillsbury Bakeoff.
</P>
<P>
   Sonefeld, 35, took the $1 million top prize with her recipe for
Cream Cheese Brownie Pie, a 600-calorie-a-slice confection that the
judges dubbed ``the best of two worlds _ a pie and a brownie.''
</P>
<P>
   An administrative assistant and mother of two young boys,
Sonefeld submitted her winning recipe over the Internet. It was
selected as one of 100 finalists from among ``tens of thousands''
of entries by Pillsbury, and Sonefeld was invited to San Francisco
to pit it against such contenders as Chicken Waldorf Pizza, Seaside
Shortcakes and Guess Again Candy Crunch.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists came from 36 states, and included a trial
attorney, a chemistry professor, a farmer, an Emmy winner and 21
full-time homemakers.
</P>
<P>
   The bakeoff began, as it always does, with the Grand March.
After a very Pillsbury breakfast of snack breads, bacon and french
toast topped with peach salsa (including bits of red and green
pepper), the contestants slapped on their aprons and proceeded to
the bakeoff ballroom at precisely 8 a.m. Led by elderly family
heiress Sally Pillsbury _ resplendent in red, white and blue _ and
a woman in an inflated Doughboy costume, they toured the ballroom
clapping their hands in time to a blurry rap tune.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Traylor of Rome (Georgia's only contestant this year),
took her position at Range No. 59 and ripped open a bag of Green
Giant broccoli florets. Her mission: to prepare her winning recipe
for Broccoli-Jicama Salad three times. Once for display. Once for
onlookers to try. And once to submit to the sequestered jury of
food writers and cookbook authors. The recipe is a heavily adapted
version of a salad Traylor clipped from Southern Living that used
broccoli and water chestnuts. She added dried cranberries and a
creamy dressing made with lemon yogurt.
</P>
<P>
   Deep in the midst of the ``Yummy Vegetable'' aisle, Traylor was
a coil of pure adrenaline. A small woman with short-cropped black
hair and big glasses, she inherited an addiction to cooking
contests from her mother, with whom she lives. Until now, neither
mother nor daughter had made it to the bakeoff _ the big kahuna of
cooking contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother was shocked when they called,'' said Traylor, 43, as
she took a chef's knife to a jicama. ``But that's because she hates
broccoli. Boy, these knives are sharp! Hold on just a minute, I
don't want to cut myself.''
</P>
<P>
   With many small slices, Traylor removed every bit of peel and
turned the jicama into a multifaceted white jewel. She set a
steaming basket in a saucepan for the broccoli, grabbed a box
grater and zealously reduced the jicama to shreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother said, `Why don't you julienne the jicama?' I said,
'Mother, I've already injured myself once with a jicama.''' She
held out her hand to show the faint scar.
</P>
<P>
   As Traylor talked, she noticed a disturbing pool of juice
forming in the bowl of grated shreds. ``Looks like they just sent
them down to Mexico to pick it fresh,'' said Traylor. ``I've never
seen such a juicy jicama.'' She reached into her mini-cabinet and
grabbed a strainer.
</P>
<P>
   Other details were wrong as well. The flat-surface range heated
so quickly that she overcooked the broccoli. The yogurt didn't look
as yellow as lemon Dannon yogurt in Georgia. So the first batch,
with overcooked broccoli, went to the display table. The second
batch would be for the judges.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Range No. 92, Lauren Eggeman of Massillon, Ohio, worried
that she put too much ginger in her first batch of Sugar &AMP; Spice
Black Pepper Cookies. But she was poised and nonplussed.
Particularly for an 11 year old.
</P>
<P>
   Eggeman, the youngest contestant this year, candidly admitted,
``I never follow recipes. But, you know, nothing turns out that
good the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6th grader's earliest memory of cooking is of sitting on the
kitchen table watching her mom cook when she was 2. From her
Grandma she learned to make cookies _ and put black pepper in them.
``I added more ingredients like clove and ginger. My brother liked
them, and it was my Mom's idea to enter them.''
</P>
<P>
   At Range No. 49, Hal Fisher of Inman, S.C., fashioned a delicate
pile of Corn and Pea Salad with Cinnamon-toasted Pecans. All of his
buddies in his Spartanburg Harley Owners Group are ``100 percent
behind'' his Bakeoff dreams. Fisher, a mild-mannered funeral
director who looks nothing like a ZZ Top member, likes to cook for
his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   A few contestants seemed deep in concentration, trying to make
everything perfect. Others took the ``quick and easy'' credo to
heart. Rachel Kluger, a sociology student from Palm Springs, Ca.,
chuckled when I asked her if I was bothering her. ``Are you
kidding? I'm just opening cans!''
</P>
<P>
   At about half past 10, Linda Traylor and her escort brought a
covered casserole dish filled with Broccoli-Jicama salad to the
judges for consideration. They marched past a media table. They
marched down a cordoned aisle and turned a corner to meet a phalanx
of Pillsbury execs who looked like the Men in Black.
</P>
<P>
   Head honcho Dave Schmitt clocked her in at 10:37 a.m. and handed
her a serious yellow form. ``Read this, make sure it's true, sign
the bottom line,'' he commanded. She signed and handed him the
casserole. Yummy Vegetables is serious business.
</P>
<P>
   As the Bakeoff rolled to its 1 p.m. cutoff, contestants began
putting out samples. Sally Pillsbury clutched the gold chain of her
purse as she made the rounds in the company of her nephew, and it
hung so low it swung alongside her red patent leather pumps with
red-white-and-blue houndstooth bows. She helped herself to two
servings of broccoli-jicama salad. ``Is it good?,'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmmph,'' she answered.
</P>
<P>
   As giddy contestants exited, the Doughboy stood ready for the
perpetual photo op. Though he/she couldn't talk, people could
communicate with the fleshy center by shouting into a netted hole
in the side of the costume.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, the awards were announced on a live
Oscar-style telecast hosted by TV star Phylicia Rashad
(''Cosby'').The four $10,000 categories were called up to the
stage: Easy Weeknight Meals, Yummy Vegetables, Casual Snacks &AMP;
Appetizers, and the engine that drives the Pillsbury machine, Fast
&AMP; Fabulous Desserts &AMP; Treats.
</P>
<P>
   Pillsbury staffer Sally Peters wheeled a domed platter big
enough to conceal a Sheltie onto the stage and lifted the top to
reveal Cream Cheese Brownie Pie. Bobbie Sonefeld held her hands to
her face and yelped. She was a new millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Rockwell, eat your heart out.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
