<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2309 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-KATHIELEE01-COX     02-29 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-KATHIELEE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kathie Lee calls it quits with Regis
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it the Reege Effect: Nothing can exist that exists opposite
Reege.
</P>
<P>
   Not any show that any network airs against Regis Philbin on
ABC's ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' And now not even Kathie
Lee Gifford, who for 11 years has been the other half of ``Live
With Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford announced during Tuesday's syndicated show (airing
locally at 9 a.m. on WSB) that she was leaving the popular coffee
klatch when her contract expires in July. Yet after the initial
``ooooh'' of suprise from the studio audience _ ``I was hoping you
would do that,'' Gifford said _ the show became less about her
leaving than about Philbin staying.
</P>
<P>
   Guests Lorraine Bracco (``The Sopranos'') and Dolly Parton both
arrived with roses for Philbin and joked they were ready to fill
Gifford's seat the second she left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live in New York ...'' Bracco cooed.
</P>
<P>
   No replacement has been announced.
</P>
<P>
   As for Philbin, he looked neither bothered by Gifford's exit,
nor excited by the prospect of replacing her. Instead, he looked
exactly like a guy who'd just signed a $20 million contract for
``Millionaire,'' and whose rich morning show contract runs through
August 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Both loved and despised for the depth of her self-absorption,
Gifford, 46, said she was tired of the public ridicule often heaped
on her children, whom she told stories about nearly every morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very thing that has made the show so successful _ host
chat _ is the thing that caused a real concern in my life that my
children be protected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gifford became a frequent subject in the tabloids in 1997 after
her husband, pro football Hall of Famer Frank Gifford, was caught
in an affair with a flight attendant, and a target of labor
activists who said her clothing line was produced in foreign
sweatshops.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, she has performed in the Broadway musical revue
``Putting It Together''; Philbin got a standing ovation the night
he walked to his seat in the theater. Gifford also has an upcoming
album, on which Parton sings backup. And last week she hosted CBS'
``Late Show With David Letterman,'' after Philbin backed out
because of a previous commitment.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
