<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MCCAIN-ART-NYT     02-29 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN AGREES TO CALIFORNIA DEBATE HE HAD PLANNED TO MISS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKTON, Calif. _ Sen. John McCain did an about-face Tuesday,
agreeing to participate in a planned Republican debate in
California on Thursday and challenging Gov. George W. Bush to two
other debates before next week's string of crucial primaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've accepted every offer and we're not the ones who have
ever turned down debates,'' McCain told reporters traveling with
him on his campaign bus.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator said that he had decided to change his
campaign schedule, canceling a planned rally in Long Island on
Thursday so that he would be able to participate by satellite in
the debate sponsored by CNN and The Los Angeles Times. The forum is
the only Republican debate scheduled in the nation's most populous
state, and it comes five days before the high-stakes primary.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Bush and Alan Keyes faced each other Tuesday in
primaries in Virginia and Washington state and in a caucus in North
Dakota. But that trio of races served as a mere warm-up to next
week's so-called ``Mega Tuesday'' primaries, when Republicans vote
for their presidential nominee in 11 states _ New York, California,
Connecticut, Georgia, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, Missouri,
Ohio, Rhode Island and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had baffled rivals and supporters alike with his
announcement last Sunday that he was withdrawing from the Los
Angeles debate. His aides said that he had decided to pull out of
the debate to campaign in New York, which also holds its primary
next Tuesday. The McCain campaign said that it had agreed to the
debate weeks ago, but that Bush had only consented last week after
his losses in Michigan and in Arizona. By then, McCain aides said,
the Arizona senator had made other plans.
</P>
<P>
   His decision to participate was an abrupt reversal. On his
campaign bus en route to a town hall meeting Tuesday morning in
Stockton, McCain said again that he would be a no-show at the
debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no possible way,'' McCain replied when asked by
reporters about participating. He also ruled out appearing via
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   But less than an hour later, he reversed himself and said he
would participate in the debate via satellite _ stopping in St.
Louis or Kansas City en route to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're able to adjust our schedule in order to land, cancel
events in New York and participate via satellite,'' McCain told
reporters after his town hall meeting here.
</P>
<P>
   He also challenged Bush to debates on Wednesday night on the
MSNBC news show ``Hardball,'' and on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Even some officials within the McCain campaign were quoted as
saying that his original decision to withdraw from the debate had
been a tactical error.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain wrote off his reversal Tuesday as merely a change in
scheduling that allowed him to stop mid-trip on his way back to the
East Coast and to participate in the debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give you any larger explanation than that because
that's simply the reason behind it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaigned Tuesday in Cleveland, where he met with Catholic
Charities workers at a half-finished family center. Bush used the
opportunity to try again to distance himself from criticism of his
appearance at Bob Jones University.
</P>
<P>
   ``My regret is that I didn't speak out against anti-Catholic
bias when I had the opportunity to do so,'' Bush said Tuesday. ``I
had the mike.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor expressed similar regrets Sunday in a letter
to Cardinal John O'Connor of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Bush accused McCain of making religion a campaign issue and
challenged his rival's claim that he was the political heir to
Ronald Reagan. Bush said that Reagan did not have ``a spiteful
agenda,'' an oblique reference to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an optimistic agenda as I do,'' Bush said of Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday about Bush's criticism that he had injected
religion into the race and that he was tearing apart the winning
coalition that Reagan had put together, McCain replied, ``Which
winning coalition are we talking about that stayed together?
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost the last two presidential elections, we've lost the
last two congressional elections here in California; it has been
electoral disaster,'' McCain continued. ``To somehow allude to some
winning combination flies in the face of electoral results.''
</P>
<P>
   And McCain continued his drumbeat against Pat Robertson, the
founder of the Christian Coalition, and the Rev. Jerry Falwell, the
founder of the Moral Majority.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have led our party out of the mainstream of
America, they are exclusive and not inclusive, they practice
politics of division, not addition,'' he said. ``I'm the candidate
that independents, and Democrats, and Libertarians and vegetarians
have been coming over to support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
