<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2314 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-EGYPT-DIVORCE-560(2TA     02-29 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGYPT-DIVORCE-560(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EGYPT TO EXPAND WOMEN'S DIVORCE RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ The narrow corridors of Family Court were once
painted a cheerful red, but now they are pitted and stained with a
dull brown patina of grime and the smoke from countless acrid
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The stories told in these trash-strewn hallways are just as
dismal: children abandoned, families impoverished and women trapped
in marriages they can escape only with permission from their
husbands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't find my husband,'' said Saida Muhammad Osman, a
careworn 50-year-old woman perched on the surviving half of a
broken plastic chair in the crowded hallway of the courthouse in
central Cairo. ``Every few years he comes back for a few days, but
usually I am on my own with my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Osman's hopes are as meager as her circumstances. She dreams of
one day getting a divorce so she can at least collect her dead
father's pension _ hardly a princely sum at 70 Egyptian pounds a
month, the equivalent of just over $6. Knowing her husband can
delay a final judgment for years, she fears that any relief will
come too late to do her family much good.
</P>
<P>
   But change _ no less than a social revolution _ is about to
shake the dingy halls of Egypt's crowded and melancholy courtrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Wednesday, Egypt will put in place one of the Muslim
world's most far-reaching reforms of family law. Enacted with the
support of the country's religious establishment, it makes divorce
for the first time an equal-opportunity alternative to an unhappy
marriage. Among countries in the region, only Tunisia has a similar
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before this, I really did not want my own daughter to get
married because I saw again and again the trap that a woman can be
in in this country,'' said Muhammad Amer, a Cairo lawyer who is
considered an expert on Islamic family law and who lobbied for the
changes. ``Now I'm not worried, because she can get rid of the man
when she wants.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new law, a woman will be able to divorce her husband,
with or without his assent. And she will also be able to call on
the Egyptian government to garnishee her husband's wages if he
refuses to provide for her. And if he disappears or cannot pay a
court-ordered living allowance, she will be able to draw from a
special state bank to keep her family afloat.
</P>
<P>
   When they were proposed by President Hosni Mubarak late last
year, the changes drew fierce opposition from conservative
lawmakers, who said women were too flighty to be entrusted with the
option of no-fault divorce. The proposals also were widely
lampooned in the press as the work of man-hating feminists and of
secularists who were trying to twist Islam for their own ends.
</P>
<P>
   But an alliance of moderate Muslim clerics, women's advocates,
civil court judges and divorce lawyers endorsed the reforms. In an
effort to head off a backlash from Islamic hard-liners, they
mounted a public relations effort to convince people that the law
is a modern rendering of the equal rights that Islam bestows on
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe Egyptian society is not in the best condition now to
discuss this law,'' said Fathi Naguib, an assistant justice
minister who drafted the law. ``But every society needs a shock,
one that doesn't go so far that it can't be absorbed but one that
is still a little step forward. This was a necessary and overdue
shock.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Family law is generally based on Sharia, or the 1,400-year-old
Islamic legal code, in Muslim countries, including Egypt. In
general, this has come to mean that a Muslim man can get a no-fault
divorce automatically. But a woman is entitled to one only if she
proves to a court that her husband beats her, is a drug addict, is
sterile or does not support the family.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, though, it is even harder for women. They often are
stymied by judges who discount their complaints, according to human
rights reports prepared by private organizations and the U.S. State
Department. Even when she is granted a divorce, a woman may not be
free because her husband can appeal the decree indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   In Egypt, where the civil and criminal codes are an amalgam of
secular and Islamic law, there have been occasional attempts to
eliminate what many women saw as discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, President Anwar Sadat issued a decree requiring a man
to inform his wife if he intended to marry a second wife. If she
objected, she could divorce him after a year's cooling-off period.
But the decree was later declared unconstitutional on procedural
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Sadat's successor, Mubarak, did not try to restore that law, but
he did approve the Parliament's more modest 1985 amendment that
repealed an Ottoman-era rule making it a crime for a woman to run
away from an abusive husband.
</P>
<P>
   The impetus for the new, more sweeping change in Egypt's laws
came from people who have spent years watching the system in
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dreamed of having this new law for 28 years, ever since I
was just a small judge working in the field of family law and
seeing how women suffer from the system,'' said Naguib, who
described himself as a lifelong advocate of women's rights. ``I saw
how they could stay in the courts 12, 14, 15 years without getting
a divorce. It was very painful to witness.''
</P>
<P>
   Little has changed in Egypt's divorce courts, where a total of
1.2 million cases are filed each year by both men and women, but
only about 71,000 are granted by the system's overworked judges.
</P>
<P>
   Fathi Shaheen, a gaunt man of 75, has made his living for the
last 40 years at the Shobra courthouse helping illiterate women
prepare their requests for divorce. He said he had seen more tears
than he cared to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always see women crying because they have no one to provide
for them,'' he said recently. ``These men, they are greedy and they
want to make the woman suffer, so they keep filing appeal after
appeal. In my time, men saw women as something sacred.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away, a young woman who would give her name only as
Samia leaned against a filthy wall. Dozens of people jostled around
her, trying to spot their names on a handwritten list of 150
divorce cases to be heard that day by a single judge. Samia, who
was granted a divorce three years ago on the ground that her
husband beat her, was an island of resigned calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm an expert at this,'' she said. ``I go to court all the
time because my husband keeps appealing our divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, who was trying to distract Samia's young daughter
with a cracker, chimed in. ``They treat women like animals,'' she
said. ``Why can they keep appealing? Appeals are for murderers and
criminals. Meanwhile, the man goes out and gets married and has a
happy life, while the wife has to wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with Egypt's new law, a wife who wants a divorce over the
objections of her husband will have to return to her husband any
money or property that he paid as a bride price upon the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   That provision was the price paid for the support of some of
Egypt's leading Muslim authorities. It is a specific reference to
an event from the life of the Islamic prophet Muhammad, who once
permitted an unhappy woman to leave her husband but required her to
return the garden he had given her when they married.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you touch a sensitive area like this, you must speak to
society in its language,'' Naguib said. ``And here, the language of
religion is most convincing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1801EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0276 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-AOL-MERGER01-COX     02-29 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MERGER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AOL, TIME WARNER SAY MERGER WOULD NOT DOMINATE CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The chairmen of America Online Inc. and Time Warner
Inc. told skeptical senators Tuesday that their planned mega-merger
would not create an all-controlling gatekeeper for cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the Senate Judiciary Committee began a hearing on
the pending deal, Time Warner, the world's biggest media company,
and AOL, the leading Internet service provider, pledged to open up
their combined cable TV system to rival Web-access firms.
</P>
<P>
   While the companies portrayed their agreement on cable systems
as a sensible business decision, their vow was also clearly aimed
at easing lawmakers' bipartisan concerns about the potential impact
of their giant combination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to ensuring that our merger creates new
choices for consumers and promotes a diversity of voices in the
culture,'' AOL Chairman Steve Case told the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Case's views about deal, valued at about $185 billion when it
was announced on Jan. 10, were echoed by Time Warner's Gerald
Levin, whose testimony waxed rhapsodically on the promise of the
Internet while skirting the senators' widely voiced antitrust
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Said Levin, who would head the joint company: ``Although the age
we've entered will be brutally unsparing of companies that can't or
won't move fast enough, it will also empower citizens as never
before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of what I have heard sounds good,'' Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah, the committee chairman, told the two witnesses. ``But I
believe a degree of healthy skepticism is in order given what is at
stake here.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the close of the three-hour hearing, Hatch noted that
their new open-access ``memorandum of understanding'' wasn't a
binding document and that it was ``subject to all pre-existing
(exclusionary) obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   Would Levin, Hatch wanted to know, be willing to now bind the
company to the terms?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a legal nicety,'' Levin replied. ``It's a
personal commitment. When we went into (cable modems), it was an
untested area. ... But it's clear now that there's capacity (for
other providers) in this digital bank account. So today's
commitment has true significance.''
</P>
<P>
   As laid out by Levin and Case, the new policy places no fixed
limits on the number of Internet providers who can link up to the
new company's high-speed network. Nor, squelching another potential
objection, would the company block or limit their competitors'
ability to offer video streaming _ in effect, a real-time Internet
TV program.
</P>
<P>
   To show that their hearts were in the right place, Case and
Levin arranged for the hearing to appear on the Web site of the
committee's senior Democratic member, Sen. Patrick Leahy of
Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Seated on the dais, Leahy watched himself on his wireless
laptop. He also tracked e-mail questions and comments from Internet
viewers, some of which he posed to the witnesses as the hearing
progressed. This interactive real-time feedback loop was a first in
Senate history, Leahy noted.
</P>
<P>
   Also present, although in a low-tech mode, was Sen. Mike DeWine,
R-Ohio. ``The more I examine this deal, the more I am convinced
that it does raise very significant competition and public policy
issue that must be thoroughly explored.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of same merger issues will be reviewed on Thursday in a
session called by the Senate Commerce Committee. And Hatch pledged
to hold at least one additional hearing soon to solicit the views
of consumer groups and technology and antitrust experts.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
