<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2324 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r l BC-HOME-THEMES-LADN &LR;      02-29 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-THEMES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONCE UPON A (PLAY)TIME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: This story originally moved for use Feb. 19; RETRANSMITTING
for Foster's Daily Democrat. ART was sent to NYTNS clients) 
 
 
captions: 
In the ``Pooh Corner'' of the Disney-themed playroom, 4-year-old
Justin Dial reads to his 10-month-old sister, Jessica. Phil
McCarten/Staff Photographer 
 
 
Thousand Oaks artist Doreen Behnke painted the Disney-themed
playroom at the Dial house in Agoura Hills. Phil McCarten/Staff
Photographer 
 
 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The room began as an empty canvas. But Joan Dial had an idea
and, more importantly, an artist to make her dreams and those of
her children come true.
</P>
<P>
   The result could be called Fairy Tale Magic. It's a children's
playroom where several of 4-year-old Justin Dial's favorite
characters _ including, ``Toy Story's'' Buzz and Woody, Christopher
Robin and the Seven Dwarfs _ all share wall space. Justin's baby
sister, Jessica, 10 months, doesn't have favorites just yet, but
her parents figured she might like to share a room with Snow White
and Cinderella. Artist Doreen Behnke added Tarzan and Jane after
Justin saw _ and flipped for _ the summer Disney movie.
</P>
<P>
   Male and female. For Justin and Jessica. And for any other
additions to the Dial family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted the whole upstairs for the kids to be really fun,''
said Joan Dial, who lives in Agoura Hills, ``a fun and inviting
place, something that reflects their interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooms getting a theme makeover aren't necessarily for children.
This, after all, is L.A. _ land of dreams. If you imagine it,
somebody can build it. Somebody who knows where to track down
hard-to-find items or how to get a waterfall into a bedroom. But
the more elaborate your fantasy, the more it's likely to impact
your pocket book.
</P>
<P>
   Interior designers cited specific examples: a recreation room
done with `50s soda fountains; an animator with a passion for all
things circus; a replica of the Egyptian Theatre in a subterranean
screening room; a big game hunting enthusiast who _ political
correctness aside _ insisted on decorating a room with actual
stuffed animals in his room of choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are more interested in having their living space
reflect what they believe to be a statement about themselves or
something they're really interested in,'' said Leah Vasquez, an
artist and designer based in Laguna Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed by your desire for an in-home design fantasy? You
shouldn't be, said the dream builders. A themed room is simply an
extension of that interest. The practice isn't common yet, but
there will always be a client with a mania for something.
</P>
<P>
   When they were hired to design the North Carolina recreation
room of former NASCAR racer Ernie Irvan, officials at Rancho
Cucamonga- based Penwal Industries went positively hog wild: a
symphony of chrome, from ceiling to floor, authentic gas pumps,
crankshafts and tires. Even a portion of a Formula 1 race car above
the custom-designed bar.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan had trophies and racing outfits that he wanted displayed,
but he had no idea how to pull it off. He has young children at
home, but this room was primarily for the entertainment and
pleasure of Irvan, his friends and sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Penwal designers met with the racer, submitted sketches and went
to work. The rec room was completed in three months, about half the
time it takes Penwal to do a commercial job.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the entertainment field have been creating these
props and faux finishes,'' said Diane Bader, a marketing executive
at Penwal. ``We're saying you can bring these same elements into
your home. If you want to create a storybook look, we would be the
ones to sculpt, do the molds, create the fiberglass models,
whatever it took to create that whole look.''
</P>
<P>
   The Irvan rec room was Penwal's first job, and now they're
hungry for more. Having built the company's reputation on interior
design of toy stores, movie-themed stores and a Las Vegas hotel,
Penwal is looking to bring what they have termed ``home-theming.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether they'll have competition from other commercial designers
or set builders is anybody's guess. Many design companies
accustomed to building movie sets say they aren't likely to start
assembling the Knights of the Round Table fantasy in a private
living room.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the scale they work, I don't know that my companies would
want to build two or three trees,'' said Jim Presnall, executive
director of the Themed Entertainment Association. ``We would rather
do 2,000 to 3,000 trees for a Disney project.''
</P>
<P>
   Interior designers will remind their richly dreaming clients
that any room in any house has to weather the test of time and
changing impulses. Children's rooms, bathrooms and play areas lend
themselves most easily to theming, but will your son be the same
L.A. Dodgers fanatic at age 13 that he was at age 8? If not, his
parents will be the ones forking out the bucks to change the
display.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to go to a themed restaurant and another to
live in it every day,'' said B.J. Peterson, an interior designer
who has offices in the Pacific Design Center. ``People who wax
nostalgic tend to incorporate it into a certain room of the
house.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dial rooms might be called low-key thematic. The playroom
contains shelves of carefully organized books and toys, but the
only piece of furniture that ties into the wall mural is a small
couch with a Winnie the Pooh throw pillow. Placed next to a
newsstand-style book shelf, the couch is tucked in an enclave by
the painting of Christopher Robin reading ``The Dial Fairy Tales''
to Pooh, Piglet and a couple of characters from Disney's ``A Bug's
Life.'' Together, couch and wall illustration make up a true ``Pooh
Corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the playroom was done, the process became addicting. With
Behnke's help, Dial and her husband, Greg, turned one bathroom into
an under-the-sea dreamworld _ with accessories to match. A third
bathroom, leading directly into the playroom, became a castle with
painted vines and pewter accessories.
</P>
<P>
   For the undersea bathroom, Behnke did not stop at the walls and
ceiling. Step stools match the walls; soap dishes, toothbrush
holders and towels all have oceanic elements. Inside the tub,
stencils of fish dot the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really see the kids outgrowing this,'' said Dial. ``It
can become very addicting. As you start to go, you realize how
personalized it is and how much fun it is. Justin watched Doreen
during the whole process. He was completely fascinated.''
</P>
<P>
   Behnke, who began doing murals following the birth of her
children, agrees. It's all in fun, and she gets lots of referrals
from people who see her work and are willing to let their
imaginations run free.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's endless,'' she said. ``I just did the kitchen for a
single guywho has a beach home in Malibu. It's the sky, and in the
middle, there's a great big pineapple. He loves it, and he has no
kids.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
