<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-THEATER-NAMES-ART-     02-29 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-THEATER-NAMES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A THEATER GOES THE WAY OF ARENAS, WITH AN AIRLINE NAME 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ROBIN POGREBIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Broadway's historic theaters have been named for
actors and actresses, playwrights and critics, producers and
patrons of the arts. Not until Tuesday have any of them been named
for airline companies.
</P>
<P>
   But in an $8.5 million dollar deal that may well foreshadow the
corporate renaming of a host of Broadway houses, the nonprofit
Roundabout Theater Co. is rechristening the venerable Selwyn
Theater on 42nd Street the American Airlines Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Winter Garden Theater, where ``Cats'' is expected
to close in June after nearly 18 years, may soon become the
Cadillac Theater or the Cadillac Winter Garden. The Shubert
Organization, which owns the theater, has been in discussions with
General Motors about the possibility of such a deal.
</P>
<P>
   And with some trepidation over whether widespread corporate
renaming will cheapen the theater district, officials at Broadway's
two other major chains say they are open to putting the logos of
corporations and products on their theaters as well.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists may shudder at the thought of corporations'
buying their way onto the marquees, but theater owners and
marketing experts say these alliances will grow and could become a
widespread and lucrative practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to change both the face and the economics of
Broadway,'' said Lindsey Gruson, the president and chairman of
STET, a marketing group that has been advising the Shuberts on the
Cadillac deal. ``It's a marriage made in heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   But even among some of those who would stand to benefit
financially there is uneasiness. ``The name of the game is
maximizing the value of your assets and branding them,'' said Rocco
Landesman, president of Jujamcyn, which owns five Broadway
theaters. ``But if you take a long-term view of our properties, we
certainly have other interests besides that, like maintaining the
dignity and quality of the experience of going to the theater and
protecting the buildings and protecting the American theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just marketers,'' Landesman continued. ``We're also
producers and custodians of a proud theatrical tradition. The
Walter Kerr still sounds a lot better to me than `the AT&AMP;T.'''
</P>
<P>
   The interest has arisen since Times Square's recent
transformation into a family-friendly destination as well as a wave
of corporate namings of sports stadiums, bowl games, shopping
centers and out-of-town theaters that left the historic Broadway
houses, almost all of which have official New York City landmark
status, intact. Only 42nd Street's combined and rebuilt Lyric and
Apollo playhouses took on a corporate name _ the Ford Center for
the Performing Arts _ when Livent Inc., opened the house with
`Ragtime'' in early 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Money, of course, is driving the naming trend. Roundabout's deal
with American provides for the airline _ represented by the
marketing firm Entertainment Management Group (EMG), which has
handled several musical tours and Broadway productions _ to
contribute $850,000 a year to the theater over a period of 10
years. The funds will help underwrite the operations of the
35-year-old Roundabout, which has an annual budget of about $20
million. The Selwyn, which was built in 1918 by Edgar and Arch
Selwyn, has been renovated at a cost of $21 million over the last
two years. To date the company has raised about $17.5 million from
donors including the city, board members and subscribers. It will
open for use on April 11 with previews of a new production of
Chekhov's ``Uncle Vanya.''
</P>
<P>
   American's name will remain on the marquee for the duration of
the partnership as well as on other materials associated with
theater, including all tickets and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Haimes, the artistic director of the Roundabout company,
said that naming the refurbished house the American Airlines
Theater seemed no different to him than naming it for an individual
benefactor, as the company did when it named a theater after Laura
Pels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's wonderful that a major corporation would support
the arts and want their name on our theater,'' Haimes said. ``I
don't have a philosophical problem with it.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   An executive at American, which has attached its name to sports
arenas in Miami and Dallas, said the naming would underscore its
presence in New York, where it has begun construction on a $1.3
billion terminal at John F. Kennedy Airport. ``It's one of our most
important markets,'' said Tom Gleason, the regional vice president
for American's eastern division. ``We wanted to look at a different
way of being part of the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The theater's focus on classics and musical revivals already
reduces the risk of controversial content, but what happens if the
Roundabout's artistic content comes into conflict with the
airline's corporate agenda?
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly made it completely clear that we have to have
complete control over what appears on our stage,'' Haimes said.
``And they were completely comfortable with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Birch, a senior vice president at Octagon Marketing in
Stamford, which has been working with the Shuberts, said that
Gerald Schoenfeld, chairman of the Shubert organization, had been
urged by his friend Gruson, a former correspondent for The New York
Times, to reach out for corporate alliances.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld said the deal was nowhere near consummation and
declined to discuss details. ``This is a matter that has to be
submitted to the board here,'' he said. ``I cannot tell you
anything now.''
</P>
<P>
   Birch said he was fairly certain that the Shubert partnership
with General Motors would come to pass, though he said he suspected
that the Shubert Organization would leave the names of most of its
16 theaters intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to do it,'' Birch said. ``You never know
what's going to happen, but we have met about it a few times and
it's clear that the concept works.''
</P>
<P>
   Birch said that the theater in general offers corporations an
attractive group of upscale, cultured consumers. ``I think they
realize that theater is a great target market and it's relatively
uncluttered,'' Birch said of Cadillac.
</P>
<P>
   Gust Kouvaris, a managing director at GM RWorks, a promotion and
special events company, who has been involved in the discussions,
did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the Shubert organization was a particularly
attractive partner because in addition to its theaters it owns
Telecharge, the telephone ticket service. ``They own a lot of
terrific, leverageable assets,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This, Birch said, means that Shubert has a direct line to
theatergoers by mail and telephone, providing a company like
General Motors with easy access to potential customers. ``One could
ask them, `Would you be willing to take a test drive of an
automobile to get a free ticket along with one you buy?''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To some extent, these developments are a logical extension of
the growing corporate presence on Broadway, which includes new
producers like Disney, Cablevision and SFX Entertainment, which
about a year ago renamed the Palace Theater in Chicago the Cadillac
Palace. Livent, which had a short life on Broadway, led the
corporate naming drive by setting up Ford Centers not only in New
York but in Chicago, Vancouver and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Broadway establishment has turned increasingly to a
corporate marketing. The League of American Theaters and Producers
has established partnerships with as the ``official airline of
Broadway'' and with Visa U.S.A. as the ``preferred card of
Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Minskoff theater, where ``Saturday Night Fever'' is
playing, the Nederlanders have made a deal with Mercedes-Benz to
place a car in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole issue of sponsorship is becoming an active
conversation for all theater owners,'' said Nick Scandalios,
executive vice president of the Nederlander Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Scandalios said his company would nevertheless tread lightly in
deciding whether to rename any of its nine theaters. ``It's always
a tricky thing,'' he said. ``We certainly aren't going to look at
renaming the Richard Rodgers and put a beer title over it. You have
to look at the value of a name.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
