</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARDI-GRAS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carnival parades draw millions of revelers to New Orleans
 &HT;    By Stephen J. O'Brien
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ March 3, 1699, had been going like any other day
for French explorer Pierre LeMoyne Sieur d'Iberville and his men.
The crew of haggard travelers had been exploring the southern
reaches of the Mississippi River and, at least for a night, had
found a home on her western banks near New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   They sunk their shovels into the soft earth of the Atchafalaya
Basin and pitched camp. Noting the day was being observed around
the world as the pre-Lenten festival of Mardi Gras, Iberville
called the spot Point du Mardi Gras.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the party started.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Mardi Gras Creole-style has become one of the
biggest, baddest parties on Earth. Though other cities, including
Galveston, also celebrate the pre-Lenten occasion, New Orleans is
the uncontested Mardi Gras capital of the United States. Official
celebrations there started Feb. 20 and culminate on fat Tuesday,
which this year falls on March 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going back to 1699 and the first parade, one thing is a
constant,'' said Beverly Gianna, vice president of public affairs
for the New Orleans Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``Everybody
loves a parade.''
</P>
<P>
   And when Gianna says ``everybody,'' she means everybody. The
12-day parade season preceding Ash Wednesday attracts millions of
revelers to the Big Easy.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, there is no theme for Mardi Gras, but as Gianna puts
it, the general mood is understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitude is the way (people in New Orleans) live their
culture,'' she said. ``It's not something that we have to
manufacture, a mood we have to create. It's about having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration of Mardi Gras, or fat Tuesday, is followed by
Ash Wednesday and Lenten observations that call on Catholics to
make personal sacrifices leading up to Easter. Mardi Gras can occur
on any Tuesday from Feb. 3 through March 9. The date fluctuates
because it is tied to Easter, which is a floating religious holiday
set by the Catholic church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parades always evolve,'' Gianna said. ``They've gotten
bigger and more elaborate, but the fun is always the same. Families
get together, put costumes on, stake out their spots along the
parade routes and bring their picnic baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   Mardi Gras actually means ``fat Tuesday'' in French, but the
celebration has grown far beyond a meager one-day party in places
such as New Orleans and Rio de Janeiro, Brazil. In New Orleans,
Mardi Gras includes elaborate private balls that start each year
Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Parish ordinance dictates that the New Orleans Mardi Gras parade
season not officially begin until the second Friday before fat
Tuesday. During the 12-day period, nearly 60 parades are held in
the four-parish area of Orleans, Jefferson, St. Bernard and St.
Tammany, according to the ``Arthur Hardy's Mardi Gras Guide.'' The
New Orleans parades and street parties attract close to a million
people each night during the three days leading up to the night of
fat Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what police estimate, but it's hard to determine
exactly how many show up,'' said Arthur Hardy. ``We don't sell
tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest celebrations are the parades known as Bacchus,
Endymion and Orpheus, which are always held the three nights before
fat Tuesday. They feature a total of 110 floats and 90 marching
bands. From their floats, thousands of parade organizers throw more
than 2 million cups, 3.5 million Mardi Gras coins and 400,000
strings of beads.
</P>
<P>
   The official colors of Mardi Gras are purple, gold and green.
Although originally selected because of their aesthetic appeal, the
colors have taken on symbolic meaning: purple for justice, green
for faith and gold for power.
</P>
<P>
   Mardi Gras in New Orleans generated $929 million in the
metropolitan area during the carnival season, according to an
economic impact study by Dr. James McLain of the University of New
Orleans. Before the age of recycling, though, the success of Mardi
Gras in New Orleans was judged by how much trash was generated. In
the 1980s, the 12-day parading season annually generated more than
2,000 tons of trash.
</P>
<P>
   Although other cities are attracting more attention annually for
their Mardi Gras festivities, Hardy said New Orleans will continue
in its role as Mardi Gras headquarters for the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of the people who might be going to Mardi Gras
celebrations outside New Orleans wouldn't be coming here anyway,''
Hardy said. ``I don't think there's anywhere that could compare in
quality and quantity.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information on New Orleans' Mardi Gras celebration,
call the New Orleans Convention and Visitors Bureau at (504)
566-5031.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
