<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE HISTORICAL PARK GETTING READY FOR TEXAS BIRTHDAY EVENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Texas _ Texas will be 164 years old Thursday, and it
is here, among spreading live oaks and ancient native pecans, that
the official birthday party will take place this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It was at this location, in what is now the
Washington-on-the-Brazos State Historical Park, that 59 delegates
met in a hastily and ill-prepared meeting hall to claim Texas'
independence March 2, 1836.
</P>
<P>
   Winter winds whipped through the gaps in the walls as they
received word that the Alamo was under siege. William Barrett
Travis, commanding the Texas forces there, made his impassioned
plea, calling on the convention ``in the name of Liberty, of
patriotism, and of everything dear to the American character, to
come to our aid with all dispatch.''
</P>
<P>
   Park officials expect 10,000 to 15,000 visitors this weekend to
tour a re-creation of the Independence Hall, view the exhibits in
the state-of-the-art visitors center, tour the Star of the Republic
Museum and to celebrate the opening of the park's new living
history farm.
</P>
<P>
   The Barrington Living History Farm is the final link in the
park's $6 million improvement package. Scattered along the Brazos
River bottom, the farm is named after Anson Jones' plantation,
which was about five miles from the park. Jones was the last
president of the Republic of Texas and the man who oversaw the
transition to statehood.
</P>
<P>
   ``This completes the story,'' said Barrington Farm manager Bill
Irwin. ``Independence Hall, the town site, all tell the story of
early colonization of Texas. The Star of the Republic Museum does a
great job of telling the story of the 10 years of Texas'
independence; and the farm and the last president speak to the
transition from a republic _ a raw frontier _ to a civilized state
in the union.''
</P>
<P>
   The farm is clearly the jewel of this majestic park. Jones'
home, a 2-story, dogtrot frame, has been beautifully restored. It's
at the farm's center with barns, slave quarters, a kitchen,
smokehouse and chicken coop distributed throughout the flat river
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farm represents a different form of interpretive history,
living history,'' Irwin said. ``You can touch it, feel it, smell it
and taste it. It allows us to use a different technique to teach
the past and its importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Five full-time workers assist Irwin with the farm. They wear
period clothing and take on the same kinds of tasks that people in
the 1850s would have. They tend a quarter-acre garden, a cornfield,
cotton field, cattle, pigs and chickens.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have a 100-tree orchard with peach, pear, cherry and
plum trees,'' Irwin said. ``This all came from Jones' account books
and diaries. He kept good track of his planting _ when he planted
and the varieties.''
</P>
<P>
   All farm produce will be used on the farm. The chickens will
provide eggs, meat and feathers. The livestock could end up in the
smokehouse, and the grain crops will be used for animal feed.
</P>
<P>
   Workers will gin, spin and weave the cotton.
</P>
<P>
   The farm will officially open Saturday. Staff and volunteers
will populate the farm, as well as the reconstructed town site.
Visitors can walk among blacksmiths, woodcarvers, furniture makers
and weavers. A ceremony honoring the convention delegates will take
place Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington-on-the-Brazos State Park Association sponsors the
annual two-day birthday celebration, for which admission is free.
The park is on Farm Road 1155 off Texas 105 between Brenham and
Navasota. For more information, call (409) 878-2214.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
