<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, March 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, temperatures soared into the 60s across the western
Great Lakes as breezes from the south imported unseasonably mild
air into the region. Wednesday, the axis of warmth will shift
eastward, causing 60-degree readings to reach as far north as
Pennsylvania and New Jersey. The day will dawn with sunshine across
the Northeast, however clouds will thicken during the afternoon
ahead of an approaching cold front.
</P>
<P>
   A narrow corridor of showers will accompany the cold front as it
presses eastward through the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley. Isolated
thundershowers may also form as a jet stream disturbance passing
overhead augments the ascent of a moistened air mass. Gusty breezes
from the northwest will follow the front, bringing cooler air to
the upper Middle West and northern Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Plentiful sunshine will promote another day of unusual warmth in
the Southeast, where temperatures reach into the 70s in most areas.
Eighty degree readings will be common over the Florida peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   A vigorous jet stream disturbance will spiral through the
southwest Rockies on Wednesday, causing locally heavy snow
throughout the mountains of northern Arizona and southern Utah.
Later Wednesday night, the disturbance will reach the south-central
states, setting the stage for strong thunderstorms to erupt in
western Texas and Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Generally dry weather will cover the West Coast, although there
will be showers on the Northwest coast Wednesday afternoon as moist
Pacific air is lifted by an approaching cold front.
</P>
<P>
   When Winter Ends
</P>
<P>
   While the calendar indicates that winter isn't over until March
20, many meteorologists would say that the season has already
ended. The event commemorated on the calendar is the end of
astronomical winter, a time when the most direct rays of the sun
shift from the southern to the northern hemisphere. For the
purposes of official climate records, winter began on Dec. 1, 1999
and ended on Feb. 29, 2000. According to another unofficial
measurement, winter will pass on March 5th, the end of the coldest
90-day period of the year in most of the northern United States.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
