The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Wednesday, March 1. If you
have any questions, please call The Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
IMAC (Phoenix) - AZW.Com, a San Jose based site for teens, held a
contest to give away an iMac. It launched a search of the winner
and found Myra Jodie, 13, who lives in a remote area without a
telephone. She had entered the contest surfing the internet on her
teacher's desk top. By BETTY REID. Story will move in the `A`
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ONEOK (Phoenix) - Oneok Inc., which last month withdrew its $912
million offer for Southwest Gas Corp., is seeking $85 million in
damages from the state on grounds Corporation Commission Chairman
Carl Kunasek and his aid Jerry Porter improperly prejudiced the
deal. By MAX JARMAN. Story will move in the `A` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PM10 (Phoenix) -In the first two months of the year, Maricopa
County air-quality officials have written six citations for
violating dust rules. That's as many as they wrote in all of 1999.
County officials, with the federal government breathing down their
necks, say they're getting tougher on dust violators. To prove it,
they now have 14 offenses for which they plan to issue immediate
citations, up from the old list of two. By MARY JO PITZL. Story
will move in the `A` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TV-GOODY (Undated) - Anyone who has watched one of Errol Morris'
films knows how brilliantly he captures people's obsessions. Turns
out Morris is a bit obsessed himself. Not with building a better
electric chair or finding out all there is to know about the naked
mole rat, as some of his subjects were. Morris is obsessed with the
interview. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story will move in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
