<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, March 1 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   ELN-RDP (Richmond, Va.) _ A ledeall on the voting, beginning
with Virginia; North Dakota and Washington will be wrapped in
later. By Richard L. Berke. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   With daily photos of Bradley, Bush, Gore and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ELN-ASSESS (Richmond, Va.) _ A news analysis on the voting. By
R.W. Apple Jr. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   ALA-DEATH-PENALTY (Opelika, Ala.) _ At a time of a nationwide
debate over the quality of legal defenses in death penalty cases,
Alabama is close to the bottom of the barrel. There, divorce
lawyers moonlight defending death penalty case for as little as $5
dollars an hour. Alabama ranks second or third per capita in the
country in number of death row inmates. By Sara Rimer.
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-U.S. (Beijing) _ A request by Taiwan to purchase some of
the United States' most advanced defensive weapons is causing a
split within the Clinton administration and threatens to complicate
the delicate three-way relationship among Taiwan, China and the
United States. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EGYPT-DIVORCE (Cairo) _ A new divorce law takes effect in Egypt
on Wednesday that greatly expands women's rights. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   (MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-TORTURE-TRIAL (Dakar) _ The torture case against Hissene
Habre, the former president of Chad who is now under arrest in
Senegal, will be watched closely in Africa, where brutal rulers
have engaged in widespread human rights violations with impunity.
It has already stirred some impassioned comments among African
intellectuals, some of whom defend Habre by arguing that guilt
cannot be assigned to African leaders of his generation, because
they were merely creations and pawns of Cold War superpowers. By
Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOSP-FINE (New York) _ In one of its harshest actions against
a New York City hospital in over a decade, the state Department of
Health on Tuesday cited Staten Island University Hospital for 40
violations and fined the hospital $80,000 for failing to monitor
and discipline its chief of neurosurgery, who the state said, among
other things, operated on the wrong side of a patient's brain, for
the second time in five years. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
</TEXT>
