<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2350 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS &LR;      02-29 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MCCAIN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     McCAIN FACES TOUGH RACES IN CALIFORNIA AND NEW YORK  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL and DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. John McCain faces an increasingly tough race
in next Tuesday's presidential primary in New York because Roman
Catholic voters are responding to Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
apology for his comments at Bob Jones University, a New York-based
pollster said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   John Zogby, a Utica, N.Y.-based pollster without ties to any
presidential candidate, said McCain's narrow lead over Bush in New
York is vulnerable because of continued movement toward Bush by
Roman Catholic voters. Another factor, he said, was the tens of
thousands of pro-Bush telephone calls orchestrated by the political
organization of New York Gov. George Pataki and state GOP chair
William Powers.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby said the 16 percentage point edge that McCain held over
Bush among Roman Catholic voters as recently as last Saturday has
been eliminated by Bush's apology to Cardinal John O'Connor and the
repetition of his apology on a daily basis. Roman Catholics make up
about 45 percent of New York's GOP primary electorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually have Bush pulling ahead among Catholics by a few
points _ enough to make it a trend _ still a statistical dead heat
but a tremendous turnaround among Catholics,'' Zogby said.
``Perhaps the letter has taken hold.''
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Democratic Gov. Gray Davis of California told
reporters that McCain faces an uphill fight in the GOP primary in
the Golden State in which only the votes of registered Republicans
will be counted in the selection of the state's slate of 162
delegates to the GOP national convention.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, a veteran of the Vietnam War who praised McCain's service
as a downed Navy pilot imprisoned by North Vietnam for more than
five years, said McCain needs wider appeal than heroic military
service to carry California in his struggle with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California, it is not enough to have served your country, a
candidate must champion the issues,'' Davis said, adding that
McCain, like Bush, is ``on the wrong side of issues that matter to
Californians'' such as environmental protection, gun control and
abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   Bush retains a comfortable lead over McCain in California,
according to The San Francisco Examiner poll conducted for the
newspaper and KTVU-TV by the Research 2000 polling organization in
Rockville, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Bush outpaces McCain 28 percent to 24 percent among all
California voters but the Texas governor's lead over McCain
mushrooms to 41 percent to 30 percent among the Republican voters
whose votes alone will be counted in the selection of the state's
GOP convention delegates. The poll, which has a margin of error of
plus or minus 3.5 percentage points, was conducted Feb. 21 through
23 among 803 Californians who say they regularly vote. Among
Republican voters only, the margin of error is 6 percentage points
because the sample size is smaller.
</P>
<P>
   California and New York, the two most populous states in the
nation, together award a total of 263 delegates to the GOP
nominating convention _ 25 percent of the total of 1,034 needed by
a candidate to secure the GOP presidential nomination. The
delegates in both states will be selected in winner-take-all
primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's apology has far less impact in California, where Roman
Catholics make up about 28 percent of the state's electorate. But
in New York, where Roman Catholics are about 45 percent of the
state's GOP primary electorate, Bush's apology is having a wider
impact.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, the latest Zogby International survey completed
Monday shows McCain just 1.4 percentage points ahead of Bush _ a
statistical dead heat in a survey with a margin of error of 4.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Zogby said McCain's edge among Roman Catholic voters has
been erased by Bush, who now leads McCain among Roman Catholics, 43
percent to 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   McCain continues to criticize Bush for failing to repudiate the
anti-Catholic teachings and prohibitions on inter-racial dating at
Bob Jones University in South Carolina when he spoke there Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   McCain defended his criticisms of Bush in remarks in Stockton,
Calif., on Tuesday, saying Bush's remarks at a school associated
with anti-Catholic bias was ``a fair issue for me to raise.''
</P>
<P>
   Campaign manager Rick Davis said the McCain campaign continued
making authorized ``Catholic voter alert'' telephone calls to
voters in Washington state in advance of Tuesday's primary to
remind voters that Bush had spoken at Bob Jones University _ ``the
same Bob Jones who said the Pope was ``the Anti-'Christ`` and
called the Church ``a satanic cult.''
</P>
<P>
   The calls added, according to the campaign transcript: ``Sen.
John McCain has strongly criticized this anti-Catholic bigotry,
while Gov. Bush stayed silent while gaining the support of Bob
Jones University.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush addressed several thousand students and faculty at the
predominantly southern Baptist school on Feb. 2 in a bid to rally
Christian conservatives in South Carolina following a stinging 19
percentage point loss to McCain the night before in the New
Hampshire presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy paid off for Bush in the short term, igniting an
unprecedented GOP turnout in South Carolina's Feb. 19 primary that
enabled the two-term Texas governor to defeat McCain, 53 percent to
42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush has paid a political price among Roman Catholic voters
in large industrial states. Bush lost to McCain in Michigan last
Tuesday in part because McCain's campaign aides made telephone
calls to Roman Catholic voters
</P>
<P>
   that helped swell the turnout, enabling McCain to overwhelm
Bush, 51 percent to 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to O'Connor, bush said, ``On reflection, I should
have been more clear in disassociating myself from anti-Catholic
sentiments and racial prejudice.'' His appearance at Bob Jones
University was ``a missed opportunity, causing needless offense,
which I deeply regret,`` Bush wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush reiterated his regrets on Tuesday, telling Catholic
Charities workers at a campaign stop in Cleveland, Ohio: ``My
regret is that I didn't speak out against anti-Catholic bias when I
had the opportunity to do so. I had the mike.''.
</P>
<P>
   Zogby said his latest polling in New York detects a ``tremendous
turnaround'' by Bush among Roman Catholic voters.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain has hope among the rank and file Republican voters,
Zogby said, in part because of the state GOP leadership's
ham-handed effort to keep McCain's delegates off the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he has got to count on is that people are turned on by
his biography and turned off by the behavior of the Republican
party _ and then there's a shot,'' Zogby said. ``He's
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the
e-mail address stewart(at)hearstdc.com )
</P>
</TEXT>
