<HEADLINE>
KATHIE LEE GIFFORD SAYS SHE'LL CALL IT QUITS THIS SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From now until her announced departure from the morning
airwaves, Kathie Lee Gifford can expect to hear a question made
famous by her cohost, Regis Philbin:
</P>
<P>
   Is that your final answer?
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it is. Tuesday, Gifford, 46, startled ``Live With
Regis and Kathie Lee'' viewers by saying she would not renew her
contract with the popular talk show, which expires in August.
Gifford cited family concerns, not contractual issues, as her
reason for moving on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started together,'' Gifford told Philbin, ``I was not
married, I was childless, and the world was a different kind of
place, too. We could make jokes about things and tell what we did
last night without anyone taking it and sensationalizing it and
making it disgusting and lurid and horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   All that has changed, Gifford suggested, now that her children
are older and the boundaries between her personal life and TV
persona seem more important to maintain. Cody and Cassidy Gifford
are 10 and 7 years old, respectively, and practically since birth
their every burp and boo-boo has been fodder for Gifford and
Philbin's breezy top-of-the-show banter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very thing that has made the show so successful _ host
chat _ is the thing that caused a real concern in my life that my
children be protected,'' explained Gifford, who has hinted at
retirement before _ though never so forcefully _ when contract
negotiations loomed.
</P>
<P>
   Philbin seemed to take the bombshell in stride, treating it
seriously while joking that he might not need a cohost at all once
Gifford leaves. He and Gifford have been paired together for 15
years, the last 12 in national syndication as the king and queen of
happy chat. There has been speculation that Joy Philbin, Regis's
wife and a perennial guest host on the show, might fill Gifford's
shoes if she ever did step down.
</P>
<P>
   However, according to general manager Mike Carson of WHDH-TV
(Ch. 7), which carries ``Live'' in Boston, the show's producers
informed him Tuesday that a search would be conducted for a new
cohost who would ``preserve the show's chemistry,'' in Carson's
words, but that no such selection had been made yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody seems terribly concerned,'' says Carson, ``which is not
to say Kathie Lee doesn't bring a special dimension to the show.
She does.''
</P>
<P>
   Gifford has also suffered her share of public travails in recent
years, one reason why she may have decided to lower her profile.
Her girl-next-door image was tarnished by revelations that a line
of designer clothes bearing her name was being manufactured under
sweatshop conditions, and that her husband, ABC sportscaster Frank
Gifford, had conducted an extramarital tryst, which was splashed
across the tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Philbin has seen his own star soar to unprecedented
heights _ one more reason why Gifford may sense the limelight
dimming on their partnership. As host of the phenomenally
successful ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire,'' Philbin recently
signed a reported $20 million-a-year deal with ABC. Philbin and
Gifford have also substituted for David Letterman on CBS's ``Late
Show'' and Gifford has been starring on Broadway weekly in
``Putting It Together.'' There are also, of course, Gifford's
cruise ship commercials and Christmas specials, none of which is
dependent on Philbin for star support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Live'' remains a powerhouse ratings draw. With two days to go
in the current ratings book, according to Carson, the show is
averaging a 5.2 in Boston _ nearly double that of its nearest
competitor. Nationally the show is tied for fourth (with ``Montel
Williams'') among syndicated talk shows, trailing only those by
Oprah Winfrey, Jerry Springer, and Rosie O'Donnell.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1833EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0301 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2353 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-29 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLITICS IN THE NAME OF GOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Since the birth of the nation, religion has
influenced political campaigns but usually in indirect, underground
ways that are hard to quantify.
</P>
<P>
   In this primary season, however, religious tension is playing a
central role not seen since John F. Kennedy was forced to publicly
confront Protestant fears of his Catholicism during the 1960
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain
have all ostentatiously paraded their faith in God before various
audiences. Bush even cites Jesus Christ as his favorite political
philosopher. Only former Sen. Bill Bradley keeps his religious
views to himself.
</P>
<P>
   But the real religious crunch has come in the McCain-Bush
contest. Bush agents on the religious right are trying to paint
McCain as bigoted against Christian conservatives, and McCain
agents are trying to paint Bush as bigoted against Catholics. Up
front and out in the open, both claim the other is intolerant of
opposing views and biased against religious voters.
</P>
<P>
   After Ronald Reagan invited the Christian right into the
Republican Party in 1980 by backing constitutional amendments to
support school prayer and oppose abortion, the evangelical movement
swiftly came to dominate the GOP. Conservative Christians are now a
fourth to a third of party voters with even heavier concentrations
in some states.
</P>
<P>
   But Catholics were also attracted by Reagan's conservatism and
anti-communism. With Reagan gone, the coalition of Catholics and
born-again Christians is coming unglued, and now Catholics divide
their support almost equally between Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's task is to pry those voters away from Bush while still
appealing to independents and moderates who are put off by
religious zealots. Bush's task is to hold them without getting
pushed so far to the right that he cannot return to the middle in
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   McCain decided to go for broke when he attacked by name two
icons of the Christian right in their own home base of Virginia on
the eve of the state's GOP primary. ``Neither party should be
defined by pandering to the outer reaches of American politics and
the agents of intolerance whether they be Louis Farrakhan or Al
Sharpton on the left or Pat Robertson or Jerry Falwell on the
right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a brave speech, one that should have been made by all
presidential candidates of both parties long ago. It was a
politically defining moment that will have repercussions far beyond
this year's election returns. McCain is destined to make history
for breaking eggs whether he makes it to the White House or not.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, for his part, is on the defensive. No such vision of party
reformation for him. He apologized to New York Cardinal John
O'Connor for sending the wrong signal by appearing at Bob Jones
University without condemning its officials' anti-Catholic views.
In his apology, he lamely regretted not being ``more clear in
disassociating myself from (the) anti-Catholic sentiments and
racial prejudice'' of the school's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   More clear? At the university he didn't mention the subject at
all. Bush's problem is that he represents the status quo, which
does not encourage substantive distinctions between the bad and the
good in the party establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy became the first Catholic president because he
understood, as McCain does and Bush does not, that it was necessary
to tackle the religious issue directly and fearlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy had been accused of being ``a captive of a system'' by
prominent Protestant clergymen. They claimed his church was
determined ``to breach the wall of separation of church and state''
and that his presidency would undermine the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy eloquently defended himself in a televised appearance
before them in Houston. He said, ``What kind of church I believe in
should be important only to me.'' He asked to be judged on his
record, not his religion. ``I do not speak for my church on public
matters, and the church does not speak for me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy derailed the issue, but it did not entirely die. Three
hundred different anti-Catholic tracts were distributed to more
than 20 million homes. His opponent, Richard Nixon, kept the
subject alive by continually deploring religious bigotry. In the
end, defensive Catholics rallied to Kennedy, and Protestants proved
they were not bigots. But Kennedy's margin of victory was only a
half of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy won because he convinced the country he would not dig a
tunnel to the Vatican. For McCain to win, he has to convince
Republicans that he will not throw the GOP baby out with the
religious bath water. In politics, there are limits.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1835EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
