<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0302 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-AUSTRRIA-HAIDER-BOS &LR;      02-29 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTRRIA-HAIDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS STILL NERVOUS ABOUT AUSTRIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Most of the European governments that diplomatically
isolated Austria when Joerg Haider's far-right Freedom Party gained
power last month said Tuesday that his resignation as party leader
has done nothing to ease their concerns about the party's extremist
views.
</P>
<P>
   If one of Haider's goals was to ease the barrage of diplomatic
sanctions and international condemnation aimed at Austria,
including the European Union's refusal to name Austrian officials
to international posts, there was no indication that would happen
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Many European leaders vowed to keep up the pressure on Austria,
saying they believed Haider's resignation Monday was a cynical ploy
and that he would continue to call the shots from the remote
province of Carinthia, where he is governor.
</P>
<P>
   Haider's domestic enemies were similarly defiant, vowing to
continue the weekly street protests in Vienna to demand the Freedom
Party's removal from government.
</P>
<P>
   From London to Berlin, from Lisbon to Brussels, the leaders of
the mostly left-of-center governments across Europe charged that
Haider still wants to be Austria's chancellor and that the
colleagues who assumed his party's leadership harbor xenophobic
sentiments that are antithetical to the European Union and its
plans to expand. Haider's sympathetic remarks about Nazis have also
caused alarm in capitals around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Freedom Party wants to halt immigration and is skeptical
about expanding the 15-nation European Union to include eastern
European countries that border Austria. Capitalizing on
anti-immigrant sentiment in a country with the third-highest
percentage of foreigners in Europe, the party contends that
immigrants take jobs and commit a disproportionate amount of crime,
and say EU expansion will make the problems worse. Austria has one
of the lowest unemployment rates in the west, at 4.2 percent, and
is one of Europe's most affluent countries.
</P>
<P>
   Most European governments said they believe Haider's gesture was
purely tactical, intended to ease the international pressure aimed
at Austria since the Freedom Party formed a coalition with the
mainstream conservative People's Party. The controversy has
tarnished Austria's image and hurt its important tourist industry.
Some skiiers have stayed away from the Austrian Alps, and many
touring artists and celebrities have refused to perform in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese government, which holds the presidency of the
European Union, said there is no immediate prospect of restoring
normal diplomatic relations with Austria.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is not Joerg Haider but what his party
represents,'' said Antonio Guterres, Portugal's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Israel was similarly unimpressed, saying it will not allow its
ambassador to return to Vienna. He was recalled last month.
</P>
<P>
   In London, a Downing Street spokesman said that it still
considers the Freedom Party extremist, and that British Prime
Minister Tony Blair is concerned ``with policies, not
personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   In Berlin, a spokesman for the German foreign ministry said he
doubts Haider's move would be enough to lift the EU sanctions and
said the German government's position ``is unchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Washington's sentiments are similar to
those voiced in European capitals. ``The EU statement is a pretty
good capturing of how we all feel right now,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Schuessel, the Austrian chancellor, praised Haider's
gesture as generous and pleaded for the European Union to give
Vienna's government a chance to prove it is not xenophobic and
opposed to EU expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I interpret it as a symbol that he wants to support this
government but also that he wants to take a personal responsibility
for easing the tensions with our partners in the EU,'' Schuessel
told reporters in Vienna.
</P>
<P>
   Lamberto Dini, Italy's foreign minister, seemed to hint that his
country would be willing to see whether Austria would behave ``more
in sync with European Union objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then we can see if we can establish normal relations with a
country that has been such a friend of Italy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice Chancellor Susanne Riess-Passer, Haider's closest aide,
took over as party leader and said she is determined to prove that
``the prejudices against the Freedom Party are not justified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
