<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BARAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK TO BARGAINING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A dramatic step was taken on the path toward an Israeli-Syrian
peace agreement Sunday when Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak told
his Cabinet that Yitzhak Rabin, before his assassination in 1995,
had given conditional assurances to Syria that Israel would
withdraw completely from the Golan Heights as part of a
comprehensive peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's swiftly leaked disclosure was interpreted as a trial
balloon meant to prepare Israeli public opinion for the compromises
that will be necessary to forge a peace treaty with Syria. But
since Barak is committed to a referendum on any deal struck with
Syria's ruler, Hafez Assad, there can be no true gauge of public
opinion until Israelis are presented the actual terms of a
negotiated peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Hence the primary effect of Barak's revelation is to signal that
Israel now acknowledges Syrian contentions about Rabin's
conditional offer and tacitly accepts Assad's demand that
bargaining begin where it left off five years ago. One implication
of this signal from Barak is that Assad no longer has any excuse
for refusing to talk nor any justification for allowing the
Hezbollah militia to expand military operations in southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   With this gesture of accommodation, Barak has invited Assad back
to the bargaining table. It is now up to the Syrian dictator to end
his boycott of the American-sponsored talks and to begin telling
Israel what kind of security arrangements he is willing to make on
the Golan and in southern Lebanon. Israel must have the means to
assure ample warning time of any attack from Syrian soil. Assad
also has to reveal what he proposes to do about water resources and
what degree of normalization he is ready to accept in trade and
cultural exchanges with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Henceforth a peace treaty is there for the taking. If Assad
truly wants peace with Israel, he can have it. He can have the
Golan Heights back and return to the lines of June 4, 1967,
provided that Syrian sovereignty does not reach to the shore of the
Sea of Galilee. Israel can have peace on all its borders provided
that it withdraws from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   This bargain, which may be struck this spring, suits the vital
interests of both countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
