<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STRAWBERRY-NYTR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY COULDN'T SAY NO AND NEITHER COULD BASEBALL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB PADECKY   The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   c.2000
N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX, Ariz. _ Great musings always have entertained us in
baseball. What if Mickey Mantle had good knees and Sandy Koufax a
good elbow? What if Ted Williams hadn't fought in two wars and
Willie Mays didn't have to fight the wind at Candlestick Park? What
if the Negro Leagues didn't face racism?
</P>
<P>
   What if Darryl Strawberry put only a Kleenex to his nose?
</P>
<P>
   What if Strawberry hadn't been treated like a man of privilege?
</P>
<P>
   What if baseball had stopped playing the sucker to him?
</P>
<P>
   What if there hadn't been so many what ifs about Darryl
Strawberry?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he wouldn't be considered what he is today, a loser.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had incredible talent that transcended his age and his
team,'' said Giants general manager Brian Sabean. ``But maybe
everyone told the lie often enough that Darryl convinced himself
that it was the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the lie: Strawberry needed to stay in baseball to
become clean and sober; maybe that's the lie you have to tell when
you label a Los Angeles teen-ager the black Babe Ruth. The truth
is, however, a lie is a lie. It is one perpetuated even at this
very moment, as Strawberry was suspended Monday for the third time
in his career for substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Darryl needs baseball,'' said Yankee second baseman
Chuck Knoblauch, ``and I hope he gets to rehabilitate and he has
another chance (to play again).''
</P>
<P>
   The inference is, without baseball Strawberry's very life is in
danger.
</P>
<P>
   As if it's not now?
</P>
<P>
   As if baseball cleaned him up before?
</P>
<P>
   As if the game has been the sanctuary to make him whole again?
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch should look at it this way: Charisse Strawberry was
four months pregnant when her husband tested positive. Does
Knoblauch, or baseball for that matter, need a more telling example
of how dangerous Strawberry is to himself right now?
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry doesn't need baseball. He doesn't need the cocoon. He
doesn't need the fantasy world that a professional athlete
inhabits, one that has made Strawberry a well-known and easy mark
to every dealer in every American big city.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry needs reality. Strawberry needs to figure out why he
can't say no. In 1994, for example, he joined the Giants and was
given specific instructions. To simplify his life, Strawberry was
not to grant any one-on-one interviews, the desire for the media to
explore his problems would be never ending and distracting. He
needed to focus. Strawberry agreed. That instruction was repeated
the day before the Giants flew to New York to play the Mets,
Strawberry's old team.
</P>
<P>
   On the day he arrived at Shea Stadium, Strawberry was giving a
New York sportswriter a one-on-one interview. When a Giants
official asked Strawberry later why he did that, when he had just
agreed the day before he wouldn't, Strawberry replied, ``I didn't
want to hurt his feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't say no and neither could baseball. Strawberry was
given second chances because _ other than Ken Griffey Jr. _ no one
in baseball in the last 15 years had such a rhythmic swing. Others
generated as much power but watching Strawberry's whisk through the
strike zone was like melting butter. It just flowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to control,'' Sabean said, ``that which we
cannot.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's the lesson Darryl Strawberry has taught us. Try as
baseball did, as well-intentioned as the sport may have been, it
didn't help the black Babe Ruth become the black Babe Ruth. Maybe
no one could. We'll never know.
</P>
<P>
   What we do know is that Darryl Strawberry will never have
fulfilled his promise, even with 335 homers and 1,000 RBIs. Even
with the real possibility, as crazy as this sounds, that another
team, maybe even the Yankees, will employ him in 2001. Darryl
Strawberry always will be a song never completely sung.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Koufax and his elbow, we won't spend much time
deliciously reminiscing about Darryl and his nose. The man had
control of the pain this body part caused. Sandy didn't. That
doesn't leave us wistful. That leaves us with a sour taste in our
mouth, made all the more sour because the man had such a sweet
swing.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Padecky writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif.
The Press Democrat is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
