<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SCREEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING IN NEWBORN CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a year now, newborn babies in Massachusetts have undergone a
sophisticated test that detects 30 inherited diseases. With early
intervention, many disorders can be stopped from developing or
their effects curbed. Without timely detection, some of the
disorders can kill or disable their victims.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts is a pioneer in using tandem mass spectrometry to
screen for these conditions, many of which are related to the
child's metabolism. Yet while experience in Massachusetts shows the
benefits of such testing, it also shows why it must be teamed with
follow-up and counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Expense is one reason this testing is not done in more states.
Each full test costs $20 to $50, with the higher figure including
tracking and counseling. In Massachusetts, state law requires the
testing and follow-up, which insurers cover.
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics argue that the money might be better spent on more
prenatal care or to make sure all pregnant women get enough of the
vitamin folic acid, lack of which causes birth defects. But early
detection can save lives and head off lifelong conditions that are
expensive to treat.
</P>
<P>
   Another concern: With some rare diseases, the technology used
for detection has outstripped understanding of how to deal with the
disorder. Elevated results ``will cause parental anxiety for
disorders that are not well defined at this time,'' says Dr. Roger
Eaton, director of UMass Medical School's New England Newborn
Screening Program.
</P>
<P>
   For this reason, says Eaton, whose program does testing for
Massachusetts, some of this state's testing is still on a pilot
basis, with parents permitted to opt out of screening for several
disorders. But only 3 percent make that choice, he says.
</P>
<P>
   A task force from the American Academy of Pediatrics and the
federal Health Resources and Services Administration will advise
states later this year on whether to follow Massachusetts' lead. We
are generally skeptical of mandating health procedures by law. But
in this case, as long as the more extensive screening is combined
with follow-up and counseling, evidence shows it is a good
investment of the health-care dollar.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1839EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
