<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-AMTRAK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE RIGHT TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amtrak's ambitious plans to expand passenger rail service draw
on solid achievement and reflect growing confidence in the future
of rail travel.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak deserves continuing support from Congress as it offers
fresh hope for reaching its mandated balancing of operating costs
and revenues by the end of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion program is practical in concentrating on
relatively modest extensions of routes, more frequent service on
existing routes, and additions to Amtrak's specialty package
express service. It includes only one conspicuous initiative _ a
luxury New York-to-Los Angeles train designed to make the trip in
60 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Given the convenience, speed, and dependability of air travel,
Amtrak will never recapture the glory of American passenger
railroading, but it nevertheless remains an important part of the
overall long distance travel system. Some travelers do not care for
air travel, are unable or unwilling to drive, and are averse to bus
travel. Amtrak offers service to more than 500 communities in 45
states to accommodate this traffic.
</P>
<P>
   In heavily traveled corridors like those serving Boston, New
York, and Washington, Amtrak is highly competitive with all other
forms of travel. It is improving its service steadily, most notably
with the recent electrification of the New Haven-Boston stretch and
impending arrival of high-speed, high-tech trains. Similar gains
are being made in about 10 other major corridors around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Money remains a problem. Amtrak has yet to break even, much less
turn a profit. The expansion plans in all cases are designed to add
revenue _ a sensible approach given the prospective loss of
operating subsidies starting in fiscal 2003.
</P>
<P>
   That is an important target for Amtrak to hit, in order to
cement its credibility with a Congress sometimes skeptical about
ever seeing an end to deficits. Congress, in turn, will serve the
nation's interest by continuing to fund improved equipment for a
system that is indispensable for millions of travelers every year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1840EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
