<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GET-ORGANIZED-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME MANAGEMENT EXPERT TEACHES ORGANIZATION, NOT OBSESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LENEVA MORGAN   
 Star-Banner, Ocala, Fla.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it's any comfort, Deniece Schofield says she hasn't always
been this way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was once a very disorganized person,'' said Schofield, who
has since been identified by Publishers Weekly as possibly ``the
most organized person on earth.'' She quickly adds that getting her
life in order wasn't a choice. It was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Schofield, who is now a home management expert, travels around
the country sharing her insights on how she learned to be more
organized.
</P>
<P>
   Her books include: ``Confessions of a Happily Organized
Family,'' ``Confessions of an Organized Homemaker,'' ``Kitchen
Organization Tips and Secrets,'' and ``Springing The Time Trap.''
She is a regular contributor to Woman's Day magazine, and has made
appearances throughout the United States and Canada on television
and radio programs.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't careful planning that led Schofield to change her
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was out of sheer desperation. I had hit rock bottom after
the birth of my third child,'' said Schofield, speaking of the time
her children were 4, 2 and newborn. ``It just seems like there were
always wet clothes on the floor, or toys on the floor, or dishes in
the sink,'' she said, sighing. ``Enough was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Schofield said the next step she took was a crucial one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just sat down and wrote out a list of everything I could
think of,'' she said. ``Once I wrote it down, it relieved some of
the pressure. I just knew that there was no way that I could stay
like that.'' This was 1974 and there weren't many professional
organizers back then. ``There was a lot of trial and error to find
out what would work for me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Changes she made included scheduling laundry days and
encouraging her children to play with one toy at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seemed that there was always laundry, and always
clothes which had to be washed, folded, ironed or put away. It
seemed like there was never a day without laundry.'' Her solution
was to dedicate Monday, Wednesday and Friday with an optional
Saturday to laundry. ``And it worked. At least we were better able
to stay on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Schofield adeptly balances being a wife, mother of five,
and grandmother of four with a busy career as an author and
motivational speaker on a topic that near and dear to her heart.
She mostly advises people to pause to think before acting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cringe every time I hear someone say after my seminar
they're going out to buy some new containers,'' Schofield said.
``First, you should make sure you'll know what you'll do with them,
and if you even have space for them. I always tell people to slow
down, and make do with what you have before going out to buy all
that stuff.'' After all, she said, containers can cause more
clutter.
</P>
<P>
   Schofield laughs at some gadgets she has seen such as an
electric butter dispenser with attachments that allowed it to
spray, brush or squirt butter. Another device could put butter and
salt on corn on the cob at the same time. ``These are just
ridiculous and unnecessary,'' she said
</P>
<P>
   What does it mean to be organized?
</P>
<P>
   `` I wanted to be able to nurture my family and manage my home,
and yet still have time and energy to pursue interests,'' she said.
``That was my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Schofield acknowledges that different people have different
ideas on the meaning of being organized. ``Choose the level of
organization that comfortable for you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, organization can go too far. Schofield knows of one woman
who displays a bronze sign on her door directing people to remove
their shoes before entering her home. Another example is the woman
who flips her throw rug upside down just to save it for when ``good
company'' comes. ``Now this is extreme,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons people hold on to clutter can be more than
superficial. ``In some cases, people need a doctor and not an
organizer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled how one friend found help by attending Al-A-Non
meetings even though she had no problems with alcohol or drugs. She
recognized that not being able to rid herself of clutter was also
an addictive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are afraid to throw things away because they
think they'll want it back one day. But it's selfish to keep
them,'' Schofield said, suggesting that these stored items could be
put to better use by someone who will use them. ``Why not donate to
a charity, and give to someone who will appreciate it. This makes
it easier to let go of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Schofield maintains a busy speaking engagement
calendar, her husband of 30 years said he admires how his wife is
able to keep her priorities in order.
</P>
<P>
   ``She lets me and our children know that we are important to
her,'' Jim Schofield said. He considers his wife his best friend.
``She makes our home my most favorite place to be, and not too many
husbands can say that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Leneva Morgan writes for the Star-Banner in Ocala, Fla., which
is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group. This
article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1841EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0309 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-VIOLENCE-WORKPLACE-NY     02-29 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-WORKPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AGONY OF DOMESTIC VIOLENCE AT THE OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After her husband smashed the liquor bottle over her head, after
the blood dried and her two young sons stopped crying, Rosa
Schirripa realized the marriage was over. Although she got
emotional support from her friends, she was afraid to approach the
one person who might have given her the most practical help: her
boss.
</P>
<P>
   She said she feared that he would view her as weak or stupid for
staying with her husband for so long and that he would try to get
rid of her. Eventually she did talk to him and, to her surprise, he
gave her a few days off, at his convenience. Before that talk,
however, she felt she had nowhere to turn for advice and
protection. Instead, she spent a lot of time sobbing in the office
bathroom and asked her colleagues to cover for her when the divorce
lawyers called. Anything so her boss would not know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't tell him what was happening,'' Schirripa, a
38-year-old New Yorker, said of her ordeal, which ended in divorce
two years ago. ``I know of people who stay in abusive relationships
because they're afraid to go to their boss. They're afraid of the
stigma, afraid that they'll be replaced.''
</P>
<P>
   That attitude appears to be changing, though, as more companies
become aware of how domestic abuse affects workplace morale and
productivity, and as more cities and states consider legislation to
protect victims against discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, only a handful of companies in the United States
had formal policies to help employees deal with domestic violence,
but today hundreds do, said Donna Norton, manager of the Workplace
Resource Center in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The Philip Morris Companies, with 57,000 employees, has been
active in the campaign for greater awareness of the problem,
holding workshops and conferences around the country. Last spring,
it joined with Liz Claiborne Inc., American Express Co. and Bell
Atlantic Corp. to sponsor Safe at Work, a coalition of companies,
labor unions and government agencies that seeks to spread the word
about domestic violence and its effect on the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   A number of state and local governments have also taken action.
Since 1998, Rhode Island and California have enacted laws
prohibiting employers from terminating employees who take time off
to get restraining orders against abusive partners. Similar
legislation is pending in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Maine and Dade County, Fla., enacted legislation last year to
provide unpaid leave for domestic violence victims. Ten states,
including California, Connecticut, New York and New Jersey,
recently passed legislation making victims eligible for
unemployment insurance if they lose their jobs. Mark Green, New
York City's public advocate, says he plans to introduce a bill soon
to broaden the rights of city employees in the event of domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
   When it becomes known that employers cannot retaliate, ``more
women will come forward,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic violence is probably a greater drain on productivity
than most employers realize. Ten years ago, the Bureau of National
Affairs, a private company that monitors workplace trends,
estimated the cost of domestic violence in lost output at $3
billion to $5 billion a year. And a study commissioned by Liz
Claiborne in 1994 estimated that family disputes, including
domestic violence, kept a million Americans off the job every day.
Last year, Victim Services, a nonprofit assistance agency in New
York, received 95,000 calls from women who needed help because of
abusive partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of the callers talk about issues at work, because for
women that's a prime place where domestic violence happens,'' said
Bea Hanson, a director at Victim Services. ``We get calls from
women who are being stalked by their boyfriend or husband at their
job, or they've gotten repeat phone calls that prevent them from
focusing on their work. We get calls from women whose partners come
in unannounced and demand they leave. Most women don't feel safe to
talk about this issue at work, so it's important for women to know
they can disclose this information and not lose their job.''
</P>
<P>
   That sort of uncertainty once haunted Brooke McMurray. McMurray,
a vice chairwoman of Victim Services, worked at Time Inc. for more
than 20 years before leaving in January. She was in an abusive
relationship for 12 of those years, she says, but never sought help
at work. ``You didn't talk about it then,'' said McMurray, who is
50 and, like the other women interviewed for this article, provided
corroborative evidence of the abuse they described. ``I was afraid
to tell my boss for fear he'd fire me,'' she said. ``The guy
operating the freight elevators was the only one I told,'' and that
was because she used the freight elevator for years when her
husband used to wait in the lobby for her. Time Inc. does not have
a formal domestic-violence policy, a spokesman said, but it does
now have an employee-assistance program that can help victims.
</P>
<P>
   Such a self-imposed wall of silence as McMurray's can come
tumbling down at a company that advertises its eagerness to help
people in her predicament. Janice Munson, a Philip Morris employee
in upstate New York, says the company's policy helped save her
sanity. Shortly after joining Philip Morris in 1990, she was
divorced. Abusive calls and letters kept coming in, she says, but
in the open atmosphere at Philip Morris she was able for the first
time to talk to her superiors about her plight and to get help. She
was encouraged to provide a description of her former husband to
the security desk. She even got the mailroom to throw out letters
from him so she wouldn't have to see them.
</P>
<P>
   Schirripa, the woman who was hit over the head with a liquor
bottle, is now a full-time administrative assistant at the College
of Staten Island and is taking courses in social work there. She
also works part time in Green's office as an advocate for more
enlightened workplace policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the employer give the employee a chance, let her get on
her own two feet,'' Schirripa said. Unpaid leaves are a big help,
she said. Speaking for victims of violence, she added: ``I'm not
even asking for pay. I'll lose the money, but if I lose my job I
lose my lifeline.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1848EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
