<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2377 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-COPBEAT-COX     02-29 0544
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-COPBEAT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Community policing `New Cop' doesn't show innovation
 &HT;    By Lou Grieco
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a police force in which recruits must study child
development, where ranking officers can study clinical psychology
at Yale, and where any officer must surrender his pager number to
any citizen who requests it.
</P>
<P>
   They're doing that in New Haven, Conn., where a 10-year
experiment in community policing is still under way. New Cop on the
Beat a one-hour PBS documentary airing at 10 tonight, shows a
little about what New Haven is doing but skimps on some key
information.
</P>
<P>
   Community policing, of course, is nothing new. Some experts
consider it a throwback to when officers walked a beat. Others see
it as a chance to build new, creative partnerships with the
community and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   What community policing has become in the 1990s is a buzzword.
Both Dayton police and the Montgomery County Sheriff's Office have
assigned ``community-based'' officers to work specific
neighborhoods in recent years. New Haven is going further. All of
the department's 417 officers are trained in community policing.
All of the 11 substations have ``community rooms'' with computers
and kitchens, which people are encouraged to use for programs and
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the partnerships. There's one with the school
board, which places an officer in each of the city's high schools.
There's one with the Yale University Child Study Center, where the
officers learn about child development and psychology. Another
partnership is with the local drug court, in which an officer works
with other officials choosing and monitoring which drug-addicted
criminals will be sent for rehabilitation instead of prison.
</P>
<P>
   New Cop backs this up with plenty of documentary footage, mostly
of friendly cops patiently explaining things to minor criminals.
``The minute you come on like a madman or you talk down to them,
well, now they're saying `This guy's looking at me like a piece of
trash,''' one officer explains.
</P>
<P>
   Makes sense. But while there's no doubt New Haven is doing some
innovative things, the documentary does little to show either the
effects or the costs of this 10-year direction.
</P>
<P>
   No detractors are quoted. No dollar figures for training are
offered. No discussion is shown of response-time rates, or of
whether the ``partnerships'' take officers from other important
duties. No statistical evidence is offered that community policing
works, or has any impact at all.
</P>
<P>
   Only one filmed annecdote suggests it does. A suspect doesn't
want to go to jail, so he kicks out a cruiser window. Police pull
him back out, and a crowd forms. Some from the crowd urge the
suspect to behave.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards one cop says it would have been different 10 years
earlier, that the crowd would have turned on the cops.
</P>
<P>
   That's it for results.
</P>
<P>
   Community policing principles are shaping police work
nationwide, including locally. It's an intriguing concept with a
lot to offer. But any new direction in policing, arguably the most
important function our governments undertake, should face tough
questions. New Cop doesn't even ask.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
