<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0315 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-COOKIES&AMP;MILK-ART-2TAK     02-29 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKIES&AMP;MILK-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COOKIES AND MILK? ITS ALL IN TNE PRESENTATION AT NEW YORK CITY
RESTAURANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By MELISSA CLARK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you order the plate of warm cookies at Thalia and
ask for a glass of warm milk to go with it, the waiter doesn't
snicker. The quintessential kids' dessert is presented with all the
pomp and ceremony usually reserved for the Triple Chocolate
Overload with Banyuls, a port-like French wine. Maybe more. It's
delivered with a solicitousness that a souffle never inspires, with
an almost palpable understanding that when you request the ultimate
kids' comfort food, it has to be done to your very specific
childhood satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   And lately, more diners are regressing at the end of dinner. In
the city's most sophisticated restaurants, meals that might have
closed with creme brulee or profiteroles are being polished off
with cookies and milk. You see fashionable women at Le Cirque 2000
ordering tall glasses of skim milk to drink with the tray of petits
fours. There are the thick chocolate chunk cookies being dunked in
whole milk by the club kids at Moomba. Some restaurants like
Tapika, Heartbeat and the Lenox Room have just given up and put the
combination ``cookies and milk'' on the dessert menu.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Atlas. The cookies arrive on a large white
plate, a selection that includes oatmeal-cranberry, white chocolate
macadamia bars and iced sugar cookies. The milk is presented like a
fine wine, still sealed in its container: a small school-lunch
carton of whole or chocolate. It is poured tableside and garnished
with two paper-wrapped straws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the presentation would be fun,'' said James Danos,
the general manager at Atlas. ``We didn't really expect anyone to
drink the milk, but it turns out that they are.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, diners are ordering milk with the finickiness normally
reserved for double-decaf-skim lattes. Should it be whole or skim?
Warm or ice cold? A tall glass or a short one? Cow or goat?
</P>
<P>
   ``We started doing cookies and milk as something for children,''
said George McKirdy, the pastry chef at Heartbeat, who offers
organic goat's milk with his cookie plate. ``But we find that it's
the adults who are ordering it.''
</P>
<P>
   And many of them have issues about it, too. Just listen to
Jeffrey Banks, the men's wear designer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father always ordered milk when I was growing up,'' he
said. ``But it had to be really, really cold. Sometimes, he would
order a glass of milk, and then a glass of ice on the side. He'd
pour the milk into the ice to chill it down, then pour that very
cold milk back into the milk glass. That's part of what I love
about ordering milk. It's just so homey in a Mommy and Daddy way.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Baum, a partner in the B.E. Group of restaurants and a
restaurant consultant, dines out almost every night. After a
complicated meal, he said, cookies and milk are almost a relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have many decisions to make: first there is a choice of
cocktails or an apertif, then you have to read the menu and discuss
the wine list with the captain,'' he said. ``At the same time you
are socializing and are stimulated by the decor and what's going on
around you and, of course, by the food. It's exhausting. By the
time you get to dessert, all I usually want is a hammock to lie
down in and take a break from all that intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   He drinks skim.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurants seem to understand this need for coddling. Dunking
is precisely the point of many cookie-and-milk combinations, where
there is too little liquid for serious drinking but just enough for
dipping. At the Lenox Room, the milk comes in a shallow coffee cup
rather than a glass. Tapika serves it in an oversize shot glass
garnished with slim chocolate curls. At Atlas, of course, they're
careful to pour the milk into a wide-mouth ``rocks'' glass.
</P>
<P>
   Although Union Square Cafe doesn't pair its cookie plate with
milk, the manager, Mark Maynard-Parisi, has noticed more people
ordering it on their own. On most nights the cafe sells only a
glass or two; last Sunday it sold eight. ``We usually suggest that
people order a glass of dessert wine with the cookie plate,'' he
said. ``But it looks like milk is getting popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Hort, a sales representative at a printing company who eats
out six nights a week, is one of those milk orderers. ``I order
milk everywhere I go, including all the best places,'' he said.
``For me, it's not worth eating the cookies unless I can wash them
down with a glass of milk.''
</P>
<P>
   It also seems that the later it gets, the more likely people
long for childish pleasures. At 3:30 a.m. at Moomba recently, the
crowd was thinning and the last tables languidly finishing their
martinis, cosmopolitans _ and cookie plates, served with that
age-old night-cap, a glass of milk. Moomba's warm chocolate chunk
cookies are among the best of their kind: thick, soft in the center
and densely packed with Callebaut chocolate chunks. Not far away,
at Grace, a new restaurant and bar in TriBeCa, most of the requests
for milk with the cookie plate are a late-night thing, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always hoping that people will order a really nice Cognac
or single malt Scotch or glass of port with their cookies,'' said
Fred McKibbin, the restaurant's owner and cookie maker, ``but late
at night they go for the nostalgic kid thing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRALINE COOKIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Adapted from David Cunningham, Lenox Room &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Time: 1{ hours, plus 3 hours'' chilling &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups hazelnuts, shelled and toasted (about 6 ounces)
</P>
<P>
   1} cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   { cup plus 2 tablespoons almond flour
</P>
<P>
   3 sticks butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   [ teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3} cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt.
</P>
<P>
   1. To make praline powder, place nuts on a nonstick or lightly
oiled baking sheet. In a small heavy saucepan combine } cup sugar
and \ cup water, and bring to a boil over medium heat, stirring
constantly until sugar dissolves. Increase heat to medium-high, and
boil undisturbed until sugar caramelizes to a deep amber color,
about 7 minutes. Immediately pour caramel over nuts. Let cool, then
break into 1-inch pieces. Place in a food processor, and grind to a
powder. In a bowl, combine praline powder with almond flour, and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In bowl of a mixer fitted with paddle attachment, cream
butter and remaining sugar until mixture is light and fluffy, about
2 minutes. Scrape down sides of bowl. Add eggs one at a time,
beating well between additions. Add vanilla, and beat mixture for
another minute.
</P>
<P>
   3. Meanwhile, in another bowl, whisk together the flour,
cinnamon, baking powder and salt. Add to the butter mixture, and
mix until just combined. Stir in the praline mixture until fully
combined. Form dough into a disk, wrap in plastic and refrigerate
for 3 hours or until firm.
</P>
<P>
   4. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease several baking sheets, or
line with parchment paper. Unwrap dough, and put between two pieces
of plastic wrap. Roll out to ] inch thick. Cut out cookies using a
2{-inch cookie cutter, and place on prepared baking sheets 1 inch
apart. Reroll all scraps to cut out more cookies. If dough gets too
soft, put it into freezer for a few minutes until firm. Bake
cookies for 12 to 14 minutes, until pale golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 dozen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHOCOLATE CHIP COOKIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Adapted from Wendy Israel, Moomba &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Time: 1 hour &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 pound good-quality bittersweet chocolate, coarsely chopped.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 325 degrees. Grease several baking sheets or
line with parchment paper. In bowl of a mixer fitted with paddle
attachment, cream butter and sugars for 4 minutes, scraping down
sides after 2 minutes. Add eggs one at a time, beating well between
additions. Add vanilla extract and beat for one minute. Scrape
sides of bowl and beat for another minute.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add flour, salt and baking soda to bowl and beat until
combined, about 1 minute, scraping bowl once. Add chocolate and mix
until combined.
</P>
<P>
   3. Drop scant \-cup amounts of cookie dough onto prepared baking
sheets, spacing them 1{ inches apart. Bake cookies for 10 to 12
minutes, or until golden brown.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 dozen cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LEMON CORNMEAL COOKIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Adapted from Alana Ford, Tapika &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Time: 1 hour &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2\ cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   } cups sugar, more for sprinkling
</P>
<P>
   } cups yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   } teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   } cup (1{ sticks) unsalted butter, cut in cubes
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   \ cup pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Grease several baking sheets or
line with parchment paper. In the bowl of a mixer fitted with the
paddle attachment and set on low speed, combine flour, sugar,
cornmeal, baking powder and salt and mix until combined. Add lemon
zest and butter and mix until mixture resembles coarse meal.
</P>
<P>
   2. Separate one egg, discarding the white. In another bowl,
whisk the egg yolk together with one egg. Add to flour mixture and
mix until evenly incorporated and dough comes together.
</P>
<P>
   3. Scoop cookie dough 2 tablespoons at a time and form into
logs, about 2{ inches long. Place logs 2 inches apart on prepared
baking sheet.
</P>
<P>
   4. Whisk remaining egg with one tablespoon water. Brush onto
tops of cookies. Press about 5 pine nuts into top of each cookie
and sprinkle with sugar. Bake for 12 to 15 minutes, until golden
brown around edges.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 dozen cookies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
