<HEADER>
A2387 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDIT-BIRTH01-COX     02-29 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BIRTH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Oh, baby, this doesn't belong on TV
 &HT;    By Andrea Sarvady
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Now that Rick Rockwell and Darva Conger of ``Who Wants
to Marry a Multi-Millionaire'' have morphed into television trivia,
it's time to look toward the future: What other personal rites of
passage can we expect to see on the small screen? Someone's first
sexual experience? No, that's every Fox show. Someone giving birth
on television? No, I know for a fact that was done by ``Good
Morning America'' a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I should know. I was asked to be that someone.
</P>
<P>
   The year: 1992. The place: New York City. My first pregnancy was
proceeding like that of many New York women, sick in the subway,
knocked over in Times Square, ignored by taxi drivers, mistaken for
a taxi myself.
</P>
<P>
   So I was thrilled when our Lamaze coach at New York Hospital
left a message on the machine with a ``special proposal.'' Free
diapers? Better yet, a free epidural? (One look at those movies and
I had lost all interest in giving birth without drugs.)
</P>
<P>
   It turned out our coach had something far more dramatic in mind.
</P>
<P>
   She'd received a phone call from the idea people at ABC. They
were looking for an expectant father to profile for ``Good Morning
America.'' The story would follow the new dad from labor and
delivery to the family home weeks later, recording the joys and
challenges of becoming a father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought of you folks immediately,'' the coach assured me.
</P>
<P>
   This didn't sound like a compliment. You want to be thought of
immediately when people see a gorgeous movie star, or are in a
present-buying mood. But giving birth on national television?
Screaming and flailing about like an insane person for 15 minutes
of fame?
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the screaming and flailing?'' I asked my coach, who
had suddenly become my agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, the cameras will be discreet,'' she assured me. Discreet?
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that my husband would also hate the idea, but hoping to
stretch the anecdote potential of the offer, I called the ABC
people for more information. Yes indeed, they planned to film the
birth, but the focus would be on my endearingly anxious husband. I
wouldn't be seen on-camera at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' I said to the ABC people. ``That takes care of the
flailing. But what about the screaming?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You mean, you?'' the young PR flak responded. I think she sort
of forgot I had to be there too. ``Well, hmm. It will be hard to
edit out the sound effects.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound effects.
</P>
<P>
   I passed. ``But thank you,'' I added cheerfully, feeling
sufficiently covered in the anecdote department. That night, I
shared the details with friends all over the country. Would you
have done it? I asked, over and over. Would you give birth,
off-camera, on national television? Would you?
</P>
<P>
   The vote was almost unanimous. Two women said yes, dozens more
gave a firm no. Not for a first birth. Not for any birth. Not for
money. Not for a good story. Not for anything.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, ``Good Morning America'' found a young doctor and
his wife willing to share this rare, once-in-a-lifetime experience
with millions of Americans. I bet he worked for the hospital. I bet
she worked for ABC.
</P>
<P>
   As for my first birth, it was a glorious and breathtaking
12-hour miniseries that at least two viewers found utterly
riveting.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of those ``sound effects'' is now 7 years old, and the
world seems to have changed a lot since then. People do everything
on TV now, with anyone; perhaps the most surprising thing about the
``Rick and Darva Show'' was its capacity to still shock an
increasingly jaded audience.
</P>
<P>
   No one's asking, but I'm still pretty firm in my resolve to keep
the major life events off screen. Heck, I don't even like home
videos.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Sarvady is a writer living in Druid Hills, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
