<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2388 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-EDIT-MCCAIN01-COX     02-29 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MCCAIN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: McCain's new GOP
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Wednesday's Atlanta
Constitution.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Republican leaders are trying to boot John McCain out
of their party, stripping him of his conservative credentials and
shipping him back to Arizona with a dishonorable discharge.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain being McCain, he's not going home without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   In a remarkable speech Monday in Virginia, the former fighter
pilot brought candid clarity to what's at stake in his battle for
the Republican presidential nomination. As McCain pointed out, he
has a long record as one of the most conservative members of
Congress. He opposes gun control and abortion, supports school
vouchers, advocates more spending on defense and distrusts
environmentalists and their cause. The charge that he is somehow a
liberal Democrat in disguise is hard to sustain.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, McCain is being called a traitor to his party because
of his stance on three issues:
</P>
<P>
   _ He does not kowtow to the Christian Coalition and others who
would impose a mean-spirited form of Christianity on the rest of
us.
</P>
<P>
   _ He opposes large tax cuts for the rich, believing that the
federal surplus would be better spent reducing our massive national
debt and bolstering Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   _ He advocates reform of the campaign-finance system, believing
that government influence should not be peddled to the highest
bidder.
</P>
<P>
   In the minds of GOP leaders, those three issues apparently
define what it means to be a Republican. Those who disagree aren't
welcome in their party.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, on the other hand, believes there must be a place in the
Republican Party for people who believe as he does. In fact, he
argues that such people are the party's future. And he's not alone.
In states that allow it, he has been joined by hundreds of
thousands of independents and Democrats who have crossed party
lines to vote in his favor. The GOP establishment tries to dismiss
those voters as meddlers out to cause trouble, but that's crazy.
People treat their vote with more respect than that.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, moderate voters are backing McCain out of a
heartfelt hope that he will transform the Republican Party into
something they can respect and even support again. In large part,
they are mainstream Americans who were left stranded by the GOP's
rightward lurch of the '80s. Those voters stayed in the Republican
camp as long as it was headed by Ronald Reagan, whose genial
personality softened the harsh edges of that new ideology. But once
Reagan left the scene, they left with him.
</P>
<P>
   That's not mere theory. In the 1992 presidential election,
George Bush got 38 percent of the vote. In 1996, Bob Dole got 41
percent. The voters who in the '80s had given the Republicans
landslide victories had disappeared by the '90s. To paraphrase
Reagan, they didn't leave the Republican Party. The Republican
Party had left them.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those stranded voters ended up in the Reform Party,
which appealed to their conservative distrust of government without
requiring them to pay homage to religious ayatollahs or fatcat
special interests. And a lot of them ended up in the Democratic
camp, seduced by Bill Clinton's apparent moderation on social
issues. Clinton's success drove many Republicans to distraction,
wondering how the American people could twice put such an obviously
flawed man in the White House. They blamed Clinton for being the
devil, they blamed the voters for being so easily fooled. They did
everything but ask themselves the question that mattered:
</P>
<P>
   If in two consecutive elections, voters found Bill Clinton more
trustworthy than the Republicans, what did that say about the
Republicans?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, McCain is asking that question, but the GOP
establishment refuses to hear it. The truth is, they would rather
lose with George W. Bush than win with John McCain, and there's a
practical reason for that attitude. It's not motivated by ideology
or faith or what's best for the country. It's about power and
money.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush should run in November and lose, the lives of GOP
bigwigs don't change. McCain described them Monday as ``people who
have turned good causes into businesses,'' and that's about right.
They'll stay in Washington, still happily skimming off a nice
percentage of the soft money flowing into that town, still milking
their direct-mailing list for contributions, still throwing their
weight around as the self-appointed champions of whatever interest
group _ the anti-tax lobby, the Christian right, the gun
enthusiasts _ they happen to represent.
</P>
<P>
   But should McCain win the nomination, the jig is up. Ralph Reed
and Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell fall out of power, their grip
on the Republican Party broken. The money-changers _ the lobbyists
who change money into legislation _ will be tossed from the
nation's secular temple. A new Republican Party would be formed,
still conservative on social issues, still distrustful of
government, but willing to compete for votes on the basis of ideas,
not campaign cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it's loyal to suggest that the Republican
Party cannot stand on its own feet and fight for public opinion
without six and seven-figure contributions from people with
interests before government ... ,'' McCain said Monday. ``I don't
believe it's loyal to suggest that the Republican establishment is
more important to save than a Republican majority.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a powerful message, in part because McCain knows
something about loyalty and about the high price you sometimes have
to pay for it. He has his faults, like the rest of us, but betrayal
just isn't in him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
