<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS NOMAR OVERDOING IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Nomar Garciaparra's going to miss at least a
week of spring training because of a sprain in the lateral
collateral ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   The star shortsop underwent an MRI early Tuesday, and Red Sox
physician Bill Morgan recommended a week of rest.
</P>
<P>
   This means Garciaparra won't be in the lineup when the Sox open
their spring schedule against the Twins Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There goes the pennant,'' was the deadpan summation offered by
veteran Mike Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Missing some Grapefruit games is no big deal, and the Sox might
be babying their franchise infielder in this instance. But the
larger question seems to be _ is Nomar training too hard and is he
going to be injury-prone throughout his career?
</P>
<P>
   Life's unfair. Garciaparra works harder than any player on the
Red Sox. His offseason Navy Seal-conditioning routine is the stuff
of legend, and each year he comes to camp bigger and stronger. He
showed up in Fort Myers last week looking as if he'd swallowed a
couple of barbells. His body fat was measured at 5 percent, down
from last year's Belushi-like 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Is there such a thing as over-training (a common problem for
generations of Shaughhnessys)?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not that I know of,'' answered Nomar. ``I don't know. I'm sure
you can. Everyone's going to make excuses _ you do this and you do
that. But they're not complaining when you're successful, I'll tell
you that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I back off? No, I don't back off. I do everything I'm
supposed to do, all the things I've done to this point. I focus on
other areas every year, what I feel I need to do looking back at
last year and I just need to focus on . . . I never try to get
bigger. I never try to get big, period. I haven't. I'm not much
bigger than I was last year. So there's nothing changed. I came in
actually more flexible better than I have any years.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to say everything they want, but I separated
my shoulder in college, too. You pull a muscle in college, you
sprain an ankle, and they said I was big then. They say it now just
because . . . they're not complaining when the guy hits 30 home
runs and doing all this other stuff. It makes me laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring Garciaparra strained his throwing elbow and missed
11 days. He flew to the West Coast to get a second opinion. He
missed six games with a strained hamstring in April, then another
11 games with a strained left groin before the All- Star break. In
September, he was hit on a wrist by a fastball and missed the last
eight games of the regular season and one playoff game. In 1998 he
was on the disabled list with a sprained joint in his right
shoulder. He missed only nine games in his rookie season, but in
his final year in the minors he suffered a sprained ankle and a
hamstring tendon tear behind his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Injury-prone?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just weird things like this one,'' he said. ``Last year,
you get in the cold, you pull a hammie. When you hurt something,
everything's connected. During the season you try to come back and
play and you put stress on other areas. Then a freak thing like
getting hit in the wrist. And it's like, `Well, you have all these
injuries,' well, I didn't hit myself in the wrist. Things just
happen, so you play through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra sustained this latest injury while fielding
grounders last Friday. He hurt the knee when he planted his right
leg to throw to first. Tuesday he stretched with teammates, played
catch, stood in the infield during batting practice, and hit in the
cage. But he won't run or do anything strenuous for a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be a week, it could be longer, it may be less,'' he
said. ``We're just going day by day now. I'm just going out there
doing what I'm capable of doing. I'm not going to aggravate it any
more, especially now. There's no need to aggravate it anymore. If
you're going to take time, now's the time to do it. I don't really
think it's going to set me back any at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will linger. If we take care of it now, it
won't linger so that's what it's all about. If this were during the
season, you'd probably see me trying to get out there. I've felt
improvement every single day and that's a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those things that just happens. You can walk and
step off the curb and have something happen. You can't simulate
those sorts of things. You can say, why did it happen. But it did.
You plant wrong, you slip a little bit, anything's going to go.
Things like that just happen. (Jeff) Frye went down last year on a
freakish thing. You know what I mean? Weird things happen. There's
no explanation especially when you're dealing with things like
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about falling behind. If I didn't train as hard
as I do in the offseason then you could say I might need a full
spring training to get in shape. But I came in ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The glut of great young shortstops in the American League has
spawned more than a few barroom arguments. In baseball history,
there have never been three shortstops _ playing simultaneously _
who are on a par with Garciaparra, Yankee Derek Jeter, and Mariner
Alex Rodriguez. But Nomar's going to fall behind his All-Star
brethren if he spends too much of his career on the shelf.
</P>
<P>
   Relax, Nomie. Take a few days off. Eat a cupcake. Stay loose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
