<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-AIDS-ART-NYT     02-29 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-AIDS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZIMBABWE'S SAD LACK: LAND TO BURY AIDS VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ This struggling country has been short of a
lot of things lately. Fuel to fill up its cars. Foreign currency to
pay for its imports. And now, space to bury its dead.
</P>
<P>
   Not even five years after it opened, the country's biggest
cemetery, on the outskirts of the biggest city, Harare, is filling
up faster than planners ever expected. That is largely because of
one of the few things the country unfortunately has no shortage of:
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, we were burying six or seven bodies a day,''
said Wilson Chiperesa, who oversees the grave digging and
groundskeeping for most of Granville Cemetery, as the sprawling
graveyard is known. ``Now we're doing 15, 16, 17 a day.''
</P>
<P>
   The problems faced by officials here in this corner of Harare
show how the devastating AIDS epidemic in sub-Saharan Africa has
had an impact on virtually every aspect of community life.
</P>
<P>
   The cemetery, spread over about 250 acres of former farmland,
will not be turning away corpses this year and probably not even
this decade, but it will be a lot sooner than planned, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the cemetery's office, adorned with calling cards and
calendars from funeral homes but little else, every burial is
recorded in longhand, with the name, date, cause of death and other
particulars neatly noted. So far nearly 8,000 people have been
buried here, said Chiperesa, who has worked in city burial grounds
for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they built this, they said it would take 30 or 40 years
to fill it up,'' he said. ``Now, it will take 15, maybe 20,
years.''
</P>
<P>
   And that is assuming that the rate of AIDS deaths does not
climb. Already, the disease is taking as many as 2,500 lives a
week, and a quarter of the country's 6 million adults are believed
to be infected with the virus that causes AIDS, according to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   A look at a page in the cemetery's ledger from the week of Feb.
11 to Feb. 17 hints at the pattern. A sample of the ages: 32, 28,
70, 10, 17, 24, 29, 25, 37, 61 and 35. The listed causes only make
it clearer: immunosuppression appears only once, but pneumonia and
tuberculosis, illnesses that prey on immune systems weakened by
AIDS, appear frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worries me,'' said Chiperesa, 47, who and is otherwise
matter-of-fact about his work. ``I see a lot of breadwinners
passing away.''
</P>
<P>
   No country in Africa has been harder hit by AIDS over the last
two decades. Mounting economic problems here have only compounded
the crisis, driving more and more Zimbabweans into poverty and
straining the state's resources to help them. The looming shortage
of burial space is but one small symptom of the pain, present and
future.
</P>
<P>
   City officials were so worried by the surge in burials at
Granville that they raised the idea of encouraging cremation as an
alternative to a traditional burial, said Eladinos Zimbwa, the city
official in charge of cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposal was quickly abandoned, and from his dealing
with many grieving Zimbabwean families, Chiperesa said, it was
clear why. ``They don't want to hear about it,'' he said. ``They
have a culture of beliefs in God and tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   So with little relief in sight, all that Chiperesa and his
gravediggers can do is dig. When the cemetery opened, the workers
numbered about 15. Today there are about 3 dozen, and no shortage
of work. Each day, they dig at least a dozen plots for the
following day's burials.
</P>
<P>
   On a day in January there were 27 burials, the most the cemetery
can accommodate in a single day. Making sure every family is
properly attended to and has its space is no easy feat on such
days. ``Sometimes, it's very hard,'' Chiperesa said.
</P>
<P>
   Along the road to the cemetery, roadside stands sell memorial
decorations. They hang from wire strung up between trees _ hearts
and crosses fashioned out of plastic foam or plastic sheeting,
painted blue for men and pink or yellow for women, and often
inscribed with words Rest in Peace.
</P>
<P>
   Lameck Mhlanga, 32, has been selling decorations along the road
for three years, and he has noticed the change. ``We are selling
more than before,'' he explained late one afternoon as he and his
family prepared to pack up their goods for the night. ``It used to
be a few a day. Now it's five or six, especially on weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the cemetery, items sold by Mhlanga and his growing
number of competitors dot many of the fresher graves. It is not a
fancy burial ground. In many places, the grass grows a couple of
feet high.
</P>
<P>
   One area of the cemetery is better maintained, but burial there
costs more and this is a poor country. So for most people who die
in and around Harare, the rougher area will be their final resting
place. Burial here costs the equivalent of about $14 for an adult,
$8 for an infant.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the graves have tombstones. Most have only textbook-size
metal plates, with the deceased's name and dates of birth and death
painted by hand. They stand just a foot or a foot and a half above
the ground, and are soon covered by the fast-growing grass that was
planted years ago for hungry cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping pace with the grass is hard, and keeping pace with the
burials is growing harder, said Zimbwa, the city official in charge
of cemeteries, adding, ``We'll have to keep looking for space.''
</P>
</TEXT>
