u i BC-CANADA-ASYLUM-BOS &LR;      02-29 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ASYLUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNGER STRIKE WEAKENS ALLEGED CUBAN SPY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ The health of the alleged spy who refuses to come in
from Canada's cold was said to be ``deteriorating'' Tuesday as the
result of a hunger strike staged to protest his expulsion from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Flouting Canada's demand that he leave the country, Jose
Imperatori _ a diplomat assigned to Cuba's office in Washington
until he was deported last week amid allegations of espionage _
remained holed up in the Cuban Embassy in Ottawa in a peaceable but
strange stand-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is starving because of a situation created by the United
States,'' said Camilio Garcia, second secretary at the embassy.
``This is not a problem with Canada, it's a problem between Cuba
and the US.''
</P>
<P>
   But the situation has become an irritation and embarrassment for
Canada, which allowed the United States to fly Imperatori to
Montreal Saturday with the understanding he would immediately board
a commercial flight to Havana.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 46-year-old envoy bolted for Ottawa, vowing to
remain within the walls of Cuba's embassy in the Canadian capital
until the United States apologizes and permits him to resume his
duties in Washington. ``This is a struggle against slanders that
hurt my honor,'' he declared through a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Canada unhappily stuck in the crossfire of the
latest row between Washington and Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian government ordered Imperatori Tuesday to leave the
country immediately, but Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy conceded
there is little that can be done to evict the alleged spy since the
embassy is Cuban territory under international law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a serious breach,'' Axworthy told reporters. ``I trust
(Cuba) recognizes they have a responsibility in this matter. . . .
We pointed out to them this is not the way to conduct affairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what started as a fairly minor diplomatic fray has
grabbed front-page attention across Canada, sparked protest
demonstrations in Havana, and bemused Cuba watchers, who can't
understand why Fidel Castro's regime is willing to risk harming
relations with Canada, a crucial diplomatic ally and the island's
most important source of investment, tourists, and foreign aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's weird about this case is the guy's righteous
indignation,'' said David Welch, a Cuban affairs specialist at the
University of Toronto. ``He's personally offended. . . . What an
overreaction. Why not just go home?''
</P>
<P>
   Imperatori got the boot from the United States after being
accused of maintaining ``illicit contacts,'' in the State
Department's phrase, with a senior official of the Immmigration and
Naturalization Service who has been charged with passing secrets to
the communist island state.
</P>
<P>
   The spy ruckus comes as the United States and Cuba are at
loggerheads over the fate of a 6-year-old Cuban boy, Elian
Gonzalez, who was rescued from the sea last November by the US
Coast Guard after his mother drowned trying to flee Cuba. Elian is
living with relatives in Florida, but the Castro government wants
him returned to his father in Cuba.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1910EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0323 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-     02-29 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-STRAWBERRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONDERING A CAREER TRANSITION FOR STRAWBERRY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., N.J., Fla., Canada)   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ They shared a life with Darryl Strawberry, riding
buses, planes and trains. They have spent many months on baseball
fields all over the country with him. They have prayed with him.
But even after all that time, his teammates do not know what he
might do outside of baseball now that his career is in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry was suspended for a year on Monday by Bud Selig, the
commissioner of baseball, in response to a failed drug test Jan.
19. It was Strawberry's third violation of his drug aftercare
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to get his life back on track,'' David Cone, a
longtime teammate of Strawberry, said. ``He's got to get his
addiction under control. Beyond that, he's got a lot of life to
live.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has discussed the possibility of going into a
substance abuse treatment center, an American League official said.
This is something Strawberry has done twice in the past, in 1990
(Smithers Center in New York) and 1994 (Betty Ford Clinic in
California).
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry cannot play baseball in the major leagues, or even
those minor league teams that are a part of the national
association. He eventually could play in an independent league
again, as he did in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Executives from teams in Newark and Montclair, N.J.; from Long
Island and from St. Paul, Minn., say they would welcome Strawberry.
But he would make far less than the $750,000 he would have made
this year playing for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone and others expressed hope that Strawberry will
concentrate on something other than baseball, for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things to look forward to, regardless of
whether he plays baseball again,'' Cone said. ``I think he needs to
be told that right now. If the baseball career is over, that can be
depressing in and of itself for a lot of players, much less someone
with an addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter said: ``What he should do is get help. I'm sure
baseball has something set up where he can get some help. He's
going to be faced with a lot of time where he's used to playing and
used to coming to the field every day, and it's a situation where
he doesn't have that. We're all going to be supportive of him. But
he's got to find something on his own to do as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry could play professional baseball, but for teams in
leagues that have no affiliation with Major League Baseball, no
big-time television exposure, no big money.
</P>
<P>
   The Newark Bears play in the Atlantic League, and can pay a
maximum of $3,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not going to get rich in our league,'' Rick Cerone, a
former Yankees catcher who owns the Bears, said. ``But he is going
to get a chance to play and stay sharp. We are a viable option for
Darryl.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees do have a roundabout affiliation with the Montclair
Jackals, who play next to the Yogi Berra Museum, which is filled
with artifacts donated by George Steinbrenner, the Yankees'
principal owner. The possibility of having Strawberry in Montclair
is being discussed, Greg Lockhard, president of the Jackals, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if we'll pursue it,'' Lockhard said. ``I guess
it's already become apparent it's a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, however, no one in the Yankees' organization had any
tangible insight into what Strawberry will do next. Several
teammates tried calling but couldn't reach Strawberry, and
Steinbrenner said that when he tried calling Strawberry's home, but
the phone was blocked from receiving more calls.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez suggested that perhaps Strawberry would continue
to make speaking appearances, contribute to charity work. Cone
vagely mentioned business opportunities. There might be a time
when Strawberry could coach. He could use ``help with career
transition,'' said Cone. ``Try to help him with an educational
program to get him into a career transition, if that's the
direction he decides to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying that his baseball career is over. But assuming
that it is, he's going to need a lot of support right now. I think
it goes a lot deeper than just the team _ I think management and
the union could do a lot better job in this regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Martinez: ``We need to keep talking to him, let him know
we're thinking about him. We've just got to keep calling, can't
abandon him and forget about him. We've just got to keep bothering
him as much as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   They spoke with concern for Strawberry, in worried voices. But
no one criticized Selig's decision. ``I didn't envy the
commissioner in this particular case,'' said Cone. ``Last year, it
was supposed to be a year, and it was reduced to 120 days. It's
pretty hard to make a strong argument that this penalty was too
harsh.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   Ed Yarnall, expected to replace Hideki Irabu as the Yankees' No.
5 starter, is hampered by a sore lower back and probably won't
resume throwing for a few days. Club officials don't think
Yarnall's ailment is serious. ``Camp Cramps, I'm calling it,'' said
general manager Brian Cashman, referring to the minor physical
problems of Yarnall, Orlando Hernandez and others ... Andy
Pettitte's father, Tom Pettitte, is visiting the camp. The elder
Pettitte said he worked with his son in the off-season on his
change-up, a pitch that Andy Pettitte intends to re-establish this
season... Jake Westbrook, the pitcher acquired for Irabu, will
start the Yankees' first exhibition game Thursday, against the
Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
</TEXT>
