<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2398 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AFRICA-TORTURE-TRIAL-     02-29 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-TORTURE-TRIAL-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PRESIDENT OF CHAD TO BE TRIED IN SENEGAL FOR HUMAN RIGHTS
ABUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAKAR, Senegal _ In a human rights case that was inspired by the
one against Augusto Pinochet, the former president of Chad is
expected to stand trial later this year for his government's crimes
against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   The case against the former president, Hissene Habre, is being
watched closely in Africa, where brutal rulers have engaged in
widespread human rights violations with impunity. The accusations
against Habre are already resonating across a continent where laws
are applied inconsistently to the powerful and powerless.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a message to other African leaders that nothing will
be the same any longer,'' said Delphine Djiraibe, president of a
human rights group working on the case. ``It shows that Africa can
also play a role in the fight for human rights and can fight on its
own soil.''
</P>
<P>
   The case against Habre, 57, who has lived in exile in Dakar
since being toppled from power in 1990, has also stirred some
impassioned comments among African intellectuals. Some of them
defend Habre by arguing that guilt cannot be assigned to African
leaders of his generation because they were merely creations and
pawns of Cold War superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   But several human rights organizations have worked quietly for
months to collect evidence against Habre, on the legal basis that a
person can be tried for crimes against humanity in any country and
that former heads of state are not immune. The human rights groups
say they have documented 97 cases of political killings, 142 cases
of torture and 100 cases of people who have disappeared in Chad, an
impoverished, land-locked desert nation in central Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was considered an extraordinary sight when the former
president appeared in a Sengalese court Feb. 3. He has been in
Dakar under house arrest since being indicted on torture charges by
a Sengalese court.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps even more startling had been the testimony, a few
days earlier in the same court, of a half-dozen ordinary Chadians
who told of being arrested and tortured during the Habre regime.
</P>
<P>
   One of the prisoners, Souleyman Guengueng, was a civil servant
who was arrested in August 1988 by the Chadian government's
notorious security and documentation squad and accused of being an
opponent of the government. Guengueng, who was still recovering
from an operation he had undergone just days before the arrest,
said he then spent the next two years being tortured.
</P>
<P>
   According to Guengueng, he lost consciousness for so long on
three occasions that his fellow prisoners left him for dead. Up to
10 men were kept in one cell built for a single prisoner, so that
their legs eventually became paralyzed. And he said that three to
four people died every day from malaria, flea infestation, lack of
food, suffocation or sheer heat.
</P>
<P>
   He also recalled how 300 of their fellow prisoners had been
jammed into one small cell; the guards would pour water into the
cell from the ceiling, forcing the men to lick the floor or their
bodies so as not to die of thirst.
</P>
<P>
   Guengueng, reached by telephone in N'djamena, the capital of
Chad, said he still has trouble walking and suffers from poor
vision because of a powerful light that, at one point during his
incarceration, was directed continuously at him from a close
distance. ``My joy was great in that courtroom. Hissene Habre never
thought that one day he would be brought to justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chad, the ``untouchable'' are the elite who gravitate around
the president and are above the law, said Djiraibe, president of
the Chadian Association for the Promotion and Defense of Human
Rights. Those who engage in the ``politics of the belly'' are
political opponents who make enough noise to earn some money and
find some protection under the law, while the rest of society
cannot count on the law to protect them, Djiraibe said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the terms may change, inequality before the law is a
given elsewhere in Africa. In the Ivory Coast, the three classes
described by Djiraibe are sometimes described as officials of
steel, wood, and cotton. That is why the case against Habre _ who
as a former head of state was the ultimate untouchable or official
of steel _ carries a greater significance in Africa, human rights
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Senegal is regarded as having one of the few independent
judiciaries in Africa, and that is one of the main reasons that
international human rights organizations, including Human Rights
Watch and the International Federation of Human Rights, have joined
in the case against Habre.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is now showing that there are African countries in which
you can put these principles of human rights in practice,'' said
Reed Brody, advocacy director of the New York-based Human Rights
Watch. ``The case has profound implications in a way that it would
not if it were being held in a European country, particularly a
colonial country. That's one of the things that Latin Americans
were saying about the Pinochet case _ that it was Europe imposing
its laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Brody pointed out that while several other African dictators are
in exile _ for instance, Uganda's Idi Amin in Saudi Arabia or
Ethiopia's Mengistu Haile Mariam in Zimbabwe _ the courts in those
countries are not free enough to pursue a similar case against
those former leaders.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Chad _ a creation of French colonial mapmakers who threw
together different populations into a desolate patch of land twice
the size of Texas _ has experienced continual war since gaining
independence in 1960. In 1982, Habre, a rebel chieftain, seized
power and ingratiated himself with France and the United States for
being one Africa's staunchest opponents of Lybia's Col. Moammar
Gadhafi.
</P>
<P>
   During Habre's eight-year rule, his U.S. and French backers
often portrayed him positively, describing him as a charismatic
leader and intellectual who genuinely cared about issues facing the
developing world.
</P>
<P>
   But the French eventually tired of Habre, who was increasingly
being criticized by human rights monitors, just as French President
Francois Mitterand talked of openness and democracy in a post-Cold
War Africa. And in December 1990, after a French-supported invasion
from Sudan, Idriss Deby _ who had served as Habre's military
commander and had been the country's No. 2 _ overthrew Habre and
sent him into exile.
</P>
<P>
   In Dakar, several Senegalese intellectuals said that it was
hypocritical of Western human rights organizations to pursue Habre
now, given their governments' previous support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hissene Habre was received and honored in Paris as a head of
state and ally,'' said Babacar Sine, one of Senegal's most famous
intellectuals. ``France never regarded him as a dictator.''
</P>
<P>
   Sine, who has known Habre for 40 years, added: ``This case is
much more complex than the role of Habre. There is the role of
France that supported him. There is the role of the United States
that supported him. If we are to judge Hissene Habre, we have to
also judge those who supported him.''
</P>
<P>
   Another complicating factor is that Deby is still president of
Chad, where human rights monitors say arbitrary killings by the
government's security forces, torture, beatings, and other forms of
abuse remain common. Human rights organizations behind the case are
pushing for the trial to take place in Senegal; if Habre were
extradited to Chad, they say, it is unlikely that there would be a
fair trial because his testimony would inevitably implicate members
of the current government, including Deby.
</P>
<P>
   Madicke Niang, a Senegalese lawyer defending Habre, said that
his client acknowledged that human rights abuses had occurred under
his rule, but denied its scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``He denies the acts he is accused of,'' Niang said. ``And if
these acts did occur, he denies having had any knowledge of them.
It is Idriss Deby who should be held responsible for those acts
because he was Hissene Habre's military commander.''
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to determine the exact scale of the abuse under
Habre because the only extensive report was made by a truth
commission set up by Idriss. The commission said that the Habre
government carried out 40,000 political killings and 200,000 cases
of torture, and that Habre gave direct orders to target certain
groups or persons. Habre is said to have fled Chad with more than
$11 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
