<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elbow's a pain to Chipper Jones
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kissimmee, Fla. _ Chipper Jones had plenty to challenge him this
spring, namely trying to follow an MVP season. Now he has something
else to worry about _ a bone spur in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves hope the injury, caused by strain from the repetition
of throwing, won't cost Jones playing time this season and that he
can have it operated on after the season.
</P>
<P>
   Pieces of the spur have broken off and are floating in his
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty common,'' Braves team orthopedist Joe Chandler
said. ``He's had it for a while. It's just now bothering him. It's
something we hope we can take care of at the end of the season.''
``There's nothing you can do for it, just take stuff to keep the
swelling down,'' Jones said. ``I'm not real big on injections.
That's only going to shoot it full of cortisone. But, really, it
hasn't bothered me that much. It just bothers me when I get in
front swinging left-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the elbow doesn't hurt that much until at night, away
from the ballpark. He is taking anti-inflammatories and is counting
on playing at his usual high level.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jones might need more rest, even if he doesn't want it,
and that's where Bobby Bonilla could help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like taking days off,'' said Jones, who played in a
career-high 160 games last season ``I wouldn't mind a couple of
innings here and there. Like in the sixth inning, when we have a
seven, eight-run lead, let those guys get some at-bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones has been healthy since what was supposed to have been his
rookie year in 1994. He tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his
left knee in a spring training game and missed that season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones continued the same rigorous offseason workouts that helped
him get off to a hot start in last year's spring training. However,
the workouts were interrupted by a few more trips to awards
ceremonies. Jones said he reported to camp at his heaviest weight
ever, 225 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   He aggravated the elbow injury while lifting weights, doing a
triceps press, three weeks before the start of spring training. He
took three weeks off but has started lifting again.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Jones' mind this spring is his contract, as he seeks to
become baseball's highest-paid player. He wants to have it worked
out by the time the Braves break camp; otherwise, he said he'll
wait until after the season, when he becomes a free agent, to try
to work out a deal.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, Jones has stayed busy getting ready to defend his
MVP title. His goals, however, remain the same, he said: hitting
.300, driving in 100 runs and scoring 100.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he would not try to hit 45 home runs again. ``I
don't expect to hit that many,'' Jones said. ``That's a lot of home
runs. But I know if I have a good year, I'm capable of hitting 50.
I feel like I'm getting better and improving every year. I just may
not go through a stretch like I went through last year when
everything I hit for a week or two went out.''
</P>
<P>
   His work habits and attitude have impressed his new hitting
coach, Merv Rettenmund.
</P>
<P>
   ``You watch guys like that, you know he's good,'' Rettenmund
said. ``Whether he hits the ball good or not, you know the swing is
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
