<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Freshman Forte leads Tar Heels
 &HT;    By Pat Donahue
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chapel Hill, N.C. _ Michael Jordan didn't do it. Vince Carter
didn't do it. Neither did Antawn Jamison. Or Jerry Stackhouse.
</P>
<P>
   None of those future NBA stars did what Joe Forte is about to do
_ lead the North Carolina Tar Heels in scoring as a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   Going into tonight's game with Georgia Tech, Forte is averaging
16.2 points per game, seventh in the ACC, just 0.1 behind Tech's
Jason Collier in sixth. Forte, who scored 26 points Saturday at
Maryland, also is third on his team in rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Forte has done it so quietly that it escaped the attention of
coach Bill Guthridge. ``I didn't even know he was our leading
scorer,'' Guthridge said.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina's freshman class was supposed to be one if its best.
But Jason Parker never made it into school, which left Forte as the
lone blue-chipper to go to Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Forte, who went to middle school in Smyrna and was recruited
heavily by Georgia Tech, has scored in double figures in all but
three games. He has been named the ACC rookie of the week three
times and in a surprisingly strong ACC freshman class _ including
Jason Williams, Carlos Boozer, Damien Wilkins and Travis Watson _
Forte tops all frosh scorers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Forte doesn't regard himself as the first option in the
offense, especially when such established players as Ed Cota,
Brendan Haywood and Jason Capel are on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're a freshman, you don't want to go out and shoot the
ball all the time,'' he said. ``The seniors have put in their
time.''
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't taken the 6-foot-4 Forte long to get used to
playing at Carolina. His 24 points in the 82-65 season-opener
against Southern California set a UNC record for points in a debut
by any player. It helped him earn the MVP honors for the Maui
Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, for someone who averaged 22 points a game as a
senior at high school powerhouse DeMatha Catholic, Forte was
expected to have an impact. At least by the coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joseph came from a good high school program,'' Guthridge said.
``He's an ingredient we thought we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's clearly established himself as one of the best young
players in college basketball,'' N.C. State head coach Herb Sendek
said.
</P>
<P>
   Offense is Forte's forte and his best output was 27 against
Virginia. But scoring isn't his only strength. He also leads
Carolina in steals.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
