<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shot-putter: Bigger is better
 &HT;    By Mike Fish
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the big problems that female shot-putters face in selling
their discipline is their size.
</P>
<P>
   The guys can get away with being bulked-up behemoths.
</P>
<P>
   Cover girl/beach volleyball player Gabrielle Reece can earn a
handsome living off her image and book by the same title, ``Big
Girl in the Middle.''
</P>
<P>
   But a female shot-putter is looked at funny. The unlady-like
stigma lingers.
</P>
<P>
   For Connie Price-Smith, the stigma was there the day she picked
up a shot almost two decades ago. It's been there on three trips to
the Olympic Games and more international competitions than she can
remember. And it will follow her Saturday to the Georgia Dome,
where she's favored to win a fifth title in the USA Indoor Track
and Field Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a stigma,'' said Price-Smith, ranked as the
No. 1 women's shot-putter in the United States for the past nine
years. ``You have to be strong, and it's usually the bigger girls.
Everyone is going to perceive we're not as pretty or feminine as
the sprinters or pole-vaulters. Shot-putters come in all shapes and
sizes. If you look across the board, they're more feminine than in
the past, but the stigma probably will always be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of shrug it off and don't think abut it. If you worry,
you'll just be frustrated. I know a lot of girls have problems with
it. I'm blessed with the size I have, and I do the best with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The pleasant, soft-spoken woman has been among the elite
American throwers since she came to the sport, ranking in the top
10 every year since 1986. Price-Smith won nine outdoor U.S.
shot-put titles and four indoors, not to mention six national
discus titles and a silver medal in the shot put at the World
Indoor Championships _ the best showing by an American woman in the
event and the first Olympic or world championship medal won since
1960.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ultimate hope is to make another Olympic team and do well
(in Sydney). (And) I'd like to win another indoor title.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, this country's leading shot-putter will call it a career.
</P>
<P>
   She's thought about retirement before, but this time it's for
real.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this for a long time,'' said Price-Smith,
defending Pan American Games champion. ``It gets harder and harder
at 37 to get up and fight every day. After '88, I said I would
retire. After '92, I said I would retire. After '96, I didn't feel
that way. I decided after '96 I would go four more years. I wanted
to be in four Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to go on to another life after this. I think I'd
like to start a family. I'm not getting any younger.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of the sport in recent years has been staying
mentally focused, but Price-Smith is renewed by thoughts of a final
Olympic shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very motivational, and I work harder because of it,''
she said. ``I'm excited. I think my chance (of an Olympic medal)
are pretty good. I can throw as well as a majority of the people in
the world. It's who is ready on that day. But the important thing
is to make the (U.S.) team and take care of the rest later.''
</P>
<P>
   1/17/96 - Bloomington, Indiana Ranked No. 6 in the world,
Olympic shot put hopeful Connie Price-Smith trains with here
husband John Smith (center) and up-and-coming putter John Schulte.
L-R Connie Price-Smith, John Smith and John Schulte at the Iron
Pitt Gym. pls credit; Post-Tribune photo by Larry Bretts.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Price-Smith has won nine outdoor shot-put titles and four
indoor crowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution HHHHHH Wednesday, March 1, 2000
C
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
