<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DESSERTS-EMERGENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN BEST-LAID PLANS FAIL, IMPROVISE A TRIFLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do you do when it's 6:30 p.m. and you have just discovered
that the fancy custard you were planning to serve 12 people at
dinner is still sloshing around instead of standing firm?
</P>
<P>
   Remaking the dessert is out of the question: not enough time.
For me, running to the store and buying a substitute was one
possibility, but I knew I wouldn't fool anyone. It's a little hard
to get away with serving a store-bought dessert when you are a food
writer, especially when the party has been planned five months in
advance.
</P>
<P>
   So I started improvising a dessert in my head. I knew I had a
12-egg-white disk of meringue in the kitchen, left over from the
creme brulee that I had left on the stove for a second too long. I
thought the meringue could be the base of a trifle, and as I drove
to the store I envisioned the other ingredients: heavy cream to
whip, mascarpone to use as a thickener, poached dried cranberries
for tartness and ladyfingers soaked in Marsala wine. As I dashed
through the store I spied a jar of lemon curd and added it to the
still evolving dessert.
</P>
<P>
   I folded the mascarpone and lemon curd into the whipped cream
along with the cranberries, and stirred in some Marsala. The
components were arranged and layered. It looked great. I served it,
and it tasted OK, but I knew there was a better dessert lurking in
there.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later my son, Michael, who owns a restaurant in
Spain, was visiting, and we decided to play with the original
dessert. We tried various combinations of coffee-flavored liqueur,
sherry and creme fraiche.
</P>
<P>
   We got rid of the meringue, substituted toasted pecans for the
cranberries to add some crunch, changed the too-sweet Marsala to
very dry sherry and soaked each ladyfinger in it, and added lemon
rind and lemon juice for tartness. We named the new creation
Emergency Trifle.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, we decided that creme fraiche would do as well
as mascarpone and that very strong coffee mixed with a little
coffee liqueur could be used in place of the sherry.
</P>
<P>
   We also decided that if savoiardi, the much firmer and larger
Italian ladyfingers, are too hard to find, American ladyfingers can
be substituted. When you are in a hurry you can't be too fussy.
</P>
<P>
   EMERGENCY TRIFLE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 25 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   16 ounces mascarpone
</P>
<P>
   2 pints heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   \ cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   Finely grated peel of one large lemon
</P>
<P>
   1} cups dry (fino) sherry
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 cups chopped, toasted, lightly salted pecans
</P>
<P>
   1 8- to 11-ounce jar lemon curd
</P>
<P>
   30 or more Italian ladyfingers (savoiardi)
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate-covered espresso beans, grated lemon rind, curls of
lemon rind, jellied lemon slices for garnish (optional).
</P>
<P>
   1. In a bowl, beat mascarpone to soften it. Add cream, sugar and
lemon peel, and beat until mixture is partly thickened. Slowly beat
in lemon juice and } cup of the sherry, and continue beating until
the mixture is thick.
</P>
<P>
   2. Fold in the pecans. Stir in lemon curd so that it makes
streaks in the whipped cream mixture.
</P>
<P>
   3. Quickly dip the ladyfingers one by one on both sides into
remaining sherry; do not allow them to soak in sherry or they will
become mushy. Place some to fill the bottom of a 12-cup
straight-sided glass bowl. Place additional ladyfingers side by
side, standing up, around sides of bowl. Spoon in half the whipped
cream mixture. Arrange remaining ladyfingers on top of whipped
cream; top with remaining whipped cream. Finish with garnish of
your choice. Refrigerate if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 12 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
