 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
McCAIN TO PARTICIPATE IN GOP DEBATE 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRESNO, Calif. _ Presidential hopeful John McCain abruptly
reversed a decision Tuesday not to debate Gov. George W. Bush this
week, saying he would change his schedule to participate by
satellite hookup in the Los Angeles forum.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign responded that it would participate ``one way
or another,'' either by satellite or in person.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Times and CNN are sponsoring a Democratic debate
with Al Gore and Bill Bradley on Wednesday night and a Republican
presidential debate Thursday. Conservative commentator Alan Keyes
will also participate in the GOP debate. Both debates will be
broadcast live at 9 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   McCain complained that the debate could ``hurt'' him with voters
in New York because it will force the cancellation of a rally there
Thursday night, which was scheduled before he and Bush worked out
their scheduling problems.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement surprised reporters, who had asked him only an
hour before if he planned to pass up a chance to debate the Texas
governor. McCain said there was ``no possible way'' he could
rearrange his schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot flex our schedule just because George W. Bush is
blown by the electoral winds,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   But a few hours later, the Arizona senator apologized and
reversed course. He said he felt no obligation to share ``the inner
workings and contemplation of our campaign'' with reporters who
travel with him aboard his ``Straight Talk Express'' bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``From now on, straight talk,'' he laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the campaign ``tore up our
entire schedule to go back to California.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said if it is possible to attend the debate by satellite,
then Bush will probably do that and continue to campaign somewhere
in the East on that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will participate one way or another,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain acknowledged the importance of the California primary,
with its winner-takes-all delegate prize of 162.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I need to win California. It's a critical state,'' McCain
told a small crowd in Stockton early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Later he told packed auditorium at California State University
in Fresno that he was optimistic, although conservative Republicans
have so far shown little sign of responding in great numbers to his
message.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
