<HEADLINE>
AKAMAI TO INVEST $5M IN LOUDEYE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Akamai Technologies Inc., the 1999 IPO juggernaut that still has
venture-capital backers bragging, made a venture investment of its
own last week.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai, which is in the business of speeding up the Web,
promised to invest $5 million in Seattle's Loudeye Technologies
Inc. This is Akamai's first private-equity investment in an outside
company.
</P>
<P>
   Loudeye, formerly called encoding.com, is an Internet
infrastructure company whose product improves sound and video over
the Web. As part of the deal, Akamai said it would use Loudeye's
technology in its content-delivery business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Digital media is not easy to create, encode, manage, or
deliver,'' Akamai President Paul Sagan said in a press
release &UR;  &LR; from the company's Cambridge, Mass. headquarters. By
working with Loudeye, he added, audio and video on the Web will
become more engaging.
</P>
<P>
   Akamai has made two acquisitions in its four months as a public
company, but this is its first pure investment. Earlier this month,
the company bought InterVU Inc., a provider of live radio and
broadcasting services over the Internet, for $2.8 billion. In
January, Akamai bought Network24 Communications for $200 million,
for its fast telecommunications connections that allow broadcasts
to move more quickly over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Dagres, a general partner with Battery Ventures, the
Wellesley venture capital firm that was Akamai's first investor,
said Akamai doesn't intend to become a big investor. But this deal
represents a trend among entrepreneurs, who often take key partners
on as investors, in addition to traditional venture investors and
large corporations.
</P>
<P>
   This is a late-stage investment in Loudeye. The company in
December said it had raised $48 million in its third round of
financing. Some big names showed up in that round, including
America Online, CBS, Intel, Microsoft, and NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Though it's late in the game, Akamai and its investors stand to
profit when Loudeye goes public. The IPO is slated for March 7.
Loudeye plans to sell 4.5 million shares at $8 to $10 a share.
Akamai's closing stock price Tuesday was 261 1/4, up 4 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
