r f BC-PHONEBILLS-TEXAS-COX     02-29 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHONEBILLS-TEXAS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Phone charges to increase
 &HT;    By Amy Schatz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Local and long-distance phone charges will rise
slightly again today as part of a deal that lowered in-state
long-distance charges by about 5 cents a minute in September.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two months, local and long-distance telephone bills
have carried a notice that the Texas Universal Service Fund charge
would increase today by about half a percent. The increase has
already been figured into this month's phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   The Universal Service Fund subsidizes service by local phone
companies to consumers in high-cost rural areas and to a small
percentage of hearing-disabled and low-income families.
</P>
<P>
   For years, state policy was to keep local phone rates low
through a high ``access charge'' that long-distance companies paid
Southwestern Bell Telephone Co. to complete their long-distance
calls. That higher charge was justified, in part, as a way to pay
for rural and special phone services.
</P>
<P>
   But because that meant the access charge for in-state calls was
substantially higher than for interstate calls, long-distance
companies usually charged more for in-state calls. As a result, a
customer in Central Texas could pay more to call Dallas than to
call New York.
</P>
<P>
   Starting in the 1980s and into the 1990s, long-distance
companies began to complain that the access charges were much too
high and distorted long-distance charges.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state authorities responded by creating the
Universal Service Fund at each level, fed by a separate charge on
both local and long-distance telephone bills. Still, in Texas the
access charge remained high compared to many other states.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature last year agreed to cut the access charge, thus
making possible lower in-state long-distance bills. But it also
decided to maintain the subsidy for serving rural areas and the
deaf by raising the state Universal Service Fund charges on all
telecommunications bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be better because we've taken subsidies out of
places where they don't work anymore,'' said Public Utility
Commission chairman Pat Wood.
</P>
<P>
   So in September, the Universal Service Fund surcharge was raised
from .787 percent to 3.579 percent and is charged on both local and
long-distance bills. In exchange, the cost of in-state long
distance service was dropped by about 4 cents a minute. The amount
of the decrease depends on the long-distance company.
</P>
<P>
   The switch was calculated to be as revenue neutral as possible,
Wood said. ``It's a wash. That's how it was intended to be,'' said
Wood. This way, ``customers will know what they're paying for.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups argue that the change is anything but fair to
people who don't call other parts of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses and very high end residential customers end up
saving a whole heck of a lot of money,'' said Janee Briesemeister,
senior policy analyst for Consumers Union's southwest office.
</P>
<P>
   With the Universal Service Fund charge assessed on every phone
bill, lower income customers who don't call long distance in the
state are paying higher phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another example of those who use the least service
getting hit with higher prices because of deregulation,'
Briesemeister said.
</P>
<P>
   The Universal Service rate increased again today because of
tinkering by the commission and phone companies on how the charges
are figured. The commission is not scheduled to review the charge
again for three years, although its possible that the rate could
decrease in the interim, said Wood.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
