<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UPS, Delta go nose to nose for right to fly to China
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two companies are involved in a dogfight over air
rights to China.
</P>
<P>
   United Parcel Service and Delta Air Lines are among seven air
carriers seeking new flights being awarded this year under the
U.S.-China air treaty.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines filed formal applications Tuesday with the U.S.
Transportation Department.
</P>
<P>
   UPS ranks a China route as its ``top international priority,''
Chairman and Chief Executive Jim Kelly said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Sandy Springs, Ga.-based delivery giant says it needs air
rights to compete effectively for air express business with rival
FedEx, which already flies to China.
</P>
<P>
   UPS also told the DOT that direct flights to China would create
1,200 new jobs at the company, adding that the ``increased movement
of goods'' would generate more than 77,000 jobs in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Delta wants to fly passengers seven days a week
nonstop from New York to Beijing and three days a week nonstop from
Cincinnati to Beijing. The New York flights would originate in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Delta Chairman Leo Mullin said the New York-Beijing market is
``by far the largest U.S.-China market without nonstop service,''
adding that the one-stop link to Delta's Atlanta hub would serve
``vast numbers of additional travelers.''
</P>
<P>
   The DOT will award 10 weekly flight frequencies and is expected
to issue a decision this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The case is unusual because it puts passenger and cargo airlines
in competition for the same flights. Usually, passenger and cargo
flights are awarded separately.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to UPS and Delta, applicants include American
Airlines and Polar Air Cargo, which have no flights to China.
FedEx, United and Northwest, which do, are seeking additional
flights.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT will name only one new entrant, creating a
winner-take-all battle for that distinction among UPS, Delta,
American and Polar. It also could split the new frequencies between
one new carrier and one of the incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   UPS last week set up a separate Web site, chinaquest.ups.com,
where it presents its arguments publicly.
</P>
<P>
   The delivery giant argues that FedEx has a monopoly to mainland
China that can only be broken if ``the DOT permits UPS to compete
on a level playing field.'' UPS serves China through third-party
delivery services, but that arrangement restricts growth and
reliability, a company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Yohe, Delta's senior vice president for government
affairs, said Delta believes its proposal for passenger service
from New York is superior to that of American, which would fly from
Chicago. United already provides one-stop service from Chicago, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Yohe said the critical decision is whether the DOT makes cargo
or passengers the priority for new service.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had to handicap it, we really feel UPS is probably going
to be our strongest competition,'' Yohe said.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies' applications include long lists of supporters in
Congress and from various cities with a stake in the outcome. Two
members of Georgia's congressional delegation contacted Tuesday are
being careful not to choose sides between UPS and Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Max Cleland and Rep. Mac Collins each have written letters
supporting UPS if the DOT decides to add cargo flights, and Delta
if it opts for more passenger service, spokespeople said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really does not favor one over the other,'' said an aide to
Cleland. ``It puts the entire delegation in a bind, really.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
