<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-SEARCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES TACKLE VALIDITY OF POLICE SEARCHES IN GUN, DRUG CASES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Tuesday grappled with how far
police may go in searching people and their belongings for guns and
drugs, without having a warrant or reason to suspect any crime has
taken place.
</P>
<P>
   The justices heard arguments in two criminal cases: one
challenging the validity of a police officer's reliance on an
anonymous tip and the other addressing the constitutionality of a
federal agent squeezing a person's luggage without a warrant.
</P>
<P>
   In the anonymous tip case, the court considered whether Miami
police Officer Carmen Anderson was justified in summarily frisking
a teen-ager on a street corner based solely on information from an
unknown source. The mysterious tipster said only that a black youth
in a plaid shirt was standing in front of a pawn shop with two
friends and carrying a gun.
</P>
<P>
   In a Texas case, the high court weighed whether the Constitution
allowed Border Patrol agent Cesar Cantu to squeeze the luggage of a
bus passenger in Sierra Blanca, without either the owner's consent
or suspicion that a crime had been committed.
</P>
<P>
   Both searches proved fruitful: The frisk revealed a firearm, and
the luggage inspection uncovered methamphetamine. Attorneys for the
defendants argued before the justices that police in both cases
violated their clients' constitutional right to be free from
unreasonable searches.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, in hearing the appeals, weighed the delicate
balance between the constitutional right of citizens to be free
from unreasonable searches and the need for law enforcement to
protect the public from dangerous crime.
</P>
<P>
   The cases brought directly before the court the
constitutionality of the often aggressive efforts of police to keep
guns and drugs off the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The high court in recent years has interpreted that
constitutional right, contained in the Fourth Amendment, narrowly
and has given police ever-increasing latitude to search individuals
and their possessions for evidence of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, in their consideration of the two cases, appeared
poised to continue that trend.
</P>
<P>
   Many justices showed strong support for the prosecutors who
argued that the officers were justified in frisking one suspect for
guns and squeezing the other's luggage in search of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Justice David H. Souter, for example, rejected the Florida
defense attorney's argument that police should not be allowed to
rely solely on anonymous tips before searching a suspect for a
weapon. Souter said officers, upon being told that a bomb had been
planted in a crowded school, might be justified in immediately
checking student's belongings,``Fourth Amendment or no Fourth
Amendment.''
</P>
<P>
   But several justices questioned prosecutors on whether the
officers should have been more respectful of the suspects' rights.
Justice John Paul Stevens, for example, told the attorney for the
Border Patrol that people have a reasonable expectation that their
private belongings will remain private.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Florida Attorney General Michael Neimand argued that
officer Anderson's concern for public safety justified her frisking
the boy without a warrant or suspicion that a specific crime was
committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are dealing with a dangerous weapon,'' Neimand said,
referring to the tipster's message that the boy, identified in
court papers as ``J.L.,'' was carrying a gun. While officers must
respect the Fourth Amendment, they also must consider the
``totality of the circumstances'' and conclude that an armed
suspect presents a threat to the public, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Solicitor General Irving Gornstein, pressing the
Clinton administration's support for Florida, said police can make
``common-sense judgments'' about the reliability of an anonymous
tip and the potential danger a suspect presents to the public.
</P>
<P>
   But assistant public defender Harvey Sepler, representing J.L.,
said the Constitution requires that police reasonably suspect that
a person is engaged in illegal activity before they conduct a
frisk.
</P>
<P>
   If police could act simply on a ``bald allegation'' that someone
is carrying a gun, nobody would be safe from being frisked by
officers, added Sepler, an assistant public defender in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you've got to say is `He's got a gun,''' Sepler added.
``Anybody, anywhere can be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas case, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld
the luggage search.
</P>
<P>
   Luggage owner Steven Dewayne Bond, as a passenger on a bus, must
have expected that luggage placed in an overhead bin would be
touched by fellow passengers, and possibly law enforcement
officials, the 5th Circuit said. The court upheld Bond's conviction
on drug possession and his sentence of 57 months in prison and
parole of three years.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney M. Carolyn Fuentes, urging the court to
overturn Bond's conviction, said the Border Patrol agent had no
justification for squeezing the bag. Bond had a ``reasonable
expectation'' that his bag would not be handled by other people,
including passengers or law enforcement, when he put it in the
overhead compartment, added Fuentes, an assistant federal public
defender in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decisions by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY XXXX &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
