u f BC-CANADIANS-RAID-BOS &LR;      02-29 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADIANS-RAID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANADIANS OFFER CASH TO LURE US BIOTECH EXPERTISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Seeking to lure American research business, the
Canadian province of Ontario is announcing $270 million in
incentives to U.S. biotechnology companies that perform medical
research at Ontario universities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ultimate goal is to develop the Kendall Square North and
I'd love for a significant part of that to be owned by
Massachusetts companies,'' Calvin Stiller, chairman of the Ontario
Research and Development Challenge Fund, said Tuesday. Kendall
Square is a section of Cambridge, adjacent to Boston, which is a
hotbed of biotechnology research and development.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is also looking at six other U.S. cities, but sees its
biggest recruiting effort in the Boston-Cambridge area, a short
flight from Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Ontario research funding, requiring matching dollars from
participating U.S. companies, is a first step by Canada to develop
a strong biotechnology industrial base.
</P>
<P>
   By attracting medical research from the Bay State, Ontario hopes
these companies will go the next step and expand their operations
near the University of Toronto and other Ontario universities, just
as the biotech community did in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Stiller points to Amgen Corp. of Thousand Oaks, Calif., the
world's largest biotechnology company, which late last year began
building an eight-story research facility in Kendall Square. The
site is just a few blocks from the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology where Amgen has funded several research programs for
more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   Ontario's goal is to invest as much as $35 million in
Boston-area companies this year, Stiller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can't do that amount, then I have not done my job or I
don't have a case,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ontario's faces several big risks, however. One is the potential
loss of top-notch university scientists who might emigrate to the
U.S. after working on American-sponsored research _ an acceleration
of Canada's ``brain drain.''
</P>
<P>
   Stiller said the Challenge Fund wants to invest in new
``platform'' technologies, rather than product specific research.
He acknowledged there will always be a ``tension'' between
universities and private industry over these issues.
</P>
<P>
   American biotech companies, for their part, will have to
consider whether the quality and scope of the research projects are
worth doing in Ontario or at a U.S. university, where the overall
costs will be higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada has not been on the radar screen of many U.S. biotech
companies and that's what we want to change,'' added Stiller.
``Look, we are pretty dull people but we speak the same language,
have an excellent university research focused on health care and
you can not ignore us.''
</P>
<P>
   At least two Cambridge biotech companies, Genzyme Corp. and
Vertex Pharmaceuticals Inc., said they would consider the Ontario
offer.
</P>
<P>
   But the details of the company-sponsored research program are
critical, said Richard Douglas, senior vice president of corporate
development at Genzyme.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have ongoing research collaborations around the world and,
while we have nothing in Canada now, we might be interested,'' said
Josh Boger, chairman and founder of Vertex Pharmaceuticals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
