<HEADLINE>
HOWARD STERN ON KATHIE LEE AND HIS NEW TV SHOW, `SON OF THE BEACH'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a press conference for the upcoming cable series ``Son of the
Beach,'' Howard Stern, who puts on a suit and assumes executive
responsibilities for the show as its executive producer, did what
he does best _ promote himself _ but he also took time out for a
little batting practice on his favorite target, Kathie Lee Gifford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son of the Beach'' stars Tim Stack, star and creator of the
underappreciated ``Nightstand With Dick Dietrich,'' a parody of
talk-show flotsam and jetsam, as Notch Johnson, the flaccid but
heroic lifeguard of a Malibu-adjacent beach. Think ``Baywatch,''
only the laughs are intentional, though Stern likened it to ``'Get
Smart' meets `The Beach.' It points out the ridiculousness of beach
shows. And Tim is hotter than David Hasselhoff.''
</P>
<P>
   It also offers plenty of anatomically ample women and puns about
genitalia and mammillae. ``It's not politically correct,'' allowed
Stern, stating the obvious. ``We don't even care if women don't
like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern won't appear in the series, which will debut on March 14
on the FX cable channel. ``Like you, I've never heard of FX
either,'' Stern deadpanned. ``I thought I was doing this show for
Fox.''
</P>
<P>
   The shock jock said the production process for the series was
``remarkably smooth, unlike my radio career. We had to check out
that the butt-cheek-to-fabric ratio (in the bathing suits) was
acceptable _ that was the kind of meetings I've been dealing with.
This is more exciting for me as opposed to radio, where there's
constant fighting, constant screaming and shouting. This is a new
role for me: responsible businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern insisted he was a hands-on executive, ensuring the series
keeps its wit about it. ``My name will bring audiences to exactly
one episode _ the first. If it's not funny, they won't come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Also in Stern's pipeline is an animated series for UPN titled
``Pipeline,'' and he's currently mulling over the future of his
radio career _ his contract expires in a couple of months. ``I'm
going to figure out if I want to go on in radio; I don't know if I
do,'' he said. Stern also reacted to Kathie Lee Gifford's
announcement that she was leaving the morning jabberfest ``Live
With Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee.'' ``It sounds like a contract ploy to
me,'' Stern said. ``If she's out of work, we should all celebrate.
That show is so irrelevant _ it's everything that's wrong with
television. Kathie Lee looks like a train hit her at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``She announced that she is leaving `Regis &AMP; Kathie Lee' because
of her children; she wanted to keep them out of the limelight,''
Stern continued, adding, ``The only person putting them in the
limelight is Kathie Lee. She needs to take them off the magazine
covers, take them out of her holiday specials. If it wasn't for
her, none of us would ever see or care about Kathie Lee's kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's just coincidence, but an evil, effeminate character
in ``Son of the Beach'' shares a name with Gifford's most
celebrated progeny: Cody. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1956EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
