<SLUG> BC-CALIF-MCCAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHING SIMPLE ABOUT CALIFORNIA'S PRIMARY
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MCCAIN-NYT) 
(nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Picture this: Sen. John McCain wins more total
votes than Gov. George W. Bush in the California primary next
Tuesday, as some polls here suggest is possible. California's
secretary of state, Bill Jones, a Republican who also happens to be
McCain's most prominent California supporter, would certify him,
under state law, as the Republican winner of the state's blanket
primary, in which the names of all candidates appear on the same
ballot regardless of party.
</P>
<P>
   Simple? Not.
</P>
<P>
   Rule 32b9 of the Republican National Committee prohibits the
party from recognizing the results of so-called jungle primaries,
in which voters of any party may vote for candidates of any other
by skittering down the very same ballot. So, state and national
party officials insist, all of California's 162 Republican
delegates will go to the candidate who receives the most Republican
votes, as determined by a second, computer-coded count of
party-members only.
</P>
<P>
   And so far, Bush has maintained about a 2-to-1 lead among
Republicans in the polls, while he and McCain are within a few
points of each other overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the loser goes the spoils,'' said Tony Quinn, a Republican
political strategist and expert on redistricting in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   That anomaly could conceivably produce the first real fight over
credentials at a Republican National Convention since the contest
between Dwight D. Eisenhower and Robert A. Taft in 1952, before
primaries became the main means of choosing nominees.
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds complicated, it is.
</P>
<P>
   Courts have consistently given the parties wide leeway in
setting their own rules and choosing delegates. The McCain camp's
only recourse would be for a registered California Republican who
could otherwise have been a delegate to file a challenge with the
party's nine-member contest committee, which would make a
recommendation to the full Republican National Committee. The
leadership's ruling could in turn be appealed to the credentials
committee, and could ultimately wind up as the first order of
business on the floor of the convention in Philadelphia this
summer. In that decision, California's disputed delegation could
not vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the party leadership is controlled by officials sympathetic
to Bush. Moreover, Bush, McCain and Alan Keyes have all filed
notarized affidavits with the California Republican Party agreeing
to abide by the results of the Republican-only count and to forgo
undertaking or supporting any challenges, so McCain would face an
uphill fight.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some Republicans here say there are arguments to be made.
In states like Michigan and South Carolina, any registered voter
may request a partisan ballot to vote in a primary. In others, like
New Hampshire, Republicans and independents may vote in a
Republican primary, but not Democrats. These are known as ``open
primaries,'' and while the party establishment may not like them,
it has accepted them in an effort to draw crossover voters who may
stick with Republicans in November.
</P>
<P>
   But in California, Washington and Alaska, western states without
strong partisan traditions, the names of all candidates are listed
on the primary ballot, allowing voters to mix and match, without
even a one-day pretense of party affiliation. Neither major
national party tolerates such heresy, and the Republicans adopted
their rule in 1988, shortly after Washington state adopted its
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a difference without a distinction,'' said Quinn.
``What it says is you can accept somebody who walks in in a state
like Virginia, and says `Give me the Republican ballot,' but you
won't accept our blanket system here.''
</P>
<P>
   California's system was passed in 1996 ballot measure,
Proposition 198. Its chief sponsor was Tom Campbell, then a
Republican state senator and now a congressman from Northern
California, who had lost a primary for U.S. Senate to a more
conservative candidate in 1992 and believed he might have won with
crossover voters. But from the beginning, the major political
parties here have opposed the measure as an unconstitutional
meddling with their right of free association. Federal courts have
upheld the law and the parties' challenge is to be heard before the
U.S. Supreme Court in April.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the parties sought to ``re-close'' the
presidential primary, first with a 1998 ballot measure that failed
at the polls, and then with a bipartisan bill signed last year by
Gov. Gray Davis specifying the two counts, one of the overall vote
and one of the partisan vote.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday, a former Democratic state senator, Barry Keene,
filed a challenge asking the California Supreme Court to overturn
the dual-count law, on the grounds that under the California
Constitution, a ballot initiative may only be amended by another
initiative, not legislation. He asked the court to block the public
release of any partisan count next week, pending a hearing on the
merits.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Jones, the secretary of state, has argued that the
parties should change their rules to accept the blanket system.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 1956EST &QL; 
