</P>
<P>
   LEDE STORY:
</P>
<P>
   CAP-ERNST (Paris) _ Cap Gemini will buy Ernst &AMP; Young's
consulting business for $11.1 billion, taking Europe's biggest
computer services company into the United States. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISPLAY:
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-TELECOM (Hong Kong) _ Pacific Century CyberWorks, a
nine-month-old company founded by Richard Li, an heir to the most
powerful family dynasty in Hong Kong, is acquiring the territory's
flagship telephone company, Cable and Wireless HKT, with seeming
ease, despite his company's small size and meager assets, and
despite a formidable counterbid by the much larger Singapore
Telecommunications. The deal has troubled some people in Hong Kong,
who say it smacks of the kind of favoritism and old-boy cronyism
that characterized business in Hong Kong during 154 years of
colonial rule. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 9 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM CENTER:
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-CABLE (London) _ When Graham Wallace became chief
executive of Cable and Wireless PLC a year ago this week, he had
been expected to be the consummate company man, reluctant to shake
up the far-flung telecommunications company that once symbolized
Britain's imperial reach. But Wallace quickly began selling pieces
of his company, orchestrating a number of large deals that
culminated with the sale of Cable and Wireless' stake in Cable and
Wireless HKT, the Hong Kong phone company, to Hong Kong's Pacific
Century CyberWorks Ltd. In so doing, Wallace has proved he can defy
conventional wisdom. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   (With photo NYT24)
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:15 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM RIGHT:
</P>
<P>
   CLEAR-SFX (Undated) _ The nation's third-largest broadcaster,
Clear Channel Communications, agrees to acquire SFX Entertainment,
the biggest producer of concerts, theater and sporting events for
$3.3 billion. The advertising column by Stuart Elliott.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM LEFT:
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The debate over the future of
U.S. securities markets entered high gear on Tuesday as Wall
Street's top executives told senators that the current system is
sometimes unfair to investors and could cost the United States its
position as the world's financial capital. By Alex Berenson.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move by 8:30 p.m.)
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Digest of the day's financial stories.
</P>
