<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT &LR;      02-29 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HALL-OF-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON, ONLY MANAGER TO WIN WORLD SERIES IN BOTH LEAGUES, ELECTED
TO HALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ Sparky Anderson promised himself that he would not
enter the Baseball Hall of Fame unless he was elected as a member.
Anderson can satisfy his curiosity about what is in the shrine in
Cooperstown, N.Y., after the Veterans Committee chose the former
manager of the Cincinnati Reds and Detroit Tigers as the newest
Hall of Famer.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, the only manager to win World Series in both leagues,
will join Tony Perez, one of his former players with the Big Red
Machine of the 1970s, when the induction ceremonies are held on
July 23. On that day, Anderson, who will wear a Reds' cap on his
plaque, will finally walk into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go into the most precious place in baseball
unless I belonged there,'' Anderson said. ``If I got elected, I'll
go in and spend hours looking at everything. Then I'll know I'm in
a place that's a dream house.''
</P>
<P>
   There was controversy during Tuesday's meeting as the committee
members were told not to vote for Dick Williams, the former manager
who won the 1972 and 1973 World Series with the Oakland A's. He was
a runner-up in the voting last year. But Williams pleaded no
contest to charges of indecent exposure last January and the Hall
of Fame wanted to put some distance between the incident before
making Williams eligible again.
</P>
<P>
   At least one committee member challenged the directive and said
that the members should be able to make their own decisions on
Williams, but the ruling stood. Joe Brown, the chairman of the
committee, did not mention Williams as one of the men who received
votes in the category for former managers, executives, umpires and
Negro Leaguers. One person familiar with the committee's previous
thinking said Williams, a special adviser to the Yankees who was
instructed not to come to spring training, would probably have been
inducted if he had not been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to me down in Fort Myers when I was arrested
evidently hurt me quite a bit,'' Williams said in a telephone
interview. ``What came out on that in the papers was not true. I
was not masturbating on the balcony. I'm going to issue a statement
about it so the explanation goes across the country.''
</P>
<P>
   While Williams was not specific about what he was doing, he
called the incident embarrassing. Williams tried to tread carefully
about the apparent slight because the members will be considering
him next year, but he admitted that it seemed unfair that members
were forbidden from voting for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anything about that,'' Williams said. ``I don't
want to say anything against the committee. But that doesn't seem
fair. Sparky was going to get in anyway. That just complicated my
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Anderson, Turkey Stearnes, a Negro Leagues
outfielder with a .352 career average, and Bid McPhee, a second
baseman who played for the Reds in the 1880s and 1890s, were also
inducted. Bill Mazeroski, Gil Hodges, Dom DiMaggio and Tony Oliva
were among the players who were strongly considered for induction
in the former major leaguer category, but none of them received
enough votes.
</P>
<P>
   It took a 75 percent vote from the 14-man committee, or 11
votes, to be inducted and Mazeroski, the former second baseman for
the Pittsburgh Pirates, received 10 votes. Hodges, the stoic
manager of the Mets and the former first baseman for the Brooklyn
Dodgers, fell three or four votes shy. Normally, the committee has
15 members, but Buck O'Neill was unable to attend because of an
arthritic condition. The committee votes in four different
categories.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson managed the Reds from 1970-78, winning two World Series
titles, and managed the Tigers from 1979-1995, winning another
championship. He had a 2,194-1,834 managerial record, trailing only
Connie Mack (3,731) and John McGraw (2,784) for the most victories
in major league history.
</P>
<P>
   As the 16th manager to be elected to the Hall of Fame, Anderson
had two successful and disparate parts of his career. He was the
brains behind the Big Red Machine of Johnny Bench, Joe Morgan, Pete
Rose and Tony Perez, winning the title with the Reds in 1975 and
1976. Then Anderson went to the Tigers and won another title in
1984, guiding the likes of Kirk Gibson, Alan Trammell, Lou Whitaker
and Willie Hernandez. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Anderson walks through the doors in Cooperstown for the
first time, Perez and Marty Brennaman, a Reds broadcaster, will be
inducted as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never worn a World Series ring, and I'll wear this ring
until I die,'' Anderson said. ``That, to me, is how much of a
difference there is between the World Series and the Hall of
Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
