<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-HERRING01-COX     02-29 1617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERRING01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Companies pitch ideas hoping investors will catch at Red Herring
market
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the search for the Next New Thing, this was _ at
least for the moment _ the place for seekers to be.
</P>
<P>
   Red Herring's Venture Market South, which wraps up today at the
Ritz-Carlton, has been a high-octane mix of entrepreneurs from
around the Southeast and a crowd of folks with money to invest.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of money that only the Internet economy can
entice _ or create.
</P>
<P>
   John Mecklenburg, Red Herring editor of events, talked of the
Internet's spectacular growth, arguing that even a conservative
projection will make the Net a $1.5 trillion industry within three
years, eclipsing industries like telecommunications and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   He told of casually giving his card to a cab driver on a trip to
a remote part of Egypt, then months later receiving an e-mail from
the man asking whether he should take his savings and buy stock in
Yahoo. ``It means that there is almost no place on the Earth that
you can go anymore where people aren't participating in the
Internet economy, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Mecklenburg promised investors Tuesday that their presence would
be rewarded. ``Half of the 44 companies here were formed in 1999,''
he said. ``They are young and very hungry _ and they are here to
cut deals.''
</P>
<P>
   In trade for some money, the entrepreneurs would part with some
control.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as, one by one, the chief executives began stepping into the
spotlight, they revealed as much confidence as hunger. Their
markets are measured in billions of dollars, their approach is
distinctive, their management stellar, or so they told the
prospective investors.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Galileo Development wants to raise $5 million for
its Web-based software solutions business, said CEO Rebecca W.
Bass. ``We see a $50 billion potential market by 2004.''
</P>
<P>
   Each entrepreneur took the few minutes allotted to explain why
his or her idea, technology or business is a platinum-plated chance
to invest onto a rocket before it leaves the pad.
</P>
<P>
   But then, tickets are apparently not that hard to hawk.
</P>
<P>
   The start-ups at this conference have been culled from hundreds
of companies. And listening to their stories is an audience of
hundreds of venture capitalists who represent investors across the
country _ and hundreds of millions of dollars that they are
scrambling for ways to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ryan, chief executive and co-founder of Inanta, said his
company, which has a technology for delivering high-speed audio and
video, last year received about $2.5 million in ``seed money'' from
a Toronto fund to get started. Now he's looking for 10 times that.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, he's feeling picky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll have no problem finding the money,'' Ryan said.
``The issue is finding the right money.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta money is particularly interested in companies using the
Net to sell from one business to another _ the ``B-2-B'' play.
Incanta has technology that will be sold to Internet Service
Providers, but the fact that it is delivered to consumers tarnished
its luster, Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Atlanta, it's a very tough sell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Incanta is giving part of itself to charity. The company on
Friday will announce a donation of 2 percent equity interest to the
Atlanta-based Boys and Girls Clubs, Ryan said. ``You have to have a
shared vision. You have to have a belief set.''
</P>
<P>
   At the edge of the tech boom are other companies that hope to
serve the surge of start-ups. For instance, new companies can look
to incubators like eHatchery or the Advanced Technology Development
Center at Georgia Tech as places to percolate and grow.
</P>
<P>
   And there are new entries there, too.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Hall Green, president of Green Machine, says his company
has plans to rent space in a building near Georgia Tech that would
house nascent tech firms. The company hopes to offer everything
from marketing to ad agency assistance, and may even invest its own
money at times, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having cool space with a start-up is important. We will have
the coolest space in town.''
</P>
<P>
   In the room where the investors could meet the entrepreneurs, a
tide of people surged between rows of booths. People picked up a
flier, stared intently at a demo, listened to an entrepreneurial
pitch before shifting to the next display. They jostled each other
as if milling in a bustling station, watching signs for a host of
trains departing and wondering whether to board.
</P>
<P>
   In the air hung the scent of possibility. Or perhaps just the
ghosts of IPOs past.
</P>
<P>
   Keynote speaker Robert Young was introduced as the chairman and
co-founder of Red Hat Inc., a company that sells Linux-based
software and has reported revenues totaling less than $13 million,
but has shares worth $9.3 billion. And that is after the stock lost
more than 50 percent of its value in the recent market decline.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Atlanta-based companies also have swiftly passed
from start-up to publicly traded welterweights, including Internet
Security Systems, Healtheon/WebMD and EarthLink.
</P>
<P>
   But Young, wearing red tie, red socks and eventually donning his
signature red baseball cap, alternately doused the hype and played
to it. ``What are the statistics? Four out of five businesses go
bust in the first year and most of the rest go bust in the second
year.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned against fanatical adherence to business plans or
religious devotion to technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The value of our product was not the bits and bytes, the value
was in the licensing model. We treated our customers as partners
not servants.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those hoping to follow Young's example _ or at least Red
Hat's success _ were a slew of CEOs with resumes studded with
corporate brand names.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan and the other Incanta founders came from Nortel Networks.
CEO Eric Grossman was a senior manager at Ernst &AMP; Young before
becoming CEO of SimplyHealth.com. Mike Bruce of Virginia-based
SingleShop.com started working for Bellcore as a software developer
_ when he was in the seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Buttermore was MediaOne's top engineer in Atlanta before
leaving late last year to start PurePacket Communications, which
will offer high-speed Internet access through a variety of methods.
</P>
<P>
   Having the right people is key, said Chris Kidd, managing
director of the executive search firm, Korn/Ferry International.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any of us in this business can raise $50 million with five
phone calls, if you have the right management team,'' he said
Monday. ``Culture, structure and process will all follow if you
choose your people carefully.''
</P>
<P>
   But Herring hopefuls arrived with varying angles ranging from
those with a consumer service to business-to-business. There were
some with technology behind the curtain that consumers will never
see, even as they use the service. Others offer Web-based ways to
pool information that consumers will want _ along with various
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Benefits of Atlanta, for example, offers to connect
insurers, administrators, employers, employees, consumers and
others who need access to information about insurance. The company
has $250,000 get-started money from its management and is seeking
$6 million more.
</P>
<P>
   By eliminating paper, Digital Benefits stands to win big, said
CEO John Nail. ``Bottom line, there are hundreds of billions of
dollars of waste.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar kind of waste permeates the legal profession, where
potential customers should be able and anxious to save time and
costs, said Samuel B. Kellett Jr., chief executive of Atlanta-based
eAttorney.com. ``It is a huge, affluent demographic. There is $73
billion lost to inefficiencies. With our technology, lawyers could
do their work in half the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerging Net technologies also permit increasingly customized
responses to users _ and some of the start-ups would like to
capitalize on them.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta-based Chutney has already raised $2 million for its
software aimed at letting Web sites personalize the responses given
to surfers, said CEO Aninya Datta, a professor at Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia-based iClique.com has technology to tailor Web sites _
like those of matchmakers _ to the cultural bent of the user, said
CEO Barry E.A. Johnson, former president of MSBET, the Microsoft
venture with Black Entertainment Television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seniors don't date the way teen-agers do, and Latino men don't
date the way white men do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   IClique, which hopes to raise up to $7 million, believes its
answers are unique. What it shares with so many other start-ups is
the notion that cyberspace is the place for romance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's looking for love,'' Johnson said. ``And especially
on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   And then you ask, how badly does someone want love?
</P>
<P>
   Some Red Herring entrepreneurs will have a shot at locking up $1
million in financing before the conference even closes. PTEK
Ventures, the investment arm of PTEK Holdings, late this afternoon
will pick four presenting companies and let them compete for a
portion _ or all _ of $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a Regis Philbin lookalike, four hungry
entrepreneurs, and a public quiz in the style of television's ``Who
Wants to Be A Millionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Jon Steelman, founder and CEO of Atlanta-based Chatfish, said he
is looking for $4 million to fund the company, which has developed
interactive Web technology. He is not sure he wants to take up
PTEK's Millionaire Challenge, figuring that like any other funding,
it would no doubt come with strings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cute. It's a good gimmick. But it's not free money.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
