u i BC-CHECHNYA-JOURNALIST-B     02-29 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-JOURNALIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREED REPORTER'S CLAIMS OF TORTURE RAISE CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ A senior Russia commander, saying the last major rebel
stronghold in Chechnya had been captured, Tuesday declared that the
full-scale offensive against separatist militants in the republic
had come to an end.
</P>
<P>
   But a first-hand account by a freed Radio Liberty reporter of
the abusive treatment of inmates in a detention camp in Chechnya
raised new questions about what fate awaits the populace as Moscow
tightens its grip on the breakaway region.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel General Gennady Troshev, the deputy commander of
Russia's 100,000 troops in Chechnya, said the fall of the mountain
town of Shatoi meant that ``the bandit formations have been
defeated.'' He said troops were mopping up remaining pockets of
resistance after overrunning Shatoi, and predicted hostilities in
Chechnya would cease altogether in a matter of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can speak of the conclusion of the military operation to
destroy large bandit groups,'' Troshev said.
</P>
<P>
   Troshev's announcement was sure to provide a boost for Acting
President Vladimir Putin, already the favorite to win a March 26
presidential vote. But the scathing account of journalist Andrei
Babitsky, who returned to Moscow Tuesday after a mysterious
six-week disappearance, took some of the sheen off Moscow's victory
declaration.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky, who was detained by Russian forces in January,
described a regimen of heavy beatings and torture at the
``filtration camp'' in Chernokozovo, in northern Chechnya, where
Russian authorities hold suspected Chechen rebels. Babitsky said he
was held there in late January before being turned over to masked
men who kept him captive in Chechnya until his release.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups and Chechen refugees have alleged that
inmates at the Chernokozovo camp are subjected to systematic
torture, rape and executions by Russian troops, charges Moscow
heatedly denies as anti-Russian propaganda. Babitsky provided a
look at conditions in the camp at a time when Moscow is stepping up
detentions of young men in areas recently occupied by federal
troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the first three days I was there the beatings continued
24 hours a day,'' Babitsky told Russian NTV television, describing
his captors as ``sadists.''
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky said in an interview with the Russian service of Radio
Liberty that he himself had undergone a ``routine initiation, which
everyone without exception goes through when they arrive there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a few dozen blows of a truncheon on the body, which go
fairly painlessly after two or three days and do not leave any
serious irreparable internal consequences,'' he said, adding he was
spared much worse treatment afforded suspected rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Torture, I cannot find another word,'' he said, describing the
ordeal of one woman who he said was beaten for several hours on
Jan. 20. ``There were cries which showed a person is experiencing
torturous, unbearable pain and experiencing it for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian investigators looking into alleged human rights
violations at Chernokozovo have repeatedly described the situation
there as ``normal.'' The camp warden told journalists Tuesday he
had heard no complaints from prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say the military operation in Chechnya is an
effort to restore peace and order after three years of lawlessness
under the rebels, who had driven out Russian troops in 1994-1996
war.
</P>
<P>
   As Troshev handed a Russian flag to a paratrooper to raise over
the war-wrecked town of Shatoi, he promised villagers that their
troubles were over.
</P>
<P>
   Troshev, shown on NTV television, said Russian troops would have
to conduct frequent sweeps of Chechen settlements to ensure
militants did not return _ as they were able to do repeatedly in
the previous war.
</P>
<P>
   News agencies reported that most of the 2,000 rebels who had
been holed up in Shatoi had escaped into nearby villages and could
be expected to regroup. Others were believed to be trying to cross
Chechnya's mountainous southern border into the former Soviet
republic of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In Chechnya last week, Russian soldiers said they believed that
many rebels had returned to their homes disguised as civilians,
where they could hide out and plan new guerilla attacks. Chechen
civilians in villages south of the destroyed capital, Grozny, say
all males aged 15 and older are detained by the local police. When
some of them do not come back, people assume they have been taken
to Chernokozovo.
</P>
<P>
   This week, journalists who were allowed to visit the
Chernokozovo detention center saw no signs of mistreatment, and
described freshly painted walls and hot meals. But when a group of
Chechen women tried to speak with the journalists after the tour of
the facility, the Russian organizers refused to stop the bus and
armed troops pushed the women back.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky resurfaced in the Dagestani capital Makhachkala Friday
after weeks of speculation about where he was and whether he was
even alive.
</P>
<P>
   He had been held in police custody in Dagestan on charges of
holding a false passport and was released only after Putin
intervened by saying he opposed his detention for the offense.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky, whose scathing reports from the war zone infuriated
the Kremlin, still faces questioning on charges of aiding the
rebels, and is not allowed to leave Moscow. He promised eventually
to tell everything about his detention and release, but he did not
speak to reporters gathered on the street outside his Moscow
apartment Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, Andrei is exhausted,'' his wife Lyudmila said. ``He is
sleeping. I'm very sorry. I also haven't slept in two days myself.
Come back tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Correspondent Brian Whitmore contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
