<HEADLINE>
E-COMMERCE SOFTWARE FIRM SHARES TRIPLE ON FIRST DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of net.Genesis Corp., an Internet marketing software firm
founded by two college students, more than tripled Tuesday in
initial trading.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge, Mass. company designs software that helps Web
businesses analyze information about site visitors to help convert
them into frequent buyers. This niche market continues to grow
rapidly, fueled by the number of firms flocking to the Web to sell
everything from Pokemon video games to sports utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Although many online retailers are expected to struggle in an
increasingly crowded market, the software companies that help build
better Web sites should perform well over the next several years,
industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of which Web site eventually wins, the companies
providing the infrastructure are expected to survive,'' said Steve
Tuen, an analyst with the IPO Value Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   In its first day of trading on the Nasdaq Stock Market,
net.Genesis shares climbed from its opening price of 18 to close at
56 13/16. The company raised $76.5 million amid a robust market for
technology stocks Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The software firm's backers include the Waltham, Mass. venture
capital firm, Charles River Partners, which owned about 12 percent
of net.Genesis after the offering. Its 2.4 million shares were
worth about $134 million Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive Larry Bohn held nearly 7 percent, worth
approximately $79 million.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street has rewarded several other providers of Web consumer
analysis. Shares of Accrue Software Inc., initially priced at 10
apiece last July, closed Tuesday at 46 15/16. WebTrends Corp.,
which went public at 13 per share in February 1999, closed at 95 a
share.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Genesis is among several Massachusetts companies going
public this week. Also holding IPOs this week are MatrixOne Inc., a
Chelmsford software firm, and Switchboard Inc., a Westborough firm
that provides a huge directory of individuals and businesses
online.
</P>
<P>
   Net.Genesis was founded by pals Eric Richard and Matt Cutler in
1994, when they were juniors at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology. Richard is the firm's chief technology officer, while
Cutler has been dubbed the ``chief e-business intelligence
officer.''
</P>
<P>
   The company underwent rapid change under Bohn, who was brought
in two years ago. Sales ballooned, and net.Genesis' staff grew from
24 employees in 1998 to 170 today.
</P>
<P>
   Like many technology start-ups, net.Genesis is hemmorrhaging
money even as revenue grows. For the year ended Dec. 31, it lost
$17.9 million on $6.5 million in sales. That compared to a net loss
of $6.4 million the previous year on sales of $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Investors face other risks.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent federal filing, net.Genesis warned that limits or
bans on cookies _ files that companies plant in computers to
collect information about individuals' Web activities _ could make
its software less effective. To serve its corporate customers,
which include SmarterKids.com and Fidelity Investments, net.Genesis
needs data collected from cookies.
</P>
<P>
   Although many online sites require users to accept cookies to
access their Web pages, consumers are increasingly becoming
concerned about invasions of their privacy. And federal regulators
are starting to look into their complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is gaining momentum,'' analyst Tuen said.
</P>
<P>
   Bohn and other technology executives argue that most information
collected from cookies is used to help e-commerce players cater to
their consumers. And if the federal government cracks down on
cookies, companies can always find other ways to get information on
their shoppers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   `If cookies disappear, God will need a reason to invent them
again,'' said Bohn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
