<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2456 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER01-COX-1STL     02-29 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER01-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST LEDE
 &HT;    EDs: Corrects, clarifies time zone in 11th brief
 &HT;    
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Decision day arrives in 3 states
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush was expected to beat John McCain in the Virginia
primary and North Dakota caucuses Tuesday, but was in a close
primary race in Washington state. The three contests were not
expected to settle much in the bitter fight between the two unless
Bush loses Virginia _ a potentially fatal blow to his campaign. But
the three contests could set the tone for next week's Super Tuesday
on March 7, when voters in 12 states, including New York,
California and Ohio, hold Republican primaries or caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE THE DELEGATES ARE _ AND AREN'T
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia Republican primary on Tuesday, also open to
Democrats and independents, has 56 delegates at stake, winner take
all. The North Dakota GOP caucuses have 19 delegates at stake,
awarded proportionally. The GOP primary in Washington state, open
to Democrats and independents, has 37 delegates at stake, 12 to be
awarded to today's top vote-getter and 25 at caucuses on March 7.
Washington state's Democratic primary is a nonbinding ``beauty
contest,'' with no delegates at stake.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE REVERSAL, OF SORTS
</P>
<P>
   It looks like there could be a debate after all between John
McCain and George W. Bush in advance of next week's big round of
Super Tuesday primaries. McCain had canceled plans to take part in
Thursday's debate in Los Angeles, but he reversed himself Tuesday
and said he would debate Bush before next week's California primary
if he can do it by live satellite feed. McCain said he was willing
to change his campaign schedule in New York to appear. He also
offered to debate Bush on Wednesday via satellite on MSNBC's
``Hardball,'' or in person Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
Thursday's debate, to be telecast nationally on CNN, will also
include Alan Keyes.
</P>
<P>
   WHY PULL OUT TO BEGIN WITH? 'TIS A MYSTERY
</P>
<P>
   To Californians, it was all a little baffling. Why would John
McCain pull out of the only Republican debate scheduled in the
nation's largest state the week before the highest-stakes primary
on the political calendar? McCain's decision to withdraw from the
forum Thursday in Los Angeles, citing scheduling conflicts, took
everyone by surprise, including the debate's sponsors, CNN and the
Los Angeles Times. It also caused dissension in McCain's own
campaign: His communications director, Daniel Schnur, was quoted as
saying that the withdrawal was ``definitely a mistake'' and ``a
tactical error at the staff level.''
</P>
<P>
   REGRET AT HOLDING TONGUE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush expressed regret Tuesday for not speaking up
sooner against anti-Catholic bias. He says he should have done so
when he spoke at Bob Jones University in Greenville, S.C., which
has harbored anti-Catholic sentiment. Bush said he felt ``things
are coming my way'' as voters cast ballots in GOP primaries Tuesday
in Virginia and Washington state and in North Dakota's caucuses.
Bush made plans to appear via satellite on David Letterman's
late-night talk show tonight. Tuesday, he met with Catholic
Charities workers in the half-finished Fatima Family Center, which
will offer social services in Cleveland's impoverished Hough
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   SOME UNEASINESS, BUT STILL BEHIND MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   Conservative activist Gary Bauer, who endorsed John McCain after
dropping his own presidential bid, said Tuesday the senator's
remarks reflected a ``very personal'' dispute between McCain and
Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell. Bauer said McCain went too far by
comparing the two Christian leaders to ``fringe'' leaders on the
left, but urged conservative voters to support McCain as the
candidate more strongly opposed to abortion and same-sex marriage.
``Politics is an uncomfortable business,'' Bauer said on NBC's
``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE HEART THAN VOTES
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley's presidential campaign stopped in San Francisco on
Tuesday, but left its heart in Washington state, where he hoped
voters would give him a desperately needed boost. Though no
delegates were at stake in Washington _ they will be assigned at
statewide party caucuses next Tuesday _ the Democratic ``beauty
contest'' was important for Bradley after Al Gore defeated him in
Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   END OF THE ROAD IN PACIFIC NORTHWEST?
</P>
<P>
   The National Journal's Political Hotline, citing an anonymous
high-level official in Bill Bradley's campaign, reports that
Bradley will drop out of the presidential race today if he doesn't
win Washington state. Barring that, Bradley is slated to debate Al
Gore in Los Angeles tonight, then take a red-eye to New York, where
polls give him a better shot at notching a significant win March 7.
</P>
<P>
   APPEALING TO LATINOS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was in California on Tuesday, addressing a Hispanic
event in Los Angeles and headlining two fund-raisers. Speaking at a
local community center in Cudahy, where nine out of 10 residents is
Latino, Gore called education and health care key to expanding
economic prosperity throughout the Latino community. Gore noted
that over the past seven years, incomes for Latino families have
risen, Latino homeownership has increased, and the Latino
unemployment rate has reached its lowest level in history. But, he
said, more must be done.
</P>
<P>
   WIN THE BATTLE, LOSE THE WAR?
</P>
<P>
   Polls show John McCain tied with George W. Bush in California's
popular vote, but well behind among the Republicans whose votes are
the only ones that count toward choosing California delegates.
McCain said if he wins the overall vote but loses the delegate
race, the Republican Party will have to decide, ``Do they want
somebody who wins the majority or do they want somebody who wins
only Republican votes?''
</P>
<P>
   THE LAST WEEK _ DECISION TIME
</P>
<P>
   Polls in California also show a lopsided Democratic contest,
with Al Gore far ahead. But Bill Bradley insisted, ``Californians
make their decision in the last week. There's no question about
that.'' Bradley and his aides also were completing work on an
unusual, five-minute TV ad to be broadcast Thursday at 10:54 p.m.
PST and EST (9:54 CST and MST) across the country on CBS. ``It's
Bradley speaking personally to voters about his vision for the
country and the basis of his candidacy and why he would be a better
president,'' spokesman Eric Hauser said. The campaign did not
reveal the cost of the ad.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO CUT THROUGH MANAGED CARE
</P>
<P>
   Aetna U.S. Healthcare has decided to continue skilled nursing
care for a baby whose case caught Al Gore's attention. The
company's chief medical officer, Dr. Arthur Leibowitz, said
evaluation of Ian Malone's case was sped up due to Gore's interest.
The baby, now about 5 months old, has brain damage caused by a
difficult birth. He suffers seizures, can't swallow and is prone to
choking. The 12-hour-a-day, in-home nursing care costs about $300 a
day, the Malones said. A reviewer had recommended that nursing care
be terminated and that the family care for the infant full-time.
Leibowitz said the final decision to continue nursing help would
have been made even if the case had not become a presidential
campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   HE'S THE FIREFIGHTER WIELDING THE HOSE
</P>
<P>
   Declaring that ``politics isn't about votes only,'' Alan Keyes
said he won't drop out of the GOP race because he is calling
attention to moral problems in the country. ``I'm not giving up. I
won't give up; America's moral house is on fire,'' he said. In a
speech at Syracuse University, Keyes said George W. Bush hasn't got
a chance to win the presidency. He said Republicans won't win on
economic grounds, because the national economy is strong under
President Clinton's administration.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
