<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY SHARES LIFT NASDAQ TO ANOTHER RECORD HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stock prices staged a broad, sharp advance in heavy
trading Tuesday. Demand for technology stocks was especially
intense, and the Nasdaq composite index rose to a record.
</P>
<P>
   Led by networking and computer-related stocks, the Nasdaq jumped
118.84 points, or 2.6 percent, to 4,696.69.
</P>
<P>
   The gain capped an amazing month for the index: In February, the
Nasdaq rose more than 19 percent. For the year, the index is up
15.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology, telecommunications and biotechnology are areas
where it is hard to argue with a good story and big promises,''
said Michael Clark, head of United States stock trading for Credit
Suisse First Boston. ``The market loves the story, the growth and
the promise.''
</P>
<P>
   The gains were not limited to stocks listed on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   For a second straight session blue-chip stocks moved higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, helped by big gains in
Hewlett-Packard, AT&AMP;T and General Electric, rose 89.66 points, or
0.9 percent, to 10,128.31.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 18.37, or 1.4
percent, to 1,366.42, led by big gains in Texas Instruments,
Motorola and Oracle.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small cap stocks soared and set a
record.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for small but fast-growing technology and biotechnology
companies helped to propel the Russell 2000 index by 20.03, or 3.6
percent, to a record 577.71. So far this year, the Russell
technology index has jumped 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Trading was heavy.
</P>
<P>
   Volume on the Nasdaq stock market set a record Tuesday, at 2.07
billion shares. On the New York Stock Exchange 1.2 billion shares
changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the specter of additional moves by the Federal
Reserve Board to raise short-term interest rates, most analysts
said gains in sectors of the market that are sensitive to rising
rates are likely to be somewhat limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been in a trading range on the Dow of between 10,000
and 12,000 for much of the last year,'' said Philip Orlando, chief
investment officer at Value Line Asset Management. ``We are likely
to stay within that band for a while longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando said that recently he has been a buyer of stocks like
Wal-Mart, International Paper, General Electric and Johnson &AMP;
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Micron Technology, the biggest domestic maker of computer-memory
chips, was one of the session's brightest performers.
</P>
<P>
   Micron shares surged 17 15/16, to 96, spurred by a 10 percent
rise in chip prices over the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, which signed a licensing deal with Psion PLC, Europe's
largest maker of palmtop computers, gained 12, to 170{. The company
later announced a three-for-one stock split.
</P>
<P>
   3Com was another contributor to the S&AMP;P 500's advance.
</P>
<P>
   The stock, which has been a big winner so far this year, soared
again Tuesday in advance of the initial public offering of its Palm
division.
</P>
<P>
   3Com shares jumped 18 15/16, to 98.
</P>
<P>
   Biotechnology shares were higher.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech rose 11 3/8, to 192~. Immunex closed at 197 7/16, up 6
11/16. And Biogen gained 3 1/16, to 107 5/16.
</P>
<P>
   Oil and oil service stocks also did well. Exxon Mobil rose 1
13/16, to 75 5/16. Philips Petroleum gained 1, to 38[.
</P>
<P>
   Among oil service stocks, Halliburton was up 3 5/16, to 38 3/16.
Schlumberger gained 4 33/64, to 73 55/64. And BJ Services closed at
57 1/16, up 4\.
</P>
<P>
   Retailing stocks, which have been under selling pressure so far
this year, did better.
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart, a Dow component, gained 2} to 48~. Staples was up 2[,
to 27. And Circuit City rose 4|, to 40 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
