<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0381 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HONGKONG-CABLE-NYT &LR;      02-29 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-CABLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAR-FLUNG COMMUNICATIONS COMPANY NOW STRIVES FOR FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: England, Germany, Texas, Australia)   (See also HONGKONG-TELECOM)  
(jw) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ When Graham Wallace became chief executive of Cable and
Wireless PLC a year ago this week, he had been expected to be the
consummate company man, reluctant to shake up the far-flung
telecommunications company that once symbolized Britain's imperial
reach.
</P>
<P>
   But Wallace quickly began selling pieces of his company,
orchestrating a number of large deals that culminated with the sale
of Cable and Wireless' stake in Cable and Wireless HKT, the Hong
Kong phone company, to Hong Kong's Pacific Century CyberWorks Ltd.
In so doing, Wallace has proved he can defy conventional wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace is reinventing Cable and Wireless from a
telecommunications holding concern with a scattering of interests
around the world into a leaner telecommunications business focused
on serving other business customers, not the more visible but less
profitable consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   With the sale announced Tuesday of Cable and Wireless HKT, in
which the British parent held a 54 percent stake, Wallace may also
be putting his own company on the market. Some analysts said a
throng of hungry rivals in the telecommunications business might be
looking at Cable and Wireless to increase their own size.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace acknowledged the possibility that the sale of Cable and
Wireless might make the parent company more appealing to his
rivals. ``I think we're an extremely attractive company, we have a
unique set of assets,'' he said. ``But whether or not we attract a
bid isn't in my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace has rid Cable and Wireless of its two largest businesses
aimed at the consumer market. First, he sold Cable and Wireless
Communications, its British consumer telephone, cable and Internet
properties, to NTL, the communications services company, for 8
billion pounds or $12.8 billion in July. Weeks later, he sold the
company's 50 percent stake in the British mobile telephone provider
One 2 One for 3.5 billion pounds or $5.6 billion to Deutsche
Telekom.
</P>
<P>
   An underlying reason for these sales has been to change the
relatively dim perceptions among investors about the worth of Cable
and Wireless, which had been dogged by lingering questions over the
value of a company with assets so far afield.
</P>
<P>
   In typical British understatement, Wallace said: ``All I've done
is taken the array of assets that Cable and Wireless had and said,
`Look, if we want to get rid of this holding company discount we've
got to become a much clearer and more focused player.' '' He added:
``I'm a great believer in focus.If you try to be all things to all
men you just don't have the management or the financial
resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts praise Wallace on his single-minded drive to increase
shareholder value, even if it is at the expense of keeping assets
that have been part of the company's heritage for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you had was a grossly undervalued conglomerate,'' said
Kevin Lapwood, an analyst at Charterhouse Securities Ltd. in
London. ``We're seeing that the sum of the parts are worth more
separately.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's moves seem to be succeeding. Shares of Cable and
Wireless are up 54.4 percent since he took over from Richard Brown,
an American who left to become the chief executive at EDS, the
computer services company based in Plano, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Cable and Wireless is not weighed down by its
investment in Hong Kong, analysts speculate that possible suitors
like Deutsche Telekom, which is looking to expand its footprint
throughout Europe, Bell Atlantic, SBC Communications, the Baby Bell
based in San Antonio, Texas, and MCI WorldCom also may approach
Cable and Wireless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very surprising if companies didn't look at it,''
said Paul Sharma, an analyst at J.P. Morgan in London. Besides the
Cable and Wireless presence in Europe and a scattering of interests
in Asia and the Caribbean, it also owns a major Internet backbone
in the United States that it bought from MCI. It also owns Optus,
an Australian telephone network.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's constant maneuverings have defied market expectations.
``It's fair to say that Graham has been much more aggressive than
we expected,'' said Lapwood.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping into the shoes of Brown, who had been known as a
freewheeling executive with grand ambitions, was not as hard as it
seemed, Wallace said. ``The big advantage I had is that I knew the
company very well,'' he said. His previous job was as chief
executive of the unit he recently sold to NTL, Cable and Wireless
Communications PLC. ``I didn't have to spend a lot of time having a
strategy review.''
</P>
<P>
   With the sale of Cable and Wireless HKT, Wallace said he planned
to continue building the business from within rather than through
acquisitions. ``We wouldn't want to buy a massive telco with lots
of legacy assets,'' he said. ``That's what were getting out of.''
</P>
<P>
   All or at least part of the proceeds for the Cable and Wireless
HKT sale will be in Pacific Century stock. How long Cable and
Wireless will hold onto that stock, with its high but risky
valuation as an Internet company, remains an open question.
Analysts said it would be hard for Cable and Wireless to dump the
Pacific Century stock quickly, but the company is expected to
continue diluting its stake in Pacific Century.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said the decision over whether to sell Cable and
Wireless HKT to Pacific Century or Singapore Telecommunications was
difficult, and he admitted the choice was somewhat politically
charged. Pacific Century's founder, Richard Li, is the son of Li
Ka-shing, one of Hong Kong's most influential business executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think PCCW's contacts and connections, particularly Richard
Li in Beijing and his family's connections will be a plus,''
Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Investments bankers here and in Hong Kong negotiated the
transaction. Cable and Wireless was advised by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
and Greenhill &AMP; Co. Pacific Century was advised by UBS AG's Warburg
Dillon Read and Bank of China International. Goldman Sachs Group
Inc. advised Singapore Telecommunications.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2020EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0382 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2468 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT &LR;      02-29 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAIRMAN OF JOINT CHIEFS PROTESTS USE OF U.S. TROOPS OUTSIDE
MISSION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Irritated that American troops had to retreat from
a bottle-throwing mob in Kosovo, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, Gen. Henry Shelton, has written to NATO's supreme
commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, telling him not to use American
troops outside their designated sector.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, according to Pentagon and NATO officials, told Clark
that other countries involved in the NATO peacekeeping operation
had to send more troops to Kosovo before significant numbers of
American troops would again be allowed on a mission outside the
sector assigned to the United States' control.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton sent the letter to Clark a few days after the retreat on
Feb. 20 of 350 American soldiers from Mitrovica. The American
soldiers had been sent to the troubled city, where Albanian and
Serbian residents are at a standoff and where French troops needed
reinforcements.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials acknowledged Tuesday that Shelton had
concurred with Clark's plan to send the troops from their sector in
southeast Kosovo to Mitrovica before the mission was under way.
</P>
<P>
   Although Shelton had agreed ahead of time to the mission, the
underlying tone of the letter, according to officials, questioned
the wisdom of sending American troops into a volatile situation
involving hostile Serbian civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Shelton's letter, and a mood of discontent about the Kosovo
peacekeeping operation in the Senate Armed Services Committee
during a hearing with Clark Tuesday, reflected anger at European
allies for not contributing as many troops as requested or expected
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Several senators complained that after the United States had led
the air campaign in the Kosovo war, the Europeans had pledged to
lead the peacekeeping in Kosovo but had failed to live up to their
promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is more than whiff of hype, where the Europeans talk of
doing more,'' then fail to carry out their commitments in Kosovo,
said Sen. Carl Levin, Democrat of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the committee, Sen. John Warner, R-Va., asked
Clark why American troops were involved in house-to-house searches
for weapons in Mitrovica.
</P>
<P>
   Warner recalled that in Somalia, where American troops were
involved in an ill-fated peacekeeping operation in 1992,
house-to-house searches by American soldiers were ruled out as too
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said that in contrast to Somalia, where American troops
were not welcome, the NATO troops in Kosovo were respected and
wanted by large groups of the local population.
</P>
<P>
   But pressing ahead, Warner questioned the utility of a weapons
search in a city that was only a few miles from a porous border
with Serbia across which weapons freely flowed.
</P>
<P>
   Warner asked, ``What was the total number of arms'' seized in
Mitrovica?
</P>
<P>
   Clark replied, ``Twenty-five.''
</P>
<P>
   A NATO official explained after the hearing that the searches
for weapons in Mitrovica were conducted by troops of several
nations and were announced to the community by community leaders
just beforehand so that the searches appeared evenhanded.
</P>
<P>
   Both Albanian and Serbian homes were searched, in north and
south Mitrovica, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony, Clark said that the Yugoslav president,
Slobodan Milosevic, was very much in control in Serbia and that he
was unlikely to be defeated or disappear any time soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
