<HEADER>
A2471 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA-HEART01-COX     02-29 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-HEART01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Heart-transplant golfer has high hopes
 &HT;    By Craig Dolch
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ For many players, it takes years on the PGA Tour before
they can accomplish something significant. Erik Compton will make
history Thursday with one swing.
</P>
<P>
   When Compton's driver strikes his first tee shot in the
Doral-Ryder Open, the 20-year-old Miami native will become known as
the first heart-transplant recipient to compete on the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't expect Compton to take a bow when the amateur picks
up the tee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it's going to be special week,'' Compton said.
``But I don't step up to the first tee and say, `I'm Erik Compton,
the heart-transplant golfer.'''
</P>
<P>
   Making history is nothing new for Compton. When he was 12,
Compton became the youngest heart-transplant recipient at Miami's
Jackson Memorial Hospital. The surgery was performed Feb. 26, 1992,
and Compton got out of the hospital in time to graduate from sixth
grade.
</P>
<P>
   Compton, now a sophomore at the University of Georgia, also was
the first heart-transplant recipient to qualify for the U.S.
Amateur and earn an athletic scholarship to an NCAA school. But
he's not at Doral on a sponsor's exemption just to become a
historical footnote. He wants this to be the start of his journey,
not a stopping point.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at all my friends who have played as amateurs, Aaron
Baddeley (who won the Australian Masters) and Sergio Garcia, I've
played with those guys, and there's not much difference,'' Compton
said. ``The big difference is just getting out here. I've only got
one week to do it. The hardest part is getting out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton will have plenty of support this week both inside and
outside the ropes. His mother, Eli, estimates there will be more
than 100 friends and family members at Doral. Compton also will
have Doral's teacher (and his personal coach), Jim McLean, on his
bag.
</P>
<P>
   McLean said he isn't making his PGA Tour debut as a caddy for
ceremonial reasons. He believes Compton, who recently won the
prestigious Palmetto Dunes tournament at Hilton Head, S.C., can
have an impact this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he can make the cut,'' McLean said. ``I know that's not
easy _ it took Tiger Woods eight tournaments (as an amateur) before
he made his first cut. But I will be very surprised if Erik doesn't
play well.''
</P>
<P>
   So would Compton. ``I shot 72 in the pro-am today, and I really
didn't play all that great,'' he said. ``I've just got to get used
to playing with these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton played most sports as a kid, but the transplant helped
direct him toward golf because he couldn't do anything too
strenuous for a year after the surgery. McLean believes the way
Compton had to be brought along slowly helped his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He spent a lot of time learning how to use his body properly
without hitting balls because that was all he could do after the
surgery,'' McLean said. ``He also worked on his short game a lot
because it didn't take a lot of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Compton requires no special treatment on the course. At Georgia,
he walks and carries his bag like any other college player. ``I'm
in better shape than a lot of guys out here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Twice a day, usually at 9 a.m. and 9 p.m., he takes four
immunosuppressant pills to make sure his body doesn't reject the
heart. He also faces a hospital stay once a year for several days
to have a biopsy performed on his heart.
</P>
<P>
   But unless his shirt is off, to reveal a small scar where the
surgery was performed, one wouldn't know the ordeal Compton went
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you have transplants, so you can continue living a
normal life,'' said his mother, the director of development for
South Florida Transplant Foundation. ``Erik is no different than
any other amateur golfer out there chasing his dream.''
</P>
<P>
   But Compton is different. Few people have had to deal with the
prospect of death so young in life. Maybe that's why his idol isn't
Woods, but Paul Azinger, who overcame lymphoma four years ago to
return to the winner's circle last month at Hawaii (Azinger,
unfortunately, withdrew from Doral on Monday).
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why a 4-foot putt with 3 inches of break isn't
something he's going to beat himself up over. Compton wants to do
well this week, but he sees the bigger picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't really matter how well I do here,'' Compton said.
``The point is I got here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
