<HEADER>
A2473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-700     02-29 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-CAMPAIGN-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL DEMOCRATS CRITICIZE REPUBLICANS FOR INTOLERANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hoping to make Republicans squirm over their visits
to Bob Jones University, House and Senate Democrats introduced a
resolution on Tuesday condemning the college for intolerance and
criticizing its many visitors for staying silent on its virulently
anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   With speeches decrying bigotry and racism, the Democrats made
clear that it was Gov. George W. Bush's stop at the university, and
his failure to denounce the college's policies, that compelled them
to draw up the resolution. Bush later apologized for not seizing
the chance to condemn the evangelical university's anti-Catholic
teachings.
</P>
<P>
   By heaping criticism on Bush, the Democrats hope not only to
draw attention to a campaign misstep, but also to turn the
university's policies into so much of a political mudbath that any
candidate who has ever spoken there will end up vulnerable. Sen.
John Ashcroft, a Republican who is in a tough re-election bid in
Missouri, has already been criticized for receiving an honorary
degree from the college. Bush's rival for the Republican
presidential nomination, Sen. John McCain, has also condemned the
Bush visit. But on Tuesday it was Democrats who were using it in
hopes of tarnishing Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had not Governor Bush gone to Bob Jones University I doubt if
we would be standing here,'' said Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich., at a
news conference that included a Mormon, an African-American and two
Catholic lawmakers, as well as a nun.
</P>
<P>
   With the words of Dr. Bob Jones, the university's president,
calling the papacy ``the religion of anti-Christ and a satanic
system'' as a backdrop, Rep. Joseph Crowley, D-N.Y., said the
visits were a silent endorsement of the college's principles, an
endorsement Americans should not tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This issue here is of a presidential candidate or candidates,
or other people from political life who have gone to Bob Jones
University, and by doing so have said it's OK, that this school is
OK, and it's not,'' said Crowley, who co-sponsored the resolution
with Sens. Harry Reid of Nevada and Robert Torricelli of New
Jersey. ``It's not OK.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans, who also have been embroiled in a separate
dispute for passing over a Catholic priest as House chaplain,
quickly did some condemning of their own.
</P>
<P>
   They accused Democrats of fear-mongering and pandering to
Catholics, a crucial voting block, in an election year. And they
made clear that the resolution was not likely to ever reach the
floor of either the House or Senate. Republicans hold majorities in
both houses of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing is baloney,'' said Rep. Henry Hyde of
Illinois, the dean of Catholics among House Republicans. ``It's
being played for all its worth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we are going to adopt a principle that where you go seeking
votes is an indication that you accept the dogmas and doctrines of
the institution to which you are going, what does that say about Al
Sharpton, and the two major Democratic candidates for the
presidency, as well as Mrs. Clinton,'' Hyde said in an interview,
referring to their visits with Sharpton who has been accused of
anti-Semitism.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, of Oklahoma, the second ranking Republican in
the Senate, was so angered by the resolution that he said he could
draw up a slew of his own resolutions, if need be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we could have a resolution about Al Gore's acceptance
speech to NARAL, where he basically gave them a blank check,'' he
said, referring to the abortion-rights group. ``Or maybe we could
have a resolution of his acceptance of the gay rights community in
New York, or his acceptance of the unions, where he basically gave
them a veto over any legislation. If they want to play politics, we
can play politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Closing the door to any floor debate on the resolution, Sen.
Trent Lott, the majority leader, said simply, ``I don't expect an
amendment to be offered on Bob Jones or Buddhist temples or
anything else.'' The reference to the Buddhist temples harkens back
to Vice President Al Gore's visit there in 1996 to raise money for
Democrats.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Until this year, stopping off at Bob Jones University raised few
eyebrows, and a long list of politicians, Democrats and
Republicans, did so frequently. Several of McCain's allies have
ties to the school.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the co-chairman of McCain's South Carolina campaign,
Terry Haskins, who is also the state House speaker pro tem and a
Bob Jones University graduate, resigned from the campaign, saying
he disagreed with the way McCain has handled the issue. McCain has
been criticized for capitalizing on the visit by Bush and approving
telephone calls which portrayed Bush as anti-Catholic. Another
adviser, Rep. Lindsey O. Graham, R-S.C., received an honorary
degree from the college.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, Rep. Asa Hutchinson and Sen. Tim Hutchinson,
Republicans from Arkansas and brothers, both received their
undergraduate degrees from there.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are now seeking to portray the school's policies as
unconscionable. As Torricelli put it, ``the leaders of Bob Jones
University are to Christianity what the Ayatollah Khoemeni is to
Islam.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Representative Hutchinson called it is impossible to
support the policies and teachings of Bob Jones University, from
which he graduated in 1972. He said he called Dr. Jones, the
president, after the South Carolina primary to let him know that
when reporters called, Jones should not expect him to defend the
university.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly think they are trying to take political advantage
and divide our country and exploit this opportunity,'' Hutchinson
said in an interview on Tuesday. ``But there is ammunition out
there. The fact is you have an indefensible policy at Bob Jones
University.''
</P>
<P>
   The university, on its web site, calls itself
``anti-Catholicism'' and asks why it has become the ``whipping
boy'' of the political establishment. ``If there are those who wish
to charge us with being anti-Catholicism, we plead guilty,'' the
web site says. ``But we are not Catholic-haters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
