<HEADER>
A2476 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SCIARRINO-MUSIC-$ADV0     02-29 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCIARRINO-MUSIC-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITING ON THE EDGE OF SILENCE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Recitativo Oscuro,'' the title of the concerto by Salvatore
Sciarrino that Maurizio Pollini will play this week at Carnegie
Hall, with Pierre Boulez and the London Symphony, is consistent
with others in this composer's recent output, where ideas of night
and darkness often lurk. But the embodiment of such ideas here is
far more incisive, more vehement and, indeed, louder than has been
usual for Sciarrino.
</P>
<P>
   The work is more characteristic in its slow, unyielding tempo,
and so its sense of an inexorable clock, against which the musical
gestures may propose more fluid and human ways of telling time.
Here they do so under conditions of extremity, even panic, which is
dramatically expressed, but more typically the pressures on and in
Sciarrino's music are so severe they almost stifle any sound at
all.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always so. Sciarrino, who was born in Palermo, Italy,
in 1947, made his name in the early 1970s for music of fluorescent
if gentle brilliance, often playing in the high treble, using
unusual effects and making a show of instrumental virtuosity. In
his newer scores, the dynamic levels have remained spectral, but
the substance has become more attenuated.
</P>
<P>
   Virtuoso demands are now most likely to center on precision, on
the ability to act with maximum intensity and immediacy at the
right moment, and on playing at the edge of silence, or rather, at
the fuzzy boundary where the barely audible draws the keenest
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Generalizations, though, are hazardous. Sciarrino is a believer
in hard work, and his output includes concert and theater pieces of
all kinds, few of which have been performed here (despite his
European standing as a dominant composer of his generation) and
none too many recorded. He has also extended himself to produce
numerous arrangements, of Mozart, of medieval and Baroque music and
of songs by Johnny Mercer and others.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent CDs show something of the range of his recent
chamber-scale pieces. One, on the Kairos label, offers a program of
Gesualdo arrangements and Tasso recitations leading toward
``Infinito Nero'' (``Black Infinity''), based on the mystical
utterances of St. Maria Maddalena de' Pazzi. As Sciarrino tells the
story in his note on the piece: ``Maria Maddalena was attended by
eight novices: four repeated what she said, because she spoke much
too fast to write it all down at once, and the other four wrote
everything down. She did not `speak' _ words actually shot out of
her like a machine gun, and then she fell silent for a long
period.''
</P>
<P>
   Sciarrino's musical and dramatic realization of this behavior is
engrossing, chilling and moving. Instrumentalists, from a small
group, suggest the sounds of breathing, of panting and of
heartbeats: this is music right on the verge of being sound effect,
but the gestures are so varied, so exactingly conceived and so
tightly played that while conveying natural sounds with exceptional
accuracy, they mean more.
</P>
<P>
   One might imagine that they speak for Maria Maddalena's body,
waiting to be overtaken by her reeling mind, or that they stand for
her attendants, watching her in expectation.
</P>
<P>
   When the words come, they come in prestissimo flashes,
especially in the first half of the piece; the composer's
machine-gun image is apt. The voice stammers in a high register, on
the edge of ululation, and is sliced or chopped off by an
instrumental action.
</P>
<P>
   As the piece proceeds, the declamation becomes more continuous
and arrives at something like a fragment of a nursery tune, which
the saint-singer cannot get out of her head. It gets fixed into the
instrumental music, too, as the half-hour piece moves toward its
pinpoint close in the upper treble.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Turchetta and the Ensemble Recherche give a performance
that grows more disturbing and surprising with repetition. They are
also responsible for ``Le Voci Sottovetro'' (``Voices Under
Glass''), which comes from Sciarrino's recent obsession with the
music and history of Gesualdo, the source of an opera and music for
a puppet play as well as this sequence of four arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   At times the adaptation of Gesualdo for modern instruments
quaintly recalls the period, 40 years ago, of Stravinsky's
``Monumentum pro Gesualdo.'' But Sciarrino's abrupt changes of
color and register are distinctive, as is his dramatization of the
dialogue of different ages in the grating of nonvibrato strings,
sounding like viols, against warm, modern woodwinds.
</P>
<P>
   In its final movement, the piece really becomes something
special. By leaving just one singer in a five-part madrigal,
``Moro, Lasso,'' and giving the other parts to instruments,
Sciarrino suggests the bottled-in voice of his title. Or perhaps
the instrumental voices are the bottled ones, no longer able to
verbalize. There are attacks here, too, that have the scary
immediacy of ``Infinito Nero.''
</P>
<P>
   The other new CD, on Stradivarius, includes instrumental pieces
played by the Alter Ego ensemble, which has a close feeling for
Sciarrino's softnesses: the softnesses of intimate touch and
breathing. One of the most beautiful works in the selection is ``Lo
Spazio Inverso'' (``Inverse Space''), for barely blown flute with
matchingly gentle, caressing, impalpable sounds from clarinet,
violin, cello and celesta.
</P>
<P>
   Other pieces for three or four instruments are interleaved with
a violin fragment, longer solos for flute and clarinet, and _ like
a wound _ the violently reiterative Fourth Piano Sonata.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2030EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2480 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      02-29 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ((RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED IT. ALSO MOVING IN
THE ``L'' CATEGORY)) Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of
new books:
</P>
<P>
   ``ROBIN HOOD WAS RIGHT'' &QL; 
By Chuck Collins and Pam Rogers (Norton, $28.95) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wait! Don't mail those checks yet. Collins and Rogers have
advice about charitable giving that will help you donate your money
with thought and purpose rather than with guilt and self-interest.
Americans gave $109 billion to charity last year, yet one in four
top earners gave nothing, the wealthy gave smaller portions of
their assets than did the poor, and only 13 percent of the money
went to direct public benefit through human service programs (most
went to churches, the arts, elite private universities and
hospitals). Here, the authors attempt to redefine modern
philanthropy in order to affect change _ instead of focusing on the
immediate symptoms of social or economic problems, they want our
dollars to chip away at the CAUSES of those problems. Collins and
Rogers are dedicated, energetic, knowledgeable and frankly, a bit
daunting in their zeal. But you'll learn something if you listen to
them. As Alfre Woodard writes in her preface, ``Robin Hood was
right. And he had a damn good time.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
``HAWKE'S COVE'' &QL; 
By Susan Wilson (Pocket, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here's one for the ``Bridges of Madison County'' crowd, another
novel that attempts to parlay yearning and denial into a bad but
bittersweet bestseller. A young journal-keeping woman named Vangie
retreats to her grandmother's farm in a small coastal town (note
the title) to recover from the death of her baby and to wait for
news of her husband, who is overseas fighting in World War II. It's
not long before a down-on-his-luck stranger named Joe shows up, and
we know what that means. Vangie hires him to work on the farm, they
drink tea and lemonade, they watch each other through lowered
lashes, they swim (``There is,'' Wilson writes, ``a strange
intimacy in swimming . . .''), she spreads ointment on his
blistered hands. When Vangie's husband is declared missing in
action, she and Joe have a hot night together in the hayloft, but
word comes the very next morning that the husband is still alive.
Denial commences. Years pass. Violins play. Their children grow up
and get nosey. Have you been here before? You betcha. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``FOREVER LIESL'' &QL; 
By Charmian Carr (Viking, $23.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We were hoping to find some dirt here, but according to Carr,
there was precious little of it on the set of ``The Sound of
Music.'' Until now, the only relief from the unrelenting sweetness
of the film was an anecdote about Christopher Plummer, who played
Baron von Trapp and who allegedly hated the movie so much he called
it ``The Sound of Mucus.'' But Carr, who played the von Trapp
daughter Liesl, debunks that story, saying that Plummer himself
denies it (he did despise the song ``Edelweiss'' and tried to have
it tossed from the film). Mostly, this book is a cheerful report on
a cheerful experience, with some funny moments on the side. When
she attended the Mexican premiere (the film was called ``La Novicia
Rebelde,'' or ``The Rebellious Novice''), the unsuspecting Carr was
taken to a bullfight. The matador dedicated the bull to her, and
she watched in horror as the bull was tormented by the matador and
the matador was then run over by the bull. She visited the matador
in the hospital, as Liesl certainly would have done if she'd been
there. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``THE VISION OF EMMA BLAU'' &QL; 
By Ursula Hegi (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hegi's new novel is a family saga that begins in the early
1900s, when scrappy teenager Stefan Blau comes to America from
Germany (specifically from Burgdorf, which figures into Hegi's
earlier books, ``Stones From the River'' and ``Floating in My
Mother's Palm''), and sets out to make his fortune. After a fire in
the New York restaurant where he works, he leaves the city and goes
to a small town in New Hampshire because a fellow immigrant has
told him it reminded him of Germany. There, Stefan marries twice
and loses both wives to the births of his children before he
returns to Burgdorf to bring back and marry Helene Montag, his
childhood friend and the character through which Hegi explores the
difficult adjustment of the German immigrant. Serving as a backdrop
for the story is the Wasserburg, the grand and glorious apartment
building that Stefan builds, which reflects the fortunes of his
family. Hegi's characterization is superb, part of a story that is
as well-constructed as the Wasserburg itself.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2031EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
