<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG12-TEX </SLUG>
 BIG 12 IS GOOD, BUT DON'T LOOK FOR IT IN FINAL
FOUR (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By WENDELL BARNHOUSE
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Here's a Vaunted Hoop Expert's early word of
NCAA Tournament advice for those of you planning to participate in
March Madness bracket pools: Don't pencil in a Big 12 Conference
team to reach the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   (Coaches and administrators around the league are now doing
handsprings and hive-fiving each other. Given the past track record
of this V.H.E., predicting that no Big 12 team will be playing in
Indianapolis a month from now virtually guarantees a Final Four
team for the Big 12.)
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the Big 12 doesn't have a team worthy of winning a
national championship or reaching the Final Four is not a rip. It's
more a realistic assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of good teams, but we don't have any great
teams,'' Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson said.
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of good teams has translated into a lot of good
basketball. The Big 12 this season has provided some of the most
exciting and intense games in the country. Games such as Texas at
Missouri, Oklahoma State at Oklahoma, Oklahoma at Kansas and Texas
at Iowa State have been as entertaining and watchable as anything
the Big Ten, the Pac-10 or the ACC is throwing down on a regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   When the Big 12's top six teams _ Iowa State, Oklahoma State,
Texas, Oklahoma, Kansas and Missouri _ have played each other this
season, the games have been NCAA Tournament quality. Some of the
offensive performances have been more worthy of a brickyard than a
court, but that's because no quarter is given.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think you're going to score points easily on anybody in
this league, you're in for a rude awakening,'' said Kansas coach
Roy Williams, whose team has survived basically because it ``sells
out'' defensively every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top teams in this league, when they play, everybody brings
it,'' said Kansas senior forward Nick Bradford. ``And you better be
ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jayhawks found that out Monday night in Austin. Kansas is no
longer King of the Big 12. After winning 30 of its first 32 Big 12
games, Kansas is 21-10 the past two seasons. It's good for the Big
12 that it's no longer the Jayhawks and the 11 Dwarfs. The rest of
the Big 12 has caught up.
</P>
<P>
   You've got Rick Barnes trying to build a power in Austin, you've
got Sampson's every-possession intensity with the Sooners, you've
got Oklahoma State's Gray Fox, Eddie Sutton. Then there's young
guns such as Iowa State's Larry Eustachy and Missouri's Quin
Snyder.
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12 also is benefiting from stars such as Oklahoma
State's Desmond Mason and Oklahoma's Eduardo Najera, Texas' Chris
Mihm and Iowa State's Marcus Fizer. Mason and Najera are seniors;
Mihm and Fizer are juniors who face NBA early-entry decisions. Next
year, the Big 12 could be ``down,'' less competitive with fewer
stars.
</P>
<P>
   When the NCAA Tournament field is announced March 12, the Big 12
can expect to have five teams. Iowa State, Texas and Oklahoma State
have a shot at being seeded No. 4 or higher. That seeding will be
crucial if the Big 12 hopes for reasonable representation at the
Sweet 16 level.
</P>
<P>
   The league's top teams all have fatal flaws that are likely to
prevent a deep NCAA run. Iowa State lacks depth; Oklahoma State's
offense is limited by Doug Gottlieb's shooting woes; Texas needs
consistent guard play/outside shooting; Oklahoma's Najera might be
broken down after carrying a big load all season.
</P>
<P>
   The Big 12, in four seasons, has yet to produce a Final Four
team. If that trend continues, so be it. But for this season, at
least, the basketball has been worth savoring.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
