<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-SPARKY-TEX </SLUG>
 OATES HELPED BY SULLIVAN (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ When Johnny Oates was going through times
of deep personal distress, one man was always there for him.
</P>
<P>
   When he was fired in Baltimore and when his wife, Gloria, fell
ill in his first year in Texas, one man was right there when Oates
needed him.
</P>
<P>
   Sparky Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Johnny Oates was thrilled yesterday when the
veteran's committee selected Anderson for induction in baseball's
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very deserving,'' Oates said. ``I have so much respect
for that man, I can't tell you what he means to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently a great deal, even though Oates never played for
Anderson, coached under him or worked in the same organization. On
the field, all Oates ever tried to do was beat him.
</P>
<P>
   But that didn't stop Anderson from supporting Oates through some
of the roughest periods of his life, beginning in Baltimore when he
was under attack, both publicly and privately, from Orioles owner
Peter Angelos.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped me through that period by telling me I was okay,''
Oates said. ``I needed somebody to tell me I was okay, what you're
doing is not wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one day after a game, he walked up to Gloria, put
his hands on her shoulders and said, honey, every time he tries to
put on one of those pity parties, tell him how fortunate he is.
Don't let him feel sorry for himself because he's going to be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said the same thing happened in 1995 when his wife had to
be hospitalized and he had to take a two-week leave of absence to
be with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Gloria got sick, he called twice a day, morning and
afternoon,'' Oates said. ``This was in spring training when he was
battling the media because he had walked out of camp and refused to
work with replacement players. But he was still willing to call me
twice a day to see how she was doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers third-base coach Jerry Narron is also a close friend of
Anderson's even though they never were on the same team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would always take the time to talk baseball with me,''
Narron said. ``A lot of guys of his stature aren't going to talk
with some first or second-year coach but he was always willing to
do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates celebrated Anderson's election by telling two favorite
stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Henneman was in Detroit,'' Oates said. ``He had just
blown a save. He came into the clubhouse yelling, screaming and
throwing everything. So Sparky came out to the clubhouse and said,
Mike, I want to see you here tomorrow at 12 o'clock. You and I have
got something to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``So Mike met Sparky the next day. He had no idea what was going
to happen. Sparky took him over to the children's hospital there in
Detroit and took him into the terminal illness ward, where kids
have two or three weeks to live. Afterwards, they were walking out
and Sparky said, ``Hey Mike, a blown save is not so tough after
that, is it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Oates said Anderson had a unique way of getting his point
across.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another time in Detroit, a pitcher _ I'm not going to say who
it was _ hit Rob Deer in the elbow,'' Oates said. ``Hit him on
purpose. Deer, who's a big guy, was hurt and as he goes to first
base, the pitcher is still yelling at him. So Sparky's afraid that
Deer is going to charge the mound if this pitcher keeps yelling at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he goes from the third-base dugout in Detroit to first base
to make sure Deer is all right. Then, as he walks back to the
dugout, he goes by the mound and said real quietly to the pitcher,
if you really want to get it on with that big guy over there, I'll
go over there and ask him to meet you right here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid didn't know what to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Oates, ``He won a lot of games but he also influenced a lot
of people. Some of them don't even know it. I tried to thank him
once, but he wouldn't let me. He said, I'm just doing my job.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
