<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 DRANSFELDT TO SPEND YEAR IN MINORS (For
use by NYTimes News Service clients) By T.R. SULLIVAN c.2000 Fort
Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Second base could be the most intriguing
position in Rangers camp this spring. Luis Alicea is the starter,
but the Rangers will take a good look at Frank Catalanotto, Edwin
Diaz, Jorge Diaz and Scott Sheldon.
</P>
<P>
   Left out of the mix, both as a potential starter or backup, is
Kelly Dransfeldt. The Rangers prefer to let Dransfeldt spend the
season at Triple-A Oklahoma trying to regain his stature as one of
the Rangers' top minor-league prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``He recognizes he needs a lot of work with his bat,'' Rangers
general manager Doug Melvin said. ``Even if he has a good spring,
he needs to take those at-bats somewhere and use them on a regular
basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Dransfeldt was last seen in Arlington in May, when he filled in
while shortstop Royce Clayton was on the disabled list. The Rangers
liked what they saw on defensive, but he hit only .189 in 16 games.
He then went back to Oklahoma and batted .218 the rest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were hoping he would recover with a strong
winter-league season in Puerto Rico, but he hit only .163 in 13
games for Bayamon before returning home in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough down there,'' Dransfeldt said. ``We had a lot of
rain and played 10 games in 40 days. We had a hurricane. Then I got
food poisoning and I was in the hospital and lost a lot of weight.
That's when I decided to go home. It was a bad experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Dransfeldt can play all three infield positions, but Melvin
doesn't see him making the team as a utility player. He'd rather
see Dransfeldt go back to Oklahoma and play every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't look at him as a part-time player,'' Melvin said.
``Down the road he may be that, but we don't think so. He's got a
chance to be a front-line shortstop.''
Contract deadline coming Pitcher Ryan Glynn agreed to a new
contract yesterday worth $205,000 and Catalanotto signed for
$305,000, leaving six players unsigned: outfielder Ruben Mateo and
pitchers Jeff Zimmerman, Francisco Cordero, Dan Kolb, Mike Venafro
and Matt Perisho.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers want them signed before their first exhibition game
Friday. Under the Basic Agreement, any player with less than three
years experience who is not signed can have his contract
automatically renewed by the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might be one renewal, but there doesn't seem to be any
problems,'' Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said. ``We'll get
it done before the games start.''
DH watch Manager Johnny Oates could have some interesting choices
for designated hitter when a left-handed pitcher is on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed hitter Lee Stevens is a lifetime .241 hitter against
left-handed pitchers but hit .304 against them last year. Oates
also has two attractive right-handed hitters, Chad Curtis and Mike
Simms.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis was used primarily against left-handers by the Yankees
last year and hit .297 off them, matching his career average.
Simms, who hit .296 with 16 homers in 186 at-bats in 1998, was
supposed to platoon with Stevens last year until he injured his
left Achilles tendon and missed most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Oates said he's not sure if Curtis or Simms will make the team,
or if Stevens will sit against left-handers. Simms could be traded
before the spring is over if the Rangers have another need on the
bench besides a right-handed power hitter.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
