<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 FLYERS LIMP INTO TOWN (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) By JEFF CAPLAN c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Philadelphia Flyers come to town with an
injury list close to, if not, as formidable as any the Stars have
fashioned this season.
</P>
<P>
   Stars you won't find on the ice for the Flyers tonight: captain
Eric Lindros (back), center Keith Primeau (rib), 18-year veteran
defenseman Ulf Samuelson (left rotator cuff) and defensemen Dan
McGillis (groin) and Luke Richardson (right collarbone).
</P>
<P>
   The Stars point of view: tsk, tsk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, there's no sympathy from this camp for teams that
come in and have a few injuries,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   These two teams deadlocked 1-1 in their only other meeting of
the season in Philadelphia. The injuries definitely softens the
anticipation of on-ice matchups. Stars defensemen Derian Hatcher
(6-5, 230) and Richard Matvichuk (6-2, 215) trading paint with
Lindros (6-4, 236) and company is as anticipated a matchup as any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I don't know if I look too forward to it to be honest,''
Hatcher said. ``When you know you're playing against him 25
minutes, you have to be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars get the Flyers on the tail-end of back-to-back road
games. The Flyers faced the Blues in St. Louis last night.
Thornton fitting in
</P>
<P>
   In the past five games, Scott Thornton has scored two goals and
chalked up an assist. Putting pucks in the net had seemed like a
lost art to Thornton in Montreal. Two in five games might not seem
like much, but consider he is one-fifth of the way to his
career-high of 10 in 11 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get your hands above your head for a change,''
Thornton said.
Langenbrunner plays with pain
</P>
<P>
   Each game, Jamie Langenbrunner plays with a sore neck stemming
from a nagging pinched nerve. The forward has missed 14 total games
because of it. Tonight will be his third game back after missing
three games with soreness.
</P>
<P>
   He endured a crosscheck to the back late in Friday's game
against Chicago that sent him to the ice face-first and kept him
there a few minutes, sending team trainer Dave Surprenant to his
aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult, it wasn't that hard of a hit that got me, so
that was frustrating,'' Langenbrunner said. ``It's more the
irritation in it right now that's causing the problems. It's there
pretty much all the time. You just deal with it.''
Lukowich swaps stick
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defenseman-turned-forward Brad Lukowich traded in his
thicker hockey stick for a slimmed-down, graphite model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm using \RMike\S Modano's pattern now. It's the exact same
stick, it's unbelievable,'' said Lukowich, who is taking a crash
course in learning how to play forward. He only chuckled when logic
suggested he will now score like Mike, too.
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull did not skate for a third consecutive day due to a
hip flexor, a nonserious injury that won't go away, Hitchcock said.
Hull is not expected to miss any games. Hull has earned points in
six consecutive games (2-6-8) going back to Feb. 18 at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hitchcock said center Joe Nieuwendyk (separated right
shoulder) Jan. 19 could return in 10 to 14 days.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
