<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 HOCKEY-FIGHTING SITES GLORIFY DONNYBROOKS,
NOT MCSORLEY (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By TOMMY
CUMMINGS c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ It's an online community that spans North
America and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   They post images of bloodied NHL players. They collect and trade
video and audio of memorable fights. They rank the best goons
and/or enforcers. They list the penalty-minutes leaders. They
huddle on message boards to review the latest knock-down-drag-out.
</P>
<P>
   They seem to do everything but collect broken teeth of famous
fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite their passion for a good drop-the-gloves donnybrook,
these creators of hockey fight sites all abhor the recent incident
involving Marty McSorley, the Boston Bruins defenseman who was
handed the stiffest on-ice-related suspension in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   In the closing seconds of Vancouver's 5-2 victory on Feb. 22,
McSorley used his stick to slash the Canucks' Donald Brashear on
his right temple.
</P>
<P>
   That, online fight fans contend, is not in the spirit of their
tributes to fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like two guys consenting to dropping the gloves and
throwing punches,'' said Marc Nagy, a St. Catharines, Ontario
resident and creator of Zero Reality (zeroreality.com), a site that
sells fight tapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheap shots like this have nothing to do with fighting, and
have no place within the game of hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   Jill Johnson of St. Louis authors The Penalty Box
(welcome.to/thepenaltybox), which tracks penalty-minute leaders.
``Of course, the people who read my site are mostly fight fans, but
they are not fans of what McSorley did,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Petti, a resident of Nova Scotia, ranks the all-time best
hockey fighters on his site (www.hockeyfighters.8m.com). He said
the McSorley incident is an ``argument for hockey fighting, not
against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a stick-swinging incident,'' Petti said. ``They were
not fighting at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Neall Alden, an Edmondton, Alberta resident who authors
Knuckles, Blood and Ice! (www.angelfire.com/ca/hockeyfights) said
fighting is not to blame for McSorley's outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``McSorley broke the code _ the fighter's code that he lived by
all of his career,'' Alden said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Piaker, a student at New York University who has
animated graphics of fighting hockey players at his Mike's Hockey
Fight Homepage (members.aol.com/MarkMess11), said McSorley's
actions were stupid and dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``However _ and I want to make myself clear that I am not
blaming the victim _ if Donald Brashear had dropped the gloves with
McSorley I don't think this incident would have happened,'' Piaker
said.
</P>
<P>
   B.B. Lynn of Memphis, Tenn., follows hockey fights in a section
called Fight Card at Inthecrease.com, an e-zine about professional
and amateur hockey. McSorley simply snapped, Lynn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If fighting were to be banned in hockey, you would begin to
see more incidents like this one,'' Lynn said.
Bytes Chat highlights: St. John's men's basketball coach Mike
Jarvis is scheduled to tip off the first in a series of chats that
introduces the National Association of Basketball Coaches' official
site (www.nabc.com) today. Jarvis starts the site's Chat Madness at
11 a.m. followed by Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson at 1 p.m.
Friday's lineup begins with 1999 NABC Coach of the Year Mike
Krzyzewski of No. 4 Duke answering questions at 10:30 a.m. while
Mike Montgomery of No. 1 Stanford will reply to fans at 1 p.m. ...
Michael Jordan's first live chat since becoming part owner of the
Washington Wizards is scheduled for 8 tonight on CBS SportsLine.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
