<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY TO APPEAL DIRECTLY TO VOTERS IN PRIME-TIME TV SPOT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT17 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hours before the polls closed in Tuesday's
nonbinding Democratic primary in Washington state, former Sen. Bill
Bradley announced that he would buy five minutes of prime time on
national television Thursday evening to make a direct appeal to
voters five days before the crucial Super Tuesday primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides said the taped spot, which will be broadcast at
the end of CBS News' ``48 Hours,'' would feature Bradley talking
about why he would make the best president of the four major
candidates now running.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign's decision to take the extraordinary step of buying
national television time reflects not only Bradley's difficult
straits _ he is running well behind Vice President Al Gore in
almost all state polls _ but also his frustration with the meager
amount of media attention he has been receiving. News coverage of
the presidential race has been dominated by the Republican battle
between Sen. John McCain of Arizona and Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's spot will be competing with ``E.R.'' on NBC, one of
television's most popular programs. Asked why they had not bought
time on ``E.R.'' instead, Bradley's aides said that it was probably
too expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign declined to say how much the spot would
cost. But several political consultants who buy television time for
candidates estimated that it would be about $1 million. They also
estimated that the commercial would be seen by more than 7 million
people, though many would be in states that do not vote next
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen states, including California, New York, Missouri, Ohio,
Georgia and most of New England, hold Democratic primaries or
caucuses on March 7, when nearly a third of the delegates to the
Democratic national convention will be selected.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Carrick, a Democratic political consultant in California
who is not involved in the race, said the last time he could recall
a Democratic presidential candidate buying so much television time
during the primaries was when Sen. Ted Kennedy of Massachusetts
purchased 30 minutes on New England stations after he lost the Iowa
caucuses in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley does better when he can talk to voters in a
conversational setting where he tries to tell them what he's all
about,'' Carrick said. ``I think this is a smart decision to try to
get voters to tune in and pay attention and get a clear,
unchallenged version of his message.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides strenuously denied rumors that swept through
Washington, D.C., on Tuesday that Bradley would drop out of the
race if he failed to win in Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   ``This camp is working hard towards March 7 and beyond,'' said
Douglas C. Berman, Bradley's campaign chairman. ``I know everybody
wants to write a different story. But the velocity with which
things change in this political climate is incredible. And that's
the view of the campaign, and certainly the senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley campaigned in California on Tuesday after having spent
six days in Washington, where his aides had hoped a strong showing
would resuscitate his flagging campaign. He opened his day at a San
Francisco hospital where he spoke about the need for stronger
gun-control restrictions. He has proposed licensing all handgun
owners, registering all handguns and banning inexpensive handguns
known as Saturday Night Specials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are threatened from within by handguns,'' Bradley told
about 80 hospital workers. ``They are a threat to the most basic
parts of our lives, those things we take most for granted, like
going to school in the morning, or walking down a neighborhood
street.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he had been scheduled to return to San Francisco after a
debate with Gore in Los Angeles on Wednesday night, Bradley's
campaign said he would be returning instead to New York, where some
of his top supporters have sharply questioned his decision to focus
on Washington for the last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2042EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
