<HEADER>
A2500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-ART-     02-29 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-ART-860(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH COMPANY SALE, HONK KONG SHEDS ANOTHER VESTIGE OF COLONIAL
PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ The last British governor sailed out of this teeming
Asian port in 1997. And Tuesday, with the decision of Cable and
Wireless P.L.C. to sell its Hong Kong telephone company to a local
Internet start-up, Hong Kong has thrown off another vestige of its
colonial past.
</P>
<P>
   But while Cable and Wireless HKT is passing out of British
hands, it will still be firmly part of the local establishment. The
company is being bought by Pacific Century CyberWorks, a
nine-month-old company founded by Richard Li, an heir to the most
powerful family dynasty in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   The seeming ease with which Li snatched Cable and Wireless HKT _
despite his company's small size and meager assets, and despite a
formidable counterbid by the much larger Singapore
Telecommunications _ has troubled some people here. They say it
smacks of the kind of favoritism and old-boy cronyism that
characterized business in Hong Kong during 154 years of colonial
rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the free-market city that people always talk
about,'' said Michael DeGolyer, director of an academic project
that surveys public attitudes about Hong Kong's return to China.
``Politics and personal ties have always ruled in Hong Kong.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no hard evidence that Li's political connections were
the decisive factor in his victory over Singapore
Telecommunications. The Hong Kong government said Tuesday that it
had not interfered in the process.
</P>
<P>
   But the chairman of Cable and Wireless, Graham Wallace,
acknowledged that Li's family ties were attractive. And another
executive close to the company said it had been eager to find a
``local solution'' to the sale of its Hong Kong operation.
</P>
<P>
   There is hardly a more ``local'' choice than Richard Li. His
father, Li Ka-shing, is perhaps Hong Kong's most successful tycoon.
He also has sterling connections in mainland China. With Pacific
Century's takeover of Cable and Wireless HKT, the Li family will
control companies that account for more than a third of the total
market capitalization of the Hong Kong stock market.
</P>
<P>
   On the day that Asia's largest-ever takeover battle ended,
executives close to Singapore Telecommunications complained that
their company was a victim of politics. They said the Singapore
company's bid was comparable to Pacific Century's offer, and they
pointed to its strategic partnership with Rupert Murdoch's News
Corp. Nevertheless, Cable and Wireless went with a local favorite _
and a financially shaky one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Telecom's outsider status was compounded by its
ownership. It is 79 percent owned by Temasek Holdings, the
investment arm of the Singapore government. Its chief executive is
Lee Hsien Yang, the 42-year-old son of the founder of modern
Singapore, Lee Kwan Yew. Executives close to Singapore Telecom said
those facts weighed against it with Hong Kong and mainland Chinese
authorities. They said this opposition was relayed to the Cable and
Wireless board by Hong Kong business executives with ties to
individual directors.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's antipathy toward Singapore Telecommunications may
partly originate from its own sense of insecurity. Singapore has
been a perennial rival of Hong Kong for the title of Asian
financial center _ a competition that has intensified in the last
two years as Singapore has liberalized its financial markets. Hong
Kong, by contrast, is still climbing out of a deep recession, and
it has drawn criticism for government intervention in its stock and
property markets.
</P>
<P>
   Given that situation, some officials here were unnerved by the
prospect of the Singapore government's taking over the local phone
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The telephone company is a strategic asset in any country,''
said Sin Chung-kai, a Hong Kong legislator. ``I think it would be a
matter of concern if the Singaporean government indirectly owned
the Hong Kong phone company.''
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's role in this corporate drama is murkier. Executives
close to Singapore Telecommunications said Chinese officials had
initially expressed concern about the proposal. Shortly after news
of the talks emerged, Wenhui Bao, a Beijing-controlled newspaper,
noted, ``If Cable and Wireless intends to sell its stake, there are
quite a few consortia in Hong Kong strong enough to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, though, officials from Singapore Telecom's adviser,
Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co., sounded out mainland officials, who signaled
they would not hold up a merger.
</P>
<P>
   Still, China's proxies made their preference for Pacific Century
clear. Newspapers here reported that China Telecom, the Hong
Kong-based arm of China's state telephone monopoly, favored Li's
offer for the company. China Telecom owns 10.7 percent of Cable and
Wireless HKT, a stake that will convert to a holding of less than 5
percent in the combined Pacific Century-HKT.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is a great accepter of what it calls problems left over
from history,'' said an analyst here, who asked not to be
identified because his firm was involved in the deal. ``But if the
status quo is going to change, I suspect they would try to exercise
some influence on how that happens.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2043EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2501 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-ART-     02-29 0472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-TELECOM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HONG KONG: that happens. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It would have been hard for Hong Kong's authorities to block a
deal between Cable and Wireless and Singapore Telecommunications
outright. But it had other ways to exert pressure. The sale, for
example, must be ratified by the board of Cable and Wireless HKT,
which is composed of Hong Kong business people. That vote is now a
formality, but it might not have been so, had Singapore Telecom
prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Pacific Century dismissed suggestions that the
process had been rigged. ``I wouldn't think so,'' said Francis
Yuen, the deputy chairman. ``We certainly didn't feel that we were
favored in our negotiations with Merrill Lynch and Greenhill,'' he
added, referring to Cable and Wireless' advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Yuen said Pacific Century pursued HKT because it felt the
company's assets, like its high-capacity phone lines, would
complement its nascent Internet-access service. He said the
acquisition would accelerate the deployment of Pacific Century's
broadband service.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore Telecommunications, Yuen said, based its initial
proposal on the cost savings it could squeeze out of Cable and
Wireless HKT by combining operations. He said Singapore Telecom
would have brought little strategic direction to its Hong Kong
counterpart because it operates in a sheltered market that had only
recently been deregulated. Cable and Wireless HKT has had to
contend with competition for years _ a challenge that he said had
sharpened that company's management.
</P>
<P>
   For Pacific Century, however, the more pressing challenge will
be preserving the value of its bid. The company made two offers
that value Cable and Wireless HKT at $35.9 billion and $38.1
billion, respectively. The larger bid is in the form of stock,
while the smaller one offers stock and cash. But both rely heavily
on Pacific Century's stock, which has risen to stratospheric levels
in the last nine months.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said the shares, in which trading has been halted
since last Friday because of pending news, were likely to fall, now
that details of its offer are known. Pacific Century's stock may
also deflate somewhat as investors begin to value it according to
the realities of the local phone business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment these companies are detached from the cyberworld
and put into the real world, they are valued according to the real
world,'' said Marc Faber, who heads an investment firm here.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview Tuesday, Li said that he was confident
Pacific Century could inject Internet magic into Cable and Wireless
HKT's utilitylike phone business. ``I think it's a good transaction
for both parties,'' he said. ``An old pipe is only valuable if you
create new value.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Li's remarkable victory proves mostly the value
of good connections.
</P>
</TEXT>
