<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JOURNALIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHNYA CAPTIVE TELLS OF BEATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ More than a month after he disappeared, Andrei
Babitsky, a Radio Liberty reporter, returned to Moscow Tuesday, and
said he had been held in a Russian camp for detainees outside
Chechnya, where he said he and others were routinely beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The case of Babitsky has spurred concerns about press freedom in
Russia. Before his arrest, Russian authorities were angry about
Babitsky's reporting from Chechnya. Russian troops detained him as
he left Grozny, the Chechen capital, on Jan. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky then went through a strange sequence of events, in
which he was held incommunicado, jailed, beaten, traded to masked
men for two Russian soldiers and thrown into the trunk of a car.
</P>
<P>
   He was then driven through Chechnya and told he would be taken
to Azerbaijan before making his way on Friday to the capital of
Dagestan.
</P>
<P>
   After threatening a hunger strike and after protests from human
rights groups, Babitsky is back in Moscow. But Russian prosecutors
are threatening to try him for carrying false documents and
cooperating with Chechen militants, an allegation he has denied.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky put on a brave face in his Radio Liberty interview,
published on its Russian-language Web site, and a separate
televised interview on the independent NTV network. Colleagues say,
however, that he has been shaken by his experiences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they did not break him,'' Savik Shuster, the
director of Radio Liberty's Moscow Bureau said in an interview.
``But he thinks they did. There is a lot of fear inside of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The identity of the masked captors who took him from the
Russians is not clear. Babitsky's friends suspect they were
pro-Russian Chechens or even agents working for the Russian
intelligence services.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky did shed some light on his ordeal, which began when he
was taken to the Chernokozovo center soon after he was detained.
</P>
<P>
   At the camp, 30 miles north of Grozny, he said, ``I underwent a
`routine light initiation,' which everyone, without exception, goes
through when they arrive there,'' he told Radio Liberty, the
U.S.-financed news organization and his employer. ``That is a few
dozen blows of a truncheon on the body.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the prisoners, similarly treated, he said, were not
militants but ordinary citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that we have read about concentration camps of the
Stalin period, what we know about German camps, can be found
there,'' he told NTV.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky has agreed not to leave Moscow while charges are
pending. But he told Shuster he wants to return to work in the
North Caucasus.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
