<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 MAVS SALE IN FINAL STEPS (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) By DWAIN PRICE c.2000 Fort Worth
Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Mavericks' Big Three flew to New York after
last night's game against the Philadelphia 76ers to face one of the
biggest days of their life.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks owner Ross Perot Jr., owner-in-waiting Mark Cuban and
president and chief executive officer Terdema Ussery made the trek
to the Big Apple as Cuban goes through the final stages toward
gaining controlling interest in the Mavericks. Cuban will interview
with 11 members of the NBA Board of Governors today at NBA
headquarters and will need at least 22 of the 28 owners to vote
``yes'' in order for the sale of the Mavericks to successfully
change hands.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect a final vote from the owners today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one misconception that he needs to clear up a little bit
is the idea that \Rtoday\S there's going to be the interview and
there's going to be a vote,'' Ussery said. ``That's just not going
to happen, and I don't think it's ever happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Ussery said the final and formal vote may not come until the NBA
Board of Governors meets April 1. He also pointed out that the
owners still have not voted on Michael Jordan's interest in the
Washington Wizards and the ownership change of the Vancouver
Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan purchased part of the Wizards on Jan. 19, and the NBA
Board of Governors interviewed Grizzlies owner-to-be Michael
Heisley on Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia 76ers owner Pat Croce said he would be shocked if
Cuban doesn't meet final approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited he's in the league,'' Croce said. ``I love a guy
who's got enthusiasm and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, now they don't look at me as a maverick. He can be `The
Man.' '' Rodman ruckus The NBA might be looking into the
possibility of levying a fine against Dennis Rodman or the
Mavericks because the controversial forward is not making himself
available to the media after ballgames.
</P>
<P>
   The final straw may have come after Monday night's game in
Boston, when pushing and shoving and a fight nearly broke out among
reporters, Fleet Center security and some hanger-ons as Rodman made
his way to the Mavericks' team bus after the 108-100 victory over
the Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear there was an overzealous radio reporter that got a
little bit out of control,'' Mark Cuban said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodman lifts weights for about 30 minutes after each game and
then it's another 20-30 minutes pass before he appears. Most of the
time, though, he exits via a back door. Once the media spots
Rodman, the chase is on, and a lot of pushing and shoving ensues.
</P>
<P>
   Told that the NBA may fine Rodman and/or the Mavericks if
Rodman's not cooperative to the media, Cuban said: ``The guy's got
to work out after the game, right? That's physically what he's got
to do. You can't bust on a guy for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, on his walk back \Rto the team bus, or to his limo
during home games\S he always makes himself available.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban also denied an ESPN report that he has given Rodman a
Lamborghini to drive around Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do these people get this \Rstuff\S?,'' Cuban asked. ``I
got in trouble \Rwith the NBA\S for leasing a '92 Lexus to Greg
Buckner that I had to take back; that was $15 a month, and we
stopped that.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, yeah, I'm going to turn around and give Dennis a
Lamborghini? Please.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
