<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2506 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX     02-29 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
 
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ While Deion Sanders remains a lame duck for the
Cowboys and a long shot with the Cincinnati Reds, .MDBU/two[ a pair
of].MDNM/ unrestricted free agents have begun the audition process
for a chance to compete for the starting right cornerback job that
Deion Sanders has held since 1995.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ryan McNeil, a six-year veteran who started for the Cleveland
Browns last season and was the NFL's interception leader (nine)
with the St. Louis Rams in 1997, visited Valley Ranch yesterday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   .MDBU/Phillippi.MDNM/ Sparks, an eight-year veteran and a
full-time starter with the New York Giants since his second year in
the league (1993), arrived in Dallas last night and will meet with
Cowboys' management and coaches today. Sparks and Cowboys strong
safety Darren Woodson were childhood friends. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just playing it by ear,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said
of the cornerback visits. ``We don't have any plan \Rfor signing
either one or both\S ... nothing that succinct.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones added that ``possibly other cornerbacks'' will be invited
to Valley Ranch, along with ``three or four quarterbacks'' from
which one will be signed to replace Jason Garrett as Troy Aikman's
backup. Jones declined to name names.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McNeil and Sparks become only the second and third unrestricted
free agents to visit the Cowboys. The other was cornerback
De.MDBU/R.MDNM/on Jenkins, who later signed with San Diego. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Jones, Cowboys vice president//director of player
personnel, said that the Cowboys' next step will be to ``continue
doing our homework on \RMcNeil and Sparks\S ... and contact their
agents.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McNeil's agent is Eugene Parker. Sparks is represented by Frank
Bauer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are expected to release Sanders on June 2, which is
the window that allows them the greatest salary-cap relief. Sanders
told reporters in Florida over the weekend that he definitely is
done in Dallas and wants to continue his NFL career with a team
that has a chance to get to the Super Bowl.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cornerbacks Kevin Smith and Kevin Mathis, who missed eight games
apiece last season because of injuries, will be back next season.
Joining them will be 1999 rookie cornerback Duane Hawthorne, who
has been assigned to NFL Europe, and possibly five-year veteran
Charlie Williams, an unrestricted free agent. &QL; 
