<SLUG> BC-CLEAR-SFX-450(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEAR CHANNEL IN $3 BILLION DEAL TO ACQUIRE SFX ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Advertising) 
(bl) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The big broadcast and outdoor advertising company
Clear Channel Communications Inc. said Tuesday that it would
acquire SFX Entertainment Inc., the largest producer of live
concerts, theater and sports events, for about $3.3 billion in
stock. The deal is emblematic of the increasing consolidation and
concentration of media and entertainment interests.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, which includes the assumption of about $1.1
billion in SFX debt, would create a diversified powerhouse with
stakes in everything from Broadway theaters, television and
billboards to monster truck rallies, radio and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is intended to help Clear Channel extend its
advertising reach to concerts and sporting events. Such a move will
help the company gain additional advertising dollars from the
nation's largest marketers by delivering the consumers whom the
advertisers crave most, particularly younger men.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also be able to use its radio stations to
promote SFX events. Clear Channel will become No. 1 in radio after
completing a $23.5 billion deal to buy another big owner of radio
stations, AMFM Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a nice, natural fit here,'' said Christopher Ensley,
an analyst at Lazard Freres &AMP; Co. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clear Channel already participates in over a thousand concerts
a year, promoting them through its radio stations, driving
listeners to local car dealerships or Sears outlets by raffling off
tickets,'' he added. ``Knowing who the concertgoers are, whether
the live acts are being received well in those markets, creates a
lot of opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal emulates those that have produced entertainment and
media conglomerates like News Corp., Time Warner Inc. and Tribune
Co., which offer advertisers cross-promotional programs meant to
deliver diverse types of consumers across operations like broadcast
and cable television networks, sports teams, magazines, movie
studios, newspapers and Web sites. The goal is to integrate as
seamlessly as possible content _ whether a sitcom, a rock concert
or a wrestling match _ and the means to distribute that content.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a primal DNA of this,'' said Robert F.X. Sillerman,
executive chairman at SFX in New York. ``If you have distribution,
and you then distribute the proper content, it makes your
distribution better. And the improved distribution encourages
better content.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had remarkable success creating national platforms for
advertisers and marketers such as Levi Strauss, Anheuser-Busch and
American Express in live entertainment,'' he added. ``What they're
gaining is access to the 60 million people who attend our events.
When you overlay a broadcast component, it's even more
compelling.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sillerman disputed suggestions that deals like the acquisition
of SFX, which is expected to be completed early in the third
quarter, unfairly concentrate ownership of premier entertainment
and media properties in too few hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is true we're both getting bigger,'' Sillerman said. ``And
in this case, bigger is better. But one of the wonderful things
about America is that there's fierce competition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't deny the fact people are concerned,'' he added, ``and
there are things you have to be careful about. But some great
things come from having the size and resources to experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Sillerman said, SFX ``built stages outside our
amphitheaters'' so that less well-known bands could gain exposure
by playing for concertgoers on their way in to see the headliners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That required a company of our size to do that,'' he said.
``And if you take a look at the radio business, owning multiple
stations provides an opportunity to experiment with different
formats.''
</P>
<P>
   The SFX holdings, which have been broadened through recent
acquisitions worth $2.2 billion in stock, loans and debt, include
concert tours and theatrical entertainment in 31 of the top 50
markets; figure skating championship exhibitions; Internet
operations like www.firstinline.com, a ticket sales Web site; and
management agencies that represent active and retired athletes like
Andre Agassi and Michael Jordan in sports including baseball,
basketball, soccer and tennis.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of SFX to Clear Channel, which owns or has deals for
867 radio and 19 television stations that reach more than 120
million people weekly, is, well, clear. SFX can help Clear Channel
appeal to advertisers seeking fans of music and sports,
particularly the elusive demographic group of younger men.
</P>
<P>
   And ``they can use the Clear Channel radio platform to promote
events in a bigger way and increase attendance,'' said Frank L.
Bodenchak, a broadcast analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter in
New York. ``They can also sell advertising sponsorships at the
venues and on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel, which is based in San Antonio, will have radio
stations and billboards in virtually every market where SFX owns
arenas and amphitheaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This transaction allows Clear Channel, through SFX, to gain
immediate leadership in the highly attractive live entertainment
segment,'' Lowry Mays, chairman and chief executive at Clear
Channel, said in a statement, ``while taking advantage of the
natural relationship between radio and live music events.''
</P>
<P>
   Clear Channel will also ``pursue initiatives relating to the
Internet and music,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The deal is subject to approval by SFX shareholders and
regulators. Terms call for each Class A share of SFX to be
exchanged for sixth-tenths of a share of Clear Channel common
stock. Each Class B share of SFX would be exchanged for one share
of Clear Channel common stock.
</P>
<P>
   SFX Class A shares rose 50 cents Tuesday, to $38.50, on the New
York Stock Exchange. Shares of Clear Channel fell $8.5625, to
$66.625.
</P>
<P>
   SFX had 63.8 million Class A shares outstanding as of November
and 1.55 million Class B shares. The shares differ in voting power:
Class A is entitled to one vote each and Class B, 10 votes each.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon Smith Barney advised Clear Channel in the acquisition,
while Bear Stearns advised SFX and Lehman Brothers advised an SFX
committee of independent directors.
</P>
<P>
   It was ``a surprisingly easy decision'' to accept the Clear
Channel offer, Sillerman said, which came ``so quickly, less than a
month'' ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't talking with CBS,'' he added, referring to
speculation that he had been in negotiations to be acquired by CBS
Corp., which is itself being bought by Viacom Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were approached by Clear Channel,'' Sillerman said, ``and
we know them well; these are friends of mine. They wanted to make a
compelling argument that it would be a good idea to merge the
companies, so I said I'd listen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have Jones Beach Amphitheater in Long Island,'' he added,
``and Clear Channel has many radio stations in New York like Z-100.
It was pretty easy to see the benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   After the acquisition, Sillerman said, ``100 percent of the
operating people'' at SFX will remain at Clear Channel. As for his
future, he continued: ``It's unclear. Certainly there'll be a
transition period for at least some time. Ordinarily, I wouldn't
think about staying on, but there's such an interesting
opportunity, I'm seriously considering it.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal brings SFX full circle, Ensley noted, because the
company was originally spun off from SFX Broadcasting, a radio
station group, when Sillerman decided that ``his best bet was
pursuing the concert venue business'' because ``he realized he
wasn't going to be able to compete with a Clear Channel'' for
dominance in radio.
</P>
<P>
   Sillerman said, Mays ``has ended up acquiring close to 150 radio
stations we used to own.''
</P>
</TEXT>
