<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-BUSH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush win in Virginia keeps bad news at bay
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Gov. George W. Bush's solid win in Virginia, a
victory that guaranteed at least a split decision in Tuesday's
contests, was good-enough news for a candidate who might not be
able to survive more bad news.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, better news would include a victory in Washington
state, proving his ability to win north of the Mason-Dixon line.
Washington votes still were being tallied late Tuesday, however,
and polls were giving Arizona Sen. John McCain an early edge.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bush was ready to portray Virginia as a big win that put
him ``one step closer to victory'' and the GOP ``one step closer to
having a united party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, in an open primary, by a solid margin of what appears
to be 15 to 16 points, the voters of Virginia rejected the politics
of pitting one religion against another,'' Bush told supporters
here, referring to McCain's attempts to paint the Texas governor as
anti-Catholic because he spoke at a Bob Jones University, a South
Carolina school with anti-Catholic philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush victory rally came as votes were still being counted in
Washington and while North Dakota caucuses _ where Bush was
expected to do well _ were still in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials packaged the Virginia win with his
weekend victories in American Samoa, Guam, the Virgin Islands and
Puerto Rico and declared themselves on a roll.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been 113 delegates at stake since Michigan and
Arizona,'' said Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes. ``So this is the
biggest week yet in the primaries and we hope to win the lion's
share of the delegates.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's Virginia victory, in which he picked up all 56 of the
state's delegates, comes at a crucial time. Super Tuesday is March
7, when 613 delegates will be awarded in 12 states around the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, crummy Tuesday for Bush, McCain took a surprisingly
easy win in Michigan and trounced Bush in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Bush believes he has the right message but has been hampered by
the wrong electorate in primaries open to all voters, instead of
just Republicans. McCain's overwhelming strength among independents
and Democrats has served him well in the open primaries held so
far.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's exit poll numbers showed Bush pulling 33 percent of
the independent vote in Virginia. Last week in Michigan, Bush
earned only 26 percent of the independent votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two weeks, 1,132 delegates will be awarded,
including 505 in contests open only to Republicans. The first
candidate to earn 1,034 delegates wins the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The Virginia exit polls also showed Bush winning among almost
every demographic group, other than independents and Democrats.
Sixty-five percent of the Virginia voters identified themselves as
Republicans, and 71 percent of them voted for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Only 19 percent identified themselves as members of the
religious right, and 83 percent of them voted for Bush. McCain and
Bush split the other 81 percent of the Virginia vote.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line for Bush in Virginia is that the victory was a
significant boost, but not as significant as a loss would have
been. McCain would have garnered a lot of mileage out of a win
there.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas government professor, said
the Virginia win, no matter how you slice it, is big for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's reinforcement for the Bush people who've argued right
along that when you get into Bush territory, his natural advantages
start to assert themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan also believes McCain scored no points in Virginia by
bashing Virginia-based religious right leaders Pat Robertson and
Jerry Falwell _ both Bush backers _ on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The tactic, however, might pay off for McCain in New York and
other states, according to Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's basically playing a risky national game now in an effort
to redefine the heart and soul of the Republican Party,'' he said.
``I don't think he regards the Virginia loss as particularly
unexpected.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
