<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-BAXTER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite past, GOP South behind Bush
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just a dozen years ago, voters much like those who
stood in line together Tuesday to give Gov. George W. Bush a solid
win in Virginia were at each other's throats across the South.
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, factions supporting Pat Robertson and former
President George Bush went to court over who had control of the
facility where the state convention was held. In North Carolina, a
Republican caucus nearly turned into a brawl.
</P>
<P>
   The feud went all the way to the national convention in New
Orleans, and provoked quite a few Southern Republicans to red-faced
rage, which is all the more reason they don't want to be reminded
of it this year.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe in their heart of hearts, some supporters of the elder and
younger Bush didn't disagree entirely with Arizona Sen. John
McCain's fiery denunciation Monday of Robertson and Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   But the bitter memory of the religious wars of the '80s has only
firmed the resolve of the Southern Bushites to stand by their man,
judging by the Texas governor's success in Virginia Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His (McCain's) message is not projecting an image of
inclusiveness, like Reagan. It's saying let's run somebody out of
the damn party,'' said Oscar Persons, a Bush supporter in Atlanta
who had his share of run-ins with the Robertson forces back in '88.
</P>
<P>
   McCain really wasn't appealing in his speech to the party
regulars, who have grown accustomed over the past decade to sitting
next to the Christian Coalition table at party functions. Both
groups this year share a common aversion to McCain's ideas about
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was trying to strike a chord with a younger, less
involved group of voters, who may very well show up in California,
New York and other states next week.
</P>
<P>
   The problem for McCain is that even if he can bring in a lot of
Republican moderates and newcomers, the combination of antagonists
from another decade in the South and Midwest helps to harden Bush's
lock on the nomination, like asphalt baking on a Sun Belt road.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60 percent of those who voted in Virginia on Tuesday
described themselves as conservative and more than 70 percent said
they were Republicans. In the national eye, it makes no difference
whether they were Robertson Republicans, which is one hospitality
room at the state convention, or Bushites, which is quite another.
</P>
<P>
   While the results from Virginia seemed to blunt McCain's gamble
in Virginia Beach as a nomination strategy, the early returns from
Washington State signaled a continuing worry for the Bush camp.
</P>
<P>
   One Bush aide was heard to grumble after McCain's speech that he
was trying to burn down the party as he's leaving it. Bush's letter
to Cardinal John J. O'Connor, regretting that he didn't stress his
opposition to anti-Catholic bigotry in his Bob Jones University
speech, is another token of the discomfort the religious struggles
of the past week have caused him.
</P>
<P>
   The South appears to be delivering the nomination to Bush while
his strength outside the region remains suspect. And McCain's
challenge to Robertson and Falwell, whether it gets immediate
results at the polls or not, is likely to resonate throughout this
election year.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
