<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 ANALYSIS: McCAIN FAILS TO MAKE HEADWAY AMONG CONSERVATIVES IN(With ELN-RDP) 
(sw) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Whatever else Sen. John McCain of Arizona
achieved in his short, sharp foray into Virginia this week, he
certainly moved no closer to the Republican presidential
nomination. His long-shot attack on the leaders of the religious
right bore no immediate fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's primary here was a victory for Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas in more than one sense.
</P>
<P>
   He piled up an imposing margin and took all 56 delegates in the
nation's 12th largest state _ a southern state, like South
Carolina, where Bush won just 10 days ago, but a much less
provincial one, with huge military installations as well as wealthy
Washington suburbs where some of the nation's fastest-growing
high-technology companies are based.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Texan's first triumph in a large, economically and
politically diverse state with aspirations to national leadership.
</P>
<P>
   More important, he once again denied McCain the kind of showing
among Republican voters that McCain desperately needs. The Arizonan
took only 26 percent of the Republican vote in South Carolina and
only 29 percent last week in Michigan; after a week of proclaiming
himself ``a proud Reagan Republican'' in costly barrages of
television advertisements, he did no better in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where 55 percent of the voters described themselves
as conservatives, McCain did poorly among them. Twice as many
self-described conservatives voted for Bush as for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Adherents of the religious right were not as numerous in
Virginia as in South Carolina, accounting for only about 20 percent
of the electorate, but they once again exerted a potent influence
on the outcome. Bush won the backing of an overwhelming percentage
of them _ almost eight out of ten, according to the exit polling _
but he and McCain ran even among voters who said that they did not
identify with Christian conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did well, and Bush did badly, among Democrats and
independents who crossed over into the Republican primary. That
brought no cheer to Bush backers, because the Texan has been
striving to picture himself as the man who can lead the Republicans
to victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   Bush seems unable to break out of a right-wing box, even though
he has begun re-emphasizing ``compassionate conservatism.'' On
Tuesday night, however, in a victory speech delivered at a rally in
Cincinnati, he asserted that ``we are expanding our base without
destroying our foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt McCain has galvanized much of the country, including
many people who have been alienated from politics in recent years.
His national approval rating in the most recent ABC News/Washington
Post poll has risen to 60 percent from 36 percent at the end of
October, while Bush's has been slipping. He is well situated for a
general election contest.
</P>
<P>
   But as Prof. Larry Sabato of the University of Virginia
commented, ``You can't possibly win the Republican nomination with
just Democratic and independent votes. You need Republican as well
as Democratic and independent support.'' Moreover, Democrats and
independents will be barred from voting for McCain (or any other
Republican) in the New York primary next Tuesday or in the
delegate-selection election in California on the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show McCain trailing in both of those states, as well as
Texas and Florida, which will vote a week later, on March 14. Those
four states, the nation's four largest, will among them choose more
than 45 percent of the 1,034 delegates needed for the Republican
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The week between the Michigan primary and the voting on Tuesday
_ the state of Washington also held a primary and North Dakota
staged caucuses _ had been marked by frantic repositioning efforts.
McCain tried hard to counter suggestions that he was insufficiently
or unreliably conservative, and Bush struggled against suggestions
that he was anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   But not much changed in the pattern of voting. The same acute
ideological split that has shown up elsewhere was evident in
Virginia, with Bush, for example, winning most of those who oppose
abortion and attach great importance to moral issue and McCain
winning most of those who back abortion rights and care more deeply
about taxes and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   Some of McCain's supporters had suggested that his speech on
Monday in Virginia Beach, in which he denounced Pat Robertson and
the Rev. Jerry Falwell, two of the Christian right's best-known
leaders (and both Virginians), would prompt an outpouring of
liberal and moderate Republicans o his behalf. According to exit
polls, nothing like that happened; indeed, of the small number of
voters who said they had decided at the last minute, most went to
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the McCain camp hinted that the senator had been
looking beyond Virginia to New York and California, hoping to win
the backing of the numerous centrist voters there who object to the
religious right. From that perspective, it is too early to evaluate
the Virginia Beach speech.
</P>
<P>
   The debates over which candidate was the real reformer and which
was more honest, so steamy only a few days ago, seemed not to have
fazed most Virginians. They said both were reformers and both
talked straight.
</P>
<P>
   McCain had hoped for a victory here to build upon his Michigan
upset, and if he had brought it off it could have demoralized the
Bush campaign on the eve of the biggest test of the year, the
voting next Tuesday, which will include primaries in Ohio, Georgia,
Massachusetts, Missouri and other states as well as California and
New York. But no Republican has won on two big election nights in a
row this year, and the pattern held.
</P>
<P>
   With the backing of Gov. James S. Gilmore III and Sen. John W.
Warner, Bush was always the clear favorite; indeed, before
Michigan, McCain had seemed ready to give Virginia a pass. By not
doing so, he made the contest seem more important than it would
otherwise have been.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
