<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2523 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-CARNIVAL-MUSIC-$ADV05     02-29 1009
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARNIVAL-MUSIC-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARNIVAL IS A GOOD IDEA FOR ALL OF US  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carnival dances in this weekend across the Caribbean, South
America, southern Europe and that splendid cultural biosphere, New
Orleans. From now through Fat Tuesday, carnival's first paradox is
that it ties profane delights to the church calendar, wrapping up
before Lent begins on Ash Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, real men are wearing feathers and sequins,
making public spectacles of themselves in costumes that take weeks
or months of work but will vanish in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   Giant parade bands are massing in the streets, resurrected
annually by volunteer, amateur musicians who casually execute grand
feats of memory and coordination. Whole musical repertories, with
old songs and new, are heard only while the season lasts, among
them sambas, calypsos and the funky war chants of Mardi Gras
Indians in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival's miraculous outpouring of creativity, in thousands
upon thousands of individual choices to sew a costume or join a
steel-drum orchestra or parade through the center of town, is
enough to make those of us in more temperate zones feel culturally
deprived. Carnival would be good for all of us.
</P>
<P>
   The singular joy of carnival isn't in the mass public
inebriation or flashes of skin; you can find those at spring break
in Florida. It's not merely a parade, a costumed ball, a concert,
dancing in the street, or all of them combined. Nor is it an
entertainment that can be simply imported or commissioned.
</P>
<P>
   Although many carnival bands sound great all by themselves _ and
time-tested carnival rhythms are the secret ingredient in all sorts
of dance music _ they're better when everyone is singing along.
Carnival means more because it has traditions forged in a long
history of paradoxical balancing acts, a gradually negotiated
covenant between authority and rebellion, rich and poor, pagan and
devout.
</P>
<P>
   With the continuity of a ritual, carnival gives people a
connection to the past; it's no accident that carnival songs, like
African griot songs, are full of reminders about history. And in
the present, carnival is an exuberantly stylized celebration of
everyone learning to get along.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in places where Roman Catholic colonialists met
native and African cultures, carnival is a piquant, living memory
of past frictions and ingenious adaptations. As a public outlet for
impulses that are suppressed in ordinary life, carnival was, and
still is, a pressure valve for the frustrations of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   For the length of the masquerade, trappings of everyday class
and status are upended; men can become women, children can become
princes and empresses, workers can be demons or clergy or animals.
It is also, in the humorous but sometimes biting satirical songs
that are part of many carnivals, a way for those frustrations to be
aired publicly without reprisals.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, in places where slaves were imported, carnival has
been a covert survival and transmission mechanism for old,
African-derived rhythms. All that cultural sedition is masked as
nothin' but a party.
</P>
<P>
   The parade groups that appear for carnival season are community
organizations as much as performing ensembles. Preparing for
carnival _ designing and making the costumes, rehearsing the music
_ involves hundreds and sometimes thousands of people in a project
that is anything but frivolous.
</P>
<P>
   It's a symbol of perseverance and teamwork, of shared memory and
neighborhood pride, along with meanings that aren't necessarily
clear to outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the most visible and enduring carnival
groups are the Mardi Gras Indians of New Orleans, groups like the
Wild Magnolias and the Golden Eagles who parade in the city's
uptown neighborhoods. They started making their meticulously beaded
and expansively feathered costumes a century ago, when poor blacks
were exposed to Buffalo Bill's Wild West shows and saw the Indians
as fellow rebels against white domination.
</P>
<P>
   Long ago, groups of Indians used to have street fights on Mardi
Gras morning. Now their songs, with syncopations that found their
way into New Orleans jazz and rhythm-and-blues, still allude to
battles, but the tribes don't get any more physical than dancing.
</P>
<P>
   New York doesn't entirely lack carnival; we just get it later,
off the liturgical calendar. Every Labor Day weekend brings the
West Indian-American carnival in Brooklyn, which draws a million
spectators to a magnificent homemade sequel to the carnivals of
Trinidad and Tobago and the other English-speaking Caribbean
islands. But it's a transplanted carnival tradition, not an
indigenous one; it looks back to the West Indies.
</P>
<P>
   New York's annual Halloween parade in Greenwich Village also has
a strong element of carnival with its eye-popping and sometimes
politically motivated costumes. But neither event produces songs
the whole city will sing.
</P>
<P>
   That's what carnival-deprived places lack most: street songs. In
carnival cities, a song can sweep through an entire populace for
the season. Trinidad has turned the process into a contest, giving
an annual award for the Road March, the song heard most often on
the streets of its capital, Port of Spain, during carnival. (Lord
Kitchener, who died on Feb. 11, was Trinidad's king of the Road
March, winning the award 10 times between 1963 and 1976.)
</P>
<P>
   A carnival season's conquering street song might well be a
celebration of the pleasures of the flesh, a pre-Lenten indulgence
that turns lewd come-ons into a light-hearted singalong. It could
also be a thinly veiled outlet for public discontent, with
double-entendres that seem transparent to everyone except the
potentially offended authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a carnival for every locality, as neighbors turned down
boomboxes to sing along with neighbors, and even miscreants
couldn't resist humming the tune that denounces them. With
carnival, there'd be a party in party politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
