<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAP-ERNST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAP GEMINI WILL BUY ERNST &AMP; YOUNG'S CONSULTING BUSINESS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In a move to create a global computer services
consulting firm, Cap Gemini SA of France announced Tuesday that it
is acquiring the consulting practice of Ernst &AMP; Young, one of the
world's largest accounting firms, in a deal worth $11.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Cap Gemini said it will pay 375 million euros, or $362 million,
in cash and issue up to 43.5 million new shares, if all the
consulting businesses of Ernst &AMP; Young accept the offer.
</P>
<P>
   The stock will be divided among Ernst &AMP; Young's 1,000 consulting
partners, who will now work for Cap Gemini, and the 4,000
accounting and tax partners that will remain with the auditing
firm. About a third of the shares will go to the consulting
partners and another third to the accounting and tax partners, who
must sell their stock within five years. The remainder will go to
fund Ernst &AMP; Young's pension plan and to pay for a variety of other
expenses, including tax bills and transaction costs.
</P>
<P>
   The deal represents the latest attempt by the accounting
industry to try to address competitive pressures facing consultants
and to allay regulators' concerns about the integrity of corporate
audits. If it succeeds, it will be the first time one of the
largest accounting firms has sold its major consulting business and
will afford Cap Gemini, the biggest European computer services
company, a major entry into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hermelin, a Cap Gemini director, said the combined
companies were ``transforming Cap Gemini into a real global firm.''
Combined revenue, he said at a news conference to announce the
deal, will amount to as much as $7.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Philip A. Laskawy, chairman and chief executive of Ernst &AMP; Young
who will remain at the head of the auditing practice, said both
companies complemented one another ``from a strategic and
geographic perspective,'' and are equally committed ``to the
development of e-offerings.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the world's biggest accounting firms have come
under growing pressure to separate their accounting and consulting
businesses. The latter has become their most profitable and
fastest-growing area, but friction between consultants and
accountants has grown. The consulting business requires
significantly more capital than the firm's traditional auditing
practice, and firms have scrambled to retain and attract their
consulting employees.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has also been pressuring
firms to avoid the conflicts of interest that come when supposedly
independent auditors are tempted to make compromises in reviewing a
company's books rather than risk losing lucrative consulting
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, PricewaterhouseCoopers, which advises and
audits many of the world's biggest corporations, said it plans to
separate its auditing and consulting practices into two or more
separate entities. Its biggest rivals, including KPMG, Arthur
Andersen and Deloitte &AMP; Touche, are all trying to devise other
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   While the sale by Ernst &AMP; Young represents a possible answer to
the problem of auditor independence, the transaction has not yet
been approved by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Ernst &AMP; Young's audit partners will still own a sizable piece of
Cap Gemini, and regulators may view the arrangement as one that
continues to pose a conflict of interest for the firm's auditors.
</P>
<P>
   The move will catapult Cap Gemini into the big league of global
computer service consultants, a field now dominated by American
giants like IBM, EDS, Andersen Consulting and Computer Sciences.
Pierre Hessler, president of Gemini Consulting, said he expected
the combined group to generate roughly a fourth of its revenue from
Internet companies this year, up from about 16 percent in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will also strengthen Cap Gemini's position in the
United States, which will account for about a third of the group's
revenue, and reinforce its status in Germany, another major market.
</P>
<P>
   But some industry observers say Cap Gemini may face a challenge
in keeping Ernst &AMP; Young's clients happy. In the United States, Cap
Gemini's image was bruised recently after several major computer
installations failed to live up to expectations. In January, the
company reached an amicable settlement with the United Way of
America over a failed $12 million project; last summer, the U.S.
Chamber of Commerce canceled a $75 million contract with Cap
Gemini, contending that one of its systems failed to deliver what
was promised.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cap Gemini's bid would create a consulting giant with a
strong position in the financial and insurance industries, but also
in the media and telecommunications businesses. Analysts said the
combination makes sense, given Cap Gemini's strong presence in
Europe, while Ernst &AMP; Young has a solid position in the United
States and Germany, a European market where Cap Gemini has
struggled to develop a significant presence.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the alliance enables both companies to better service
the Internet economy, which is enjoying sustained growth and strong
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Investors appeared to agree. Cap Gemini's share price soared
almost 14 percent at the start of trading in Paris Tuesday, to a
record 291.9 euros, or $283.14. The price has risen almost 50
percent since early December, when the companies began serious
talks.
</P>
<P>
   The deal with Cap Gemini involves its consulting practices in
the United States, Canada, Britain, France, Germany, Italy and
Spain, countries where Ernst &AMP; Young generates roughly 85 percent
of its total consulting revenue of $3.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Other countries are expected to be included later, including
Belgium, the Netherlands, much of Scandinavia, Australia and New
Zealand. The deal requires the approval of Ernst &AMP; Young partners,
who will vote country by country in coming weeks. The results are
expected in April. Cap Gemini shareholders must then approve the
arrangement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
