<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Corporate Raider of '80s Quits as Chief of Insurer
</P>
<P>
   Saul Steinberg, one of the best-known corporate raiders of the
1980s, stepped down as the chief executive of Reliance Group
Holdings, the troubled insurance company. Steinberg will remain
chairman and will focus on the company's e-commerce strategy. The
company also posted another quarter of disappointing earnings and
agreed to sell one of its units to Travelers Property Casualty for
$580 million.
</P>
<P>
   Mirage Rejects Bid by MGM
</P>
<P>
   Grand Mirage Resorts rejected a $3.3 billion takeover bid from
casino rival MGM Grand as inadequate. But Mirage, which is run by
casino mogul Stephen Wynn, said it would be willing to consider a
transaction at a higher price. Before Mirage made its announcement,
its shares fell 18.75 cents, to $15.75, while MGM Grand declined
31.25 cents, to $19.875.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Sets Record in Sharp Rally
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices staged a broad advance in heavy trading with the
Nasdaq composite index rising to a record. The Nasdaq gained 118.84
points, or 2.6 percent, to 4,696.69. The Dow Jones industrial
average rose 89.66 points, or 0.9 percent, to 10,128.31, and the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed 18.37 points, or 1.4
percent, to 1,366.42.
</P>
<P>
   Helping the Spouse in Business, Too
</P>
<P>
   Charles Sacarello, a consultant, sees a huge need for managers
to pay more attention to their spouses' appearance and behavior.
His firm recently rolled out a program to polish spouses' public
persona.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's Alters Commission Rates
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after Christie's changed its commission rates
because of a federal antitrust investigation, Sotheby's revised its
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers Question AOL Merger
</P>
<P>
   The proposed merger of America Online and Time Warner drew
skeptical questioning from the Senate Judiciary Committee as
lawmakers challenged a new pledge by the companies to open Time
Warner's cable television system to other Internet service
providers.
</P>
<P>
   Lazard Executive Is Stepping Down
</P>
<P>
   Steven Rattner, the deputy chairman of Lazard Freres, is leaving
and plans to join three other Lazard bankers in starting Quadrangle
Group, a firm that plans to invest privately in media and
telecommunications companies. People who know Rattner, who is close
to Vice President Al Gore, had speculated he would go to
Washington, possibly as a cabinet member, if Gore became president.
But this move makes that possibility more remote.
</P>
<P>
   CPI Said to Be More Accurate
</P>
<P>
   More than three years after concluding that the Consumer Price
Index overstated inflation by 1.1 percentage points a year,
economists say changes made to the index have narrowed the
overstatement to about 0.8 of a percentage point a year.
</P>
<P>
   No Source of Web Attacks Identified
</P>
<P>
   The official in charge of the government's cybercrime-fighting
unit told a Congressional panel that the FBI was uncertain whether
more than one group was responsible for the recent attacks on
e-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa Electric to Upgrade Plant
</P>
<P>
   The government's campaign to make seven utilities bring old
coal-fired electric plants up to modern pollution standards showed
its first results when Tampa Electric in Florida agreed to spend
about $1 billion to switch one plant to natural gas and make
significant changes at a second.
</P>
</TEXT>
