<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: CHRISTIAN DEMOCRATS ELECT AIDE
</P>
<P>
   The embattled Christian Democratic Union elected Friedrich Merz,
a 44-year-old financial expert, to lead its parliamentary group.
Merz replaces Wolfgang Schaeuble, who quit after admitting taking
illicit cash payments for the party. The successor to Schaeuble in
the separate, and more important, post of party chairman will be
decided in March.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: SUING BANK OF NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   Natasha Kagalovsky, a former senior vice president at the Bank
of New York who was suspended during a money-laundering
investigation, said she had filed a $270 million suit in Moscow
against the bank. Kagalovsky, who resigned in October, headed the
bank's East European division. The bank called the suit ``a
nuisance and without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIA: `IMPOTENCE' ON KARADZIC
</P>
<P>
   The top U.N. official in Bosnia said the failure to arrest
Radovan Karadzic, the Bosnian Serb leader and an indicted war
criminal, ``shows the impotence of the West in the face of evil.''
Jacques Klein, a former American military officer who is
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's special representative in Bosnia,
said Karadzic's ability to roam around Bosnia indicates that there
is no political will to bring him to justice.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: JOSPIN'S DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   The socialist prime minister, Lionel Jospin, defended his recent
pro-Israel remarks, telling the National Assembly that foreign
policy was not exclusively the domain of President Jacques Chirac.
Speaking for the first time since he was stoned by Palestinians,
Jospin played down his rivalry with the conservative Chirac, saying
the two had few problems compared with power-sharing periods of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: ARMS PLAN
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance Party, which represents Protestants and Catholics,
proposed a six-point plan of matching moves by the rival Sinn Fein
and Ulster Unionist parties aimed at breaking a stalemate over the
disarmament of guerrillas. John Hume, the Nobel Peace Prize
laureate and head of the Catholic Social Democratic and Labor
Party, supported the suggestion, saying, ``It is time to stop
pointing fingers at one another.''
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: POLICE CHIEF BURIED
</P>
<P>
   Tijuana buried its police chief, Alfredo de la Torre Marquez,
who was assassinated by gunmen after weeks of drug-related
bloodshed there. President Ernesto Zedillo sent his interior
minister and attorney general to Ciudad Juarez, another border city
mired in drug violence, and on to Tijuana. In both cities, the two
ministers took part in ceremonies spotlighting previously-budgeted
federal anticrime funds.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: NO CHANGE OVER HAIDER
</P>
<P>
   Israel will not send its ambassador back to Austria following
Joerg Haider's resignation as leader of the far-right Freedom
Party, Foreign Minister David Levy said. The party, which Israeli
leaders have called neo-Nazi, remains in the governing coalition.
</P>
<P>
   PALESTINIANS: MOVE ON PROTESTS
</P>
<P>
   With the number of political and labor protests in the West Bank
and Gaza growing, the Palestinian Authority declared that all
demonstrations and public meetings must be authorized by the
police. Human rights groups condemned what they saw as an attempt
to stifle free speech and dissent.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   CHINA: RIGHTS CRITICISM
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. high commissioner for human rights said in Hong Kong
that China's human rights situation had deteriorated. The
commissioner, Mary Robinson, will attend a U.N. regional meeting on
rights that starts in Beijing on Wednesday. She said that in
meetings with Chinese officials she planned to raise concerns about
repression of political and religious views.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: 300,000 HOMELESS
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Pascoal Mocumbi and South Africa's defense
minister, Mosiuoa Lekota, flew over the flooded Limpopo Valley to
assess the damage from the cyclone and torrential rain that have
left an estimated 300,000 people without homes or livelihoods.
About 800 people were rescued by the South African National Defense
Force, which lent Mozambique seven military helicopters.
</P>
</TEXT>
