<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2532 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WATERWAR01-COX     02-29 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WATERWAR01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Water war negotiators try to pump life into talks
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Negotiators in Georgia's rancorous water war with
Alabama and Florida tried desperately to break their impasse
Tuesday _ agreeing to make a last-ditch effort on one front and to
aim lower on a second.
</P>
<P>
   In one of two negotiating sessions in Atlanta, deliberators for
Georgia and Alabama agreed to hold one more session this month to
try to keep alive talks to share the waters of the Alabama, Coosa
and Tallapoosa rivers, or the ACT.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're gasping for air,'' Alabama's chief negotiator Jim
Campbell said of the stalled talks. He said Georgia's refusal to
budge on water allocations for the ACT means it may be useless for
the two states to continue bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   In a second session, arbitrators for Georgia, Alabama and
Florida made little headway in reaching an agreement to share the
waters of the Apalachicola, Chattahoochee and Flint rivers, or the
ACF.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the prospect of a complete breakdown in the talks,
negotiators for Georgia and Florida said that instead of aiming for
a 50-year agreement, they might consider an interim water-sharing
formula for only seven to 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean recasting flow targets for the rivers. Alabama
would have to agree to any plan the other states came up with, and
there is no guarantee the states could eventually reach even a
short-term settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Both disputes could end up in the U.S. Supreme Court, where it
could take millions of dollars and years to settle, and in the end,
no state may get what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   In the ACT feud, Georgia has promised that water flowing from
the basin into Alabama would never dip below a certain minimum at
the state line, even during severe droughts. Alabama wants higher
flows, but Georgia negotiators say those demands would draw down
Lake Allatoona and Carter's Lake in North Georgia to dangerously
low levels.
</P>
<P>
   The two states' negotiators agreed to take the matter to their
respective governors during the next two weeks to see if they want
the talks to continue or close. The arbitrators then will meet in
another session this month to determine if the talks have a future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be the last meeting of the ACT,'' Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that Alabama Gov. Don Siegelman already has expressed
his sentiments in a letter released last month: If Georgia does not
loosen its stance, ``we will see them in court.''
</P>
<P>
   In the battle over the ACF, Florida wants more water from
Georgia at the state line than Georgia is willing to deliver during
droughts. Alabama also wants more water, to support its growth.
</P>
<P>
   Working out a shorter-term agreement would give the states time
to develop more scientific data and complete an intensive study of
irrigation practices in southwest Georgia. Then the negotiators
would come back to the bargaining table and hash out a longer term
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The states have until May 1 to reach a settlement on both
disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
