s e BC-LONDON-SYMPHONY-$ADV0     02-29 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-SYMPHONY-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN MUSIC, NOT METHOD, MATTERS MOST  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pierre Boulez's four concerts with the London Symphony Orchestra
at Carnegie Hall in Manhattan beginning on Friday are, in their
way, the closing of a book. The title of this book might be ``An
Age of Exploration,'' and we have been turning its pages for about
100 years.
</P>
<P>
   There will be new pieces by Salvatore Sciarrino, Peter Eotvos,
Olga Neuwirth and George Benjamin, but none will offer
groundbreaking methodology or send music into some unexplored
orbit. They will make sounds, maneuver in time and hope that we
like what we hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Discovery'' will apply only in that each piece will have an
unexplored life of its own. Terms like ``vanguard'' or
``manifesto'' are not likely to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   The book being closed concerns the most political century in
musical memory. Music's politicians laid out their platforms and
trolled for votes of confidence cast by new composers. How would
they write music of the future? What direction promised rescue from
chaos? Who or what was to guide them?
</P>
<P>
   Tonal music ran out of room. Its hold on our ears was (and still
is) as strong as in the days of Haydn and Mozart, but key
relationships and harmonic progressions were worn and stretched to
such extremes of ambiguity that they were about to break apart.
Composers, furthermore, couldn't see much up ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss and Mahler just kept on stretching. Stravinsky brought a
sublimated savagery from his Russian origins and, with a mercurial
eclecticism, relived older styles in a completely new voice. When
Schoenberg composed ``Moses und Aron,'' everyone knew which role
was played by the composer, a man who would lead music to the
promised land along a road laid out by him alone.
</P>
<P>
   Revolution led to trends that hardened into schools and ended in
factions. Much of the postwar era was taken up with bickering over
who had the right idea. American universities, flush with money and
holding the powers of tenure and promotion, attracted the serialism
crowd to their faculties.
</P>
<P>
   Members, now with steady jobs, didn't have to care whether the
public hated their music or not. Opposing views were either shut
out, laughed to scorn or both. Later, when teaching posts dried up
and composers needed audiences again, the agility of all those
quick descents from various ivory towers was a sight to see.
</P>
<P>
   Once many years ago, when I expressed a love of Neo-Classical
Stravinsky to my teacher in Vienna, she, a rabid follower of the
Darmstadt Festival and its cult of experiment, dismissed me: ``This
is 1960. You travel by airplane, not by horse and buggy.'' The
words have stuck with me because they explain a musical age when
first on the minds of most musicians was not what one composed but
how one composed. The nobility of the music lay less in the
sentiment than in the originality and rectitude of the language.
</P>
<P>
   The other composers chosen for these four concerts were indeed
explorers in their time. But just as tonality seemed to be wearing
out a century ago, so, too, is the present search for doctrines and
messiahs.
</P>
<P>
   The march of history is enjoying a breather. Schoenberg (twice),
Berg, Bartok, Mahler and Stravinsky are being scheduled along with
Boulez's ``Originel'' from ``... explosante-fixe ...'' and the
Ligeti Violin Concerto. A lot of these items are closer to the
start of the 20th century than to the end. Now we call them
``modern classics,'' a little oxymoronic, but a workable
description.
</P>
<P>
   Could we possibly be at a new stage in concertgoing, where
cognoscenti enter the hall, pick up the program and groan, ``Not
Berg's Three Pieces for Orchestra again''? Believers in the
posterity syndrome (products of lonely garrets destined for
posthumous glory), of course, would be ecstatic, but I wonder
whether any amount of exposure will bring ``... explosante-fixe
...'' to your local elevator or to the lips of singers in the
shower.
</P>
<P>
   The gulf between art music and popular culture has become too
wide. Music in the concert hall once grew naturally out of popular
styles, but no longer.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance for concerts like these, on the other hand, has
surprised a lot of us this season. This public, moreover, seems
interested in Schoenberg's ``Pelleas und Melisande'' and the Piano
Concerto less for their historical groundbreaking than simply for
what they are.
</P>
<P>
   It is also interesting that the spiritual biography of the
conductor for these events is remarkably like the things that he
will be conducting. The young Boulez was impatient with the old,
suspicious of a lot of newness and quick to tell us that the method
mattered, and mattered very much.
</P>
<P>
   Boulez at 75 has become a composer of severe yet very beautiful
musical textures and less a maker of doctrine. As a conductor he
has opened himself to a wide and inclusive repertory; the
thought-driven young musician has become an interpreter of
surprising warmth.
</P>
<P>
   With Schoenberg, Stravinsky, Debussy, Boulez, Hindemith, Cage
and the Minimalists running off in their different directions, the
Tower of Babel has emerged as the telling 20th-century metaphor:
many languages, no lingua franca as yet.
</P>
<P>
   But let's try another image. Think of all these composers as
budding, if frustrated, Mercators. Terra incognita cried out for
map makers, and maybe that is what these concerts bring us: a
series of navigational charts that disagree on routes and
topography, and lead to no one place in particular. Audiences would
do well to forget all the possible destinations and simply
contemplate the beauty of the draftsmanship.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
