<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2539 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-ELN-RDP-ART-870&AMP;ADD-N     02-29 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELN-RDP-ART-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH WINS BIG VICTORY IN VIRGINIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Gov. George W. Bush won a forceful victory over
Sen. John McCain in the Virginia primary on Tuesday, picking up a
large cache of delegates as well as a considerable morale boost
after his discouraging loss in Michigan a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates drew heavily from the same voter groups that
have supported them in earlier contests for the Republican
presidential nomination. Bush captured faithful Republican voters,
as he did in his victory in South Carolina 10 days ago,
particularly conservatives and those who call themselves members of
the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won the overwhelming support of independents and
Democrats. While those voters were responsible for the Arizona
senator's first-place finishes in Michigan and New Hampshire before
that, they accounted for a much smaller proportion of the
electorate here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the results show that the wave of publicity after
his upset victory in Michigan, and his fresh appeal that he was ``a
proud Reagan conservative,'' were not sufficient to carry him over
the finish line. And McCain's blunt attacks Monday on leaders of
the religious right failed to rouse independents and Democrats,
although the senator's advisers argue that message will play better
in upcoming states with higher proportions of moderates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Tuesday night characterized his victory as a
condemnation of McCain's recent efforts to paint Bush as a captive
of the religious right. ``The voters of Virginia rejected the
politics of pitting one religion against another,'' Bush declared
at a rally on Tuesday evening in Cincinnati. ``This campaign is
winning and we're doing it the right way. We are uniting our party
without compromising principle.''
</P>
<P>
   With 80 percent of the precincts reporting in Virginia, Bush had
55 percent of the vote, McCain had 42 percent and Alan Keyes had 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In delivering his celebratory speech in Ohio rather than here in
Virginia, Bush underscored how the looming jumble of contests next
Tuesday overshadowed the voting on Tuesday. The election on March 7
is tantamount to a national primary, with Republicans going to the
polls in California, New York, Ohio, Georgia, Missouri and seven
other states. As a result, the contenders have raced from one coast
to the other - and in between.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not stumped in Virginia since Friday night, when he
spoke here at party dinner. McCain rushed out of the state early
Monday afternoon after condemning Pat Robertson and the Rev. Jerry
Falwell, two leaders of the religious right, in a speech in
Virginia Beach. On Tuesday, as he bounced in California from
Stockton to Fresno to Bakersfield, Mr. McCain seemed as clearly
focused on next Tuesday. ``California is a critical state,'' he
said. ``And I need to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Virginia was the largest delegate prize of the day,
Washington state also held a primary on Tuesday. Both candidates
spent as much time in recent days competing there as in Virginia.
The McCain campaign viewed that state _ with a history of rewarding
insurgents _ as more hospitable to their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also went to caucuses on Tuesday in North Dakota, which
has only 19 delegates. There was also a Democratic primary in
Washington state, where no delegates were at stake. Bill Bradley
campaigned vigorously there, struggling for a symbolic victory as a
first step in catching Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In this roller-coaster of a primary season, the outcome in
Virginia was a substantial victory for Bush because by capturing
all of Virginia's 56 delegates to the national convention (1,034
are needed for the nomination), he surpassed McCain in the total
delegate tally. Bush was well organized in this state, relying on
the energetic support of the state's most prominent elected
Republicans, particularly Gov. James S. Gilmore III and Sen. John
W. Warner, and vastly outspending McCain. McCain had boasted that
he would beat the ``Gilmore-Warner machine'' just as he had topped
Gov. John M. Engler's organization in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain just played it wrong in attacking the Gilmore-Warner
machine in Virginia,'' said Mark J. Rozell, a professor of politics
at Catholic University and an expert on Virginia politics. ``He
named probably the two most popular figures in Virginia politics.
And by making several campaign stops in Virginia, McCain raised the
expectations for his candidacy and failed badly. It gives momentum
to George W. Bush going in to Super Tuesday.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as they played down the significance of the outcome on
Tuesday, McCain's aides had significantly stepped up his budget for
the state in recent days after the senator's victory in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The McCain folks were working very hard; they bought our whole
voter file,'' said Ed Matricardi, executive director of the
Republican Party of Virginia. ``They ran a full-fledged campaign
here. The Bush people did too.'' Told that the McCain operation
said it was never particularly serious about Virginia, Matricardi
said, ``How can you advertise heavily in the most expensive
television market _ northern Virginia _ and say you didn't campaign
here?''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While McCain's supporters dismissed Bush as simply winning
another southern state, this state is more diverse than South
Carolina, from the tobacco country in the south to the coal country
in the west to the Washington suburbs to the north.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you know that the western tip of Virginia is further west
than Detroit?'' Matricardi said on Tuesday as he pointed to a
brightly-colored map on the wall of his office. But although this
state is more diverse than South Carolina, it is significantly more
conservative than Michigan _ and that helps explain why Bush won.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that McCain still has difficulty winning significant
support from loyal Republicans may also be a promising sign for
Bush as the contests turn largely to states where only Republicans
can vote. More than six in 10 of the voters on Tuesday described
themselves as Republicans and they overwhelmingly backed Bush,
according to a survey of voters leaving the polls.
</P>
<P>
   But nearly three in 10 voters said they considered themselves
independents _and they just as overwhelmingly backed McCain. Less
than one in 10 voters described themselves as Democrats, and they
overwhelmingly backed McCain. Bush was far more successful here
than in Michigan because voters in Virginia are more conservative.
Nearly six in 10 of voters here described themselves as
conservatives, compared to just over four in 10 in Michigan. The
conservative voters in Virginia backed Bush over McCain by a margin
of more than two to one.
</P>
<P>
   But moderates, who accounted for about three in 10 of the voters
on Tuesday, backed McCain over Bush by nearly the same margin.
Liberals, who made up one in 10 of the electorate, overwhelmingly
backed McCain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
