<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA UTILITY SETTLES AIR POLLUTION LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The government's campaign to make seven utilities
bring old coal-fired electric plants up to modern pollution
standards showed its first results Tuesday when a Florida utility
agreed to spend about $1 billion to switch one plant to natural gas
and make major changes at a second.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Electric Co. did not admit guilt but agreed to pay a
penalty of $3.5 million to settle civil charges brought by the
Environmental Protection Agency under the Clean Air Act. The
utility also agreed to spend $10 million on pollution control
research and experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   The federal agreement supersedes a settlement that the utility
had made with the state of Florida. That agreement was contingent
on Tampa Electric being allowed by the state Public Service
Commission to pass along the cost of the re-engineering of the
plants to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said Tuesday's settlement in the case that was
brought last November was a legal wedge to gain agreements with the
other six utilities. They hinted that they would bring charges
against more utilities under a provision of the Clean Air Act
requiring that when old plants are modernized they be brought up to
current air pollution standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a precedent that will send a signal to the other
companies that this is what we think is appropriate control,'' said
Sylvia Lowrance, principal deputy assistant administrator of the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   Carol M. Browner, the agency administrator, said the change
would reduce emissions that cause or aggravate respiratory
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said that willingness to convert the plant was
based in part on plans now taking shape for a new gas line in
Florida, and on the fact that existing equipment is near the end of
its life, and that a new gas plant could make electricity as the
same price as the old coal plant.
</P>
<P>
   The plant, Gannon, was built in 1957, and company officials said
that rebuilding it as a gas-fired plant would allow them to use the
steam turbines and some other equipment and raise its output at a
time when the demand for electricity is growing rapidly. The
agreement, they said, would also protect them in case the agency
set more stringent rules on coal plants in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is actually a business decision, in light of what all is
going on in the environmental area,'' said Spence Autry, a vice
president of the utility, who negotiated the deal. ``It puts us in
a very good position for whatever could come down the pike later
on.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebuilt Gannon plant, using high-efficiency natural gas
technology, would produce electricity for about the same price as
the coal plant, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other utilities charged with Tampa Electric in November were
adamant that the settlement, which had been rumored since the
company reached the state agreement in December, did not have any
bearing on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The settlement with TECO really has no impact on our case,''
said Pat Hemlepp, a spokesman for American Electric Power, which
uses the most coal among the investor-owned utilities. ``We don't
feel pressured by this to have any rush to settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemlepp said that there were no settlement discussions under way
now but that ``we are always willing to talk about reasonable
solutions to this enforcement action.''
</P>
<P>
   Electricity experts pointed out that Tampa Electric is smaller
than the other utilities in the case and, unlike the bigger
defendants, can commit to switching to natural gas without
affecting the national market for that fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The federal settlement requires Tampa Electric to to make
changes at a second coal-fired station, Big Bend. The company has
agreed to improve the performance of scrubbers, which reduce
emissions that cause acid rain, and to install another kind of
system to control smog-forming nitrogen oxide emissions by 2010. If
the utility cannot meet that deadline, the plant must be shut down
or switched to natural gas by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Changing to natural gas reduces emissions sharply. Browner said
that switching Gannon to natural gas would reduce emissions of
sulfur dioxide, which causes acid rain, by 60 tons a year, and fine
particles, which are lung irritants, by 2,000 tons per year.
Nitrogen oxide would fall by 30 tons per year. ``These are very,
very large reductions,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
