u w BC-INTERNET-ATTACKS-NYT &LR;      02-29 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ATTACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTIMONY HINTS AT SLOW PROGRESS ON INTERNET ATTACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ariz., Va.)   (bl)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The official in charge of the government's
cybercrime-fighting unit told a congressional panel Tuesday that
the FBI was uncertain whether one or more groups was responsible
for the recent attacks on e-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a Justice Department official warned that
``online crime is rapidly increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   In testimony suggesting that progress on the investigation has
been slow, Michael A. Vatis, director of the National
Infrastructure Protection Center, said agents were ``working
aggressively'' and ``continue to make good progress.'' But he also
acknowledged that much work remained in finding those responsible
for attacks in February on Yahoo, eBay, CNN and Amazon.com, among
others.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too early to tell whether this is the result of copycats
or the same people involved in the first attacks,'' Vatis told
members of a joint hearing by subcommittees of the Senate and House
judiciary committees to study the government's response to the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Vatis officially acknowledged for the first time that
investigators had sought and received cooperation from foreign
governments. Debra Joy Weierman, an FBI spokeswoman, said that did
not necessarily suggest the government believed that some attacks
had originated overseas but only that some leads suggested the need
to gather information internationally.
</P>
<P>
   Vatis' comments seemed to undercut the weight of testimony Feb.
16 by the FBI director, Louis Freeh, that the case was producing
``fast-developing leads,'' suggesting that a break in the case
might be imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Vatis said agents still had ``hundreds of leads we're following
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts, executives and computer security experts have
said it might be difficult, if not impossible, to determine who was
responsible and perhaps an even greater challenge to prove guilt in
court. Computer crimes are a forensics challenge because they are
typically designed to mask their origins.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators pressed both the law-enforcement officials and
Internet industry executives Tuesday on whether the attacks argued
for increased penalties for cybercrime and whether more financing
was needed for tracking and prosecuting cybercriminals.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric H. Holder Jr. told the panel that
federal law enforcement urgently needed the $37 million that
President Clinton had requested in new financing in 2001 to expand
staffing, training and tools for fighting cybercrime.
</P>
<P>
   Holder said the susceptibility of the nation's private and
public computer infrastructure was ``astonishingly high.'' And he
added, ``Online crime is rapidly increasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers on both sides of the aisle echoed Holder's sense of
urgent concern, though not all seemed to agree the money should be
automatically appropriated.
</P>
<P>
   But almost without exception, they said the role of the
government should be limited in creating measures to prevent the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they said the private sector should take the lead in
protecting its sites, much as homeowners are expected to put
adequate locks on their doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't fool ourselves that Congress alone can solve the
problem,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   He and Sen. John Kyl, R-Ariz., have proposed legislation that
would lower the barriers federal agents would need to trace an
electronic signal to a single warrant, even if the signal traveled
through several states and companies.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, investigators must get a separate warrant for each
network service provider whose system the signal crosses, which can
be hundreds in a single instance.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Robert Scott, D-Va., asked the law enforcement
officials who would have jurisdiction to issue such warrants and
whether all states and companies would support federal
jurisdiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
