<HEADLINE>
US CHARGES HUSSEIN SQUANDERING MILLIONS ON PALACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said
Tuesday that Iraqi President Saddam Hussein was building more
palaces with gold-plated faucets.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Iraqi president was reaping millions of dollars by
illegally shipping refined oil in defiance of UN sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin suggested the Iraqi elite was a bunch of drunks.
</P>
<P>
   The broadside against Iraq, only the latest in a series of US
presentations against Baghdad, was issued as the Clinton
administration feels an increasing pressure from UN Security
Council members and some members of Congress to lift the nine years
of economic sanctions imposed since the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin's statements veered in new directions, not always put
diplomatically.
</P>
<P>
   After presenting ``newly declassified satellite imagery''
showing the Iraqi leader's palace additions, available on
www.usia.gov, after clicking on ``Near East,'' Rubin said oil
smuggling has grown in recent months from a rebuilt refinery
destroyed during four days of bombing in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   One legal import, he said, was alcohol, which goes through the
port of Aqaba, Jordan, bound for Iraq under the food-for-oil
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The regime in Baghdad is consuming more than 10,000 bottles of
whiskey, 350,000 cans of beer and 7,000 bottles of wine per week,
and alcohol is illegal in Iraq,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol, actually, is legally sold out of Christian-run
storefronts in Baghdad, though banned in restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important point here is that the regime is getting drunk
while it claims its people don't have enough to eat,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said Hussein spends billions of dollars building palaces
and buying the loyalty of security guards ``so that he can prevent
them from putting a bullet in his head.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, three top UN officials have resigned from
their jobs in Iraq in protest of the UN sanctions, which they said
unfairly harmed the people of Iraq and not the government. The most
recent one to quit was Hans von Sponeck.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin Tuesday called von Sponeck ``well-intentioned but
misguided,'' adding, ``He seems to think, in what I and what this
administration considers a matter of wishful thinking, that if
sanctions were (lifted), somehow the people of Iraq would be
getting the benefits of sanctions relief when all the indicators
are the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   But Mahdi al-Bassam, a founding member of the Iraqi National
Congress, a coalition of opposition groups aiming to oust Hussein,
said Rubin's comments Tuesday seemed far-fetched or were only
recycled charges against the Iraqi regime. The Congress opposes the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to find excuses to go on with the failed
policy of sanctions,'' said al-Bassam, a Houston doctor. ``There is
guilt in the US and I guess with the Western powers, about what is
going on in Iraq in terms of starvation.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Bassam also said the administration doesn't want to implement
the Iraq Liberation Act, a $97 million plan to supply cast-off
Pentagon equipment to opposition groups. So far, the United States
has spent $20,000 toward the effort, nearly a year and a half after
passage by Congress, said Francis J. Brooke, executive director of
the Iraq Liberation Action Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Iraq's UN mission received a transcript of Rubin's
comments. An Iraqi official laughed at the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know the Americans were keeping track of people who
were drinking in Iraq,'' the official said.
</P>
</TEXT>
