<SLUG> BC-NY-HOSP-FINE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE FINES HOSPITAL, CITING BOTCHED BRAIN SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Subs to clarify operations mentioned in the lead)  
(jw) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The state Department of Health cited Staten Island
University Hospital on Tuesday for 40 violations and fined the
hospital $80,000 for failing to monitor and discipline its chief of
neurosurgery, who twice in five years operated on the wrong sides
of patients' brains.
</P>
<P>
   The state's action was the harshest penalty and stiffest fine it
had imposed on a hospital in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the neurosurgeon, Dr. Ehud Arbit, bungled a cranial
procedure on a severely ill Staten Island patient who then died,
Health Commissioner Antonia C. Novello announced at a news
conference Tuesday. Arbit was fired from Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Hospital in 1995 for operating on the wrong side of a patient's
brain after confusing two patients.
</P>
<P>
   While the state investigation did not conclude that Arbit's
surgery caused the death of the Staten Island patient, it said that
one other patient of his had died after a questionable procedure,
and that others had become disabled. In several instances, the
state said, the hospital did not report any of the medical errors,
as it is required to do, and violated several provisions of New
York's health laws.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the fine, which the state said could not be
appealed, Novello ordered the Staten Island hospital to hire an
outside consultant to monitor the quality of care there.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital issued a statement Tuesday, in which it said it had
cooperated with state investigators and would work to improve its
monitoring system, in neurosurgery and throughout the hospital. It
said it was preparing a line-by-line response to the state's
findings.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit's lawyer, Anthony Scher, said Tuesday night, ``There was
an investigation into this issue and it is absolutely clear that he
did not operate on the wrong side of the brain. I have not seen the
state report, but it seems to me that they also understand that
that is not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of Arbit's colleagues said in interviews that he had
been unfairly maligned by other hospital workers as a result of
political battles within the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The state began its investigation after receiving several
complaints, and issued its findings Tuesday in a strongly worded
23-page report outlining many allegations, all stemming from
surgical procedures performed by Arbit.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators found that Arbit and the hospital failed to
prepare for surgery properly. The state also cited the hospital for
its decision to allow physicians' assistants to take critical roles
during surgery, performing duties that the state said should have
been done by doctors. In one case, the state charged, Arbit sought
the medical advice of an equipment salesman for spinal plates
during an operation that was going badly. (The salesman, who was
observing the surgery, declined to answer.)
</P>
<P>
   Novello's investigators also outlined, in charge by charge,
gruesome details of what it said were botched operations. In the
case involving surgery on the wrong side of the brain, state
investigators found that a 54-year-old patient, with multiple
illnesses including brain and lung tumors, liver disease, diabetes
and pancreatitis, went into the operating room. The state report
said the patient's CAT scans were not brought into the operating
room, and that Arbit made an incision on the left cerebellum, only
to be told by a physician's assistant that she recalled the tumor
was on the right side.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit told state health investigators that he had intended all
along to remove the entire back of the skull, and that the side of
the placement of the first incision did not matter. He asserted
that he followed acceptable neurosurgical standards, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The patient, identified by those familiar with the case as
Johnnie Artis, a security supervisor from Staten Island, fell into
a coma and died on Feb. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that case, the most serious allegation in the state's
report involved treatment of a 21-year-old patient, who suffered
from a brain tumor and was left to bleed excessively, the state
said. The doctor had used a device that others complained produced
a fuzzy, unusable image, the state said. He switched from
performing a biopsy to brain surgery, catching other staff
off-guard and ill prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Because the anesthesiologist had not anticipated more than a
biopsy, the patient's blood was not typed, and he had not prepared
to replace large quantities of blood, the report noted. A second
procedure was necessary to stop the bleeding, the state said. ``The
patient was unresponsive after surgery and died several weeks
later,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Another case involved a patient requiring spinal surgery. An
anesthesiologist and a physician's assistant told Department of
Health investigators that Arbit's hand slipped and lacerated the
patient's spinal cord, leaving her partially paralyzed, according
to the state's report. In another instance, the doctor and his
staff failed to perform proper follow-up blood work on a
62-year-old patient, exposing her to high risk when she underwent
additional surgery, the state found.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In the case involving the equipment salesman, a patient
complained of weakness in her hands after an operation. A CAT scan
revealed loose screws on a plate that had been implanted in the
patient's spine along the back of the neck, the state noted. Arbit
failed to replace the screws properly, the state said, at one point
asking a medical equipment salesman in the operating room whether
he thought the plate was positioned correctly, the investigators
found.
</P>
<P>
   These medical errors so disturbed the hospital's chief
neurosurgery anesthesiologist that he refused to work with Arbit
and complained to hospital officials, who declined to take action,
the state said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the state rebuked the hospital for failing to report
these cases and for failing to deal with them properly in internal
reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigation found an alarmingly high number of
deficiencies in the hospital's controls and procedures that need to
be in place to ensure patients receive proper care,'' Novello said.
``Worse yet,'' she added, the hospital failed to notify the state
of any worrisome cases, nor did it move to discipline the doctor or
properly investigate the cases when alerted of them.
</P>
<P>
   In its statement, Staten Island University Hospital officials
said they would begin instituting new monitoring procedures to
ensure patient safety and quality of care within the next few days.
But the hospital cautioned that the state's Office of Professional
Medical Conduct, which licenses physicians in the state and
disciplines doctors, had yet to complete interviews with all
personnel involved or to finish its investigation of Arbit.
</P>
<P>
   Novello's announcement Tuesday of stiff fines and a slew of
health violations underscored her decision to make the disciplining
of doctors and quality of care monitoring at hospitals a hallmark
of her tenure, which began in June. For instance, the state of New
York had only twice suspended a doctor's license before an
investigation was completed, both times on Novello's watch and both
in the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit surrendered his license on Feb. 18. The other doctor who
surrendered his license while being investigated was Dr. Allan
Zarkin, who admitted to carving his initials into the stomach of a
patient on whom he had performed a Caesarean section last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Novello's tough stance comes at a time when President Clinton is
pressing states to adopt strict regulations for reporting medical
errors, after a recent report that found medical errors kills
hundreds of thousands of people each year. ``I want to be perfectly
clear,'' Novello said Tuesday. ``When and if the Department of
Health finds that a hospital is not operating up to high standards,
we will move swiftly and decisively.''
</P>
<P>
   The state began its investigation into Staten Island University
Hospital on Feb. 9, when it received complaints that Arbit had
operated on the wrong side of Artis' brain. When state
investigators contacted the hospital, Novello said, its
administrators told them, ``it was a rumor,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The state made an unannounced visit to the hospital the next
day, during which several hospital staff members volunteered
information about the surgeries, Novello said. A week later,
investigators returned and found corroborating evidence, she said.
On Friday, the state concluded its ``intensive investigation'' into
the hospital, the commissioner said, concluding that ``serious
quality problems'' existed.
</P>
<P>
   Arbit was chief of neurosurgery at Memorial Sloan-Kettering
Cancer Center at the time he mistakenly operated on the healthy
right side of the brain of Rajeswari Ayyappan, the 59-year-old
mother of a famous Indian film star, Sridevi Ayyappan, instead of
the left side, where a cancerous tumor was situated.
</P>
<P>
   After the error was discovered, the patient, who had gone to the
hospital with a very poor prognosis, had the tumor removed at New
York Hospital-Cornell Medical Center. She later died in India, and
Arbit was fired from Sloan-Kettering. The state gave him one year's
probation in that case. But he quickly found work at Staten Island
University Hospital, which has been trying hard to raise its
reputation from a community hospital to a world-class cancer
center.
</P>
<P>
   Hiring Arbit was part of that grand plan, said several doctors
at the hospital. Before the case at Sloan-Kettering, Arbit had a
polished reputation in his field as the author of textbooks and an
authority on neurosurgery.
</P>
<P>
   He is known for taking on last-resort patients in a field that
has few happy stories, and for caring for the poorest of the poor
as well as the wealthy types of patients who are the only ones who
can afford care at places like Sloan-Kettering. More than a dozen
patients have expressed support for Arbit in telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a hospital was fined so much money was in 1986,
when Harlem Hospital faced $125,000 for allowing an unlicensed
physician to perform a routine operation in which complications
developed that led to the amputation of the patient's leg. But the
state Department of Health suspended $86,000 of the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   A fine reduction in the Staten Island case, ``is not an
option,'' said a Department of Health spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
