<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2553 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MA-HMOS-BOS &LR;      02-29 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-HMOS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MORE HMOS POST '99 LOSSES; RESERVES WEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LIZ KOWALCZYK  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ With Harvard Pilgrim Health Care already in
receivership, two more of the state's major HMOs reported Tuesday
that they lost millions of dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts Health Plan and Fallon Community Health Plan also said
that their cash reserves dropped in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at both plans, which aggressively raised insurance
premiums in January, said they see hints of a 2000 recovery and
expect to end this year with a profit.
</P>
<P>
   HMOs must filed their 1999 financial reports with the Division
of Insurance by Wednesday. Harvard Pilgrim, which was forced into
state receivership Jan. 4, was granted an extension until April 15.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts's report, filed Tuesday, showed that it lost $41.8 million
last year, compared to $12.8 million in 1998, said its chief
financial officer, Richard Hallworth.
</P>
<P>
   The losses, he said, occurred entirely in the Maine, New
Hampshire, and Rhode Island operations, which Tufts closed in
November. Its Massachusetts HMO, which has about 970,000 members,
reported a surplus of $24.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue from premiums increased from $1.7 billion in 1998 to $2
billion last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year looks worse than 1998, but after we made the
decision to leave those states, we turned the corner and were
profitable,'' Hallworth said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been profitable in Massachusetts, and there's no
reason we won't continue to be. We've put the bulk of our problems
behind us, but that doesn't mean there won't be bumps in the road.
This is a very difficult industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Fallon lost $12.8 million last year, an improvement from 1998,
when it lost $21 million, according to preliminary figures. Fallon,
with about 222,000 members, planned to file its annual report.
Premium revenue grew to $544 million from $487 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expected to begin our financial turnaround in 1999, and we
did,'' said Fallon's spokesman, Richard Burke. ``We certainly
believe we have the reserves to complete the turnaround this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim also aims to return to financial health this
year. But the future of the state's largest HMO and its 1.1 million
members is uncertain while state regulators decide whether they can
attract enough investors to revitalize Harvard Pilgrim, or whether
they must sell it to a for-profit company or liquidate it. A
decision could come this week.
</P>
<P>
   Important considerations for investors are whether Harvard
Pilgrim's finances have improved in receivership and if its
turnaround plan seems realistic.
</P>
<P>
   A source close to the negotiations said that if the turnaround
plan works, Harvard Pilgrim would lose $5 million to $7 million
this year, versus nearly $200 million in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim needs cash from investors or a buyer to increase
its reserves, which have fallen to negative $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators and legislators have called for laws that would
require HMOs to keep a minimum amount of money in reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts and Fallon both saw their reserves fall last year; they
used some of the money to make up for operating losses. Tufts ended
the year with $68 million in reserve; Fallon, with $32 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Turnbull, a former state insurance regulator now at the
Harvard School of Public Health, said Tufts and Fallon appear to be
on the mend _ provided Tufts escapes expensive lawsuits brought by
members and providers in the states it left.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely good news,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But ``I don't think it's time to declare the health plans in
robust financial condition,'' she added. ``They're seriously
undercapitalized and are going to need to be profitable for the
next couple of years before we can declare them out of the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   This month, Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts reported
earning $61 million last year, on revenue of about $2.1 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
