<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2554 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-DEBORAH-YATES-THEATER     02-29 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBORAH-YATES-THEATER-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF HUNDREDS TRYING, ONE STOOD OUT  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBIN POGREBIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From the moment she enters in that siren's dress, it
is clear that what is happening is not just another striking
theatrical performance. It is the uncommon but unmistakable
emergence of a star.
</P>
<P>
   In the new Lincoln Center dance-play, ``Contact,'' reopening at
the Vivian Beaumont Theater after a sold-out run at the Mitzi E.
Newhouse, Deborah Yates dares you to take your eyes off her. And
not just because she makes flying through the air look as
effortless as a fox trot.
</P>
<P>
   It is because Yates commands the stage with an authority that
never seems arrogant, combining a playful grit with an elegant
grace that makes you want to know more about her. Likening Yates to
``a razor-edged Grace Kelly,'' Ben Brantley wrote of her
performance in The New York Times: ``She's not only dangerously
beautiful. ... She can act, too, projecting the requisite fire of
wistfulness beneath the icy exterior.''
</P>
<P>
   John Simon said in New York magazine: ``As dancer, actress,
woman, she is every man's dream and headed for a manifest career.''
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly why Susan Stroman, the director-choreographer of
``Contact,'' picked Yates out of hundreds of dancers to be the
mysterious, riveting Girl in the Yellow Dress (costume courtesy of
William Ivey Long) who gives the despairing advertising executive
Michael Wiley reason to go on living.
</P>
<P>
   Stroman said Yates showed in her audition that she had emotional
depth as well as physical technique. She also had that certain
something that made the choreographer and her colleagues feel as if
they had just made a significant discovery. ``She really was very
powerful,'' Stroman said.
</P>
<P>
   In case you don't hate her yet, Yates is also apparently just
plain nice. She never complained, for example, when she was stepped
on by some of the guys she danced with during rehearsals. Boyd
Gaines, who plays Wiley and is not trained as a dancer, said he
appreciated that, adding, ``Deborah was good about making it appear
I was leading, when in fact I wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to resent Yates for being perfect because she has that
irresistible story of small-town girl makes good. Born in
Jacksonville, Texas, Yates _ who will not give her age (dancers
never do) _ started dancing at about age 6. At 16, she moved with
her family to Austin, where she got serious about ballet training.
(Her father, who sells industrial cleaning supplies, and her
mother, a psychologist, are divorced and remarried; Yates has four
siblings between the two families.)
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Southern Methodist University with a
degree in communications, Yates joined a modern dance company in
Chicago and waited tables, performed on a cruise ship to get her
Actors' Equity card, and then moved to New York ``with a little
money and a lot of moxie.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, she became one of the anonymous high-kicking women in
the quintessential chorus line: the Rockettes. And she said she was
happy doing it. The Radio City Music Hall gig was her first big
break, convincing her parents that maybe it wasn't so bad for their
daughter to be in show business after all.
</P>
<P>
   But Yates was no wide-eyed Broadway wannabe. First, she is a
member of Mensa, the high I.Q. society _ she took the test in
college on a whim _ and has lately been on ``a Russian author
kick,'' working her way through ``War and Peace,'' ``Anna
Karenina'' and ``The Brothers Karamazov.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, she is acutely aware of the opportunity that ``Contact''
has given her. Yates has long admired Stroman's work, like her
choreography for ``Crazy for You,'' which emphasizes characters who
think and feel as well as move. And the irony is not lost on her
that, after trying to blend in as a Rockette, she has a role now
that demands standing out.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't an easy transition. When she comes onstage the second
time, Yates has to throw a door open with a bang before entering
the room. ``It took me three days to do it without giggling,'' she
said. ``Now I just love it. I think every girl should have the
chance to make an entrance like that once in her life.''
</P>
<P>
   People who work with Yates say the attention the actress has
been getting has not changed her. She still lives in the theater
district apartment she has rented for almost three years and still
sees the same man she has dated for a year and a half _ John
Mattey, who recently finished a stint in ``Tony and Tina's
Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She leaves the theater in her sweats and sneakers, as if she's
untouched by all that,'' Stroman said. ``Though I think she carries
herself a little higher now.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, although Yates said, ``The fuss is all about the
Girl in the Yellow Dress,'' she also conceded that her life may
never be the same: ``It has been a seminal moment for me _ years
and years of training and all of a sudden you cross over. That's
not to say I won't go back to struggling, and I may have to wait
tables again. But now people know who I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
