<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Ohio, Okla.) (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   GORE IN LOS ANGELES: Campaigning in Los Angeles on Tuesday, Vice
President Al Gore referred briefly to the fading campaign of his
rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley, saying it was time to unite.
Paying attention to the diverse ethnic populations in California,
he had an interview with Univision, which he was asked to conduct
in Spanish. He declined, saying, though, that he once ``was
completely fluent.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Katharine Q. Seelye
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   OHIO LEANS TO BUSH: In Ohio, the first independent statewide
poll of likely Republican voters taken since the primaries in South
Carolina and Michigan showed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas ahead of
Sen. John McCain, 53 percent to 36 percent. The poll of 386 likely
Republican voters, questioned on Wednesday through Sunday, was
released on Tuesday by the Institute for Policy Research at the
University of Cincinnati. A similar poll of likely Democratic
voters showed Vice President Al Gore ahead of former Sen. Bill
Bradley, 66 percent to 22 percent. The margin of error is plus or
minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   _ By David E. Rosenbaum
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   BETWEEN GOVERNORS: Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma has some
neighborly advice for Bush. Keating, a devout Roman Catholic and
early supporter of Bush, has suggested that the Bush campaign
schedule a speech at a major Catholic university to counter any
hint of anti-Catholic bias that might have emerged after Bush's
appearance at Bob Jones University in the South Carolina primary
campaign. Noting that Bush was at a Catholic center in Cleveland on
Tuesday, Ari Fleischer, a campaign spokesman, said, ``We do
appearances at faith-based organizations all the time, so we rule
nothing out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Ross E. Milloy
</P>
<P>
   THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   GAY MARRIAGE OPPOSED: A proposition to prohibit California from
recognizing same-sex marriages performed elsewhere has majority
support. The Field Poll found in its latest survey that 53 percent
of respondents favored the measure and 40 percent were opposed.
Among Republicans, 77 percent supported it and 16 percent were
opposed, while 42 percent of Democrats supported it and 45 percent
opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   _ By James Sterngold
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE: Democrats, live on CNN 9 p.m. Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: Huntington Park and Los Angeles, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Duluth, Ga., St. Louis and Springfield, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: Riverside, Los Angeles and Westminster, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
