<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2556 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      02-29 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NO HOOVES! NO TAILS! 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Friday night the president was hanging out with
the cast of ``Hanging Up.''
</P>
<P>
   After a White House screening of the hit chick flick, he took
Meg Ryan and Diane Keaton and their kids and other guests for a
late-night tour of the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   He was at his most charming, telling Franklin Pierce anecdotes
and joking that a lucky Indian totem he had just been given had
come ``too late'' to do him any good.
</P>
<P>
   He got some calls from Hillary in Chicago, seeking advice on how
to react to the Amadou Diallo verdict, which had just come down.
Harold Ickes and some others in her campaign thought she should go
to the Bronx and make a speech on Sunday. Susan Thomases, who was a
guest at the White House, thought that was a lame idea. So did the
president, who told his wife that Rudolph Giuliani could speak as
an elected official, but Hillary should not grandstand at such an
incendiary moment.
</P>
<P>
   The president told his guests he was amazed that George W. Bush
had gone to Bob Jones University. He thought Bush had been very
badly served by his advisers on that.
</P>
<P>
   On politics, Bill Clinton is still a smart cookie.
</P>
<P>
   When W. started his race, he said that the gaps in his knowledge
didn't matter because he knew which advisers to trust. That boast
has not been borne out by his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Like his father, he does not connect what he does to get elected
with what's in his heart. He saw Bob Jones the way his dad saw pork
rinds _ just positioning. Now he's hurt, saying he didn't do
anything wrong because his sister-in-law is Catholic and Mexican.
</P>
<P>
   Once in 1988 I asked Bush pere how he could portray himself as a
good candidate for blacks, since he had silently watched for eight
years as the Reagan administration watered down civil rights laws
and never once invited black leaders to the White House. The vice
president looked genuinely hurt. ``But I helped found the Yale
chapter of the United Negro College Fund,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Boosted by the religious right and Big Tobacco _ which hate John
McCain's campaign finance bill _ Bush won big in Virginia. But in
New York he will probably face some questions from the Irish
Catholic community about the close friendship of Bob Jones Jr. and
Ian Paisley, the leader of Northern Ireland's Democratic Unionist
Party, who has denounced the pope as ``the Antichrist'' and ``the
great fornicator,'' and the Catholic Church as an instrument of the
Devil _ echoing the Bob Jones sentiment that Catholics are ``a
Satanic cult.''
</P>
<P>
   (When my mother was in law school, in the mid-1930s, a fellow
student from southern Virginia expressed surprise when he learned
she was a Catholic. Why, he wondered over beers, didn't she have a
mark on her forehead? ``Some Southerners,'' she recalls, ``thought
priests wore cassocks to hide their tails.'')
</P>
<P>
   Bush is still shaken by the Bob Jones tempest. He misspoke last
Friday at a press conference and declared, ``I denounce interracial
dating.''
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland on Tuesday, he complained about John McCain,
noting, ``Oftentimes, politics is nothing but this ``he said, she
said'' type of politics.'' Pray tell, who's the ``she''?
</P>
<P>
   Bush does tactical penitence. He apologizes to John O'Connor,
the cardinal of a key primary state.
</P>
<P>
   At the Catholic Fatima Center he bemoaned the McCain campaign's
calls to Catholic voters about Bob Jones: ``It's the kind of
politics that John F. Kennedy rejected in the 1960s.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's campaign embodies precisely what JFK was battling _
Jesus in the middle of the debate, and Southern preachers telling
their congregations whom to vote for.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Kennedy had to vow that he would keep church and state
apart. W. embraced the Southern preachers who fuse church and state
for profit.
</P>
<P>
   It was a thrill akin to watching Wile E. Coyote push the plunger
on a load of Acme dynamite to hear McCain tag Pat Robertson, Jerry
Falwell, Louis Farrakhan and Al Sharpton, all in the same breath,
as ``agents of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator can pander and his campaign can deceive. But
he's irreverent enough to tell the truth about the reverends.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
