<HEADER>
A2563 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-PGE-PGE_SFCHRON &LR;      02-29 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PGE-PGE </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 PG&AMP;E Stuns PUC by Lowering Gas Rates  &HT;     By David Lazarus 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Pacific Gas and Electric Co., which recently was handed one of its
largest rate increases ever, will inform state regulators today it
is cutting average residential gas rates by $11 a year, The
Chronicle has learned.
<P>
   PG&AMP;E will include the lower gas rate, along with a one-time
credit of about $60 per customer, as part of a filing with the
California Public Utilities Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC last month approved a general rate increase of more than
$450 million to accommodate what PG&AMP;E had characterized as a
near-emergency in meeting the state's growing demand for power.
</P>
<P>
   The utility had warned that as many as 3,500 employees could be
fired and tree-trimming around electrical lines could be scaled
back without sufficient funding.
</P>
<P>
   Such threats resonated with the PUC, which approved the most
generous of three rival funding proposals amid concerns that a
lower rate increase would ``cut too deep into muscle and bone.''
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E officials were at pains yesterday to distinguish between
the latest rate increase, which will be applied primarily to future
distribution costs, and the gas-rate reduction and credit resulting
from past events. They stressed that there is no direct relation
between the two.
</P>
<P>
   But Nettie Hoge, executive director of The Utility Reform
Network, a San Francisco consumer group, said the decrease in gas
rates indicates that the utility has no clear idea of its true
budget needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new gas credit just shows that they forecast wrong
before,'' she said. ``If they're telling you they need $100 million
and they're giving you money back from the last time they asked for
$100 million, do you believe them?''
</P>
<P>
   Hoge said her group will study whether to include the gas-rate
reduction as part of its pending appeal of the PUC's rate-increase
decision. The appeal is expected to be made later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could be grounds to reopen the case,'' said Ken
McEldowney, executive director of Consumer Action, a San Francisco
grassroots organization. ``It calls into question all the
projections PG&AMP;E is using.''
</P>
<P>
   PUC President Richard Bilas said PG&AMP;E had offered no indication
that residential gas rates were heading down during the months that
the general rate increase was under discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that never came up during the hearings,'' he
said. ``There's nothing in the record about this.''
</P>
<P>
   PG&AMP;E officials countered that they had discussed the gas rate
with PUC staff members but not with the five commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   Bilas had proposed a compromise rate increase of $357 million,
which the commission rejected. An administrative law judge who had
investigated PG&AMP;E's financial requirements recommended a $264
million increase, while the utility itself had originally sought
more than $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flabbergasted,'' said Commissioner Henry Duque, who voted
in favor of Bilas' proposal. ``This is not business as usual. It
could be that PG&AMP;E was not leveling with the commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Utility rates are determined by forecasts of future use. In the
case of gas rates, PG&AMP;E estimates what its customers will need
based on predicted weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The utility is required to refund rate payments to customers
when weather conditions end up being milder than expected or if it
collects a greater-than-expected amount of revenue from increased
usage of its pipes and wires.
</P>
<P>
   However, this factor apparently was given little attention by
PG&AMP;E as it made its case to the PUC for higher rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very hard trying to get an idea of what was needed and
appropriate,'' said Commissioner Carl Wood, whose $453 million
funding proposal ultimately passed 3 to 2.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Malekos, PG&AMP;E's manager of rates, said yesterday that the
reduction in residential gas rates _ a decrease of about 3 percent
for the average bill _ is the result of the utility having
over-collected from customers in the past to compensate for an
earlier revenue shortfall.
</P>
<P>
   The average customer pays about $30 in monthly gas bills.
Electricity rates, meanwhile, are expected to remain frozen until
early next year under legislation that deregulated the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Malekos said the separate $60 gas credit, to be offered in the
spring, stems from economies of scale related to increased usage of
PG&AMP;E's pipes by other energy companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The savings come from having sold more gas than expected and
receiving more revenue than expected,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
