<HEADER>
A2564 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROW-GROW_SFCHRON &LR;      02-29 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-GROW </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROW A BUSINESS/PETER SINTON 
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   A Taxing Situation on the Internet 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; Q: I have a small store and am angry that many dot-com companies
are immune from paying sales taxes. What can I do to lobby for a
level playing field so e-tailers pay the same sales taxes as
brick-and-mortar retailers such as myself?
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;   &LR; A: You are not alone. A lot of businesses are ticked off that
their customers can go online and save 8 percent or so in sales tax
if they purchase from companies with no physical presence, or
nexus, in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``As consumers learn how to shop in a tax-free environment, they
will,'' worries Clifford Waldeck, who runs Waldeck's Office
Supplies in San Francisco. ``This leaves local companies holding
the tax burden bag on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   Waldeck recommends contacting your representatives in
Washington, D.C., starting with Sen. Barbara Boxer, who has
endorsed extending the moratorium on taxing dot-coms.
</P>
<P>
   Also check out the e-Fairness Coalition at www.e-fairness.org.
This Washington, D.C., group represents more than 350,000 retail
stores nationwide and explains some of the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Vertex Tax ``Cybrary'' provides detailed summaries of state
activity in the area of Internet taxation (www.vertexinc.com).
</P>
<P>
   At the root of the controversy is the 1992 Quill vs. North
Dakota decision where the U.S. Supreme Court ruled that to avoid an
undue burden on interstate commerce, merchants should only have to
collect sales taxes in states where they have a physical presence
such as a store, a warehouse or employees.
</P>
<P>
   (Most people don't realize that if they are not charged a sales
tax on an online or mail-order transaction they are supposed to pay
a ``use'' tax of the same amount. Consumers almost always ignore
this little-known law unless the transaction involves a big-ticket
item like an automobile, which must be registered with the
California Department of Motor Vehicles. And the California state
Board of Equalization doesn't go after consumers who fail to pay a
use tax on books, boots and most everything else ordered from
out-of-state.)
</P>
<P>
   The Internet tax issue is so hot that President Clinton
discussed it at this week's meeting of the nation's governors. It
has been festering since 1998, when U.S. legislation imposed a
three-year 3-year  &LR; moratorium on new Internet access taxes or other
levies on electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation also created the Advisory Commission on
Electronic Commerce to consider issues associated with the taxation
of sales over the Internet. The Commission will issue its
recommendations to Congress on April 5, but the e-Fairness group
feels the deck is stacked against conventional stores. The panel
has 19 commissioners, including eight from states and cities, eight
from companies tilted toward electronic commerce and three from the
administration.
</P>
<P>
   E-Fairness proponents maintain that by exempting Internet and
other remote retailers from the responsibility to collect taxes on
sales to consumers in states where they don't have a physical
presence, it essentially increases the burden on other businesses.
It also hurts low-income individuals who are less likely to have
Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Q: How much business are traditional retailers really losing to
their online competitors and how much less tax revenue is
California collecting as a result?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Forrester Research says all 50 states lost $525 million in
retail sales taxes last year as a result of Internet transactions.
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like a lot, but the number needs to be put in
context. California alone collected $27 billion in sales taxes last
year. That was up 8.5 percent from 1998, according to the Board of
Equalization, despite the loss of about $200 million in tax
revenues resulting from sales to out-of-state vendors that were not
taxed. Incidentally, out-of-state Internet sales were responsible
for about $60 million of the lost tax revenues to California,
compared with about $140 million from mail order.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Internet sales are increasing faster than catalog
sales, but a new report from McKinsey &AMP; Co. suggests that consumers
are not that easy to catch online.
</P>
<P>
   The consulting firm studied the behavior of about 150 million
visitors to Web sites and 3 million customers and came up with its
first ePerformance index. It shows less than 4.5 percent of Web
visits result in a sale and only 1.3 percent of visitors were
repeat buyers in the second quarter of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Many people fear that giant companies, including some of the
biggest booksellers, are setting up sham online subsidiaries to
evade state sales taxes. But a California Board of Equalization
official says the state has 1,000 auditors vigorously tracking
cases. ``If it is really a single business and the store says
`visit our Web site' or the Web site says `buy online and return to
our store,' then it is not a real subsidiary and sales taxes are
due.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many store owners are worried by Internet interlopers,
some state officials believe that most big online companies like
Gateway Computer eventually require a physical presence in major
states like California and end up paying sales taxes. They argue,
too, that forcing small online businesses to cope with some 6,000
sales tax jurisdictions around the country is not fair, either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send small-business questions to entrepreneurs &LR; sfgate.com, or to
Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
