<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 02/29/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) PARIS -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- PARIS-FASHION -- A
burnished-gold satin coat for Yves Saint Laurent by Alber Elbaz,
from the first round of Paris shows. Over the past three weeks, the
fashion crowd has gathered for the Fall 2000 ready-to-wear
collections, in New York, London, Milan and now Paris. (Jean-Luc
Hure/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) LONDON -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- HONGKONG-CABLE -- Graham
Wallace, chief executive of Cable &AMP; Wireless, in his London office
in October, 1999, before a portrait of Lord Inverforth, who founded
the company that became what it is now. When Wallace took the helm
of Cable and Wireless P.L.C. a year ago this week, he was supposed
to be the consummate company man, reluctant to shake things up. But
with such a bevy a huge deals on his watch, culminating with the
sale of Cable and Wireless prize stake in Cable and Wireless HKT,
Wallace is quickly proving he is willing to ruffle the conventional
wisdom about the century-old institution. (Jonathan Player/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) PERSIAN GULF -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- TAIWAN-CHINA -- The USS
Port Royal in the Persian Gulf as it conducts surface and air
defense operations for the USS Nimitz battle group in November,
1997. The Ticonderoga class cruiser is equipped with AEGIS combat
systems. A request by Taiwan to purchase some of the United States'
most advanced defensive weapons, including the AEGIS system, is
causing a split within the Clinton Administration and threatens to
complicate the delicate three-way relationship among Taiwan, China
and the United States. (Christopher Mobley, U.S. Navy/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- RESTAURANT-MONITOR-2 -- At
the restaurant Jean Georges, a computer program keeps information
on regular diners. In a city where people prize anonymity almost
more than fame, restaurants are increasingly adding surveillance
and information gathering to their functions. But they aren't
exactly boasting about it. (Barbara Alper/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- THEATER-NAMES -- The
renovated Selwyn Theater on 42nd Street nears completion Tuesday.
Plans are for the theater to bear the name American Airlines
Theater. Traditionalists may shudder at the thought of
corporations' buying their way onto the marquees, but theater
owners and marketing experts say these alliances will grow and
could become a widespread and lucrative practice. (Chester Higgins
Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- NY-CONEYISLAND-STADIUM -- A
view Tuesday of the old roller coaster and parachute jump in Coney
Island. Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New York wants to build a
publicly financed minor league baseball stadium at the site, an
artist rendering of which appears below. Critics of the plan say
that baseball stadiums do not make much of an economic impact on
the surrounding community. (Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) COLUMBUS, Ohio -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- BUSH-2 -- Gov. George
W. Bush of Texas, running for the Republican presidential
nomination, greets supporters during a rally at Westerville High
School, Tuesday. With voters in Virginia, Washington State and
North Dakota going to the polls Tuesday, Bush tried to blunt
McCain's attacks on his support by conservative religious groups by
shifting the focus of the increasingly nasty race. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- AOL-CONGRESS-- American
Online Chief Executive Officer Stephen M. Case, left, and Time
Warner Chief Executive Officer Gerald M. Levin prepare to testify
on Capitol Hill Tuesday before the Senate Judiciary Committee
hearing on the proposed AOL-Time Warner merger. The two companies
faced heavy skepticism from senators on the promised benefits of
their planned merger. (Shana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SAN FRANCISCO -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- BRADLEY -- Reporters
take notes as Bill Bradley, running for the Democratic presidential
nomination, takes part in a television interview, Tuesday at the
St. Francis Hotel. While Washington state voted its preference
Tuesday, Bradley prepared to argue his case against his opponent,
Vice President Al Gore, directly to the nation in a paid,
five-minute network TV appearance on Thursday night. (Nicole
Bengiveno/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) STOCKTON, Calif. -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- MCCAIN -- Sen. John
McCain, running for the Republican presidential nomination, confers
with chief political strategist Mike Murphy, left, and Kenneth
Khachigian, right, backstage at Memorial Auditorium in Stockton on
Tuesday. Virginia, North Dakota and Washington state cast ballots
or attended caucuses Tuesday in the Republican race. (Ruth
Fremson/New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- SQUONK-THEATER-REVIEW --
Jana Losey, one of the creators of ``Squonk,'' is also a performer.
``Squonk'' opened Tuesday night at the Helen Hayes Theater on
Broadway after running in the East Village in August. To put it
simply, ``Squonk'' has shrunk, almost to the point of invisibility.
Placing this small, eccentric charmer in a Broadway house is a
brutally misguided transplant. (Sara Krulwich/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) RAMALA, Israel -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- EICHMANN-DIARY-3-B&AMP;W
-- Nazi war criminal Adolf Eichmann in his prison cell in 1961.
Eichmann's diary was released by Israeli authorities on Tuesday.
Eichmann, a Nazi bureaucrat who historians say played a key role in
the genocide of 6 million Jews, penned the 1,300-page manuscript in
the months leading up to his 1962 execution by Israel. (Israeli
Government/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- BLACKGISWWII-2-COX -- Harold
Vaughan during World War II. The armed forces that drafted Vaughan
and nearly a million other blacks during the war were almost
entirely separate from white units, with little pretense of being
equal. Even during the costliest combat in the Pacific and Europe,
nearly all blacks were held back from the fight. Most were assigned
to support roles: packing supplies, loading ammunition, driving
trucks. (Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. -- Feb. 29, 2000 --
BLACKGISWWII-1-COX --Harold Vaughan, now a retired attorney, in his
home during a recent interview where he talked about his experience
as a soldier during World War II. The armed forces that drafted
Vaughan and nearly a million other blacks during the war were
almost entirely separate from white units, with little pretense of
being equal. Even during the costliest combat in the Pacific and
Europe, nearly all blacks were held back from the fight. Most were
assigned to support roles: packing supplies, loading ammunition,
driving trucks. (Bruce R. Bennett/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
