REDSOX-ASADOORIAN-BOS -- Boston Red Sox first round draft pick Rick
Asadoorian does a timed wind sprint duirng spring traning. The Red
Sox hope Asadoorian will put tiney Whitinsville, Mass., on the map.
(Frank O'Brien/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BOSTON -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- AUTHOR-BRANCACCIO-BOS --
David Brancaccio spending some money at the race track earlier this
month. Brancaccio, the host and senior editor of ``Marketplace'' on
public radio, is the author of the recently-published book,
``Squandering Aimlessly: My Adventures in the American
Marketplace.'' The 39-year-old Maine native, who lives in Los
Angeles with his wife and three children, took 10 trips in 16
months and then turned his meanderings into a 283-page look at 10
possible ways of disposing of burdensome cash. (Suzanne Kreiter/The
Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BOSTON -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- BIRACIAL-GENERATION-BOS --
Cody Jones and his sister Julia. The Jones say they prefer not to
be categorized by a specific race. A new generation of biracial
people is refusing to be categorized within the slim confines of
black, white, Hispanic, Native American, or Asian/Pacific Islander.
(Wendy Maeda/The Boston Globe)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CUDAHY, Calif. -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- GORE -- Vice President
Al Gore at the Clara Street Recreation Center where he addressed
supporters on topics ranging from education to healthcare. Gore
campaigned Tuesday as if he were already the Democratic
presidential nominee, ignoring his opponent Bill Bradley and,
instead, ridiculing the Republicans' ``huge identity crisis.'' At
right is Gloria Molinas, a county school supervisor. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CLEVELAND -- Feb. 29, 2000 -- BUSH -- Gov. George Bush of
Texas, running for the Republican presidential nomination, during a
leadership forum at the Fatima Family Center, a Roman Catholic
outreach group, Tuesday. At right is Thomas Mullen, head of
Catholic Charities. With voters in Virginia, Washington State and
North Dakota going to the polls Tuesday, Bush tried to blunt
McCain's attacks on his support by conservative religious groups by
shifting the focus of the increasingly nasty race. (Stephen
Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
