<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2568 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-STARTOVER-STARTOVER_S     02-29 2043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARTOVER-STARTOVER </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Financiers Leave Firms to Create Their Own Businesses  
 By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
After a dozen years as an investment banker helping entrepreneurs
launch their businesses, Abby Adlerman decided it was time to start
her own enterprise.
<P>
   In mid-1998, she created Visualize.com to sell limited-edition
original prints and photographs to fill the void between expensive
gallery pieces and mass-produced posters. ``I went from Wall Street
to wall art,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Adlerman is not alone. Hundreds of investment bankers, venture
capitalists and securities analysts have plunged into building
their own enterprises or taking top jobs with those who have.
</P>
<P>
   Many, like Adlerman, were high-priced partners with little to
prove by remaining at their investment banking firms. Peter Hunt, a
former managing director at Montgomery Securities who loves working
with wood, quit the merger and acquisition trade last year to build
CornerHardware.com, an online site for home improvement products
and information.
</P>
<P>
   Other financiers who jumped to startups include twentysomethings
who view a stint in investment circles as akin to an MBA degree. It
helps prepare them for life as an entrepreneur. In the Bay Area,
the roster of such financiers includes:
</P>
<P>
   _Will Clemens, 28, who spent four years with two investment
banks before joining one of the firm's software clients and then
starting his own company, Respond.com, in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _Andrew Solomon, 26, worked for Solomon Smith Barney for two
years, used his savings to try to launch his singing career and
recently moved to the Bay Area to merge his music and management
interests as director of business development for EMusic.com in
Redwood City.
</P>
<P>
   It's too difficult to say how well investment bankers do as
entrepreneurs because it's not a niche that has been tracked. But
Frank Quattrone, head of Credit Suisse First Boston's Technology
Group, said, ``If they've been part of building successful
organizations and observed how good decisions are made, then they
probably have the right entrepreneurial DNA.''
</P>
<P>
   Adlerman, who grew up in a tiny art colony called Roosevelt,
N.J., recalls receiving her first piece of art, a woodblock print
of a a &LR; horse racetrack, as an eighth-grade graduation present.
</P>
<P>
   She got the equivalent of an MBA degree from Yale and then, like
many of her peers, was drawn to the financial fast track. At L.F.
Rothschild in New York, she toiled on initial public offerings and
convertible debt issue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Then she was lured to Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in San Francisco,
where she became a managing director head of private placements _
the final financial fattening step before startups launch their
IPOs. After that, Adlerman spent three years as head of H&AMP;Q's
thriving consumer banking business and helped Jeff Bezos of
Amazon.com and Howard Schultz of Starbucks take their companies
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I realized that instead of living vicariously through my
customers' experiences, I wanted to have the experience myself,''
said Adlerman. ``I wanted to do something more entrepreneurial,
more strategic, more growth oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Art of the Deal
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Adlerman started thinking about creating a business herself
after more than a decade helping others turn their dreams into
reality. The only question was what type of business.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on her longtime long-time  &LR; interest in art, it dawned on
her that art is one of the most difficult things to buy. And she
perceived ``a vast no-man's-land'' between galleries and auction
houses at the top of the market and poster and framing shops at the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   According to Alderman, most galleries are ``intimidating
places'' that are loath to answer basic questions like explaining
the difference between a lithograph and a serigraph or why one
piece of art costs $1,000 and another $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to make buying limited edition art as easy as buying
quality furniture at the Pottery Barn and, in fact, teamed up with
former Pottery Barn buyer Jen Lawrence to start Visualize in
mid-1998.
</P>
<P>
   The two wanted to demystify and democratize the fine art
business by offering limited editions of ``quality art'' for $100
to $1,100 online or though the company's direct mail catalog.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to pitching pictures, their Web site and online arts
magazine called Off the Wall provide offer  &LR; information and
collecting tips. The company has signed 350 artists to offer some
of their works exclusively through Visualize in editions of 80 to
300 autographed copies.
</P>
<P>
   Adlerman pegs the ``underserved art market'' as a $17 billion
sales opportunity. One of the biggest segments, she said, ``is
people living with bare walls and people who are still holding on
to their college dorm posters.''
</P>
<P>
   Visualize is targeting consumers as well as businesses that buy
art for their offices. Because it has lower real estate costs than
a gallery and can sell anywhere online and by mail order, Adlerman
pictures profit margins in excess of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The profit equation is enhanced by the fact that Visualize
drives a hard bargain with artists. It also can produce much of the
art itself, including high-class computer-generated digital images
called  &LR; gicl &LR; e &LR; e &LR;  (pronounced zhee-CLAY) prints.
</P>
<P>
   After reading thousands of business plans during her investment
banking tenure, Adlerman said she did not have much trouble writing
a tight 20-page plan of her own. However, she said researching the
potential market took several months.
</P>
<P>
   One of the important lessons she said she learned as a financier
is that ``it is good to hold onto the equity as long as possible.''
So for the first year, Adlerman and associates invested $1 million
of their own money in the startup.
</P>
<P>
   The business was launched last March. In July, Visualize raised
more than $5 million from Brentwood Venture Capital, Hambrecht &AMP;
Quist and Venture Strategy Partners. It expects to close an
additional another  &LR; $15 million to $20 million venture round soon.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Hunt also recently gave up a lucrative investment banking
career to try his hand as an entrepreneur. After 13 years plying
the merger and acquisition trade, he quit Banc of America
Securities (successor to Montgomery Securities) last April to build
CornerHardware.com, an online hardware store.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, 36, attended Washington &AMP; Lee University in Virginia,
where he helped support himself by running the Campus Linen
Service. Then he took a trainee job at J.P. Morgan and enjoyed
working on deals like the sale of the Baltimore Orioles. The intern
program turned into a seven-year stint before Hunt moved west in
1994 to head Montgomery Securities' health care M&AMP;A practice.
</P>
<P>
   When NationsBank acquired Montgomery on its way to buying Bank
of America, Hunt began thinking about becoming an entrepreneur. ``I
always wanted to do something on my own,'' he recalled. ``I reached
the pinnacle of an investment banking career. And being bought out
by a bank created a difficult situation with more bureaucracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt loved hardware stores. He also was keen on building
everything from wooden toys and outdoor play structures for his
kids to Adirondack chairs for his second home in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   So why not combine passion and profession? With some help from
Montgomery home improvement products analyst Bo Cheadle, Hunt
refined his business plan and was introduced to his current
partner, Richard Tanaka, former CEO of Eagle Hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Their company, CornerHardware.com, received $6 million in
first-round financing in August from private investors including
Alta Partners and Venture Law Group. Five weeks ago, the San
Francisco startup launched its business site, which offers 37,000
products as well as animated guides on how to build and install.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're marrying the service of an old-fashioned corner hardware
store with the selection, speed and convenience of the Internet,''
said Hunt. CornerHardware.com is looking for a second round of
financing and Hunt anticipates an IPO as early as next year.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Valenti, 40, also retooled himself as an entrepreneur after
a varied career, most recently as a venture capitalist at Rosewood
Partners. In 1998, he left the San Francisco VC firm, which was an
early investor in such companies as Noah's Bagels and Jamba Juice.
</P>
<P>
   Because his company is still in ``stealth mode,'' Valenti is
unwilling to divulge details other than to say it will manage Web
sites and distribution channels for specialty consumer products
companies.
</P>
<P>
   It took awhile before Valenti discovered his entrepreneurial
passion. After studying industrial engineering at Georgia Tech, he
served on a submarine and was a manager for several companies,
including Proctor &AMP; Gamble, where he worked the Pepto-Bismol and
Tide accounts. Then he got an MBA degree at Stanford and became a
consultant for McKinsey &AMP; Co. before landing at Rosewood.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he and his venture capital partners were
searching for a CEO to lead a startup called Echo Online Networks,
when Valenti realized he wanted the job himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It dawned on me I didn't want to own a piece of a piece of
another e-commerce company,'' Valenti said. ``And I felt I couldn't
transfer my understanding of it and passion for it to someone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   The Redwood City company, still code-named Echo, has raised $9
million in venture backing from Rosewood, Sutter Hill Ventures,
Stanford and others. It has 35 employees and plans to launch its
service in June.
</P>
<P>
   Many other entrepreneurs are taking the corporate reins after
just a short stint in the financial world.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clemens, 28, lasted only four years before making the
switch. He joined Morgan Stanley as a trainee in New York after
studying history at University of Virginia, and then followed the
firm's technology investment banking chief Frank Quattrone out to
Palo Alto. When Quattrone jumped to Deutsche Morgan Grenfell,
Clemens left, too. Like other recruits, he worked around the clock
many days and occasionally fell asleep in his car at stoplights
stop lights  &LR; on his way home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun because we had a lot of responsibility,'' Clemens
recalled. But he figures the $125,000 he was making as an associate
was ``pretty lousy relative to the hours I put in.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Clemens especially admired the entrepreneurs at startups
he worked with, he left in 1997 to join one of them _ Advent
Software. The San Francisco company makes portfolio management
tools for the brokerage industry.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in late 1998, Clemens was talking to a former DMG
colleague now working at Hummer Winblad Venture Partners who
happened to be looking for a CEO for a new online shopping service.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens jumped at the opportunity, took the CEO job and
co-founded Respond.com. The Redwood City company lets shoppers
describe what they want and then get personalized e-mail responses
from businesses offering the specified products and services.
Already, Respond.com has raised close to $60 million in capital
from Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, Access Technology partners,
Barksdale Group and others.
</P>
<P>
   Despite notable successes, one should not assume that former
financiers are able to pursue any dream successfully and forever.
</P>
<P>
   Take Andrew Solomon, 26, and his dream of becoming a
professional singer and songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   He toiled as a financial analyst in Salomon Smith Barney's
leveraged buyout division in New York after graduating from
Dartmouth. Then, after two years of ``living at my desk,'' he left
with $40,000 in savings to pursue a career in music.
</P>
<P>
   He developed his own Web site, pressed his own CD, worked the
club scene and met recording industry honchos and lawyers. He
received some positive reviews and sold more than 1,500 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   But after a year, faced with becoming a starving artist, Solomon
switched priorities to finding a job where he could combine both
music and management.
</P>
<P>
   He recently moved to San Francisco to become director of
business development at EMusic.com, a publicly traded company that
lets customers sample and buy music downloaded music over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Peter Sinton at psinton  &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
