<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TOBACCO-REGULATE-NYT &LR;      02-29 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-REGULATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW POSTURE FOR PHILIP MORRIS, BUT OLD SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why did Philip Morris, a company that long regarded the federal
government as its arch-enemy, suddenly announce it was willing to
accept some government regulation?
</P>
<P>
   The company's new posture, many say, reflects a campaign to
recast its battered image. But it also comes as a number of events
affecting the tobacco industry's present and future are moving
toward a conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami jury is about to render a verdict in a case that could
financially devastate some cigarette producers. The U.S. Supreme
Court is set to decide this spring whether the Food and Drug
Administration has regulatory authority over tobacco. And a
scientific panel is reviewing whether it is possible to produce a
less-hazardous cigarette, a decision critical to the industry's
future marketing plans.
</P>
<P>
   The company's new stance represents a sharpening of positions
taken in 1997 by Philip Morris Cos. and other tobacco producers
when they reached a $368.5 billion settlement of lawsuits brought
by state attorneys general against the industry. But that deal
collapsed and some of its provisions were not contained in later
settlements of the state lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the disclosure that Philip Morris, the nation's
largest cigarette maker, wanted to start talks about tobacco
regulation left government officials, anti-smoking activists and
analysts alternately encouraged, suspicious or just perplexed about
the company's intentions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great first step,'' said Jeff Nesbit, a consultant who
has long worked with anti-tobacco groups. ``But now there are some
hard questions that needed to be asked, for this industry has
practiced deceit and deception.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Steven Parrish, the senior vice-president of Philip
Morris, said that company would not oppose federal regulation in
areas like the marketing of cigarettes to minors, the disclosure of
ingredients and the development of cigarettes that may pose fewer
risks.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish said the company would still oppose regulation of
nicotine by the FDA as a drug. But that might not prove to be a
stumbling block because a failed congressional tobacco bill
sponsored by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., carved out a special
regulatory authority for tobacco within the FDA, said Nesbit, who
worked on that bill.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Aronson, the president of Aronson Washington Research, a
company that follows tobacco litigation, said she was confused
about Philip Morris' motives. But Aronson said that cigarette
makers face grave courtroom threats including a decision soon by a
Miami jury in a class-action lawsuit brought on behalf of all
Florida smokers. That verdict may y produce a punitive damage award
of tens or even hundreds of billions against Philip Morris and
other companies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many industry analysts like Aronson said they believed that the
Supreme Court would decide that the FDA did not have statutory
authority over tobacco. But even with that victory, the industry
would face more legal pummeling from mounting lawsuits, including
an action by the Justice Department seeking to recover hundreds of
millions in federal health care costs spent treating
tobacco-related ills.
</P>
<P>
   Those legal threats have sent the prices of tobacco industry
stocks to some of their lowest levels in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Such threats apparently caught the attention of Philip Morris
officials, who began an informal round of talks about possible new
tobacco regulations several months ago. At the same time, the
company was stepping up a public relations campaign based on the
theme that it was eager to shed its past and confront the health
risks of its products.
</P>
<P>
   Aronson said that renewing congressional discussions about
tobacco regulation might give Philip Morris and other producers a
chance to devise a compensation plan that would resolve the
lawsuits against them.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of scientific experts assembled by the Institute of
Medicine, a division of the National Academy of Sciences, is
reviewing an issue that probably will be part of an industry
marketing strategy in the future _ the production of potentially
less-hazardous cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the FDA requested that the institute review related
questions, including the issue of what constituted a reduced-risk
cigarette and whether such a product was possible. This week,
cigarette industry officials and public health experts are to
testify before the panel, said Tommy Payne, a vice-president with
the R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   While no decision is imminent, the panel's conclusions could
have a major impact on how future cigarettes are marketed. Any
claims that a new cigarette poses a lower risk than a traditional
one would require FDA approval and its jurisdiction over that area
of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Payne said that R.J. Reynolds is not opposed to some reasonable
congressional regulation of tobacco in areas like safer producers.
Mark Smith, a spokesman for the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Co. said
that it wants to engage in more discussions with its critics and
public health officials but has not pressed for new federal
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been down that road before,'' said Smith, referring to
the 1997 settlement proposal that collapsed in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-smoking advocates like Nesbit said that the positions of
R.J. Reynolds and Brown &AMP; Williamson may not be consequential
because Philip Morris dominates domestic tobacco sales and the
industry's political clout.
</P>
<P>
   Just how Philip Morris will exercise that muscle remains
unclear. But one thing is certain. As the disconnect between the
company's public pronouncements and its statements in lawsuits
grows, Philip Morris is on the verge of developing a
multiple-personality disorder.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as Parrish was discussing the company's willing to
accept federal regulation, the Associated Press reported that a
psychiatrist hired by Philip Morris and other tobacco producers as
an expert witness in the Florida case testified that his review of
two smokers in that lawsuit showed that they were not addicted. He
also testified that he had never done any research on tobacco
addiction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
