<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAPING LATEST HURDLE, COMPUTERS FORGE AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If Newton's laws covered bureaucracies, he might
have written that once a federal agency is set in motion, it tends
to stay in motion.
</P>
<P>
   The parallels between physics and politics were on display
Tuesday at the command center of the President's Council on Year
2000 Conversion, where the chairman, John A. Koskinen, noted that
the United States _ and the world _ suffered very few of the
computer problems some people expected to develop on Leap Day.
</P>
<P>
   He took the lack of a problem as a sign of the council's
success, another victory after very few Year 2000 problems
developed over New Year's weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few days ago, Koskinen had openly discussed the
possibility of closing his shop by the end of March. But he did not
take the lack of serious problems as an opportunity to announce
Tuesday that his agency would fade away any time soon. ``We have
not focused on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert F. Bennett, R-Utah, and Sen. Christopher J. Dodd,
D-Conn., have suggested that the agency be made permanent to ensure
the security of computer-based information against attacks from
hackers.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his agency should be preserved, Koskinen said,
``That's an option that will have to be considered.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Ricci, a spokeswoman for the Office of Management and
Budget, the White House agency handling the issue, said: ``We have
not yet made a decision. We are looking at the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's report on leap-year glitches, caused when some
computers were not programmed to recognize the day as Feb. 29 and
instead regarded it as March 1, was tiny when compared with the
report on the Jan. 1 events, which were themselves mostly minor.
</P>
<P>
   The seed of the Jan. 1 issue was planted years ago when computer
programmers coded years with two digits, leaving many machines
confused by the change from 1999 to 2000. The Feb. 29 issue has
roots in the late 16th century, when the Roman Catholic Church,
trying to adjust for an annual orbit around the sun that is not
exactly 365.25 days, decreed that years ending in 00 would not be
leap years, unless they were divisible by 400. Thus, 1600 was a
leap year, but 1700, 1800 and 1900 were not.
</P>
<P>
   Some computer people who knew a lot _ but not enough _ about the
exceptions got the year wrong; others who knew nothing about
exceptions got it right, for the wrong reasons. And of course some
programmers knew exactly what to do and why.
</P>
<P>
   All of that left Koskinen unsure until Tuesday what would
actually happen. In the end, the Coast Guard reported that it was
having trouble shifting messages into its archives (but no trouble
in transmitting the messages themselves) and some telephones with
caller ID were recording calls as having been received on March 1
(but most will correct themselves on March 2).
</P>
<P>
   At Ronald Reagan National Airport in Washington, D.C., Koskinen
said, there were delays at some skycap luggage check-ins.
</P>
<P>
   When the final results are in, he said, perhaps a dozen
glitches, all minor, will have occurred in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, 1,200 of the 25,000 ATMs in post offices did not work
but were quickly repaired. And some weather forecasts in Japan were
wrong because of computer glitches, and some in the Netherlands
were correct but could not be sent out promptly.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching deeper to find another problem, Koskinen said that some
passports in Bulgaria had to be processed by hand because automated
machines malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Koskinen listed one last possible miniconcern. On Dec. 31, he
said, some computers may get confused because 2000 will have had
366 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
