<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN30-COX     02-29 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman's free-spirited life captured in obit
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ There is an indefinable age at which folks
begin to scan the morning paper's obit section, not so much to see
who has left in the night, but to reassure themselves that whoever
it was, he or she was a lot older than they.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Smith, 1911-2000. OK. Old Joe had a nice long life and now
he's gone. But as the years pass, and the birth dates begin
creeping forward, edging their insidious way into our decade,
reality hits. ``No matter what you do, you're gonna' die.''
</P>
<P>
   That succinct bit of wisdom is just one of dozens of memorable
lines from my all-time favorite movie, ``Moonstruck.'' Cosmo
Castorini, a philandering almost-over-the-hill spouse (played by
Vincent Gardenia), is reminded by Rose (Olympia Dukakis), his
exasperated but loving wife, that in spite of his hussy and her
cleavage, he's not going to live forever so he might as well get
over it.
</P>
<P>
   Cosmo sees the light _ even though the awareness of his
mortality is a tough pill to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   Flash back to the early '50s when I was in high school. The
English teacher, in an attempt to stimulate a bunch of 16-year-olds
into thoughts somewhat deeper than hair and Saturday night movies,
assigned us to interview another classmate and write his or her
obituary _ truthfully and without exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Obituary? Like in dead? We were dumbfounded.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, when the entire class showed up obituary-less and
worried, the wise woman smiled and told us it was OK ... that she
understood. ``You had nothing to write because you haven't really
done anything. But remember, you have a lifetime ahead of you to
remedy that.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, a reader in Massachusetts sent along a clipping
from her local paper that had caught her eye. It was the obit for a
54-year-old woman in a neighboring town. ``It knocked me out,'' the
reader writes. ``It made me realize that if I didn't get busy, my
obit would be 20 words long and as exciting as reading the back of
a cereal box.''
</P>
<P>
   ``... a musician, artist, and free spirit,'' the death notice
begins. ``Born and raised in Portage, Wis., she spent three
formative years at the Brook Farm in Roxbury, Mass., an idealistic
experiment in communal living.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a child she developed a love for animals, nature,
adventure, and drumming. Later, she ranched and made music in
Texas, and lived on horseback in the Ozark mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``She drummed with the Berbers of Morocco, formed a women's
commune in Arkansas, and played carnie in Rockland, Maine, to
finance the purchase of a lobster boat that she sailed to
Provincetown in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1977, she co-founded the Provincetown Horse and Carriage
Co., the town's first horse-drawn tour, and in 1979, opened
Gabriel's Apartments and Guest Rooms, one of the first women's inns
on the East Coast. For many years she hosted Friday sunset drumming
on Herring Cove Beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``... was also a street musician, composer, playwright, poet,
boatwoman, restoration specialist, organic gardener, political
activist, breath-work facilitator and prolific artist in a variety
of media.
</P>
<P>
   ``She won the Hometown USA Video Festival, the nation's highest
award for public access television, for her drumming video,
`Weaving the Matrix'.''
</P>
<P>
   The obit ends with a request that instead of flowers, donations
be directed to a fund to help provide low-cost practice and
recording space for local musicians.
</P>
<P>
   The reader is sending a small check. And so am I.
</P>
<P>
   Tribute to a woman who had the courage to chase her dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
