<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PENALTIES HAUNTING `PROGRAMS' 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wheels are coming loose at many so-called programs. College
basketball teams are hoping to hold parts together with chewing gum
and baling wire and appeals and briefs just to get through the
national tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After that, they'll just let attrition and penalties and
ambition and professional money take their natural course. Since
undergraduates started flocking to the crass-but-honest dollar
standard of the National Basketball Association, college basketball
has become a year-by-year proposition, now operating on day-by-day
eligibility bulletins.
</P>
<P>
   Or, sometimes it is even minute-by-minute. Tuesday night,
shortly before before St. John's took on Seton Hall in Madison
Square Garden, Erick Barkley was suspended by St. John's,
essentially on the orders of the National Collegiate Athletic
Association. This was the second time this season that Barkley had
been suspended for violating financial rules. St. John's said it
would seek his immediate reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was originally suspended for two games for trading cars
with somebody who was identified as a family friend but who also
had ties to a major summer basketball league in New York. This time
Barkley was suspended for apparently having accepted between $2,500
and $4,000 to help pay the hefty tuition at a Maine prep school he
had attended for a year. The tuition had been paid by a committee
at Riverside Church that maintains a powerful amateur basketball
program partly underwritten by Ernie Lorch, a wealthy New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Why Lorch and Riverside thought the payments _ which are illegal
_ would never be discovered is hard to fathom.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's had reported the tuition payment itself, and was
hoping for a light treatment by the NCAA. The penalty had to come
soon because the Big East tournament begins next week, and the NCAA
tournament the week after that, and then Barkley is liable to be
off to the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's took a seven-game winning streak into Tuesday night's
game, having beaten Duke last Saturday, with another Barkley
scandal already hanging over it. Coach Mike Krzyzewski, appealed to
the Duke students to spare Barkley from their witty heckling,
which, by and large, they did.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski almost never has to deal with indiscretions by his
Duke players, but he did feel a sense of vulnerability last spring
when three players departed with eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   At other schools, college players were undergoing various
investigations, allegations, suspicions, rumors, confessions, mea
culpas and nolo contenderes and all that other good legal stuff
that makes big-time college basketball such a wholesome sight.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to make any kind of wage for their labors, the players
are hounded by the NCAA for every dime or favor they have accepted,
in all their youthful innocence, you understand.
</P>
<P>
   This has popped up at Auburn, Cincinnati, UCLA and Michigan,
while Connecticut has had its own discipline problems. The latest
incident was at Auburn, where the star forward Chris Porter has
been suspended for taking $2,500 from a sports agent. The story
coming out of Auburn is that Porter took the money to help keep his
mother from being evicted, which could very well be true, but
Porter is not likely to get any mercy points from the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn officials are now saying that they have been keeping
track of ``suspicious people'' who hang around the team hotels,
trying to do ``favors'' for the players _ no surprise there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sick of people who prey on young people and hit them at a
weak moment,'' said Cliff Ellis, the Auburn coach, surely not
referring to the high-minded practice of recruiting young players
for college.
</P>
<P>
   Many people want to do favors for basketball stars _ get them to
camps, get them into so-called amateur programs, get them into
college, alleviate problems at home.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, DerMarr Johnson of Cincinnati was suspended for
one game by the NCAA for accepting $7,000 from an Amateur Athletic
Union coach to attend the same prep school that Barkley went to.
JaRon Rush, the star at UCLA, took $6,525 from an amateur coach,
but when Rush agreed to pay the money back, the NCAA shortened his
suspension to nine games, making him eligible to play again
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Given the hardships and realities of life, it is no wonder why
players might reach out and accept tuition money or rent money. The
NCAA tries to maintain an amateur look, but it is a weary, grinding
business, and it is hard to imagine that anybody has any heart for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Most coaches just want to keep the vehicle barreling toward
March Madness, and deal with the details down the line. How long
can this system survive? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
