<SLUG> BC-COMPAQ-DEFECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPAQ ADMITS 1.7 MILLION PRESARIOS HAVE DEFECT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Compaq Computer Corp. has conceded that at least 1.7 million
of its Presario computers have a defect similar to one that
prompted the Toshiba Corp. to agree to a $2.1 billion settlement in
a class-action suit last October.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq, which is being sued by the same lawyers who won the
Toshiba settlement, posted software that fixes the problem on its
Web site Friday. It also began sending postcards to owners of the
affected computers notifying them of the software, which they can
obtain for free from Compaq's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokesman for the Houston-based computer maker said in a
statement that its computers ``work as intended,'' and that Compaq,
which has sold 60 million computers, has never received a single
report of the problem occurring.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq had denied its products had the same problem as
Toshiba's. It had said, and continues to say, that it would fight
the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But a letter entered into the court records showed that Compaq
has engaged in settlement discussions with the plaintiffs. The
letter, written Jan. 5 by Steven M. Zagar, a lawyer representing
Compaq, said that the computer maker believed it had sold 1.7
million Presario computers with the problem. Zagar wrote that the
information was being provided ``as part of our ongoing settlement
discussions.''
</P>
<P>
   Toshiba shocked the computer industry by agreeing to a $147.5
million settlement because it, like Compaq, had maintained that no
customers had ever complained of a problem as a result of the
defect. The defect, which the industry has known about for years,
occurred in a chip that controls the floppy disk drive and can
cause errors in recording information. Toshiba contended that the
error can occur only in rare circumstances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
