<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: SOUTHWEST AIRLINES' SUCCESS WITH ONLINE BOOKINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (duplication warning: also sent with `t' code)  
(bl) 
 By JOE SHARKEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines sent an e-rocket through the travel industry
this week when it announced that a quarter of its passenger revenue
last month came from bookings on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The figure caught even the most enthusiastic boosters of online
travel somewhat by surprise. ``It's pretty amazing,'' said Philip
Wolf, president and chief executive of PhoCusWright Inc., a major
online travel consultant. ``We probably would have guessed it would
have been around 15 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like pure number-crunching, but travel is now
among the top money generators in Internet retail commerce.
Southwest also said that its online passenger revenue was up 140
percent, to more than $250 million, in the fourth quarter of 1999.
Its galloping Web fortunes are being welcomed in the fiercely
competitive Internet travel industry as validation of the most
optimistic projections for online booking, which analysts estimate
will exceed $30 billion annually in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest, which consistently gets high marks for service and
reliability in surveys of business travelers, is by far the leader
among the world's airlines in online bookings, Wolf said. Most
major airlines are currently selling 3 percent to 8 percent of
their seats online, according to industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf credited Southwest's simple, user-friendly Web site design
as a major reason for the surge in business. ``If Southwest can't
sell travel on their Web site, nobody can,'' he said. ``They have
the simplest, easiest price and schedule paradigm in the
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the airline industry, carriers are investing heavily
in their own Web sites to compete with the big full-service
third-party sites like Travelocity.com and Expedia .com, as well as
literally dozens of other sites, some of which are geared for niche
markets, offering, for example, the lowest last-minute fares for
those on a flexible schedule, or the lowest fares or hotel rates
for a specific group of cities. At the same time, other companies
like American Express, GetThere.com and even big travel agencies
like Rosenbluth International have been spending heavily to design
custom Web sites for corporations to book their own travel directly
from airlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southwest raises the bar for everybody,'' Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, as analysts have tried to get their arms
around the evolving world of online travel, studies have shown that
one of the main drags on the business has been a widespread
consumer reluctance to entrust credit card information to an online
business. That is changing, however, Wolf said. ``Credit card
security is rapidly losing steam in terms of being a major barrier
to online booking,'' he said. ``Consumers are much more trusting.''
</P>
<P>
   The outlook, however, isn't all rosy. ``If I were an online
travel business, I would be more worried about privacy issues in
general than about basic credit card security,'' he said. In fact,
he tells people in the industry to brace themselves for negative
public reaction to security breaches involving online companies
that invade customer privacy by tracking Web activity and selling
information on personal preferences and online purchases. ``I
believe there will be a negative impact on the industry this year
over those kinds of security breaches,'' he said. ``But I see it as
more of a pothole than a detour.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of online travel, the big Web site that is being
developed by Continental Airlines, United Airlines, Delta Air Lines
and Northwest Airlines _ with 23 other carriers participating _ is
still on schedule to start ``late in the second quarter,''
according to a spokeswoman for Boston Consulting Group, which is
managing the project.
</P>
<P>
   But the big question is: what are they calling this thing? One
hot tip among analysts is that the site is code-named ``T-2,''
which is said to mean ``Terminate Travelocity.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, the spokeswoman said. ``We call it the travel industry
portal. It's kind of awkward to talk about this because it really
doesn't have an official name yet.''
</P>
<P>
   How did the T-2 confusion originate? ``Very early on, we called
it T-2, which meant travel, second generation,'' she said. ``Some
tech analysts picked it up, and the name has sort of stuck. We
don't use it anymore. I think some competitors have probably spread
that rumor to convey the Darth Vader image.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
