<SLUG> BC-RELIANCE-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHIEF EXECUTIVE QUITS AT RELIANCE GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID LEONHARDT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Saul P. Steinberg, one of the best-known corporate
raiders of the 1980s, stepped down Tuesday as the chief executive
of Reliance Group Holdings, a troubled insurance company that
announced another quarter of disappointing earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said that it had reached an agreement to sell
one of its healthiest businesses to Travelers Property Casualty for
$580 million to shore up its balance sheet.
</P>
<P>
   But investors, who bid down Reliance's shares $1.25, to $4.125,
remained disappointed that the company was not taking more
aggressive steps, said David Schiff, the editor of Schiff's
Insurance Observer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Robert S. Miller, a turnaround specialist who
joined Reliance as president only three months ago, quit Tuesday
and accepted a job as an adviser to Aetna's new chief executive,
William H. Donaldson. George R. Baker, who had been a special
assistant to Steinberg, will become president and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg, 60, will remain chairman and will focus on the
company's e-commerce strategy, including Cybercomp, which uses the
Internet to help sell workers' compensation insurance, said Lowell
C. Freiberg, Reliance's chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the central deal-makers of the 1980s, Steinberg used
Reliance to make unsuccessful bids to take over Chemical Bank and
Walt Disney and bought stakes in UAL as well as other insurance
companies. Corporate governance experts regularly criticized him
for the large salary he paid himself, which often exceeded that of
executives at larger insurance companies and which came on top of
the dividend Steinberg received as one of Reliance's large
shareholders. In 1998, he made $8.5 million in salary and bonus.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, Steinberg's star faded as Reliance had
one setback after another. Its attempt to expand its commercial
insurance business did not fully succeed, and a partnership on
workers' compensation reinsurance ended badly. Reliance remains
more heavily leveraged than many rivals, Schiff said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Reliance posted a fourth-quarter loss of $123 million,
or $1.08 a diluted share, compared with a $31 million gain, or 26
cents a share, in the quarter a year earlier. The company lost $311
million in 1999 as insurance prices fell, compared with a profit of
$326 million in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The company announced Tuesday that it was suspending the payment
of dividends to shareholders and would consider paying them again
once it had refinanced its debt.
</P>
<P>
   But Freiberg said the company was now in a stronger position to
do better the next few years. In recent months, Reliance has
settled a lawsuit it had filed against one of its partners in the
workers' compensation arrangement. It also gained a five-month
extension from its banks on $238 million in loans that had been due
on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers Property Casualty, a unit of Citigroup, is buying
Reliance's surety unit, which helps insure against construction
delays. The $300 million gain that Reliance will realize from the
sale will help increase its capital _ its investment holdings minus
its anticipated claim payments _ to $1.7 billion from $1.2 billion
at the start of 2000, Freiberg said. Investment gains have
accounted for the remaining growth.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the company's debt and recent losses, insurance
rating agencies have begun reviewing Reliance's rating to determine
whether it should be lowered. A.B. Best said Tuesday that it was
upgrading Reliance from ``under review with negative implications''
to ``under review with developing implications'' because of the
improved balance sheet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
