<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HODGES-FAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALL'S SHUTOUT HAS HODGES FANS UPSET 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By COREY KILGANNON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once again, as they say, they wuz robbed.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime Brooklyn Dodgers fans have been pushing in recent years
for the baseball Hall of Fame to induct Gil Hodges, the team's
beloved first baseman who later, as manager, guided the 1969 Mets
to a World Series championship. But Tuesday, they learned that
Hodges had been passed over again.
</P>
<P>
   Wait till next year?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, fans of Hodges have been doing just that for the last
19 years, and many said that this year, with its lack of strong
contenders, was their idol's best chance to get into the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Many fan organizations and even Hodges' widow, Joan, campaigned
tirelessly to foster a groundswell of support to sway the members
of the Hall of Fame's Veterans Committee, which selects new
members.
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 years after he last played in Ebbets Field, Hodges
still has a particularly strong following in the city, which has
named a bridge, a Little League, and a school after him. His wife
continues to live in the Brooklyn home the couple bought 40 years
ago, and Tuesday, family members gathered at her Brooklyn house to
commiserate.
</P>
<P>
   As the news spread that he was not voted in, Brooklyn Dodgers
fans registered their outrage by flooding Internet message boards
and calling radio talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought this year it was finally gonna happen, because the
field was the weakest,'' said Marty Adler, president of the
Brooklyn Dodgers Hall of Fame, which has a display in the Brooklyn
Historical Society in Brooklyn Heights.
</P>
<P>
   The group sends a quarterly Brooklyn Dodgers newsletter to 5,000
subscribers. Last fall, Adler, 63, sent 5,000 ``Cooperstown Needs
Gil Hodges'' bumper stickers along with the newsletters.
</P>
<P>
   Proving that there is no fury like a Brooklyn Dodgers fan
scorned, Hodges fans filled Web sites, Internet message boards and
chat rooms with elaborate theories on why their hero is being
snubbed by the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph R. D'Agostin, who runs the Committee to Elect Gil Hodges
Into Baseball's Hall of Fame, in Norwalk, Conn., has a Web site
dedicated to Hodges' induction. He sent out mass e-mailings to the
network of hundreds of Hodges fans, urging them to write to the
hall. ``We want Gil to get his day, and we'll keep badgering the
committee until he gets it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, Hodges was in tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an absolute disgrace,'' she said. `I'm in shock. Gil's
had more votes than anyone in history that's in the hall. I want an
explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges, 73, began a campaign over the last year to get her
husband elected, she said, including holding news conferences with
the Brooklyn borough president, Howard Golden, and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Marino Amoruso, a Hodges biographer, called the news ``a
monumental glaring injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New York did have better ballplayers, but none more beloved,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges was 19 in 1943 when he played his first major-league game
with the Dodgers, and won the gold glove for outstanding defensive
play the first three years it was awarded. He played in more World
Series games at first base (38) than any player in the major
leagues. He died of a heart attack in 1972 at the age of 47.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gillie was beloved by everybody from Brooklyn,'' said the
former pitcher Ralph Branca, who roomed with Hodges when both
played for the Dodgers in the '40s and '50s. ``I'm very
disappointed, because he looked like he really had a shot this
year.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
