<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2587 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH01-COX     02-29 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush courts Catholics in pass through Ohio
 &HT;    By William Hershey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTERVILLE, Ohio _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush barnstormed
through Ohio on Tuesday, blasting away at Arizona Sen. John McCain
and casting himself as the compassionate, tax-slashing reformer who
can unite the Republicans and win the White House in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I proudly stand before you as a uniter, not a divider,'' Bush
said to the approval of 2,000 cheering students and adults at
Westerville North High School in this Columbus suburb. He also
campaigned at the Catholic-sponsored Fatima Community Center on
Cleveland's east side and at a packed evening rally at Memorial
Hall in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   At the Cincinnati rally, Bush told 700 pompon-waving supporters
that he appeared headed for a big victory in Virginia and that next
Tuesday Ohio Republicans would have a chance to keep the momentum
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Buckeye State is going to send a signal that his nation is
ready for a fresh start,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also met privately with a small group of families,
including two from the Miami Valley who are in disputes with their
health insurers over coverage for their children. The plight of one
family, Ed and Lydia Bogan of West Alexandria, has caught the
attention of the presidential candidates. The health company
refuses to pay for the formula the family says is necessary to keep
their daughter Kaitlynn alive. She cannot eat normal food.
</P>
<P>
   During his Westerville speech, Bush named McCain as the
``divider,'' but lashed out frequently during the day at the
Arizona senator for phone calls the McCain campaign made last week
in Michigan, reminding voters of Bush's visit to Bob Jones
University, whose leaders have espoused anti-Catholic views.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign at first said it didn't make the calls but
later acknowledged responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   At a morning news conference in Cleveland, Bush said the McCain
campaign was making the same kind of calls in advance of Tuesday's
voting. Bush said the calls label him an ``anti-Catholic bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't appreciate the politics that still goes on by Senator
McCain,'' Bush told reporters after visiting a Catholic-run
community center in Cleveland. ``It's the politics of saying one
thing and doing another.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said, however, he regrets not using his visit to the
university to speak out against anti-Catholic bias.
</P>
<P>
   The invocation at the Cincinnati rally was given by the Rev.
John Putka, who teaches political science at the University of
Dayton. He attended the rally with about 15 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe George Bush is anti-Catholic,'' Putka said. He
said, however, his vote is undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he considered ``Clintonesque'' about McCain, Bush
said that McCain ``demonizes people'' and holds them up to scorn.
</P>
<P>
   He was still fuming when the subject came up again in a meeting
with Ohio reporters after the Westerville rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is that really what we want, name calling and slanderous
campaigning?'' the governor asked.
</P>
<P>
   He brushed aside complaints from McCain about phone calls that
evangelist Pat Robertson made on Bush's behalf, blasting McCain.
The calls were not paid for by the Bush campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like me complaining about the Sierra Club doing something
against me. Therefore, I'm going to do something against my
opponent. These are independent expenditures over which I have no
control,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor sidestepped a direct answer to a question about
whether his visit to the Fatima Community Center was designed to
shore up support from Ohio Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   He said he came to the center to ``herald the greatness of
America.''
</P>
<P>
   LaJean Ray-McNair, center director, said she didn't think the
visit would have been scheduled if the flap over Bob Jones
University had not occurred. Nevertheless, Ray-McNair said she was
glad to have the governor there to discuss education, foster care,
housing and related issue.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign aides said the visit was scheduled last Saturday but
that the center had been included on a list of possible sites three
months ago
</P>
<P>
   What campaign aides said could be Bush's last Ohio visit before
next Tuesday's primary here came as an Ohio Poll, conducted by the
University of Cincinnati, showed him leading McCain by 17 points,
53 percent to 36 percent. The lead is half the 34 point lead from a
poll taken earlier in February, but Bush still was pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm winning by double digits because I've got a positive
message,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   All day that message echoed the ``compassionate conservatism''
that Bush has tried to make the trademark of his campaign, uniting
government with faith-based institutions to improve lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the American dream to touch every willing heart,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That touching can come with Americans paying lower taxes, he
said. Taxpayers, not the government, own the federal government
budget surplus from which a tax cut would come, he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said Bush's tax proposals are irresponsible and would
benefit only the rich. Not so, said Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to give everyone who pays taxes in America a tax
cut,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the topic of education, he said he would leave it to the
states to decide whether to have school voucher programs. But he
said, for schools that don't achieve success, he would take the
federal money they receive for special programs and give it
directly parents.
</P>
<P>
   The midday rally here showcased Bush's strong support from Ohio
Republicans. Gov. Bob Taft, House Speaker JoAnn Davidson of
Reynoldsburg, Senate President Richard Finan of Cincinnati and
state Treasurer J. Kenneth Blackwell all came to cheer on Bush, who
faces McCain in Ohio's Republican primary next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. John Kasich (R-Westerville), who withdrew from the
presidential race and threw his support to Bush, warmed up his
hometown audience for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   It was Taft, however, who predicted that Bush would prevail in
his second encounter in a Midwestern industrial state, reversing
his loss last week in Michigan to McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also have a chance to send a message to that state up north
... The Buckeye State loves George Bush,'' Taft said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
