<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIALLO-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INQUIRY OF ACQUITTED OFFICERS TO TAKE MONTHS FOR POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By KEVIN FLYNN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One of the four officers acquitted in the slaying of
Amadou Diallo has returned to work, but police officials predicted
Tuesday that it would be months before the Police Department could
complete an internal investigation into whether the officers should
remain on the force.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Edward McMellon became the first of the officers to
return when he reported to his desk job in a Brooklyn police office
Monday, said his lawyer, Stephen Worth.
</P>
<P>
   None of the officers, who had been involved in aggressive street
patrols prior to Diallo's death, have said whether they would seek
to return to full duty, although the lawyer for Officer Sean
Carroll said he believed his client hoped to resume his career as a
patrolman.
</P>
<P>
   To remain on the force, Carroll and his colleagues _ McMellon,
Richard Murphy and Kenneth Boss _ would have to pass an internal
review to determine whether their conduct in the shooting of Diallo
violated any department policies, such as a guideline that requires
officers to identify themselves adequately during street
encounters.
</P>
<P>
   But that review will not begin, police officials said, until
federal officials decide whether to file new criminal charges
against the officers. The Justice Department has said it is
reviewing the evidence in the case to determine whether the
officers violated Diallo's civil rights when they fired 41 times at
him as he stood unarmed in the vestibule of his Bronx apartment
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been requested by the federal investigators not to
initiate the firearms discharge review investigation because they
may be doing their own investigation and they do not want any
compelled testimony,'' said Deputy Chief Thomas Fahey, a department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers can be compelled to answer questions _ or face
administrative penalties _ in internal disciplinary matters, but
the statements they make under those conditions cannot be used
against them in a criminal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said it would likely be months before the federal
review and a subsequent department investigation could be
completed.
</P>
<P>
   If the officers are found guilty of misconduct, they could face
penalties from reprimand to dismissal. Currently, they are each
charged administratively with ``prohibited conduct,'' based on the
original murder and reckless endangerment charges on which they
were indicted. Those administrative charges may be amended or
dropped as the investigation proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, the officers will remain on modified duty, in
which they are paid but are assigned to desk jobs, without the
right to carry a badge or a gun. The other officers, aside from
McMellon, are expected to return to work in a few days or weeks,
their lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike criminal trials, in which the evidence must show the
defendants are guilty beyond a reasonable doubt, in police
administrative proceedings the department must show that defendants
violated a policy based only on a preponderance of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confident that that review will find the officers
blameless in the same manner that the criminal trial did,'' Worth
said. ``The facts remain the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the same unit of Internal Affairs investigators,
known as Group 54, that handled the criminal investigation was
likely to handle the upcoming administrative review. The unit will
try to determine whether the officers properly followed guidelines
and training bulletins that outline the tactics they should use
during street encounters and that govern the situations in which it
is permissible to fire their guns.
</P>
<P>
   The unit's findings will then be presented to a firearms
discharge review board, a five-member panel led by Chief of
Department Joseph Dunne, officials said. If the officers are found
to have followed procedures, the current charges against them would
likely be dropped, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   If the review board were to find that the officers engaged in
misconduct, their cases would be forwarded to the department's
in-house prosecutor for a disciplinary trial, in which the verdict
would be rendered by an administrative law judge. The judge's
decision in such a case would then be forwarded to Police
Commissioner Howard Safir, who would make the final decision as to
any disciplinary action, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Safir has spoken in recent days of his compassion for
what he described as the trauma the officers have suffered through,
he has withheld comment on whether they deserve to remain on the
force, citing the pending investigation.
</P>
<P>
   It is clearly in the officers' favor that they were acquitted at
the criminal trial, but the outcome can be different during a
disciplinary proceeding, in part because of the different standard
of proof.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent case, Officer Michael Meyer was acquitted of
attempted murder in the shooting of a squeegee man in the Bronx but
was later found guilty at a departmental trial of using excessive
force. He was dismissed on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A discussion of possible disciplinary charges would become
unnecessary if the officers resigned, as the Bronx district
attorney, Robert T. Johnson, has suggested.But none of the officers
have indicated plans to do so.
</P>
<P>
   And Officer Carroll's lawyer, John Patten, said his client had
indicated he wanted to continue on the force, despite the angry
protests and threats that surfaced since the acquittals. ``He did
not indicate any desire to leave and he hopes to get back to full
duty,'' Patten said.
</P>
<P>
   James Culleton, the lawyer for Murphy, said he would have a hard
time advising his client to make a similar choice. ``He has to make
a decision on what he wants to do,'' Culleton said. ``But if I was
in his position, I would not want to be a police officer because
you would always be second-guessing yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2215EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
