<HEADLINE>
MIRAGE REJECTS TAKEOVER BID BY MGM GRAND  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mirage Resorts Inc. rejected a $3.3 billion takeover bid Tuesday
from its casino rival, MGM Grand Inc., as inadequate and
opportunistic, and it put in place a ``poison pill'' takeover
defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Mirage, which is run by Stephen A. Wynn, said it would be
willing to consider a transaction at a higher price ``that
recognizes the real value of Mirage Resorts.'' It did not specify
the price.
</P>
<P>
   That statement could be merely an attempt to mollify Mirage
shareholders who have been angered by Mirage's low stock price. But
it appears it is now up to MGM Grand, which is controlled by the
billionaire Kirk Kerkorian, to make a higher bid. It is also
possible that other companies, particularly Harrah's Entertainment,
will enter negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was encouraged by the fact that they are willing to discuss
a transaction,'' said David Anders, an analyst with Credit Suisse
First Boston. ``There was a chance that this would be just
dismissed out of hand.''
</P>
<P>
   The takeover defense would give shareholders the right to buy
substantially more stock at a discount if a person or group
acquired 10 percent or more of Mirage's stock or began a tender
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, MGM Grand offered to pay $17 a share, either in cash
or a combination of cash and stock, for Mirage shares, which had
been trading at about $11. The combined company would be a
powerhouse on the Las Vegas Strip and the second-largest gambling
company in the nation behind Park Place Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn was expected to reject the offer and try to hold onto his
empire, setting up a possible clash between two titans of the
casino industry, although MGM Grand has said that it wants a
friendly merger.
</P>
<P>
   After the Mirage board met Tuesday at the company's Bellagio
Hotel in Las Vegas, it issued a statement saying that the bid had
come at a time when casino company stocks were weak, Mirage's in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   But, the statement said, ``Mirage would be willing to consider a
transaction which would fairly reflect the long-term values
inherent in the Mirage properties, brand name and good will, rather
than an opportunistic bid which is timed to maximize values for the
bidder.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirage shares fell 18.75 cents, to $15.75, Tuesday, while MGM
Grand declined 31.25 cents, to $19.875. Mirage issued its statement
after the close of trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
