<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-REGIONAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING STUDYING 70-SEAT VERSION OF 717 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. is studying a possible 70-seat version
of its new 717 which, if developed, would out the aerospace giant
smack in the middle of new and risky territory _ the hotly
contested market for regional jets.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the 100-seat boundary has separated the two biggest
guys in the industry _ Boeing and Airbus _ from the smaller
regional jetmakers such as Bombardier of Canada, Embraer of Brazil
and Fairchild of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   But with the regional market booming, Boeing is at least
exploring the possibility of dramatically shrinking the 717-200,
which can seat around 117 passengers in two classes.
</P>
<P>
   Although analysts believe the company will decide against making
any such move, detailed configuration studies are under way for a
shortened 717, said Thomas Croslin, the program's chief engineer in
Long Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to determine if it needs to be 80 or 70 seats,''
he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Boeing's marketing people are conducting a
broad-ranging study of the regional market, Croslin said. The
study, which will make recommendations, should be finished before
mid year.
</P>
<P>
   Shrinking a commercial jetliner has been done successfully by
Airbus and Boeing with the A320 and 737 respectively. But it is
much more difficult to shrink a plane and keep it as efficient as
the original design since it will carry fewer revenue-producing
passengers and less cargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trying to take an airplane that is designed to carry more than
106 passengers and shrink it down to a 70-seater would give you a
plane that is not optimized for efficiency,'' said Paul Nisbet,
aerospace analyst with JSA Research in Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would seem to me that Boeing's studies would rule this out.
I would be very surprised if they went ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing inherited the 717 program when it acquired McDonnell
Douglas in 1997. The 717 was then known as the MD-95 and was
developed as a replacement plane for older DC-9s still in service
with many airlines around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing executives have said before they are considering a ``717
family'' consisting of the current 717-200 as well as a stretched
version that would seat upwards of 125 passengers and a shorter
model that would seat from 80 to 90 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   But they have not previously discussed, at least publicly, a
possible 70-seater.
</P>
<P>
   Croslin said Boeing's goal is to win 1,000 orders for the
717-200, and about 500 orders for the two variants, assuming they
are developed.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, Boeing has received only 130 firm orders for
the 717-200. Of those, 50 came from launch customer AirTran
(formerly ValueJet) and 50 came from TWA. Each airline also placed
options for 50 more.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing has an aggressive cost-cutting program under way that
could make a 70-seater competitive, Croslin said. The goal, he
said, is to reduce production costs up to 10 percent by plane
number 100; 20 percent by plane number 200; and 30 percent by plane
number 300.
</P>
<P>
   Lean-manufacturing programs are in place at Boeing's production
factory in Long Beach, and the company is working closely with
suppliers to get their costs down, Croslin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have teams out all over the world'' Croslin said. ``I have
a team over in Italy this week. We will have teams in Japan and
Taiwan next week.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Boeing is able to meet its cost reduction goals,
analysts are not sure the company should even be thinking about
entering the regional market with a 70-seater.
</P>
<P>
   The competition could not be hotter. Regional manufacturers had
a record 669 firm orders in 1999, with conditional orders for 568
more planes.
</P>
<P>
   At last year's Paris Air show, it was not Boeing or Airbus that
announced the most new orders in terms of dollar value, but Embraer
and Bombardier.
</P>
<P>
   Fairchild Aerospace is also a big player in the regional market.
</P>
<P>
   All three are producing 70-seat jets, or plan to do so. They are
looking at stretched versions that seat more than 100 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question for Boeing is can they be sure the market is
sufficient to support another aircraft in that size class,'' said
Peter Jacobs, analyst with the Ragen Mackenzie Group in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Nisbet is more blunt. He noted that the regional jet
manufacturers are heavily subsidized by their respective
governments, which would make it tough for Boeing to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Only one regional airplane is produced in the United States, he
noted. That's a 19-seater from Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only one that has been able to coexist and make money
against these subsidized planes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Nisbet does see possibilities for a 717 that would seat from
85 to 90 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see perhaps a family of the 717 from about 85 seats up
to 125 or more on the other end,'' he said. ``I can understand
that. But going down to 70 seats seems like a huge stretch, or in
this case a shrink. Why they want to take the 717 down to 70 seats
and get right in the middle of a hornet's nest I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
