<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2594 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-RENZO-PIANO-ARCH-2TAK     02-29 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENZO-PIANO-ARCH-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOWCASING A RISE FROM REBELLION TO RESPECTABILITY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Renzo Piano chuckled as he remembered how he and Richard
Rogers were ``young boys, really young and quite bad boys'' in 1971
when they won the architecture competition for the Georges Pompidou
Center with a design that they considered a parody of technology.
</P>
<P>
   Their aim was to create a sort of anti-monument, a cultural
center that was anything but institutional in appearance, and the
proof of their success was the outcry that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even now, at 62, Piano, a good-natured Italian, seemed
amazed that France allowed two young foreigners _ he was 33 and his
British partner was 37 _ to challenge the sober 18th-century stone
facades of eastern Paris with an immense metallic structure
variously described (by its critics) as a refinery or an ocean
liner and (by its architects) as ``a Jules Verne spaceship that
can't fly.'' An international jury chose the design, but the French
government nonetheless accepted it.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Pompidou was very courageous, that's for sure,''
Piano recalled with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that was almost 30 years ago, and time has a way of
spawning respectability. The Pompidou Center finally opened in
1977, it proved immensely popular and today it (italics)is(end
italics) a monument. Piano in turn made his name, his long black
beard gave way to a salt-and-pepper stubble and he collected
architectural honors, including the highly regarded Pritzker Prize
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   So it seems altogether appropriate that the center should now
play host to the largest retrospective to date of his prolific
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``This exhibition is a bit like an incestuous relationship with
the building,'' Piano said while guiding a visitor around the show,
which runs here through March 20. ``It will then go to the Neue
Nationalgalerie in Berlin, Mies van der Rohe's building. There it
will be like going into a Greek temple.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, which includes scores of models, drawings,
videos and photographs of Piano's principal projects, will be on
display in Berlin from June 1 to Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Berlin's interest in his work is hardly accidental. The Renzo
Piano Building Workshop, as his Paris- and Genoa-based practice is
called, has recently given new form to what was the prewar heart of
Berlin by designing both the overall plan and eight of the
buildings of the Potsdamer Platz, the largest new urban complex to
rise in the reunified German capital.
</P>
<P>
   But if the first exhibit in the Paris show is dedicated to the
Pompidou Center, it is not only because this project began Piano's
international career. For the last few years he has again been busy
here, building a reconstitution of Brancusi's studio at one end of
the sloping plaza in front of the center, then overseeing
repainting of the entire structure and, most recently, playing a
central role in reorganizing and renovating the center. After 27
months' work, the center reopened on Jan. 1, with additional space
given over to its public library and modern art museum.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Piano is happy with everything that has changed. Both
he and Mr. Rogers have criticized the decision to end free access
by escalator to a viewing platform overlooking Paris. On the other
hand, Piano has suggested, only half-jokingly, that the center
close every 25 years so its function can be rethought. And the fact
that it can be easily rearranged, he noted, is a tribute to its
flexibility. Indeed, one new space is the 15,000-square-foot south
gallery that houses his show.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition's curator, Olivier Cinqualbre, who has worked
closely with Piano and his workshop, has chosen to present the
architect's projects not chronologically but rather around three
broad themes: invention, urbanism and sensitivity. Models and other
illustrations of completed buildings are spread over some 20
tables, each hanging by wires from the ceiling, while a half-dozen
wall panels around the gallery show drawings of projects still at
the design stage, among them new buildings for Harvard University's
art museums and for the Nasher Sculpture Center in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't show everything, we can't say everything,''
Cinqualbre explained. ``Rather, we want to show the visitor as
clearly as possible how Renzo and his workshop work and have worked
for 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Piano likes to describe the exhibition as ``the imaginary
city,'' which seems reasonable enough because it contains examples
of just about everything found in a modern metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   In the section on invention, for instance, there are displays of
the San Nicola soccer stadium in Bari, Italy; of the milelong
terminal at Kansai International Airport in Osaka, Japan; of a
commercial center in Nola, outside Naples, inspired by the conical
shape of Mount Vesuvius; of a gigantic shell-like church being
built at the shrine to the Italian mystic Padre Pio in San Giovanni
Rotonda, Italy; and of office and residential towers overlooking
the Botanical Gardens in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   The section on urbanism naturally includes the Pompidou Center
and the Potsdamer Platz, both catalysts for urban transformation.
In the case of the renovation of the old port in Piano's hometown,
Genoa, to mark the 500th anniversary of the voyage of another
native son, Christopher Columbus, urban improvement was the
principal objective.
</P>
<P>
   With the old Fiat-Lingotto factory in Turin, Italy, the aim was
to preserve the structure of an admired 1925 industrial building
while converting its space into a convention center and hotel.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The section on sensitivity presumably covers those projects
closest to Piano's heart. One of these is the widely acclaimed
museum that he built in Houston in the mid-1980's for the art
patron Dominique de Menil, to house the Menil Collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was very much about atmosphere,'' Piano said, standing
beside a model of the museum, ``trying to balance the presence of
art and the beauty of the building. Some people believe that to
make a good building for art, you have to make white boxes. This is
absolutely not true. You kill art by making a neutral building.
Others believe you must compete with the art, and I think that is
also very wrong. So you have to find the balance. What we worked on
here was the idea of creating space with a lot of character, not
for formal reasons, but for immaterial reasons, such as the sense
of lightness, the sense of transparency.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, this same approach was used in his elegantly
simple design of a museum for the Beyeler Foundation in Basel,
Switzerland, with its naturally lighted galleries and its large
windows looking out onto the surrounding countryside.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, the project that has most excited Piano is one
that even his closest admirers have probably seen only in models
and photographs: the Jean-Marie Tjibaou Cultural Center in Noumea
on New Caledonia, a French-run island in the Pacific. Commissioned
by the French government, Piano took his inspiration from
traditional Kanak tribal huts and designed eight semicircular
wooden structures, varying in height from 60 to 90 feet, that seem
to float over low-lying exhibition spaces.
</P>
<P>
   The building looks like nothing Piano has designed before. On
the other hand, even with wooden models giving a certain uniformity
to the exhibition, what is most striking is the absence of a Renzo
Piano ``look.'' While Rogers echoed the Pompidou Center in his
Lloyd's of London building in the mid-1980s, Piano set off
simultaneously in several directions.
</P>
<P>
   His upbringing offers one explanation. His father was a Genoa
builder and, although young Renzo chose architecture, he always
felt close to the crafts and materials used in construction. Thus,
unlike architects with an artistic background who are often more
concerned about how buildings look, he is among those who approach
architecture through engineering or construction and are more
interested in how buildings are made. So a ``look'' has never
interested Piano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think style is a very dangerous concept,'' he said. ``It's a
narcissistic attitude. Why should you worry about style? Worry
about coherence. That is a better idea. Style is like a rubber
stamp, a designer label; it becomes quite commercial. Even artists
like Giacometti, in his later years, he was trapped by people
telling him, `I want this.' So style becomes a limitation, a sort
of golden cage, in which you worry about being recognized. What I
like about the Menil Collection is that the building is a portrait
of the client, not of the architect.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, reassuringly, he seems all too aware of the potentially
dangerous power enjoyed by architects.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a bad writer, no one reads your book,'' he said.
``If you're a bad musician, no one listens to your music. But if
you're a bad architect, you impose something on a city forever. I
believe architecture can transform life, it is a utopia, it can
bring lightness and beauty and poetry. But the architect has a
great responsibility. Aesthetics and ethics are very much
connected, but I didn't understand that when I was 30 or when I was
40 or when I was 50.''
</P>
<P>
   Having caused a furor with the Pompidou Center in his 30s, Piano
now looks back with some alarm at how little he knew at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, ``my feeling is that you should live as
an architect only after you are 50 because for the first 50 years
you just learn. I am not joking. You learn and you make so many
mistakes. Then, when you reach 50, maybe you can work properly for
50 years.'' He paused to light his pipe and smiled. ``And after
that maybe you have another 50 years to teach other people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
