<SLUG> BC-BAUER01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bauer asks McCain to ease GOP right
 &HT;    By Jim Bebbington
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Former presidential candidate Gary Bauer,
stumping for Arizona Sen. John McCain in Dayton on Tuesday, said
McCain needs to reassure religious right voters that his attacks on
Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell Monday do not distance him from the
party's conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the confusion about (Monday's) speech he needs to
very directly, and very openly, reach out to pro-family and
pro-life voters,'' Bauer said at the Crowne Plaza Hotel in downtown
Dayton. ``Otherwise, they will be confused about where he really
stands.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer dropped out of the presidential race and endorsed McCain,
he said, not because of issues, but because McCain has a better
chance to beat Vice President Al Gore in November's general
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faced with two candidates I think are virtually alike on most
of the social issues, I decided to go with the candidate I thought
could most likely win in November and end what has been a very
difficult and, in some cases, embarassing eight years for the
United States,'' Bauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering a speech in Virginia on Monday, McCain called Moral
Majority founder Jerry Falwell and Christian Coalition founder Pat
Robertson ``agents of intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Kyte, McCain's Ohio coordinator, said the speech was not an
attack on religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``(His point was) the tent of the Republican Party should be as
large as the country,'' Kyte said. ``What he advocated very clearly
was inclusion, and not exclusionary politics. He is opposed to
those who advocate exclusionary politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer said McCain needs to re-emphasize his conservative record
and reassure religious right voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The senator right now has a very personal argument going on
with two individuals,'' Bauer said. ``I believe his comparison
yesterday of those individuals with Louis Farrakhan and Rev. (Al)
Sharpton was inappropriate. I would not have made such a
comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
