<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-NYT     02-29 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE ROAD TO FALL, PARIS AT LAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Isabella Blow, the English stylist, was there in her
Junya Watanabe platter-collar dress and her blue Chinese savant
spectacles and red suede shoes. Michael Roberts, the photographer
and fashion editor of The New Yorker, was there. So was Andre Leon
Talley, the Vogue editor, in a fire-engine-red Prada crocodile
coat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Isabella!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the first day of school,'' Blow said before the
start of Watanabe's show on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three weeks, the fashion crowd has gathered and
regathered for the fall 2000 ready-to-wear collections, in New
York, London, Milan and now here _ clean slate, new day _ Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In a lot of ways, the French collections are like the first day
of school. Expectations run higher here, with so many big names
jostling for attention. There is also the feeling that the action
will be livelier, the clothes more inventive, and the intrigue,
thickening like a good bechamel, closer to uncovering some of the
more rotten aspects behind this ruthlessly chic business.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, that for all the cooing about Paris talent, there is an
equally powerful realization, brought on Monday evening by Marc
Jacobs' show for Louis Vuitton and again Tuesday by John Galliano's
threadbare collection for Christian Dior, that some of the best
talent is being squandered on clothes that nobody expects to be
produced, let alone seen anywhere but on a runway or in a magazine.
Of course, the more commercial clothes are in the back room. Of
course, the name of the game is money-making accessories. Of
course, luxury houses are so mindful of their images they'd rather
burn their clothes than risk seeing them stuck on mark-down racks.
</P>
<P>
   But at some level, down among artists or farmers or those who
equate what they do with who they are, a person who takes himself
seriously as a designer, and expects the same consideration in
return, has to start wondering if it's worth it. Is it worth
designing clothes in a fabulous . . . vacuum?
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, to a journalist looking at Galliano's collection _
his limpid reprise of the tramp theme from his recent couture show,
the familiar hodgepodge of funky denim and asymmetrical cuts, the
pointlessness of showing models in see-through slips with faces
that look as if they have taken a swan dive into a jar of Vaseline
_ there was nothing worth commenting on. The rhinestones stuck on
the soles of boots, which only someone looking up at a runway would
notice, said it all: Who needs them?
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' show had its own problems. While a lot of the clothes
looked cool, particularly low-sashed trench coats in subtle logo
prints and big sweaters that spilled off one shoulder, the
overwhelming impression was that he was taking another trip down
fashion's memory lane. A belted blouson jacket with rounded
shoulders _ think Claude Montana or Thierry Mugler. An oversize
blazer _ think of those slouchy boyfriend coats that sprang out of
``Annie Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the biggest names in French fashion were giving
lessons on drumming up publicity for mundane things like handbags
and scarves. A few were using their noodles, and saying something
new.
</P>
<P>
   There was the diminutive Rei Kawakubo, who hardly looks like the
type to listen to rock 'n' roll, much less relatively obscure bands
like Placebo, opening her brilliant Comme de Garcons show with an
electronic blast and overtones of punk regalia. None of that old
ladylike business for her. She literally took the stuffing out of
that notion by showing jackets exploding with clumps of shredded
wool and what looked like the remains of petticoats. The punk
elements included white coats printed with red lips and razor
blades, but her use of jackets zipping one inside another showed
how Kawakubo can artfully manipulate a current trend.
</P>
<P>
   Fashion's avant-garde were generally in top form. Junya Watanabe
sent out cocoons of glistening, pleated organdy that fanned open
like paper party favors. Yohji Yamamoto's collection, with its
background chanting and Eskimo allusions to a frozen wasteland,
could have amounted to a flaming baked alaska. But then there were
coats in tattered buff suede and old-world tapestries, all set off
by ultraromantic fur hats.
</P>
<P>
   Coats with high Edwardian collars, men with French twists, white
chiffon tops with jodhpurs _ Josephus Thimister made intriguing
points in his show, but they were scattered to the winds.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch design team of Viktor &AMP; Rolf, who made a name as
couturiers despite selling practically nothing, are now making
ready-to-wear, and the collection of natty jeans, ruffled shirts
and sleek pantsuits that draw on their distinctive silhouette is
terrific. Nine American retailers, including Barneys New York and
Linda Dresner, have placed orders, and a clever Stars and Stripes
print from the designers, which turns up on jackets and shirts and
was loosely inspired by the song ``American Pie,'' is proof of
their ingenuity and hidden business sense.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the runway, Valentino opened with fresh-looking
leathers over lacy knits and those ladylike suits in tweed of which
he is the king, but then he wandered into predictable territory
where the lesson is: if you have to repeat yourself, don't show so
many outfits. Gilles Dufour's show for Balmain was a mishmash of
pubescent styles (T-shirts spackled with the word ``Gilles'') and
cloying examples of chic (mint-green satin suits dotted with
Kleenex-like clumps). To borrow from ``Saving Private Ryan,'' it
was as if he fell out of the ugly tree and hit every branch on the
way down.
</P>
<P>
   Alber Elbaz is a lesson unto himself _ how to endure when the
deck seems hopelessly stacked against you. Elbaz arrived at Yves
Saint Laurent three seasons ago fresh from success at Guy Laroche.
He was given the reigns of a design house whose principal designer
is a god, whose men's wear designer, Hedi Slimane, is a star, and
whose owners would soon be selling the house to Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Elbaz was caught in such a bind he probably thought he had to
please Saint Laurent's mother.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he settled down, alas too late, if the rumors are
true and Tom Ford, the house's creative director, who was sitting
front and center, plans to take over by the next collection. The
old wood planks out on the floor were a cue: Elbaz, after trying
awkwardly to push Saint Laurent in a different direction, went back
to basics. That meant a somber silhouette in black and chocolate
brown enlivened with leather shirts and blouses tied chicly at the
neck.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes had a mildly subversive edge, a Saint Laurent
signature, though it would be wrong to think Elbaz was trying to
imitate Slimane's sleek, erotic silhouette. Elbaz was making his
own points, with brown suede dresses, belted and worn with
high-heeled boots, and evening suits and tuxedos in burnished-gold
satin.
</P>
<P>
   There was something odd, even mournful, about Elbaz's hurrah. It
was as if he were not part of the real action, which is taking
place far from his sentimental runway. There was Ford, with Mark
Lee, the new managing director of Saint Laurent, in one corner. In
another corner was Pierre Berge, the former chief executive of
Saint Laurent, sitting next to Betty Catroux, a longtime friend and
muse of Saint Laurent.
</P>
<P>
   In another part of the room was Slimane, who may or may not
leave Saint Laurent. It was a strange confusion of personalities,
very Proustian in its sense of the unspeakable, and it was summed
up in the song that opened the finale: ``Are You Lonesome
Tonight?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
