u a BC-NY-NASSAU-TAXES-NYT     02-29 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NASSAU-TAXES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A REVERSAL, NASSAU COUNTY GOP LEADERS BACK PROPERTY
REASSESSMENT
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ Faced with a fiscal meltdown and a major
lawsuit challenging Nassau County's antiquated property tax system,
two Republican county officials reversed course Tuesday and agreed
to press for the reassessment of all 415,000 residential and
commercial properties in the county.
</P>
<P>
   The reversal by the officials, County Executive Thomas S.
Gulotta and Charles O'Shea, chairman of the Board of Assessors,
makes reassessment, a longstanding political hot potato that
recently won the support of the Democrat-led County Legislature, a
near certainty. And it sets in motion what is likely to be a long,
politically perilous process that will increase taxes in many of
the wealthiest areas of the county.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, reassessment has been considered too politically
risky, largely out of fears that it would raise property taxes,
especially those of wealthy homeowners who would then take out
their anger at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   But the county's continuing financial crisis, which has led
rating services to downgrade the county's bonds to a level just
above junk, and a lawsuit challenging the current assessments as
racially discriminatory forced the county to act.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of wealthy communities along the North Shore of Long
Island, including Great Neck, Manhasset and Port Washington, stand
to see tax increases, officials say. Homeowners in poorer areas
along the South Shore, like Roosevelt, Freeport and Hempstead, will
probably see their taxes fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the political fallout remains unclear because both Democrats
and Republicans now have their fingerprints on the reassessment
proposal, and because the process, which is expected to take at
least two years, will not be completed before November 2001, when
all 19 county legislators and the county executive are up for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, houses in Nassau County are assessed based on land
costs from 1964 and earlier and building costs from 1938 _ before
the Long Island Expressway was built, before acres of farmland were
sold to developers, and before the construction of Levittown
ushered in a new era in suburban living.
</P>
<P>
   Those tax assessments have remained the same ever since, even
though houses in wealthy, mostly white areas have increased in
value much more than houses in poorer, mostly black and Hispanic
areas. The result is that the owner of a $300,000 house in Garden
City can pay the same $8,000 in property taxes as the owner of a
$110,000 house in Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   O'Shea made his call for reassessment less than a month after
defending the current system as ``fair'' before a hearing of the
County Legislature. He explained his switch by saying that members
of a commission he formed last year to study the system recently
told him that while their work is not yet done, they have concluded
that reassessment is overdue.
</P>
<P>
   His announcement led to an even more stunning turnabout, as
Gulotta said for the first time that he would strongly support
property tax reassessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``While I have traditionally opposed reassessment,'' he said in
a statement, ``the county's fiscal condition mandates we stop the
hemorrhaging and undertake reassessment with procedures that
provide maximum protection for our homeowners.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came less than a month before opening arguments
are scheduled in a lawsuit filed by the New York Civil Liberties
Union, the state attorney general's office and the Justice
Department. The suit charges that the current tax system
discriminates against black and Hispanic residents.
</P>
<P>
   In supporting reassessment, county officials said they were not
admitting that the current system was discriminatory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2249EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
