<SLUG> BC-AOL-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AOL-TIME WARNER PLEDGE QUESTIONED BY SENATE PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT18 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The proposed merger of America Online and Time
Warner drew skeptical questioning Tuesday from the Senate Judiciary
Committee, as lawmakers challenged a new pledge by the companies to
open Time Warner's cable television system to other Internet
service providers once the deal is completed.
</P>
<P>
   The pledge, announced just hours before the panel's hearing, was
not binding, but it provided a framework for how the two companies
would ensure that consumers have access over Time Warner Cable to
service providers other than AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the framework is a provision that allows consumers to
choose Internet providers not affiliated with AOL Time Warner and
still get high-speed, or broadband, services over cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said the memorandum tried to ease the concerns
of regulators, online rivals and other open-access advocates that
the proposed $165 billion merger could limit competition in the
hotly contested Internet field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to deflect FTC scrutiny of this merger,'' said Gary
Arlen, an analyst with Arlen Communications, a market research
concern that studies interactive media. ``It certainly is
politically motivated, but it's also just the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, who heads the judiciary panel, said
the commitment was vague and nonbinding, and he urged the companies
to condition their merger on a more detailed, ironclad agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe a degree of healthy skepticism is in order, given
what is at stake here,'' Hatch said. ``Given that this document
lacks both enforceability and specificity, this committee remains
to be convinced of its value beyond the boardroom and public
relations office of AOL-Time Warner.''
</P>
<P>
   Before its decision to acquire Time Warner, which has extensive
cable assets, AOL pushed for the government to require open access
to cable systems by Internet-service providers. Now, AOL seems to
have joined the ranks of cable operators, like AT&AMP;T, in calling for
a voluntary approach.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has no formal role in the merger, which the Federal
Trade Commission is now reviewing to ensure it complies with
federal antitrust laws. Such reviews are supposed to be free from
all political considerations.
</P>
<P>
   But several House and Senate committees have broad legislative
and oversight responsibilities for issues that affect the industry,
like privacy concerns and open access.
</P>
<P>
   In their first testimony on Capitol Hill since announcing their
planned merger six weeks ago, Stephen M. Case, AOL's chief
executive officer, and Gerald M. Levin, his counterpart at Time
Warner, took pains to underscore their commitment to open access,
vigorous free-market competition, technical innovation,
journalistic excellence and privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, those were also the senators' main areas of
concern. ``We share the same goal,'' Case said. ``Protecting
consumers and their families and establishing a new standard of
privacy and security for the digital age, while permitting the
Internet to flourish in these changing times.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin said the merger would be a boon to consumers of music,
movies, publishing, communications and financial services.
``Although the age we've entered will be brutally unsparing of
companies that can't or won't move fast enough, it will also
empower citizens as never before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But many senators, while acknowledging the merger would likely
be approved, were not sold on its merits. ``This proposed merger
reminds me of `A Tale of Two Cities' with portents of either the
best of times or the worst of times,'' said Sen. Patrick J. Leahy,
D-Vt., the panel's ranking Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators, like Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., who said the
proposed merger offered ``an exciting marriage,'' voiced few
qualms.
</P>
<P>
   But the response from Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, was more
typical: ``The more I examine this deal, the more I am convinced
that it does raise significant competition and public policy issues
that must be thoroughly explored.''
</P>
</TEXT>
