<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZAGAT-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GUSTATORY LIFE OF DINING-SCENE ROYALS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Picholine? 21?'' asks Tim Zagat, his cell phone
poised, as his driver attacks midtown traffic. ``Whatever
restaurant in the city you want!''
</P>
<P>
   Reservation, shmeservation.
</P>
<P>
   Picholine, he suggests, will be quiet at lunch, perfect for
conversation. At the 21 Club, ``We'll be interrupted because we'll
have to say hello to so many people!'' His eyes gleam. When the
choice is tossed back to him, the answer is predictable.
</P>
<P>
   Nina, his wife, checks her Palm Pilot for 21's phone number.
``This is Mr. Zagat,'' Zagat says. ``Can you take us?'' It is peak
lunchtime rush hour. ``If we can be in the front section? Well, do
your best. We'll be there in five minutes. And tell the chef we're
coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, when the Zagats sweep into 21, their rings
are kissed and their desired table awaits.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Tim nor Nina Zagat votes in the restaurant surveys, so
they do not bother trying to remain anonymous. But as acknowledged
king and queen of the dining scene, descending upon restaurants
eight times a week, their influence is such a given that it is
merrily tweaked in the current Off Broadway hit ``Fully
Committed.''
</P>
<P>
   And if publishing 35 different vox populi guides to restaurants,
resorts and, beginning next week, New York City's nightlife
(undertaken by their elder princeling, Ted Zagat, 25) couldn't snag
them a good table anywhere and anytime, then last month's
announcement of their Internet invasion, reinforced by $31 million
from food-loving venture capitalists, ought to clinch it.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the voice of the plebeians has been very, very good to
them: Even before this infusion, the enterprise that began as a
freebie Xeroxed restaurant survey by the Zagats' friends in 1979
now has revenues of more than $20 million. On Monday, the Zagats
expanded their offices at 4 Columbus Circle, tripling their space
for 75 employees, many of them itchy dot-commers and law firm
refugees half the age of Mom (57) and Pop (59) Zagat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little hard to tell them what to do,'' Zagat says,
rolling his eyes. Mrs. Zagat adds, ``These kids want a playroom for
a Ping-Pong table or foosball. And a place to keep their dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   As Zagat eagerly scans 21's dining room, Mrs. Zagat _ usually
more cautious, organized and, by the way, Cordon Bleu trained _ is
bubbling about the future site, the risk she persuaded her husband
to spend millions on. She envisions online reservations, menus,
restaurant locators, merchandising, and greater capacity to conduct
surveys. ``Nina used to be my wife,'' cracks Zagat. ``Now she's my
Webmistress.''
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't quite gotten the hang of e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Zagat is the expansive, bearlike one _ ``I'm bombastic in a
warm and fuzzy way,'' he proclaims _ the dreamer, glad-hander, tour
leader and philosophizer. He says things like, ``We've codified the
power of the people; that's why we're powerful.'' (``Codify'' comes
readily to the Yale Law School graduate and former top lawyer for
Gulf &AMP; Western. He and his wife, who joined the survey full time a
decade ago after years as a lawyer embroiled in the battles over
the Johnson &AMP; Johnson fortune, met at Yale.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, when Tim helped compel prestige restaurants to offer
$19.92 prix fixe lunches during the Democratic Convention, he has
been promoting the city's leisure life. He is now chairman of NYC &AMP;
Co., which oversees the city's Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   So last year, when Tim began talking up a ``Diner's Bill of
Rights'' _ common-sense basics ranging from courteous service to
the ability to send back unsatisfactory food without charge _
attention had to be paid, although restaurateurs' eyebrows were
raised.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than complaining to management about a meal, ``most
people prefer not to be confrontational,'' Zagat says. ``They
swallow their unhappiness but they just won't come back.
Restaurateurs would prefer to know right then.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Zagat, who, when her husband pauses for breath, steps
forward as a cozy woman who's fun to gab with, is fretting: she's
pushing her fork around 21's chicken hash, a signature dish. She is
dissatisfied with its cream sauce and also guilt-ridden, having
urged their dining companion to order it.
</P>
<P>
   The manager, Bryan McGuire, inquires about the meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a very good lunch!'' she says brightly.
</P>
<P>
   Why not tell the truth?
</P>
<P>
   She whispers: ``I think my not liking the chicken hash was my
fault. I should have asked how it was prepared. I was imagining
crispy.''
</P>
<P>
   Zagat: ``You're being defensive!''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Zagat: ``I'm not being defensive, am I?'' (At regular
intervals during the afternoon, she apologizes about the chicken
hash.)
</P>
<P>
   Tim Zagat booms across the room: ``Bryan! She hated it!''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout a 35-year marriage it has been like this: two smart,
adroit people with their pleasure centers well exercised, both from
comfortable New York-area families, checking and balancing each
other, picking food off each others' plates, building a lifestyle
that has occupational hazards most people can only dream of.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest problem,'' he says, ``is having to insist to
owners that we pay the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   She says: ``And it's really a problem when chefs keep sending
out an extra dish of this or that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At a certain point,'' he adds, ``there's just too much food.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2254EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
