<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2625 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FLEA-THEATER-ART-2TAK     02-29 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEA-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW SPACE (AND LITTLE MORE) FOR CHOREOGRAPHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5)  
 (af)  
 Kevin Giordano is a writer and dance critic living in New York
City.  
 By KEVIN GIORDANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until recently, the 80-seat Flea, on White Street in
TriBeCa, has been thought of mainly as an Off Off Broadway theater.
Its productions have included Mac Wellman's ``Infrared''; ``Chere
Maitre,'' starring Irene Worth; Rudy Stern's Theater of Light and
``Benten Kozo,'' a Kabuki play, which won an Obie.
</P>
<P>
   And the three-year-old theater, which has given itself a broad
mandate to be an irritant to the establishment, is no stranger to
controversy: in 1998, Karen Finley appeared there in ``The Return
of the Chocolate-Smeared Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Flea has also presented comedians like the maniacal Rick
Shapiro and music concerts of 20th-century composers and jazz. And
now it is becoming known downtown as a dance venue hoping to give
some competition to more established spaces like P.S. 122, Dixon
Place, the Joyce SoHo and the Kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   This month the Flea is presenting ``Get Up! Two,'' a free
festival of short dances by more than 15 choreographers that will
run Tuesday nights at 8:30 through March 21. ``Get Up! Two,'' now
in its second season (thus the ``Two''), will feature the Bessie
Award-winners David Neumann and Headlong Dance Theater, along with
Jeanine Durning, Nami Yamamoto and Mark Heim, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The program's hosts will be Timothy (Speed) Levitch, the tour
guide in the documentary film ``The Cruise,'' and the 20-year-old
stand-up comic Louis Schwadron, in addition to a 4-year-old named
Henry who will tell jokes between performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to show short works each night and make it really
fun,'' says Lizzie Simon, the Flea's creative producer. ``What
we're interested in is just having it be interactive, exciting and
exhilarating.'' Jim Simpson, the theater's director and founder,
adds: ``What I wanted was the tried and true people,
(italics)and(end italics) those who weren't heard of. I thought,
`Let's make it free and invite the dance community.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Flea can offer occasional free events because it operates
seven days a week, often layering two paying shows, ranging in
price from $12 to $35, in one evening. The ``Get Up! Two'' festival
follows two other dance programs that charged admission.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the theater presented Sara East Johnson's
all-female group Lava in ``Lava Love,'' which featured trapeze
artists and modern-dance movement. And in January, Nicholas
Leichter Dance, a modern-dance company, enjoyed a three-week run.
</P>
<P>
   The nascent dance program at the Flea can be traced directly to
Simon, who is 23. As a child in Providence, R.I., she acted in
theater, on radio and in film before going to a private school at
13. She later attended Columbia, majoring in American history and
graduating in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While there, she worked at WKCR, the university's FM station,
where she still produces the weekly talk show ``Art Attack,'' in
which she interviews artists. Through WKCR she met Steve Greco, a
founder of Platform.net, an Internet urban-youth-culture magazine,
and began writing freelance articles for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized she had a big career in front of her and lots of
ambition,'' says Greco, who is a former editor at Interview
magazine. ``And it was kind of my duty to serve that in a way, as
others helped me when I was young.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Greco, a member of the committee that hands out the New
York Dance and Performance Awards (known as the Bessies),
recommended Simon as a possible member. ``We wanted a range in
ages,'' Greco says. ``We needed young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon, who was 21 at the time, remembers the invitation: ``I was
like, `Why do they want (italics)me?'(end italics) I was the
youngest by at least 15 years.'' As a member of the Bessie panel,
Simon saw a lot of dance and performance art. ``It was kind of a
crash course on what's going on,'' she says. ``It gave me
confidence I otherwise might not have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon was planning to attend law school when she spoke with
Simpson one night before interviewing him for her radio show. ``I
think we started talking about being child actors,'' recalls Simon,
who learned that Simpson was also an actor in his youth, in theater
and television.
</P>
<P>
   Simpson offered her a job, on spec, as program director for
music at the Flea. ``I could see she was very sharp,'' Simpson
says. ``I knew she was part of the Bessies and liked performers.''
At the time, Simpson was producing and directing but needed another
producer. ``Originally, I had a board of directors full of artists,
and we were going to produce our own work,'' he says. ``It turned
out not to be a viable solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the summer of 1998, Simon has put together more than 40
music concerts and more than a dozen full-scale theatrical events
at the Flea. Impressed by Simon's work, Simpson was amenable to the
idea of having dance performances.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Flea's first dance event was actually a dancer-theater piece
in October 1998, Wellman's ``Girl Gone'' with Annie-B Parson's Big
Dance Theater. Feeling the show was a success, Simon asked a
childhood friend who was a dancer, Ayla Yavin, to help her organize
a dance festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a bunch of submissions and we went out seeing stuff,''
Simon recalls. The first ``Get Up!'' was the result.
</P>
<P>
   The program featured 16 choreographers, including Leichter,
Neumann and Durning. ``I had not seen an audience like that
before,'' says Leichter, who performed a solo in the festival.
``People were unafraid to feel something.'' Leichter's performance
was such a success with the audience, and with the producers, that
Simon and Simpson offered him a season this January.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson of Lava was performing at the Kitchen last spring and
wanted to do another run somewhere else. ``I heard the Flea was
doing dance,'' Johnson recalls. ``It's great as a dance space, and
the most appealing thing is that they're interested in doing longer
runs.'' Lava's run in September was so successful it was extended
through October.
</P>
<P>
   As a dance venue, however, the Flea is in fact not ideal. The
1865 cast-iron building, once an avant-garde film house where Andy
Warhol showed his work, then an art gallery, has a 24-by-44-foot
performing space, which will almost certainly preclude the
appearance of larger dance companies.
</P>
<P>
   There are no wings or backstage area, and, some dancers say, the
floors may not be the best. ``Obviously, it's not the place for a
large company,'' Greco says. ``I see it really great for solo and
small ensemble work, and conceptual. The intimacy promotes great
focus and careful attention.''
</P>
<P>
   But intimacy is only one of the selling points. The first
advantage, Simpson says, is offering choreographers long runs and
the possibility to extend, which is rare in dance. ``What I
discovered was that dancers perform maybe two weeks a year,'' he
says. ``For them to get a long run was something I was deeply
interested in.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many other nonprofit theaters, the Flea sometimes allows
performers to take 100 percent of the gate, while requiring them to
pay the overhead for each night. They can then make all production
decisions, from the design of programs to ticket price ($20 to $25
is usual) to number of performances.
</P>
<P>
   The theater can also be literally transformed for each event. In
the case of ``Lava Love,'' Simpson had a temporary balcony
suspended over the regular floor seats to enhance the excitement of
watching trapeze artists. For Leichter's performance he set up an
area for a DJ.
</P>
<P>
   Simon's criterion for choosing dance is relatively simple. ``I
see a lot of dance that doesn't resonate with me; it's either
boring or academic,'' she says. ``Dance is festive. It's supposed
to be fun and joyous. I'm not saying I think dance should be one
big party, but the whole experience can be exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   During this year's ``Get Up! Two,'' Simon will have an eye out
for performers she thinks are ready for a full season. ``I'm on the
lookout for someone like Nick or Sara,'' she says, referring to
Leichter and Johnson. ``I'd like to be presenting three seasons a
year of choreographers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the Flea as a place where a quantum leap happens in
dancers' careers,'' she adds. ``If they're ready, it's a beautiful
and comfortable place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
