<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 22:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2632 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-PRIMARIES-MCCAIN01-CO     02-29 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-MCCAIN01-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST UPDATE
 &HT;    EDs: 1ST LEDE WRITE-THRU; updates throughout
 &HT;    
 &HT;    McCain marks Bush as regional candidate
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKERSFIELD, Calif. _ John McCain tried to paint George W. Bush
as a regional candidate Tuesday after Bush easily won Virginia's
primary.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona senator said that he has a broad enough appeal to
help Republicans re-capture the White House in November. In
particular, McCain said, California would go to the Democrats in
the fall if the Texas governor is the nominee.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was hoping for a split verdict Tuesday, balancing
Virginia's results with a win in Washington state that he could use
as a springboard to the March 7 primary in California. He has
expected the loss in the North Dakota caucuses, a format that
favors a candidate with superior organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems as if he has a Southern strategy, doing well in
Southern states,'' McCain said of his rival, shortly after calling
to congratulate Bush on his victory in Virginia. ``We'll look
forward to Super Tuesday, when we have a broad section, a
cross-section of America voting all on that same day.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also won South Carolina's primary last month, but McCain
has defeated him in Arizona, Michigan and New Hampshire. Bush won
the Iowa caucuses and the Delaware primary, but McCain did not
campaign in either state.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of who would be the stronger candidate in the general
election ran through McCain's remarks as he campaigned in the
nation's largest state Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here in California, I have found my Republican friends
yearning for victory ... It's time to put California back in the
winning column,'' McCain said at a news conference in Stockton,
Calif. ``I now firmly believe that I, only, can make that happen
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring the importance of California's March 7 primary to
his chances against Bush, McCain reversed course Tuesday and agreed
to participate in a debate with Bush and Alan Keyes on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said he would take part in the CNN-Los Angeles Times
debate via satellite, perhaps from St. Louis. Missouri also will
hold a primary March 7.
</P>
<P>
   But to rearrange his schedule for the debate, McCain said he has
canceled a rally Thursday evening on New York's Long Island. New
York's primary also is March 7, among the 13 contests scheduled for
that day.
</P>
<P>
   None looms as large as California, where McCain aides
acknowledge they trail Bush among Republicans by 10 to 20 points.
</P>
<P>
   The state offers the primary winner 162 delegates, more than 15
percent of the 1,034 delegates needed to win the GOP nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about the absolute importance of
California,'' McCain said as he rode on his campaign bus from
Stockton to Fresno, part of a day in California's fertile Central
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   McCain will spend five of the next seven days in California,
taking time out for a quick trip to New York as well as stops in
New England and Ohio for a last pitch for votes there before March
7.
</P>
<P>
   His campaign will stop today at the University of Southern
California, where McCain will tape an edition of MSNBC's ``Hardball
with Chris Matthews.'' A similar appearance a few weeks back at
Clemson University was well-received. He also will appear tonight
on the ``Tonight Show with Jay Leno'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also will hold a rally in the Little Saigon neighborhood
of Los Angeles. The former POW during the Vietnam War ran into
trouble recently for using an ethnic slur against Asians to refer
to his North Vietnamese captors.
</P>
<P>
   Picking up the theme he laid out Monday, McCain said in
Bakersfield, ``We will not let Jerry Falwell and Pat Robertson run
the Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said the GOP's alliance with the religious conservative
leaders has contributed to Republican defeats in the last two
presidential elections by forcing Republican nominees too far to
the right on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Both men have been critical of McCain. Robertson made strongly
worded anti-McCain telephone calls in Michigan before last week's
Republican primary, which McCain won.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on Falwell and Robertson have two related goals _ to
push Bush into an ideological corner that would dissuade moderate
Republicans, independents and Democrats from supporting him and to
demonstrate that McCain is the more electable of the two men.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's outreach to independents and Democrats also sets up
the intriguing possibility that Bush could win the Republican vote,
and with it all of California's delegates, but that McCain could
wind up with more votes overall in the state's open primary.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to know at this point how likely that outcome is, but
McCain supporters already are using the possibility to suggest that
McCain's campaign could go on even if Bush wins the state's
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a split decision ... then that's going to have to
be a debate that takes place within the Republican Party. Do they
want someone who wins a majority or someone who only wins
Republican votes,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   California Secretary of State Bill Jones, a McCain supporter who
backed Bush until recently, said he would urge the Republican Party
to change its rules. ``The parties would be wise to be guided by
the results of the blanket primary, whatever their rules, for their
own good,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
