<HEADLINE>
TO REST OR NOT TO REST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ There's an interesting dilemma facing USC as it
leaves for the Bay Area today.
</P>
<P>
   Should the Trojans, who play No. 1-ranked Stanford on Thursday,
rest their starters if the game gets out of hand and try to save
their energy for Saturday's game at Cal?
</P>
<P>
   USC needs a sweep to keep its NCAA hopes alive but believes it
could remain on the bubble if it splits and finishes with an
overall record of 17-13.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem to make sense to give the starters a break if the
Stanford game is a blowout.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be smart,'' forward David Bluthenthal said. ``A lot
of coaches would do that. But that remains to be seen. If I was the
coach, that's what I would do.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's top four players _ Bluthenthal, Brian Scalabrine, Jeff
Trepagnier, Brandon Granville _ are all averaging at least 37.6
minutes per game. And the Trojans have admitted they often feel
less energetic on the second game of road trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, playing (37) minutes Thursday would take something
out of you on Saturday,'' Bluthenthal said.
</P>
<P>
   Added coach Henry Bibby: ``Right now, Stanford is the game.
Maybe we can sneak out a win.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Clancy ready: Forward Sam Clancy (broken right foot) has not
been officially cleared by doctors to play until Saturday but
intends to play against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can go Thursday,'' Clancy said.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy began running offensive plays and shooting drills in
practice Monday and began one-on-one drills against freshman center
Luke Minor on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``His foot is ready to go,'' Bibby said. ``The doctors have
given him 100 percent (clearance) on Saturday. It's maybe 90
percent against Stanford. But it's Sam's call.''
</P>
<P>
   Bibby said he envisions playing Clancy about 15-16 minutes per
game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Women's update: USC's women's basketball team (12-12, 7-7)
hosts Cal and Stanford at the Sports Arena this weekend. Stanford
is in first place, but the Trojans have defeated three teams
(Oregon, Arizona, UCLA) who were atop the standings at one point
this season.
</P>
<P>
   If USC wins its final four games, the Trojans could make the
NCAA Tournament. They also have a good chance of making the women's
National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a point in our development to where (the NIT)
wouldn't be a bad experience,'' USC women's basketball coach Chris
Gobrecht said. ``And it would represent an excellent turnaround
from 7-20 last season.
</P>
<P>
   If USC wins one more game, Gobrecht will enjoy the most
successful season in her three years as head coach.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
