<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHILDREN-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHILDREN WITH GUNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 1:
</P>
<P>
   Americans should be outraged that any 6-year-old could get a gun
and fire it to kill another 6-year-old in their first-grade
classroom. The shooting Tuesday at Buell Elementary School, near
Flint, Mich., is the latest episode of gun violence in schools.
Investigators say there might have been a playground quarrel
between the two children the day before. But sorting out intent may
be difficult, if not irrelevant. The responsibility for the death
has to lie with the adults who allowed a first-grader to get access
to a gun. It also lies with lawmakers in Washington who have
blocked efforts to protect children from this kind of senseless
death.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo., less
than a year ago shamed Congress into considering stronger gun
control laws. But the measure that emerged from the Senate, and is
now stalled in a conference committee, was a pale version of
President Clinton's proposals. Among other defects, it does not
include a child-access-prevention provision. Seventeen states have
laws that make gun owners criminally liable when they allow a child
access to a weapon that causes injury. Those laws have reduced
accidental shootings. But federal legislation is needed to make
this a national standard.
</P>
<P>
   Child-safety locks are an inexpensive, easy reform. Many
handguns have so little trigger resistance that they can be fired
by a 3-year-old. Yet Congress has done nothing about this problem
yet, and the safety-lock provision languishing in the conference
committee would not require that the devices meet minimal technical
standards to ensure that they can effectively stop accidental
firings by children.
</P>
<P>
   On other fronts, Congress has shown scant interest in aiding the
development of ``smart gun'' technology that would prevent the
unauthorized use of weapons. It has also failed to limit sales to
individuals to one gun a month.
</P>
<P>
   After the shootings at Columbine and at other schools around the
country, the gun lobby has typically tried to divert attention from
guns to issues like violence in movies and other social factors.
But it is impossible, even for the gun lobby, to escape the clear
meaning of Tuesday's school killing. It happened because a very
young child was able to obtain and fire a loaded weapon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2300EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
