<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BURCH-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
 FAMILY ILLNESS PUT GOLF IN PERSPECTIVE FOR
CLARK DENNIS (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By JIMMY
BURCH c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Clark Dennis has yet to face his first
knee-knocking par putt of the professional golf season. But the
Fort Worth resident already has recorded the biggest save of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis, 34, will make his belated debut this week on the Buy.com
Tour because he and his wife, Vickie, have been playing since Feb.
4 for much larger stakes than any tournament purse. That's when
Vickie, one day after the birth of the couple's third child, quit
breathing and went into a seizure while awaiting clearance to be
dismissed from Harris Methodist Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   For someone who had undergone a routine delivery the previous
day, the post-birth bout with toxemia _ a rare blood disorder that
can affect mothers and newborns _ was unexpected and dangerous.
Dennis, who immediately summoned a nurse after Vickie went into
convulsions, learned as much from medical personnel after his
wife's condition stabilized.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wasn't in the room when she had the seizure, she would
have died,'' Dennis said. ``That puts everything in perspective. It
still gives me chills to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those chills returned a few days later, when Vickie Dennis
flipped on the bedroom light and began pointing at her head. She
couldn't talk, but her husband got the message. Within minutes,
they were at the emergency room. Vickie Dennis' blood pressure had
soared to 244/122, well above the norm of 120/80.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the stroke range. I was seeing stars and had a
horrible migraine headache,'' she said. ``It was surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   It was toxemia, back for another visit. At least, that's what a
battery of tests concluded after countless other medical
explanations were ruled out.
</P>
<P>
   Mercifully, the toxemia never affected the couple's newborn,
Phillip Michael Dennis. During each episode, Vickie spent roughly
48 hours in an unconscious state. She has no memory of the delivery
and is sketchy on details from her on-again, off-again hospital
stay that covered two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers the morning she woke to the sound of sobbing
beside her bed. It was Clark, who had kept an all-night vigil. She
also recalls the flowers she received from PGA Tour commissioner
Tim Finchem. And the last conversation the couple shared before the
toxemia symptoms arose.
</P>
<P>
   After listening to Clark break an appointment with his personal
trainer, she lobbied for him to reconsider. The delivery, she
pointed out, had been routine. Mother and child were resting
comfortably.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Dennis never budged.
</P>
<P>
   ``This all started 10 minutes after that conversation,'' Vickie
Dennis said. ``I couldn't have called the nurse. I couldn't have
yelled for help. For once, I'm glad he didn't listen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   So is her husband, who has not played a full round of golf since
failing to keep his PGA Tour card during the November qualifying
school. His practice schedule, understandably, has been almost
nonexistent for the past month. Admittedly, Dennis has few
expectations heading into tomorrow's opening round of the
Mississippi Gulf Coast Classic in Gulfport, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   But he has a new resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know nothing on the golf course can scare me the way I've
been scared,'' Dennis said. ``If I catch a bad break or a bad lie,
I definitely will think, `Big deal.' It won't bother me. That's a
perspective I've never had before.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Dennis hopes a bolder approach to adversity on the
golf course will result in lower scores and a return to the PGA
Tour. This week, he's simply hoping to assess what areas of his
game need the most work. He expects his mind to wander back home,
to Vickie and his three sons, who will be joined by Vickie's
mother, Genoveva Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I could care less about golf,'' Dennis said. ``I
feel blessed the Lord had me in that room when Vickie had her
seizure. I love her and I just want to take care of her. As long as
she gets better, that's all I'm concerned about.''
</P>
<P>
   Spoken like a man who truly understands that saving a par pales
greatly in comparison to saving a life.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
