<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 SELIG'S RULING HELPS BASEBALL AND
STRAWBERRY (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) By GIL
LeBRETON c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ For once, somebody told Darryl Strawberry
no.
</P>
<P>
   We must applaud baseball commissioner Bud Selig for that. For
all too long, there was a helping hand, a check-writing
Steinbrenner and an adoring New York public, ready to forgive and
forget.
</P>
<P>
   As long as Strawberry was sending baseball missiles long into
the night, there seemed to be fans and teammates willing to see
nothing but the home run. If he were a .240 hitter with average
power totals, Strawberry would have been excised from baseball's
consciousness long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, judging from his words Monday, even Selig himself,
despite the one-year suspension he handed down, was ready to buy
into the sob story and give Strawberry a life vest to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting I had with Darryl and his wife, Charisse, was an
emotional experience for all of us,'' the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me, but I thought ``Kenesaw Mountain'' Selig just got a
big raise not to be so emotional about baseball-type things. The
owners voted to give him the big belt buckle and commissioned him
to step on toes.
</P>
<P>
   But consider this quote: ``I had no doubt that his remorse and
sorrow were genuine, and I worried about the effect my decision
would have on his health and the welfare of his family.''
</P>
<P>
   Selig said that. And there must be players union negotiators
chortling aloud at this very minute.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine a year from now, when baseball's labor well-being is
again up for negotiation, and Selig says, ``I had no doubt that the
players' pleas of poverty and requests for personalized jet skis
were genuine, and I worried about the effect my decision would have
on their 12,000-square-foot mansions and the welfare of their golf
games.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners don't need that. They need a Maximum Bud. (Insert
gavel sound here). Next case, please.
</P>
<P>
   For the life of me, I can't understand when in his scarred
baseball career, Darryl Strawberry lapsed from home-run hitter to
pinstriped Mother Teresa. Teammates babble dotingly about the guy.
Yankees owner George Steinbrenner had him last season for only one
month, yet reportedly bailed him out and paid Strawberry's full,
$2.5-million salary.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Strawberry has been under a dark cloud. He was
diagnosed with colon cancer in 1998, and doctors removed a 16-inch
portion of his intestine. And what rotten luck _ he got picked up
in a bad neighborhood in Tampa, Fla., last April, cruising for
hookers and with drugs in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean Strawberry has an excuse. He has an
illness.
</P>
<P>
   And if a full year in 1999 under baseball's structured
environment, knowing he was going to be regularly tested for drugs,
did not sober up Darryl Strawberry, why should anyone think that
this season was going to be any better?
</P>
<P>
   Let me suggest that there are far more touching sob stories to
be heard every week at an Alcoholics Anonymous meeting. But we
don't see Steinbrenner offering them contracts.
</P>
<P>
   We can only imagine Strawberry's mindset. Even as a drug addict,
even as someone who had repeatedly let his fans down, he could
still hit the home runs and hear the cheers. What incentive was
there to clean up?
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry's first wife, lest we forget, accused him of beating
her and breaking her nose, while also threatening her with a
.25-caliber handgun. Strawberry was also arrested once for
allegedly striking his then-fiancee Charisse. She declined to press
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry doesn't need baseball. He needs help.
</P>
<P>
   And Maximum Bud Selig, thank goodness, just gave Strawberry 12
free months to look for help.
</P>
<P>
   Until some judge or arbitrator tells us otherwise, Selig
deserves our applause. A strong commissioner should give baseball
fans hope. For too long, baseball has had this mindset that
strength in commissioner's office meant sitting in short sleeves at
the World Series and occasionally telling Pete Rose no.
</P>
<P>
   There are more weighty issues to come, of course, like telling
Jerry Colangelo that he has no choice and the Arizona Diamondbacks
must move to the American League.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, so good. Strawberry deserved a hard sentence.
</P>
<P>
   And baseball needs a hard hand.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2313EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
