s e BC-CARNIVAL-BRAZIL-2TAKE     02-29 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARNIVAL-BRAZIL-2TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE MUSIC TO THE STREET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 5) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BEN RATLIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALVADOR, Brazil _ The symbol of the pre-Lenten carnival in the
state of Bahia _ and, in many ways, the symbol of Brazilian popular
music today _ is the trio eletrico, a hulking vehicle loaded down
with massive speakers. Musicians play on the top level and carnival
celebrants jump around the vehicle as it cuts through the throngs.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the most lavish ones _ like those used by the pop singers
Ivete Sangalo and Netinho _ are full bars, televisions, lounges.
This year, one of them is reported to have a swimming pool on top.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival in Salvador, the capital of Bahia, is purely a street
carnival, different from the Folies Bergeres-like televised
festivities that take place in Rio de Janeiro. The music played on
top of the trio eletrico _ it's usually the popular new Brazilian
samba-reggae or axe music _ has a direct relationship to the street
and takes part in a kind of natural selection: each year carnival
starts with dozens of songs written specifically for the
festivities, and by the end of the week that repertory has been
narrowed to a handful.
</P>
<P>
   The trio eletrico is the medium, and the street decides. It is a
powerful, mythical machine, memorialized in countless songs. And it
began with two musically inclined inventors, a 1929 four-door Ford
with two conical speakers and a few homemade electric cavaquinhos,
a four-stringed, ukelele-like instrument.
</P>
<P>
   Carnaval 2000 in Bahia, which started on Friday and runs through
Wednesday, is a special one: it not only marks the 500th
anniversary of the founding of Brazil but is also the 50th
anniversary of the trio eletrico. Dodo and Osmar, the two inventors
of the trio eletrico, will be honored with a special trio manned by
Moraes Moreira, one of Brazil's favorite musicians and songwriters
and himself an important part of the story of the trio's
development.
</P>
<P>
   A new book, ``50 Anos do Trio Eletrico,'' by Fred Goes, recounts
the story of the trio and its meaning in carnival culture.
</P>
<P>
   Osmar's son Armando Macedo, known professionally as Armandinho
and now in his late 40s, says the story of the trio eletrico really
began in 1942. While working as a radio technician, Dodo ordered
electrical parts from the Sears, Roebuck catalog and managed to
electrify a hollow-body cavaquinho. He was intrigued after having
seen the classical violinist Benedito Chaves, who had performed in
Bahia with an electrified violin the previous year. But the
feedback from an electric cavaquinho _ even with flannel cloth
stuffed inside _ was so unbearable that he decided to create a
solid-body instrument.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dodo and Osmar went to a music shop called Primavera, which is
still here in Salvador,'' Armandinho recounted in an interview last
week, ``and asked for two cavaquinhos of medium quality. Right
there in the shop, they smashed the bodies of the guitars; they
just wanted the necks.'' They connected the neck to slabs of thick,
compact wood cut from a table, affixed four strings and two
electric pickups to them _ with a magnetized bridge on top of the
pickup, so the electrical currents from electric wires in the
street wouldn't interfere with the guitar's own electric signals.
</P>
<P>
   The result was what they called the pau eletrico, or electric
stick. They even figured out how to amplify it where there was no
electricity, by connecting the instrument to car batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Les Paul, the American guitarist, is usually credited with
inventing the solid-body electric guitar in 1941. But in some way,
Dodo and Osmar _ who are never mentioned in histories of the
electric guitar _ may have had a relationship to Paul similar to
the one the early Brazilian aviator Alberto Santos-Dumont had to
the Wright brothers. In both cases, the North Americans receive the
official credit, but there is a parallel history of South American
ingenuity.
</P>
<P>
   Dodo and Osmar played these instruments semiprofessionally until
1950, when, 20 days before carnival, the 150-musician Vassourinha
orchestra from the northeastern Brazilian state of Pernambuco
visited here. Its music inspired Dodo and Osmar to take up the
bright, march-rhythm Pernambucan music called the frevo.
</P>
<P>
   Frevos were already popular in Bahia, but were not a major part
of carnival. Dodo and Osmar changed that irrevocably the first time
they ventured out in their four-door Ford as the Dupla Eletrica
(Electric Duo), with two loudspeakers on the front of the car and a
few drummers marching around it. They wanted to replicate the force
of a huge orchestra with their electric instruments, and they had
hit upon the perfect music for a street parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play sambas, people dance in one place,'' Armandinho
said. ``With frevos, they have to move forward.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, the second year Dodo and Osmar took a moving vehicle
out into the carnaval parade, a third guitarist was added in the
car. It was now a trio eletrico and was such a success that the
name quickly became a generic phrase: other bands popped up, riding
in cars through the streets and calling themselves trios eletricos,
and soon the trio eletrico denoted the vehicle, not the band.
</P>
<P>
   Before long there were dozens of trios (sometimes with more or
less than three members). They were assuming more and more
beautiful shapes and designs; the singer Caetano Veloso remembers
one designed as a giant alligator with rows of loudspeakers in its
mouth disguised not as teeth, but as flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Another, sponsored by a soft-drink company and designed by
Osmar, was a horizontal bottle with neon lights mimicking the
decanting of its contents. In 1971, when Veloso returned to Brazil
after a year and a half in London as a political exile, he was
honored with a special trio called the Caetanave, or Caetano Rocket
_ a shiny silver vehicle with fins, a high platform for the
guitarists and lower platforms for the drummers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In last year's carnival, a replica of the Caetanave was
commissioned by the popular musician Carlinhos Brown and became one
of the high points of the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The trios were playing anything and everything popular _
Paganini, Beethoven's Fifth Symphony, Ravel's ``Bolero,'' the
Catholic hymn ``Senhor do Bonfim,'' the Beatles' ``I Want to Hold
Your Hand'' _ all frevo-ized. In 1969, Veloso's song ``Atras do
Trio Eletrico'' (``Behind the Trio Eletrico'') became a nationwide
hit, and it was only then that trios eletricos became a profitable
symbol of Bahia.
</P>
<P>
   By this time they had passed out of Dodo and Osmar's hands;
starting in the 1960s, the entrepreneur Orlando Campos developed
the trios eletricos into a business. Now they work almost like
sports teams, with each one owned privately and charging high
prices _ up to $300 this year _ for the privilege of wearing the
trio's official shirt and dancing around the trio.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1970s, Bahian music was changing, and the trios changed
along with it. In 1975 Moreira, who had just left the popular band
Os Novos Baianos, brought some radical modifications to the
tradition. He was the first to sing atop a trio _ though he
remembers that the first year it was a complete technical failure.
And he started to write an entire catalog of songs meant for that
purpose. He also incorporated afoxe rhythms _ derived from the
Yoruban heritage of this heavily African-influenced city _ into the
music and brought the drums onto the same platform as the other
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   Inasmuch as Moreira was a rock musician, his form of rock was
heavily influenced by the sound of the trio eletrico. So it was
only natural that the trio eletrico would be equally influenced by
rock when Moreira got involved with it.
</P>
<P>
   Armandinho remembers buying distortion and phase-shifting pedals
for his small guitarra Baiana and working a strain of Jimi
Hendrix's ``Bold as Love'' into the theme song of his trio in the
early 1970s. ``When Dodo saw the pedals the first time,''
Armandinho remembered, ``he said: `I can't believe I worked so hard
to take all the distortion out of the sound, and now you're putting
it back in. It's either me or these pedals.' And he left, and
waited for me to get rid of the pedals before he got on the truck
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The sound system had progressed from old-fashioned loudspeakers
to sophisticated amplifiers; it was an imitation of a rock band's
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the thickening commerce around the trios since then has not
dampened their popular power or their suggestiveness. They can be
whatever the crowd is ready for. Carlinhos Brown has worked hard to
keep a spirit of creativity, surprise and renovation in the
procession of the trios; he owns the trio for the band Timbalada,
which last year was festooned with an amazing mixture of ancient
and futuristic totems (not to mention seminude dancing women).
</P>
<P>
   This year the singer Daniela Mercury has turntablists scratching
and mixing on her trio _ a first. The Brazilian-American musician
Arto Lindsay played noise-rock guitar on top of a trio during last
year's carnival; one of his dreams is to create a trio composed of
two smaller trucks that would move together, one bearing treble
speakers, the other bearing bass, for a strange, different sonic
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas Santtana, an important member of the next wave of young
innovators in Brazilian music, sees a natural connection between
the pipoca (or popcorn, the term for the jumping, exploding crowds
around the trio) of carnival and the audience at Berlin's Love
Parade, a procession that is more like a mobile techno-music rave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trio is a rootsy thing, but it's not old, in the folkloric
sense,'' Santtana said. ``It's pop. And when I listened to the
techno music that they play in the Love Parade, I recognized many
things I heard when I was a kid in Bahia. I recognized the sub-bass
of the trios, and the high-hats _ things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   His debut record, to be released in two weeks in Brazil, is
called ``Eletrobendodo'' _ an invented word that refers to the trio
eletrico, the musician Jorge Ben and Dodo.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to capture the ecstasy of the trio experience in any
still medium. For such a valued part of a carnival culture, the
trios were scarcely photographed before the 1970s; aside from the
original car and the original paus eletricos, which remain in the
Macedo family's possession, the history is largely oral. That might
be a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's not very photogenic, not very good for
television,'' says Caetano Veloso, ``carnival in Bahia has been
protected from becoming artificialized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
