<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore, Bradley move on to California, Super Tuesday
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While the nonbinding Washington state primary was
taking place Tuesday, former Sen. Bill Bradley and Vice President
Al Gore were in California, pointing toward next Tuesday's big
primary there.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley campaigned in both Northern and Southern California
after winding up six days of campaigning in Washington state, where
he hoped to regain some momentum with a victory in the ``beauty
contest'' with no delegates at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the outcome there, Bradley said he would fight
until the Super Tuesday primaries March 7.
</P>
<P>
   In a TV interview with KTVU, Bradley said, ``This race has just
begun. March 7 is the takeoff time for this campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   To underscore that point, Bradley's campaign said Tuesday that
the candidate has purchased five minutes of television time on CBS
to air an unusual political ad Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign said the ad, airing at 10:54 p.m. EST, will
``reaffirm Bill Bradley's role as a reformer'' and make ``a
compelling case for his candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   In an apparent effort to distinguish himself from Sen. John
McCain (R-Ariz.), who has also seized the reform mantle, the ad
``will affirm (Bradley's) position as the only presidential
candidate who represents reform with a consistent dedication to
core Democratic principles.''
</P>
<P>
   All polls in California show a one-sided contest, with Gore far
ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president spoke at a Hispanic event and attended two
fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   He stressed health care and education issues and also mentioned
the battle against Proposition 187, the voter-approved and
court-rejected California ballot measure that attempted to prevent
the state from providing public services to illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   He also told elementary school students in Cudahy, where 90
percent of the residents are Latino, that Tuesday's fatal shooting
of a Michigan first-grader by a classmate showed the importance of
gun controls, especially child safety trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   But Bradley claimed he was the strongest presidential candidate
on gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning the day at San Francisco General Hospital, Bradley
argued that his gun control proposals are stronger and more
comprehensive than Gore's. Bradley has proposed requiring all hand
gun owners to be licensed and all guns to be registered.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Bradley addressed about 500 students at UCLA. ``I need
you,'' he told them. ``I need your idealism and your energy.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention Gore by name, but he called the primary
contest a ``choice between a Democratic Party that protects the
established interests and those who believe the Democratic Party
should fulfill its historic mission of defending old ideals against
complacency, indifference and selfishness.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley plans to speak this morning at a Los Angeles clinic to
promote his health care plan before spending the majority of the
day preparing for a 90-minute debate tonight in Los Angeles. The
debate between the two Democrats airs live on CNN at 9 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's campaign said that after the debate, the candidate
would be returning to New York, where some of his top supporters
have sharply questioned his decision to spend almost an entire week
focusing on Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
