<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2781 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PORGY-AND-BESS-3TAKES     02-29 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORGY-AND-BESS-3TAKES-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN WHO BREATHED LIFE INTO `PORGY AND BESS'
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: S.C., N.Y.)  (FOR RELEASE: Sunday, March 5) 
 (jw) 
 David Schiff is a composer on the faculty of Reed College in
Portland, Ore. 
By DAVID SCHIFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Porgy and Bess'' comes to the New York City Opera on Tuesday
evening, so it is a good time to celebrate the man largely
responsible for the opera's resilience: DuBose Heyward, the author
of the 1925 novel ``Porgy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are those fabulous Gershwin tunes, but no other
Gershwin show has proved revivable, and in no other Gershwin show
do the songs embody dramatic characters, even when sung out of
context or played without the lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   Listen to Miles Davis play ``Gone, Gone, Gone,'' and you are
still in Catfish Row, mourning for Jake Robbins. Heyward invented
those characters, and their provocative mixture of good and evil,
poverty and power makes the opera endlessly fascinating and has
allowed it to survive in many forms, from folk opera to musical
comedy to movie musical (with dubbed voices) and even its current,
but not necessarily final, form, grand opera.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward was born in Charleston, S.C., in 1885. His father died
when he was young, and his mother, a published poet, brought him up
in genteel poverty made worse by bouts of polio and pleurisy. His
mother had taken an interest in the Gullah dialect spoken by
Charleston's blacks. She passed this interest to her son, who (as
he wrote in the introduction to the play ``Porgy,'' which his wife,
Dorothy Heyward, helped adapt from the novel) developed a romantic
image of the ``mystery and movement of Negro life,'' the powerful
motion of the stevedores and the emotional force of spirituals,
which produced ``a contraction of the solar plexus and lachrymal
glands that he was powerless to control.''
</P>
<P>
   After developing enough of a reputation as a poet to be invited
to the MacDowell Colony, Heyward began work on a novel inspired by
a notice in The Charleston News and Courier about Samuel Smalls, a
crippled beggar who had tried to shoot his lover. Smalls was a
well-known figure on Charleston's streets, remembered mainly for
the goat that pulled his cart through town. Heyward's surprising
reaction to the news hints at the complex way he viewed the
characters in ``Porgy and Bess'': ``Just think of that old wreck
having enough manhood to do a thing like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Heyward turned Smalls into Porgy and surrounded him with other
characters he had observed in Charleston: Crown, the muscular
stevedore; Bess, Crown's abused lover; Sportin' Life, the mulatto
purveyor of ``happy dust''; and the inhabitants of the slum known
as Catfish Row. Here were all the ingredients for a best-selling
novel and then a hit play: sex, violence, religion, love both
requited and betrayed, an exotic setting.
</P>
<P>
   Its racial theme resonated with other novels and plays of the
era, like Carl Van Vechten's ``Nigger Heaven,'' Eugene O'Neill's
``Emperor Jones'' and Paul Green's ``In Abraham's Bosom.'' The
black author Zora Neale Hurston called these white authors
Negrotarians, not entirely a term of abuse. The historian David
Levering Lewis writes that soon after its Broadway opening (in a
segregated theater), ``Porgy'' became ``Harlem's play'' and
``Harlemites knew the lines of the play almost as well as the
understudies did.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics _ mostly, but not all, white _ hailed Heyward's novel
for its realism, probably the last word that would spring to mind
for readers today, for whom the book will seem condescending in its
romantic idealization of Charleston's poorest blacks. But Heyward's
characters are more complex and mysterious than they first appear.
Porgy is a sage, a saint, a trickster, an inveterate gambler,
eventually a murderer. He is an idealized ``good'' man who, like
the stereotypical Good Negro, is good only at the cost of his
manhood. In the novel he is of an indeterminate age, but he briefly
regains his youth when Bess moves into his room, only to shrivel
back into old age when she abandons him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bess, Crown and Sportin' Life form a diabolical trinity of
mythical and subversive powers. Metaphorically speaking they are
the blues counterweight to the spirituals sung by the ``God-fearin'
ladies.'' Crown and Sportin' Life, in their very different ways,
appeal to the audience despite their evil deeds. Viewed as an
emblem of rebellion, courage and sexual power, Crown prefigures the
black superstars and super-athletes to come, while Sportin' Life
(dope pusher, pimp and God-denying Voltaire all in one) is the
entertainer, demanding the likes of a Cab Calloway or a Sammy Davis
Jr. to fill his tap shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Bess appears surprisingly late in the novel, emerging out of the
shadows like a visitor from the dark side, which is the way Catfish
Row views her. Although her portrayal seems sketchy in the novel,
her finest operatic moment, ``I Loves You Porgy,'' is all there:
``Oh, fuh Gawd sake, Porgy, don't let dat man come an' handle me!
Ef yuh is willin' tuh keep me, den lemme stay. Ef he jus' don't put
dem ho han' on me, I kin be good, I kin 'member, I kin be happy.''
(Heyward's Gullah is easier to sing than to read.)
</P>
<P>
   In the play, Bess' character is filled out to show her strength
and independence, as she leads the ``shout'' to fill the burial
collection plate (transformed operatically into ``Oh, the Train Is
in the Station''), and in her attempts to resist Crown (turned
almost verbatim into ``What You Want wid Bess?''). These changes
only confirm the essence Bess shares with Crown and Sportin' Life,
a fierce independence of spirit which undermines the servile piety
that is the community norm.
</P>
<P>
   Porgy, who seems at times like a type of Christ, at times like
Adam before and after the Fall, is torn between ``doctor Jesus''
and his ``sometime thing'' Princess of Darkness, but it is no
contest. For the play, Dorothy Heyward created a new upbeat ending,
with Porgy following Bess to the promised land of Upper New York.
The secular, urban North is the new Jerusalem, even though it will
be filled with as many Sportin' Lifes and Crowns as Serenas and
Marias. Gershwin set this ending to ``Oh Lord, I'm on My Way,'' a
pseudospiritual with a disturbingly Broadway razzle-dazzle that
mirrors the play's inverted religiosity perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward was not a political radical, and by today's standards
his description of blacks as ``primitives'' seems racist, but
compared with the rabidly anti-black message of the film ``The
Birth of a Nation,'' which appeared in 1916, ``Porgy'' seemed
progressive; its view of blacks as separate but equal in their
humanity was an improvement on D.W. Griffith's movie, which
portrayed them as animals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the novel's denouement, retained in the play and opera,
seems to express racial fears. Porgy murders Crown and proclaims:
``Bess, you got a man. You got Porgy!'' This transplant of sexual
potency proves futile, because Bess leaves Porgy anyway, and the
murder of a strong ``bad'' black man by a crippled ``good'' one
feels like a primitive white fantasy about black sexual power.
</P>
<P>
   Heyward and Gershwin seemed uneasy with this crucial turn in the
plot. In the novel the murder happens between paragraphs and is not
described; in the opera, Gershwin merely transplanted noisy music
from the fight scene in Act I, leaving to the director the
difficult task of making the struggle convincing.
</P>
<P>
   Turning the novel into a play moved the characters farther away
from stereotypes to complex human figures. But the experience of
staging the play profoundly altered Heyward's view of blacks. In
his preface to the published script of the play, Heyward praised
the black cast, many of them drawn from all-black musicals like
Eubie Blake's ``Shuffle Along'' and James P. Johnson's ``Runnin'
Wild,'' as collaborators who contributed important ``bits,'' and
noted that many of them came from theatrical families going back
several generations: anything but primitive.
</P>
<P>
   Already the black performers of ``Porgy'' were transforming the
show, a process that has continued to the present.
</P>
<P>
   As Hollis Alpert wrote in his indispensable study ``The Life and
Times of Porgy and Bess,'' Heyward now ``foresaw Negroes breaking
down the bastions traditionally reserved for whites.'' His next
novel, ``Mamba's Daughters,'' published in 1929, imagines an
all-black opera, with music that would be ``primitive _
sophisticated _ neither? _ both?'' performed on the stage of the
Metropolitan Opera, ending with the singing of James Weldon
Johnson's anthem ``Lift Ev'ry Voice and Sing.'' (Years later Ned
Rorem considered making ``Mamba's Daughters'' into an opera.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2319EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0521 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 23:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2783 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-PORGY-AND-BESS-3RDDTA     02-29 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORGY-AND-BESS-3RDDTAKE-$ADV05-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: an opera. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before he had even discussed an opera with Gershwin, Heyward was
predicting the very different shape ``Porgy'' would take once it
was set to music. It would become a work of affirmation rather than
nostalgia, and its musical genre would be hard to define.
</P>
<P>
   Enter George and Ira Gershwin _ but not exit DuBose and Dorothy
Heyward. The opera libretto follows the play faithfully. The
biggest changes are the replacement of the many traditional
spirituals in the play with newly composed songs, and the expansion
of dramatic moments in the play into musical shape, like the
insertion of the love duet ``Bess, You Is My Woman'' before Bess
leaves for the picnic.
</P>
<P>
   Although the original plan was for Ira Gershwin to write lyrics,
DuBose Heyward asked to try his hand, and he eventually wrote or
helped write most of them, including the words to ``Summertime,''
``My Man's Gone Now'' and ``A Woman Is a Sometime Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What did George Gershwin bring to the show besides cloaking
Heyward's characters in imperishable musical garb? That
accomplishment alone would have assured the opera's success, but
Gershwin amplified the complexities that already existed, sometimes
in subliminal ways.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Melnick, in his recent book, ``A Right to Sing the
Blues,'' notes that ``Summertime'' echoes the melody of the
spiritual ``Sometimes I Feel Like a Motherless Child.'' The
troubling words of the spiritual thus steal into the song as an
ominous undercurrent and so, as Melnick says, forecast the tragic
events to come. The subtly ironic use of musical allusions appears
again in Sportin' Life's ``It Ain't Necessarily So,'' whose melody
recalls the blessing chanted in synagogues before the reading of
the Torah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Porgy and Bess,'' however, differs from the earlier novel and
play in a more profound way that reflects the conditions of 1935.
As much as or more than an opera about blacks, it becomes an opera
about poverty, in which the inhabitants of Catfish Row are no
longer the ``other'' but are ``us.'' It is hard to say who was
responsible for this change, but it was inherent in Gershwin's
desire to compose a folk opera rather than the blackface musical Al
Jolson wanted or the grand opera Otto Kahn asked him to write for
the Metropolitan.
</P>
<P>
   The main character of a folk opera is the people, a peasantry
who sing communally in a distinctive national idiom. ``Porgy and
Bess'' presents its African-Americans not as exotic Gullahs but as
the American peasantry singing a music that is American first,
African second. Choral music frames all the action, and the fate of
the leads is always framed by the struggles of the community. The
most popular number in the score, ``I Got Plenty o' Nuttin,' ''
with lyrics by Ira Gershwin and DuBose Heyward, became its theme
song. It is at once a minstrel show banjo tune and a typical
Depression-era celebration of the pleasures of penury, like ``Now's
the Time to Fall in Love'' and ``Let's Take a Walk Around the
Block.''
</P>
<P>
   George Gershwin further enforced the universality of the story
by borrowing a device from ``Wozzeck.'' In the first scene of
Berg's opera, the title character suddenly breaks into a passionate
phrase that seems directed at the audience: ``Poor folks like us,
don't you see, Captain, must have money.'' The melody of this
phrase returns several times to become a call for compassion.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in the first scene of ``Porgy and Bess,'' Porgy, who
has at first appeared as a ``crap shark'' well liked by the
community, suddenly gets introspective about his condition: ``When
Gawd made cripple, he mean him to be lonely. Night time, day time,
he got to trabble dat lonesome road.'' Gershwin treats his ``Night
time, day time'' melody just as Berg did his tune, bringing it back
as a plea for compassion at the end of the first scene and, later,
as the lead-in to ``Bess, You Is My Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   What would DuBose Heyward and George Gershwin think of ``Porgy
and Bess'' today? They would certainly be gratified that it is
still up and running and pleased that it has served as a
springboard for the careers of so many great black singers,
including Todd Duncan, William Warfield, Leontyne Price, Donnie Ray
Albert, Clamma Dale and Wilhelmenia Fernandez. But they might be
saddened that the more at home the work becomes in the opera house,
the more it becomes ``grand'' (at the New York City Opera as well
as the Met), the less ``folk'' it remains.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
