</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIMARIES-MAIN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Religious right buoys Bush in Virginia
 &HT;    By Ken Herman and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Once again prevailing in the South, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush easily won Tuesday's GOP presidential primary in
Virginia amid a growing Republican squabble over religion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also trounced Arizona Sen. John McCain in the North Dakota
caucuses Tuesday night. Results from a primary in Washington state
were not available.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Bill Bradley and Vice President Al Gore
squared off in Washington, in the only Democratic contest Tuesday.
No delegates were at stake, but the former New Jersey senator hoped
for a symbolic victory there to resurrect his faltering campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen delegates were at stake in North Dakota, where Bush won
76 percent of the votes to 19 percent for McCain. Radio commentator
Alan Keyes got 5 percent. Bush won 14 delegates and McCain got
four. Keyes won a delegate.
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, Bush won 53 percent of the vote and all 56
delegates. McCain got 44 percent of the vote and Keyes got 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was stunned last week when he lost primaries in
Michigan and Arizona, was relieved by his Virginia victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got some good news from the commonwealth of Virginia,''
Bush told cheering supporters at a rally in Cincinnati. ``Tonight,
the people of that state spoke. Tonight, the people of that state
sent a signal. Tonight, the people of that state, full of great
people, sent a message that they want George W. Bush to be the
Republican nominee for president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13-state presidential showdown March 7, he told
supporters, ``I can't wait.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain congratulated Bush, but dismissed his victory in Virginia
as part of ``a Southern strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We look forward to Super Tuesday, when we have a broad
section, a cross-section of America voting all on that same day,''
McCain said in California.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in Atlanta late Tuesday night, Bush said he's regained
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``When March 7 is over, one of the things that will be on your
TV screen is: Here's who's got what number of delegates,'' he said.
``It will be pretty clear, and it's going to be more clear who the
nominee is going to be. It's
</P>
<P>
   going to be very clear after March 14.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas and Florida, where Bush's brother Jeb is governor, hold
their primaries March 14.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will speak this morning at 9:40 at the Gwinnett Civic and
Cultural Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep working hard,'' he said. ``March 7 is the
big day, and Georgia is an important part of March 7. You're going
to hear me talk tomorrow about what I believe and where I want to
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   In Virginia, both candidates drew heavily from the same blocs
that have supported them in earlier primaries. Bush captured
stalwart Republicans, as he did in his South Carolina victory Feb.
19. He particularly picked up votes from conservatives and those
who call themselves members of the religious right.
</P>
<P>
   McCain won the overwhelming support of independents and
Democrats. While those voters were responsible for the Arizona
senator's first-place finishes in Michigan and New Hampshire, they
accounted for a much smaller proportion of the Virginia electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Already looking ahead to next week's Super Tuesday primaries,
Bush campaigned Tuesday in Cleveland, Columbus and Cincinnati,
including stops at a Catholic charity.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in Ohio, New York, California, Georgia and nine
other states vote March 7 as part of the contests that will award
more than half the delegates needed for nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland, where Bush talked with officials at Fatima Family
Center, a Catholic charity, Ohio Gov. Robert Taft predicted Bush
would carry the state and its 69 delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is a good candidate for Ohio because he is in
the mainstream of America, the mainstream of where the independents
and the Republicans who will be voting in our primary are,'' said
Taft, a Bush supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has been hurt by Democrats and independents voting for
McCain, could be helped in Ohio by contested Democratic races,
including the Gore-Bradley match-up.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appearance at the Catholic charity came two days after he
announced he regrets not speaking out against anti-Catholic
policies at Bob Jones University, where he spoke Feb. 2. In a
letter to Cardinal John O'Connor of New York, Bush said he regrets
the ``missed opportunity'' to speak out against the views at the
South Carolina school.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain campaign has been using phone calls to remind voters
of Bush's appearance at Bob Jones and his effort to lure support
from ``Southern fundamentalists who have expressed anti-Catholic
views.'' Bush has angrily accused McCain of attempting to portray
him as an ``anti-Catholic bigot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the Catholic center was
identified months ago as the kind of faith-based program Bush might
want to highlight.
</P>
<P>
   But Tom Mullen, president of Catholic Charities of Cleveland,
said Tuesday's event was not finalized until Sunday, the same day
Bush released his letter to O'Connor and other Catholic leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Bush denied using the Cleveland event as part of an effort to
make sure he is not viewed as anti-Catholic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to Catholic Charities because I want to herald the
greatness of America,'' Bush said. ``The greatness of America lies
in the hearts and souls of our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, Bush continued to hammer McCain for using
tape-recorded phone messages reminding voters that Bush spoke at
Bob Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of politics needs to be set aside,'' said Bush.
``It's the kind of politics that John F. Kennedy rejected in the
1960s. It's the kind of politics we thought we put behind us in
America. It's the kind of politics that continues to persist today
because of Senator McCain.''
</P>
<P>
   He also accused McCain, who on Monday criticized evangelical
Christian leaders Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell, of ``demonizing
people, holding people up for scorn.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's campaign manager, Rick Davis, accused Bush of
``Election Day hysteria.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is that George W. Bush is trying to run a
Jekyll and Hyde campaign where he is a Pat Robertson and Bob Jones
Republican in one state and a compassionate moderate in another,
and he's not going to get away with it,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   In California, McCain continued his attack, accusing Robertson
and Falwell of having an ``evil influence'' over the Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stand up and take on the forces of evil _ that's my job,
and I can't steer the Republican Party if those two individuals
have the influence that they have on the party today,'' he said to
reporters on his campaign bus as it traveled down the Central
Valley of California.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're supposed to tolerate evil in your party in the name of
party unity?'' he continued. ``That's not what the party is all
about. That's not what Abraham Lincoln said our party was about.
Theodore Roosevelt fought the forces of evil in the Republican
Party to his demise. Ronald Reagan rejected extremism in our
party.''
</P>
<P>
   While complaining about McCain's telephone calls, the Bush
campaign also used mass callings to Virginia voters in recent days
to remind them that McCain ``as chairman of the powerful Senate
Commerce Committee has pushed and fought for 48 additional flights
into Reagan National Airport.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As Governor, George W. Bush believes in limited government and
supports letting local citizens make decisions that affect their
community. The differences are clear. Senator John McCain, who is
using his power to interfere in our local issues, or Governor
George W. Bush, who believes local decisions should be made by
Virginians.''
</P>
<P>
   The calls went to voters in the airport's flight path in
Washington suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won in Virginia because Republican voters overwhelmed
independents and Democrats who crossed party lines in support of
McCain, according to surveys of Virginia voters conducted by Voter
News Service, a consortium of The Associated Press and television
networks.
</P>
<P>
   The day after McCain labeled Robertson and Falwell ``agents of
intolerance,'' religious conservatives accounted for 20 percent of
the Virginia vote. They backed Bush 8-to-1, prompting the governor
to say, ``The voters of Virginia rejected the politics of pitting
one religion against another.''
</P>
<P>
   Backed by Gov. James Gilmore and the rest of the Virginia GOP
establishment, Bush could not afford a loss in Virginia after
leading polls there for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bush dismissed suggestions by McCain's campaign that the victory
reaffirms that Bush only can win Southern conservative states. ``I
won Iowa. I won Delaware. We'll see what happens March 7,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   As he did in South Carolina 10 days earlier, Bush won in a
generally conservative, Southern state where he is popular with
rank-and-file Republicans _ the same voters who may hold the key to
victories in states where independents and Democrats are shut out
and only GOP votes count.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
