<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Ohio, Okla., Md.)  (Eds: Adds item on Bob Jones Univ.; Updates briefs on Gore and adds
Maryland poll to Ohio poll item.) 
 (nk) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   BOB JONES RESPONDS: Bob Jones University, the fundamentalist
Christian institution that has become a lightening rod since Gov.
George W. Bush of Texas visited it during the South Carolina
campaign, has responded on its Web site to attacks against it.
</P>
<P>
   The university described Sen. John McCain, Vice President Al
Gore and former Sen. Bill Bradley as ``the political `three
tenors,''' who together ``sing the same off-pitch tune of the
liberal left.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it really a compliment to Bob Jones University that the
likes of John McCain, Al Gore and Bill Bradley seethe and fulminate
against us?'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The university, which had previously declined to respond to
requests for comment, said its policy against interracial dating
was based on its understanding of the story of the Tower of Babel.
``The university wishes to give God the benefit of the doubt and
avoid pursuing any direction that would give assistance to the
renewed efforts of man to create a one-world community, consisting
of one religion, one economy, one government, and one race,'' the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The university denied that it hates Catholics, saying it
regarded Catholicism on theological grounds as ``false.''
</P>
<P>
   The school said it believes it has a biblical mandate to preach
salvation by faith alone to Catholics, Jews, Buddhists, Mormons,
Muslims, atheists and ``unbelieving and religiously liberal
Protestants.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Gustav Niebuhr
</P>
<P>
   BETWEEN GOVERNORS: Gov. Frank Keating of Oklahoma has some
neighborly advice for Bush. Keating, a devout Roman Catholic and
early supporter of Bush, has suggested that the Bush campaign
schedule a speech at a major Catholic university to counter any
hint of anti-Catholic bias that might have emerged after Bush's
appearance at Bob Jones University in the South Carolina primary
campaign. Noting that Bush was at a Catholic center in Cleveland on
Tuesday, Ari Fleischer, a campaign spokesman, said, ``We do
appearances at faith-based organizations all the time, so we rule
nothing out.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Ross E. Milloy
</P>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   GORE IN LOS ANGELES: Campaigning in Los Angeles on Tuesday, Vice
President Al Gore referred only briefly to his rival, former Sen.
Bill Bradley, criticizing his health care plan. He had an interview
with Univision, which he was asked to conduct in Spanish. He
declined, saying, though, that he once ``was completely fluent.''
At a fund-raiser where he raised $100,000, he paid homage to the
``wonderful mosaic'' in the audience of Indians, Pakistanis, Jews,
Koreans and Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Katharine Q. Seelye
</P>
<P>
   THE POLLS
</P>
<P>
   OHIO LEANS TO BUSH: In Ohio, the first independent statewide
poll of likely Republican voters taken since the primaries in South
Carolina and Michigan showed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas ahead of
Sen. John McCain, 53 percent to 36 percent. The poll of 386 likely
Republican voters, questioned on Wednesday through Sunday, was
released on Tuesday by the Institute for Policy Research at the
University of Cincinnati. A similar poll of likely Democratic
voters showed Vice President Al Gore ahead of former Sen. Bill
Bradley, 66 percent to 22 percent. The margin of error is plus or
minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In Maryland, another state with a primary next Tuesday, Bush led
McCain 47 percent to 40 percent in a Potomac Survey Research poll
of likely voters for The Baltimore Sun. The poll, released Tuesday,
showed Gore ahead of Bradley, 58 percent to 23 percent. The margin
of error was plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   _ By David E. Rosenbaum
</P>
<P>
   THE WEST
</P>
<P>
   GAY MARRIAGE OPPOSED: A proposition to prohibit California from
recognizing same-sex marriages performed elsewhere has majority
support. The Field Poll found in its latest survey that 53 percent
of respondents favored the measure and 40 percent were opposed.
Among Republicans, 77 percent supported it and 16 percent were
opposed, while 42 percent of Democrats supported it and 45 percent
opposed it.
</P>
<P>
   _ By James Sterngold
</P>
<P>
   WEDNESDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
<P>
   DEBATE: Democrats, live on CNN 9 p.m. Eastern time.
</P>
<P>
   BILL BRADLEY: Huntington Park and Los Angeles, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE W. BUSH: Duluth, Ga., St. Louis and Springfield, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   AL GORE: Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   JOHN McCAIN: Riverside, Los Angeles and Westminster, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
