u f BC-HOTEL-WORKPLACE-ART-N     02-29 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOTEL-WORKPLACE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (Attn: Texas)  
 COLUMN: CHEERS FOR WORK! RAH! RAH!  (jw) 
 By CHARLOTTE ST. MARTIN with CHARLES BUTLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlotte St. Martin is the executive vice president for
marketing, Loews Hotels.
</P>
<P>
   I work 70, 80 hours a week _ I love to work. It has been that
way since I was 12 and I got my first job at a movie theater in
Grand Prairie, Texas. That is also when I made up my mind that I
was going to be an executive and not have any children.
</P>
<P>
   I needed that job to buy a cashmere sweater. My mother probably
thought I would do baby-sitting. Well, I got a job as a
concessionaire, and I loved it. I love work _ the interaction, the
creativity, the products. I love making sales.
</P>
<P>
   My funniest job was when I was a junior at Grand Prairie High
School. I was a cheerleader, but the cheerleader costumes were very
expensive. To pay for them, the cheerleaders would work during the
summer at the Susan Crane Packaging Co., which did package
decorations for Neiman Marcus. After a day's work, our hands would
be frayed, but the job was a hoot. Here were six girls who spoke no
Spanish on an assembly line that was virtually all Hispanic,
stapling, cutting, pasting decorations. And yet we somehow learned
how to communicate, and we made some wonderful friends.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure how I got my business drive. It wasn't from my
father. He was killed in World War II, in May 1945, two months
before I was born. He was only 21. But my mom worked, as did my
grandmother, and they were very supportive of my desire to be
successful, which was unusual for a girl growing up in the late
'50s and early '60s.
</P>
<P>
   But I'll be honest: I'm not a feminist. My attitude was never,
``Why are men holding me back?'' It was, ``If I work harder, if I
find a solution, then I'll be recognized, and that will make it
easier for other women.'' I believe each gender should have to pay
its dues and get the experience.
</P>
<P>
   And believe me, the hotel business was a man's business when I
started out. My first job in the hospitality industry was planning
all the opening events when the Fairmont Hotel in Dallas opened in
1969. I left the Fairmont in 1977 and became the first person hired
by the Anatole Hotel, which is also in Dallas and even today is one
of the largest convention hotels in the country. I ended up staying
17 years, becoming the first woman to be CEO of a major hotel.
</P>
<P>
   I remember once, after I had become the CEO, my uncle picking me
up at the airport and asking me, ``Why does your husband let you
travel so much?'' It made me think, ``Oh, my God! Would I be any
different if my dad had lived, and if I had grown up in Boston,
where he was from, in a regular Catholic family?'' Until that
moment it had never occurred to me that I was doing something
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   At Loews Hotels, as keeper of the brand, it's my job to give
7,000 employees the ``Loews personality'' so they can deliver a
unique experience to guests. Four years ago we started our largest
expansion in history. I'm in charge of developing our hotels'
image; it's a perfect job because I can be my creative self. We're
in the entertainment business. People want to be pampered. Instead
of just giving guests a mint on their pillow, I came up with the
idea of having warm chocolate-chip cookies and milk served in cow
mugs waiting for them.
</P>
<P>
   But you know, I've been entertaining for a long time. High
school football in Texas was a big show; that's where people went
on Friday nights. And there is nothing like being a cheerleader.
Funny, I still have my cheerleader shirt and jacket that I worked
all summer to pay for. And they fit, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
