u p BC-MCCAIN-2NDLD-WRITETHR     02-29 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN RENEWS ATTACK ON RELIGIOUS RIGHT, CALLING THEM `EVIL' 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Recasts lede into 2 grafs; Clarifies graf bgng, The decision
to pull out ..., to make clear that McCain's decision to pull out
of LA debate sparked criticism, sted Tuesday's reversal.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT16 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKERSFIELD, Calif. _ Sen. John McCain intensified the battle
over the political power of the religious right Tuesday as he
accused Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell of having an ``evil
influence'' over the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gov. George W. Bush sharply attacked McCain,
his rival for the Republican presidential nomination, for ``pitting
one religion against another.''
</P>
<P>
   Their comments Tuesday came as the see-saw battle for the
Republican nomination tilted once again to the Bush side with the
Texas governor winning a lopsided victory over McCain in the
Virginia primary.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Cincinnati, Bush said the Virginia results bring the
Republicans ``one step closer to victory'' and ``one step closer to
a united party.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's statements Tuesday, following his incendiary attack
on the leaders of the Christian right the day before, seemed to
continue if not escalate his effort to marginalize what has been an
important segment of the Republican Party for two decades.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Monday, McCain called Robertson and Falwell
``agents of intolerance.'' He went further Tuesday, criticizing
them for ``the evil influence that they exercise over the
Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To stand up and take on the forces of evil, that's my job, and
I can't steer the Republican Party if those two individuals have
the influence that they have on the party today,'' he said Tuesday,
speaking to reporters on his campaign bus as it traveled down the
Central Valley of California.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're supposed to tolerate evil in your party in the name of
party unity?'' he continued. ``That's not what the party is all
about. That's not what Abraham Lincoln said our party was about.
Theodore Roosevelt fought the forces of evil in the Republican
Party to his demise. Ronald Reagan rejected extremism in our
party.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though McCain's assault on the Christian Right did him
little good, if any, with voters in Virginia, he is casting himself
as the one candidate who can rescue the Republican Party from
religious leaders who, he argues, preach ``a message of intolerance
and exclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   He has portrayed Bush as deeply indebted to the leadership of
the Christian right, which sprang to his aid during the bitter
weeks of campaigning in South Carolina before the state's
Republican primary on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   To further that effort, McCain's campaign said Tuesday that it
had been calling voters in Washington state, which also held its
Republican primary Tuesday. The calls, McCain aides said, alerted
voters that Bush had campaigned at Bob Jones University in South
Carolina without condemning that school's anti-Catholic teachings.
The senator's campaign made similar calls in Michigan for its
primary, which McCain won last week.
</P>
<P>
   McCain also complained Tuesday about ``vicious attacks'' by
leaders of the religious right on Gen. Colin Powell, the former
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and on former Sen. Warren
Rudman, R-N.H., the co-chairman of McCain's national campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that one of the motivations for embracing our
vision is that every one of Falwell's and Robertson's candidates
lost in the 1998 elections _ every single one of them,'' McCain
told reporters. ``Now, if your job is to go on continued kamikaze
missions, then fine. But if you want to change that and start
regaining the majority that we had in the '80s, then you've got to
change the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Falwell and Robertson said both declined to comment on
McCain's attacks.
</P>
<P>
   In Stockton, a reporter asked McCain whether he was worried that
his speech on Monday would fracture a winning coalition for the
Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excuse me,'' McCain cut in. ``A winning coalition? Which
winning coalition are we talking about in a state that has lost the
last two presidential elections, that has lost the last two
congressional elections. Here in California, it's been an electoral
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain also announced Tuesday that he would participate after
all in a debate here on Thursday night. The debate, sponsored by
The Los Angeles Times, will be broadcast live on CNN. On Sunday,
McCain's aides said that he had pulled out of the debate in order
to campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to pull out resulted in a wave of unfavorable news
coverage, and the Bush campaign gleefully portrayed it as a
strategic retreat by McCain, who still trails badly among
California Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Although McCain's aides tried to counter that impression by
pointing out all the time and television money they are spending
here, they came to recognize that it looked terrible for their
candidate not to appear at the only debate scheduled before this
state's primary next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want the debates, symbolically, to be
misinterpreted,'' said McCain's senior strategist, Mike Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   McCain plans now to participate by satellite hook-up, and Bush's
staff said he might do the same.
</P>
<P>
   But in addressing one controversy, McCain created yet another,
this one over his level of candor with reporters when confronted
with sticky questions about the conduct of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, McCain and his aides first denied responsibility for
a series of phone calls to Roman Catholic voters in Michigan
telling them about Bush's appearance at Bob Jones University.
Later, they acknowledged that the campaign had paid a telemarketing
firm $8,000 to make 24,000 phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday morning, when first asked whether he had ruled out
appearing at the debate, either in person or by satellite feed,
McCain replied in seemingly unambiguous terms. ``There's no
possible way,'' he said, adding that ``we cannot flex our
schedule'' to debate Bush.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, minutes after finishing a town hall meeting,
McCain called a press conference to say that he would debate after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, reporters asked why he had changed his mind, and
over and over McCain repeated the same response: ``Because we were
able to change our schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, under persistent questioning, McCain, who calls his bus
the Straight Talk Express and who concludes almost every stump
speech by promising ``to always tell you the truth, no matter
what,'' acknowledged that he had not been candid with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real deal is that as frank and honest and straight talk as
our express is, sometimes I don't share all of the inner workings
and contemplations of our campaign,'' he said, revealing that he
had earlier instructed his aides to explore the possibility of
participating in the debate by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we were ready to make that change, I apologize for not
sharing my musings with you as to how we achieve being in the
debate,'' he said, then adding with a cackle, ``But from now on,
straight talk.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
