<HEADLINE>
COURT RULES AGAINST NURSING HOME CHALLENGES TO MEDICARE
REGULATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIUS A. KARASH  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid nursing home bankruptcies and growing concerns about the
quality of care, the U.S. Supreme Court ruled Tuesday that nursing
homes could not challenge Medicare regulations in federal court
unless they first go through an administrative hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-4 ruling comes at a time of heightened awareness of
nursing home problems. In December, the Clinton administration said
it would expand the use of immediate federal financial penalties
against homes that violate health and safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Missouri officials said low wages were driving down
the quality of care at Missouri nursing homes and declared an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, seven big nursing home operators have sought
bankruptcy protection in the past seven months.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court decision was criticized by the American Health
Care Association in Washington. In a statement, the association
said the ``requirement to use an overly bureaucratic administrative
review process to challenge an entire regulatory scheme prevents
the timely judicial scrutiny of a system that has harmed both
patients and providers.''
</P>
<P>
   The high-court ruling also was criticized by Arkansas-based
Beverly Enterprises Inc., the largest U.S. nursing home chain,
though Beverly was not a party in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system is broken,'' said Dan Springer, a spokesman for
Beverly, which has nursing homes in Kansas and Missouri. ``It makes
absolutely no sense. One has to wonder what the end game is in a
system that focuses on punishment rather than rewarding good
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   But Douglas Carter, a Kansas City lawyer who specializes in
nursing home abuse and negligence cases, said the Supreme Court
case indicated that ``there are a lot of nursing home operators
with a lot of money that are willing to fight in any way possible
to avoid having people looking over their shoulder and making sure
they do what they're supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Krisztal, an Overland Park lawyer who also specializes in
cases of nursing home abuse and negligence, said the nursing home
industry had been challenging federal regulations for many years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice to consumers is to keep on making complaints to the
appropriate agency, to investigate poor care in nursing homes and
keep a close eye on their loved ones,'' Krisztal said. ``They have
to visit, they have to view their conditions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
