u s BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT &LR;      02-29 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIWIS' CUP LEAD MOVES TO 4-0
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUCKLAND, New Zealand _ Mercifully, the end is near.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of an early, lethal Prada blunder, Team New
Zealand coasted to its fourth consecutive victory over the Italian
challenger Wednesday to stake a commanding 4-0 lead in the
five-of-nine-race finals for the America's Cup. Race 5 is scheduled
for Thursday and, should the result hold true to form, for the
sailors from Milan the end will not have come a moment too soon.
</P>
<P>
   As in the first three races of the series, the Kiwis won the
start, took control up the first windward beat, then denied the
challengers any semblance of a passing lane around the rest of the
track. There was only one small difference in Wednesday afternoon's
lopsided duel. For a brief, shining moment, the Italians made a
race of it.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Prada crew showed some true heart in the early
going and, at one point up the first windward leg, even held the
lead. But it gave it away with a tactical error that summed up its
sad overall performance in the regatta. Frankly, once again, the
better team won.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps in celebration of his 38th birthday, or maybe simply to
break the monotony, in the prestart sequence the Kiwi skipper,
Russell Coutts, ordered the hoisting of what is known as a Code
Zero genoa, a light-air headsail that supposedly would provide
extra acceleration in the trifling 7-to-8-knot northeasterly, and
which was making its first appearance in the regatta.
</P>
<P>
   It did not make much difference, for despite the Prada tactician
Torben Grael's assertion, ``We must have the left,'' he was
perfectly content off the starting line to direct Luna Rossa to the
right-hand side of the course. But it would prove to be a telling
remark.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Kiwi tactician Brad Butterworth had NZL 60 in
the right place at the right time for, from his spot to the left of
Prada, he was perfectly positioned for the tiny left-hand shift
that filled in soon after the starting gun sounded. And up the
first third of the beat, Butterworth was cautious to protect his
turf.
</P>
<P>
   But Prada was hanging tough, showing a good turn of speed, and
when the boats came together for the second crossing, the Italians
were on starboard tack _ which means they held nautical
right-of-way _ and in an ideal position to maintain and consolidate
what was clearly a slight lead. Grael had two options: to tack back
and cover the Kiwis, the conventional match-racing move, or to
cross them and sail off to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Though circumstances had changed drastically, the latter choice
was the one Grael had wanted early on. Now, he gambled everything
that the left would still hold the more favorable breeze.
</P>
<P>
   But Grael was dead wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The next significant observation came from Coutts, who had been
happy to dip behind the Italians, take the right side of the
course, and accept a small loss for the risk of a far greater gain.
``This is a right-hander,'' he said soon after, noting a swing in
the breeze. For the Italians, the translation was, ``Game and
set.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kiwis had exhibited, yet again, an uncanny ability to stay
in phase with the shifts. Prada continued to the left. From a
racing standpoint, it had just sailed off the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a nice little puff coming down here,'' said
Butterworth, as the Kiwis built on their fresh and soon-to-be
untouchable lead. At the top end of the leg, Butterworth called for
repeated tacks and used the inside advantage to push the Italians
out past the lay line to the mark.
</P>
<P>
   For Prada, it was once again going from bad to worse. The body
language on the Italian boat spoke volumes. The fight was no longer
a fair one.
</P>
<P>
   The New Zealanders rounded the top mark with a 45-second lead,
but Prada took back 6 seconds on the ensuing run. It was not an
indication of things to come. The Kiwis' final margin of victory
was 1 minute 49 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, Coutts brought his record to 9-0 in America's
Cup finals, tying the mark set by the legendary cup skipper Charlie
Barr, who also posted nine straight triumphs in three successful
defenses between 1899 and 1903.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Coutts will try to reach and define a new standard
of excellence in the long, storied history of cup competition. The
stunned, defeated Italians are the only ones who can reverse what
appears to be a date with destiny. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2356EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
