<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0529 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2800 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-1ST     02-29 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PENALTIES HAUNTING `PROGRAMS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: UPDATES throughout with St. John's beating Seton Hall,
comments from athletic director; deletes some earlier material.) 
 (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wheels are coming loose at many so-called programs. College
basketball teams are hoping to hold parts together with chewing gum
and baling wire and appeals and briefs just to get through the
national tournament.
</P>
<P>
   After that, they'll just let attrition and penalties and
ambition and professional money take their natural course. Since
undergraduates started flocking to the crass-but-honest dollar
standard of the National Basketball Association, college basketball
has become a year-by-year proposition, now operating on day-by-day
eligibility bulletins.
</P>
<P>
   Or, sometimes it is even minute-by-minute. Tuesday night,
shortly before before St. John's beat Seton Hall, 66-60, in Madison
Square Garden, Erick Barkley was suspended for the second time this
season for violations of rules of the National Collegiate Athletic
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was originally suspended for two games for trading cars
with somebody who was identified as a family friend but who also
had ties to a major summer basketball league in New York.
</P>
<P>
   This time Barkley was suspended for apparently having accepted
between $2,500 and $4,000 to help pay the hefty tuition at a Maine
prep school he had attended for a year. The tuition had been paid
by a committee at Riverside Church that maintains a powerful
amateur basketball program partly underwritten by Ernie Lorch, a
wealthy New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   The weird thing about the Barkley's absence is that after weeks
of speculation and legal skirmishing, St. John's still has not been
able to broker a definite penalty, so it can know if it can depend
on Barkley for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will appeal for immediate reinstatement,'' said Ed Manetta
Jr., the athletic director, who said the university did not concede
any violation by Barkley on the tuition money. ``We divert from
each other on interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   One game might seem to be the going rate, since last Wednesday
DerMarr Johnson of Cincinnati was suspended for one game for
accepting $7,000 from an amateur coach to attend the same prep
school as Barkley. But St. John's is not helping itself with the
NCAA by delaying its submission until Tuesday, and not
acknowledging wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The tone was continued by Mike Jarvis, St. John's coach, after
the game. He called Barkley ``a young man who has done nothing
wrong'' and said, ``He's lost three games that he should never have
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The response by the NCAA must come soon because St. John's has
one game left and the Big East tournament, and the NCAA tournament
and then Barkley is liable to be gone _ off to the NBA for real
money.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's lengthened its winning streak to eight Tuesday night
after having beaten Duke last Saturday. The Duke coach, Mike
Krzyzewski, appealed to the Duke students to spare Barkley from
their normal dosage of vicious but witty heckling, which, by and
large, they did.
</P>
<P>
   Krzyzewski almost never has to deal with indiscretions by his
players, but he did feel a sense of vulnerability last spring when
three players departed with eligibility remaining, a sign of the
times, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   At other schools, college players were undergoing various
investigations, allegations, suspicions, rumors, confessions, mea
culpas and nolo contenderes and all that other good legal stuff
that makes big-time college basketball such a wholesome sight.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to make any kind of wage for their labors, the players
are hounded by the NCAA for every dime or favor they have accepted,
in all their youthful innocence, you understand.
</P>
<P>
   This has popped up at Auburn, Cincinnati, UCLA and Michigan,
while Connecticut has had its own discipline problems.
</P>
<P>
   The latest incident was at Auburn, where the star forward Chris
Porter has been suspended for taking $2,500 from a sports agent.
The story coming out of Auburn is that Porter took the money to
help keep his mother from being evicted, which could be true, but
Porter is not likely to get mercy points from the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   JaRon Rush, the star at UCLA, took $6,525 from an amateur coach,
but when Rush agreed to pay the money back, the NCAA shortened his
suspension to nine games, making him eligible to play again
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Given the hardships and realities of life, it is no wonder why
players might reach out and accept tuition money or rent money. The
NCAA struggles to keep up with the machinations, but it is a weary,
grinding business, and it is hard to imagine anybody has any heart
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Most coaches just want to keep the vehicle barreling toward
March Madness, and deal with the details down the line. How long
can this system survive?  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
