r a BC-POLL-KAN &LR;      02-29 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH, GORE FAVORED TO WIN MISSOURI PRIMARY, POLL SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
 -KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Sen. John McCain of Arizona trails Texas Gov.
George W. Bush in a Missouri GOP primary match-up but would be the
better candidate in the general election, a statewide survey
indicates.
</P>
<P>
   In a hypothetical race against Vice President Al Gore _ the
likely winner of the Democratic contest Tuesday _ McCain would win
by 48-38 percent, according to the poll commissioned by The Kansas
City Star. When Bush is matched against Gore, however, the result
is a statistical dead heat, 44-42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As he has in other states, McCain scored highest among
Missouri's independent voters. And when all likely voters were
asked by pollsters about which of the four leading presidential
candidates had the strongest ``personal character and highest
integrity,'' the poll showed McCain far ahead with 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The next-highest rating went to former Sen. Bill Bradley of New
Jersey, 19 percent. Bush had 16 percent, Gore had 13 percent and
the remainder of the respondents were unsure.
</P>
<P>
   Respondents to the poll by far rated personal character _ 47
percent _ to be the most important factor in voting for the next
occupant of the White House. Less than three in 10 chose the
candidates' stands on issues. Experience was important to 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
   With Missouri's Republican presidential primary just six days
away, the survey by Mason-Dixon Polling &AMP; Research showed Bush with
a 48-36 percent lead with 13 percent still undecided. Alan Keyes,
the conservative former ambassador, drew 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, Gore appeared to be headed to an easy
victory in Bradley's home state. The vice president led Bradley,
who grew up in Crystal City, Mo., by 53-33 percent with 14 percent
undecided.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri will be one of 16 states participating in next week's
Super Tuesday round of primaries and caucuses that will go a long
way toward determining each party's nominees. Voters in Missouri
will be able to select a presidential-preference ballot from among
five parties: Democratic, Republican, Libertarian, Reform and
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Because Missouri does not register voters by party, they are
free to take a ballot from any of the parties.
</P>
<P>
   In other poll findings:
</P>
<P>
   - When asked which option was favored for any federal budget
surplus, only 14 percent said ```cut taxes across the board for all
Americans,'' a major policy of Bush. Twice as many called for
strengthening Social Security and Medicare. About one out of five
suggested paying down the national debt and 19 percent would invest
the money in new programs to improve education and health care.
</P>
<P>
   - On the question of which candidate has taken positions on
issues that were most similar to the respondent's, McCain had 29
percent to Gore's 27 percent. Bush was third with 18 percent, while
Bradley had 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   - Gore topped the field with 37 percent to Bush's 24 percent
when respondents were asked which candidate had the most experience
and was ``best qualified to do the job.'' McCain had 20 percent and
Bradley 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Star poll displayed a deep disparity between Bush and McCain
when it came to drawing support from independents and rank-and-file
Republicans. In a development seen in other states, Bush draws
nearly three times more support _ 63 percent to McCain's 22 _ from
voters who identified themselves as Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But among independents who said they planned to vote Tuesday,
McCain had a sizable edge _ 57-26 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Independent voters could make up 40 percent of next Tuesday's
vote, said J. Bradford Coker, Mason-Dixon managing director. He
estimated that about six of 10 independent voters would take
Republican ballots.
</P>
<P>
   ``The independent vote is critical in Missouri,'' said David
Steelman, McCain's Missouri chairman. ``Independents hold the key
not only to the November election, but they hold the key in the
primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush supporters also are confident of their strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased by those numbers,'' said Catherine Hanaway,
Bush's executive campaign director in Missouri. ``It means the
campaign we're running for the nomination in Missouri is going very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has made the theme of ``compassionate conservatism''
the cornerstone of his campaign, did much better, 53 percent, among
likely women voters in the GOP primary. McCain got slightly less
than one in three. Among Republican men, Bush received 44 percent
and McCain 39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has said that Missouri is a must-win for him. Still
struggling to notch his first victory of the campaign season, the
former senator from New Jersey has suggested that he will
reconsider his candidacy if he doesn't have a strong showing on
Super Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think obviously we have to score some victories on March
7,'' Bradley spokesman Tony Wyche said. ``We think Missouri is a
good state for us. It's a state where people appreciate plain
speaking, which is what this campaign has really been about.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, Gore's spokesman, said, ``It's nice to be up in
the polls, especially in Missouri. But we're not taking anybody's
vote for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore scored the highest of any candidate among women, with 59
percent, a better than 2-to-1 advantage over Bradley among likely
female Democratic voters. Among men, he led 46-39 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley attracted more independents, however.
</P>
<P>
   In the future general election match-ups, the survey indicated 3
percent would support Pat Buchanan, a Reform Party candidate, in a
race involving Bush, and that dropped to 2 percent if McCain were
on the GOP ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-29-00 2359EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000229.0531 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-02-29 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2804 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NY-DEMOCRACY-NYT     02-29 0352
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-DEMOCRACY-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: COUNTING DEMOCRACY'S FRIENDS IN ALBANY  (jw) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, March 1:
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times said i A vote scheduled for Wednesday in the
New York Senate will test which comes first with Republican members
_ party loyalty or democratic principle. At issue is the fate of
Senate Bill 6482, the measure devised by the Democratic minority
leader, Martin Connor, to clean up the closed-ballot system that
forced Sen. John McCain to wage an expensive legal battle to
compete statewide in New York's March 7 presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
   Under Connor's legislation, the onerous petition rules that
quadrennially trip up leading White House hopefuls, and make the
Empire State look like a petty dictatorship, would be history. So
would the ability of Republican leaders to rig the primary ballot
for their presidential favorite, much as Gov. George Pataki and
other GOP bosses tried to do for Gov. George W. Bush. Instead, the
executive director of the State Board of Elections would simply put
on the ballot all ``nationally known and recognized candidates''
who wish to appear. Those names, moreover, would appear in easily
readable type, not in the minuscule lettering that will confront
voters in next week's Republican contest here as they hunt for the
delegate slate committed to their presidential choice.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's key vote will come on a motion to bring Connor's
bill to the Senate floor for consideration on the merits. Joseph
Bruno, the Senate majority leader, plans to rally his Republican
caucus to cast a party-line vote against the motion, playing down
the significance of the showdown by labeling the vote merely
``procedural.'' That should fool no one. A vote against discharging
Connor's bill from the certain burial ground of the Elections
Committee is the equivalent of a vote against the bill itself.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno says he supports reform, but calls Connor's bill
``flawed.'' A reformer, though, would amend the bill to correct any
real flaws. He would not kill it.
</P>
